<HEADLINE>
FINAL ARRANGEMENTS FOR GOLDWATER'S ASHES UNCERTAIN
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS MOESER 
 and BETTY REID 
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barry Goldwater's body will be
cremated after his funeral service Wednesday, but it's still
unclear what the family will do with his remains.
</P>
<P>
   Family members gave conflicting reports about arrangements for
Goldwater's ashes, but it appears likely that the remains eve
ntually will be scattered in the Grand Canyon. The ashes would be
left where the crystalline waters of the Colorado River meet the
muddy waters of the Little Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   That was Goldwater's favorite spot on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Goldwate r, Goldwater's widow, on Tuesday told Bill
Shover, director of public affairs for The Arizona Republic, that
the ashes would be scattered near the two rivers.
</P>
<P>
   But Joanne Goldwater, the sena tor's daughter, and Bob
Goldwater, his broth er, said no plans had been made.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Goldwater, who will deliver the eulogy at the service today,
said his brother always wanted the Grand Canyon to be his final
resting place. But no plans have been made, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's saying we're going to be scattering anything,''
Goldwater said. ``I do know that Barry would have liked that. He
loved the Grand Canyon. But we don't want to do anything to upset
people.''
</P>
<P>
   As news reports leaked out Tues day about the p lan, that's
exactly what happened.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. James Henderson, D-Window Rock, issued a statement
saying the Navajo Nation opposed plans to scatter the ashes. Hender
son is running for president of the Navajo Nation.
</P>
<P>
   But George J oe, a Navajo Nation spokesman, disputed the
statement, saying the tribe had taken no position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all speculation at this point,'' Joe said. ``The Navajo
Nation and the Goldwater family have had a long tradition. Anything
that wo uld happen, we would work with them.''
</P>
<P>
   To scatter ashes in the Canyon would be contrary to traditional
Navajo philosophy about death. Navajos believe that when a person
dies, the corpse enters the realm of an evil world and has the pow
er to haunt the living and inflict physical and mental pain on
them.
</P>
<P>
   It is their belief that the Holy People, known as Wind People
and Water People, live in the Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   During journeys to the confluence of the rivers, traditional
</P>
<P>
   Navajos bring corn pollen, sprinkle it into the Canyon and pray
that they might achieve ``hozho,'' a state of beauty and harmony.
</P>
<P>
   Navajos make a claim that the western boundaries of the Navajo
Reservation are defined by the Colorado
</P>
<P>
   River.
</P>
<P>
   There remain hard feelings among some Navajos toward Gold water
because he sided with the Hopi Nation during a land dispute while
he was in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Taylor Jr., the chairman of the Hopi Nation, was traveling
and
could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Canyon officials say that each year, 20 to 30 people ask
to scatter remains in the Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Mengel, a park ranger who oversees the requests, said
remains are required to be scattered a way from public areas and
water, which could complicate a plan to scatter Goldwater's ashes
near the rivers. Mengel said families often sprinkle remains over
the Canyon by aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The Goldwater family has not contacted park officials
</P>
<P>
   about a permit, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they do, we would be more than happy to help them,'' Mengel
said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
