<SLUG> BC-BBO-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITCHING'S SAD STATE BAFFLING FOR RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a sultry summer's night nearly three years ago, baseball fans
at The Ballpark in Arlington witnessed a matchup of the two best
pitchers in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson and Hideo Nomo were more than All-Stars that week.
They were marquee superstars. The toasts of the All-Star Week
papparazzi.
</P>
<P>
   They looked like they were going to dominate baseball straight
into the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   But, oops. Will the last one headed for the airport please turn
out the lights?
</P>
<P>
   With Johnson expected to be on his way out of Seattle and Nomo's
days in Los Angeles now officially numbered, the numbing state of
big-league starting pitching is being underscored again.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers general manager Doug Melvin confirmed yesterday that he
has talked to the Los Angeles Dodgers about acquiring Nomo, the
National League starter that 1995 night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I called is to find what they're looking for,''
Melvin said, ``whether they were looking to do something for
prospects or for major-league players.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, Melvin learned, want players. Maybe they'll get
back to Melvin. Maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   There are indications that the Dodgers already are close to
finalizing a deal for Nomo. At least two general managers have
talked to the club and come away with that impression.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Randy Johnson Factory Liquidation Sale has reminded
us, closing a trade for a starting pitcher is not the same deal as
reporting about one.
</P>
<P>
   The American League standings today show the Rangers
quasi-solidly atop the Western Division. But how can this be, when
three-fifths of their starting rotation keeps turning the manager
gray?
</P>
<P>
   Collectively, Darren Oliver, John Burkett and Bobby Witt are
averaging seven earned runs and 12 boxes of Rolaids every nine
innings.
</P>
<P>
   They need a Hideo Nomo, even a struggling, lost-all-confidence,
can't-control-his-sinker Nomo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have two guys pitching pretty well in Triple A,'' Melvin
said, noting the minor-league work of Matt Perisho and Todd Van
Poppel. ``Todd had an outstanding game (Monday) night _ 13 ground
balls, seven strikeouts, no walks. He threw the ball real well.''
</P>
<P>
   But Melvin has repeatedly said that the organization would
prefer to nurture their prospects carefully, letting them earn
success at each level, before calling them up to the big club.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends,'' Melvin said yesterday. ``I think it depends on
how these guys go up here.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a veteran player, you're limited in what you can
do, too. You keep giving them the ball, and hope things work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran pitchers, in other words, have no-trade clauses and few,
if any, options. The pitcher's success may be a faint memory _ but
at least it's success.
</P>
<P>
   Take Nomo. Statistically, he has not been the same since being
struck in the elbow by a Scott Rolen line drive last July. The
injury required off-season surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Dodger-watchers say that Nomo has had trouble controlling his
once-diabolical sinker. He has fallen behind National League
hitters and, no longer mesmerized by his whirling delivery, they've
been able to sit and wait on his flat fastball.
</P>
<P>
   The same critics point to Nomo's record. His earned-run average
is up 1.92 runs since the injury, and his hits allowed have climbed
1.4 per game.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a diamond in the rough to me.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles just bestowed a multiyear, $6 million-per-season
contract on Scott Erickson, whose hits-per-nine-inning ratio is
nearly the highest in the league. The Indians did the same for
Charles Nagy, who has been allowing home runs at a near McGwire-ian
pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times clubs get upset at young pitchers struggling,''
Melvin said. ``They always say, `When are they going to learn? When
are they going to develop?
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're not the only club whose veteran pitching is
struggling. I think you can take a look at the veteran pitchers,
and there's a whole list of veteran guys that are sitting on 5.00
and 6.00 ERAs.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin sighed, sounding like a guy who doesn't expect to get any
you-won-the-Nomo-lottery phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``When league leaders in hits and home runs allowed get contract
extensions,'' Melvin wondered aloud, ``where's our pitching coming
to?''
</P>
<P>
   If the Dodgers call, therefore, what would Melvin be willing to
offer? Roberto Kelly, remember, is on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Greer? Ouch. The Dodgers dearly yearn for a left fielder.
But for more reasons than his batting average, the Rangers wouldn't
do it.
</P>
<P>
   The one intriguing player that Melvin could relinquish is center
fielder Tom Goodwin. But it would be difficult. Goodwin has been
the Rangers' second-biggest surprise (behind Aaron Sele), with his
patience at the plate and his defense.
</P>
<P>
   With Kelly out, however, who'd play center?
</P>
<P>
   It is only June, Melvin reminded yesterday. Things happen. A
good starting pitcher _ even a one-time All-Star pitcher _ might
fall from the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right. And I'm Randy Johnson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
