<SLUG> BC-XXX-XXX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS WOMEN AIM TO END LSU STREAK IN NCAA OUTDOOR CHAMPIONSHIPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By ANDY FRIEDLANDER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1986, Texas won the NCAA outdoor championship in women's
track and field.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, there has been only frustration _ and only Louisiana
State.
</P>
<P>
   In the 11 NCAA outdoor meets since '86, the Longhorns have
finished second four times, including three of the past four years.
LSU, anchored by its dominant sprint corps, won them all.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it appears to be Texas' turn again. The Longhorns, who lost
to LSU by one heartbreaking point last year, head into the opening
session of the 1998 NCAA outdoor championships today in Buffalo,
N.Y., with the speed and depth to derail the LSU dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Longhorns, TCU's men are seeking redemption from '97,
when the favored Horned Frogs dropped the baton in the 4x100
meters. The '98 Frogs come to Buffalo with the nation's fastest
sprinter in Percy Spencer and the No. 2-ranked relay team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was a bitter pill to swallow, but it made us a
better team this year,'' said Texas women's coach Bev Kearney, who
a year ago watched LSU roar from behind with 43 points on the
meet's final day to win 63-62. ``This year, we have enough
firepower to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns proved that with an awesome display of sprint
might at the Big 12 Championships two weeks ago. Entering the
meet's final day, Texas had not scored a point. When the afternoon
ended, the Longhorns had exploded for 151 points, taking first and
second in the 400 meters, the first three places in the 100 and the
first four in the 200.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Longhorns won't match that feat Saturday, the last
day of the NCAA meet, they are expected to score big in every
sprint event, led by LaKeisha Backus, Angie Vaughn, Suziann Reid,
Toya Brown and the 4x100- and 4x400-meter relays.
</P>
<P>
   LSU, meanwhile, has fallen considerably since last year, in part
because the Tigers are missing Astia Walker, who scored 28 points
by winning the 100-meter hurdles, finishing second in the 200 and
leading off the national champion 4x100 team. Walker was ruled
ineligible for the outdoor season after it was discovered that she
ran in a meet as a sophomore at Riverside (Calif.) Junior College.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we have the personnel to win the
championship,'' LSU coach Pat Henry said. ``Emotions are a big part
of track and field. Emotionally, you have to have the right things
happen. If you get on a roll, you can hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas hit it in March, ending LSU's string of five consecutive
NCAA indoor titles with a victory in Indianapolis. To follow that
with an outdoor crown, Texas must outscore high-powered UCLA, which
will be hurt by nagging injuries to hurdler Joanna Hayes, and
Brigham Young, led by versatile Tiffany Lott. Both those teams are
capable of making a charge.
</P>
<P>
   TCU's men seemed to have a chance to make a title run, but coach
Monte Stratton took the conservative route with his star, Spencer,
entering him in the 100 but not the 200, in which he placed second
last year. That leaves the Frogs with enough potential points to
climb into the top five, but not enough for a realistic shot at the
team championship.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas, with its strength in the distance events and jumps, is
a heavy favorite to win its eighth consecutive men's outdoor title.
Arizona, LSU and Clemson are other top contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Stratton said the decision not to double Spencer was made in
part because the senior from Jamaica was behind in conditioning
because of an early season injury and in part to give him a better
chance to win the 100, in which he is the No. 1 seed with a best
time of 9.96.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no easy races at the NCAA meet,'' Stratton said.
``If he doubled, he'd have to run six rounds of sprints and two of
relays against the highest level of competition in four days.
That's not to say he couldn't do it, but it would be very
difficult, and we prefer to take the cautious approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd rather do one thing exceptionally well than a lot of
things pretty good, and risk blowing up.''
</P>
<P>
   Stratton knows about that, having watched the Frogs
self-destruct last year in the NCAA 4x100 relay preliminaries,
dropping the baton before Spencer touched it.
</P>
<P>
   This year the Frogs, whose qualifying time of 38.71 is .02
behind No. 1 LSU, are again one of the teams to beat in the relay,
with Bryan Howard, Jarmiene Holloway and Syan Williams joining
Spencer. Spencer, Holloway and Howard could score in the 100, and
Williams is ranked fourth in the 200.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Khadevis Robinson's 1:46.06, the third-fastest 800
time in the nation, makes him dangerous in a race that includes big
names Seneca Lassiter and David Krummenacker. He will also anchor
the fourth-ranked 4x400 relay team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 0038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
