<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1441 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-BLUEJAYS-B     06-03 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX ROUT BLUE JAYS, STAY ON UPSWING 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-BLUE JAYS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ By any measure, this was not your typical
businessman's junket.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, who left town last week with spirits scraping the
sidewalk on Yawkey Way, bottomed out in the belly of the beast in
the Bronx, overnighted on an airplane grounded by a divine light
show, then stumbled without sleep into an outbreak of Dennis Rodman
disease here.
</P>
<P>
   Who could have blamed the Sons of Jimy Williams if they'd made a
bonfire out of their boarding passes?
</P>
<P>
   And yet Tuesday night the Red Sox returned to the sweet embrace
of home jauntier than ever, sounding as if they'd just spent the
last two nights in Tahiti instead of Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   What could have been the trip from hell, especially when their
season-worst losing streak stretched to six games after their first
two nights in New York, instead was salvaged by four straight wins,
including Tuesday night's 11-3 victory over the Blue (and
Orange-Blond) Jays.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we go out and believe in ourselves and play the way we're
capable of, we can play with anybody,'' said Mo Vaughn, who was a
bit player in this one with an RBI double in the ninth but whose
cameo tirade Sunday in New York might have had a carryover effect.
``I'm not surprised we got ourselves some wins. I knew we could
play like this. That's why I reacted the way I did Sunday, to put
that into effect. I know we're capable. The key is the guys have to
know they can do it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   With lefthander Steve Avery unveiling a streamlined delivery and
Rich Garces flaunting his same XXL form, the Red Sox completed a
two-game sweep by hitting three home runs, including a three-run
jump starter by Nomar Garciaparra in the third and a three-run
nightcap by Darren Bragg in the eighth. The other, Troy O'Leary's
13th of the season, touched off a five-run rally in the eighth,
which all took place after two were out.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's tormentors _ the Blue Jays beat the Red Sox twice in
Fenway Park _ became this week's toast, if you don't mind peroxide
instead of jelly.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, 9-5 winners Monday on a four-run ninth-inning
rally, scored six runs in the last two innings Tuesday night and
outscored the Blue Jays, 20-8, in the two-game set.
</P>
<P>
   While all that offense has been nice, and John Valentin threw
his glove into the mix, robbing Jose Canseco of extra bases with a
diving stop with the game still close in the fifth, the secret to
the Red Sox' road show revival was easy to detect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two words,'' reliever Jim Corsi said. ``Starting pitching. I
rest my case.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Sox left town last week, their starting pitching had
begun to look shabbier than Willy Loman's suitcase.
</P>
<P>
   But then Bret Saberhagen went out and stood down the Yankees
last Saturday, and suddenly, there was new life not only in his
artificial shoulder but in the rest of the rotation as well. Pedro
Martinez won the next day, Tim Wakefield held the Blue Jays to four
hits in six innings Monday, and Tuesday it was Avery's turn to
claim rebirth.
</P>
<P>
   Abandoning the straight overhand style that had made him a
playoff MVP at the age of 21, Avery dropped his arm down to a much
lower angle, something he first tried just four days earlier in a
practice session in New York. It wasn't entirely an artistic
success _ Avery walked six Blue Jays in five innings _ but he
allowed just three hits and three runs and emerged with his second
win of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball had a little better movement, my delivery was a
little more deceiving, and my velocity was up,'' said Avery.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, I was a little timid and nervous, trying
something new. At times, I was afraid to let it go. I told
(pitching coach Joe Kerrigan) as we were walking in from the
bullpen, `Joe, are you sure we want to do this?'''
</P>
<P>
   With Kerrigan's encouragement, and an unexpected assist from
Canseco, who twice was picked off first by Avery, the lefthander
took the plunge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's inconsistent, as you might expect,'' Kerrigan said, ``and
there's a lot more work to do, but it looks like we've finally got
a place to go: forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Garces is looking anywhere but back. El Guapo (The
Handsome One), as he was nicknamed by teammates, is an easy target
because of his girth.
</P>
<P>
   But Garces, who relieved Avery, pitched a 1-2-3 sixth, then
pitched out of a first-and-third, no-out jam in the seventh by
striking out Jose Cruz and Shannon Stewart, then retiring Canseco
on a ground ball. He has not been scored upon in eight of his last
nine appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can call me whatever they want,'' said Garces. ``As long
as I go out and do my job, they can call me whatever they want to
call me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a name: Richard Garces. El Guapo? That's OK, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Take it from a teammate who also has been accused of being fat.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can talk about size all you want,'' Vaughn said. ``It's
what you do on the field. And the kid has got a big heart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 0038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
