<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS SINGING OF CROSBY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Bubba Crosby, a power-hitting outfielder from Rice
University in Houston, was selected by the Los Angeles Dodgers on
Tuesday in the first round of the Major League Baseball amateur
draft.
</P>
<P>
   Crosby, who returned from an early-season hamstring injury to
bat .394 with 25 homers and 91 RBI in 58 games, has been labeled by
some scouts as the most well-rounded player in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Crosby, 21, was taken with the 23rd selection overall. He is an
All-American selection of The Sporting News, Baseball America and
Baseball Weekly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really nervous this morning,'' said Crosby, who will be
represented by the Houston-based Hendricks brothers. ``We were
listening to the draft on the Internet and we were just looking for
the name Crosby. It was a cherished moment. I can't really explain
the feeling. I know I'm not in the big leagues yet, but this is the
first step.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers like Crosby's power but are more impressed with his
all-around skill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think he could start at Single-A,'' Dodgers scouting
director Terry Reynolds said. ``He plays solid defense and runs
well. He adds up to a solid player. He brings all the intangibles
to the ballpark everyday.''
</P>
<P>
   __ McGwire out: Cardinals slugger Mark McGwire, who leads the
majors with 27 homers, will miss all three games of the Dodgers
series after suffering back spasms Monday night in San Diego. He
will not even take batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire said his back condition is not serious, but rest is the
best treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know my back like the back of my hand,'' said McGwire, who
missed playing time several years ago with lower-back pain. ``There
is no reason to push it. I'll be back soon.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Reyes in: At 5 p.m. Tuesday, Dennis Reyes didn't know what
the future held. He was told he would replace Hideo Nomo in the
Dodgers' rotation on Monday after Nomo was taken off the roster.
</P>
<P>
   That meant starting Friday night in Seattle. But then he was
told the Dodgers' negotiations with Mariners left-hander Randy
Johnson might change the day of his start.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all pretty weird,'' Reyes said. ``Nothing was
certain.''
</P>
<P>
   Reyes is coming off a weird outing Friday night against
Cincinnati. He came on in relief after Scott Radinsky blew a
ninth-inning lead. He retired the first eight batters he faced then
gave up five straight hits in the 12th and lost 8-4.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are confident, however, that Reyes can make the
transition to the starting rotation. He started the season at
Triple-A Albuquerque after pitching poorly this spring. He was
recalled after posting a 1.69 ERA in 18 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot about concentration and focus down there,''
Reyes said. ``I kind of lost that during spring training. I'd be
out on the mound and let things get to me. Going to Albuquerque
helped me get that back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
