<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS STUDY OPTIONS AT DEFENSIVE END
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ With Tony Tolbert's status still unclear, the
Cowboys offered a glimpse of their defensive-end plans without the
former Pro Bowler yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Kavika Pittman started at one end while first-round draft pick
Greg Ellis and veteran Hurvin McCormack alternated at the other the
first day of the team's final minicamp at the Valley Ranch training
complex.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said he considers Tolbert part of the
plans for next season _ though he said things could change,
considering Tolbert's salary and health.
</P>
<P>
   Tolbert, who will count $3,447,000 against the Cowboys' cap next
season, recently had surgery on both knees. It is uncertain whether
he will return. If he does, the Cowboys hope to sign him to reduced
contract. He also could retire or be released.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much depends on his knees, his feelings and where we are as
a team,'' Gailey said. ``There is so much going on there. Only time
will tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys defensive coordinator Dave Campo said the team can be
successful with Pittman, who recorded 11 tackles and one sack the
past two seasons combined, the rookie Ellis and McCormack, a former
tackle.
</P>
<P>
   His confidence is rooted in a defensive philosophy change that
he said maximizes the ability of that group while lessening the
impact of not having a Pro Bowl-caliber player at the position.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of having a definite right and left end as in the past,
the ends will change sides depending on the offense and defensive
call. Pittman plays rush end and will go to the weak side, while
McCormack and Ellis play the strong side, which will usually be on
the side of the tight end.
</P>
<P>
   McCormack and Pittman said they like the change. They said it
will allow them to blossom into productive players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better for me,'' Pittman said. ``I'm in open space and
I'm not cluttered up. I'm not a big guy or the strongest guy. But
I'm fast and quick. This gives me an opportunity to use it.''
</P>
<P>
   McCormack, who flip-flopped between end and tackle the past four
years, said he plans to battle Ellis for the starting job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starting is my goal,'' McCormack said. ``It's definitely a
competitive state right now with the first-rounder. But I'm
comfortable with the position change. It suits my skills. I'm ready
to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis, however, said he understands that most of the pressure
and the spotlight will be on him, thanks to his draft position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starting is realistic for me because of the coaching staff and
the owner,'' Ellis said. ``I think they drafted me to start. They
are not going to waste the eighth pick in the draft on somebody who
is not going to start and play a whole lot.'' &QL; 
BRIEFLY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said the Cowboys are deciding whether safety Bill Bates
and running back Herschel Walker fit into their plans for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys got a surprise at practice when former coach Barry
Switzer made a cameo appearance. Switzer talked briefly about his
blossoming film career. Switzer has filmed one movie and is being
courted by Oliver Stone for a part in an upcoming movie about
professional football.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie linebacker Darren Hambrick missed the afternoon workout
for personal reasons. Gailey said Hambrick should be back at
practice today.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Tolbert, cornerback Deion Sanders (ankle) and
receiver Macey Brooks (groin muscle) missed practice because of
injuries. Sanders is not expected back until training camp, while
Brooks is day-to-day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 0045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1447 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBC-USC-LADN     06-03 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC OUSTS MISSISSIPPI STATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. _ USC freshman right-hander Rik Currier, who was
knocked early in his first start in the regional tournament, hurled
the Trojans into a rematch with powerhouse Louisiana State by
beating Mississippi State, 7-1, Tuesday night in the College World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   Currier gave up just four hits - two the first seven innings -
and struck out 12 to eliminate Mississippi State and leave just
four teams in the CWS, three of them from the West: USC, Long Beach
State and Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth club is two-time defending champion LSU, which
outslugged USC in the first round, 12-10. The Trojans and Tigers
will meet again Thursday at 12:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Brad Ticehurst slugged two homers, the sixth and
seventh of the Series for the Trojans, who pounded out a dozen hits
and, after three games, are the No. 1-hitting team, average-wise,
in the tournament, at .352.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Mississippi State coach Pat McMahon, pointed out, it was
the work of Currier that was the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had such a well-pitched game, he made it difficult for
us,'' said McMahon, whose club finished its season 42-23.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as the Bulldogs' shortstop Brad Freeman, said, ``He was
nasty. He would have shut down a lot of teams tonight. He's a good
one. You've just got to tip your hat to him.''
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Mike Gillespie was quick to note how vital it was for
Currier to give the Trojans some quality innings after Monday
night's 11-inning, 12-10 marathon victory over Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys who might have normally been available were not,''
Gillespie said, ``so this was an extremely important game for us.''
</P>
<P>
   It helped, too, that the Trojans provided Currier a quick lead,
going in front, 4-0, after only three innings.
</P>
<P>
   Ticehurst hit the first of his two homers to lead off the
Trojans' second. Jason Lane then ripped the glove off the hand of
Mississippi State hurler Mark Freed with a single to center. Jeremy
Freitas walked, and Seth Davidson bunted for a single to fill the
bases with nobody out.
</P>
<P>
   Wes Rachels drove in Lane with a sacrifice fly, then, with two
outs, Robb Gorr singled home Freitas for a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   In the third, Ticehurst again led off with an homer, his 17th of
the season. Ticehurst wasn't so sure about this one, which bounded
out of the right-center seats after a fan apparently got a hand on
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit it well,'' he said, ``but I saw it come back on the
field. I thought I had a triple.'' He was promptly waved home.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, USC (46-17) scored twice more to take a 6-0
lead. Ticehurst was hit by a pitch, was balked to second, then Lane
doubled him home. Lane scored on Freitas' run-scoring single.
</P>
<P>
   Currier lost his bid for his first shutout - and first at the
CWS since two Cal State Fullerton pitchers combined for one three
years ago - in the bottom of the eighth. Brad Freeman's two-out
double drove in Brian Wiese, who had beat out an infield single to
third.
</P>
<P>
   Lane had three of the Trojans' 12 hits, and Gorr, Davidson and
Ticehurst each had two.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Eric Munson said it was tough coming back after the long
game the night before, saying: ``It's tough after a long, tiring
game not to have a letdown. It's human nature. But we were able to
step up to the challenge, and we came out ready to play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
