<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE OF JOHNSON NO REAL SOLUTION TO MARINER WOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ So the Mariners have blinked. After 10 days of
discussions with at least the Dodgers, Randy Johnson is off the
trading block.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Johnson is now a ``valued member'' of the Mariner staff
and will pitch for the club ``through the season,'' club president
Chuck Armstrong said Tuesday in a one-paragraph statement.
</P>
<P>
   End of discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Right. As if anything short of a contract negotiation between
Johnson and the Mariners will end speculation about what's to
become of the Big Unit.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Mariners and Johnson's representatives appear gravely
dismayed at all the media hullabaloo surrounding the dominating
lefty, whose career could be building toward Hall of Fame
induction.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, we suppose, is hurt because he has asked the team to
trade him, and now he's been told he's staying.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners, we could understand, are miffed because they felt
they were caught in a no-win situation, so why should they have to
endure criticism for their stance on Johnson? They felt Johnson was
going to cost too much and might not have been committed to staying
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, if a team like the Mariners can't keep its payroll sane
and reject a skyrocketing market for free-agent pitchers (like
Pedro Martinez and Greg Maddux at $11.5 million or more per
season), who else is going to guard against baseball's ridiculous
spiral toward financial ruin? Rupert Murdoch? Hah!
</P>
<P>
   The answer _ as it has been since last November _ is that the
Mariners should at least have offered Johnson a contract extension.
Unless, of course, the M's truly did not want him and were afraid
he would have accepted $8.5 million or so a year.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, there is an even larger point for the Mariners to
consider. They were not getting the kind of offers for Johnson that
they had hoped. They found themselves hanging so far out on the
precipice they were about to commit an embarrassing act of historic
proportions. Trading Johnson now would have looked like throwing
deck chairs off the Titanic.
</P>
<P>
   Trading him this past winter at least would have shown that they
were committed to getting something for him. It would have allowed
the team to start the season fresh and let the chips fall where
they may.
</P>
<P>
   But trading Johnson now does nothing to improve the team,
because unfortunately for everybody _ fans, players and ownership _
the Mariner chips have fallen during this 1998 season, and they
have fallen with an incredible thud.
</P>
<P>
   After another blown save, after their 10 loss when seven or more
runs wasn't enough to win, and after 48 errors makes them the worst
defensive team in the American League, the M's finally discovered
that dealing Johnson now would have been beside the point.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson is the least of the Mariners' problems. The
Mariners are a sub-.500 team despite a $53 million payroll and a
roster full of All-Stars and award winners _ and the flop is badly
timed, one year before their amazingly grand and expensive new
stadium is due to open.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the reason Woody Woodward has seemed so reluctant to carry
out his bosses' marching orders to deal Johnson is because deep
down, the club's vice president of baseball operations knows the
Mariners are far better off with Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   What baseball executive would want to be remembered as the man
who traded Randy Johnson for two guys no one remembers in two
years?
</P>
<P>
   But Woodward and his scouts are left with a bigger problem now.
This split-personality team with the wonderful bats and woeful
bullpen has lost its way.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can write anything you want,'' Lou Piniella said Tuesday
after the Mariners' horrendous 10th-inning loss to the Orioles _
the 12th blown save of this imploded season _ sent the Mariner
manager pacing, smoking, muttering.
</P>
<P>
   Who wouldn't smoke, pace and mutter now, searching for answers
that just won't come?
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have had a three- or four-year window of
opportunity to rise to the difficult challenge of playing
championship-caliber baseball. They were supposed to be peaking now
and next season, when the new stadium opens in July. But now that
window quickly is slamming shut on Seattle's fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward and his scouting staff must have an understanding that
almost every trading deadline deal he has made in the past three
seasons has done more to deplete the Mariners than shore them up.
</P>
<P>
   In '95, it was prospects like outfielder Mark Newfield and
pitcher Ron Villone peddled for rent-a-pitcher Andy Benes. It was
too much, too late.
</P>
<P>
   And in '97, it was outfielder Jose Cruz Jr. for relievers Mike
Timlin and Paul Spoljaric, and pitcher Derek Lowe and catcher Jason
Varitek for closer Heathcliff Slocumb _ a very high price because
the Mariners waited too long to jump in for deals with the White
Sox or the Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in a season that was supposed to be a set-up for the
opening of a new ballpark, the Mariners have come undone. Not for
lack of effort. Not for lack of heart. But for lack of good, timely
deals that would have improved the team instead of depleting it and
the farm system.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariner skipper told us to write what we want. His team is
trying. He is out of answers, and the Mariner problems are nothing
a Randy Johnson trade can fix.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
