<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-DEVILRAYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS, WITT DOWN DEVIL RAYS, 7-3
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ The Rangers placed right-hander Bobby
Witt in their rotation partly for his ability to accumulate innings
and ease the burden on their bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Those days might now be beyond him.
</P>
<P>
   Witt earned the victory during last night's 7-3 triumph against
the Tampa Bay Devil Rays at Tropicana Field, but Witt, 34, failed
to record an out during the seventh inning for the seventh time in
11 starts this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't look like the same pitcher I had in Florida,'' said
Devil Rays manager Larry Rothschild, who served as Witt's pitching
coach in 1995 while both were with the Marlins. ``I don't know if
he's hurting or what. He spotted the ball at times tonight, but
he's pitching differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Witt, who entered the game ranked third among American League
pitchers in run support per nine innings with 7.95, once again
emerged as the beneficiary of the Rangers' offense.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers sponsored Witt with a six-run second inning, and he
pitched 5 1/3 innings for his fifth victory in eight decisions.
Witt averaged 5 1/3 innings during his previous 10 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers manager Johnny Oates does not view Witt as a five-inning
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope not,'' the manager said. ``Tonight he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Witt, though, remains a competitor.
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays tagged the right-hander for a run in the fourth
inning and scored twice during the fifth inning on a one-out,
two-run homer from third baseman Wade Boggs. First baseman Fred
McGriff then reached on a single, and Witt appeared in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he induced an inning-ending, double-play ground ball off
the bat of second baseman Bobby Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to get a ground ball,'' Witt said, ``and I did
with a slider.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith hit the ball into the hole between second and third base,
but Domingo Cedeno _ playing for injured shortstop Kevin Elster _
made a backhand stop and accurate throw to second base. Luis
Alicea, playing for injured second baseman Mark McLemore, turned
the pivot cleanly to complete the second of two double plays in
which both were involved.
</P>
<P>
   It represented the tandem's first work together at those
positions this season, and the two worked at those positions
together only sparingly this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second one was more difficult,'' Alicea said of the
momentum-changing play. ``He gave me a good, low feed, but we work
on that every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Alicea and Cedeno also contributed offensively during the
Rangers' six-run second inning. Cedeno, who can be described as a
free swinger, demonstrated selectiveness at the plate and drew a
bases-loaded walk that scored first baseman Will Clark with the
Rangers' first run.
</P>
<P>
   Alicea capped the inning with a two-out, three-run homer on a
3-2 fastball from right-hander Jason Johnson (2-3).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just happy I hit the ball hard, but I definitely can't be
concerned about hitting home runs,'' said Alicea, who had hit only
11 during 2,469 previous major-league at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Scott Bailes and right-handers Al Levine, Xavier
Hernandez and John Wetteland gave the Rangers' 3 2/3 scoreless
innings after Witt surrendered three runs on seven hits and four
walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to give a lot of credit to our bullpen and bench,''
Oates said. ``We thought our bench was going to be good coming into
this season, and it's lived up to that expectation. The bullpen and
bench continue to do very, very well for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Witt, who along with right-hander John Burkett and left-hander
Darren Oliver has struggled much of this season, appeared upset by
Oates' decision to remove him after a one-out, sixth-inning double
by catcher Mike DiFelice. The Rangers led 7-3, and Witt had thrown
only 90 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's his decision,'' Witt said. ``What am I going to say?
What is Burkie going to say? What is Darren going to say? We're all
capable of going out there and throwing 125-135 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't continue to go out there to the bullpen. Those guys
have done an outstanding job all season, but you feel your job is
to go seven or eight innings so they don't have to get up every
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Witt apparently wanted that opportunity last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to be happy,'' he said, ``until I finish a
game.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be a first this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
