<SLUG> BC-BBA-JOEY-CORA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORA TELLS WRITER NEXT SEASON WILL BE HIS LAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Mariners second baseman Joey Cora is planning the
final chapter of his major league career. He told a reporter from
his native Puerto Rico it will be written after next season.
</P>
<P>
   The popular Mariner divulged his plans to the reporter from a
San Juan newspaper last weekend, although he wouldn't comment
Tuesday about the article.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the time to be talking about it,'' Cora said after
the Mariners dropped a 9-8, 10-inning decision to the Baltimore
Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to finish this season and take the option for '99
and that's it,'' Cora, 33, told El Nuevo Dia. ``I've thought it
over and feel comfortable with the decision. I'll retire after
1999.''
</P>
<P>
   The option actually belongs to the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Cora, who helped the M's get into the playoffs in 1995 and '97,
is making $1.65 million this season with a $1.8 million club option
for '99.
</P>
<P>
   His remarks were published in Saturday's editions of the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Cora said the constant travel and a desire to spend more time
with family motivated the decision. Cora was married last November.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't understand that. In baseball, life is good and
there is good money, but the trips here are brutal,'' he said. ``I
want to enjoy life with my wife and my family. When you're in
baseball, you forget other things.''
</P>
<P>
   Cora, who was born in Caguas, Puerto Rico, played in 1987 with
the San Diego Padres and was traded in 1991 to the Chicago White
Sox. He signed with the Mariners in 1995 as a free agent and hit
.300 last season.
</P>
<P>
   Cora said he hasn't decided what he wants to do after 1999, but
would consider scouting or working with a team in Puerto Rico,
``but not as a coach and not as a manager.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 0104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1459 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELN-OTHER-STATES-546&AMP;     06-03 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-OTHER-STATES-546&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVE EX-LAWMAKER WINS IOWA GOP PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jim Ross Lightfoot, the most conservative of three Republicans
seeking to succeed Gov. Terry Branstad of Iowa, easily won his
party's nomination in Tuesday's primary, while two little-known
Democrats were nearly tied.
</P>
<P>
   Branstad, the nation's longest-serving governor, is retiring
after four terms. The potential presidential field of 2000 was
closely watching the primary races as a barometer of the strength
of each party's factions in Iowa, an early weeder of White House
hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   Lightfoot, 59, a former congressman and farm broadcaster, beat
two other Republicans, David Oman, a cable television executive,
and Paul Pate, the Iowa secretary of state. Potential Republican
candidates for president had long considered the frontrunner to be
Lightfoot, who stumped with Steve Forbes, Jack Kemp and Dan Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   Lightfoot told his supporters at the Hotel Fort Des Moines,
``With this vote of confidence we are ready to work together in a
unified effort to make Iowa the best neighborhood in America by
cutting taxes, improving schools and winning the fight against
crime and drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic candidates were Mark McCormick, a former justice
of the state Supreme Court who ran as a centrist, and state Sen.
Tom Vilsack, who stuck to the traditional, more liberal stands of
Iowa Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have not held the governor's mansion in Iowa for 30
years, and analysts said the Republicans once again go into the
fall with big advantages, including Branstad's continuing
popularity. The analysts said they expect Lightfoot to benefit from
the momentum of his big victory, and from the statewide name
recognition he built up during a losing bid for U.S. Senate in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Also, redistricting during his 12 years in Congress meant he
represented 44 of the state's 99 counties at one time or another.
Both Democrats, by contrast, were unknown even to some activists in
their own party.
</P>
<P>
   J. Ann Selzer, the director of the Iowa Poll, said Lightfoot had
appealed to ``the heart of the party'' during the nominating
contest. ``He's going to have to change his style and adjust his
message, but he understands that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lightfoot, who won the endorsement of Iowa Right to Life, aired
a television commercial last month in which his late mother
described how she had adopted him from an orphanage as an infant.
In an unusual twist for Republicans in today's anti-tax climate,
the other two candidates argued that Lightfoot's proposal for
cutting state income tax rates was too steep and could lead to
drastic cuts in education. Each proposed his own, more moderate
cut.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic race was more bitterly fought. Each candidate ran
television advertisements criticizing the other's legal clients.
Vilsack charged his opponent would ``give new tax breaks to
corporate real estate,'' while McCormick said his opponent
``represented banks on farm foreclosures during the farm crisis.''
Vilsack replied that in most cases, he had been on the side of
farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The five candidates spent nearly $4 million among them.
Lightfoot raised more than $1 million, compared with $710,000 for
Oman and $580,000 for Pate. On the Democratic side, McCormick had a
slight financial edge, with $780,000 in contributions and loans, to
Vilsack's $690,000.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the Democratic primary in New Mexico, Martin Chavez, a former
mayor of Albuquerque, topped a field of six to win a spot on
November's ballot against the first-term incumbent Republican, Gov.
Gary Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Two House races in New Mexico drew national attention. In one,
state Attorney General Tom Udall, a nephew of the longtime
Congressman Morris Udall, was seeking a chance to bring the Udall
name back to Washington. He was running in the Democrat primary for
the congressional seat held by Rep. Bill Redmond, a Republican
freshman. The other candidate was Eric Serna, who had sought the
seat in a special election last year. Mark Udall, a son of the
congressman, is running for a House seat in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   In another House race, for the seat of the late Rep. Steven
Schiff, a five-term Republican who died in March, the primary
winners were Heather Wilson on the Republican side and state Sen.
Phil Maloof on the Democratic side. In a preview of the November
race, the two already were slated to face off in a special election
on June 23 to fill out Schiff's term.
</P>
<P>
   In South Dakota, a member of the executive committee of the
Republican National Committee won a spot on the November ballot
against Sen. Tom Daschle, the Democratic leader, who was unopposed
for his party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican winner was Ronald Schmidt, 60, a lawyer from
Pierre. He said he stands for less government and lower taxes, and
plans to portray Daschle as being too focused on national causes.
``The people of South Dakota are going to have the most clear-cut
choice of philosophies of any voters in the country,'' Schmidt said
Tuesday night. Schmidt beat Alan Aker, a logging contractor, and
John Sanders, a businessman.
</P>
<P>
   In Montana, each party's candidate ran unopposed in the primary
for the state's single congressional district. The incumbent is
Rep. Rick Hill, a freshman Republican, who will face Robert
Deschamps, a Democrat, in November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
