<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-JOHNSON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS PULL THE PLUG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After dragging fans, players and front-office
executives around for five days, the Randy Johnson trade saga ended
Tuesday with the 6-foot-10 left-hander remaining in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers' attempt at a second blockbuster trade
in the past two weeks failed when their final bid of right-hander
Ismael Valdes and two minor leaguers for Johnson was rejected by
the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle still wanted right-hander Darren Dreifort, who started
Tuesday's game against the St. Louis Cardinals. When Dodgers
executive vice president Fred Claire said no, the Mariners said
Johnson will stay in Seattle for the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is no longer in pursuit of Randy Johnson,'' Claire
said. ``It ended at 12 noon today as far as we were concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Dodgers, who have wilted under the distraction of the
Johnson trade talks, will attempt to regroup without him. Claire
addressed the team an hour before Tuesday's 7-4 loss to the
Cardinals and stressed the need to refocus after losing three in a
row over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not need a frenzy every night at Dodger Stadium,''
Claire said.
</P>
<P>
   Claire spent part of the day fielding inquiries about
right-hander Hideo Nomo, who was designated for assignment Monday
after demanding a trade. Claire spoke to more than a dozen teams,
including the Baltimore Orioles. Claire said there was nothing to
reports that the Dodgers were close to sending Nomo to the Orioles
for closer Armando Benitez.
</P>
<P>
   The deadline on the Johnson talks was an attempt by Claire to
reaffirm his control of the Dodgers' baseball operation.
</P>
<P>
   During the 5-for-2 trade May 15 with the Florida Marlins, Fox
television head Chase Carey was the point man in acquiring Gary
Sheffield, Bobby Bonilla, Charles Johnson and Jim Eisenreich for
Mike Piazza and Todd Zeile.
</P>
<P>
   Claire was so far from the action that many questioned his role
in the Dodgers hierarchy under new ownership.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the players there should be no misunderstanding that
the direction of baseball operations is Fred Claire,'' he said. ``I
am the man.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's primary focus, however, remained fixed on Johnson.
Dodgers players said they were pleased to have the distractions end
but were disappointed a pitcher of Johnson's caliber did not join
the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely would have been better with him,'' Bonilla said.
``But it is time to regroup and get on with the season.''
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Eric Karros said the club should not be surprised
by the circus atmosphere that overtook the Johnson talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is baseball in the l990s,'' he said. ``This kind of thing
never happened in the Dodgers organization. Nothing ever gets done
out in the open. Now we are like everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Raul Mondesi said the most important thing for the players is
not to look back later this season and wonder if Johnson would have
been the difference in overtaking the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   ``All along I've thought we had a good enough team to win,'' he
said. ``None of this has changed my feelings. He is a good pitcher,
but we are a good team.''
</P>
<P>
   Claire called Mariners general manager Woody Woodward Tuesday
morning and issued a noon deadline to accept or reject an offer of
three players that included Valdes, minor league utility player
Wilton Guerrero and pitcher Eric Weaver for Johnson, who is
eligible for free agency at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   When he did not hear from Woodward, Claire prepared to address
the players that they must move forward without Johnson and regain
focus on a season that has been derailed by distractions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has hurt us,'' manager Bill Russell said. ``I think a lot
of people thought he was coming. A guy like that makes you better.
Now that it's over, I think we'll be better. We've already made
some moves that improved the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Dreifort in the deal, the Mariners turned their
attention to having Johnson pitch this season and getting him to
sign a new contract at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's own contract impasse, which began during spring
training, also has been a distraction for the Mariners. Expected to
win the American League West, they are 26-31 after losing 9-0
Tuesday night in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy Johnson is a valued pitcher for the Mariners, who is
under contract for the balance of the 1998 season,'' Seattle
president Chuck Armstrong said in a statement. ``Randy will pitch
for the Mariners throughout this season.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
