<SLUG> BC-ELN-SOUTH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALABAMA GOVERNOR FORCED INTO RUNOFF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Subs 5th graf for updating of vote) (mk) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, Ala. _ Gov. Fob James Jr. of Alabama, a
party-switching Republican whose fervid support for school prayer
has made him a national icon for religious conservatives, was
forced into a runoff in the gubernatorial primary here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Although he finished first in a five-candidate field, James, 63,
failed to win a majority and will face Winton Blount III, a
Montgomery businessman and longtime Republican loyalist, in the
runoff on June 30.
</P>
<P>
   James, who is running for reelection to his third term _ he
served the first as a Democrat from 1979 to 1983 _ nearly avoided
the runoff with a late surge as he moved steadily toward the 50
percent threshhold in the final week of campaigning. But the same
dissatisfaction that lured four Republican opponents to challenge
the incumbent apparently unsettled just enough voters to deny James
a first-round victory.
</P>
<P>
   James and Blount now face the arduous task of turning out their
voters for a midsummer runoff and competing for the support of the
three other Republican contenders.
</P>
<P>
   With 91 percent of the precincts reporting, James had 163,711
votes, or 48 percent of the vote, while Blount finished second with
139,941 votes, or 41 percent. Former Gov. Guy Hunt, who decided to
run after being pardoned of the state ethics conviction that forced
his resignation in 1993, finished third with 8 percent of the vote.
Two other candidates, Lewis Leslie McAllister Jr., a Tuscaloosa
businessman, and Phillip Williams, a former state finance director,
shared the rest of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   In the Democratic primary, Lt. Gov. Don Siegelman easily
defeated his top rival, Lenora Pate, a Birmingham lawyer. Siegelman
enters the general election with more than $3.5 million in his
campaign treasury, a team of experienced Democratic strategists and
an eye-catching policy proposal borrowed from the popular
Democratic governor of a neighboring state, Zell Miller of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Siegelman has pledged to push for a state lottery to finance
college scholarships, pre-kindergarten programs and school
construction. That plan is sure to strike a chord with Alabamians
desperate to improve the quality of the state's educational system.
But, as was the case in Georgia, it has already stirred opposition
from religious conservatives who view the lottery as a first step
toward the legalization of other forms of gambling. The Republicans
also plan to portray Siegelman as an unreconstructed liberal and a
captive of the state's trial lawyers' lobby.
</P>
<P>
   In neighboring Mississippi, meanwhile, voters in the Democratic
and Republican primaries selected congressional candidates who will
vie in the general election in November. The most closely watched
race came in the 4th District in southwestern Mississippi, where a
large field of candidates from both parties competed to succeed
Rep. Mike Parker, a Republican who is retiring after five terms.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, Delbert Hosemann, a Jackson lawyer, and
Phil Davis, a banker from Magee, finished first and second
respectively in a nine-candidate field, forcing a runoff on June
23. In the Democratic primary, Ronnie Shows, a regional
commissioner for the state transportation department, won a
majority in his campaign against two opponents.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Alabama gubernatorial race has been depicted by James'
strategists and by national leaders of the Christian conservative
movement as an important electoral test for the religious right.
</P>
<P>
   During the last 16 months, James has taken a number of
provocative stands aimed at returning religious expression to
public schools and courtrooms, a mission with substantial grass
roots support in this deeply devout, conservative and populist
state. In each instance, James has assailed the federal courts as
the mortal foe of God-fearing Alabamians, a tactic used by his
predecessor, George Wallace, when this state's deep-seated
resentment of federal intrusion was stoked more by race than by
religion.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has threatened to call out the National Guard to
defend the right of a state judge in Gadsden, Ala., to display the
Ten Commandments on his courtroom wall. He also has waged an
aggressive campaign to defend a 1993 state law that permitted
voluntary, student-led prayer in the schools. A federal judge
rejected the law as unconstitutional, leading James to assert that
the Bill of Rights does not apply to the states and that state
officials need not obey Supreme Court rulings when they believe
that the high court has overstepped its authority.
</P>
<P>
   Those positions, and the perception that James has placed more
emphasis on school prayer than on economic development and
education, quickly alienated some of the state's business leaders,
who rallied around the candidacy of Blount, a longtime Republican
activist who owns car dealerships and other companies. Blount,
whose father was postmaster general in the Nixon administration,
finished third in the 1994 gubernatorial primary.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Blount has attacked James for raising taxes
during his first term as governor, and for profiting from a
family-owned landfill that does business with the state. All of the
state's major newspapers endorsed Blount, and his strategists hoped
that Hunt, a Primitive Baptist preacher, would siphon Christian
conservative votes from James.
</P>
<P>
   But Blount's momentum seemed to stall in the final week of the
campaign, as Alabamians focused on the race and moved toward James,
whose son, Forrest James III, was quoted in the Birmingham News
this week as describing his father as ``a God-fearing redneck.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last week of the race, James promoted his pledge not to
raise taxes, a promise that Blount rejected as irresponsible. And
James, who counts Ralph Reed, the former director of the Christian
Coalition, as a consultant, won endorsements from many of the
country's Christian conservative leaders, including Pat Robertson,
Jerry Falwell, Phyllis Schlafly, James Dobson and Donald Wildmon.
</P>
<P>
   One poll published on Sunday found that 56 percent of those who
believe the Bible is literally true said they would vote for James.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
