<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINER BULLPEN BLOWS ANOTHER ON PALMEIRO HOMER IN 10TH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Six years and several million dollars ago, the
Mariners had a bullpen that pitched to expectations. Those
relievers lacked talent, and everyone knew it.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Martinez remembers it well. Those Mariners were a 64-98,
last-place team.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a tough season,'' the M's designated hitter said
Tuesday, ``but this season is more frustrating. The way we have
lost so many games makes everyone get frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Shellshocked is more appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Palmeiro beat the Mariners with a home run for the second
day in a row, this one a two-run shot off Bobby Ayala in the bottom
of the 10th to hand the Baltimore Orioles and 46,724 fans a 9-8
victory at Camden Yards.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr.'s second home run of the game, leading off the
top of the 10th off former teammate Norm Charlton, had put the M's
in position to win. But, thanks to Palmeiro, the 8-7 lead lasted
about as long as Seattle's earlier 2-0 and 5-2 leads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I hit it pretty well,'' Palmeiro said. ``The ball
carries better in the day and the wind was blowing out. So all the
conditions were right.''
</P>
<P>
   He neglected to mention that Ayala, now 0-5 with a 7.57 ERA, was
pitching.
</P>
<P>
   The towering drive, coming after a Harold Baines single, sailed
over Griffey's head in center field, landing on the grass on the
other side of the fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got to the wall, I said, `Oh ...' and it wasn't for
Oriole,'' Griffey said. ``You can't put (what he said) it in a
newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala, as usual, said nothing.
</P>
<P>
   His fifth blown save is the team's 12th and the bullpen is on
pace for 34 blown saves this season, obliterating the 27 they
accumulated last season to tie for the major league lead.
</P>
<P>
   The latest one came after two other relievers _ Paul Spoljaric
and Heathcliff Slocumb _ held the Orioles hitless for four innings.
</P>
<P>
   But manager Lou Piniella stuck with his guns and brought in
Ayala to pitch the 10th. The resulting backfire sounded like a
cannon going off at nearby Fort McHenry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not getting myself upset, I'm really not,'' Piniella said.
``I'm not getting myself upset anymore because I'm the one who
suffers. I'm not getting upset.''
</P>
<P>
   The mood outside the manager's office was understandably
subdued. Second baseman Joey Cora realizes the direction his team
is headed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have won five of the six games on this road trip and
gotten back in the race,'' he said of the M's 3-3 Eastern showing.
``In all my years, I have never seen anything like this. We have
given away too many games and you don't win a division championship
this way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players expect to win. The front office expects us to win.
Our fans expect us to win. This isn't the late '80s or early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying anybody in particular is at fault, but you
can't be giving games away the way we have. When you get a team
down, keep it down and get out of town. But even when we win it's a
struggle. I don't think we've had a comfortable game all season.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been a couple of easy victories, but regardless how
many runs the Mariners offense can produce, too many times it isn't
enough. In 10 of their losses this season, the M's have put seven
runs or more on the board.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey hit his 20th and 21st home runs Tuesday and drove in
four runs. David Segui had three hits. Alex Rodriguez slugged his
21st home run in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle has hit a club-record 13 homers in its past three games,
scored 28 runs _ and lost twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This club goes out and plays hard every day,'' Piniella said.
``We battle our butts off but we just can't get the right things to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The right things were happening, if only for a while, in the
bullpen Tuesday. Spoljaric retired all seven batters he faced,
striking out four. Slocumb retired all five batters he faced,
striking out three.
</P>
<P>
   Then Piniella, armed with the lead in the 10th, called for his
closer. Ayala faced two batters. Game over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're shellshocked,'' pitcher Jeff Fassero said. ``How many
blown saves do we have? It's tough to swallow right now.''
</P>
<P>
   On a day the Mariners could have expected a solid effort from
their starting pitcher, left-hander Jamie Moyer was rocked for the
first time this season. He entered the game with a 2.98 earned run
average, but surrendered Cal Ripken's two-run homer in the second,
offsetting Rodriguez's two-run blast.
</P>
<P>
   The M's surged ahead 5-2 in the third on Griffey's three-run
homer, but Baltimore retaliated in the fourth, scoring four runs on
homers by B.J. Surhoff and Brady Anderson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 0109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
