 (Subs for updating, re-editing throughout) 
CONSERVATIVE EX-LAWMAKER WINS IOWA GOP PRIMARY  (sw) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jim Ross Lightfoot, the most conservative of three Republicans
seeking to succeed Gov. Terry Branstad of Iowa, easily won his
party's nomination in Tuesday's primary. State Sen. Tom Vilsack,
the more liberal of two Democrats, won that party's primary.
</P>
<P>
   Branstad, the nation's longest-serving governor, is retiring
after four terms. The primary races were closely watched as a
barometer of the strength of each party's factions in Iowa, which
will be an early weeder of White House hopefuls in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Lightfoot carried about 70 percent of the Republican vote in a
three-candidate field. Vilsack won about 51 percent of that party's
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Vilsack, 47, attributed his victory to his emphasis on ``working
families.'' He stuck to the traditional liberal stands of Iowa
Democrats and won the endorsement of labor unions and other
Democratic interest groups. His opponent, Mark McCormick, a former
justice of the State Supreme Court, ran as a centrist and argued
that the party needed to broaden its appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Lightfoot, 59, a former congressman and farm broadcaster, beat
David Oman, a cable television executive, and Paul Pate, the Iowa
secretary of state. Lightfoot, long considered the front-runner,
had been courted by three possible Republican candidates for
president _ Steve Forbes, Jack Kemp and Dan Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   Lightfoot told his supporters on Tuesday night, ``We are ready
to work together in a unified effort to make Iowa the best
neighborhood in America by cutting taxes, improving schools and
winning the fight against crime and drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have not held the governor's mansion in Iowa for 30
years, and analysts said the Republicans once again go into the
fall with big advantages, including Branstad's continuing
popularity. The analysts said they expect Lightfoot to benefit from
the momentum of his big victory, and from the statewide name
recognition he built up during an unsuccessful bid for U.S. Senate
in 1996. Also, redistricting during his 12 years in Congress meant
that as one of Iowa's five House members, he represented 44 of the
state's 99 counties at one time or another. Both Democrats, by
contrast, were unknown even to some activists in their own party.
</P>
<P>
   J. Ann Selzer, the director of the Iowa Poll, said Lightfoot had
appealed to ``the heart of the party'' during the primary contest.
``He's going to have to change his style and adjust his message,
but he understands that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lightfoot, who won the endorsement of Iowa Right to Life, aired
a television commercial last month in which his late mother
described how she had adopted him from an orphanage as an infant.
</P>
<P>
   The other two candidates argued that Lightfoot's proposal for
reducing state income tax rates was too steep and could lead to
drastic cuts in education. Each proposed his own, more moderate
cut.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic race was more bitterly fought. Each candidate ran
television advertisements criticizing the other's legal clients.
Vilsack said that his opponent would ``give new tax breaks to
corporate real estate,'' while McCormick said his opponent
``represented banks on farm foreclosures during the farm crisis.''
Vilsack replied that in most cases, he had been on the side of
farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The five candidates spent nearly $4 million among them.
Lightfoot raised more than $1 million, compared with $710,000 for
Oman and $580,000 for Pate. On the Democratic side, McCormick had a
slight financial edge, with $780,000 in contributions and loans, to
Mr. Vilsack's $690,000.
</P>
<P>
   In the Democratic primary for governor in New Mexico, Martin
Chavez, a former mayor of Albuquerque, topped a field of six to win
a spot on November's ballot against the first-term incumbent
Republican, Gov. Gary Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez, 47, said his fall campaign will focus on education,
including his plans for smaller class sizes, better teacher pay and
full-day kindergarten. ``I don't know if New Mexicans want less
government, but they want their government to work properly,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Two House races in New Mexico drew national attention. In one,
State Attorney General Tom Udall, a nephew of the former longtime
congressman Morris Udall, won a chance to bring the Udall name back
to Washington in the Democrat primary for the congressional seat
held by Rep. Bill Redmond, a Republican freshman. Mark Udall, a son
of the congressman, is running for a House seat in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   In another House race, for the seat of the late Rep. Steven
Schiff, a five-term Republican who died in March, the primary
winners were Heather Wilson on the Republican side and State Sen.
Phil Maloof on the Democratic side. In a preview of the November
race, the two already were slated to face off in a special election
on June 23 to fill out Schiff's term.
</P>
<P>
   In South Dakota, a member of the executive committee of the
Republican National Committee won a spot on the November ballot
against Sen. Tom Daschle, the Democratic leader, who was unopposed
for his party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican winner was Ronald Schmidt, 60, a lawyer from
Pierre. He said he stands for less government and lower taxes, and
plans to portray Daschle as being too focused on national causes.
Schmidt beat Alan Aker, a logging contractor, and John Sanders, a
businessman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
