<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1507 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CA-PROPS-LADN     06-03 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CA-PROPS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEASURE TO OVERHAUL BILINGUAL EDUCATION WINS EASILY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
(Daily News Staff Writer Rick Orlov contributed to this report.) 
BY DAVID R. BAKER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Proposition 227, which would end a quarter-century
experiment with bilingual education in California public schools,
easily won passage with overwhelming voter support.
</P>
<P>
   But even before the votes were counted Tuesday, opponents
prepared to mount a legal challenge to block it in the courts.
</P>
<P>
   The English for the Children initiative would give non-English
speakers a year of intensive language instruction before placing
them in regular classes with some exceptions allowed. About 1.4
million California children have limited English skills.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide initiatives were all leading with the exception of a
measure affecting state contracting.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Proposition 227 said the measure was needed to
salvage the education of children who aren't learning English
quickly enough, spending years in Spanish-language classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If our initiative passes tonight, and it looks like it will,
it will be a tremendous victory for the people of California and
all of California's immigrant children,'' said Silicon Valley
entrepreneur Ron Unz, who drafted the initiative. ``They are the
ones who will benefit the most.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure faced broad opposition from educators for taking
away the ability of individual school districts to decide how to
educate children with limited English skills. Opponents also
complained it could damage such kids by throwing them into
English-only classes before they understood the language.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bad idea for all limited-English students,'' said Laura
Ferreiro, spokeswoman for the Mexican American Legal Defense and
Educational Fund. ``It would eliminate all flexibility that schools
have to teach these kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Another hotly debated statewide measure, Proposition 226, was
caught in a virtual dead heat. Voters appeared divided over the
proposal to require labor unions to have written permission from
their members before spending dues on political causes.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 223, which would limit spending on administrative
costs in schools, was too close to call. The 95/5 measure would
impose a financial penalty on California public school districts
that do not limit their central administrative costs to a maximum
of 5 percent of their total district budget.
</P>
<P>
   Like earlier statewide initiatives that focused on immigration
and other racially or ethnically sensitive issues, the drive to
modify bilingual education provoked strong emotions among backers
and opponents.
</P>
<P>
   But support for the initiative did not follow strict ethnic
lines with many Latino parents strongly supporting the measure in
polls.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 227 still might face the same legal hurdles that
have tripped up other hotly contested ballot measures. Several
groups, including United Teachers Los Angeles and the Mexican
American Legal Defense and Educational Fund, are considering legal
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Organized labor mounted a vigorous campaign against Proposition
226, fearful that it would undercut the political vitality of
unions by hamstringing their political spending.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans, led by Gov. Pete Wilson, described it as a
matter of fairness, to guarantee that no worker represented by a
union would have a portion of his or her earnings deducted and
spent for political purposes against the wishes of the employee.
</P>
<P>
   Organized labor, and the Democrats it often supports, blasted
the proposition as a way to destroy their ability to raise funds.
The measure's backers, they said, want to muzzle the political
voice of workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are not interested in the slightest in protecting
workers' paychecks -- they're interested in taking labor out of the
picture,'' said Steve Blazak, communications director for United
Teachers Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In a demonstration of just how seriously UTLA took the threat,
Blazak said the organization had been forced to spend on
Proposition 226 most of the money it otherwise would have spent
fighting the bilingual education initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the monster at the gates,'' Blazak said.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the fight over spending on administrative costs by
school districts had drawn relatively little public attention. But
Proposition 223, which would force many districts to sharply rein
in their outlays for administrative functions, has alarmed many
school district officials and leaders who see it as a financial
nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents expressed worry that the measure, created by UTLA to
target the Los Angeles Unified School District, would seriously
damage small school districts, which contend that they already have
relatively few administrators and therefore would be hard-pressed
to make cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a local battle UTLA was having with their own district,
and unfortunately, it applies to everyone in the state,'' said
Wayne Johnson, campaign consultant for Parents, Teachers and
Educators for Local Control, a group opposing the measure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
