</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-GEORGE-KARL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER SONICS COACH CELEBRATES `GREAT RUN' WITH FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first thing George Karl asked for was a cold bottle of Coors
Light. His second request was for closure.
</P>
<P>
   Karl, appearing carefree and somewhat content, hosted a party at
Floyd's Place Tuesday night. Between gulps, Karl jibed with media
and captivated a capacity crowd of fans.
</P>
<P>
   If it was Karl's intention to show that being labeled a ``former
Sonic coach'' hasn't worn on him, he played the part well.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I want to do is clear it up, get it over with and close,''
Karl said with an euphoric grin. ``I want to celebrate a good
run.''
</P>
<P>
   Karl entertained reporters for the first time since the Sonics'
playoff run ended May 12. He sat on a stool in a private section of
Floyd's Place with a pool table directly in front of him. Just 15
feet away was the occasional roar of fans, who came to pay tribute.
</P>
<P>
   Karl was forthright, witty and cheeky _ all the reasons Sonic
president Wally Walker cited last week while announcing the team
would not rehire Karl as coach.
</P>
<P>
   Walker had intimated that Karl was the source of many ``leaks''
within the organization. But Karl said hardly a bad word about
Walker.
</P>
<P>
   Given a chance to guess who will succeed him as Sonics coach,
Karl rolled off the name of Sonic legend Lenny Wilkens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lenny Wilkens has a Wally Walker feel to me,'' Karl said in
speculating about the Atlanta Hawks coach, who has four years left
on his current contract.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, Karl and Walker were toxic toward the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime a relationship breaks down, it's a 50-50 thing,'' said
Karl, refusing to get specific. `` ... I have trouble with (blaming
me). I have to be honest with myself. I know that's gotten me in
trouble at times. But it's also earned me respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Karl won 72 percent of his regular-season games as Sonic coach.
But he had one Finals appearance, two first-round exits and two
second-round losses in seven postseason appearances with the
Sonics. Plus, his ``foibles'' drove Walker crazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt pressure all year long. I felt if we went on a
five-game losing streak, we would get fired,'' Karl said. `` ...
Once we finished the season, the best business option for me was to
become a free agent anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was clear that (Walker) and I couldn't continue. (Team
owner) Barry Ackerley decided on Wally, and I respect that. It's
time to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Although at no time did Karl seem bitter, he responded with a
simple ``no'' when asked if he could accept Walker's reason for
letting him go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was funny when he said it wasn't personal,'' Karl
said later with a little prodding. ``Then he tried to divide the
team and me.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker made strong overtures about Karl's system wearing thin in
the playoffs. Walker questioned whether the trapping and pressure
defense could produce a title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love my system,'' Karl said. ``I see teams stealing from us.
Pressure defense ... that wins everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Where Karl will wind up is anyone's guess. He has permission to
talk with the Denver Nuggets and Los Angeles Clippers, but Karl has
yet to do so. Other teams interested in Karl must get permission
from the Sonics, since Karl remains under contract until July 1.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Karl seems resigned to wait. He will play golf, hang
out and enjoy himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a sad time,'' Karl said. ``I've had a great run.
I'm juiced about coaching ... and I've got one more run in me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
