<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CA-GOVRACE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS ESCAPES DEMOCRATIC PACK TO FACE LUNGREN IN NOVEMBER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY PAUL HEFNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Rejecting a well-heeled airline executive and a
three-term congresswoman, Democratic voters _ aided by an unknown
number of crossover Republican votes in the open primary _ picked
party stalwart Lt. Gov. Gray Davis to take on GOP Attorney General
Dan Lungren in the fall campaign for governor.
</P>
<P>
   Once written off for lacking the campaign cash to keep pace with
Northwest Airlines executive Al Checchi or Rep. Jane Harman,
D-Torrance, Davis apparently won voters over with the slogan
``experience money can't buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis grabbed a sizable lead that grew into a landslide as more
votes were counted, with Checchi falling to a distant second and
Harman trailing in third place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The name `open primary' is really fitting,'' Davis said in a
victory speech at the Biltmore Hotel in Los Angeles. ``You've
opened your hearts and you've opened your minds to me and I will be
eternally grateful.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side of the primary, Lungren breezed ahead of
four minor candidates. In a speech to supporters in Newport Beach,
Lungren said his campaign would press for school choice for
parents, cutting the crime rate and reduction of the state's car
tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a huge surplus in the state of California right now,''
Lungren said. ``I define a surplus as the government taking more
money from hard-working taxpayers than (it) should have. Some
portion of that should be returned to the rightful owners, the
people of the state of California.''
</P>
<P>
   Lungren also said Tuesday's results were a strong signal against
campaigns centered around 30-second television spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like virtual campaigning is not the campaigning of
the future for the state of California,'' he said. ``People want to
see their candidates, they want to hear from their candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said his top priority would be improvement of the state's
public schools, but he also touched on fighting crime, keeping
California's economy humming and protecting the environment.
</P>
<P>
   And he harkened back to the days before Republicans took over
the governor's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time has come to put an end to 16 years of stagnation,''
Davis said. ``It's time for us to move again, time for us to grow
again and time for us to aspire to do great things again.''
</P>
<P>
   Harman conceded defeat Tuesday night and pledged to help Davis
in his effort to defeat Lungren.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning is more fun, but losing with honor ain't bad,'' Harman
told supporters. ``We ran a positive campaign, the only kind I have
ever run. We addressed the critical issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Partisan spin doctors were already giving their candidates the
edge in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to win,'' said Mike Madrid, political director for
the California Republican Party. ``Gray Davis is one of the last
liberal lions in California. It's basically a choice between Dan
Lungren and a Jerry Brown. That's the kind of contrast we want.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats said they believe Lungren is vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lungren has the six troubles,'' said Bob Mulholland, a
political adviser for the Democratic Party. ``Choice, education,
the environment, tobacco, assault weapons and Saturday night
specials. He's wrong on all those issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulholland also said that Democrats would focus on education in
the fall campaign, and blame 16 years of Republican governorship
for the disrepair of California's public schools.
</P>
<P>
   But Madrid countered that Republicans back charter schools and
other reform measures popular with parents _ and opposed by
teachers unions that support Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   And Lungren wins with voters with his tough-on-crime approach,
Madrid said. ``Dan Lungren owns the crime issue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren enjoyed a free ride in the primary, facing only token
GOP opposition and assured of his party's nomination at the outset
of the campaign. He began advertising early _ due to uncertainty
over the new blanket primary, and because of appeals to
conservatives by some Democrats _ but Lungren emerged unscathed
compared to the Democratic nominee.
</P>
<P>
   In the bruising three-way Democratic primary, Davis, 55,
campaigned on his experience in California politics.
</P>
<P>
   One of his television ads lifted a line from a San Francisco Bay
Area newspaper which called him ``perhaps the best-trained
governor-in-waiting the state ever produced.''
</P>
<P>
   A Vietnam-era Army officer, the New York-born Davis was chief of
staff to Gov. Jerry Brown from 1974 to 1981.
</P>
<P>
   He then moved to the state Legislature, spending two terms in
the Assembly before winning his first statewide race in 1986 as
controller. He held that post until his election to the lieutenant
governor's job in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But some experts credited missteps by Davis's primary opponents
for his success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until now, Davis has risen not because he has run a
particularly skilled campaign, but because Harman and Checchi have
blundered from one mistake to another,'' said Republican campaign
strategist Dan Schnur.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
