</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS CAN GET NO RELIEF IN LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 THROUGH-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARC J. SPEARS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On the night the Randy Johnson rumors finally
ended, the facts remained clear. The Dodgers need help in their
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, after learning that Johnson was staying in
Seattle, the Dodgers dropped their fourth straight when reliever
Jim Bruske allowed a two-out, three-run homer to Brian Jordan in
the eighth inning of a 7-4 loss to the Mark McGwire-less St. Louis
Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was the first batter Bruske faced after replacing Darren
Dreifort, the pitcher the Dodgers refused to send to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   On the third pitch, Jordan made the crowd of Dodger Stadium
crowd of 36,367 forget McGwire, the major-league home run leader
(27), who will miss the series with back spasms.
</P>
<P>
   He also reminded the Dodgers (27-30) that they are getting no
relief from their bullpen. Over the weekend closer Scott Radinsky
blew two save attempts against the Cincinnati Reds. And the club
will not be getting Baltimore reliever Armando Benitez, whose name
was mentioned in a trade for deposed Dodger Hideo Nomo.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we (still) need is subjective,'' Dodgers executive vice
president Fred Claire said. ``We haven't settled down after
everything that happened. I believe in this club.'
</P>
<P>
   For Jordan, who leads the National League in hitting (.378), it
was his first homer since May 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Jordan) was sitting on a curveball and he got one,'' said
Bruske, who has appeared in a team-high 25 games. ``(The bullpen
is) struggling a little right now, but we haven't lost our
confidence.'
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers blew a 4-0 lead that was built by three of the four
ex-Marlins who were acquired in a May 15 blockbuster trade. The
Dodgers are just 8-8 since making the move.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Bonilla, dropped from cleanup to the sixth spot after
batting just .237 in his first 15 games with the Dodgers, gave the
club a 1-0 lead with an RBI single in the second.
</P>
<P>
   An out later, Charles Johnson made it 3-0 when he hit a two-run
homer into the left-field seats on a 1-2 pitch from St. Louis
starter Kent Mercker. Johnson, who had a career-high 19 homers last
season, hit his third in the past four games and now has 10 this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield, who has 11 RBI since joining the Dodgers, made
it 4-0 on a sacrifice fly in the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   But that was not enough for Dreifort, who said he was not
affected by the trade talks that involved him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those things happen upstairs, not down here,' Dreifort said.
``It is not like I've been thinking, `God if I pitch good I'm going
to Seattle, or if I pitch bad I'm going to Seattle.' It really
hasn't bothered me at all.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis was another matter.
</P>
<P>
   In the first four innings, Dreifort (3-5) got out of two jams
and showed why the Dodgers front office refused to make him a
Mariner. But the former reliever, who came in with a three-game
winning streak, struggled in the middle innings as he did earlier
this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals scored four runs in the fifth to tie the game.
Despite striking out a career-high eight batters in 72/3 innings,
Dreifort walked six and allowed six runs and nine hits.
</P>
<P>
   Mercker (7-2), who threw a no-hitter at Dodger Stadium with the
Atlanta Braves in 1993, recovered from his early problems, pitched
seven innings and did not allow a run after the third..
</P>
<P>
   ``I pitched (badly),'' Dreifort said. ``I walked six and how
many of them scored (three)? I made bad pitches and I failed to
make my adjustments.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
