<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 02:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1518 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RANDY-JOHNSON-SPI     06-03 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANDY-JOHNSON-SPI </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ The Seattle Mariners last night ended 10 days of
Randy Johnson trade rumors with a surprise _ by vowing not to trade
him. But the baseball team wouldn't comment on whether trade or
contract talks regarding their star pitcher might resurface before
the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy Johnson is a valued member of the Mariners who is under
contract for the balance of the 1998 season,'' M's President Chuck
Armstrong said in a statement issued after yesterday's 9-8 loss to
the Orioles here. ``Randy will pitch for the Mariners throughout
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Accordingly, we have no plans to trade Randy Johnson. The club
will have no further comment on Randy's status with the club.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if those ``plans'' could change, Armstrong said: ``I'm not
going to engage in further talk. The statement speaks for itself
and I have no further comment. That's all we're saying.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong also refused to comment on whether ownership would
reverse the decision it made last November and offer the winningest
pitcher in franchise history a contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who will be 35 on Sept. 10, is in the option year of a
four-year, $24 million contract and eligible for free agency at the
end of the season. He is due to start tonight at the Kingdome when
the M's open a two-game series against the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Although Armstrong called reports of trade talks
``unsubstantiated rumors'' in the opening line of his statement,
Los Angeles Dodgers officials acknowledged the team had given the
Mariners a final trade proposal yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers offered right-handed pitcher Ismael Valdes and
infielder-outfielder Wilton Guerrero for Johnson, who repeatedly
has asked to be traded since the M's refused to offer a contract
extension in November.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners originally asked the Dodgers for right-hander
Darren Dreifort, but the Dodgers refused and countered with Valdes,
agreeing to include either outfielders Todd Hollandsworth, Roger
Cedeno or Guerrero in the swap.
</P>
<P>
   The National League club finally settled on Valdes and Guerrero,
giving the Mariners a noon deadline yesterday to consummate the
trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had come to the decision that this had dragged on too
long,'' said Dodgers general manager Fred Claire. ... ``I told him
to call me back before 4 p.m. if he had any further thoughts. He
called me and said they were not going to trade Randy Johnson.''
</P>
<P>
   A source close to the Mariners said the organization was divided
on the proposal and that team ownership, fearing a public relations
nightmare, nixed the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was heading back to Seattle on the team's charter flight
last night when the M's made their announcement. But his agent,
Barry Meister, said he was disappointed that the deal with the
Dodgers collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, at this point, it's the right time for Randy to move
on,'' said Meister from his Chicago-area home. ``I would just like
to say the media and all of the other parties involved could have
handled this situation with a lot more dignity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way it played out showed very little regard for Randy and
his family. Through no doing of his own, he has been the subject of
a lot of rumors that were unsubstantiated.
</P>
<P>
   ``No person should be forced to go through what Randy has gone
through the past 10 days. The whole process has been difficult for
him. ... They could have put an end to this long ago instead of
having him twist in the wind.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if Johnson would be willing to listen to a contract
extension offer, Meister said, ``I haven't even spoken to him about
that, but I think Randy's feelings on that subject are well
documented.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has said it would be difficult, if not impossible, to
put everything behind him and extend his career with the Mariners
to a 10th season.
</P>
<P>
   He was acquired from the Montreal Expos in 1989, along with
pitchers Gene Harris and Brian Holman, for pitchers Mark Langston
and Mike Campbell. The deal is regarded as the best trade in
Mariners history.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, nicknamed ``The Big Unit'' because of his 6-foot-10
frame, developed into the most dominating major-league pitcher this
decade.
</P>
<P>
   His 105-44 record from 1991 to 1997 is the best among active
pitchers; he led the American League in strikeouts four consecutive
seasons (1993-96); won the AL Cy Young Award in 1995, finishing
second in '93 and '97; entered this season with more strikeouts
(1,845) than any active pitcher; pitched the franchise's first
no-hitter (1990); and struck out 19 batters twice last season.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, this has been his worst season in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, admittedly distracted by the trade talks that began six
months ago and lasted into spring training, is 5-3 with a 5.47
earned run average.
</P>
<P>
   He won his last two starts, striking out 27 Tampa Bay Devil Ray
batters in 17 innings, demonstrating the emotion that helped
generate his success.
</P>
<P>
   Will that change now that he hasn't been traded?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Randy's job is to get prepared to pitch every fifth
day and everything else will take care of itself,'' Meister said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
