<HEADER>
A1741 &Cx1f; tab-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPECIALS-BUDGET-NYTSF     06-03 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPECIALS-BUDGET-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No 388 - JUNE 3, 1998  
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. HARRISON FORD : STARDOM WITH A SHRUG Harrison Ford can justly
claim to be the most popular movie star in the world, with more
than $2 billion in tickets sold. But in his latest film, Ford steps
away from his recent string of action-hero performances for a
romantic comedy/drama opposite Anne Heche - ``Six Days, Seven
Nights.'' Ford talks about the new movie, why he found it no
problem to be playing a romantic lead opposite one of Hollywood's
highest-profile lesbians, why he doesn't plan to ``stretch'' into
more atypical roles and why he expects to reappear as Jack Ryan and
Indiana Jones, but is just as happy not to be involved in the new
``Star Wars'' films. By Cindy Pearlman. 1,400 words + photo. 
____________________________________________________________________
____
</P>
<P>
   2. JIM CARREY : A WILD MAN'S WALK ON THE SERIOUS SIDE Jim
Carrey's newest film, ``The Truman Show,'' is at once a typical,
eye-bulging Carrey special and something much more profound.
Directed by Australian visionary Peter Weir, it's the offbeat saga
of a man who learns that his whole world has been an artificial set
for a television show about him. Carrey talks about the new film,
the challenge of working with an internationally respected director
such as Weir, the art of balancing his madcap persona with his own
desire to stretch as an actor and why he himself often feels
imprisoned within a television program. By David Kronke. From
Canadian TV Guide. 1,300 words + photo. 
____________________________________________________________________
____
</P>
<P>
   3. PETER WEIR : A ONE-OF-A-KIND DIRECTOR STEERS
</P>
<P>
   ``THE TRUMAN SHOW.'' Peter Weir may not be the world's richest
film director, but many observers think he is its most interesting
one. In films from ``Picnic at Hanging Rock'' (1975) and
``Witness'' (1985) to ``Dead Poets Society'' (1989) and his latest,
``The Truman Show,'' the Australian-born director has proven
himself a world-class master. Weir talks about the new movie, the
challenge of controlling zany star Jim Carrey, why he thinks film
directors are like mountain climbers and why he doesn't really care
if his film is a hit. By Ian Spelling. 1,400 words + photo. 
____________________________________________________________________
____
</P>
<P>
   4. THE MAGIC WORDS Magic Johnson ruled the basketball court for
more than a decade. Now, with the June 8 launch of his TV show
``The Magic Hour,'' he's trying to capture the talk-show world as
well. Johnson talks about the show, his struggles to master the art
of the talk show, how new drugs have enabled him to get the upper
hand in his battle with AIDS and why the quintessential talk-show
guest thinks he may be just as good a host. By Frank Sanello. 1,400
words + photo. 
____________________________________________________________________
____
</P>
<P>
   5. THE THINKING MOVIEGOER'S GUIDE TO SUMMER MADNESS Ivor Davis
offers a thinking moviegoer's guide to summer -- a dozen films that
might stand out from the crowd this summer, plus a sidebar on
movies for children. 1,300 words + photos. (Not available Great
Britain and Australia.) 
____________________________________________________________________
____
</P>
<P>
   6. SANDRA BULLOCK KEEPS ``HOPE'' ALIVE It was the big action hit
``Speed'' that made Sandra Bullock a star, and the big action dud
``Speed 2 : Cruise Control'' that almost derailed her career. Now
she is looking for a hit in ``Hope Floats,'' a throw-back to the
lush, romantic women's films of old Hollywood. Bullock plays an
aging beauty queen who, when her marriage crumbles, returns to her
small Texas hometown and her larger-than-life mother, searching for
happiness. ``It's definitely a woman's piece,'' Bullock agrees. ``A
lot of men have a strong reaction to it one way or another. I was
so scared about that at first, but then again, when they're making
``Godzilla,'' do you think they're thinking about the women?
........'' By concentrating on work she deems vital to her own
happiness, Bullock has been able to weather the inevitable storms.
By Joshua Mooney. BPI Entertainment News Wire. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
LIVING TO THE BEAT ``The Last Days of Disco,'' the latest film by
writer-director Whit Stillman, finds its lifeblood in the disco
beat. Set during the early 1980s, it tells the stories of recent
college graduates and other young New Yorkers trying to make their
way in the city as disco was waning not only as popular music, but
as a way of life. Although its disco rhythm is important to this
film, Stillman believes the central story of people trying to find
personal and professional happiness in the big city ``could have
taken place any time in the last 50 years.'' By Renee Graham. From
The Boston Globe. 1,400 words.
</P>
</TEXT>
