<SLUG> BC-CPT-GATEWAY29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;    Gateway to offer browser choice
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In a move seen as loosening Microsoft Corp.'s
grip on the major computer makers, Gateway Inc. said recently that
it will include competing Internet browsers on desktop computers
with Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   PCs shipped to consumers in June will include Netscape Navigator
in addition to Microsoft's Internet Explorer 4.0, Gateway chief
executive Ted Waitt told reporters in New York.
</P>
<P>
   That will make it far more convenient to choose Netscape
Communications Corp.'s browser over Microsoft Corp.'s version than
is currently available among any of the major PC makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as we know, we are the only PC maker that has made it
as easy as possible'' to choose the browser, Waitt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have worked with Microsoft and they have allowed us to do
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Gateway and Microsoft officials said they reached their
agreement recently but declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's bundling its Internet browser with its Windows
operating system is a major point of the recent antitrust lawsuits
filed against Microsoft last week by the U.S. Department of Justice
and 20 states.
</P>
<P>
   They charge that Microsoft uses its monopoly of the operating
system to steer computer users to its browser at the expense of
Netscape's browser.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft says the browser is integral to the operating system
and that blocking such steps will slow innovation on the computer
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Gateway will sell Windows 98 computers for June shipment that
enable users to click on its Internet service icon and immediately
be sent to another screen, designed by Gateway, that gives them a
choice of Internet access and browser.
</P>
<P>
   Users must choose Gateway's Internet access service to use
Netscape's browser.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, people who clicked on the Microsoft Internet access
icon were sent to Microsoft's own online service. Those who
preferred Netscape had to load it separately themselves or have
Gateway do it. Microsoft would not say whether the negotiations
with Gateway were spurred by the antitrust suits.
</P>
<P>
   Gateway officials recently said the company wanted more
flexibility on the browser issue in a deposition taken as part of
the Justice Department's case against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The comments by Gateway executive Rick Brownrigg were included
in the Justice Department's motion that sought a preliminary
injunction preventing release of Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   With 1997 revenues of $6.3 billion, Gateway is the
second-biggest direct seller of computers behind Dell Computer
Corp., whose revenues were $12.7 billion in the latest fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Dell said the company has no plans to change its
browser offering.
</P>
<P>
   Because Internet Explorer is bundled in the Windows operating
system, it is the default browser for the vast majority of
computers shipped by Dell. Dell's policy has been to add Netscape's
browser only for customers who request it.
</P>
<P>
   The cost is $66 extra for the software and $15 to load it during
the assembly process, said Dell spokesman T.R. Reid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers typically do not specify the type of browser they
want,'' Reid said.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq Computer Corp.'s computers feature Internet Explorer
exclusively unless a customer or reseller requests otherwise.
Presario models sold by Radio Shack have both browsers loaded at
the factory.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Mahoney writes for the Austin American-Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-28-98 1752EDT &QL;
</P>
