 &HT;    Q &AMP; A on the news
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Start-date of the Vietnam war?
</P>
<P>
   Q: After reading about the Supreme Court's decision that Ellis
Island belongs to New Jersey and not New York, I looked at a map
and noticed that the Statue of Liberty appears to be at least a
half-mile inside New Jersey. Has New Jersey ever made a claim to
Miss Liberty also?
</P>
<P>
   A: No claim is necessary. There's no disputing that Liberty
Island and the Statue of Liberty are in New Jersey waters outside
New York harbor. But most people _ and guidebooks _ include them as
attractions of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the dates for next year's Chelsea Flower Show in
England? Where can I get information about tickets and travel
packages?
</P>
<P>
   A: Dates for 1999: May 25-28. The show is restricted to members
of the Royal Horticultural Society the first three days, and is
open to the public only on the last day, said Gillian Cooper of the
British Consulate. So she recommends joining the society for a
modest fee, which allows you to attend any of the days. For
information about joining, and a membership application, write:
Shows Department, Royal Horticultural Society, Vincent Square,
London SW1P 2PE, England. Information: 011-44-171-834-4333.
</P>
<P>
   The British Tourist Authority in New York says several tour
operators routinely offer travel packages that include tickets to
the show, if you don't want to join the horticultural society.
Information can be obtained from travel agents. For general tourism
information on Britain, including the Chelsea Flower Show, call
1-800-462-2748 or, on the Internet, check this address:
www//visitbritain.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: Other than the United Kingdom and Japan, in what countries do
people drive on the left side of the road?
</P>
<P>
   A: The American Automobile Association reports the following
worldwide: Antigua, Australia, Bahamas, Barbados, Bermuda, Bhutan,
Botswana, Brunei, Cayman Islands, Channel Islands, Cyprus,
Dominica, Fiji, Grenada, Guyana, Hong Kong, India, Indonesia,
Ireland, Jamaica, Kenya, Lesotho, Macao, Malawi, Malaysia, Malta,
Mauritius, Montserrat, Mozambique, Namibia, Nepal, New Zealand,
Pakistan, Papua-New Guinea, Peninsular Malaysia, Seychelles,
Singapore, South Africa, Sri Lanka, St. Christopher, Nevis &AMP;
Anguilla, St. Lucia, St. Vincent, Surinam, Swaziland, Tanzania,
Thailand, Trinidad &AMP; Tobago, Uganda, the Virgin Islands, Zambia and
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is the new artificial sweetener sucralose available in
stores?
</P>
<P>
   A: You may have to wait awhile for the no-calorie sweetener,
which recently was approved by the Food and Drug Administration, to
become available. McNeil Specialty Products, a division of Johnson
&AMP; Johnson, which will market sucralose, says the product will be
rolled out over the next two years. It will be available as a table
sweetener, and will be added to processed foods. It has been
approved for use in beverages, dairy products, desserts, chewing
gum, puddings, jams and jellies, and sauces and syrups, among other
products. Information: 1-800-777-5363 or, on the Internet:
www.sucralose.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: NBC has canceled ``Union Square,'' but a recent article
listed it as the seventh-highest-rated program in the Nielsen
ratings for the season. Why was it canceled?
</P>
<P>
   A: The NBC sitcom ``Union Square'' played between ``Friends''
and ``Seinfeld,'' thus seeming to guarantee it a huge potential
audience. But it regularly lost a lot of ``Friends'' viewers, which
is a bad sign. Also, it generated no positive word of mouth and was
considered a creative disappointment by the network. So out it
went.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I once read about a particular type of berry British pilots
ate during World War II to improve their night vision during night
flying missions . Do you know anything about it?
</P>
<P>
   A: You're referring to bilberry (Vaccinium myrtiullus) which, on
the basis of folk beliefs, was consumed in the form of jam by Royal
Air Force pilots before flying off into the night. They had
discovered, as you say, that bilberry improved their night vision
by helping the eyes adjust from light to darkness. After the war,
scientists investigated the claim and confirmed that the berries
and bilberry extract contained compounds known as anthocyanosides
that help maintain visual sensitivity. Subsequent clinical trials
confirmed that bilberry extract improves night vision in air
traffic controllers, pilots and automobile drivers, and also
reduces eye strain and fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   Another antioxidant that has been demonstrated to improve
circulation to the eyes, with a possible benefit to eyesight, is
ginkgo biloba. Other herbs and nutrients that may help vision
include lycopene (in tomatoes), grape seed extract and vitamins C
and E.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I vaguely recall a kidnapping case involving Frank Sinatra.
Will you refresh my memory?
</P>
<P>
   A: On Dec. 8, 1963, Frank Sinatra Jr., 19, was abducted from
Harrah's Casino at Lake Tahoe, Calif. He was released unharmed Dec.
11 after the elder Sinatra paid $240,000 in ransom. The FBI
announced Dec. 14 that it had arrested three men _ one of them
being the accused mastermind, Barry Keenan, a stock market player
who had become addicted to drugs and alcohol _ and had recovered
most of the ransom money. The defense team later argued that Frank
Jr. dreamed up the kidnapping as a publicity stunt to jump-start
his career; it also was rumored that the Mafia was involved. On
March 7, 1964, a federal court convicted the three and sentenced
them all to prison.
</P>
<P>
   It was reported in January that Columbia Pictures had snagged
the rights to ``Snatching Sinatra,'' an article recounting the
episode, with plans to make a movie about it.
</P>
<P>
   (END)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
