<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  EPA'S PLAN TO POST CHEMICAL RISKS ON  INTERNET RAISES SECURITY
WORRIES &HT;     By JULIA MALONE    c.1998 Cox News Service   WASHINGTON _ The
<TEXT>
Environmental Protection Agency is setting off security alarms with
plans to post details about the nation's hazardous chemical sites
on the Internet.
<P>
   The EPA is preparing to collect and make public information
about the ``worst-case'' potential disasters for some 66,000 U.S.
facilities that store dangerous chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosures are required by Clean Air Act amendments passed
in 1990 to alert people to dangers in their neighborhoods, ranging
from small propane gas distributors and chlorine tanks used for
water treatment to major chemical manufacturing plants and oil
refineries.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists hope the glare of publicity will lead to
greater attention to safety.
</P>
<P>
   However, the CIA and FBI have quietly expressed concerns that
the EPA's plan to use the Internet to distribute the information
would make it too accessible to criminals and terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also seems to conflict with a new White House focus on
terrorism. In a speech this month to the graduating class at the
U.S. Naval Academy, President Clinton focused on the threat and
outlined new measures to protect domestic facilities.
</P>
<P>
   James Makris, the EPA official who is overseeing the chemical
information program, said Thursday his agency is negotiating with
the security agencies, but that plans are proceeding to post some
form of data on the Internet next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very awkward problem for us,'' he acknowledged.
``It's pretty hard for someone to be worrying about terrorism and
agree to put out information.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that the EPA is urging disclosure because the
probability of a chemical accident is much higher than of a
terrorism incident. There are about 500 accidental releases of at
least small amounts of toxic substances each week.
</P>
<P>
   Makris said that his agency is working on an electronic method
to limit access to the most sensitive data, although he said that
computer hackers can eventually overcome such obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists have said that they plan to post the
information on the Internet if the government makes it public in
more limited ways. They also argue that the security concerns are
overstated.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no credible history of terrorist threats'' involving
chemicals, said Fred Millar, an environmental consultant and former
official of Friends of the Earth, who helped write the disclosure
law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's necessary to inform the public in order to get an
appropriate level of concern'' so that companies will ``reduce
their risks of accidents,'' Millar said.
</P>
<P>
   Security experts outside government raised questions about the
Internet posting, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's insane,'' said Damon Camp, associate professor of
criminal justice at Georgia State University. ``People who use the
Internet are anonymous. What would inhibit someone who is thinking
about dirty deeds?''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Baker, associate professor of international business law at
the University of Texas, agreed that a centralized source for
chemical storage information could encourage terrorists. ``Any
information that's more readily available will whet their
appetites,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Baker said that the government should proceed to post
the data, because otherwise ``we'd be living in fear'' of
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   (Samar Abulhassan of the Cox Newspapers Washington Bureau
contributed to this article.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
