<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEANUT-CHICKEN04-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Peanut-Crusted Chicken goes well with an outing
</P>
<P>
   By Reagan Walker
</P>
<P>
   C. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   This chicken crisps as it cools, which makes it ideal for
picnics. It's a favorite with the Junior League of Charlotte, N.C.,
which included it in its cookbook, Dining by Fireflies: The
Unexpected Pleasures of the New South (Delmar Printing and
Publishing, $21.95).
</P>
<P>
   PEANUT-CRUSTED CHICKEN
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings 2 cups dry-roasted peanuts, finely ground
</P>
<P>
   cup yellow cornmeal 5 large cloves garlic, minced 2 tablespoons
fresh ginger, minced 1 teaspoon ground black pepper 2 tablespoons
salt 3 cups all-purpose flour 2 cups buttermilk 8 chicken breast
halves
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Combine the ground peanuts,
cornmeal, garlic, ginger, pepper, salt and cup flour in medium
bowl. Place remaining flour and buttermilk in separate bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Dredge chicken in flour, dip in buttermilk and roll in peanut
mixture. Bake chicken, covered with foil, 15 minutes in greased,
shallow baking dish. Carefully remove foil and bake another 20-25
minutes or until chicken is golden brown.
</P>
<P>
   Remove chicken from baking dish and cool. Chicken will become
crisp as it cools.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving : 466 calories, 23 g fat, 97 mg
cholesterol, 714 mg sodium.
</P>
<P>
   A simple twist on a standard summer favorite -- potato salad.
This light approach comes from Fabulous Creations caterers. Sweet
Potato Salad With Cider Vinaigrette
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2pounds sweet potatoes, peeled and quartered lengthwise
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons olive oil, divided
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup thinly sliced green onions
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup diced red onion
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Place sweet potatoes in a
9-by-13-inch baking dish. Drizzle with 1 tablespoon olive oil; toss
to coat. Sprinkle potatoes with salt and pepper. Cover with
aluminum foil and bake 20 minutes. Uncover. Using a spatula, turn
potatoes and bake, uncovered, until tender and light brown, about
15 minutes more. Cool potatoes and cut into 1-inch pieces. Transfer
to a serving bowl. Sprinkle with green and red onions. Whisk
vinegar and remaining 1 tablespoon oil in a small bowl. Pour over
potatoes and onions and toss to coat. Serve at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 229 calories, 3 grams protein, 5 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 21), 43 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 18
milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Rafeedie's Catering offers this simple, crisp and tasty take on
bean salad. Perfect for a big family reunion. Beanie Bean Salad
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   1can (13 ounces) light kidney beans
</P>
<P>
   1can (13 ounces) black-eyed peas
</P>
<P>
   1can (13 ounces) chickpeas
</P>
<P>
   1can (13 ounces) white navy beans
</P>
<P>
   1/2pound fresh green beans
</P>
<P>
   2/3cup finely chopped red onions
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup finely chopped green onions
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons finely chopped garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup red bell pepper, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup yellow bell pepper, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1medium-size tomato, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons fresh cilantro leaves
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons finely chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Drain the kidney beans, black-eyed peas, chickpeas and white
navy beans and rinse with cold water. Blanch the fresh green beans
in lightly salted boiling water for 2 minutes. Drain and plunge the
beans into ice water to cool. Drain and add to the canned beans.
Add the red onions, green onions, garlic, red pepper, yellow
pepper, tomato, cilantro and parsley. Salt and pepper to taste. In
a small bowl, whisk the olive oil into the red wine vinegar. Add
more salt and pepper to taste, then add the dressing to the bean
mixture and toss.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 138 calories, 5 grams protein, 6 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 40), 17 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 5
milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   This salad from Fabulous Creations caterers is similar to an
antipasto, hearty and versatile. Serve it as is, stuff it into pita
pockets or toss with some pasta for a more complete meal.
</P>
<P>
   Sausage Salad
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 servings
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2pounds Kielbasa sausage, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1medium green bell pepper, julienned
</P>
<P>
   1/2medium red bell pepper, diced
</P>
<P>
   1bunch green onions, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1cup mild banana pepper rings
</P>
<P>
   1/2pound provolone cheese, sliced 1/8 inch thick and cut into
1/2-inch squares
</P>
<P>
   1/2pound sliced ham, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1medium white onion chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 cups Italian dressing
</P>
<P>
   Salt, pepper, garlic salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Mix the sausage, green pepper, red pepper, green onions, banana
pepper rings, cheese, ham, white onion and Italian dressing
together, then season with salt, pepper and garlic salt to taste.
Refrigerate for at least 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 705 calories, 27 grams protein, 62 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 75), 10 grams carbohydrates, 105
milligrams cholesterol, 2,133 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   This recipe is a cross between lemon bars and macaroons, an
absolutely divine marriage in our opinion. It came to us from
Events Catering. Lemon-Coconut Squares
</P>
<P>
   Makes 18 squares
</P>
<P>
   1cup plus 4 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup powdered sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup melted butter
</P>
<P>
   1cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   2eggs
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons grated lemon peel
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup shredded coconut
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350 degrees and grease an 8-by-11-inch
baking pan. Mix together 1 cup flour, the powdered sugar and the
melted butter in a bowl to form a soft dough. Press in the bottom
of the baking pan. Bake for 20 minutes. Remove from oven and allow
to cool at least 1 hour. In a medium mixing bowl, mix together 4
tablespoons flour, granulated sugar, baking powder, eggs, lemon
juice, lemon peel and coconut. Pour over cooled crust and bake for
25 minutes. Remove from oven and chill at least 1 hour. Sprinkle
lightly with powdered sugar before cutting and serving.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 140 calories, 2 grams protein, 6 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 41), 20 grams carbohydrates, 37 milligrams
cholesterol, 78 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   This fruity lemonade will quench your thirst and please the eye.
It will travel well in a thermos or Mason jar. Adults may add up to
2 cups of vodka. Strawberry-Watermelon Lemonade
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 8-ounce servings
</P>
<P>
   6pounds watermelon, seeded and cut in chunks
</P>
<P>
   2pints strawberries, washed and hulled
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   12ounces lemonade frozen concentrate, thawed
</P>
<P>
   3/4fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Puree watermelon in food processor in batches until smooth.
Strain through a sieve into a large bowl or gallon pitcher. Process
strawberries with sugar until smooth. Add strawberry puree,
lemonade concentrate and lemon juice to watermelon juice.
Refrigerate. -- From ``Dining by Fireflies: The Unexpected
Pleasures of The New South'' (Delmar Printing and Publishing,
$21.95)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 128 calories, 1 gram protein, no fat, 32 grams
carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 3 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Make it safe
</P>
<P>
   Here are some general food safety rules to keep in mind anytime
you're heading outdoors for a picnic:
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep hot foods hot, above 140 degrees to prevent food-borne
illness. You can retain heat by wrapping warm foods in aluminum
foil, then a towel, and nesting it snugly in a basket. Some
containers have heat-reflective linings. A thermos is good for hot
or cold liquids.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep cold foods cold. Use airtight containers and transport in
an insulated cooler with ice or ice packs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Put food out just before serving and store any leftovers
quickly. Foods should never be left out longer than two hours.
</P>
<P>
   _ Never partially precook chicken or burgers that you plan to
grill. If precooking is necessary, cook the food completely, chill
it and keep it cool until time to reheat on the grill.
</P>
<P>
   _ For maximum airflow, avoid overpacking coolers. Transport the
cooler in the back seat of the car instead of the trunk, where it
will warm up more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   _ Take garbage bags, paper towels and damp washcloths in
resealable plastic bags for cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
