</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DROUGHT04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Central Texans facing threat of 2nd drought in 3 years
 &HT;    By Pamela Coleman and Nichole Monroe
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ With no substantial rain since mid-March and a
rash of record-breaking heat, farmers and municipalities in Central
Texas are bracing for the possibility of a second drought in three
years.
</P>
<P>
   San Marcos city officials have imposed restrictions on water
use, and city leaders in Leander, Austin, Round Rock and elsewhere
in Texas are urging residents to voluntarily conserve water as the
area endured its third day of record high temperatures Monday, 6/1.
</P>
<P>
   Local farmers may be worst hit, however. Buoyed by high moisture
content in the soil early in the year, Williamson County growers
planted more corn and grain sorghum than ever, only to see hopes
for a record-setting crop wilt under the searing sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would have dreamed we would have gotten dry this soon?''
asked Williamson County Extension Agent Ronnie Leps. ``It looked
like we walked out of the rain forest into the Sierra Desert. ''
</P>
<P>
   After an unusually wet 1997, Williamson County growers hoped for
the best, planting 140,000 combined acres of corn and grain
sorghum. Then the rains stopped. Now it looks like many farmers
will lose most of their corn crop and much of their sorghum crop.
</P>
<P>
   And each day the heat continues, the outlook grows bleaker, said
William Albert, who raises corn and cattle and manages the Hutto
Grain Co-op.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any day with temperatures above 90, the corn is going to go
down,'' Albert said. ``We get yield damage every day.''
</P>
<P>
   If rain doesn't come soon, the face of agriculture in the county
will change drastically, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll see different people on tractors and land laying
idle,'' Albert said. ``Most will give up and quit. They'll try to
find another job in town.''
</P>
<P>
   Travis County growers are facing an equally dismal future, said
county Extension Agent Brad Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the corn is chest-high or below, and that's never a
good sign,'' Pierce said. ``Right now, it's looking like a
financial disaster for the agriculture producer.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it is too early to know how hard farmers will be hit
financially, Pierce said, the next 10 days will be the deciding
factor. The chances for improvement are faint, however. The Austin
area hasn't received any significant rainfall since March 16,
according to the National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   As the chance of rain becomes an increasingly dim possibility,
cities and water districts across the region have begun asking
residents to voluntarily conserve water.
</P>
<P>
   San Marcos City Manager Larry Gilley issued a stage one water
conservation order Sunday, prohibiting daytime sprinkler use and
limiting car washing to designated days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have kept a close watch on aquifer levels for the past
month,'' Gilley said. ``Given this extended dry spell and the lack
of sufficient rain, it is time to strengthen our efforts to
conserve water.''
</P>
<P>
   Because San Marcos relies so heavily on water from the Edwards
Aquifer, the city traditionally has been among the first to declare
a drought warning when aquifer levels get low in the summer months.
</P>
<P>
   A stage one drought warning is declared in San Marcos if aquifer
levels fall below 660 feet above mean sea level. On Monday, the
level was at 649.2 feet, a drop of more than 16 feet since the
beginning of May, said Melissa Millecam, city spokeswoman. ``We're
having a real dry spring and terrible start to the summer in terms
of rainfall,'' Millecam said. ``We're trying to be proactive.
Historically, San Marcos has been a leader in whole issue of
protecting the aquifer and conserving the aquifer.''
</P>
<P>
   With a high of 98 degrees, Monday was the third consecutive day
Austin reached record-breaking temperatures. Elsewhere in the
state, decades-old high-temperature records fell in Del Rio, where
it reached 108 degrees; Lubbock, 105 degrees; Amarillo, 103
degrees; Midland, 106 degrees; and San Angelo, 105 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   The heat was being cited as a possible factor in the death of a
man found dead on a bicycle trail at Cedar Hill State Park south of
Dallas, Cedar Hill police said.
</P>
<P>
   While this week's forecast for Central Texas promises more of
the same, a weak cold front is expected on Saturday that could
bring temperatures into the low 90s and a slight chance of rain,
said Cliff Cole, meteorologist for the National Weather Service in
New Braunfels.
</P>
<P>
   Although Austin broke the record for water use Sunday, mandatory
water rationing is not imminent, said Dan Arguijo, spokesman for
the Austin Water and Wastewater Utility. However, Arguijo said
residents are asked to voluntarily conserve water to prevent
problems during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly want to bring about awareness that we are on this
long trip called summer,'' Arguijo said.
</P>
<P>
   Barton Springs/Edwards Aquifer Conservation District officials
said Monday that water levels in some areas of the Baton Springs
segment of the Edwards Aquifer have dropped close to drought
levels. They also are asking residents to conserve water.
</P>
<P>
   In Leander, city officials are asking residents to use
sprinklers on their yards on either odd or even days, depending on
their street addresses. If the drought continues, the city will ask
residents to water yards only once every five days, said City
Administrator Gary Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can keep the odd-even voluntary plan where it's working,
or stepping up to a five-day plan, then we might not have to go to
mandatory,'' Jackson said. ``That's what we're hoping.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Coleman and Nichole Monroe write for the Austin
American-Statesman, Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
