<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1804 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUTH-BUILDERS04-COX     06-03 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUTH-BUILDERS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio community benefits from rehabilitation of homes
 &HT;    By Wendy Hundley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ In 1992, you could hardly give away one of the
dilapidated houses on Frank Street.
</P>
<P>
   Today, one home on the street recently sold for $85,000, and the
Dayton, Ohio neighborhood is on the rebound, thanks to
YouthBuilders Academy, a program that rebuilds lives by rebuilding
deteriorated properties.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gave me a goal,'' said Larry Smith, 22, who was on hand
Monday for the unveiling of four homes rehabilitated by the
YouthBuilders program.
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, Smith was an uninspired high school student
scraping by on D's. Then he become involved in the program that
targets youths at risk for dropping out of school and gives them
hands-on training in the skills needed for jobs in the construction
trade.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, school had a purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made it worth going to school,'' said Smith, who now earns
$16.10 an hour as an apprentice carpenter.
</P>
<P>
   YouthBuilders, originally known at the Builders Academy, is the
brainchild of Ann Higdon, the Dayton woman whose idea to replace
food stamps with a computer card is now a statewide initiative.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Higdon, with the backing of Citizen Federal Bank,
National City Bank and some some well-connected community leaders,
bought 12 condemned homes on Frank Street for $50,000 near the
Montgomery County Fairgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, more than 200 students, many of them involved in
drugs and the juvenile court, have spent time bringing those homes
back to life.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, they've found new direction for their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   Of those 200 students, 75 percent have finished high school, and
87 percent were employed, in the military or in college one year
after graduation.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we're doing it with hammers and nails,'' said Higdon,
founder of Improved Solutions for Urban Systems Inc., the initial
partner in the program that now includes Dayton Public Schools, the
Rotary Club of Dayton and four area construction trade
associations.
</P>
<P>
   Construction skills aren't the only lessons learned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taught me good work habits, like getting to work on time
and having all your tools with you,'' said Ebony Brown, a
17-year-old mother of two.
</P>
<P>
   She said she'll take those habits with her when she studies
cosmetology after she graduates next year from Greene JROTC
Academy, a Dayton school where students got involved in
YouthBuilders during their junior and senior years.
</P>
<P>
   The program also benefits prospective homebuyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not rich but I wanted to have a nice house,'' said
homeowner Lori Powers, who had shopped for homes in other areas but
discovered she could only afford a ``two-bedroom crackerbox that
needed repairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she found the renovated home on Frank Street. She bought it
for $64,900.
</P>
<P>
   Powers feels she got a lot for her money: a three-bedroom,
two-story home with a full basement where she and her husband Jeff
plan to add another bedroom and a family room.
</P>
<P>
   Helping at-risk youth and helping low-to-moderate income
families was the dual purpose for the program that now has a
waiting list of 200 students.
</P>
<P>
   Now Higdon _ who has a knack for turning her dreams into
realities _ has set her sights on other challenges for the
YouthBuilders team.
</P>
<P>
   With the money raised from selling the Frank Street homes,
YouthBuilders Academy has contracts to buy two more sites: the
dilapidated Rubicon apartment building at Rubicon Drive and Frank
Street, and a downtown building at 224 N. St. Clair St.
</P>
<P>
   ``These will be apartments,'' Higdon said. ``Now the focus is on
downtown development.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Hundley writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
