<HEADER>
A1806 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PELLET-GUN04-COX     06-03 0364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PELLET-GUN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Student arrested near school with pellet rifle
 &HT;    By Lady Hereford
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ An 11-year-old student suspended last
week for disrupting his class was arrested recently when he was
caught near his school with a pellet rifle. He made no threats
against students or teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The school resource officer found the Florida sixth grader
around 8:45 a.m. in an abandoned pavilion near school grounds on
Monday, June 1. Startled, the boy pointed the loaded rifle at the
deputy before dropping it. No shots were fired.
</P>
<P>
   The boy was charged with two felonies, possession of a dangerous
weapon on school property and aggravated assault on a law
enforcement officer, and a misdemeanor, trespassing on school
grounds.
</P>
<P>
   He was booked at the county jail and taken to St. Lucie Regional
Juvenile Detention Center. He was to appear before a judge today.
The Palm Beach Post is withholding his name because of his age.
</P>
<P>
   School officials have also suspended the boy, and he will be
recommended for expulsion under the zero tolerance policy,
Superintendent Bill Vogel said.
</P>
<P>
   A motorist near the school saw the boy riding his bike with the
gun across his handlebars. The woman pulled into the school parking
lot and notified the physical education teacher.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff's deputy assigned to the school found him 10 minutes
later in the abandoned structure with the rifle pointed away from
the campus. When Deputy Steve Zaring approached the boy, ``he
automatically just swung that way,'' pointing the gun at Zaring, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Zaring said he drew his weapon and shouted at the boy to put
down the rifle. The boy later said he had the gun for protection
because he ran away from home, Zaring said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the student was suspended for three days for
disrupting his class. As students signed a get-well banner for an
ill classmate, the boy shouted, ``Die soon with a heart attack,''
principal John Townsend said.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks earlier, he was suspended for bringing a small
amount of alcohol to school.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
