</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-GATES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATES' MEETING FOCUSES ON MEETING CUSTOMER NEEDS, NOT LEGAL WOES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WARREN WILSON   c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer   SEATTLE _
Microsoft chairman Bill Gates spent much of Thursday meeting with
the CEOs of more than 120 Fortune 500 companies and said at midday
that he hadn't received a single question about the company's
antitrust woes.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Guests at Microsoft's second ``CEO Summit'' focused solely on
the meeting's core topic, Gates said: how information technology
can make their businesses more efficient and more attuned to
customers' needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The antitrust lawsuit has not come up,'' he said in a strained
question-and-answer session with reporters, who were excluded from
the CEO meetings so that the participants could speak more frankly.
</P>
<P>
   Gates was joined in the Q&AMP;A session by Jeff Raikes, Microsoft's
group vice president for sales and marketing, and CEOs Eckhard
Pfeiffer of Compaq Computer Corp. and Marilyn Carlson Nelson of
Carlson Companies, a $20 billion hotel and travel services company.
</P>
<P>
   Raikes set the terms of discussion in his opening comments,
saying, ``This summit has absolutely nothing to do with the
Department of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're really talking about is where technology is
going,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gates said he had talked with the CEOs about the ``digital
nervous system,'' his term for a technology infrastructure
companies can use to reduce costs, improve communications and
respond to competition and globalization.
</P>
<P>
   He introduced the concept at last year's CEO Summit and said
Thursday that it hasn't really changed since then.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Raikes' ground rules, most of the questions reporters
asked centered on the antitrust lawsuits filed last week and their
implications for Microsoft and its customers.
</P>
<P>
   In the lawsuits, since consolidated in one action, antitrust
regulators accuse Microsoft of exploiting its dominance in desktop
operating systems to gain unfair advantage in the market for
Internet browser software.
</P>
<P>
   But those questions went unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if it wouldn't make sense to discuss that topic with the
CEOs, Gates said simply, ``No,'' and moved on to the next question.
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer, asked if he had heard any discussion of that topic,
said, ``To tell you the truth, I have not.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, asked if the antitrust issue concerned her, said, ``I
haven't spent much time even thinking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer then was asked about a specific issue in the lawsuits,
the amount of flexibility Microsoft grants to computer makers to
customize the first screen or ``desktop'' that customers see when
they turn on a new computer equipped with its Windows operating
system.
</P>
<P>
   The question was prompted by Wednesday's announcement by direct
seller Gateway 2000 that it had negotiated new terms with Microsoft
and will soon offer computers that include a customized desktop and
Netscape's Navigator browser, the target of Microsoft's allegedly
unfair tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not have any disagreements'' with Microsoft, Pfeiffer
said. ``If we wanted to do something different (with the desktop),
we would.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-28-98 2103EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
