<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1823 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-FTC-MICROSOFT-INT     06-03 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-FTC-MICROSOFT-INTEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEL AND MICROSOFT FACE DIFFERING ANTITRUST PATHS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (ja) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawyers for Intel Corp. should be well acquainted
with antitrust inquiries by the Federal Trade Commission _ a
process different from the one followed in Justice Department
antitrust cases _ because the commission has been investigating the
microprocessor giant off and on throughout this decade.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, the agency began an antitrust investigation of Intel
based on complaints that the company was illegally trying to
squeeze smaller chip makers out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, on July 14, 1993, the agency wrote to Andrew
Grove, Intel's chairman, saying that the trade commission was
dropping its long investigation of supposed ``unlawful tying or
exclusive dealing practices or other unfair methods of
competition.'' But the letter added: ``This action is not to be
construed as a determination that a violation may not have
occurred,'' and ``the Commission reserves the right to take such
further action as the public interest may require.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency opened a new Intel investigation last year, and now
that an antitrust suit against Intel seems imminent, the agency and
the company are about to enter an administrative and legal process
far different from the Justice Department's case against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC and the Justice Department have equal jurisdiction to
enforce antitrust laws, and the two agencies decide between
themselves which will handle each new case.
</P>
<P>
   Though both cases could take months to conclude, a suit against
Intel will never reach a federal district court. The initial
judicial proceedings will take place at an administrative level.
</P>
<P>
   First, the trade commission's staff members who have been
investigating Intel will forward their recommendation to the
five-member FTC. Their complaint will most likely accuse Intel of
withholding key technical information about the company's chips
from computer makers with which Intel is involved in disputes.
Without those data, manufacturers are unable to design products.
</P>
<P>
   The staff report should hardly come as a surprise to the
commissioners. Generally, senior agency officials brief the
commissioners regularly on investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Once the recommendation is in the commission's hands, Intel's
lawyers and executives will be free to meet the commissioners and
offer their version of events. Finally, the commissioners will take
a vote that is roughly equivalent to a civil indictment. A vote in
favor of moving forward means the panel thinks enough evidence
exists for a trial.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the case is forwarded to an FTC administrative
law judge who presides over a full trial in a courtroom within the
agency's Washington office building.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing evidence, the judge can dismiss the case or uphold
the charges and issue orders of compliance against the defendant.
Any initial appeal has to be made to the full commission, which
then asks for briefs and oral arguments from both sides and rules
on the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   If the company wants to appeal further, it takes its case
directly to the U.S. court of appeals, which reviews decisions by
administrative agencies like the FTC.
</P>
<P>
   After the FTC's first investigation of Intel was dropped, Intel
said it had put its employees through extensive antitrust training.
</P>
<P>
   ``Around 1987, we recognized that we might have a successful
product on our hands, and we increased our antitrust compliance
program and training to our salespeople,'' Thomas Dunlap, Intel's
vice president and general counsel, said in 1993. ``That training
program has been successful.''
</P>
<P>
   The FTC, it would seem, does not agree.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-28-98 2300EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 1040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
