<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIVA LA REVOLUTIONL! 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY   c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1937, Ernest Vincent Wright wrote a 50,000-word novel without
using the letter ``e.'' Perhaps exhausted by his labors, Wright
died the day his book was published.
</P>
<P>
   Wright's tragic end comes to mind as I contemplate a future
without Microsoft. No, they're not going out of business. I'm just
going to pretend that they have. I'm going to run a PC without
Microsoft's help, and live to tell the tale.
</P>
<P>
   It'll take some doing, but I'm going to set up my home computer
to rely entirely on non-Microsoft products. I'll try it for, say, a
month. Watch for occasional progress reports on my Web site
(http://www.monitortan.com).
</P>
<P>
   I won't be alone. Hang out in the geekier precincts of the
Internet, and you'll encounter legions of Microsoft-haters vowing
to seek a better way to compute. And the history of the past 20
years has taught me not to bet against the geeks.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not now, when history appears to be on their side.
Regardless of their merits, the federal and state lawsuits against
Microsoft are helping to unleash years of pent-up rage at the
company's arrogance. That's been a godsend to a small but
burgeoning movement to supplant Windows with a radically different
software.
</P>
<P>
   You can't open a computer magazine any more without seeing an
article about ``open source'' software. These programs are
available free, along with the underlying computer code that makes
them work. With open source software, expert users can rewrite code
to suit their needs, while amateurs like me can get powerful
programs for little or no money.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it's free, open source software is no joke. Many of
the world's biggest Web sites are powered by a server program
called Apache. It's open source, and available for free. The most
popular program for running Internet e-mail systems is called
Sendmail _ another open source product. And the embattled browser
maker Netscape Communications Corp. is issuing an open source
version of Navigator, the world's most popular browser.
</P>
<P>
   I wrote a few months ago about the best-known open source
product. Linux is an alternative operating system for PCs that
works like the ultrapowerful Unix operating system developed by
AT&AMP;T Corp. in the 1970s. Developed by computer programmers around
the world in their spare time, Linux has come to be used at major
organizations like Xerox, Eastman Kodak and NASA.
</P>
<P>
   Linux's chief strength is that no one company owns it. That
means any programmer can create improvements and bug fixes. But
Linux's biggest drawback is also that no one company owns it.
That's a turn-off to most businesses who want a single source for
product service and support _ one of Microsoft's chief strengths.
</P>
<P>
   In my earlier column, I wrote that Netscape could win a new
lease on life by becoming a major distributor of Linux to
corporations. Give away the software _ sell the service and
support. Get rich quick. A few weeks later, I made the suggestion
to Netscape CEO Jim Barksdale. He rejected it out of hand, telling
me that an alternative operating system company wouldn't stand a
chance against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Looks like this revolution will have to begin at the grass
roots, one PC at a time. I'll go first; you guys can follow me.
</P>
<P>
   I've already begun, with the help of System Commander Deluxe, a
cool disk utility available at any decent software store. System
Commander lets you chop your hard drive into multiple partitions
and store a different operating system in each one. To switch
operating systems, just reboot.
</P>
<P>
   I've got Windows 95, Windows 98 and Linux all happily
co-existing on my machine, and for the past couple of weeks I've
been tweaking the Linux setup, trying to get it ready for prime
time. It's not easy. Linux is geared to gearheads, and I'm being
forced to master cryptic commands like ``ls -alr''. (Go look it
up.)
</P>
<P>
   Linux must become a lot more user-friendly before it can win a
mass market. But If enough of us demand it, this will happen. After
another week of preparations, I'll begin my new job as designated
canary in the software coal mine. All Linux, all the time. No Gates
allowed. Will I wind up like Ernest Vincent Wright? Stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   (You can send Hiawatha Bray electronic mail at
bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-28-98 1334EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
