<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-EXPO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPO CELEBRATES GAMES' SERIOUS BOOM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL SAUNDERS   c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Atlanta has been overrun several times in its history, but no
occupying army has had the flashy abandon of the hordes of computer
game professionals who descended on the city for the Electronic
Entertainment Expo.
</P>
<P>
   The bacchanal was equal parts gaudy trade show and
self-congratulatory celebration of the industry's unbridled boom.
One could argue that General Sherman's light show and fireworks
were more awe inspiring, but today's gamers would win any tussle
over who had the most financial impact. Sales of console video
games and PC game software rose 38 percent last year, making games
the fastest-growing segment of the entertainment industry,
according to the Interactive Digital Software Association.
</P>
<P>
   Total sales and rentals of games in 1997 was $5.6 billion, the
denomination that finally afforded ``those silly kid things'' a
measure of respect. There are about 16 million game consoles in US
homes, and about 40 percent of US homes have at least one personal
computer. First-tier games are unveiled with the same hype given
films and CDs, and often perform better. For example, Sony loves to
boast that the PlayStation game Final Fantasy VII made more money
than Demi Moore's film ``G.I. Jane,'' distributed by rival Buena
Vista. (Of course, this might be an apple and kumquats comparison:
Final Fantasy VII is one of the best games ever, and Moore is
nominated for Best Fight Scene in the 1998 MTV Movie Awards.)
</P>
<P>
   The expo, or E3, is most notable for game unveilings that offer
a view of the hot titles for the all-important holiday sales
season. There will be more games for girls, including a slate of
new titles from Purple Moon. These are based on reams of
sociological and market research that attempt to determine what
girls like and want in computer games. The newest Purple Moon game
is a sports adventure prompted by growing interest in girls'
athletics. Other games in the current stable focus on problem
solving and interactions _ exactly the kinds of things rarely found
in games geared toward boys.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the testosterone set, there's another fast-twitch
fiber shooter on the horizon. Max Payne, a 3D game by the twisted
souls who set Duke Nukem loose on the world, will get its first
public preview at E3. This is likely to be one of the most
anticipated titles from 3D Realms, and one of the top sellers from
the new publishing and distribution house Gathering of Developers.
</P>
<P>
   It's expected to be a next-generation first-person action
shooter, but it has a rough release date of spring 1999. It's
likely to have some of the same campy elements of Duke Nukem,
especially the cheesy humor and high gore factor. So far, the story
reads like a classic Hollywood shoot-em-up: Max Payne is a tough
undercover cop on the lam after he was framed for the murder of his
boss. The setup may have been the work of the same people who
slaughtered Payne's family, so he becomes a one-man posse gunning
to rid New York City of its crime bosses, crackhead killers,
hitmen, sleazy pols, and a host of other ne'er-do-wells.
</P>
<P>
   Command &AMP; Conquer: Tiberian Sun is the third installment in the
wildly popular C&AMP;C series and will also preview at E3. The two
previous C&AMP;C titles (Command &AMP; Conquer and C&AMP;C: Red Alert) have
combined sales of 10 million games, making it the unrivaled leader
in the real-time strategy universe for PCs and console formats.
Last year, however, there was stiff competition on the PC front
from Total Annihilation, an excellent intergalactic war game from
Cavedog Entertainment that walked away with several top awards from
gaming magazines and industry press.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, it's no surprise that this latest C&AMP;C is set
in the future, with a storyline that weaves the fates of the Global
Defense Initiative, or GDI, and its rival, the Brotherood of NOD.
Developer Westwood says Tiberian Sun will feature an all-new game
engine and improved controls, as well as more battlefield realism.
</P>
<P>
   There were also updates on developments in on-line gaming,
including the ongoing saga involving the Cyberathlete Professional
League, or CPL, and the Professional Gamers League, or PGL. The CPL
just scored marketing and promotional support from Babbage's and
Software Etc. The PGL is continuing to secure the services of some
of the world's hottest gamers, including Thresh, the Michael Jordan
of Quake.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC;  _WGBH-TV in Boston just unleashed a new Web site for the
show ``WOOF! It's a Dog's Life,'' which features the ``dog trainer
to the stars,'' Matthew Margolis. Check pbs.org/wgbh/woof, and
peruse the training tips, Q and A's, and visitor stories about
their remarkable pets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;  _We've read this repeatedly over the past few days and can
only ask, why?
</P>
<P>
   Evel Knievel, the star-spangled, leatherclad daredevil whose
motorcycle jumping feats made countless orthopedic surgeons happy,
a man whose escapades defined the total disregard for common sense,
is now a featured advice columnist for the Tripod people, the
on-line community at tripod.com.
</P>
<P>
   I'm guessing that his first words of wisdom will be, ``Kids,
don't try this at home'' but Tripod gushes that Mr. K is actually a
font of unconventional wisdom. His monthly column, ``Ask Evel,''
revs up this week in Tripod's Sports Zone, and Knievel is ready to
answer Tripodistas' crucial questions on ``everything from keeping
the romance in a relationship and raising a family to dealing with
difficult people and asking for a raise.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Knievel: ``I've pretty much done it all, so they can ask me
for advice on just about anything.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-28-98 1333EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 1043EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 10:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1843 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-GERMANY-COMPUSERV     06-03 0325
