<HEADLINE>
BALANCE NEEDS WITH COST, LIFE SPAN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The two toughest columns to write each year are those in which I
suggest the minimum specifications for personal computer buyers.
The object of the exercise is to offer a configuration that will be
usable for a decent amount of time before inevitable obsolescence
sets in.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is what's called Moore's Law, the prime directive of
the computer industry, first laid out by Intel Corp. co-founder
Gordon Moore. It states that microprocessors _ the main brains of
personal computers _ get twice as powerful every 18 months, while
their prices stay the same.
</P>
<P>
   With ever-increasing power and ever-plummeting prices, many
prospective PC owners find themselves in consumer gridlock. They
hold off on buying, waiting forever for computer power to peak and
computer prices to bottom out.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, prices will always drop and computers will just get
more muscular. So, if you need a computer now _ buy one now. And
let the following recommendations be your guide:
</P>
<P>
   _ Processor: This always is the hardest decision to make. The
best way to approach it is to look at how you will use your
computer, both now and in the future.
</P>
<P>
   If your needs are minimal _ and you know they will be for a long
time to come _ you can do quite well with a standard Pentium MMX
system running at 233 megahertz. This is the kind of chip you'll
find powering a lot of the $999 PCs that are now available. If you
want a computer for word processing, tracking finances, Internet
access, children's software and basic game-playing, one of these
will do just fine.
</P>
<P>
   You also can consider Advanced Micro Devices' K6 chip, which
also powers some of the low-end systems.
</P>
<P>
   If you plan on working with graphics _ perhaps via a scanner or
digital camera _ then you should consider at least a 233-megahertz
Pentium II system. This also is a good choice if you want to set up
a home office. Working at home often requires running multiple
applications at once, faxing in the background and possibly
expanding to include a network.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, if you're interested in playing games, consider at
least a 266-or 300-megahertz Pentium II system. Nothing pushes a
PC's capabilities more than state-of-the-art games, a financial
irony. Serious gamers drop big money to have fun.
</P>
<P>
   _ Memory: The minimum amount of random access memory I'd
recommend remains at 32 megabytes, though if you can afford more,
get it. And make sure the system you buy has plenty of memory
expansion capabilities _ some of the sub-$1,000 machines are
severely limited in how much RAM they can hold. You want the option
of increasing to at least 96 megabytes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hard Drive: The size of your hard drive, like the processor,
again depends on what you plan to do with it. For modest users, two
to three gigabytes of space is fine. Home-office users should
consider three or four gigabytes a minimum. And gamers should shoot
for four gigabytes or more.
</P>
<P>
   _ Video: This is another tough call to make, because video needs
vary depending on different factors.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a relatively small monitor _ 14 to 15 inches _
you'll likely be running at resolutions of 640-by-480 or 800-by-600
pixels. Users of larger monitors _ 17 to 19 inches and up _ will
use 800-by-600, 1,024-by-768 or possibly more. The more memory your
video card has, the greater the number of colors it can display at
higher resolutions, for a better on-screen look.
</P>
<P>
   Modest users with smaller monitors can get by with about two
megabytes of video RAM. If you have a larger monitor, four
megabytes is the minimum.
</P>
<P>
   And game-players will want a video card with fast 3-D
capabilities, supporting both Microsoft's Direct3D and Silicon
Graphics' OpenGL standards. Consider a separate 3-D add-on card
that uses 3Dfx Interactive's Voodoo or Voodoo2 chips if you're a
hard-core gamer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Monitors: Regardless of how you use a PC, you'll want at least
a 15-inch monitor with a maximum .28mm dot pitch. It should handle
resolutions up to 1,024-by-768 pixels or more at a refresh rate of
75 hertz.
</P>
<P>
   If you are the kind of user who runs several programs at once,
or are a gamer, you'll need maximum screen real estate and may want
to consider a 17-inch monitor.
</P>
<P>
   _ CD-ROM: Most off-the-shelf systems come with at least a 24X
CD-ROM drive, if not 32X, and this is beyond adequate. Most modern
software requires at least 2X or 4X drives.
</P>
<P>
   The big decision here is whether to get a DVD-ROM drive. There
is not much software that takes advantage of it now, though that
will change.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, there's no compelling reason to consider it if
you're on a budget, and it's something that can be added later.
</P>
<P>
   _ Audio: You'll want a 16-bit sound card with 32-voice wavetable
synthesis, which makes computerized MIDI music sound great. Gamers
may want to consider some of the new audio cards that plug into a
PCI slot and allow for realistic, 3-D sound.
</P>
<P>
   _ Modem: Nearly every system now comes with a 56K fax modem.
Make sure it's upgradable to the new v.90 56K standard, if it's not
there already. The two previous, conflicting standards, X2 and
K56flex, still are prevalent, so check with your Internet provider
to see which he or she has in place. The v.90 modem you buy likely
will support one or the other, but not both.
</P>
<P>
   _ Expansion: Even if you think you'll never want to add hardware
to your PC, consider any system's expandability. If the case can't
be opened and at least one card added, avoid it _ and the more open
slots, the better.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure the system can accept both PCI and ISA type cards. The
older ISA design is slowly being replaced by PCI, but you still
want the option to install an ISA card for now.
</P>
<P>
   So how much will the minimum cost you?
</P>
<P>
   A 233-megahertz Pentium II system with 32 megabytes of RAM, a
two-gigabyte hard drive, two megabytes of video memory, a 32X
CD-ROM drive, a 15-inch monitor, 16-bit sound card and a 56K modem
from Gateway costs $1,247, according to the company's Web site
configurator at www.gateway.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Dwight Silverman can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and questions to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000 and enter
access code 1001. &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
