<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECK UPGRADE DATE TO FIND IF IT'S NEWER THAN WHAT YOU HAVE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I recently decided to see if a new driver was available for
my modem. I found the site but then realized that I couldn't tell
if this was an upgrade or not. How do I know when there is a new
driver available or if I am just reloading the already resident
driver?
</P>
<P>
   A: The best way to tell is by the date the upgrade was made
available, but first you have to determine the date of the driver
currently on your system.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, use the Device Manager feature of Windows 95.
Right-click on the My Computer icon, choose Properties and then
click on the Device Manager tab. You'll see a list of devices on
your computer _ double-click on Modem and you'll see the type of
modem you have. Now, double-click on that to bring up information
about the modem.
</P>
<P>
   You'll see a tab that says Driver. Click on it, and you'll see
information that includes a date.
</P>
<P>
   Next, go to your modem manufacturer's Web site and find the
upgrade. If the date of the downloadable driver is more recent than
what's on your screen, download it and install it. If not, leave it
alone.
</P>
<P>
   The process works for most of the other drivers on your system,
as well. And if you are having trouble locating the Web site for a
given manufacturer of a Windows-based piece of hardware or
software, try the list of company Web sites at Frank's World o'
Windows at www.conitech.com/windows/upmenu.asp.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My question regards the ``Suspend'' feature. I assume it puts
the computer in a low-power mode. Is suspend a good way to shut
down the computer after I'm done? I like the fact that you don't
have to wait for it to boot up, but I want to do what is best.
</P>
<P>
   A: The Suspend feature on newer computers works by saving what's
in memory to the hard drive, then partially powering down. When you
come back to the system and fire it up, your system is restored
just as you left it.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is with the ``just as you left it'' part.
</P>
<P>
   As you use Windows throughout the day, programs launch, grab
memory, and relinquish that memory when they are shut down _ or, at
least they are supposed to. Some buggy programs don't relinquish
memory, which eats away at your system's resources.
</P>
<P>
   Other programs may have small errors in them that aren't trapped
by Windows' error-snagging functions, which slightly destabilize
your system. You don't know this has happened until later, down the
road, when you have an odd glitch or, worse, a program crashes.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to clean out problems in Windows is to reboot the
computer. If you never reboot the computer and only use Suspend,
your system's memory becomes ``dirty.''
</P>
<P>
   I would suggest you use Suspend if you leave your computer on
all day and need to go away for a while. But at night, or for
extended periods, go ahead and shut it all the way down.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My system has a hard drive divided into three drives as C, D
and E. My C drive is getting full. When it fills up, will my system
automatically write programs on the next available drive? Or do I
need to start installing programs on D?
</P>
<P>
   A &UR; : &LR;  Once C is full, your system won't automatically start using
D. You'll have to manually install programs to your other drives.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Dwight Silverman can receive
electronic mail via the Internet. Address your comments and
questions to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000
and enter access code 1001. &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR; XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
