<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERS GIVE CHURCHES A DIGITAL HELPING HAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PARKER   c.1998 San Antonio Express-News   SAN ANTIONO _
Not long ago, most congregations kept their financial records in
ledger books, while membership activities were tracked by hand and
kept in many different files.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Compiling information for monthly reports was a slow, tedious
job.
</P>
<P>
   But computer software has revolutionized the gathering and use
of information.
</P>
<P>
   Need to know how much Joe Smith owes on his $2,000 pledge to the
building fund? Presto, punch a computer button and there it is.
</P>
<P>
   It's midmonth and you wonder how close the parish is to
exceeding the budget? Poof, up come the figures on the computer
screen, revealing that last Sunday's collection was higher than
expected, so there's a bit of a cushion.
</P>
<P>
   Or the youth group's bus broke down and 100 parents must be
notified that their children will be late arriving home.
</P>
<P>
   Make 100 phone calls? Nope. Record one message on the phone tree
and it does the rest, calling the parents automatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Computers have absolutely revolutionized financial record
keeping and our ability to track people,'' said Ronnie Loughlin,
minister of education and administration at First Baptist Church in
San Angelo, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can record contacts with potential new members, track their
status and determine how many visits it takes before someone
decides to become a member,'' Loughlin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Financial records are up to date on any given day. You don't
have to wait until the end of the month.''
</P>
<P>
   Hal Campbell, president of Automated Church Systems, a church
software company in Florence, S.C., said technology can help
churches keep detailed information on people's interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether someone works on cars or does carpentry, the
information is readily accessible. If a widow needs work done, we
can pull up a list of members and see who can help,'' Campbell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Many large churches are creating ``cell groups'' that meet
regularly in homes, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said such groups can obtain information from the church
by computer, saving a trip to the church.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Hamilton, president of Shelby Systems in Memphis, Tenn.,
another church software company, said a secretary at one work
station can send electronic mail or hundreds of messages and
produce newsletters that once had to be contracted out.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Vignes, business manager at Alamo Heights United
Methodist Church in San Antonio, said Shelby Systems' integrated
software makes her work much simpler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keeping track of 3,800 members' activities would be awfully
tedious by hand. I don't know how any church does without
computers,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Vignes said the church staff knows how often each family
attends, how much they contribute, who visits and what ministries
interest them.
</P>
<P>
   The church welcomes them and gives them information on upcoming
activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone misses several Sundays, we call to say we missed
them and see if they have problems or needs,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-29-98 1245EDT &QL;
</P>
