<HEADLINE>
FINDING EXPLORER AN ADVENTURE
</HEADLINE>
 CPT- COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Dr. EMILIO BOMBAY c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram  DEAR DR.
BOMBAY: My desktop has an Internet icon that suddenly started
giving the following message: Windows cannot find iexplore.exe. I
can still get to the Internet via the Start menu.
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ Gone But Not Forgotten
</P>
<P>
   DEAR GONE: It's that sneaky Janet Reno again, going from house
to house, computer to computer, purging Internet Explorer along the
way to make democracy safe from Bill Gates and his evil minions.
</P>
<P>
   Well, either that or your desktop icon lost track of where IE is
stashed, maybe because you installed it to someplace other than the
usual folder. You could right-click on the icon, go into Properties
and point the thing in the right direction, but that's too much
work. Why not just drag a copy of the working shortcut out onto
your desktop? Just don't let Janet know I told you. She'll be
knocking on my door wanting to dismantle me next.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Out of utter disgust with Windows and the fact
that Bill Gates is Satan _ only not as bright _ I thought of
converting to Macintosh. Since I don't want to pay $3,500 for a new
computer, I was wondering if it is possible to run the Mac
operating system on an Intel machine.
</P>
<P>
   _ Macinstein
</P>
<P>
   DEAR MACINSTEIN: Sure it is, if you don't mind great clouds of
smoke filling your house and sparks shooting everywhere. From time
to time, some well-meaning brainiac comes up with a way to run Mac
stuff on a PC, and it usually involves an expensive, circus-act
add-on microprocessor card. Listen, if you're going over to the
other side, stop straddling the fence.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to spend $3,500, either. The lowest-priced G3 can
be had for $1,700. Once you add a monitor and modem, it's about
2,300 bucks. If you go nuts and want the top of the line fully
tricked out, you could spend as much as $9,000, but what sort of
loony would do that? These prices are direct from the Apple Store
at www.apple.com, so all you Appleheads, don't write another bunch
of nasty letters implying that my head is full of fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't want to spend $2,300, then wait until August, when
you can get a new iMac for 1,300 bucks. It's got a dinky, built-in
monitor (13.8 inches viewable) and looks sort of like a Philco TV
straight out of the '50s, but it's packing a 233-MHz G3 chip and is
specially designed for cruising the Internet. Current specs list it
with a 33.6 modem, but let's hope that changes to 56K, because most
of us still connect through phone lines and won't be using the
iMac's network connector. Oh, and the last I heard, the floppy
drive is extra, although it does have a CD-ROM. The iMac is still a
lot of bang for your buck, though.
</P>
<P>
   But are you sure you really want to abandon the PC altogether?
It's not nearly as much fun to kick Steve Jobs around as it is Big
Bill.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Being a senior citizen with a new computer, I
would enjoy seeing a list of all Internet providers, pros and cons,
monthly charges, etc.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hook Me Up
</P>
<P>
   DEAR HOOK: Go find somebody who's already online and check out
thelist.internet.com for a rundown of more than 4,500 providers.
But that sounds a little intense for me. I'd check out the Yellow
Pages first. Just remember, anybody who'd ask for more than 20
bucks a month for regular dial-up service is goofy in the head. You
can probably find a company that charges an ultra-cheap rate, say
100 bucks or so, if you sign up for a year. Others charge even less
for daytime-only use, and I assure you those pictures of Courtney
Thorne-Smith are just as hot at noon as at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay does not cruise Ally
McBeal sites. He got there accidentally. Courtney can reach him at
drbombay(at)startext.net,
</P>
<P>
   via snail-mail at Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth
76101, or fax: (817) 390-7257. His real name is Michael Gerst,
editorial systems manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-29-98 1542EDT &QL;
</P>
