<SLUG> BC-CPT-TRIP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
 
(Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) 
3DO's Latest Incarnation 
By Julia Angwin c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  Trip Hawkins is
reinventing himself _ again.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hawkins, once one of Silicon Valley's most outspoken
personalities, has kept mum since his video game business crashed
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is launching himself _ and his company, 3DO _ back into
the public eye at the E3 gaming industry conference today in
Atlanta. With almost a dozen new games and a $30 million war chest,
3DO will unveil its transformation from a hardware maker to a
software company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm back and I've brought an army with me,'' Hawkins says, in
joking reference to 3DO's nearly 300 employees.This is the third
time Hawkins has reinvented himself. His current attempt to rise
from the ashes illustrates that failure is a respectable business
credential in risk-driven Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people talk about his failures, but they don't talk
about how he got all these people to invest in his vision,'' said
David Cole, senior analyst at DFC Intelligence, a market research
firm in San Diego. ``That's pretty impressive to me _ I don't think
you can count the guy out.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins, 44, has always been a good salesman first and foremost.
In his initial incarnation, he was a brash young entrepreneur who
sold the game software industry on a new business model.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than follow the practices of the software industry, which
sells software through distributors, Hawkins saw that computer game
publishing was an entertainment business that needed to emulate
Hollywood's model.
</P>
<P>
   So he started selling software directly to retailers _ much as
movie studios pitch their movies directly to theaters.
</P>
<P>
   The game industry converted to the idea in the early '80s after
seeing the success of the company Hawkins founded, Electronic Arts.
The San Mateo software games behemoth now has sales near $1 billion
and is the No. 1 independent maker of software games.
</P>
<P>
   After building Electronic Arts into a monster, Hawkins decided
in 1993 to tackle another side of the games industry _ the
hardware. Hawkins pocketed approximately $100 million when he left.
</P>
<P>
   Fed up with the clunky video game machines on the market,
Hawkins came up with an idea for a game device called the 3DO _ a
video game machine that connected to TV sets and used CD-ROMs
instead of cartridges. It ended up being a forerunner of the Sony
PlayStation and Sega Saturn.
</P>
<P>
   In his second incarnation, Hawkins convinced investors such as
AT&AMP;T to pour nearly $75 million into his Redwood City-based
startup, called The 3DO Company. He pitched his story as a
patriotic one _ American boy up against the Japanese game
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   The hype surrounding the machine was spectacular, running up the
company's stock to $48 five months after it went public at $15 per
share in May 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins, a trim, athletic man who spends his spare time climbing
mountains and in the front row at Giants games, also became a media
celebrity. He was named one of People Magazine's 50 Most Beautiful
People in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But the 3DO game machine never panned out. At $700 each, the
devices were too expensive for most customers, especially compared
to cheaper machines from Sony, Sega and Nintendo.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, when 3DO's stock had sunk to $3 per share, Hawkins
decided to give up on the hardware business and turn 3DO's
attention to software. He says now the main problem was that 3DO
wasn't manufacturing its gaming devices _ it just licensed the
technology to manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a fundamentally unstable business structure because we
didn't have any control over anything,'' Hawkins said.
</P>
<P>
   However, there was one saving grace to his exit from the
hardware business. In 1996, Hawkins sold an advanced video gaming
technology to Matsushita for $100 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   3DO has been riding on that cash infusion during the past two
years, as Hawkins _ in his third incarnation _ struggles to turn
the firm into a software games company.
</P>
<P>
   During the transition, Hawkins has been uncharacteristically
quiet, shunning industry functions and declining to hold press
conferences. He first resurfaced in public at an industry
conference in Napa last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins, who is known for his supremely confident attitude,
shocked the attendees by admitting that he'd made mistakes with
3DO.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I would see the day where Trip said, `I was
wrong,''' said Johnny Wilson, editor-in-chief of Computer Gaming
World magazine and a longtime friend of Hawkins who attended the
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any hint of what I used to perceive as ego or arrogance
appears to have disappeared,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's a more subdued Hawkins who is leading the reinvention
of 3DO.
</P>
<P>
   The new 3DO is not seeking to shatter any business models or
take on the Japanese. It simply wants to build good-quality games
for personal computers and video game consoles.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in two years, 3DO has taken a booth at the E3
gaming software conference.
</P>
<P>
   At the show, 3DO will show off 11 new games to an industry where
many had assumed 3DO was dead. Rather than breaking new ground,
however, 3DO is pursuing the standard gamut of games _ from
medieval adventures to blackjack and war strategy.
</P>
<P>
   And it will unveil its new advertising campaign ``3DO _ We're
Here to Play.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins will also host the game industry's first awards ceremony
_ which is designed to be gaming's version of the Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins said he expects to encounter skepticism about his new
vision but that he is committed to doing what he loves.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have asked, `Why is Trip still at 3DO?''' he
said. ``My answer is, `Why not? This is who I am. What else would I
do?'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-27-98 2201EDT &QL;
</P>
