<SLUG> BC-CPT-NETSCAPE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
 
(Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) 
Netscape's Grip on Browsers Slipping 
By Jon Swartz c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  Netscape
Communications is losing its grip on the Web browser market.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Mountain View company _ which pioneered Web browsing and
owned as much as 80 percent of the market in 1996 _ now has just
over half of the domestic browser market and is in danger of being
passed by Microsoft this year, a national Internet study shows.
</P>
<P>
   Navigator's market share in January was 54 percent, down from 63
percent a year ago. Microsoft's Internet Explorer, by comparison,
doubled to 39 percent from 21 percent in January 1997, according to
ZD Market Intelligence in La Jolla, San Diego County.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although more people use Navigator, the clear winner was
Microsoft,'' said senior analyst David Tremblay of ZD Market
Intelligence. ``The government's lawsuit against Windows 98 and
Netscape's decision to give away its browser could slow down the
rate, but all trends indicate that Internet Explorer will continue
to eat away at Navigator's share.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 24.2 million personal computers in the United States now
use a Netscape browser, while Internet Explorer is used on 17.3
million PCs, the survey said. Nearly 5.6 million PCs have both
products.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, based on information culled from 50,000 U.S.
households, echoes a Dataquest study released last year that
predicts Internet Explorer will bypass Navigator some time this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Among the report's other findings:
</P>
<P>
   _Nearly 45 million PCs in the United States have Web access, up
43 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   _Some 10 million domestic PCs were used for shopping on the
Internet, compared with 3.7 million a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   _The average PC is connected to the Internet for 4.5 hours a
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``In just two years, the Internet has become a home-PC
mainstay,'' Tremblay said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has made huge strides in the browser market by
including Internet Explorer with its market-leading Windows 95
operating system _ a tactic that the Justice Department says
violates a 1995 antitrust agreement. The two sides are scheduled to
meet in a federal court on September 8 to determine if Windows 98,
which will combine Web browsing and the operating system into a
single product, is anti-competitive.
</P>
<P>
   While the browser-share results represent a marketing victory
for Microsoft, it doesn't add anything to the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Browser share is a nonissue in terms of revenues,'' said
analyst Jim Balderston of Zona Research in Redwood City. ``The
market has annual revenues of zero dollars, but it is crucial if
you want to establish an access point from which consumers surf the
Web.''
</P>
<P>
   Netscape agrees. After initially charging $50 for Navigator, it
started giving away its browser in January. The company is now
concentrating on selling software to corporations and building its
NetCenter Web site into a major Internet portal to attract
advertising and online transactions.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy comes with a downside, however. Netscape is losing
Navigator as a significant revenue producer and creating a
temporary hole in its financial results.
</P>
<P>
   It lost $88 million in its fourth quarter, forcing 300 layoffs,
and if not for creating an abbreviated quarter in January, it would
have reported a second-quarter loss on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a legal, but interesting bit of aggressive accounting,''
Balderston said. ``By shifting their yearly reporting cycle, they
were able to dump a $54 million loss in January so they could break
even (in May).''
</P>
<P>
   ``What these results and the browser-share numbers indicate is
that the anything-is-possible days of Netscape have passed,'' he
said. ``They can still be a profitable company, but they better do
it soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft shares improved $2.38, to $86, yesterday. Netscape's
stock was up $1.88, to $25.75.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-27-98 2158EDT &QL;
</P>
