(Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) 
The Well Is Leaking, But It's Not Yet Dry 
By Tom Abate 
c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  The Well, the online discussion
group that pioneered the notion of cyber communities, is in hot
water.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Membership, which peaked at 10,000 two years ago, has slumped to
7,000, and sources say about 400 members a month are bailing out.
</P>
<P>
   Well Executive Director Gail Williams disputed those attrition
figures and said the number of conference participants has
stabilized at around 7,000.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, The Well's owner, Rockport shoe millionaire Bruce
Katz, is searching for a buyer. But critics say his $2-million-plus
asking price is too high.
</P>
<P>
   The Well's troubles, like the woes at Wired Magazine, prove that
being first does not guarantee success in the Internet age.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1985 by visionary Stewart Brand, the Sausalito-based
Well became the favorite online hangout of writers and
intellectuals at a time when the Internet was peopled mainly by
nerds.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 90s, as the Internet was going mainstream, Katz
entered the picture. He bought half, then full ownership of The
Well for about $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   He pumped in more money, hoping to leverage The Well's
reputation to make it a leading Internet service provider as well
as a high-brow chat room.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion flopped, largely for want of direction from Katz,
who spends several months a year on his sailboat. In 1996, he hired
online entrepreneur Maria Wilhelm to help run the business.
</P>
<P>
   She quit in January after failing to buy The Well. Her
lieutenant, Ed Long, quit in April, leaving Williams in charge of
the diminished operation.
</P>
<P>
   The Well sold its ISP business _ Whole Earth Networks _ early
this year, making it mainly dependent on the $10 to $15 a month it
charges members to participate in conferences.
</P>
<P>
   No one expects The Well to dry up, as long as its core group of
conferees continue to make it one of the most provocative
think-holes on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still feel intimidated when I post there because there are
so many really smart people reading,'' said longtime Well-head
Bruce Koball.
</P>
<P>
   Katz e-mailed me, promising that The Well is ``not going away''
as he searches for ``just the right buyer for this most famous of
online communities.''
</P>
<P>
   And so The Well drifts, a backwater in the cyberspace that its
members helped create.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Docu-dreaming: &LR;  San Francisco filmmaker Jay Capela is praying
for angels to cough up the $400,000 he needs to finish editing a
three-hour documentary on Silicon Valley startups.
</P>
<P>
   Called WildStart, the film goes behind the scenes at 15 firms
ranging from the well-known WebTV to the wacky Rotary Rocket, a
Redwood Shores firm that dreams of building a rocket with
helicopter rotors in its nose cone, so it can swoop gently to the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I envision this as a cross between Hoop Dreams and Triumph of
the Nerds,'' said Capela, who is co-producing the film with
software entrepreneur Eric Swildens (see www.wildatstart.com).
</P>
<P>
   After viewing a 12-minute trailer they're showing investors,
WildStart strikes me as a bit too ``Lifestyles of the Rich &AMP;
Famous.''
</P>
<P>
   Capela wants the production to be edgy and realistic, but so
far, all 15 of his subject firms are making it. In the real world,
90 percent of all startups fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll go back and find some bombs,'' he promises _ after they
get the money to bring his project to a happy ending.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; True lies: &LR;  Former Microsoft engineer Daniel Oran has penned a
new fiction, ``Ulterior Motive.'' It revolves around a
Seattle-based software giant, Megasoft, whose chairman, Jack
Malcolm, is running for President.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, the lead character is based more on Ross Perot than
Bill Gates,'' said Oran, who has posted a synopsis on his Web site
(www.book98.com).
</P>
<P>
   Oran won't say whether Malcolm wins the Oval Office (and fires
the antitrust department). But rest assured that when the
billionaire gets attacked at a public appearance, it isn't with
cream puffs!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Contact Tom Abate at abate(at sign)sfgate.com or 650-961-2689.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-27-98 2202EDT &QL;
</P>
