<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;    Game makes you pick: Rock, or hard place?
 &HT;    By Emily J. Minor
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It's none of his business, but, still,
Randy Horn would like to know the answer to this very bizarre and
totally meaningless question:
</P>
<P>
   Would you rather lose your perspective, or your sense of
balance?
</P>
<P>
   And now, if you've got some time, the 30-year-old Mr. Horn has
1,499 additional questions all boxed up and ready for your
consideration and, of course, each and every one of them is of
equal absurdity and unimportance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am finding that some people think I am what's wrong with
America,'' says Horn about his new invention, the board game
Zobmondo!!
</P>
<P>
   Horn is hoping, of course, that he'll get rich, just like those
two bartenders who in the mid-'80s came up with that crazy game
called Pictionary. Those guys made about a gazillion dollars on a
game they played themselves for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're golfing now,'' Horn said.
</P>
<P>
   But Horn's a little realistic about this get-rich thing because,
you see, his game has an edge to it that Pictionary does not.
Mainly, you have to have a sense of humor, you have to be able to
take the questions with a grain of salt. And you have to be willing
to answer the situation, regardless of its grossness or
ridiculousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one's actually doing this stuff,'' Horn assures.
</P>
<P>
   Would you rather never be able to sleep lying down _ OR _
instantly fall asleep every time you sit down? (You win or lose by
trying to guess how players will answer and advancing on the
board.)
</P>
<P>
   The idea started about 10 years ago when Horn earned a
reputation in college for always asking the ridiculous questions,
whether at a party or on a date. His favorite:
</P>
<P>
   How much money, in cash, would it cost to eat a live, kicking,
two-inch cockroach?
</P>
<P>
   ``I could sit and talk with my friends about that question for
an hour,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   So, he devised a series of pizza parties for his UCLA classmates
to socialize and invent new questions. He ended up with about 800.
After that, he hired 30 comedy writers to write questions and ended
up with about 6,000. From that, he pared it down to 1,500 for
Zobmondo!! Horn figures he's got about $90,000 sunk into the game's
research and production.
</P>
<P>
   Some questions were even too over-the-edge for Randy Horn which,
of course, means we won't be telling you about them in this
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   But, we're curious.
</P>
<P>
   Would you rather yank 12 inches of masking tape off the hairiest
part of your body _ OR _ have to remove a fishhook wedged 1/8 of an
inch into your thumb?
</P>
<P>
   Don't `Oo, gross,' us. Blame Randy Horn.
</P>
<P>
   Zombondo!! retails for $34.95 and is sold in only one Florida
store, The Game Keeper, in the small town of Ocoee, west of
Orlando. Call that store at (407) 523-0966 to order by credit card
or call the Zobmondo!! toll-free number at (800) 417-0017.
</P>
<P>
   Emily J. Minor is a features writer for the Palm Beach Post,
West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
