<SLUG> BC-PERFECT-SATSCORES04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Not one but two perfect SAT scores grace Florida's Suncoast High
School
 &HT;    By Stephanie Desmon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIVIERA BEACH, Fla. _ Jason Kelly did it first. And if there's
any kid you want your kid to follow off that bridge, it's Jason
Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   The Suncoast High School junior scored a perfect 1,600 on his
SATs in March, so classmate Blake Gottlieb figured he'd better give
those study guides a workout.
</P>
<P>
   Gottlieb got the good news in a crisp envelope 10 days ago: He,
too, scored a 1,600.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little jealous,'' Gottlieb conceded Tuesday. ``If he
didn't get a 1,600, I don't know if I would have worked as hard. .
. . I kind of owe it to him a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Such perfection is pretty rare. Of last year's 1,127,021 U.S.
high school graduates who took the SAT _ now called the Scholastic
Assessment Test _ 453 earned top scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is the first time we've had two,'' Suncoast
Principal Kay Carnes said.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly and Gottlieb, both 17, will tell you they're good buddies
who don't compete for grades. They even studied together for the
SAT.
</P>
<P>
   And they'll tell you that getting a 1,600 doesn't mean they're
super brains.
</P>
<P>
   ``The SAT is not a measure of intelligence,'' said Gottlieb, who
lives in Palm Beach Gardens. ``It's all about knowing how to take
the test. We cracked it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gottlieb is one of those guys who loves math. He took advanced
placement calculus Advanced Placement Calculus as a freshman and
just kept going from there. He's in the Math Club (not to mention
the National Honor Society, the varsity swim team and more).
</P>
<P>
   He has a 4.0 grade average, mostly because he likes the
``symmetry'' of it. The 1,600 adds to that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a perfectionist,'' he said. Besides, ``you get one B,
everyone knows about it. You can't let that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Fellow math lover Kelly has a classload filled with challenging
International Baccalaureate courses. He's in the National Honor
Society and Key Club and is a member of the chess team, which went
to nationals this year.
</P>
<P>
   As for the SAT, the Jupiter teen simply feels good because he
doesn't have to take it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is a big relief,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither student is sure where he'll attend college after
graduating next year. Kelly is fascinated by the field of genetic
engineering and said he'll probably choose a course of study to get
him there.
</P>
<P>
   Gottlieb has wanted to be an astronaut since fourth grade, when
he heard astronaut Mike Mullane lecture on the key to reaching the
heights he had.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `If you want to be an astronaut, here's what you do:
Study. Study. Study,' '' Gottlieb said. ``That's what I did.
</P>
<P>
   --ENDIT--
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-02-98 2357E
</P>
