<HEADLINE>
REBOOTING BILL GATES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER   c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The eye-catching new product from Microsoft Corp.
cannot be found in a shrink-wrapped box or downloaded onto your
computer. But it is getting a vigorous tryout these days on the
nation's largest networks.
</P>
<P>
   TV networks, that is. And in major newspapers. And all over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The rollout of Bill Gates, the new and improved version 2.0,
began a few months ago, long before Microsoft was hit last Monday
with potentially damaging antitrust complaints by the US Justice
Department and 20 state attorneys general. Now it's in high gear.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than using lawyers and surrogates, Microsoft has put its
billionaire chairman right out front to parry the government's
claims. It is a crucial role. The courtroom battle will not begin
until fall, but customers and business partners are forming
opinions about the company right now.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft wants to show that it is not some kind of
reincarnation of the 19th-century robber barons, but rather the
gutsy, leading edge of American prosperity, a company willing to
fight the government on behalf of consumers and entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lawsuit has them concerned about this negative impression
that they are some kind of monopoly that goes to any lengths to
achieve dominance,'' said Larry Weber, chairman of Weber Public
Relations Worldwide in Cambridge, Mass. ``It's going to impact the
way their customers view them, and maybe even stall some buying
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft denies it is marketing or repackaging its most visible
executive. But in the months before the antitrust suit was filed,
Gates had made news by showing up at schools that receive free
Microsoft software. He hawked Big Bertha golf clubs, letting on in
the ad copy that he likes golf but, aw shucks, even a billionaire
finds the game frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   People who watch the sometimes-testy mogul say he has even
switched to trendier eyeglasses and has neatened up his haircut.
And the man who once walked out on a Connie Chung interview agreed
in January to sit for celebrity chit-chat with Barbara Walters. The
segment allowed Gates to reveal that he takes singing lessons and
expects his lifetime donations to charity to top $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   By design or not, Gates seems eager to show himself as less geek
and more chic, or at least something of a common guy.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent transformation came just in time for Gates to take
one of his most important roles: chief defender of Microsoft during
the landmark antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   As talks to settle the lawsuit collapsed last weekend, Microsoft
filmed an in-house interview with its chairman and made it
available to TV stations by satellite. It posted a self-generated
question-and-answer interview with Gates on the Internet. And when
the lawsuit was finally filed, it was Gates himself who defended
the company at a press conference at Microsoft headquarters in
Redmond, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday (May 19), one day after the suit was filed, Microsoft
ran full-page advertisements in newspapers, billed as a letter from
Gates to customers, shareholders, and business partners. The
following day, The Wall Street Journal ran an opinion piece under
Gates's byline on its influential editorial page.
</P>
<P>
   The thrust of these ads and appearances was the same: The
company tried earnestly to settle the anti-trust suits, Gates said,
but government lawyers wanted it to trade away the right to make
better products for consumers. The company _ not the government _
should be trusted with the job of designing software.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is textbook public relations,'' Weber said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is smart to make Gates the front man for the company,
Weber and others said. His products introduced millions of people
to the computer age, and Gates created billions of dollars in
wealth for investors (and for himself) by guiding Microsoft to
fantastic success. The company is now the second-most valuable on
any US stock exchange, after only General Electric Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a helluva lot of people in this country who admire
his skill and entrepreneurial spirit,'' said John Brodeur, chief
executive of the Boston PR firm Brodeur Porter Novelli. ``When he
goes out in public, he's like a rock star. He's probably the
best-known businessman in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gates is also often accused of arrogance, and his geeky
demeanor is often described as smarmy rather than charming.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Shaw, a Microsoft spokesman, scoffed at claims that
Microsoft set out to soften Gates's image in advance of the
antitrust suit. The golf club ad, he said, came merely because a
friend at Calloway, which makes the Big Bertha, asked for his help.
Barbara Walters had sought an interview, and its January broadcast
was an accident of timing. Shaw said that anyone looking at other
key Microsoft moments _ like the release of Windows 95 or of
Gates's 1995 book on the future of technology _ would find that the
chairman has often been in the public eye. ``He's done the morning
shows. He's been on Jay Leno. He's been on David Letterman. This
isn't new,'' Shaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft clearly timed one PR effort to coincide with a bit of
public policy. While attending a high-profile Senate hearing on
Microsoft in March, Gates kept a diary for the company's on-line
magazine, Slate. It showed him eating pizza for dinner and catching
part of a James Bond movie on his flight from the West Coast.
``Somehow they are not as good as the ones I saw when I was young,
or maybe it's me that is different,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   And Microsoft was at least considering a sophisticated PR effort
tied to the antitrust case, until the details were leaked last
month to The Los Angeles Times. The proposal reportedly called on
Microsoft to hire local PR firms across the country and solicit
letters to the editor and op-ed pieces from local business leaders,
suggesting a groundswell of support for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw said the plan was merely a proposal from a consultant,
Edelman Public Relations, and that Microsoft decided not to adopt
it.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Microsoft is not alone in thinking about what
message to promote in the antitrust suit. Its nemesis in the
Internet browser wars, Netscape Communications Corp., has hired
former Supreme Court nominee Robert Bork, who has been writing
opinion pieces on antitrust law for major newspapers. Former
Senator Bob Dole has been working for a trade group opposing
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Even the National Association of Attorneys General has hired
some outside PR help, for the first time ever in a prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   NAAG brought on the PR firm, the Hastings Group, about a year
ago to help arrange its annual meeting and to promote its efforts
in fighting telemarketing fraud. The firm has stayed on to handle
some organizational tasks and help the 20 attorneys general that
filed suit in the Microsoft case. It does not shape the
prosecutors' message or develop ``media strategy,'' said James
Doyle, the NAAG president and attorney general for Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have their own PR challenge in suing a popular
company like Microsoft. The case not only involves technical
details of the software industry, but its purpose is partly to
prevent future harm to consumers who cannot be identified and
brought before the TV cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``An antitrust case is not normally a case with a direct
victim,'' said Doyle. ``In a crime case, you see the physical harm
against a person. In a consumer protection case, we have complaints
where people say, `I got ripped off by $100 or $1,000.' But an
antitrust case by its nature is much more abstract.''
</P>
<P>
   The government certainly has a substantial staff and budget for
its case against Microsoft. But the software company has also added
to its arsenal of tools lately, and not just by highlighting its
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few years ago, the company was barely visible in
Washington, as if the old-world ways of politics had no bearing on
the new digital world. It relied largely on trade groups to carry
the company's message as lawmakers began debating more issues of
importance, such as export rules for encryption software, changes
in copyright law, and policies on Internet access fees and
high-definition television.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft only recently started to hire lobbyists and give
significant donations to politicians, a routine practice for many
other businesses. Now, Microsoft has an established presence in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has given more money to candidates in the 1997-1998
election cycle so far than any other computer company, the
Washington-based Center for Responsive Politics reported last
month. The company's contributions totaled nearly $300,000 as of
May 1.
</P>
<P>
   And it has bolstered its roster of government and public
relations help. The list now includes Michael Deaver, Ronald
Reagan's former image-maker, who now works with Edelman Public
Relations; former Republican Party chairman Haley Barbour; and
former congressmen Thomas Downey of New York, a Democrat, and Vin
Weber of Minnesota, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-27-98 1338EDT &QL;
</P>
