<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGHSCHOOL-BOMBING04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trio charged in blasts at Ohio's Trotwood-Madison High School
 &HT;    By Lou Grieco and Joanne Huist Smith
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Three Trotwood-Madison High School students were
charged with a total of 13 delinquency felony counts after they
built and detonated three pop-bottle bombs at the high school
campus Monday, June 1, Trotwood police said.
</P>
<P>
   The students, two aged 15 and one 16, remain in Montgomery
County Juvenile Detention Center. School Superintendent Samuel C.
Brewer said the students have been suspended and may be expelled.
</P>
<P>
   With school shootings across the country since October _
including those in Springfield, Ore., West Paducah, Ky., Pearl,
Miss., Jonesboro, Ark., and Edinboro, Pa. _ school officials can't
afford to take chances with students and weapons, Brewer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very unfortunate incident,'' Brewer said. ``It was
certainly disturbing. Youngsters need to learn that decisions that
they make can be harmful to themselves or to others.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the second such case in a Miami Valley school since
Friday, when Morrow police discovered a crude explosive device in a
student's bookbag at Little Miami High School. Police said the teen
who made it showed off his handiwork to friends.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, police said the students had no intent to harm
others. It was more of a ``look what I can do'' scenario, Trotwood
Lt. Fred Beck said.
</P>
<P>
   SEE BOMBS/ 8A DENNIS...PLS STOP EDIT HERE AND PICK UP JUMP COPY
ON 8A...THANKS
</P>
<P>
   BOMBS: Hed in Utopia Reg
</P>
<P>
   CONTINUED FROM 1A
</P>
<P>
   In Morrow, ``we and the police believe the student had no intent
to use the device to harm himself, other students or staff,''
Little Miami School Superintendent Michael Verelli II said. ``It
appears to be a case of when you create something you want to show
it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Little Miami school staff heard about the homemade bomb after
three students told them the student held a private ``show and
tell'' for a group of students.
</P>
<P>
   No one was injured and no property damage was reported in either
case. In Trotwood, the students made the devices by combining
household cleaning products into three plastic soda bottles, then
went outside and threw them. One landed on school grounds, two
others on a nearby lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Police Capt. Jim Borland said the chemicals become unstable
after they are mixed and could have exploded in the students'
hands. The acid formed would have burned them, he said.
</P>
<P>
   School officials heard loud ``pops,'' investigated, then sent
the students to the principal's office.
</P>
<P>
   The three students were shocked when police arrived, Borland
said. ``They didn't realize it was going to be such a big deal,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The students were charged with delinquency by reason of
possessing a dangerous ordnance on school grounds and manufacturing
a dangerous ordnance, Borland said.
</P>
<P>
   The three appeared Tuesday in Montgomery County Juvenile Court,
where Judge Nick Kuntz entered denials of responsibility for each
boy. The Montgomery County Prosector's Office has not decided
whether to ask Kuntz to transfer the boys to adult court, said
spokesman Jim Knight.
</P>
<P>
   Two are in the temporary custody of foster parents through
Montgomery County Children Services, Knight said.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Valley Crime Lab is testing the device found at Little
Miami to determine how dangerous it is, Warren County Prosecutor
Tim Oliver said.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-year-old Morrow student made the device after a friend
called him on a boast that he could make a bomb, Oliver said.
</P>
<P>
   Morrow police took the student into custody Friday. He remains
in the Warren County Juvenile Detention Center, where he will
undergo psychological testing. He was suspended from school and
could be expelled.
</P>
<P>
   In Trotwood, Brewer said he is waiting for a report from the
school principal before deciding whether to expel them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes kids just don't think. You see the apologetic look
on their faces after the fact, but by then it's too late,'' said
Verelli, the Little Miami school superintendant.
</P>
<P>
   Educators across the Miami Valley look forward to the end of a
school year marred by violence and threats of violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to pull out all the stops to show kids it's still
safe to go to school,'' said Robert Bixler, principal of Little
Miami High School. ``Our parents know what's going on. When they
call, we invite them to come in walk down the halls and see that
everything is okay.''
</P>
<P>
   Summer break for Trotwood and Little Miami begins Thursday
afternoon, but school officials are preparing for September
</P>
<P>
   After many school violence incidents around the country, people
later said there were warning signs. Trotwood-Madison
Superintendent Brewer said the district plans to develop a list of
warning signs to help staff determine if a student is headed toward
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``These incidents are like a cry for help and attention,''
Brewer said. ``We as a society have to decide if we value our
children more than guns or weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   CONTACT Lou Grieco at 225-2057 or e-mail him at
lou_griecocoxohio.com. Contact Joanne Huist Smith at (513) 748-5642
or e-mail her at joanne_smithcoxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-02-98 2019E
</P>
