A1876 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KABAT-COLUMN04-COX     06-03 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Fifty years of love
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a story Dad loves to tell. He's the gangly country boy,
just back from serving a short spell overseas at the tail end of
World War II. She's the city girl, a majorette for the high school
band in the small town where they both grew up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took one look at her sashaying across that football field
and fell instantly in love,'' Dad recalls with a smile. Then he
regales us with how he had to win her away from a gaggle of
admirers, but with perseverance and no small amount of charm, was
able to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The rest is history. Fifty years of it, actually, a milestone we
will soon celebrate with an open house at their church in the same
small town where they grew up and lived all their lives. My
brother, sister and I, and our families, will return to our
hometown, slice up the three-tiered cake, pour the gold punch, try
desperately to remember the names of our parents' friends we
haven't seen in 20 years, and videotape it all for posterity. We
will do it up as right as we know how, because it's an occasion
worthy of celebration and honor. As the children of this union, we
are exceedingly grateful for it, and for what it has taken to
maintain it.
</P>
<P>
   My mother was one month shy of 18 when they married; my father
was four years older. Nine months later they had their first child.
They lived in a small, wood-frame house with no indoor plumbing and
a coal-oil stove in the kitchen that provided the only heat during
cold Midwestern winters. They hauled water in from town once a
week.
</P>
<P>
   Mom, raised in town, learned how to slop the hogs, feed the
chickens, can food from the garden and heat goose eggs under a lamp
in the kitchen until the goslings hatched. She also learned how to
drive cattle from one pasture to another, roust errant hogs from
the cornfield and separate squealing newborn pigs from their irate,
charging mothers.
</P>
<P>
   None of this could have been easy. At the same time, Dad learned
how to be a man _ in the shadow of his own parents who lived up the
hill and still ran the farm on which the two families now jointly
worked. It was a large shadow Papa cast. They agreed and disagreed,
fumed and fought, but still planted and plowed and harvested crop
after crop, side by side, year after year.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the hard work, screaming kids and hovering
parents, my folks also had fun. They went dancing on Saturday
nights and to this day can glide around a dance floor with more
grace than my husband and I ever managed. They had card parties
with friends, staying up late into the night, laughing and telling
stories as they played hand after hand. They had barbecues and pig
roasts, inviting the whole neighborhood over, farm folks just like
themselves who came laden with potato salad and cole slaw, creamed
new potatoes and peas, cobblers, pies and homemade ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   They went to church every Sunday and made sure we went with
them. No argument, no discussion. Every Memorial Day, we filled
huge baskets with peonies and irises from our gardens and solemnly
went around to the cemeteries to remember our deceased ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   And my parents loved each other. Every morning began with a
kiss. Dad would slip up behind Mom, who was standing at the stove
before a pan of sizzling bacon, to nuzzle her neck. Waiting in the
car together for Mom to run into a store, Dad would watch her come
toward us and ask for the hundredth time, ``Don't you have a
beautiful mama?'' Yep, I sure do.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty years of watching kids grow up, get in trouble, helping
them out of trouble, seeing them wed and helping out with
grandbabies' births. Fifty years of illnesses, both mild and
frightening. Fifty years of stoking the same home's oil furnace,
washing the same windows every spring, putting up the same storm
windows every fall. Fifty years of planting petunias and
snapdragons in the backyard flower bed and watching for the
hummingbirds each summer.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Dad loves to tell the story of how he met and fell in love
with Mom. And, 50 years later, we still love to hear it.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco (Texas) Tribune-Herald.
She can be reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
