<SLUG> BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
 
(Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) 
Microsoft Gives Gateway Some Freedom 
By David Einstein c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  Backing down just
a bit in the face of a landmark antitrust suit, Microsoft yesterday
allowed a major computer maker some limited freedom in customizing
its Windows operating system.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The software juggernaut agreed to let Gateway include an option
on the Windows 98 startup screen that will take new customers
directly to Gateway's own Internet access service, rather than to
Microsoft's Internet setup feature.
</P>
<P>
   Gateway, the nation's fourth-largest personal computer maker,
also will give users the choice of setting Netscape's Navigator
rather than Microsoft's Internet Explorer as their default Web
browser.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, these two changes will make it easier to choose
Internet services other than Microsoft's. They won't affect the
basic look of the Windows desktop.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's decision to bundle its browser with Windows 98
(which goes on sale next week), and its unwillingness to let PC
makers alter the software, were key issues leading to antitrust
suits filed by the U.S. Department of Justice and a group of 20
state attorneys general. The suits, which have been combined into
one, charge Microsoft with using its control of the PC operating
system to crush competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's move was seen as a show of flexibility by Microsoft
intended to strengthen its defense in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fairly good pre-emptive strike against the
Department of Justice,'' said analyst Mary Ryan of Ragen MacKenzie
in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Attorney General Richard Blumenthal called it a step
in the right direction that could signal a trend. ``But really
nobody can say at this point it is the beginning of a different
kind of practice on the part of Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   PC makers have sought greater leeway in customizing Windows as a
way to differentiate themselves in an era when different brands of
computers are almost identical.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the very least this will let them change the initial user
screen to better reflect what they want to present, as opposed to
what Microsoft has told them they have to present,'' said analyst
Rob Enderle of Giga Information Group.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Waitt, chief executive of Gateway, which is based in North
Sioux City, S.D., said his company has been negotiating with
Microsoft for some time to get more leeway in customizing Windows.
He also said he'd like even more freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to offer our customers the flexibility and
customization that they want,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By easing up on its licensing agreement with Gateway, Microsoft
opened the door for other companies to demand similar freedom. But
most big PC makers may still be wary of making demands on
Microsoft, which provides the operating system for nearly every new
PC.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq, the nation's top PC maker, said it had no plans to
replace Microsoft's browser with Netscape's on its PCs. And Dell,
the No. 2 company, said it does not intend to change the look of
the Windows desktop.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has consistently claimed that it gives PC makers a
wide berth in modifying the Windows experience, letting them
pre-install any software they like, including the Netscape browser.
</P>
<P>
   But the giant company remains adamant about not wanting PC
makers to change the basic look of Windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to allow users to know that when they get this out
of the box they're getting a fully featured Microsoft Windows
operating system,'' said Microsoft spokesman Adam Sohn. ``That's
important because otherwise, you could have Windows computers that
cause serious problems because users won't know they've got
everything they need.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-27-98 2159EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
