<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 10:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1884 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-INTEL-MARKETPLACE     06-03 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTEL-MARKETPLACE-645&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-ART-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 UNDATED: advise selling. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One skeptic is Larry Woods, an independent technology analyst in
Stony Creek, Ontario, and author of The Tech Review newsletter. He
said: ``Investors are paying more for less and less profitability
at Intel. The stock holds up because Wall Street analysts say that
everything will be sweet in the second half. I say nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are notoriously upbeat, of course. And their optimism
grows even rosier the further out their estimates go. For example,
according to First Call, the consensus estimate for Intel's first
quarter among analysts following the company back in July 1997 was
$1.13 a share. Six months later, when the new year rolled in, the
consensus had fallen to 93 cents a share. The actual number Intel
reported for the quarter: 81 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   What most Wall Street analysts don't want to talk about is how
much Intel's world has changed. Gone are the days when Intel had
virtually no competition. Today, Advanced Micro Devices Inc. is
producing an impressive chip called the K-6 that in many
measurements matches the speed of Intel's Pentiums at a price 25
percent less. And National Semiconductor's Cyrix chips _ the
higher-priced Media GX and lower-priced MIIs _ are winning
converts.
</P>
<P>
   Computer manufacturers that once put only Intel chips inside
their boxes are moving to other suppliers. Compaq Computer, the
world's largest computer maker, and IBM, the No. 2, are using
Advanced Micro Devices chips as well as those from Cyrix. IBM is
making its own chips and chips for Advanced Micro to compete with
Intel, too. And last week, Packard Bell-NEC, the world's
fifth-largest PC producer, announced that it was ending its
exclusive use of Intel chips in its machines. Its new supplier:
National Semiconductor's Cyrix, at much lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   Increased competition isn't Intel's only problem. The company,
which got the majority of its revenues from Pentium and related
board products last year, is selling into a computer market that is
becoming saturated. In spite of PC price cuts in the neighborhood
of 50 percent, the portion of U.S. households owning computers has
inched up only 3 percentage points over the past year-and- a-half
to 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   According to PC Data Inc., a research company that tracks the
industry, PC sales in April were up only 6 percent from a year
earlier, way down from the double-digit increases that computer
makers have grown accustomed to in recent years. The slowdown
appears to be worsening: compared with March 1998, unit sales were
down 31 percent in April and revenues fell 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Those computers that do sell go for bargain-basement prices, not
a positive factor for manufacturers' margins. The average selling
price of a PC at retail is now about $1,000, down from the $2,200
average for the past few years. Even Dell Computer, the industry's
stellar performer, saw its average sales price for a PC drop 9
percent in the most recent quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The computer industry was counting on sales overseas to pick up
some of the slack from falling demand in the United States. But the
economic turmoil and currency woes in Asia, particularly Japan,
mean computer purchases are no longer a priority for consumers
there.
</P>
<P>
   One relatively new approach for Intel is to focus on the low-end
chip market with its two-month-old Celeron chip designed for use in
under-$1,000 PCs. But users report the chip is slower than the
competition's, and it is not doing well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intel has to protect its margins to protect its stock price,''
said Fred Hickey, technology analyst and author of the High-Tech
Strategist newsletter. But this may no longer be possible. Although
Intel will not divulge its average selling price per chip, an
industry source estimates it at $200. Advanced Micro Devices has
said it can make money with an average selling price of $100 a
chip.
</P>
<P>
   Even more ominous to some Intel watchers is how many insiders
are exiting the stock. ``For years, Intel insiders were reluctant
to part with their stock,'' said Bob Gabele, who follows insider
transactions at CDA Investnet in Rockville, Md. ``Now, the
inclination of Intel insiders to sell increasing numbers of shares
into weakening share prices is troubling.''
</P>
<P>
   From July through early October 1997, Intel executives sold less
than 150,000 shares. When the shares started to tumble in October,
insiders sold almost 700,000 shares at prices of $80.86 to $85.44.
In January 1998, Intel executives sold 916,000 more shares at $75
to $82.50 each. Three months later, six insiders announced plans to
sell 800,000 shares at prices of $74 to $84.
</P>
<P>
   ``The increased selling seen at Intel is not reflected across
the semiconductor industry,'' Gabele said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-27-98 2113EDT &QL;
</P>
