 &HT;    Q &AMP; A on the news
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Carolina Gold rice . . .
</P>
<P>
   Q: Isn't there some law restricting the minutes of advertising a
network can show during TV programs? If not, there should be,
because advertisers are exceeding what we should have to endure.
</P>
<P>
   A: There's no law, but you're correct if you think you're
watching more commercials than ever. As reported previously, TV
Guide says a study by the American Association of Advertising
Agencies and the Association of National Advertisers found that the
amount of ads and network promos in prime time has increased 33
percent in the past nine years. The biggest culprit is ABC, which
has gone from 7 minutes and 22 seconds per hour to 9 minutes and 30
seconds per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Your options: when commercials interrupt your program, hit the
mute button on your remote, leave the room, or turn off the TV.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When I was growing up, I always heard the American soldiers'
final resting place and memorial at Arlington National Cemetery
referred to as the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier. Now it seems to be
known as Tomb of the Unknowns. Why the change? When was the tomb
built?
</P>
<P>
   A: Originally, there was one unknown from one war. On March 4,
1921, Congress approved the burial of an unidentified American
soldier from World War I in the plaza of the new Memorial
Amphitheater. The tomb sarcophagus was placed above the grave of
the Unknown Soldier of World War I.
</P>
<P>
   The first Tomb of the Unknown Soldier was slightly smaller than
the present base. It was torn away when the present tomb was
started Aug. 27, 1931. The tomb was completed, and the area opened
to the public, April 9, 1932. West of the World War I Unknown are
the crypts of unknowns from World War II and Korea (whose
internments took place in 1958) and Vietnam (1984).
</P>
<P>
   The white marble sarcophagus has never been officially named,
according to the Military District of Washington, which oversees
Arlington. So it's referred to both ways: ``Unknowns'' and
``Unknown Soldier.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Since the Tomb of the Unknowns is so much in the news lately,
I'm curious: How many bodies, representing what wars, are entombed
there?
</P>
<P>
   A: One each from World War I, World War II, the Korean War and
the Vietnam War (the latter exhumed in May for an attempt at
identification).
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent newspaper item listing U.S. deaths in major wars
omitted the Spanish-American War. This is the 100th anniversary,
and Teddy Roosevelt would be very put out. So what was the total
number of American dead in that war?
</P>
<P>
   A: The word ``major'' probably is the key here. The Defense
Department lists 385 battle deaths and 2,061 other fatalities in
that war, which took place from April to August 1898. Hopefully
none of the participants, including the Rough Riders under Lt. Col.
Theodore Roosevelt, would have felt insulted.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent Q&AMP;A item said the Vietnam War began in 1957. Didn't
it actually start in 1962?
</P>
<P>
   A: The item you saw was referring to American casualties in a
number of wars. U.S. civilian and military advisers began helping
the South Vietnamese in the '50s. The year 1957 was when Americans
first started taking casualties in a long, ongoing war in Vietnam,
picking up where the French left off in their war with the Viet
Minh (1946-54). In early 1965, the United States began sending
ground combat troops to Vietnam and began bombing North Vietnam.
Since the Vietnam War never officially was declared by the United
States, there's no one single starting date you can point to.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
