<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS04-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A on the news
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: I see that the decade-long renovation of Egypt's Sphinx has
just been completed. That reminds me of something I've heard over
the years, that the Italians used the Sphinx for artillery target
practice when they occupied Egypt. Is that so?
</P>
<P>
   A: Don't blame the Italians. In fact, the idea that it was used
by anyone for target practice probably is off base. Although locals
who guide tourists around the site for tips often tell them that
Napoleon's men used the Sphinx for target practice, it seems
unlikely. Napoleon's party was the first from the modern West to
catalog and praise the Egyptian antiquities, so the idea that they
then would harm something so significant is remote.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the ailments of the Sphinx appear to have stemmed from
the very rock it is made of: soft, relatively porous limestone,
hardly fit to stand eons of wind, sand, heat, water, pollution and
time.The Napoleon legend makes sense only because it's a good story
in the spirit of anti-colonialism. Absent logic and proof, however,
it's not believable.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When were the first TV commercials aired, and what were the
companies?
</P>
<P>
   A: The year was 1945. The first advertisers included Lever
Bros., Bulova Watch, Botany Worsted Mills, Pan American World
Airways, Firestone Tire &AMP; Rubber, RCA Victor, Gillette Safety
Razor, Esso gasolines, U.S. Rubber, and R.H. Macy &AMP; Co. The ads
were aired in New York on WCBW, WNBC and WABD.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Assuming an all-out nuclear attack with all available nuclear
weapons, what impact would a nuclear war between India and Pakistan
have on the Earth's environment?
</P>
<P>
   A: The effects of what would be the world's first nuclear
exchange are difficult to predict because so many variables remain
unclear. Neither country has said how many weapons it has or
intends to stockpile, or been open about the destructive power
(``yield'') of its weapons. Paul Beaver, spokesman in London for
defense publisher Jane's Information Group, said Pakistan and India
each are believed to have 12 to 18 nuclear weapons packing yields
equivalent to about 20 kilotons of TNT. That's the size of the
atomic bomb that the United States dropped on Hiroshima, Japan, on
Aug. 6, 1945. The U.S. bomb dropped on Nagasaki three days later
was more powerful.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than assuming both countries would unleash all their
weapons, consider what would happen if each attacked the other's
capital with one bomb. Nuclear experts say most of the death and
destruction would be within a half-mile radius of ground zero. Much
of the fallout would push into the stratosphere if even one bomb
exploded in the air; more fallout obviously would occur if there
were more than one explosion. People for miles around would be
threatened with radiation sickness and death, and the fallout
likely would spread worldwide through the air and water. Prevailing
winds, rain and other factors would figure into where the fallout
would go.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, the full effects of the radiation from World War II
atomic bombs exploded over Japan, and from the 1986 Chernobyl
(Ukraine, then part of the Soviet Union) nuclear reactor disaster,
which would include birth defects, aren't fully understood. So the
environment isn't the only concern outside Pakistan and India.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the Military District of Washington? I heard it
referred to after the Memorial Day concert in Washington on PBS,
and then saw it mentioned again in a Q&AMP;A item about the Tomb of the
Unknowns.
</P>
<P>
   A: The full name is U.S. Army Military District of Washington.
In 1941, about five months after the start of World War II, the War
Department created MDW to plan for a ground defense of the nation's
capital. During the WW II era, MDW gradually was reorganized as a
service and support command, with responsibility for servicing the
newly built Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, MDW has gained, lost and regained various
installations and support responsibilities.Today it's an Army
command with a three-fold mission: to respond to crisis, disaster
or security requirements in the National Capital Region; to operate
Arlington National Cemetery and provide base operations for Army
and Defense Department organizations throughout the National
Capital Region; and to conduct official ceremonies, in Washington
and worldwide, on behalf of the nation's civilian and military
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   MDW is the home of the Army's official ceremonial unit, the 3rd
U.S. Infantry (The Old Guard); and the U.S. Army Band, ``Pershing's
Own,'' units that represent the Army and the nation thousands of
times each year.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the difference between DUI and DWI? An article about
Wal-Mart heiress Alice Walton said she was convicted of DWI.
</P>
<P>
   A: Different states use different terms, but by either DUI
(driving under the influence) or DWI (driving while impaired or
driving while intoxicated), it's the same thing: driving drunk or
under the influence of drugs. Walton was found guilty Friday of
driving while intoxicated, refusing to take a blood-alcohol test at
the request of police, driving without a seat belt, and failing to
properly maintain control of her vehicle after a single-vehicle
accident in January near her Arkansas home. She will be sentenced
in July.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
