<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 11:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1923 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-McNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-03 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-McNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NMIGHTMARISH DREAM TEAM
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN McNAMARA 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What, no press conference to denounce the international child
abuse cult for concocting drunken driving charges against their
colleague?
</P>
<P>
   No medical experts to swear that the inability to recite the
alphabet beyond the letter ``N'' is indicative of a ``pre-existing
condition,'' not drunkenness?
</P>
<P>
   No support for claims by the only female member of the Louise
Woodward defense team that their colleague was abused and sexually
harassed by a State Police trooper?
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take Harvey Silverglate, Andrew Good, and Barry Scheck
long to cut Elaine Whitfield Sharp loose, did it?
</P>
<P>
   It's certainly true that the British-born barrister's version of
her predawn arrest by State Trooper Randy Cipoletta on the Lynnway
on May 22 strains credibility. She could not speak clearly; could
not walk a straight line; could not recall the second half of the
alphabet, but Ms. Whitfield Sharp would have us believe that a
trooper with an unblemished record was so overcome by desire that
he offered to drop the charges if she had sex with him.
</P>
<P>
   She insists she never told Trooper Cipoletta that she was
distressed because she now believes her client is guilty of the
murder of 8 1/2-month-old Matthew Eappen, that she never threatened
to sue him, that she never struck the EMT called to transport her
to the hospital after she had staged something of a sit-down strike
on the floor of the State Police barracks in Revere.
</P>
<P>
   The trooper made it all up, Whitfield Sharp claims, in order to
justify arresting her. No, it doesn't ring true to me, either.
Weaving across three lanes of traffic and bumping into guard rails
would seem like probable cause enough to arrest someone for driving
under the influence of alcohol. But I thought incredible defenses
were the specialty of the Sharp-Silverglate-Good-Scheck legal team.
Where are their imaginations?
</P>
<P>
   Wasn't this the crew, after all, that tried to convince a jury
that Louise Woodward put Matthew Eappen down for an afternoon nap
on Feb. 4, 1997, and his skull spontaneously ruptured without any
precipitating action on the part of the British au pair?
</P>
<P>
   That creative defense failed, of course. After deliberating for
27 hours over three days, the jury convicted their client of
second-degree murder last fall, accepting the prosecution's
contention that a frustrated Woodward caused Matthew's injuries by
violently shaking him and slamming his head against a hard surface
in his home in Newton Highlands. He died five days later.
</P>
<P>
   It was only the intervention of Judge Hiller Zobel that saved
the now 20-year-old baby sitter from a mandatory minimum of 15
years in state prison. The Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court is
still reviewing Zobel's decision to reduce the jury's verdict to
involuntary manslaughter and credit Woodward with time served, 279
days. A ruling is expected within the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   If the high court finds that Zobel abused his discretion, the
jury's verdict could be reinstated and Woodward could be returned
to Framingham state prison. Those accommodations are a far cry from
Whitfield Sharp's spacious Colonial in Marblehead, where Woodward
lived for months after Zobel set her free last October. She moved
out at the end of March.
</P>
<P>
   Why Louise left is still an open question, but Whitfield Sharp's
former colleagues are not beneath casting aspersions in her
direction. ``Unfortunately, Ms. Sharp has at times exhibited an
aberrant pattern of behavior, as at the time of her arrest,''
Silverglate, Good, and Scheck said in a stunning display of
disloyalty that accompanied their announcement that Whitfield Sharp
had been fired from the Woodward defense team.
</P>
<P>
   If only they had elaborated. What, one can only wonder, is
Harvey Silverglate's idea of ``an aberrant pattern of behavior?''
Could anything Whitfield Sharp has done been more bizarre than the
sight of the wild-eyed Silverglate on national TV accusing some of
the world's best doctors of being part of a ``child abuse cult''
because they testified to their conviction that Louise Woodward
battered Matty Eappen to death?
</P>
<P>
   A fatal case of child abuse has devolved into a game of
competitive defamation among a pack of deranged lawyers.
Silverglate defames the doctors. Whitfield Sharp defames the
trooper. Silverglate, Good, and Scheck defame their colleague. This
is one dream team that deserves the nightmare it has spawned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
