<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS, attention features, technology page editors:
</P>
<P>
   Here is a list of selected computer-related stories of the past
week that we have repeated today, from  &UR; The N.Y. Times News
Service &LR;  and its partners, The Boston Globe, Cox News Service,
Bloomberg News, Hearst News Service, The Houston Chronicle, The
Arizona Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los
Angeles Daily News, San Francisco Chronicle and Seattle
Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   All these repeated stories carry a distinguishing ``CPT'' in the
slugline and carry an ``a'' general news category code.
</P>
<P>
   INTEL-ANTITRUST-REACT-NYT (Undated) _ A claim added almost as an
afterthought in a civil lawsuit filed last fall in Birmingham,
Ala., paved the way for a broad antitrust suit that the Federal
Trade Commission plans to file soon against Intel Corp. By Lawrence
Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   INTEL-MARKETPLACE-NYT (Undated) _ Immortal. Beloved. That's how
investors see Intel Corp., the world's premier maker of
microprocessors, the guts that run computers. Even though the stock
has fallen 21 percent from its February high, Intel has remained
one of the most widely held and deeply loved stocks in America. For
many investors Intel is not just a stock, it's a religion. By
Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   NETSCAPE-MICROSOFT-BLOOM (La Jolla) _ Netscape Communications
Corp.'s U.S. Web browser market share fell to 54 percent as of
January as Microsoft Corp.'s Internet Explorer browser nearly
doubled its share, according to a new study by ZD Market
Intelligence. By Margaret D. Williams.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-GATEWAY-BLOOM (Redmond, Wash.) _ Microsoft Corp.,
facing a government antitrust suit, made a concession to
personal-computer maker Gateway Inc. that addresses a central
concern about the software maker's control of the PC desktop. By
Margaret D. Williams.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-SFCHRON (Undated) _ Backing down just a bit in the
face of a landmark antitrust suit, Microsoft allowed a major
computer maker some limited freedom in customizing its Windows
operating system. By david Einstein.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-GATES-BOS (Washington) _ The eye-catching new product
from Microsoft Corp. cannot be found in a shrink-wrapped box or
downloaded onto your computer. But it is getting a vigorous tryout
these days on the nation's largest networks. TV networks, that is.
And in major newspapers. And all over the Internet. By Aaron
Zitner.
</P>
<P>
   GAME-ZOMBONDO-COX (West Palm Beach) _ It's none of his business,
but, still, Randy Horn would like to know the answer to this very
bizarre and totally meaningless question: Would you rather lose
your perspective, or your sense of balance? By Emily J. Minor.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-SFCHRON (Undated) _ The Well, the online discussion
group that pioneered the notion of cyber communities, is in hot
water. Membership, which peaked at 10,000 two years ago, has
slumped to 7,000, and sources say about 400 members a month are
bailing out. By Tom Abate.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-DIGITAL-TV-NYT (Undated) _ Europe's antitrust regulators
Wednesday blocked an ambitious digital television alliance among
three of Germany's most powerful media companies, marking a
milestone in the growing power of the European Commission over
events in individual countries. By edmund Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   NETSCAPE-SFCHRON (Undated) _ The Mountain View company _ which
pioneered Web browsing and owned as much as 80 percent of the
market in 1996 _ now has just over half of the domestic browser
market and is in danger of being passed by Microsoft this year, a
national Internet study shows. By Jon Swartz.
</P>
<P>
   TRIP-SFCHRON (Undated) _ Trip Hawkins is reinventing himself _
again. Hawkins, once one of Silicon Valley's most outspoken
personalities, has kept mum since his video game business crashed
two years ago. Now he is launching himself _ and his company, 3DO _
back into the public eye at the E3 gaming industry conference today
in Atlanta. With almost a dozen new games and a $30 million war
chest, 3DO will unveil its transformation from a hardware maker to
a software company. By Julia Angwin.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX (Undated) _ Finding Explorer an
adventure. By Dr. Emilio Bombay.
</P>
<P>
   CHURCH-COMPUTERS-HNS (San Antonio) _ Not long ago, most
congregations kept their financial records in ledger books, while
membership activities were tracked by hand and kept in many
different files. Compiling information for monthly reports was a
slow, tedious job. But computer software has revolutionized the
gathering and use of information. By Michael parker.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS (Undated) _ The two toughest columns to
write each year are those in which I suggest the minimum
specifications for personal computer buyers. The object of the
exercise is to offer a configuration that will be usable for a
decent amount of time before inevitable obsolescence sets in. The
problem is what's called Moore's Law, the prime directive of the
computer industry, first laid out by Intel Corp. co-founder Gordon
Moore. It states that microprocessors _ the main brains of personal
computers _ get twice as powerful every 18 months, while their
prices stay the same. By Dwight Silverman.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-COMPUSERVE-NYT (Bonn) _ A judge in Bavaria sentenced the
former head of Compuserve Deutschland to two years in jail on
charges of spreading pornography, but suspended the sentence. It
was the first time in Germany that the manager of a provider of
Internet access had been held legally responsible for images
reached through its service. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTERS-EXPO-BOS (Undated) _ Atlanta has been overrun several
times in its history, but no occupying army has had the flashy
abandon of the hordes of computer game professionals who descended
on the city for the Electronic Entertainment Expo. The bacchanal
was equal parts gaudy trade show and self-congratulatory
celebration of the industry's unbridled boom. By Michael Saunders.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS (Undated) _ It'll take some doing, but I'm
going to set up my home computer to rely entirely on non-Microsoft
products. I'll try it for, say, a month. Watch for occasional
progress reports on my Web site (http://www.monitortan.com). I
won't be alone. By Hiawatha Bray.
</P>
<P>
   PACKARD-BELL-MICROSOFT-BLOOM (Sacramento) _ Packard Bell NEC
Inc. said it will offer a customized desktop display of Microsoft
Corp.'s Windows 98 operating system on its new personal computers
to be introduced later this month. By Margaret D. Williams.
</P>
<P>
   FTC-MICROSOFT-INTEL-NYT (Washington) _ Lawyers for Intel Corp.
should be well acquainted with antitrust inquiries by the Federal
Trade Commission _ a process different from the one followed in
Justice Department antitrust cases _ because the commission has
been investigating the microprocessor giant off and on throughout
this decade. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-GATES-SPI (Seattle) _ Microsoft chairman Bill Gates
spent much of Thursday meeting with the CEOs of more than 120
Fortune 500 companies and said at midday that he hadn't received a
single question about the company's antitrust woes. Guests at
Microsoft's second ``CEO Summit'' focused solely on the meeting's
core topic, Gates said: how information technology can make their
businesses more efficient and more attuned to customers' needs. By
warren Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-SCREENS-BLOOM (Seattle) _ Microsoft Corp., the No. 1
maker of personal computer software, said all PC makers using its
Windows operating system are free to customize their start-up
screens as Gateway Inc. plans to do and others already have done.
By Laura Raun.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-PRIVACY-BLOOM (Cambridge) _ America Online Inc.
Chairman Stephen Case said technology companies should join to
create an ``Internet Alliance'' that would help regulate the global
information network. By Aimee Picchi.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-HAZARD-COX (Washington) _ The Environmental Protection
Agency is setting off security alarms with plans to post details
about the nation's hazardous chemical sites on the Internet. The
EPA is preparing to collect and make public information about the
``worst-case'' potential disasters for some 66,000 U.S. facilities
that store dangerous chemicals. By Julia Malone.
</P>
<P>
   GATEWAY29-COX (Austin) _ In a move seen as loosening Microsoft
Corp.'s grip on the major computer makers, Gateway Inc. said
recently that it will include competing Internet browsers on
desktop computers with Windows 98. By Jerry Mahoney.
</P>
<P>
   LUCENT-STRIKE-BLOOM (Washington) _ Lucent Technologies Inc. said
it reached agreement with two unions to end a strike against the
telephone-equipment company over health-care costs, job transfers
and subcontractors. By Dawn Hayes.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-SFCHRON (Undated) _ When I ran a typesetting business in
the 1980s, one of my worries was figuring out what technology to
buy to keep pace with the changes in the industry. The best advice
I ever got on that score literally walked in my front door one day,
when a trio of local inventors showed me an interface that plugged
a PC into our typesetting machine. By Tom Abate.
</P>
<P>
   SMALLWEB-SFCHRON (Undated) _ It seemed like a bad omen for small
businesses when Saks Fifth Avenue gave up on electronic commerce
earlier this year. After all, if a sophisticated retailer like Saks
couldn't make money on the Web, how could more modest merchants?
Billy Blue, a San Francisco men's clothier, provides a more
optimistic model for cyber retailers: While its total online sales
have been relatively small, the site has sold more upscale apparel
in the past two months than Saks did in its 18 months on the Web.
By Carol Emert.
</P>
<P>
   SOFTWARE-SFCHRON (Undated) _ Personal computers can't run your
small business for you. But they can make it a heck of a lot
easier. By David Einstein.
</P>
<P>
   YEAR2000-SFCHRON (Undated) _ There's been a lot of fuss lately
about the Year 2000 computer problem and its potentially
devastating effect on big business. But the glitch could easily
trip up small businesses as well _ something most of their
proprietors don't seem to realize. By Arthur M. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   NETWORK-SFCHRON (Undated) _ Monica Frei, head of a Bay Area
nanny placement service, had all the people skills she needed to
spot a good housekeeper, nanny or personal assistant. But until
recently she was almost too petrified even to touch a computer.
That all changed last year when associates finally convinced her to
install a computer network in the three Bay Area offices of Town
and Country Nannies and Mothers In Deed. By themselves, the firm's
computers weren't any friendlier than before, but networked
together they became too powerful a business tool for Frei to
ignore. By Jonathan marshall.
</P>
<P>
   NETWORKSIDE-SFCHRON (Undated) _ If computers could speak, they'd
beg to be networked whenever two or more inhabit the same office.
By Jonathan Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   TECHTOOLS-COLUMN-COX (Atlanta) _ Family Tree Maker is the giant
of genealogy computer programs, with more than 1 million copies
sold. It is an excellent program, but my wife, Donna, the
genealogist, believes much of its popularity comes from the wealth
of information on the nine CDs that come with the deluxe version.
Her report: By Jack Warner.
</P>
<P>
   TECHREPORT-COX (Undated) _ It's not so much trouble to reach for
the stack of compact discs, pick the one you suddenly have a
hankering for, pop it into the CD player and hit play. But wouldn't
it be nice to just tap the CD player and have that tune start
playing? You can, if you have every single CD you own sitting in
the CD player. By Michael Kannell.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY02-COX (Atlanta) _ It looks like Windows 98 will be
released on Microsoft's original schedule of June 25. My guess is
that the publicity about the company's problems with the Justice
Department will end up hyping sales. By Bill Husted.
</P>
<P>
   MACREPORT-COX (Atlanta) _ Apple Computer faces no greater
challenge than wooing software developers back to the Macintosh. It
is they who will make or break this computer. By Charles Haddad.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE-COX (Atlanta) _ Your next fishing partner may have a
17-inch screen and a keyboard. Now that regular folks _ people like
you and me _ use computers and the Internet on a daily basis, Web
sites do a much better job of representing the non-technical side
of life. By Bill Husted.
</P>
<P>
   DATA-LAYOFFS-BOS (Undated) _ The price wars that staggered the
computer industry took another swipe at Data General Corp. The
company Monday laid off 400 workers _ 150 in Massachusetts _ and
said it would take a $125 million charge as it abandons the
manufacturing of low-end server computers. By Hiawatha Bray.
</P>
<P>
   THE NEW YORK TIMES NEWS SERVICE
