<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, June 3, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Thursday and Sunday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-PRIMARY (San Francisco) _ In California's first open
primary election, ``people voted all over the map,'' said Kim
Alexander, director of the non-profit California Voter Foundation.
``A lot of voters thought it was fun to cross party lines and vote
on the other side.'' By ERIN McCORMICK and DIANA WALSH.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-SENATE (San Francisco) _ A surge of crossover votes from
Asian-American Democrats may have helped State Treasurer Matt Fong
edge car-alarm magnate Darrell Issa in the extraordinarily close
Republican U.S. Senate primary, an exit poll indicated. By LANCE
WILLIAMS.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-ANALYSIS (San Francisco) _ California to millionaire
candidates: You can't buy us. Well, you can buy us, but you have to
do it the old-fashioned way, the Gray Davis way, with
rubber-chicken dinners, pressed flesh and contributions from
big-money interests other than yourself. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-BILINGUAL (San Francisco) _ Proposition 227, which would
virtually replace bilingual education with one-year English
immersion classes starting in the fall, won by 61 to 39 percent of
the vote. By CAROL NESS.
</P>
<P>
   WILLIE-BROWN (San Francisco) _ San Francisco Mayor Willie
Brown's plans for Treasure Island and public financing for his
protocol office were rejected as San Francisco voters handed him a
pair of stinging defeats.By CHUCK FINNIE.
</P>
<P>
   JERRY-BROWN (Oakland, Calif.) _ Former California Gov. Jerry
Brown, calling his election as Oakland's next mayor the ``first
step,'' now has a tougher task ahead _ convincing city voters to
give him the tools he says he needs to transform the job from
ceremonial figurehead to chief executive officer. By KATHLEEN
SULLIVAN.
</P>
<P>
   NURSING-SHORTAGE (Houston) _ Hospital recruiters are offering
sign-up bonuses and flying to Canada to recruit applicants.
Analysts say the broader choices in the field are triggering the
shortages. And some analysts are warning that the current shortage
could explode into a crisis in 20 years. By MARY SIT-DuVALL. (Photo
available on the New York Times photo service)
</P>
<P>
   SKIN-CANCER (Albany, N.Y.) _ When he was diagnosed with a form
of skin cancer three years ago, Harry Livingston figured it might
be a death sentence. Livingston, 64, is lucky. His cancer was
detected early, when the chance of survival is as high as 95
percent. The key is early detection. This year, about 7,300
Americans will die from melanoma, which left untreated can spread.
By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BEETLE-PORT (Houston) _ Auto imports at the Port of Houston have
nearly doubled this year compared to the first four months of 1997,
and officials say its because of the new Volkswagen Beetles. The
Port of Houston is one of five ports in the country receiving the
Beetles. By JENALIA MORENO.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GEEZERS-MOVIES (Undated) _ Michael Douglas and Gwyneth Paltrow.
Jack Nicholson and Helen Hunt. Warren Beatty and Halle Berry. See
the trend here? There's a spate of movies out now featuring young
women and old men. It's not new, but it seems to be getting worse.
What does it mean? We ask experts _ and a few movie-goers. By
CLIFFORD PUGH.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SWEDISH-SUMMER (Stockholm, Sweden) _ One of the rewards of a
harsh winter is the prospect of a brilliant summer. Nowhere is that
more true than in Sweden, where the winters can be cold and dark
and cruel, and the summers ... well, the summers are like
wildflowers _ colorful, fragrant and short-lived. By SYD KEARNEY.
(Photo available on the New York Times photo service)
</P>
<P>
   WALES (Llangammarch, Wales) _ At a time when much of the world
is acquiescing to Anglo-American cultural hegemony, Wales seems to
be moving in the opposite direction. From the sign that greeted us
as we crossed the River Severn bridge _ ``Croeso I Cymru,''
``Welcome to Wales'' _ to the red-dragon flags, it was obvious that
Wales may be part of Great Britain, but it is not part of England.
By JOHN FLINN.
</P>
<P>
   With: WALES-INFO
</P>
<P>
   MYSTERY-CASTLE (Phoenix) _ An 8,000-square-foot native stone
castle stands in the foothills of a mountain range 10 miles south
of downtown Phoenix. The hand-built castle remains a mystery _ even
to its princess. By HARRY SHATTUCK. (Photo available on the New
York Times photo service)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Two weeks after the latest school
shooting, the networks are still doing specials on guns and
schools. Legislators in several states are proposing tough
punishment for juveniles who kill. The reality is that there are
very few school killings in the United States. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ What is this? The Northeast's
balmy winter, a vicious January ice storm in New York's North
Country and into Canada, a towering tornado in a rolling community
where none has ever formed before? Is this the product of Global
Warming? El Nino? Who knows? By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   NUKE-TESTS (Albany, N.Y.) _ The nuclear tests carried out by the
Indian government of India were in fact a desperate effort to
divert common people's attention from the government's own
political turmoil and coalition crises. The nuclear tests that were
readied by the previous centrist governments came in handy for the
present right-wing coalition. By PARTHA BANERJEE.
</P>
