<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 11:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1969 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REALLIFE04-COX     06-03 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REALLIFE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The search for simplicity -- not as easy as it looks
 &HT;    By Emily J. Minor
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A bowl with two peaches.
</P>
<P>
   Eight pebbles in a stone crock.
</P>
<P>
   A bottle of water. A single piece of perfect, perfect pie.
</P>
<P>
   I am reading a simple book, about simple living, called Pure
Style.
</P>
<P>
   You've seen the type. On page after pretty page, they show us
photos of perfect places, where there are no apples, forgotten and
moldy on the kitchen counter.
</P>
<P>
   No homework on the dining room table.
</P>
<P>
   No piles of clothes all over the bed and bedroom floor.
</P>
<P>
   No nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Just a bed made from tree branches. A night stand adorned with
one rose in a spare and linear vase. A glass pitcher with two
floating sprigs of mint. Everything is plain. Everything is simple.
</P>
<P>
   Simple is good.
</P>
<P>
   Simple is everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   But I have just a few _ yes, simple _ questions for the people
who think up these simple thoughts and take these pictures and
write these books and then, quite simply, make a bunch of money:
</P>
<P>
   People? Where do you put all your crap?
</P>
<P>
   OK, I confess. I went looking for them. But in one 10-minute
sprint through the office last week I collected a virtual library
of books outlining how I, a person who wears denim overalls to work
three days out of five, can simplify my life. What a bonanza! And I
didn't even have to take a simple little drive to Barnes &AMP; Noble.
</P>
<P>
   The Simpler Life. Pure Style. Pure Style Outdoors. Simplify Your
Life with Kids. Simplify Family Travel. And, my personal favorite,
Simple Curtains, although there is nothing simple about any of
these curtains, including the zigzag jobbies on Page 58, and I know
this because _ and pardon me if I digress and boast for a moment
here _ I made an actual tea towel in eighth-grade Home Economics.
</P>
<P>
   From Simple Curtains. Step 7: Place the front panel right side
down on top of the lining. Pin and baste the layers together,
taking in the piping. Using a piping foot (a piping foot????),
machine stitch all around the sides and along the zigzag bottom of
the valance. (Enough. Enough. If this was really a book on simple
curtains wouldn't it just say, ``Order all curtains with your
credit card from Pottery Barn?'')
</P>
<P>
   But I can't help sighing when I see this stuff. Beautiful stuff.
Quiet little corners with soft cushions and glasses of iced tea.
Simple stuff where even the yard tools are precious. An old rake. A
traditional pitchfork. A shovel with a heavy wooden handle, the
likes of which would probably be worth $100 at an antique fair
because it's so damn old. Soft colors, colors that won't be in the
Crayola box for another 10 years. It's all so inviting that on the
day the Crate &AMP; Barrel catalog arrives I cannot cook or clean or
supervise math problems. All I can do is drool because it's all so
cool.
</P>
<P>
   Maya Gottfried, a publicity assistant with Stewart, Tabori &AMP;
Chang in New York, which has published a series of books by Jane
Cumberbatch, ``a pioneer in the down-to-earth-approach to interior
design,'' says we people with the complicated lives eat this stuff
up. Although she is quick to point out that she does not follow the
Cumberbatch credo because she is (gasp) messy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's attractive and it's something everyone can do and those
elements combined make it an easy style for everybody,'' says
Gottfried, earning her New York City salary for the day.
</P>
<P>
   Right, easy style. Unless you are messy. Like Maya. And me.
</P>
<P>
   So, why? Why do I wish my back yard looked more like these sweet
little scenes and less like the Clampetts'?
</P>
<P>
   Is it because my life is too complicated? Is it because I have
good taste? Could I be the long-forgotten daughter of an old Amish
farmer?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps I will find the complicated answer to this simple
question by reading an actual review of an actual book called The
Natural Home: Living the Simple Life:
</P>
<P>
   A sofa slipcovered in khaki sits next to a wicker table holding
a creamy tableau: a candlestick lamp, a crock filled with
wildflowers and Queen Anne's lace, seashells and a pair of baby
shoes. The Queen Anne-style chair painted white is dressed with a
delicately flounced gray-and-white-striped seat cover, and a rustic
folding table is just wide enough for a stack of coffee-table books
or a tray set for afternoon tea.
</P>
<P>
   Afternoon tea? A-ha. It dawns on me. No one has afternoon tea!
We might have coffee. We might have a Diet Pepsi. We might even
have a beer if it's a Saturday. But, afternoon tea? I don't think
so.
</P>
<P>
   People, it's all a scam. And the minute you open the door to
that armoire on Page 66 you will find the homework and the old
bowls of ice cream and heaven knows what else. A body or two?
</P>
<P>
   Life, you see, is not simple. It is roller skates in the laundry
room and three good books, each with a dog-eared page to alert you
where to start again, on the floor next to your bed. It is today's
mail and tomorrow's homework on the table by the front door. It is
a scooter in the driveway, right next to the two weeks' worth of
recycling.
</P>
<P>
   Life, when you live it, is cluttered and messy and complicated.
Indeed, all this clutter, all these complications, all this mess,
is what I've hoped for since I was 10. A husband with big feet who
leaves his tennis shoes in front of the couch every night. A
7-year-old who deposits his wet towel on the wood floor every
morning. These are the lovely signs that I've made it! I'm happy!
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the day I wake up and find two polished stones and a
wilted mint leaf on my nightstand is the day I'll realize, dear
God, it's finally happened:
</P>
<P>
   I've turned into a simpleton with no life.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
