<HEADLINE>
ATTN EDITORS:  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Graphics and photos are being sent to NYT clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 For Immediate Release
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; World-renowned Harvard University is an institution increasinly
under siege. From its immense endowment to its prestigious faculty
to its worldwide influence to the quality of its undergraduate
education, what some consider the world's greatest university often
finds itself on the defensive these days. In a four-part series,
Globe staff writers John Yemma and Daniel Golden take an in-depth
look at what's happening at the University on the Charles.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HARVARD-I-SPCL (Undated) _ With an endowment of nearly $13
billion, Harvard is far and away the richest university in America.
But critics say Harvard is obsessed with fund-raising and regards
its wealth not just as a means to providing the best education for
its students but as an end in itself. PHOTO, GRAPHIC: 13p6 x 12
inches, ``Harvard's financial philosophy.'' (3 takes)
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   HARVARD-RUDENSTINE-SPCL (Undated) _ Since taking over in 1991,
Harvard president Neil Rudenstine has guided a remarkably
successful fund-raising drive that benefited from the stock market
boom. But critics say he doesn't like to say no _ especially to the
powerful deans of Harvard's 12 schools. 1100 words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   HARVARD-II-SPCL (Undated) _ Given the breadth of its involvement
in so many different arenas in so many countries _ plus the large
number of Harvard graduates in influential positions in Washington
and abroad _ Harvard is now functioning as a seedbed for the global
leadership class. PHOTO; GRAPHIC: 43 picas x 4 inches, ``Harvard's
global reach.'' (3 takes)
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   HARVARD-INVEST-SPCL (Undated) _ Like Harvard's academic
influence, its financial tentacles extend far beyond Cambridge. Its
hidden realm ranges from oil wells to women's cosmetics, auto
dealerships to Internet search engines, luxury apartments to
subsidized housing. GRAPHIC: 29 picas x 11 inches, ``Priceless
possessions.'' 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   HARVARD-III-SPCL (Undated) _ As other universities rethink
tenure, or placing teaching on a par with research, Harvard clings
to a system that anoints a select group of scholar-kings, and
consigns everyone else to also-ran status, a practice that creates
poor morale and intellectual stagnation. GRAPHIC: 39 picas x 13
inches, ``The lost history department.'' (3 takes)
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   HARVARD-INSIDE-SPCL (Undated) _ At Harvard, power struggles,
personal animosities, and turf wars fester unchecked in the
university's specialized, subterranean bastions where outsiders
rarely stray. GRAPHIC: 72 picas x 3 inches, ``Harvard's
decentralized baronies.'' 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   HARVARD-SPACE-SPCL (Undated) _ Unlike competitors Stanford and
Duke, which enjoy thousands of acres of elbow room, Harvard is
hemmed into 446 acres in Boston and Cambridge. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   HARVARD-IV-SPCL (Undated) _ Harvard is an excellent research
university, a first-class name, a well-endowed treasure in American
higher education. But it is not, experts say, the place to go for
an undergraduate education that emphasizes intimate scholarly
contact, risk-taking, and intuitive thinking. GRAPHIC: 28 picas x 6
inches, ``Top choice.'' (3 takes)
</P>
<P>
