<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-CONSULATES-COX </SLUG>
    
 &HT;     ISRAELI GOVERNMENT HOLDS OFF ON CLOSING CONSULATES IN U.S.
 &HT;     By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has
``frozen'' budget-cutting proposals that might have closed Israel's
consulate in Atlanta, a spokesman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Atlanta-area Jewish community were protesting the
suggestions after they surfaced in a report in an Israeli newspaper
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But, Netanyahu spokesman David Bar-Illan said the prime minister
had decided earlier in the week to postpone any consulate closings
and look for other ways for the Israeli Foreign Ministry to meet
across-the-board budget cuts set out by the country's finance
ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have frozen all the closures,'' Bar-Illan said. ``We're
starting from square one again ... we feel that we'll have to find
another way to meet the budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel keeps 10 consulates and one embassy in the United States
and has 107 missions around the world, according to Foreign
Ministry Spokesman Aviv Shir-On. The Atlanta consulate serves five
states.
</P>
<P>
   He said staff in the ministry suggested more than 20 Israeli
missions that could be closed to save money, but the proposals were
in discussions, not a formal plan or memo.
</P>
<P>
   Shir-On said Israel, a country of just 6 million people,
supports more missions than most countries its size but has so far
avoided closing any.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu has filled in as foreign minister since David Levy
resigned from the job several months ago. Bar-Illan said he
reviewed the budget-cutting proposal last week and decided to hold
off.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Atlanta consulate was important because several
large companies that do business in Israel, including Coca-Cola,
Home Depot and BellSouth, are based there.
</P>
<P>
   Also, he called the southern United States ``important
politically'' for Israel. He said he believes some Christian
Zionist groups, in addition to local Jewish groups, objected to the
possibility of closing the consulate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For clients of the New York Times News Service &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
