<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 12:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1993 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARVARD-RUDENSTEIN-SP     06-03 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-RUDENSTEIN-SPCL-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT TAKES HEAT FOR SLOWED PACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DANIEL GOLDEN   AND JOHN YEMMA  
 c.1997 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; After President Neil Rudenstine stunned Harvard by taking a
three-month leave of absence for exhaustion in 1994-95, he relaxed
his pace and delegated more tasks. Now, concerns about his
well-being have given way to complaints about his laissez-faire
management style and seeming reluctance to fight for his vision.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Since taking over in 1991, he has guided a remarkably
successful fund-raising drive. But critics say he's such a nice guy
that he doesn't like to say no _ especially to the powerful deans
of Harvard's 12 schools. They say he's missed opportunities to lead
on a range of issues, including the integration of computers into
teaching and reform of the university's governing structure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harvard needed a leader who would push ideas that are new and
different and require a change in the way people think about the
university,'' says Jerry R. Green, a Harvard Business School
professor who spent two years as Rudenstine's first provost. ``Neil
Rudenstine has not met that standard.''
</P>
<P>
   Counters the current provost, Harvey V. Fineberg: ``He has
constantly turned the crank without creating confrontation. Neil's
presidency has never been about Neil. It's always been about
Harvard.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudenstine, 63, was paid $270,057 in 1997 _ modest compared to
other Ivy League presidents _ plus free use of a mansion off
Brattle Street and $28,107 in benefits. He also has $227,000 in
outstanding loans from Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Approachable and unassuming, Rudenstine has the slightly
absent-minded manner of the Renaissance scholar he once was. He
often arrived late at key meetings before hiring Jacqueline O'Neill
as his staff director. The daughter-in-law of the legendary
politician, Thomas P. ``Tip'' O'Neill Jr., now makes sure he sticks
to a schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Rudenstine still works as many as 85 hours a week, and &UR;  &LR; accepts
so many speaking invitations that he's booked until the year 2000.
He writes speeches in longhand at his desk, and tends to rush
through his delivery as he peers at his audience over his glasses.
He's a voluminous practitioner of the near-forgotten art of writing
letters.
</P>
<P>
   Although not naturally outgoing, he mingles with the Harvard
community. &UR;  &LR; He holds office hours for students, and often brings
pizzas and Cokes to freshmen who live in a dormitory above his
Massachusetts Hall office. As a former dean of students at
Princeton in the turbulent '60s, Rudenstine excels at calming
aggrieved students and alumni. Like another president, he feels
their pain.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Professor Henry Louis Gates Jr., Rudenstine  &UR;  &LR;  has
recruited an unprecedented array of black scholars. And unlike his
predecessor, Derek Bok, Rudenstine relishes one key task:
fund-raising. While Bok was uncomfortable begging, Rudenstine
enjoys making donors' dreams come true. When
publisher-philanthropist Walter Annenberg expressed a desire to
help freshmen, Rudenstine proposed a three-pronged gift _ for
financial aid, seminars, and a new dining commons. Annenberg handed
over $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Rudenstine has rarely devoted his fund-raising skills to the
ventures that form the cornerstone of his oft-expressed vision of a
more unified Harvard. Contributions have lagged for the
interfaculty initiatives that cross the entrenched boundaries of
Harvard's fiefdoms.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say that he's afraid of challenging the deans, while
supporters say he's just unselfish. ``The president doesn't like to
ask for himself,'' says one staffer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Beyond Harvard, Rudenstine has kept a low profile on most
education issues, such as the furor over testing of Massachusetts
schoolchildren. He has lobbied to preserve affirmative action in
student admissions and increase government funding for scientific
research.
</P>
<P>
   Rudenstine acknowledges that he had a difficult transition to
Harvard, where he received his doctorate before leaving as an
assistant professor in 1968. Returning as an outsider in 1991, he
faced immediate pressures.
</P>
<P>
   The budget was running a deficit, the endowment suffered from
poor investments, and eight major administrative slots were vacant
_ all as the university was gearing up for a fund-raising campaign.
He couldn't afford to make a mistake _ or take a vacation. After
oversleeping and missing a flight to a fund-raising event in New
York, he realized he needed a break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't collapse my whole calendar for one or two weeks to
go away,'' he says. ``There was too much hanging on it. I was no
longer 30, I was no longer 40, I was no longer 50, I was well along
in my 50s when I took the job, and 30 months of that was just
sleep-depriving. So I raised up and said, `Look, I'm not doing
myself any good, I'm not going to be able to do the university any
good unless I can really get rest.'''
</P>
<P>
   When he returned from his leave, he says, he realized he had
already made most of the hard decisions. The jobs were filled, the
endowment was flourishing, the campaign was humming. He immediately
scheduled a month's vacation for the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Rudenstine says, he's had ``four or five very
fruitful years.'' Fineberg and O'Neill have assumed much of the
workload, along with assistant Marc Goodheart, who collaborates on
many of Rudenstine's speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Their boss remains a gentle, bookish conciliator _ the polar
opposite of a certain outspoken, swaggering former college
president on the other side of the Charles River. Contrasting him
with John Silber and the Boston University leadership, one Harvard
administrator says, ``I can't imagine Neil abolishing the football
team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
