 c.1998 Medical Tribune News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the Medical Tribune News Service stories for Wednesday,
June 3, 1998. If you have questions about the availability of this
service, contact Bob Farnell at the New York Times Syndicate
(800)-535-4425.
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-HEART-MED _ EMBARGOED FOR RELEASE WEDNESDAY AT 5 P.M.
EASTERN _ A new study offers compelling evidence that the
underlying processes causing heart disease begin during childhood.
</P>
<P>
   And as the number of heart disease risk factors increases, so
does the severity of heart disease in young people, according to a
new report based on the autopsies of 93 people ages 2 through 39.
</P>
<P>
   The findings, which appear in Thursday's issue of The New
England Journal of Medicine, are likely to re-fuel a debate on when
heart disease prevention strategies and screening tests should be
implemented.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, researchers compared risk factors for heart
disease _ smoking, elevated cholesterol levels, high blood pressure
and sedentary lifestyle _ with the extent of plaque build-up in the
heart arteries among the patients, all of whom lost their lives due
to various causes, primarily trauma.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interventions related to modifiable risk factors, such as the
prevention of smoking, weight control, and the encouragement of
physical exercise and a prudent diet, if undertaken early in life,
may retard the development of atherosclerosis,'' or hardening of
the heart arteries, according to the study authors.(500 WORDS)
</P>
<P>
   ESTROGEN-INCONTINENCE-MED _ EMBARGOED FOR RELEASE WEDNESDAY AT 4
P.M .EASTERN _ SAN DIEGO _ A new study finds that estrogen
supplements are an effective and inexpensive way to significantly
reduce urinary incontinence in menopausal women, Canadian
researchers reported here.
</P>
<P>
   Women ages 62 through 72 given estrogen via an estradiol vaginal
ring experienced significantly fewer episodes of urinary
incontinence and complete resolution of symptoms including painful
urination and frequency of urgency compared to those treated with
placebo, reported Dr. Lynn Stothers of Vancouver. Estradiol is a
synthetic form of the female hormone estrogen.
</P>
<P>
   And 70 percent of women treated with the estrogen therapy
reported a more than 25 percent improvement in their quality of
life compared to only 20 percent among those treated with placebo.
The lifetime cost of using the estradiol ring was $4,500 per
patient compared to $21,500 for women taking a placebo. Part of the
reduced cost was due to the women's less frequent use of protective
garments.
</P>
<P>
   The estradiol ring provides a continuous dose of 2 milligrams
per day of estrogen and lasts for three months.
</P>
<P>
   Stothers is expected to present her findings Wednesday at the
annual meeting of the American Urological Association. (500 WORDS)
(DEVELOPING)
</P>
<P>
   OPTIMISM-IMMUNITY-MED _ Optimism under stress may improve more
than a person's mood _ a new study suggests that it may also boost
the immune system, or at least ward off the immune-related effects
of stress.
</P>
<P>
   Among 50 first-year law students, those who began the semester
confident that they would succeed had more white blood cells known
as helper T cells than more pessimistic students midway through the
semester. At the beginning of the semester, both groups had nearly
identical levels, noted lead researcher Suzanne Segerstrom, who is
now an assistant professor of psychology at the University of
Kentucky in Lexington.
</P>
<P>
   Helper T cells are the ``conductors'' of the immune system, and
help direct and amplify the body's reaction against foreign agents
such as bacteria or viruses.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, other white blood cells that can kill cancer cells
in the laboratory, known as natural killer cells, were more
effective in optimistic students mid-semester than in pessimistic
students.
</P>
<P>
   This suggests that optimism may affect physical health as well
as psychological health when healthy people are exposed to stress,
according to the report, which appears in the June issue of the
Journal of Personality and Social Psychology. (500 WORDS)
</P>
<P>
   HIV-SURVEY-MED _ WASHINGTON _ A survey of physicians reveals
that many are not treating patients with HIV and AIDS according to
recommended national guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Leading AIDS physicians, including Dr. John Bartlett, chief of
the infectious disease division at Johns Hopkins University, and
Dr. Paul Volberding, professor of medicine at the University of
California, San Francisco, are expected to discuss why doctors
might not be following these guidelines and potential solutions to
make sure each AIDS patient receives the best possible treatment.
(500 WORDS) (DEVELOPING)
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION-ADVICE-MED _ Dietitian Karen Collins of the American
Institute for Cancer Research answers nutrition questions. This
week:
</P>
<P>
   _ How does diet compare to family history and other risk factors
in terms of breast cancer?
</P>
<P>
   _ How can a person maintain a healthy diet if food allergies
require them to avoid certain food groups?
</P>
<P>
   _ It seems that obesity among children is becoming more common.
Why? (500 WORDS)
</P>
</TEXT>
