</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALES-3TAKES-$ADV07-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALES: POETRY IN MOTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 7)   (EDs: With WALES-INFO)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN FLINN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LLANGAMMARCH, Wales _ What in the name of David Lloyd George is
coming out of my television set? The picture _ of a rugby game _ is
perfectly clear, but the sound seems hopelessly, bizarrely,
garbled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ac mae Neil Jenkins newdd drosi cais,'' says the announcer,
``i Bontypridd yn erbyn Llanelli.'' (As it's later translated for
me: ``... and Neil Jenkins has just converted a goal for Pont y
Pridd against Llanelli.'')
</P>
<P>
   What I am hearing is, by some accounts, the oldest spoken
language in Europe, a tongue heard in this misty and mountainous
country since the time of the Roman legions. What I am hearing is
the voice of an ancient and storied culture.
</P>
<P>
   What I am hearing is ``Cymraeg'' _ Welsh.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when much of the world is acquiescing to _ if not
downright welcoming _ Anglo-American cultural hegemony, Wales seems
to be moving in the opposite direction, slowly but inexorably
reasserting its Welshness.
</P>
<P>
   From the sign that greeted us as we crossed the River Severn
bridge _ ``Croeso I Cymru,'' ``Welcome to Wales'' _ to the
red-dragon flags flapping from the battlements of crumbling
castles, to the newly built Druid stone circles in the villages, it
was obvious that Wales may be part of Great Britain, but _ as the
Welsh will be the first to tell you _ it is most definitely not
part of England.
</P>
<P>
   After more than 700 years of trying to remake Wales in its own
image, London has in recent years reversed course, permitting the
Welsh to vote on a measure of self-rule, which they narrowly
approved last year, and spending $120 million a year to broadcast
television in Welsh. (To hear it, turn to channel 4 in Wales; it's
called S4C.) In part because of this, the number of Welsh speakers,
which for years had held steady at 20 percent of Wales' population,
is actually on the upswing.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Americans, I tended to think of Wales _ when I thought
of it at all _ as a loosely defined place, somewhere west of
London, where Prince Charles reigned: a place where he could
practice in relative obscurity before becoming the British monarch.
</P>
<P>
   I tended to think of Wales as the home of the singer Tom Jones,
the actor Richard Burton and the singing coal miners of the film
``How Green Was My Valley.'' I tended to think of it as a place
whose language, with its confounding clusters of consonants, looks
like my tray in Scrabble after a particularly bad draw. (Think I'm
exaggerating? The Welsh word for beer is ``cwrw.'')
</P>
<P>
   And, like most Americans, I hardly ever went there. Of the 3.4
million U.S. citizens who visited Great Britain last year, only
about 170,000 made it to Wales. Most of them toured the rural
north; on this trip I wanted to see the more populated south, with
its old coal-mining valleys, its Dylan Thomas seaside villages and
its capital city, Cardiff, the future home of Wales' new national
assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Heading west on the M4 motorway from London, I crossed the River
Severn bridge, entered Wales and almost immediately encountered a
castle. Chepstow Castle, guarding the old strategic crossing of the
River Wye, was begun by William the Conqueror's troops in 1067, one
year after the Battle of Hastings.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the others, it was built in a
not-entirely-successful attempt to subdue the Welsh.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 200 stone fortresses in its 8,000 square miles,
Wales claims to be the most densely castled place on Earth. This
will give you some idea of how common they are: Bernard Llewellyn's
father-in-law bought one by mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Carreg Cennen, standing acropolis-like on a hilltop above the
tiny hamlet of Trapp, was built in 1248 as a Welsh stronghold. It
fell into English hands 30 years later and stayed there, more or
less, until Llewellyn's father-in-law came along in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   By then the castle, in ruins, was part of a vast estate
belonging to the ninth Earl of Cawdor, whose distant predecessor
figures prominently in Shakespeare's Macbeth. Financial trouble
forced the earl to sell off parts of his estate, and when
Llewellyn's family bought a parcel it discovered to its surprise
that the deed included the castle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody thought much about it for a long time,'' Llewellyn told
me over a steaming cup of tea in his shop. ``Then the earl came
back and said he'd never meant to include the castle in the sale.
He tried to buy it back, but my father-in-law would have none of
it. Carreg Cennen was finally back in Welsh hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Another castle that has figured prominently in Wales in recent
years is Caernarfon, in north Wales, where Charles was invested as
Prince of Wales in 1969. Since its construction in 1281 it has
served as a symbol of English domination over the Welsh. The
following year, the English defeated Llewellen ap Gruffydd, the
last Welsh Prince of Wales, and, ever since then, the title has
gone to the heir to the English throne.
</P>
<P>
   It's an entirely ceremonial appellation; Charles, Prince of
Wales, actually has no official standing in Wales. Still, for Welsh
nationalists, this is a recurring thorn in the side. Perhaps it's
no coincidence that the Welsh nationalist movement is strongest
around Caernarfon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody here considers Charles our prince,'' a man told me one
night in a pub near Cardiff. ``He's not a bad fellow _ he's managed
to learn a few words of our language and he visits more often than
some of the others. But nobody in the royal family maintains an
official residence here.''
</P>
<P>
   The official capital of Wales is not Caernarfon, but Cardiff.
It's a young city by British standards: in 1800 it was a fishing
village with fewer than 1,900 residents. Cardiff is often dismissed
as not very Welsh and not very interesting _ the latter charge, I
thought, rather unfair. Its thriving downtown is an appealing mix
of Victorian, Georgian and Edwardian architecture, and its National
Museum of Wales houses a surprisingly good collection of Monets,
Renoirs, Cezannes _ and what is believed by some to be Van Gogh's
last painting.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   The impressionist collection, the gleaming white-stone building
that houses it and pretty much everything else in Cardiff owe their
existence to the dirty-black substance once found in great seams
deep beneath the valleys to the north. Most of the coal extracted
from southern Wales _ a third of the entire world's supply _ was
shipped through the docks of Cardiff, transforming it from a sleepy
backwater into one of the world's busiest ports.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of the docks, the wealthy and eccentric third Marquis
of Bute, also owned the castle in town, and in the late 1800s he
hired an even more eccentric architect, William Burges, to help him
spruce it up.
</P>
<P>
   Burges had a fondness for smoking opium and walking around town
with a parrot on his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   One chamber of his castle is an exquisitely detailed celebration
of Chaucer; another is filled with sensuous Islamic wood carvings.
The marquis looked over the artisans' shoulders constantly during
construction, and when the rooms were completed he never set foot
in them.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the castle, in a vast park incorporating its old
grounds, stands a circle of Druid stones, looking a bit like a
low-budget Stonehenge. I assumed they were ancient until our guide,
Emyr Griffith, told me they were installed in recent years for an
``eisteddfod,'' the annual Welsh cultural festival held at a
different site each year in August.
</P>
<P>
   At these festivals, which include music, dance, poetry and other
arts, Wales invokes its ancient Celtic heritage with Druid rituals
and pageantry. Participants attend ceremonies in robes and hoods,
and young maidens dance with flowers and mistletoe; the president
of the eisteddfod is called the Archdruid.
</P>
<P>
   It's a pointed reminder that the culture of Wales predates the
Anglo-Saxons, the Normans, even the Romans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The coal mines that built Cardiff have nearly all shut down, but
today the city is enjoying new prosperity as the burgeoning
political capital of Wales. A number of government and media
institutions have moved there from London, and construction will
begin soon on a hall for the new national assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of growing political confidence are everywhere. Alongside
the Union Jack _ and sometimes independent of it _ flaps the
red-dragon flag of Wales, which is believed to be a direct
descendant of a Roman standard. Outside the museum stands a statue
of the most famous Welsh politician of them all, David Lloyd
George, the only Welshman ever to serve as British prime minister,
from 1916 to 1922.
</P>
<P>
   He is a hero in Wales, and the sight of the statue caused
Griffith to break out into the old Welsh schoolboy song, ``Lloyd
George Knew My Father.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the following day we were in Swansea, Wales'
second city, when word came down that it had lost out to its bitter
rival, Cardiff, as the home for the national assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wrong! Wrong! Wrong!'' screamed a headline in the
Swansea-based South Wales Evening Post, a newspaper that once
employed a cub reporter named Dylan Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Swansea has a bit of an inferiority complex, which has not been
helped by Thomas' oft-repeated description of it as an ``ugly,
lovely town.'' The phrase, it must be said, is fairly apt. Bombed
heavily by the Nazis during World War II, it was rebuilt at a time
that surely will not go down as a golden age of architecture. Yet
Swansea has a roguish charm, and, as its residents rarely tire of
pointing out, it's much more Welsh than Cardiff. You're more likely
to hear people speaking Cymraeg there.
</P>
<P>
   We spent a morning at the Dylan Thomas Centre, a museum and arts
center devoted to Swansea's most famous native son. The poet may be
more closely associated with the town of Laugharne, where he did
much of his writing, but he was born, raised and schooled in
Swansea.
</P>
<P>
   In the Thomas center, Pat Hughes, a former city council member,
and Vyz Jones staged an impromptu, 15-minute recitation of part of
Thomas' ``Under the Milk Wood Tree,'' a BBC radio play depicting a
day in the life of LLareggub, a fictional southern Welsh seaside
town. Hughes pointed out that the impish Thomas intentionally chose
the town's name, which is ``bugger all'' spelled backwards. (The
BBC changed the spelling to Llaregyb in its promotional
literature.)
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   Thomas knew little of the Welsh language _ when he was growing
up students who dared speak it in class were marched off to the
headmaster's office _ but the rhythms, cadences and bold words he
used were pure Welsh in style. He's regarded as one of the finest
products of a country that takes its poetry seriously _ Wales'
national anthem proclaims it ``gwlad beirdd a chantorion, enwogion
of fri'' (``land of poets, singers and eminent men'').
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like John Steinbeck in Salinas, Thomas is beloved much more in
his home town in death than he ever was in life. ``When he lived
here he was thought of as a drunkard, a womanizer and a sponger,''
acknowledged Hughes. One exhibit in the museum appears to confirm
two out of three: It is Thomas' long and detailed liquor bill,
marked ``cf'' for ``carried forward,'' or unpaid.
</P>
<P>
   One day we drove up through one of the great coal valleys to the
town of Blaenafon. The landscape surprised me: I'd expected to see
slag heaps, scarred hillsides and other industrial-age desolation.
But the countryside was verdant and pastoral. Only the
grass-covered lumps of the old slag heaps gave any hint of what
once transpired here.
</P>
<P>
   In the 20 years since the coal mines shut down, the countryside
of ``How Green Was My Valley'' has become green once again.
</P>
<P>
   On a hillside above town we donned miners' helmets, headlamps
and heavy battery packs and descended 300 feet into the Earth. Big
Pit, once one of south Wales' most productive coal mines, is now
one of its prime tourist attractions.
</P>
<P>
   Like everyone else who works there, our guide, Terry Mason, is a
former miner. ``See that?'' he said, pointing to a 3-foot-high
alcove cut into a shiny black wall of coal. ``I worked in spaces
just like that for seven years.''
</P>
<P>
   As we walked through the dank, dripping tunnels of the old mine,
Mason explained that children as young as six once worked all day
in pitch-darkness, opening and closing doors for ponies pulling
coal trains. Methane explosions were a constant threat, and the
mine used the proverbial canaries to detect the gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their metabolism is faster than ours, so they'd pass out first
if the methane got too high,'' he said. ``We wouldn't just leave
them to die _ we'd carry them up to the surface.''
</P>
<P>
   In the mine's museum is a box with an oxygen cylinder used to
revive the little birds.
</P>
<P>
   At its height, around World War I, Big Pit employed nearly 1,500
miners working in three shifts. It shut down in 1980, exactly a
century after it opened, and reopened three years later as a
tourist site. It now employs about 50 former miners.
</P>
<P>
   After Mason had finished telling us about the long hours of
back-breaking labor, the low pay, the omnipresent coal dust and the
constant threat of accidents, I asked him what it was like the day
the mine shut down. He looked me straight in the eye and said: ``It
was the saddest day of my life,'' and I believed him.
</P>
<P>
   One drizzly night we drove up the most famous coal valley of
them all, the Rhondda, to the town of Treorchy. In a little stone
schoolhouse, stout, barrel-chested men in their 50s and 60s were
filing in and taking their places in concentric half-circles.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly unemployed coal miners, these men are members of the
world-renowned Treorchy Men's Choir. ``In the old days we used to
sing together in the pits,'' one of them, Meurig Hughes, told me.
</P>
<P>
   Begun in 1883 as a way to keep miners out of trouble, the choir
has performed for royalty, toured the United States and recorded
with Ella Fitzgerald and local-boy-made-good Tom Jones. It has
produced 46 records and CDs, making it possibly the most-recorded
male choir in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all proceeds from recordings and performances go to
charity.
</P>
<P>
   As the men took their places for their weekly rehearsal, I
couldn't help concluding that the choir has filled a huge void in
their lives, sustaining a sense of purpose and community since the
closing of the mines.
</P>
<P>
   In blue jeans and sweat shirts, hands clasped behind their
backs, the men peered through bifocals at their sheet music. They
sang in English and Welsh, but it was the latter that captivated
me. Spoken Welsh does not fall sweetly on my ear, but as the mens'
voices blended and echoed off the wooden floor and metal pipes of
the schoolhouse, the sound was hauntingly beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah, Welsh,'' Hughes said during a break. ``We call it the
language of heaven.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
