<SLUG> BC-WALES-INFO-$ADV07-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT TO SEE AND DO IN WALES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 7)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Getting there: Although Cardiff has an international airport, it
gets few flights from the United States. A better bet is to fly to
London's Heathrow airport and proceed to Wales from there. A speedy
hourly shuttle train connects London with Cardiff, as do frequent
buses. Cardiff is about two hours west of London on the M-4
motorway.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay: For a free fold-out Wales Bed and Breakfast
Touring Map, call the British Tourist Authority's toll-free number
(800-462-2748). A booklet called ``Welsh Rarebits'' highlights
upscale country inns, many of them in former manor houses. To get
one, call the toll-free BTA number or send a fax toll-free to
800-873-7140.
</P>
<P>
   Dylan Thomas Centre: It is located at Somerset Place in Swansea;
phone: 011-44-1792-463-980. For information about tours and
performances of ``Under the Milk Wood Tree,'' call
011-44-1792-202-208; fax: 011-44-1792-422-423.
</P>
<P>
   Big Pit: The Big Pit mine is located near the town of Blaenafon,
about 12 miles north of Newport. Admission: 5.50 pounds ($9.15) for
adults, 3.75 pounds ($6.25) for children. Open March to October,
9:30 a.m. to 5 p.m. daily. (The last underground tour begins at
3:30 p.m.) For possible winter openings and other information, call
011-44-1495-790-311.
</P>
<P>
   Choir: The Treorchy Men's Choir rehearses Tuesdays and Thursdays
from 7:30 to 9:30 p.m., except holidays and the month of August, at
Treorchy Primary School in the town of Treorchy. For more
information about performances, contact Islwyn Morgan, 4 Matexa
St., Tom Pentre, CF417HJ, Wales, United Kingdom; phone:
011-44-1443-435-852.
</P>
<P>
   For more information: Contact the British Tourist Authority, 551
Fifth Ave., Suite 701, New York, NY 10176-0799; phone:
800-462-2748.
</P>
</TEXT>
