</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MYSTERY-CASTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAND-BUILT CASTLE REMAINS A MYSTERY _ EVEN TO ITS PRINCESS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photo available on NYT photo service) 
 
By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ As a child, Mary Lou Gulley would build sand castles
on the beach near her Seattle home. And she would sit on her
father's lap, listening to stories about dragons and princesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please, Daddy, build me a big and strong castle someday that I
can live in,'' she remembers pleading almost seven decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   But then Daddy ran away.
</P>
<P>
   For 16 years, Mary Lou Gulley and her mother, Francis, were
unaware of Boyce Gulley's whereabouts. They were unaware that when
informed by doctors that he had tuberculosis, Gulley fled toward
the desert to spare his family his burden.
</P>
<P>
   They also were unaware that he was hand-building his daughter's
castle in the foothills of a mountain range 10 miles south of
downtown Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Combining wit, ingenuity and hard work with knowledge gained
from two years of architectural studies at Texas A&AMP;M University,
Gulley meticulously constructed an 8,000-square-foot native stone
castle that includes 18 rooms; 13 fireplaces; a mind-boggling
hodgepodge of arches, parapets, bell towers, columns, sun decks,
stairways and trap doors; eclectic interior decorations bought or
borrowed from old railroad depots, from Mexican or Indian
marketplaces, from the vast desert landscape or from Gulley's
imagination. ...
</P>
<P>
   And now a real-life princess.
</P>
<P>
   Since learning of her father's adventure following his death
from cancer in 1945, Mary Lou Gulley has reigned over her castle.
She has lived here year-round, conducting tours nine months a year,
four days a week, to make ends meet. She introduces visitors to a
remarkable, one-of-a-kind home known as the Mystery Castle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here is the chapel; over there is the bar,'' she says. ``This
room in between, we call purgatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what my father meant by the room located nine
feet beneath the trap door in purgatory. He called it the
inlaw-outlaw room. We use it for guests who like to stay more than
three days.''
</P>
<P>
   A tombstone is positioned near the bar. The inscription: ``From
beer to eternity.'' Nearby, a makeshift bed: ``Bunks for drunks,''
Gulley explains.
</P>
<P>
   An 1860s pump organ still functions in the foyer leading to the
chapel. ``It was the first in the Tombstone Territory,'' the
Mystery Castle princess says. ``It was once played by the chocolate
widow. She supposedly killed six husbands with her chocolate cake.
And I've got the recipe.''
</P>
<P>
   Couples come from miles around to get married in the chapel.
``We give the bride the chocolate recipe,'' Gulley says, ``and we
show the groom the trap door.''
</P>
<P>
   Each room is striking in its originality. And its practicality.
</P>
<P>
   A circular window is made from wire-wheel rims of the Stutz
Bearcat Boyce Gulley drove to Arizona. Another set of windows is
made from old refrigerator dishes originally intended for storing
food. A two-level bedroom is built around the skeleton of an
enormous saguaro cactus. A brass bed is constructed on tracks so
that it can be rolled away and hidden in a wall.
</P>
<P>
   Built-in tequila bottles help stabilize the bar. The 13
fireplaces serve both as structural pillars and as an effective
heating mechanism on chilly evenings, and sunken conversation pits
beside them are considered forerunners of modern architecture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, they'd call this organic architecture,'' Gulley says.
``It's the first totally recycled castle in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at these bricks my father used,'' she says. ``They're
rejects from the kiln. In his day, they were called clinkers. Then
Frank Lloyd Wright started using them, and now they're called
expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Gulley, Wright and Boyce Gulley became friends and
learned from each other. Unlike Wright's, her father's legacy is
concentrated on this one contribution, but the Mystery Castle's
unique architecture has received numerous regional and national
awards.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, it's pure fun. Mary Lou Gulley points to a sign
fronting a steep, twisting, free-standing outdoor staircase that
says: ``If these stairs you dare to climb, you'll be pushing up
daisies before your time.''
</P>
<P>
   The main wonder is that Boyce Gulley labored alone in building
the Mystery Castle, logging water from nearby canals and mixing
native caliche with goats' milk, a technique he learned from
American Indians.
</P>
<P>
   He constructed almost every room on a different level and with
an individual shape, whimsically including secret nooks and
crannies _ and, yes, those trap doors. There was no running water;
indeed, Gulleyand her mother lived there for a quarter-century
before water and electricity became available.
</P>
<P>
   Boyce Gulley toiled part time as a shoe salesman to earn money
to pay for materials and for artifacts associated with desert life
_ and, as his daughter puts it, his dreams.
</P>
<P>
   The setting was _ and is _ spectacular: Even as the
Phoenix-Scottsdale area continues to expand, the Mystery Castle
stands alone _ save for the green cactuses that seem to spread
forever _ on the edge of a hillside, affording a wondrous panorama
of the sprawling metropolis.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Lou Gulley opens her home to visitors October through
June,11 a.m.-4 p.m. Thursdays through Sundays. She guides tours in
small groups. Cost is $4 for adults, with discounts for children.
</P>
<P>
   From the downtown area, drive south on Seventh Avenue (with one
easy zigzag at Baseline Road) to the foothills of 16,500-acre South
Mountain Park, about 10 miles. Turn left (east) on Mineral Road;
you will see the castle, and ample parking is provided.
</P>
<P>
   For information, write to Mystery Castle, 800 E. Mineral Road,
Phoenix, Ariz., 85040. Or call 602-254-6500 for information on this
and other Phoenix-area attractions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
