<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2059 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWEDISH-SUMMER-ART-HN     06-03 1354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWEDISH-SUMMER-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOW BOAT, WARM CREW ALL YOU NEED FOR STOCKHOLM ARCHIPELAGO TOUR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photo available on NYT photo service) 
 
(Eds.: adiaeresis, or two dot marks, needed over first a in Malaren
and a in Vardshus; odiaeresis mark, or two dots, goes over o in
Bullero) 
 
By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKHOLM, Sweden _ One of the rewards of a harsh winter is the
prospect of a brilliant summer.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is that more true than in Sweden, where the winters can
be cold and dark and cruel, and the summers ... well, the summers
are like wildflowers _ colorful, fragrant and short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   So the Swedes do not waste a minute of summer, rising early for
work, stopping for a sack lunch on a park bench, then bathing in
the last rays of evening sunshine on a cafe patio.
</P>
<P>
   The Swedes also spend many of these long summer days on the
water. Their playground: the Stockholm Archipelago. Comprising more
than 24,000 islands, the archipelago offers a Viking's bounty of
shoreline and recreational opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to see this region in summer is by boat, exploring
the freshwater Lake Malaren or venturing into the brackish Baltic
Sea. Along the way, you can barbecue on a rocky island, hike
through a wooded preserve or shuffle around a centuries-old castle.
</P>
<P>
   All of these activities are part of a exceptional nine-day tour
called ``Impressions of a Swedish Summer.'' The outfitter, Special
Expeditions, has long been a leader in ecotours to the Galapagos
Islands and other environmentally sensitive destinations. Wanting
to introduce travelers to the culture of his ancestral home,
Special Expeditions founder Sven-Olof Lindblad began these tours
three years ago. This season's first tour departs June 14, with six
more scheduled throughout the summer.
</P>
<P>
   The trip is lovely in its simplicity. During the day passengers
observe the rugged beauty of the Swedish coast from the deck of a
private cruiser. At night, they check into historical inns, where
traditional Swedish meals await. The excursions are varied and
memorable: a private music recital, a chatty visit with a
lighthouse keeper.
</P>
<P>
   This holiday begins in the village of Mariefred, home of the
14th-century Gripsholms Castle. Mariefred is the kind of town you
dream about: teens picnic in the park, streetlights romantically
illuminate the alleys, bikes and cars share the roads in harmony.
</P>
<P>
   I spend an afternoon at the Royal Deer Garden, a partially
wooded tract on the edge of Lake Malaren. Trudging along a
well-worn path, I spot a few fleeing tails. It is only after a stop
for a drink of water that I notice the beasts peeking out from the
brush. Dozens of tall deer are gazing back at me. We watch one
another for several minutes and then move on.
</P>
<P>
   Gripsholm Castle serves as Sweden's portrait gallery, with more
than 4,000 works in its collection. Although the castle dates to
1380, it appears now as it did in 1530 when it was remodeled by
King Gustav Vasa. The most remarkable room is the theater, which
was built in 1781 for King Gustav III, a patron of the arts who
frequently was the star of his own productions. Squeezed into a
castle tower, the theater makes the most of its space. Its
neoclassical design and the stage's odd slant make the theater
appear much larger than it really is.
</P>
<P>
   The kings' guests would have been seated on the cushioned
benches below the royal box, while high above, elaborate peepholes
provided a view of the stage for the servants.
</P>
<P>
   A private concert at the castle _ arranged by Special
Expeditions _ takes place in the Throne Room. A flute and guitar
piece commissioned by Greenpeace recalls whale songs, and the
experience is heightened by the sound of gulls over the lake.
</P>
<P>
   I watch the gulls through an open window and daydream of
Vikings. The lady next to me dozes, occasionally jerking awake to
the sound of applause.
</P>
<P>
   We spend the night across the road from the castle at Gripsholm
Vardshus, Sweden's oldest hotel. The hotel was built on the site of
a 15th-century monastery and began business as an inn in 1609. Its
parquet floors and painted walls make for appealing public areas.
The hotel's restaurant is candlelighted and formal. I opt for a
meal at the hotel's pub. Located at the rear of the hotel, the pub
is popular with the locals, who pack the place each night to enjoy
live music.
</P>
<P>
   An unscheduled performance begins on the patio with a drunken
troubadour serenading diners. He croons ``Sitting on the dock of
the bay ...'' but becomes distracted after the opening line. A few
moments later, he begins a Jimmy Buffett tune.
</P>
<P>
   I retire before he remembers the second line, heading to the
hotel's wide front lawn, where comfortable wooden chairs are
strategically placed for the best views of the lake. The last
golden rays of the day create a living zoetrope as a young boy
skates on in-lines skates past a white picket fence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A LEISURELY CRUISE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Days aboard the Swedish Islander, our cruiser, are leisurely.
There's always a snack handy, the bar is open and the deck
inviting. The 19 passengers, mostly couples and mostly seniors, are
cordial. This tour often attracts families with children, but this
was the last trip of the summer, traditionally drawing a more
mature crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The ship's crew is young and handsome. Their genuine camaraderie
translates well with the passengers. Our guide is Jenny Hartzell, a
young women from Stockholm who is well-versed in her country's
history and culture. This is Hartzell's seventh Expedition trip;
she is efficient and friendly, but no mother hen. Her claim to fame
could be knowing every ice cream stand in the archipelago.
</P>
<P>
   After a stop for nature walk on a wooded island, it is Hartzell
who guides us out of the woods and into a ice cream shop where they
make their own frozen dessert. The choices are strawberry, pear and
an egg custard with chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exquisite,'' says Fred Atton of the pear-flavored ice cream.
``Every bit is exquisite.''
</P>
<P>
   Atton and his wife, Joan, are one of two British couples on the
trip. Atton's fine head of snow-white hair reminds me of Pa Kettle.
</P>
<P>
   His interest in botany is sated on several short hikes we make
as a group, including a walk on the island nature reserve Bullero.
Bullero once was home to wildlife artist Bruno Liljefors, who
acquired it in 1908. It has been a wildlife preserve since the late
1960s and, like all the islands in the archipelago, welcomes
day-trippers.
</P>
<P>
   Sweden's public access laws give one and all the right to enjoy
the shores of its 24,000 islands. You can camp, fish, hike and swim
on any island, as long as you are not on farmland and not too close
to a home.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more interesting stops along our water route is
Landsort, where we visit one of Sweden's oldest lighthouses. The
reward for climbing the more than 100 steep steps to the top is a
magnificent view of scores of tiny wind-raked islands and the
village, which, with a population of 31, has many more buildings
than people.
</P>
<P>
   A livelier but no less lovely setting awaits in Trosa, where we
bunked for two nights at the Trosa Stadshotellet. A river snakes
charmingly through this colorful town where boats seem more useful
than cars. The houses are painted lemon, mustard and cotton-candy
pink. The traditionally painted houses are red, trimmed in white
and topped with tiles the color of cloud berries.
</P>
<P>
   Cloud berries are a local delicacy. I enjoyed them as a tart
topping for vanilla ice cream. I would like to say that I
discovered the little place that served them, but with all the ice
cream shops in the archipelago, Hartzell was there first.
</P>
<P>
   She drew a map for me.
</P>
<P>
   The nine-day ``Impressions of a Swedish Summer'' tour is being
offered June 14, 24 and 29, July 9 and 14, and Aug. 8 and 13. Trips
originate and end in Stockholm. Per-person fares start at $2,890
and cover lodging and most meals. Air fare is not included. Call
888-446-5395 or visit Special Expeditions' Web site:
http://www.specialexpeditions.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 1309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
