<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIAN AMERICANS GIVE FONG BOOST OVER MILLIONAIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LANCE WILLIAMS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A surge of crossover votes from Asian-American
Democrats may have helped state Treasurer Matt Fong edge car alarm
magnate Darrell Issa in the extraordinarily close Republican
primary for U.S. Senate, an exit poll indicated.
</P>
<P>
   Fong won the right Tuesday to challenge incumbent Democrat
Barbara Boxer in November. He won the state's first open primary,
22 percent to nearly 20 percent for Issa. The open primary allowed
Californians to cross party lines to vote for candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer won the nomination for a second term with 44 percent of
the vote.
</P>
<P>
   It was a dramatic come-from-behind victory for Fong, who was
elected treasurer in 1994. He is the son of March Fong Eu, a
Democrat who was California's secretary of state for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   An exit poll conducted by San Francisco political consultant Tom
Hsieh Jr. indicated that Asian-American voters had crossed over in
droves to vote for Fong.
</P>
<P>
   Hsieh said more than 80 percent of Asian Americans in San
Francisco voted for a Democrat in the gubernatorial primary. But
when it came to the Senate race, 76 percent of those same people
voted for Fong.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, with its high concentration of Asian
Americans, Boxer won about 20 percent of Asian-American vote and
Issa got about 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Hsieh said he thought the San Francisco survey ``is going to
mirror the rest of the state.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his (Fong's) candidacy has brought Asian Americans out
to vote,'' Hsieh said. ``... For Asian Americans, no matter what
party they're in, Matt Fong is a very credible candidate, from a
political family with great name ID.''
</P>
<P>
   If he beats Boxer in the November general election, Fong would
become the second senator of Asian descent from California. S.I.
Hayakawa served from 1976 to 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer said she expected a close race in November, but she said
the general election would give voters a clear choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the only pro-choice candidate, the only pro-environment
candidate,'' she said. ``I'm the only one endorsed by the Sierra
Club and by the California Organization of Police and Sheriffs ...
so there are some major differences here.''
</P>
<P>
   Fong was outspent by more than 4-to-1 by Issa, a San Diego
electronics tycoon who spent $12.8 million of his personal fortune
on his first stab at politics.
</P>
<P>
   Issa's television commercials began appearing in July 1997,
while the cash-strapped Fong didn't take to the airwaves until
three weeks ago. Largely as a result, the San Diego millionaire led
in the polls for most of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But as the election neared, Issa was rocked by news stories
casting doubt on claims he had made about his military service, and
raising questions about an arson fire that destroyed a factory
shortly after Issa had increased his fire insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Fong hammered Issa about his background, then launched a
statewide TV blitz of his own. Fong said he knew he could never
afford to match the expensive ad campaign Issa was mounting. So he
deliberately held back until the very end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lesson I learned in my freshman year at the Air Force
Academy,'' he said. ``Don't shoot till you see the whites of their
eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Fong said he thought Boxer was vulnerable, noting that she had
polled less than half of the votes cast.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have accused Boxer of being an out-of-touch liberal
who could be defeated by a strong Republican candidate.
</P>
<P>
   But two conservative Republicans who seemed able to make a
strong race, Reps. David Dreier and Christopher Cox, opted not to
give up powerful positions in the House of Representatives to take
on Boxer. Another high-profile Republican, University of California
Regent Ward Connerly also backed away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans said, `We're waiting for Boxer because we're
going to go after her, she's cooked,' but there was no campaign,''
Mark Petracca, a political science professor at the University of
California at Irvine. ``It's an amazing thing, the failure of
Republicans to really mobilize.''
</P>
<P>
   They left the field to Fong, a former Air Force officer, and
Issa, a political neophyte who founded Directed Electronics Inc.,
the world's largest maker of car alarms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
