<HEADER>
A2097 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NURSING-SHORTAGE-ART-     06-03 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NURSING-SHORTAGE-ART-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON HOSPITALS COURTING NURSES FROM AS FAR AWAY AS CANADA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photo available on NYT photo service) 
 
(Attn: Ottawa) 
 
By MARY SIT-DuVALL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A month before 32-year-old Lisabeth McCall graduated
from nursing school, she already had her first choice of jobs.
</P>
<P>
   McCall, who received a bachelor of science degree from Houston
Baptist University College of Nursing nearly two weeks ago, says
she and all her classmates were inundated with offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would get letters, at least three a week from hospitals.
Please come to our job fair, we have excellent job opportunities. I
got everything from hospitals to prison systems,'' recalls McCall.
``It was awesome. I knew what I wanted, and I could just get what I
wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   McCall starts a new job Monday at M.D. Anderson Hospital in
Houston, specializing in gynecological care. She'll be making
$30,600 as her base salary, but hopes to earn $40,000 with overtime
pay and night shifts.
</P>
<P>
   McCall's experience isn't unique. Houston hospitals, in the
midst of a nationwide nursing shortage, are jostling to hire new
graduates and court nurses from other hospitals, enticing them with
sign-on bonuses and specialized, hands-on training courses.
Recruiters are even flying to Canada to convince northern neighbors
to settle in the Sun Belt.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and other observers say the current shortage reflects
several factors: a typical supply-and-demand cycle, a declining
enrollment in nursing school and a broader array of career choices
as the health care field undergoes changes.
</P>
<P>
   And some are warning that unless educators develop a formal
system of identifying and training future nurses, the current
shortage will explode into a crisis in 20 years as middle-aged
nurses retire, just when aging baby boomers require more health
care.
</P>
<P>
   If a hospital has a higher than 7 percent vacancy rate in
positions available for registered nurses, the shortage is
considered a serious one, according to The American Hospital
Association, the largest trade group representing hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Houston hospitals are already grappling with a higher than 7
percent vacancy rate.
</P>
<P>
   At Houston's largest hospital chain, Columbia/HCA's 16 hospitals
have an average 10 percent vacancy rate. Hermann Hospital has an 8
percent vacancy rate. Texas Children's Hospital has a 12 to 15
percent vacancy rate with an annual average of 8 to 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage of nurses varies according to specialty.
</P>
<P>
   Critical care nurses and operating nurses are in limited supply,
and there's also a need for home health care nurses as managed care
companies enforce shorter hospital stays and send patients home as
soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely a shortage of experienced nurses,'' says
Patti Stone, senior recruiter of employment at Methodist Health
Care System. ``It cuts across the board. We can get as many new
grads as we want. The problem is most of the hospitals won't hire
new grads straight onto the units because they need to go through a
training program first.''
</P>
<P>
   To entice graduates to choose their hospital and to give them
more practical training, hospitals have started internship programs
or work-study programs for soon-to-graduate nurses.
</P>
<P>
   After its merger with the Memorial hospitals six months ago,
Hermann developed systemwide internships, offering three-month
internships in seven clinical areas, says Kathy Walsh, chief
nursing officer and vice president of operations for Hermann.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really pooled our strengths to attack the nursing shortage
as a system,'' says Walsh. ``All the nurse executives meet monthly.
And this is one of the things we talk about first and foremost.''
</P>
<P>
   Tenet Healthcare Corp., Houston's second-largest hospital system
with Northwest Medical Center and Park Plaza, started a six-week
internship program in January for graduates and a preceptor program
that matches new hires with experienced registered nurses who can
function as mentors.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to offering specialized training programs, hospitals
are resorting to more aggressive recruiting techniques to entice
nurses. Sign-on bonuses of $2,000 to $3,000 are becoming
commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals are conducting ``one-stop shopping'' job fairs where
nurses can drop off a resume, be interviewed by a hiring manager _
and walk away with a job offer all on the same day. They are
sending mass mailings to local nurses working at other hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   One hospital is enticing new hires with computers and trips to
Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   The competition for nurses has driven up salaries, which have
doubled in the past eight years. Starting salaries range from $14 a
hour for graduates to $30 an hour for nurse managers or those with
five years' experience. A year ago, starting salaries were $12.50
to $13 an hour. The average nursing salary in Houston is $20 an
hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's such a price war going on in Houston,'' says Mary Ann
Euliarte, chief nursing officer at Spring Branch Medical Center.
``We're seeing the specialty centers offering higher salaries to
recruit away. That's been going on for the last six months.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Euliarte says she hired about 100 Canadian nurses for Columbia's
16 Houston hospitals in the past seven years. Her most recent trip
was six weeks ago when she offered jobs to 23 nurses. She's
received 17 commitments so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had that much difficulty,'' says Euliarte. ``They
obviously need to work and are happy there are job opportunities
and are able to get work permits to come here.''
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, Tanie Whitby, a 27-year-old nurse who moved
to Houston from Ottawa two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The floor I was working on was closing. I was working on-call.
I would have had to get several jobs working part time,'' says
Whitby, who just completed a three-month internship in the surgical
intensive care unit at Spring Branch Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Votour, 38, a registered nurse at Methodist, also moved to
Houston from Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an advertisement in The Ottawa Citizen. I had an
interview in Toronto a month later, and three months later was in
Houston,'' says Votour, who has nine years' experience. ``The
opportunities here are endless.''
</P>
<P>
   But those myriad opportunities _ prompted by a shift from
physician-controlled health care delivery to managed care companies
in charge _ are partially what's triggering the current nursing
shortage, say analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of dynamics being created that make market
opportunities for nurses _ in nursing homes, hospices, day/night
programs, HMOs, PPOs, corporate-sponsored wellness programs. All
these create fertile opportunities for nurses,'' says Art
Dickerson, a health care consultant at William M. Mercer, a human
resources consulting firm specializing in health care, retirement,
compensation and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The current shortage cycle began about four years ago when
hospitals nationwide downsized, shrinking nursing staffs to pare
expenses. But the cost-cutting measure backfired in many cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the hospitals) had more problems,'' says Carolyn
Gunning, dean of the College of Nursing at Texas Women's University
at the Texas Medical Center. ``Patients were more dissatisfied and
not choosing to go back to those hospitals. There were more
infections and longer stays.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Patricia Starck, professor and dean of the University of
Texas Health Science Center at Houston: ``When you downsize
professional nursing staff, very likely you will see complication
rates go up that eat into the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how badly is the current nursing shortage affecting the
care patients are receiving? Hospitals insist they are making up
for the shortfall with temporary ``fill-in'' nurses.
</P>
<P>
   Hermann Hospital, for example, has a float pool staff of travel
nurses who work three-month assignments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, patient care gets affected, but I don't think it's
to the point where the patient is left alone without care,'' says
V. Kumar, professor of marketing at the University of Houston.
``Hospitals won't let that happen. They make the nurses work more
shifts, but they won't let patients' health be in jeopardy.''
</P>
<P>
   But nurses admit their days are hectic and the pace fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like sometimes I can't give as good as quality care as
I would like to,'' says Cynthia Hart, 38, a Houston-area pediatric
and surgical nurse with 19 years' experience. ``Sometimes I feel
like the doctors will walk in and do what they have to do and
finish and be gone and ready for the next patient, and I'm still
trying to finish up with the first one.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry observers don't see a quick fix to the current
shortage.
</P>
<P>
   The average age of nurses nationwide is 44; only 9 percent of
all nurses are below age 30, according to American Association of
Colleges of Nursing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all concerned about the graying of nurses,'' says
Starck. ``For faculty, the average age is 50. We're concerned about
who's going to be around to teach.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, hospitals are scrambling for creative ways to
keep the nurses they do have.
</P>
<P>
   Since there are not many areas where nurses can advance,
hospitals are offering continuing education courses _ complete with
tuition reimbursement _ so nurses can learn new specialities and
move around to pre-empt boredom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than the monetary thing, what is exciting to nurses is
an opportunity to learn,'' says UH's Kumar. ``It's important they
are recognized and trained. Science is becoming more complex, and
therefore a need for more trained nurses.''
</P>
<P>
   The health care field, which suffers from one of the highest
turnovers of all industries, must learn new ways to reward
employees, says Dickerson of William M. Mercer.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do employees value?'' Dickerson says. ``Different things
are important to different demographics. Couples over 40 with no
kids are focusing on how to save for retirement. Couples under 40
and not married want more time off, more flexible schedules, casual
work dress. Companies are trying to get people what they value, and
not just say, `We know what's best.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
