<SLUG> BC-FRENCH-FOOD-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (EDs: FILED in ``i,'' ``t'' and ``d'' categories.)  
 HERE COME THE HUNGRY TOURISTS, BUT WHERE ARE THE FRENCH GOURMETS?
 News Analysis  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Tourists coming to France, like armies, march on their
stomachs.
</P>
<P>
   So during the next couple of months, the great rush will be on
to the renowned restaurants of Paris and the provinces by visitors
armed with the latest editions of gastronomic guides reporting on
which chefs are up, which are displaying less genius than in the
past and which are the newcomers to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Some Americans I know spend all their time in France doing
little but having lunch and dinner at famous and breathtakingly
expensive eating places. Their real thrill isn't the food itself
but their anticipation of telling their envious friends at home
about the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife would sooner die than admit to her friends that we
hadn't been able to get a table at the most talked-about Paris
restaurant of the moment,'' an American businessman confesses.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, a pal of mine has avoided France for years
because he says he is intimated by the fact that, not being that
interested in eating as an art form, he knows little about the
finer points of gastronomy compared with the average French person.
``I felt embarrassed dining in a top French restaurant, so I
stopped,'' he explains.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of myth involved in France's fabled cuisine. It
may come as a shock, but the fact is that the famous restaurants
these days depend almost exclusively on foreign customers,
especially Americans. If they relied on natives, they would go
broke _ as several of them have done in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Few French people can afford the likes of Alain Ducasse (around
$250 a head) or Taillevent (more than $200). Even fewer of the
French would spend that much in a restaurant assuming they could.
</P>
<P>
   The bleak truth is that in the past 20 years or so, this has
become largely a country of fast-food eateries, carryouts and
sandwich bars.
</P>
<P>
   According to sociologist Claude Alencon of the University of
Paris, ``The French have defiantly turned away from the obsession
with good food that was characteristic of previous generations. The
young in particular regard serious interest in food as
old-fashioned, even archaic.''
</P>
<P>
   Many young French women proudly proclaim their inability to boil
water. Their male companions claim to prefer Burger King to the
Tour d'Argent, cost aside.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, while American visitors reserve tables at L'Arpege
or Grand Vefour even before they reserve their hotel rooms, the
French view their own lack of concern about what they eat as
typically American and therefore enviably modern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interest in good food has declined to the point that within a
few years France will have only about 30 or 40 luxury
restaurants,'' predicts cultural historian Alain Lemoine. ``The
remainder will be fast-food places and inexpensive Asian
restaurants. Talented French chefs will be forced to emigrate in
order to pursue their profession.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 1335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
