</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA'S $64 MILLION RACE AN EMBARRASSMENT OF RICHES 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ California to millionaire candidates: You can't
buy us.
</P>
<P>
   Well, you can buy us, but you have to do it the old-fashioned
way, the Gray Davis way, with rubber-chicken dinners, pressed flesh
and contributions from big-money interests other than yourself.
</P>
<P>
   The whole world is watching, and this has been a real
embarrassment for California. Four candidates for governor spent at
least $64 million on a primary election few voters cared about.
(Never mind car-alarm magnate Darrell Issa dumping nearly $13
million of his own dough into a failed effort to become a senator.)
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-four million. That's $64 million. No matter how you write
it, or how you say it, it's an astonishing figure. Make that
obscene.
</P>
<P>
   For that dough, the candidates who professed to care so much
about schools could have bought more than 3 million books for
California school libraries.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Gavin, who buys books for the San Francisco Unified School
District, said the average library book costs $20, and each school
gets only $600 a year.
</P>
<P>
   After contemplating the primary spending, she said, ``I remember
the teachers who had an impact on me. I don't remember who was
governor.''
</P>
<P>
   No one will remember the also-rans in this race, that's for
sure. Sorry, Al Checchi, who was seeking the Democratic nomination
for governor. You shouldn't have promised just to run once. This is
politics, land of few instant gratifications.
</P>
<P>
   The problem in this election was that when a candidate spends
gobs of his own money on himself, he is his own leading
constituency. And he has a fool for a constituency.
</P>
<P>
   Money isn't just filthy lucre that talks too loudly. It
represents a transaction and a commitment. Spending only your own
money, as Checchi did with nearly $40 million, is an egotistical
act, not a political act.
</P>
<P>
   You should have taken some contributions and gotten out a little
among the people, Al. We used to call it campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the lessons of this primary election. The lessons of
California elections change every four years, and the political
consultants are always fighting the last war.
</P>
<P>
   California to consultants: We are not complete television
victims.
</P>
<P>
   All your lousy ads do is keep us away from the polls, or turn us
against your candidate. Those ads stunk. Not just because they were
negative. I'd rather watch the worst Snapple ads.
</P>
<P>
   If that $64 million primary had been a movie, it would have
closed the first weekend.
</P>
<P>
   California to the East Coast: We're not so weird. OK, we are.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, we've had four gubernatorial candidates, ranging from
unknown to bland, do expensive, vacuous battle on TV. But now we're
into an old-fashioned, liberal-conservative battle between Davis,
the lieutenant governor and now the Democratic nominee, and Dan
Lungren, the Republican attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they're already scrambling for the middle. It's decaf
Jerry Brown vs. Nixon Lite.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the main charge that Lungren will level against Davis is
right across the San Francisco Bay, heading for the office of mayor
of Oakland. Former Gov. Jerry Brown does have an unusual career
path. He may yet end up on a school board somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But lo, outside of Jerry Brown's headquarters was something
rarely seen this year, a rally. Sure, it was a small one, but it
had bands and barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   Remember rallies?
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, all politics is personal. That was what was
missing in the governor's race. Even when Checchi got personal
against Rep. Jane Harman, another Democratic candidate for
governor, it was in those dreary, impersonal ads.
</P>
<P>
   Huge egos drive multimillionaires to try to spend their way into
office, so it isn't likely that huge defeats like Checchi's will
stop them. The Supreme Court said spending your own money on
campaigns is ``free speech,'' thus millionaires are free to shout.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign reform, forget it. At some point television, which uses
public airwaves, must provide free air time for candidates. Most
local stations don't cover politics, thus forcing candidates to buy
ads between the freeway chases.
</P>
<P>
   What's a non-jillionaire to do? Sen. Barbara Boxer, a Democrat,
hopes to hold 1,000 house parties before the election is over, each
raising perhaps $1,000. She calls it ``1,000 Points of Loot,'' but
it's about more than loot, and the loot will be worth more than if
she wrote a check to herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find people are so happy to do something and get together
and talk,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they'll talk about some of the things that could have been
bought with the $64 million that went down the tubes, on the tube,
over the last few months.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates could have bought music programs for 574 schools,
including music teachers and instruments for a 40-piece band.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates could have funded 17 charter schools like the
Garfield School in Menlo Park, which has a yearly budget of $3.6
million for 645 kids.
</P>
<P>
   Well, none of them would have done that. But they could have
saved California the embarrassment of their own riches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
