<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEETLE-PORT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON PORT GETS BOOST FROM NEW BEETLE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Calif., Del., Ga., Mass. and Mich.) 
 
By JENALIA MORENO 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ German Beetles have invaded the country, and Port of
Houston Authority officials are counting their profits.
</P>
<P>
   The Port of Houston was chosen as one of the five ports of entry
in the nation for Volkswagen's New Beetle, &UR;  &LR; all of which are made
in the company's plant in Puebla, just southeast of Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   The other ports of entry for the Beetles include Boston;
Brunswick, Ga.; San Diego and Wilmington, Del. &UR;  &LR; But Houston's Port
gets the bulk of the Beetles.
</P>
<P>
   More than a third of the 50,000 Beetles sent to the United
States in this first year of its production are imported through
Houston because of its proximity to Mexico and other markets in the
Southwest. From Houston, the vehicles are taken by truck or train
to dealerships throughout the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a central location for a lot of the dealerships in the
country,'' said Tony Fouladpour, spokesman for Volkswagen of
America in Auburn Hills, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Beetles aren't the only Volkswagen products pouring through the
Port. A third of all vehicles made in Volkswagen's plants in
Germany and Mexico also enter the country here.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, Volkswagen of America leased a 16-acre lot from the
Port and has since unloaded its Passats, Jettas, old Beetles and
its luxury vehicle, the Audi, on Houston docks. The old Beetle is
no longer sold in the United States, though it is still produced in
Puebla and sold in Latin American countries.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the company leases 70 acres near the Turning Basin and
for the past four months that lot has been filled with Beetles.
Motorists driving over a nearby bridge can see rows and rows of
colorful white, red, yellow, green or blue Beetles.
</P>
<P>
   Imports have not slowed despite a recall of the popular vehicle
last month. Volkswagen voluntarily recalled 10,100 Beetles in the
United States and Canada because of of an electrical wiring
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those repairs have been made at the company's Puebla
plant or its dealerships, and a small percentage were made at the
five U.S. ports of entry.
</P>
<P>
   The Port has benefited from the popularity of Volkswagen's New
Beetle, helping to nearly double its automobile imports for the
first four months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Auto imports at the Port increased to 19,742 for the first four
months of 1998, compared with 10,208 for the same period last year.
More than a third of those imported vehicles have been the
New &UR;  &LR; Beetle. The Port also receives a few other brands of vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Volkswagen imports 7,500 of its Jettas, Audis, Beetles
and other vehicles in its line a month by ship or rail to its
facility at the Port.
</P>
<P>
   At this pace, Port Operations Director John Scardasis expects
revenues from automobile imports to reach $300,000 by year's end.
That's only a small percentage of the $83 million in revenues the
Port earned last year, but double the amount it earned in 1997 from
imports.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Port assesses higher wharfage fees for more
expensive commodities, the auto importing business is a profitable
one for both the Port Authority and the longshoremen who unload the
ships.
</P>
<P>
   Depending upon the size of the vessel that carries the vehicles,
the Port earns more than $9,000 for every 1,000 cars unloaded on
the waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   Port officials expected the Volkswagen's Beetles to be brought
to the Port from Puebla by rail, but were surprised when most were
shipped here from the Mexican port city of Veracruz.
</P>
<P>
   For the last few years, Volkswagen officials have preferred to
transport their vehicles from Mexico by ship instead of rail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided to go with shipping because of the rail problems in
the U.S.,'' Fouladpour said. ``There is a lack of supply of rail
cars and a record of substandard performance.''
</P>
<P>
   For longshoremen, the increased auto imports also have meant
more work with less manual labor compared to lifting bagged goods
or heavy cargo.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've gotta lift the keys and that's all you gotta lift,''
quipped longshoreman Patrick Davis as he drove Audis and Passats
off the Automobil Ace vessel, which had just docked from Germany.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
