<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Thursday, June 4,
1998.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the Cox News Service spot news budget for Thursday, June
4, 1998. We will update this budget at 6 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   Separate feature and commentary budgets move at 10 a.m. EDT
Monday-Friday. Separate sports and business budgets move at 5 p.m.
EDT Monday-Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456. The night news editor, until 10
p.m. EDT, is Tom Oder at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   With questions about Washington-originated material, please call
our Washington Bureau:
</P>
<P>
   News editor Art Dalglish, 202-887-8338.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign editor Rick Christie, 202-887-8316.
</P>
<P>
   Bureau chief Andy Alexander, 202-887-8334.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ALBRIGHT-PAKISTAN _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton holds a news
conference in the White House Rose Garden before U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright leaves Wednesday for Geneva, Switzerland
to hold talks with the four other member nations of the world's
nuclear club _ France, Great Britain, Russia and China _ to dicuss
what actions to take regarding the nuclear fallout from the
India-Pakistan feud. (Deans, Cox News Service). ETA: 3 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-CONSULATES _ JERUSALEM _ Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu has ``frozen'' budget-cutting proposals that might have
closed Israel's consulate in Atlanta, a spokesman said Wednesday.
(Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-FOES _ WASHINGTON _ A family feud is underway among
anti-tobacco forces, pitting traditional groups like the Lung
Assoc. and the American Cancer Society against newer groups like
Campaign for a Tobacco Free Society which seem to be in favor with
the Clinton administration. (Carr, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   UNIONS-IMPACT _ WASHINGTON _ Pro-reform forces in Congress were
strengthened when Californians defeated Proposition 226, which was
designed to require unions to get individual union members'
permission before using union dues for political campaigns. Union
leaders rejoiced and business leaders seemed resigned in the wake
of the measure's defeat. Similar amendments on reform bills now are
less likely when the House resumes its debate on campaign finance
laws this week. And the argument by reformers that any limits must
apply equally to both corporations and unions gained strength.
(Mollison, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLPRAYER _ WASHINGTON _ With a vote scheduled Thursday on
the controversial school prayer amendment, the Cristian Coalition
has stepped up its campaign for the amendment - lobbying undecided
Congressman, distributing more than 2 million church bulletins and
spending more than $500,000 for radio ads. They are also on the
attack against opponents to the measure. The Coalition has angered
Rep. Chet Edwards, D-Texas, by mailing out hundreds of postcards in
central Texas accusing him of bigotry. (Moscoso, Cox News Service).
(Moscoso, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   YORKTOWN _ WASHINGTON _ The discoverer of the sunken Titanic
holds a news conference to discuss his expedition to the site of
the sunken World War II warship USS Yorktown in the Pacific.
(Nesmith, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   FEMA _ WASHINGTON _ James Lee Witt, head of the Federal
Emergency Management Agency, discusses Project Impact, an
initiative designed to change the way America deals with disasters.
(Abulhassan, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-DROUGHT _ AUSTIN, Texas _ With no substantial rain since
mid-March and a rash of record-breaking heat, farmers and
municipalities in Central Texas are bracing for the possibility of
a second drought in three years. If rain doesn't come soon, the
face of agriculture in the Williamson County, Texas, will change
drastically, said farmer William Albert. (Coleman/Monroe, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CHURCH-MOLESTERS _ Alarmed by epidemic increases in reports of
sexual misconduct by priests, the Catholic Church four years ago
moved to deal with the problem. The 300-member Council of Catholic
Bishops created the Ad Hoc Communicate on Sexual Abuse, a committee
chaired by Bishop John Kinney of Bismarck, N.D. Its mission was to
restore faith in the priesthood. The swift removal of Bishop J.
Keith Symons from the Diocese of Palm Beach, Fla., was an example
of the church's new philosophy on handling molester clergymen.
(Moffett, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   PERFECT-SATSCORES _ RIVIERA BEACH, Fla. _ Jason Kelly, a
Suncoast High School junior, scored a perfect 1,600 on his SATs in
March, so classmate Blake Gottlieb figured he'd better give those
study guides a workout. Gottlieb got the good news in a crisp
envelope 10 days ago: He, too, scored a 1,600. Such perfection is
pretty rare. (Desmon, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOUTH-BUILDERS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ In 1992, you could hardly give
away one of the dilapidated houses on Frank Street. Today, one home
on the street recently sold for $85,000, and the Dayton, Ohio
neighborhood is on the rebound, thanks to YouthBuilders Academy, a
program that rebuilds lives by rebuilding deteriorated properties.
(Hundley, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   REAGAN-TURNPIKE _ TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ A new state law now in
effect says Florida's Turnpike shall be designated Ronald Reagan
Turnpike. But the bill's sponsors and turnpike officials are not
interpreting it as a true name change, and are not revising any
maps, stationery or existing signs. The result has been confusion
not only among the general public but also among those who pushed
to honor the Republican ex-president. (Elmore, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS-QUESTIONS _ Questions about the Sphinx's renovation,
Sinatra's funeral, Carolina Gold rice, the Statue of Liberty,
artificial sweeteners, and more. A weekly round-up of the AJC's
news Q &AMP; A. (Bessonette, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
