<P>
   Here are the top news stories in sight at this hour from The New
York Times News Service for AMs of Thursday, June 4:
</P>
<P>
   For questions about stories call (212) 556-1927. The supervisor
is Jack Topchik, followed at 3:30 p.m. ET by Pat Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   For technical problems call Peter Trigg at (212) 499-3332.
</P>
<P>
   A rundown of culture, lifestyle, sports, and special section
stories will move shortly as AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET.
</P>
<P>
   Please note that news stories and features from The Arizona
Republic, Bloomberg News, The Boston Globe, Cox News Service, Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The
Kansas City Star, Los Angeles Daily News, San Francisco Chronicle,
Seattle Post-Intelligencer, States News Service and the New York
Times Regional newspapers are all part of your New York Times News
Service file.
</P>
<P>
   A list of stories being considered by New York Times editors for
Page 1 will move at approximately 4:30 p.m. ET as
AM-PAGE1-NYT-CONSIDER.
</P>
<P>
   Stories scheduled for Page 1 will be listed in AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT,
which will move by approximately 7 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ The day's developments in the Starr
investigation. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   LEWINSKY-LAWYERS (Washington) _ Profiles of Plato Cacheris and
Jacob Stein, Monica Lewinsky's new lawyers. By Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-ELECT (Los Angeles) _ A look at what Tuesday's primary
says about California, its demographics, and the key role played by
the Hispanic vote in defeating the referendum on bilingual
education. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-LABOR (Los Angeles) _ What organized labor's victory here
Tuesday means -- labor leaders' reactions, and a look at where the
struggle with conservatives goes from here after California voters'
rejection of a proposal to require union members' blessing before
labor leaders could funnel dues to politicians. By Richard L.
Berke.
</P>
<P>
   BILINGUAL-EDUC (Undated) _ An examination of whether the
decision in California to dismantle bilingual education will change
things there and in other states with large bilingual programs. By
Ethan Bronner.
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND-ELECT (Oakland) _ Jerry Brown, as expected, and with
fanfare, is the new mayor of Oakland. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   ALABAMA-ELECT (Montgomery) _ The power of Christian
conservatives in Republican primaries is sorely tested as Fob James
is forced into a runoff.By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   SOCCER-YOUTH-SCORES (Boston) _ The Massachusetts Youth Soccer
League decides to stop keeping score, declaring winners or having
awards for players under 10. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   BISHOP-MOLEST (Palm Beach, Fla.) _ A profile of the bishop of
the Roman Catholic Diocese of Palm Beach who resigned after
admitting that he sexually molested five boys early in his career.
By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDWATER-FUNERAL (Tempe, Ariz.) _ Barry Goldwater, founding
father of the conservative movement, is buried. By B. Drummond
Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   NY-PORN (New York) _ Court of Appeals rules for the city in its
attempt to regulate sex shops, apparently paving the way for
enforcement to begin. By Dan Barry.
</P>
<P>
   NY-FOOD-VENDORS (New York) _ The city's street food vendors go
on strike; a look at the impact. By Mike Allen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ORANGE-COUNTY (Undated) _ More about the Orange County
settlement, centering on why Merrill Lynch was so willing.
</P>
<P>
   FTC-INTERNET (Undated) _ The FTC issues a report about Internet
privacy. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-SALES (Detroit) _ General Motors and Ford report sales data
for May. By Michelle Krebs.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICA-ONLINE (Undated) _ AOL changes its service terms to
protect privacy. By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING (Undated) _ Boeing says it will stop production of the
MD-11 jetliner because demand is not sufficient. The company says
it will fire some of the 3,750 workers who build the planes in Long
Beach, Calif., Salt Lake City and Toronto. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-EARNINGS (Undated) _ AT&AMP;T says it will report a
bigger-than-expected charge in the second quarter _ more than $1.2
billion _ because more managers than predicted are taking early
retirement. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stock market developments; Dow down about 20
at midday.
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments. The long bond
was down 9/32 at midday. By Robert Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECON (Moscow) _ The Russian government issues rare
one-week treasury bills in a desperate attempt to refill its
drained coffers and stabilize its turbulent financial markets. By
Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-YELTSIN (Moscow) _ A look at how President Boris Yeltsin
has managed the latest crisis. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-RAILCRASH (Hannover) _ A passenger train collides with a
car in northern Germany, killing at least 70 people as section
after section of the train flips off the tracks. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CHINA (Washington) _ Clinton makes annual pitch to renew
most-favored-nation status for China in a Rose Garden speech that
includes warnings about the South Asia arms race. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-DEMONSTRATE (Jakarta) _ Big student demonstration
calls for President Habibie to step down; other developments. By
Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-TRIAL (George, South Africa) _ Bishop Tutu and Eugene de
Kock, the notorious killer, testify at the trial of former Prime
Minister Botha. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE  &LR; (``a'' Code)
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-VACCINE (Undated) _ The Food and Drug Administration has
granted permission to VaxGen Inc. for the nation's first
large-scale trial for an AIDS prevention vaccine. Headed by
virologist Donald Francis, who successfully battled the Ebola virus
in the Sudan and smallpox in India, the three-year trial of Aidsvax
will include 5,000 U.S. volunteers and 2,500 volunteers in
Thailand. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   SHUTTLE (Cape Canaveral, Fla.) _ The day before it is to make
its final docking with Mir, Discovery loses its ability to transmit
TV pictures to Mission Control. NASA officials said the trouble
will not affect Thursday's docking. By Warren Leary.
</P>
<P>
   HEPATITIS (Undated) _ The Food and Drug Administration approves
a combination of two powerful antiviral drugs to treat
liver-destroying hepatitis C, a therapy that promises to be almost
10 times better than standard treatment. By Denise Grady.
</P>
