<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-COLUMN-RAMSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN A BANK MOVES IN, SOME BROKERS MAY MOVE OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The stockbroker on the phone had a familiar name. I had written
about him 16 years before, when he left Foster &AMP; Marshall Inc.,
then Seattle's largest brokerage firm. The story then was that the
firm had been sold, and this broker didn't like the new owner. It
was the same story now: firm changes hands, broker walks. Piper
Jaffray Inc., his employer for 16 years, had been bought by the
holding company for U.S. Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Banks, he said, are driven to cut costs, and in his business
that comes down to cutting commissions. ``They say they're not,''
he said, but he didn't believe it. He said, ``What brokers want is
a home; what they don't want is a bank.''
</P>
<P>
   He went to work for D.A. Davidson &AMP; Co., a much smaller firm
than Piper, based in Great Falls, Mont. Davidson, founded in 1935,
has been in Seattle for just 14 months. Its operation here is
headed by Bob Magnuson, the former regional managing director of
Piper. Magnuson left, too. At Piper, Magnuson directed 165 brokers
in Washington, and more in other states. These brokers are the
cherries among which he is trying to pick.
</P>
<P>
   All businesses say employees are their No. 1 asset, but in stock
brokerage it is more true than most. The best brokers will take 90
percent or more of their customers with them; less stellar
performers, 50 to 70 percent, Magnuson says. For joining a new
firm, top brokers can sometimes get up-front payments of 45 to 50
percent of a year's gross. Their old firms can attempt to tie them
with offers of stock.
</P>
<P>
   Brokers are enticed not only by a package but by a philosophy,
which implies how they will be treated in the future. Magnuson's is
the old-time religion of the customer's man. He is suspicious of
moves to replace commissions with fees. Fees have the smell of
banks; fees undercut the broker and, he argues, do not benefit the
client. To his chagrin, the brokerage industry has added
transaction fees ($5 per trade at Piper, $3.25 at Davidson), and in
some firms, a $50 fee for closing an account.
</P>
<P>
   Magnuson is worried, too, about the tie-ins that come with being
owned by a bank. Banks will have more in-house investment products,
and they will want their brokers to sell them, he says. He recalls
some disasters over the years from such products _ stock in WTD
Industries and Bonneville Pacific, for example. With an in-house
deal, he says, the broker is biased: ``The payout is higher.''
</P>
<P>
   He thus makes a virtue of Davidson's limitations. While the
Montana firm has some capability to underwrite, it is much smaller
than that of Piper, which just underwrote a $975 million issue of
paper from the Los Angeles Unified School District.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he questions the confidentiality of personal
information in a big company. Piper clients were recently notified
that their financial records would be made available to U.S. Bank
unless they asked that records remain private.
</P>
<P>
   Piper Jaffray, as might be expected, views it all differently.
Take the letter about sharing records. Ross Rogers, director of
individual investor services at the headquarters in Minneapolis,
says, ``We are all one company here. We did give clients an
opportunity to say no, but those individuals do shortchange
themselves somewhat. Our goal here is to meet their needs.''
Perhaps the client would appreciate a consultation from the bank's
trust department, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers says in-house products increase customer choice, and that
brokers are not given a higher payout on them.
</P>
<P>
   Piper does offer fee-based accounts, though less than 10 percent
of customers choose them. Most prefer the customary commission
account. And as for the idea that U.S. Bank will squeeze these
commissions to cut costs, Rogers says, ``That's one of the old
myths that floats. When U.S. Bank bought Piper Jaffray, they bought
it with the full knowledge of how we're compensated.'' Compensation
might change, he said, ``but not on the basis of that argument.''
</P>
<P>
   Says James McColley, Piper's director for Washington state,
``Change is difficult for some people, and they long to do business
the way it was done 10 years ago. We're looking forward.''
</P>
<P>
   With the consolidations now under way in banking and investments
_ with Smith Barney, Salomon and Travelers all becoming sister
companies of Citibank, for example _ these questions are guaranteed
to come up a lot. What do terms like ``financial supermarket''
mean? When you go to a supermarket, they often don't even know your
name. Here, they know how much money you have.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution will come not from what managers say but by what
brokers and customers do. Each side will be motivated partly by
money, but also by a level of comfort. Investment is a business
where not all values are financial.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Ramsey is a writer and columnist for the P-I. His e-mail
address is bruceramsey(at)seattle-pi.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
