in 2009 when the water level reaches 175 meters (574 feet) and full
power generation begins.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE DOWNSIDE CONSEQUENCES: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Water pollution in the dammed Yangtze will double _ at least _
as the dam traps more than 50 types of pollutants from mines,
factories and human settlements that were formerly flushed out to
sea by the swift Yangtze currents.
</P>
<P>
   - About 1,300 archaeological sites will be moved or flooded.
</P>
<P>
   - Critics contend that the heavy silt in the river will form
thick deposits near the upstream end of the dam, clogging the major
river channels of the city of Chongqing.
</P>
<P>
   - Facing Inundation: 632 square kilometers (244 square miles),
19 cities, 326 villages, including 27,000 hectares (66,700 acres)
of farms and orchards.
</P>
<P>
   - Facing resettlement: 1.1 million to 1.9 million people.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE FUTURE RESERVOIR: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Average width: 1.1 kilometers (0.7 miles).
</P>
<P>
   - Length: 600 kilometers (370 miles).
</P>
<P>
   - Storage: 39.3 billion cubic meters of water (51.4 billion
cubic yards).
</P>
<P>
   - Water level: elevated 175 meters (574 feet) above Yangtze
River surface.
</P>
<P>
   - Runoff: 451 billion cubic meters (589 billion cubic yards) of
Yangtze River water will flow into the reservoir annually.
</P>
<P>
   - Silt: The muddy Yangtze will discharge 530 million tons of
silt into the reservoir in a typical year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE ELECTRICITY: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Machinery: The two power stations flanking the dam's central
spillway will operate 26 of the world's largest turbine generators,
700 megawatts each.
</P>
<P>
   - Capacity: Total generating capacity will be 18,200 megawatts,
or as much as big 18 nuclear power stations.
</P>
<P>
   - Transmission: Fifteen 500,000-volt transmission lines will
send electricity to Shanghai and elsewhere throughout East China,
Central China and eastern Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
   - Output: 84.7 billion kilowatt hours of electricity annually,
equivalent to burning 40 million tons of coal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SHIPPING: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Ship lock will consist of five locks, each 280 meters (918
feet) long and 35 meters (114 feet) wide, with a water depth of 5
meters (16.4 feet). Supposed to handle 10,000 ton barges.
</P>
<P>
   - Ship lift will be a one-stage vertical lift capable of
carrying a 3,000-ton passenger or cargo vessel.
</P>
<P>
   - River shipping through central Yangtze estimated to increase
from 10 million to 50 million tons annually, with transportation
costs cut by 30-37 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE FLOOD CONTROL: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Dam sponsors say the reservoir's 22.1 billion cubic meter
(28.9 billion cubic yards) flood control storage capacity should
lessen the frequency of big downstream floods from once every 10
years to once every 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE RANKINGS OF WORLD'S TEN LARGEST HYDROELECTRIC PROJECTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (in megawatts of installed generating capacity)
</P>
<P>
   Three Gorges, China: 18,200
</P>
<P>
   Itaipu, Brazil and Paraguay: 12,600
</P>
<P>
   Grand Coulee, United States (Washington State), 10,100
</P>
<P>
   Guri, Venezuela, 10,100
</P>
<P>
   Tucuruii, Brazil, 7500
</P>
<P>
   Sayano-Shushensk, Russia, 6,400
</P>
<P>
   Krasnoyarsk, Russia, 6,100
</P>
<P>
   Corpus-Posadas, Argentina and Paraguay, 6,000
</P>
<P>
   LaGrande 2, Canada, 5300
</P>
<P>
   Churchill Falls, Canada, 5,200
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BOTTOM LINE (THREE GORGES COSTS INCLUDING INTEREST AND
INFLATION): &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Latest official estimate: 203.9 billion Chinese yuan ($25
billion)
</P>
<P>
   Unofficial estimate by Chinese environmentalist Dai Qing: 600
billion yuan ($73.2 billion)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sources: &LR;  China Yangtze Three Gorges Project Development Corp.
and a special issue of the magazine ``Civil Engineering Practice:
The Journal of the Boston Society of Civil Engineers,''
Spring-Summer 1997, which was devoted to the Three Gorges Dam
project. Comparisons with other dams from 1998 Information Please
Almanac.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For clients of the New York Times News Service &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
