</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2161 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THREEGORGES-SIDE-COX-     06-03 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THREEGORGES-SIDE-COX- </SLUG>
   -$ADV07  
 &HT;     UPROOTED TO MAKE HUGE DAM, OVER 1 MILLION CHINESE HOPING TO
PROSPER
 &HT;     With CHINA-THREEGORGES-$ADV07; photos to be placed in the
International folder on the Cox Server and are available from the
New York Times News Service.
 &HT;     EDs: The cities of Badong and Fengdu are about 50-100 miles
east Yichang.
 &HT;     Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;     For Use Sunday, June 7 And Thereafter.
 &HT;     By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BADONG, China _ In their spick-and-span, open-front shop, a
patient Chinese couple sat on a humid afternoon waiting for their
future to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Their one-room storefront was new, brimming with sundries from
shampoo to socks. Their street was new. Their five-story building
perched on the hillside was new. In fact, the entire block of
mostly vacant shops and apartments was entertaining the finishing
touches of construction.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Li Damin and his wife was that no cars travelled
the street, no people strolled past to eye their wares.
</P>
<P>
   Few others had moved in yet from the old town's shabby
riverfront that in five years will disappear under muddy water,
once the Three Gorges Dam bottles up the mighty Yangtze River and
turns 370 miles of churning energy into a calm reservoir.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in the first stage of resettlement,'' Li, 45, placidly
acknowledged. By the time the next stage is finished in four years,
the couple should have plenty of customers in the new city,
assuming they can pay the monthly $43 rent that long.
</P>
<P>
   For now they are isolated here, their lifeline to the old town a
pocked and muddy road winding across steep hillsides.
</P>
<P>
   The new heights of Badong are China's resettlement at its best,
where the government brings visitors to sample its handling of
perhaps the most controversial facet of the immense dam project
that will uproot between 1.1 million and 1.9 million Chinese
people.
</P>
<P>
   When the dam is finished in 2003, the Yangtze waters will begin
a climb of 175 meters _ nearly 575 feet _ inundating 66,700 acres
of farms and orchards, 657 factories and mines, 19 cities and 326
villages.
</P>
<P>
   The government promises that change spurred by the dam will
create a fresh new life, most importantly a life safe from floods
for 15 million people downstream, but also one flourishing with new
economic potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``The construction of the dam has brought a rare opportunity for
the opening of the region, for the changing of thoughts and
liberation of minds,'' said Chen Gong, an earnest, 34-year-old
economic development official interviewed in the Hubei Province
capital of Wuhan, a two-day float downstream.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have realized the aim of being able to remove, to resettle
and to become rich,'' he said, describing the early resettlement as
going perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   On the opposing side, critics in China and abroad warn the
process is becoming a sociological nightmare in which funds are
squandered, resettlements botched and families ruthlessly cut from
generational moorings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Official statements give the impression that resettlement is
proceeding smoothly, but in reality it has been plagued by
mismanagement, official corruption, inadequate compensation, a
shortage of farmland and lack of jobs for the resettlers,'' said a
Chinese sociologist who wrote under the pseudonym Wu Ming
(``nameless''), in a study this spring for the U.S.-based groups
International Rivers Network and Human Rights in China.
</P>
<P>
   Many Chinese river people have nice things to say about this
project the government so strongly endorses, but some signs of
unrest have appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service interviews found feelings running strong in
Fengdu, population 40,000, where residents confided that agitated
workers recently took to the streets in protest. Their food
processing factory was sold, probably for scrap, and they received
no compensation to tide them over till finding jobs in the new town
being built on a higher bank across the river.
</P>
<P>
   It is troubling to imagine everything underwater in the lively
little city full of stores and homes, its streets crowded with
shoppers and vendors carrying loads of vegetables on shoulder poles
or hawking smoked pork bellies from corner stands. The
flower-filled park and shrine to Tianzi, known as King of the Dead,
will be lost with the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Even an official guide was unexpectedly candid about emotions in
Fengdu, as she led cruise ship tourists through the ancient city's
sites last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The older people don't want to leave. It's also hard for the
people aged 40 or 50,'' said Zheng Manman, 22. ``Younger people
don't mind because the city will be bigger. There will be new
opportunities for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Middle-aged workers, as throughout China, already are losing
jobs as economic reform shuts down old, inefficient enterprises,
she said. But in these low-lying waterfront towns every single old
factory will be closed. Resettlement plans envision modern industry
and business for which these mountain people lack skills.
</P>
<P>
   Zheng personally is stymied at how to save the 30,000 yuan, more
than $3,700, she said she will need within five years for the new
apartment she must buy in the new city.
</P>
<P>
   Even if she earned a monthly salary as high as 600 yuan _ a lot
in a Chinese country town _ her entire earnings in five years would
come to only 36,000 yuan, or about $4,460. The government would
sell her the apartment well below its construction cost. Even so,
buying it would leave Zheng with only $760 to support herself for
the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   In Badong, the merchant Li borrowed from a bank, from friends
and from family to purchase the couple's 30,000-yuan apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow they will have to pay that back. But they live in a
bigger, nicer space now. And they are better off than Xiong
Changlin, who was down on the waterfront wielding sizzling pans in
his grime-covered cafe on a recent morning.
</P>
<P>
   Xiong, 41, said he will be glad enough to move with the second
wave of resettlers, though he doesn't know exactly how he will live
in the sparkling new hilltop town. He doesn't have a shop or cafe,
or any job at all up there.
</P>
<P>
   He wouldn't comment any further on the dam and resettling
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have some ideas of my own,'' he said cryptically, ``but
since it's the project of the state, I have to support it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For clients of the New York Times News Service &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
