<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2163 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-BILINGUAL-HNS &LR;      06-03 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-BILINGUAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA VOTERS STRIKE DOWN BILINGUAL EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL NESS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Californians voted decisively to replace
bilingual education with one-year English immersion classes,
approving a ballot initiative that was being watched nationally by
proponents and critics of special programs for students who lack
proficiency in English.
</P>
<P>
   With nearly all votes in Wednesday, the margin was 61 percent
for Proposition 227 and 39 percent against.
</P>
<P>
   Just as they did in 1994 with Proposition 187, which denied
education and medical care for undocumented immigrants, and the
anti-affirmative action Proposition 209 in 1996, the losers in
Tuesday's vote are asking the court to block the initiative from
taking effect this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't intend to sink or swim,'' San Francisco school
Superintendent Bill Rojas told a spirited crowd of Proposition 227
opponents Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The `lucha' has just begun,'' he added, using the Spanish word
for struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Six civil rights groups said they would go to federal court to
block Proposition 227, Rojas said, adding that the San Francisco
school district would support the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Rojas also said the San Francisco schools would not abide by the
initiative.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, an ecstatic Ron Unz, the Palo Alto software
entrepreneur who got the measure on the ballot using $500,000 of
his own money, said the outcome proved that California voters
agreed with him that bilingual education was not best for immigrant
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were outspent by about 20-to-1 on advertising, but we had
the people of California on our side because they believe the
simple truth _ that children should be taught English when they go
to school and be taught English as quickly as possible,'' Unz said
in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tremendous victory for the people of California and
for immigrant parents in California,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The vote drew national attention because California's
increasingly multiracial population is seen as the face of the
country to come. Ten other states require bilingual education, and
others offer it. As with its bold moves against undocumented
immigrants and affirmative action, California's vote is expected to
strengthen opposition to bilingual education elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   While Proposition 187 was ultimately thrown out in federal
court, Proposition 209 was ruled constitutional in a case that went
all the way to the Supreme Court. It took effect last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will follow the same course,'' Rojas said of the
anti-biligual education measure.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature will be another line of attack, Rojas said.
While Gov. Pete Wilson supported Proposition 227, both candidates
to replace him _ Democrat Gray Davis and Republican Dan Lungren _
opposed the initiative. The Legislature could overturn Proposition
227 with a two-thirds vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 1416EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0156 </DOCNO>
