<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2168 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-THREEGORGES-COX     06-03 1969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-THREEGORGES-COX </SLUG>
   -$ADV07 
 &HT;     CHINA'S CONTROVERSIAL THREE GORGES DAM LOOKS UNSTOPPABLE
 &HT;     With THREEGORGES-SIDE-$ADV07; THREEGORGES-DATA-$ADV07; photos
to be placed in the International folder on the Cox Server and are
available from the New York Times News Service.
 &HT;     Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;     For Use Sunday, June 7 And Thereafter.
 &HT;     By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   THREE GORGES DAM, China _ Every day 18,000 Chinese mobilize to
build the most powerful _ and most disparaged _ hydro-electric dam
in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Each day they crunch more rocks, dig deeper pits, pour more and
more concrete for the edifice that within five years will stretch
1.4 miles across the Yangtze River and create a mammoth reservoir
370 miles long.
</P>
<P>
   With swells of national pride, some Chinese call this dam the
modern Great Wall.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not a place that politically cautious visitors like
President Clinton _ soon due to spend nine days in China _ will
come and admire as a new national icon. For the dam is suffused in
controversy as thick as the river mists that enfold construction
cranes angling high over the Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
   These workers and thousands more still to come will reconfigure
not just this site, but will flood the mystically beautiful Three
Gorges canyons that have inspired Chinese poets for centuries. And
they will trigger the eviction of more than one million Chinese who
fish and farm and trade along the river that carries their
livelihood and sometimes their destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``China is still a poor country,'' Lu Youmei, general manager of
the China Three Gorges Project Corp., told Cox News Service
recently. ``To catch up to modern conditions in developed
countries, we may need half a century or even a century. The
Chinese have many things to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Lu is convinced the state-constructed hydroelectric dam will
boost China in its run toward modernity, producing electric power
equivalent to the output of 18 nuclear plants, diminishing the
deadly threat of floods and making navigation more cheap, reliable
and efficient.
</P>
<P>
   The 26 generating units at this single site will have an
installed
</P>
<P>
   capacity of 18,200 megawatts, fully half the production
capability of the
</P>
<P>
   entire, multi-state Southern Company, the largest producer of
electricity
</P>
<P>
   in America.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to this central Yangtze region shows that Western
opponents who think they still can stop the Three Gorges Dam _
warning of environmental devastation and social dislocation _ had
better think again.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of Chinese peasants and villagers already have
been relocated, as new towns rise on riverbank heights to replace
the low-lying buildings exploded into rubble.
</P>
<P>
   Early stages of the dam itself are an imposing physical
presence.
</P>
<P>
   In five years, Lu's corporation has spent $3.7 billion,
harnessed the Yangtze into a channel to drain a river bed building
site, planted one stout end of the dam and blasted a massive
stair-stepped pit into the reddish-brown earth where shipping locks
will carry multi-ton vessels past the dam.
</P>
<P>
   A new high-speed road and new airport funnel supplies and people
here, new apartment buildings shelter the workers, and a new
Chinese-British joint venture every year produces 6 million
chickens, 60,000 pigs, and eggs from 200,000 hens to feed them.
</P>
<P>
   The dam is all but a fact. Yet fateful uncertainties remain:
</P>
<P>
   -- Will the dam actually end horrific Yangtze floods such as the
three major deluges that killed more than 300,000 people in this
century?
</P>
<P>
   -- Will a tangle of environmental complications result, such as
choking siltation that some predict will clog the very ports this
project is supposed to enhance? And will heavy upstream pollution
concentrate even further into a reservoir of bile as the dam
reduces river flow?
</P>
<P>
   -- Will the 1.1 million to 1.9 million people being resettled
end up with better housing and work opportunities, as the
government promises? Or will Three Gorges follow the pattern of
earlier Chinese dam projects, in which peasants were uprooted with
marginal help and resettlement funds got squandered?
</P>
<P>
   -- Does the dam itself carry the threat of deluge, either as a
wartime target or as result of earthquake or construction fault?
</P>
<P>
   They add up to the overall question of whether the dam, power
plant and resettlement, now carrying a $25 billion official price
tag by completion of Phase 3 in 2009, will be worth the many
dimensions of cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be stopped. The project is merely political,
masquerading as a development project,'' said Owen Lammers,
executive director of the International Rivers Network, a San
Francisco-based coalition of environmental groups. ``If the Three
Gorges project is implemented, it will only reinforce the hardline
elements of the government, reinforce the power of state-owned
enterprises.''
</P>
<P>
   Ecologists propose a series of smaller dams that would be
gentler to the environment and to the people while also
contributing long-needed flood control and electric power.
</P>
<P>
   The dam opponents say dissent within China has been stifled on
this issue, as on other political questions, so pressure must be
built from outside the country. With China still short of funds to
complete the dam, opponents think the most effective pressure point
is the international financial community.
</P>
<P>
   Rumblings of dissatisfaction sound faintly in the countryside
areas directly affected by the dam. Negative reports from
hydrologists or archaeologists determined to state their case were
considered, then in most cases filed away or publicly refuted.
</P>
<P>
   Whether repelled by the controversy or mistakenly thinking the
dam already has diminished the river's scenic views, only half as
many tourists visited Three Gorges this year as came at this point
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   What has long been one of China's most spectacular attractions
will not be altered until Phase 2 of the dam is finished in the
year 2003. Then the rising waters will form a narrow reservoir
through the Three Gorges and beyond, ultimately reaching a water
level 175 meters _ about 575 feet _ higher than at present.
</P>
<P>
   The reservoir will bury not only towns and orchards, but also
Chinese artifacts thousands of years old _ ancient barge haulers'
tow paths, hanging coffins and mysterious rock engravings _ and it
will cut by a third or more the majestic height of sheer-sloped
gorges that today dwarf river travelers in misty drama.
</P>
<P>
   Yet officials like Lu sound confident of reaching all the worthy
goals listed in their brochures and headquarters signboards. At the
same time, they dismiss critics as simply being wrong, either
through naivete or intent to try to sabotage an important Chinese
project.
</P>
<P>
   And the Three Gorges Dam is almost exclusively a Chinese work.
</P>
<P>
   That is partly because some financial institutions heeded the
campaign that Western environmental groups mounted against the dam
by calling it an ecological and social time bomb.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Export-Import Bank for example, opposed the dam in
1996, based on strong recommendations against the project from the
U.S. National Security Council. It asked the Chinese to bring plans
up to acceptable environmental standards before it would consider
financing any projects related to the dam, but never received a
response, said Linda Formella, a spokeswoman at the bank's
headquarters in Washington D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Some foreign banks have been more friendly, such as the
Canadians who issued export credits on behalf of General
Electric-Canada, or the Germans who are helping finance Siemens
generators for the power plant.
</P>
<P>
   But the few Americans who have grabbed a piece of Three Gorges
project _ including Caterpillar with a $30 million contract for
construction equipment and Rotec Industries winning $30 million for
concrete conveyor systems _ are supplying mostly hardware.
</P>
<P>
   An noticeably disappointed senior project manager Alfred Roider
of the giant German construction firm Philip Holzmann lamented that
the project was so ``political'' that the Chinese shut out
foreigners from engineering and building contracts.
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to assess whether the Chinese did not want to be
hamstrung by potential foreign demands for stronger environmental
and social protections, or whether the Three Gorges Dam simply is
too important to national pride to let outsiders take credit for
building it.
</P>
<P>
   The notion has kicked around since one of China's first
revolutionary leaders, Sun Yat Sen, first proposed a dam in the
gorges in 1919. But war or revolution or politics always
intervened.
</P>
<P>
   Now if the dam's major aims are fulfilled _ the erratic and
powerful Yantgze waters are brought under control, a clean new
source of electric power opens more of China to modernization and
development, and river cargo transport is expanded and made more
affordable _ those huge achievements will help propel what in many
ways is a Third World country into the 21st century circle of
wealthy nations.
</P>
<P>
   That will be the case assuming other consequences of the massive
dam are tolerable.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Environmental aftermath is among the most troubling questions.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese journalist and engineer Dai Qing published a book of
stinging critiques of the dam written by Chinese scientists, then
spent ten months in prison for it after the 1989 Tiananmen Square
massacre.
</P>
<P>
   She warns that little progress has been made in treating waste
water flowing freely into the Yangtze from cities and from big and
little industries that line the river banks. Even more polluting
factories have been allowed to locate in the new areas, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Three Gorges Dam defenders say they will prevent the reservoir
from becoming a catchment of lethal filth. Since the dam project
was approved in 1992, however, they have done little except tell
ships to stop dumping waste and sewage in the river.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are making local laws now for environmental protection of
the reservoir,'' assured Chen Gong, a development official in
Wuhan, the capital of Hubei Province which includes the dam. ``The
regulations will come out very soon.''
</P>
<P>
   The China sturgeon and three other species of Yangtze fish
already are endangered, and dam-influenced changes to their habitat
are unpredictable. Other experts worry about endangered Siberian
cranes and Swan Geese that winter downstream.
</P>
<P>
   Worries also remain about the impact of cramming at least
another 1.1 million people onto already heavily populated forest
and farmland at higher elevation, much of it more sharply sloped
than the fertile riverside banks that will be inundated.
</P>
<P>
   For China, the issues boil down to tradeoffs on a scale that the
rest of the world has seldom faced except in wartime.
</P>
<P>
   Lu, the general manager of the Three Gorges corporation, cited
hydroelectric power as the cleanest, safest way to generate
electricity, without radiation hazards of nuclear plants or the air
pollution of coal and oil generation. It does require reservoir
inundation, whose consequences he believes not only can be
controlled, but are far outweighed by gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, with completion of the project we are going to
contribute a great deal to protecting the property and life of 15
million people living in downstream areas,'' he said. ``The threat
of flood will be remote. People can develop the economy that will
lead to a better life in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``And second, it will generate enormous power which will
contribute to Central China, eastern China, Sichuan Province, to
the areas in all the Yangtze River. The power is cheap and is
clean. People will benefit from that.''
</P>
