A2185 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JERRY-BROWN-HNS &LR;      06-03 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JERRY-BROWN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTORIOUS JERRY BROWN VOWS FIGHT TO STRENGTHEN MAYOR'S DUTIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATHLEEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Former California Gov. Jerry Brown, calling
his election as Oakland's next mayor the ``first step,'' now has a
tougher task ahead _ convincing city voters to give him the tools
he says he needs to transform the job from ceremonial figurehead to
chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who won about 59 percent of the vote, took the lead at
the start. For his 10 rivals, it was a scramble for second place,
each hoping to win enough votes to force the flamboyant Brown into
a run-off race.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Blakely, who emphasized his urban planning expertise, came
closest to Brown, winning 15 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, a liberal Democrat who recently turned 60, put in long
hours on the campaign trail. He attended about 100 meetings in the
homes of supporters, where he emphasized that he had came to
listen, not lecture.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's star power frustrated his rivals, as did his popularity
with ethnic residents and blacks, who make up 43 percent of the
city's population. Eight black candidates competed with Brown for
the job, which has been held by an African American since 1977.
</P>
<P>
   The next step, Brown said, is to collect 44,000 signatures over
the next three weeks to put his ``strong mayor'' initiative on the
November ballot so it could be in place when he takes office in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Similar measures were defeated in 1989 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown, who regularly denounced Oakland's city manager system
during the campaign, is confident the people of Oakland are ready
for a change.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the first step,'' he said of his victory. ``Next
is the petition drive. Then voting on the initiative. Then there's
the carrying out of the urban agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who was governor of California from 1974 to 1982, moved
to Oakland three years ago from San Francisco. His campaign motto
was ``Oaklanders First'' and he adopted the city symbol, a gold oak
tree, as his campaign logo.
</P>
<P>
   If Brown's proposal to amend the City Charter passes, the mayor
could hire, fire and direct the city manager. The mayor would no
longer serve on the eight-member City Council and would vote only
when needed to break a tie. If the mayor vetoed legislation, it
would take six votes to override it.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said a strong mayoral form of government would dismantle
the barriers between the mayor and the people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under a city manager form of government, there is no
connection between the people and the executive branch,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown dismissed critics who said the measure would create an
anti-democratic form of government.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not true of Willie Brown,'' he said, referring to the
mayor of San Francisco. ``That's not true of Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what would happen if the charter change failed, he said:
``That makes the job a lot harder,''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's proposal faces opposition on the City Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sets up an imperial mayor,'' said council member Dick
Spees. ``If you want to get something done, you'd have to go to the
mayor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
