<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAX-RECORDS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SUCCESS OF STAX RECORDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; The soulful sound of Stax Records is so ingrained
in pop music, it's almost hard to believe it all came out of one
tiny recording studio.
</P>
<P>
   The Memphis studio that produced groundbreaking records by Otis
Redding, Booker T. &AMP; the MG's, Sam and Dave, Wilson Pickett,
Johnnie Taylor, Albert King and so many others may be gone, but the
sound lives on.
</P>
<P>
   Stax, the company that created a beat that resounds through
music to this day, is the subject of a Bravo Profiles documentary,
``The Soul of Stax,'' which begins airing at 8 and 11 p.m. Sunday
on the Bravo channel.
</P>
<P>
   The program digs up vintage music videos and concert footage,
'60s news clips, and interviews such Stax stars as Isaac Hayes,
Mavis Staples and Steve Cropper, legendary guitarist of the Stax
house band, the MG's.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Stax, we sort of took ethnic-based blues and upgraded it,''
Cropper said in an interview. ``And that's about all we did. We cut
a lot of ballads and lot of blues, but I think our success was
being able to make dance music. And I give all the credit to (late
MG's drummer) Al Jackson.''
</P>
<P>
   The show starts with a visit to the Memphis suburb where Jim
Stewart and Estelle Axton first set up a studio after Axton
second-mortgaged her home to buy equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The two soon realized they needed to be closer to the city and
after a year moved to an ex-movie theater on East McLemore Avenue
in Memphis. There, they recorded Rufus Thomas and his daughter,
Carla , performing ``Cause I Love You,'' a local hit in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, Stax built a roster of hitmakers. The label's
greatest success came with Redding, whose ``Dock of the Bay'' and
``Try a Little Tenderness'' made him the king of r&AMP;b. When Redding
died in a plane crash in 1968, Stax never really recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people told us they could always tell a Stax
record,'' Cropper said. ``And it did, I guess, have an identity. I
wasn't thinking of it in those terms, but the public knew
different.''
</P>
<P>
   During times of racial strife in America, Stax thrived with an
integrated cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early '60s, Stax was kind of like a forerunner for the
integration scene in Memphis,'' songwriter-singer William Bell says
during the documentary. ``We worked together as a group, but we
weren't too well-received outside of our little realm.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stax story is also told in a thoroughly researched new book,
``Soulsville, USA: The Stax Records Story'' (Schirmer Books, $25)
by Rob Bowman, a professor of music at York University in Toronto.
Bowman was also instrumental in the making of ``The Soul of Stax.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nashville-based Cropper, now touring as part of the ``Blues
Brothers'' band, says if he knew how to write hits like those that
came out of Stax in the '60s, ``I'd write three of 'em a day. It
was a phenomenon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
