<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-DIVAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACE NOT ALWAYS A HARMONIOUS SUBJECT IN CLASSICAL MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From her seat in the orchestra, violinist Rosalyn Story surveyed
the crowd at last month's opening gala at the Nancy Lee and Perry
R. Bass Performance Hall. The audience was virtually all white.
</P>
<P>
   Story was concerned, but she was not surprised. The only
African-American in the Fort Worth Symphony, she is also the author
of the 1990 book ``And So I Sing: African-American Divas of the
Opera and Concert,'' and is a leading authority on the role of
African-Americans in classical music in America.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the classical music arena has been mostly closed
to African-Americans. The breakthrough has been in the female
operatic voice sector, where Marian Anderson paved the way for
Leontyne Price, who in turn opened the door for a whole generation
of African-American divas. Friday, the latest addition to the
roster of African-American operatic stars, mezzo-soprano Denyce
Graves, will make her debut in Fort Worth in a gala concert at the
Bass hall.
</P>
<P>
   Graves says that her skyrocketing career has, in recent years,
elevated her above racial discrimination. As the reigning Carmen at
the Metropolitan Opera, she can write her own ticket anywhere in
the world. But it hasn't always been that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, there was some blatant discrimination,'' she
says. Once, she flew from Houston, where she was a member of the
Houston Opera Studio, toNew York for an audition; the director
looked at her, asked her what her voice category was, and then
informed her that he didn't need a mezzo-soprano. A week later, she
talked to a white, Canadian mezzo who told her that the same man
had listened to her enthusiastically.
</P>
<P>
   A later experience had a more positive outcome. Cast as
Giulietta in Offenbach's ``Tales of Hoffmann,'' she learned that
the designer of the production ``made no bones about it. He did not
want a black Giulietta.''
</P>
<P>
   She arrived for rehearsals a week before the designer, and
remembers that, the day before he was to arrive: ``I went to bed
with an upset stomach. The next morning, I worked out, put on my
best dress and makeup. At the rehearsal, he hardly spoke to me.''
</P>
<P>
   But she proved herself so cooperative and talented that he began
to relent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We became friendly, and he wanted me for another production,''
she says. ``We really got past color together. I showed him I was
committed and a hard worker. He came to respect me.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it is African-American women who have made the most
spectacular inroads in the field of opera, bass Raymond Bazemore,
an associate professor of voice at Texas Christian University who
has had a broad and distinguished career, says that, at times,
ethnicity has been to his advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``You begin with an extraordinary talent, and you get
encouragement,'' he says. ``As you get encouraged, you go
further.''
</P>
<P>
   Bazemore says that being a true bass helped him in his career,
which has included major traditional bass roles around the world as
well as unusual roles such as Caiaphas in ``Jesus Christ
Superstar.'' But he also says that the African-American community
as a whole tends to support talented individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has always been the case that blacks collectively encourage
the very talented among us to pursue our talents,'' he says. And he
points out that numerous roles can be sung only by blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Porgy and Bess gave many of us, including me, an opportunity
to display our skills,'' he says. ``If you have talent, and the
chance to keep doing it, you will succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Story, however, says that racism persists in the operatic
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are different kinds of racism,'' she says. ``One that is
happening now is the racism of being invisible.''
</P>
<P>
   She cites the scarcity of black singers at the Metropolitan
Opera and at other companies, the stereotyping of roles and the
lack of the same inroads for black men as for black women.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are threatened by a black male lead in a romantic
role,'' she says. ``Black men are seen as threat.''
</P>
<P>
   She also points out that certain roles are still seen as more
appropriate than others for African-American women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carmen and Aida are easier for black women,'' she says.
``Carmen is a dark gypsy. Aida is an Ethiopian. They both match the
stereotype of dark exoticism, and are seen as more acceptable roles
for black women.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Story says, the real breakthroughs have come only at the
top, for the stars such as Price, Kathleen Battle, Jessye Norman _
and, recently, Graves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same as in athletics,'' she says. ``It's the lower
levels that are difficult for blacks. Unless you're among the
greatest, you compete with whites, and whites are preferred. In the
1960s and 1970s, there was an agenda of choosing and helping
blacks. Now, black people have gone back to being invisible.''
</P>
<P>
   Graves, who was born in Washington, D.C., grew up close to the
black gospel tradition, singing in a family music group before she
was introduced to opera.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black people have a heritage of song,'' she says. ``There are
those of us who take the trouble to study properly. It's natural
that an African-American woman should sing on the stage.''
</P>
<P>
   And, although she has experienced discrimination, she says, ``I
see my race as an advantage in everything I do. I'm proud to be an
African-American woman.''
</P>
<P>
   (Wayne Lee Gay covers classical music for the Star-Telegram. He
can be e-mailed at wlgay\Nstar-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
