<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2271 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PIONEER-BLACK-DIVAS-T     06-03 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIONEER-BLACK-DIVAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST BLACK DIVAS FACED ADULATION, INDIGNITIES
</HEADLINE>
 
(Goes with mainbar, BLACK-DIVAS) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In times past, they suffered indignities offstage and adulation
onstage. Today, the public in Europe and America expects that there
should be at least one great female African-American opera singer _
almost as if there is a permanent niche to be filled.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas-based author Rosalyn Story, who is also a violinist in
the Fort Worth Symphony, outlined the succession of
African-American divas in her 1990 book ``And So I Sing:
African-American Divas of Opera and Concert.'' Their stories range
from the lonely, often degrading life of the pioneers to the
triumphal international careers of today's stars.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 19th and early 20th centuries, soprano Sissieretta
Jones (1869-1933) was hailed as ``the Black Patti,'' in comparison
to the leading Italian soprano of the day. She sang for presidents,
drew crowds as large as 75,000 for concerts, performed Dvorak's
music with the composer conducting and was hailed in London and
Berlin. However, because of her race, she was never hired for a
legitimate operatic production; she died of cancer, largely
forgotten and in poverty, in a hospital in Providence, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia-born contralto Marian Anderson (1897-1993) won fame
in Europe in the early 1930s, then blazed onto the American concert
scene in 1935. She won her place in the history books in 1939, when
the Daughters of the American Revolution rejected impresario Sol
Hurok's request to book her for a concert at Constitution Hall in
Washington, D.C. In a striking gesture that was one of several
roots of the civil rights movement, she sang the concert, at the
urging of first lady Eleanor Roosevelt, from the steps of the
Lincoln Memorial. In 1955, she made history again as the first
African-American to sing at the Metropolitan Opera.
</P>
<P>
   With the color barrier broken by Anderson, Mississippi-born,
Juilliard-trained Leontyne Price (born 1927), became the undisputed
leading dramatic soprano of the 1960s and 1970s, favorite of
concert and operatic audiences around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Although the field is now rich with African-American operatic
talent, only two have emerged to the same level of household
recognition as Price. Ohio-born lyric coloratura soprano Kathleen
Battle, 49, is known for an incredibly sweet voice and incredibly
difficult temperament; Georgia-born dramatic soprano Jessye Norman,
52, continues to overwhelm audiences with the power of her voice,
her unfailing musical intellect and her imperial stage presence.
</P>
<P>
   Although she emerged too late for inclusion in Story's book,
mezzo-soprano Denyce Graves, in light of her successful appearances
as Bizet's Carmen and as Saint-Saens' Dalila at the Metropolitan
Opera, is a good candidate to join the succession. She is also
blessed with a charismatic, media-friendly personality. Graves, who
sang ``Carmen'' in Dallas in 1996, will make her Fort Worth debut
Friday night at the Nancy Lee and Perry R. Bass Performance Hall.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 1524EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
