a two-day symposium and house tour that will examine the lineage of
four 19th century apostles of design. By Patricia Leigh Brown.
</P>
<P>
   EMILY-POST-STAMP (Undated) _ In her 1923 classic book
``Etiquette,'' Emily Post observed that ``older people invariably
feel that the younger generation is speeding swiftly on the road to
perdition.'' And so it is with stamps. Last week, the first
domestic image ever to appear on a stamp was unveiled, heralding
Emily Post's ``Etiquette.'' The stamp _ a 1920s place-setting with
Lafayette Towle silver, a goblet and hand-painted Copeland Spode
China plate _ is elegant and extremely proper. But beneath that
white damask tablecloth lurks a radical shift in the design and
subject matter of the United States postage stamp, from America's
calling card to adhesive pop icon. By Patricia Leigh-Brown.
</P>
<P>
   GULFCOAST-TV-TOWN (Seaside, Fla.) _ Where do you go to shoot a
movie about a perfectly ordinary American whose whole life,
unbeknownst to him, is a scripted show for television? Ideally
you'd find a place that looked so stereotypically small-town
America, so thoroughly front-porched and picket-fenced, that it
could pass for a movie set. This is what the producers of ``The
Truman Show,'' which opens Friday, were looking for _ and what they
found in Seaside, Fla. By Michael Pollan.
</P>
<P>
   WOMAN-MONEY-MAVEN (Woodstock, N.Y.) _ ``Maxing Out: Why Women
Sabotage Their Financial Security'': Just by the subtitle, you can
tell that Colette Dowling is willing to court controversy. By Alex
Witchel.
</P>
