<HEADLINE>
STANDARD AND SUBNOTEBOOKS ARE SHRINKING WITH NEW FEATURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (af)  
 By JOE HUTSKO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the mobile computer industry seeks new market niches _ the
big PC companions being one of the latest _ standard and
subnotebooks are continuing to shrink and add new features.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the most recent products are subnotebooks by
Hewlett-Packard and Sony. But while their profiles are slim, their
prices aren't: Hewlett-Packard's Sojourn is $5,799, while Sony's
VAIO 505 (available in July) will be priced at $1,999.
</P>
<P>
   Each is less than an inch thick and encased in a lightly tinted
magnesium alloy case, which gives extra rigidity and keeps each
model's weight to around three pounds _ until the user starts
slapping on extras and heavy longer-life batteries.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, money buys power, which means shorter battery life.
The Sojourn's 233-megahertz Pentium processor runs faster than the
VAIO 505's 200-megahertz Pentium chip. Sony predicts up to three
hours of continuous use from its rechargeable battery, while
Hewlett-Packard reports half as much.
</P>
<P>
   The VAIO 505 has ports to attach an external CD-ROM or floppy
drive; an optional pair of speakers snap on either side of the
10.4-inch display, giving it a decidedly Mouseketeer-like
silhouette. Also unusual is the touch pad, which can be written on
with a stylus to sign letters or scribble in simple drawings or
notes.
</P>
<P>
   The Sojourn has a 12.1-inch display, and its features include a
multimedia ``slice,'' a base that snaps onto the unit's underside.
It also has a pair of built-in stereo speakers that pop out on
either side, floppy and CD-ROM drives, and the usual ports for
connecting peripherals.
</P>
<P>
   Another snap-on base _ a $799 battery that extends usage to six
hours, increasing the total price to $6,598 _ completes the
initially lean profile, swelling the multilayered Sojourn's total
weight to a hefty six pounds. So much for keeping things light and
easy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
