<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-NOTEBOOKS-COMPARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINDOWS 95 AND ITS SMALLER SIBLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOE HUTSKO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft's colossal Windows 95 and its two-year-old little
brother, Windows CE, do essentially the same thing: act as the
computer's central nervous system and traffic cop, determining how
all other software will operate.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 95 and its forthcoming upgrade, Windows 98, run on
desktop and notebook computers with lots of moving parts: CD-ROM
drives, mice and so on. Windows CE runs on computers with no moving
parts except, in certain models, their keyboards.
</P>
<P>
   It first showed up on handheld computers, then palmtop
computers, and it is now running on the new PC companions, which
look like tiny notebook computers but are really just handhelds
with larger keyboards and color screens. Instead of a mouse, the CE
devices get their on-screen cues from a penlike stylus that is used
for tapping icons and menus on touch-sensitive displays.
</P>
<P>
   Like the machines it runs on, Windows 95 is big and able to work
with a bunch of complicated programs at the same time; Windows CE,
on the other hand, is small, simple and able to pay attention to
only one or two modest tasks at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Although Microsoft boasts that Windows CE has a Windows 95-like
interface, Windows CE is a separate operating system that includes
only a few pared-down portions of code borrowed from its full-grown
sibling. The Windows CE handhelds cannot run Windows 95 programs
like Adobe Premiere for Windows 95 or the 3-D shooting game Quake.
</P>
<P>
   Windows CE is shipped with a core suite of pared-down Microsoft
applications, including Pocket Word, Pocket Excel, Pocket Internet
Explorer and Pocket Outlook. Each can exchange information with its
desktop counterpart, though none of the programs will actually run
on a Windows 95 computer.
</P>
<P>
   But conversions of files are not complete. A desktop Word
document dragged over to Pocket Word keeps only minimal text
formatting, like the choice of font and style, and only bare-bones
outlining.
</P>
<P>
   While computers running Windows 95 can have either a few
megabytes or many gigabytes of hard disk space for loading programs
and storing files, the main Windows CE programs have a scant 4 to
16 megabytes of space for adding extra programs and storing
information.
</P>
<P>
   While the hard disk in a typical home PC running Windows 95 is
big enough to store the Bible, the complete works of Shakespeare
and an entire encyclopedia's worth of text and pictures, Windows CE
has room to store the text of four or five novels.
</P>
<P>
   Windows CE is showing up inside things other than computers,
including car radios that respond to voice commands and a
forthcoming video game system from Sega called Dreamcast.
</P>
<P>
   One thing both operating systems have in common is Microsoft,
which earns a licensing fee for every machine they run on, be it a
PC, handheld computer, car radio or, someday, a microwave oven.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
