<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2284 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-MICRO-NOTEBOOKS-A     06-03 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-MICRO-NOTEBOOKS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 NEW NEAR-NOTEBOOKS HAVE REAL KEYBOARDS BUT FIT IN A POCKETBOOK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Wash.)   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (af)  
 By JOE HUTSKO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Goldilocks would have had no end of criticism for portable
computing devices. They're either too big or too little. They're
either too smart (read: short battery life because the bigger
processors eat electricity) or too dumb (read: stripped-down
functions).
</P>
<P>
   And manufacturers never cease to try to please Goldilocks. There
are mobile computers large and small, from no-frills travelers to
big alternatives to desktop machines. There are various personal
digital record keepers and palmtop computers, none big enough for
comfortable typing.
</P>
<P>
   There is the lone Toshiba Libretto, a tiny full-fledged computer
with an even tinier keyboard. And now, in the continuous birth and
blending of categories, there is something else.
</P>
<P>
   The analysts and companies call it one of the PC companions, a
category that includes palmtops and handhelds. Like the other PC
companions, it's more than an organizer, less than a notebook and
of real use only to people who already have a full-fledged Windows
computer (most PC companions are not Macintosh-friendly).
</P>
<P>
   Like the early PC companions, which have keyboards too small to
do anything but hunt and peck, the new companions include word
processors, e-mail programs, Web surfing ability and more. And they
are meant to synchronize data with primary computers through cable
connections. Printing is most conveniently done via the desktop,
although they can print directly to a printer if it has an infrared
port.
</P>
<P>
   What's new is that these companions are bigger, with keyboards
large enough for touch typing. What to call them is a puzzle _
little sisters, minimicro-almost-notebooks, the new thing. For lack
of a better term, let's call them big PC companions. Three of them
are available now.
</P>
<P>
   Mike McGuire, a senior analyst who studies mobile computers for
Dataquest, a market research company in San Jose, Calif., that
specializes in technology, called the latest PC companions ``very
important precursors'' to the size and shape of mobile PCs to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not the user's primary computer but a companion to it,
like a snapshot of the desktop PC for taking work and presentations
away from the office, on trips or to work or at home, without all
the hassles of a notebook,'' McGuire said. ``With prices around
$900, they make an awful lot of sense.''
</P>
<P>
   The three big PC companions _ sold by NEC, Hitachi and LG
Electronics _ cost less than $1,000 and are under two pounds. They
are a little bigger than a VHS videocassette, measuring slightly
more than an inch thick and about 10 inches by 5 inches.
</P>
<P>
   They offer color screens that are wider than the screens of
their sibling handheld PCs, batteries that last up to 10 hours and
keyboards large enough for many people to type on comfortably.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the keyboards, the new PC companions are an
alternative for frustrated notebook users like Vince Broady,
editorial director of Gamespot, a Web-based magazine in San
Francisco. He said that the notebook he bought last year for $4,000
``was expensive and had extremely short battery life _ less than an
hour'' and that it also had frequent problems with its CD-ROM,
pointer, hard drive and modem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I barely got any work done and eventually stopped using it,
except to play `You Don't Know Jack' at parties,'' he said. ``That
was the end of the line for major notebook purchases for me.
They're too expensive, too quickly outdated and too unreliable.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Goetter, principal programmer at Angry Graycat Designs,
based in Seattle, also prefers a big PC companion to a notebook.
``I prefer it to a notebook for its cost, instant-on feature,
battery life, and relative ruggedness,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The new big PC companions run a less powerful operating system,
so they have less powerful programs and functions, offering only a
fraction of the performance of notebooks or desktop PCs. Based on
Microsoft Windows CE, a bantam operating system that draws its look
and feel from its big brother, Windows 95, the big PC companions
come with drastically scaled-down programs that capture the basics
of what most people do on their desktop PCs.
</P>
<P>
   For some, like Broady, the compromise is acceptable. He bought a
big PC companion after he re-evaluated his needs. ``They're pretty
basic,'' Broady said. ``e-mail, word processing, Web browsing.''
But the big PC companions, with Windows CE, do those things on a
slower, smaller scale than machines with Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, users with PCs running local area network, or LAN,
software based on Novell Netware report problems with getting their
PC companions and desktop computers to speak the same language.
Most complain that the CE software necessary to link the big and
little computers together conflicts with Netware.
</P>
<P>
   Only after complicated tweaking by network administrators do the
two get along, and they still have some problems.
</P>
<P>
   Discussing their troubles on the newsgroup
microsoft.public.windowsce, frustrated users accused Microsoft of
dragging its feet in providing Novell-friendly support for the
popular network software because it competes with Microsoft's own
office networking software.
</P>
<P>
   The product manager for Microsoft Windows CE, Phil Holden, said
in an interview that Netware support was in the works, but he would
not say when it would be available.
</P>
<P>
   A partial solution is offered by a company called River Run
Software (www.riverrun. com), which sells add-on programs that let
the CE-based PC companions dial in to a Novell-based network and
share information over a modem connection.
</P>
<P>
   The machines have clear limits. John Carter, a computer
technician for United Parcel Service, said he preferred the fuller
features and performance of what he called a ``real'' notebook in a
PC-companion-size package. ``I would occasionally read
100-plus-kilobyte text files and it would take forever to load them
into the CE machine,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   He prefers the Toshiba Libretto, called a micronotebook, which
runs Windows 95. It is about the size of the new big PC companions
and is ``more functional than a CE machine,'' Carter said. It can
handle common peripherals.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   McGuire, of Dataquest, predicts that by 2001, around eight
million PC companions will be sold worldwide. Will they take a big
bite out of the notebook market? ``I don't think so,'' McGuire
said. ``Notebook users create a lot of data, and some make it their
primary computer.'' Broady expressed a similar verdict: ``A lot of
people will still buy notebooks to replace their existing
desktops.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, McGuire said that positive responses to the new big PC
companions would ``put the fear of God'' in the makers of the more
expensive notebooks as the gap between each category's features
narrows. As the CE-based devices get larger and more useful,
vendors are continuing to slim down the proportions of the
full-power notebooks as prices continue to rise.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Hewlett-Packard's magnesium-cased 3.2-pound
Sojourn, which can run Windows 95, NT or the forthcoming Windows 98
operating system, is less than an inch thick and has a full-size
keyboard and large screen. But it costs nearly $6,000 and runs only
one and half hours on the built-in battery.
</P>
<P>
   An optional battery ``slice,'' which is like an added base for
the machine, is supposed to add four and a half more hours of use _
plus an additional two pounds to the total weight.
</P>
<P>
   The Libretto models, which cost $699 to $2,499, also run Windows
95. While a PC companion's battery lasts up to 10 hours, the
Libretto runs for about 2 hours. McGuire says this may contradict
what most people would expect for battery life in the small
Libretto. ``With these ultraportables, people think, `Wow, better
battery life,' but the smaller size means smaller batteries.''
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, the keyboard on the more robust Libretto is smaller
than the keyboards on the new, less capable big PC companions. Yet
that doesn't bother Carter. ``I don't see myself needing to type
much on the Libretto,'' Carter said. He intends to use his new
little computer to stay on top of e-mail, get access to the Web,
work with spreadsheets and lists of contacts, and ``play an
occasional game,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   But Broady said, ``I'd considered the Libretto, but the keyboard
was too small for me to type at anything approaching normal
speed.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for NEC, Kristin Fabos, said the company's
engineers had determined that ``the smallest possible key pitch you
can type on is 15.5 millimeters'' _ a reference to the space
between one key's center and the next _ and had added an extra
millimeter to the company's big PC companion keyboard just to be
safe.
</P>
<P>
   After the first few hours with his new big PC companion, a
Hitachi HPW-200EC, Broady said, ``I can already type at about 80
percent normal speed.''
</P>
<P>
   His enthusiasm wasn't limited to the keyboard. ``The styling is
really cool,'' he said. ``And I'm `connected' to it already in a
way that I haven't been since my first Mac _ the original model.''
</P>
<P>
   A close look at the first three big PC companions turns up their
pros and cons.
</P>
<P>
   All three devices are priced at $899. The NEC Mobile Pro 750C
(www.necnow. com) has a silvery finish and squarer edges. The
Hitachi HPW-200EC (www.hitachi.com) and LG Electronics' Phenom
Ultra (www.lgeus.com) are identical, except for their names and
labels; their keys are slightly larger than the NEC Mobile Pro.
</P>
<P>
   All three offer the same basic programs, though the Mobile Pro
also includes a program called Calligrapher, by Paragraph PI
(www.paragraph.com), for converting handwritten words scribbled on
the screen to text. The devices have backlighted color
touch-screens that measure just over eight diagonal inches and have
640-by-240-pixel resolution.
</P>
<P>
   They are large enough to show about 16 lines of a full-width
word processing document in a 10-point font. All include styluses
for tapping the screen to select icons and menus.
</P>
<P>
   Because the keyboards are more accommodating than those on a
micronotebook and will encourage real typing, McGuire, of
Dataquest, wonders if the stops and starts necessitated by the use
of a stylus _ it is picked up to tap the screen then put down to
resume typing _ is a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll work to a degree,'' he said, ``but the cost and power
requirements are coming down enough to add touch pads,''
electronically sensitive surfaces that are activated by touch. That
would mean smoother typing.
</P>
<P>
   The vendors promise up to 10 hours of battery life from their
units, due in large part to the fact that they have none of the
vulnerable, power-hungry moving parts found in ordinary notebooks,
things like hard and floppy disks and fans to keep the processors
from overheating. And unlike notebooks, which often make the user
wait up to a minute for them to ``wake up,'' the CE devices turn on
instantly.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of having a floppy or CD-ROM drive, each of the big PC
companions connects to, and utterly depends on, a desktop Windows
PC for loading new programs and sharing information. The connection
is made with either a cable, a wireless infrared port or an
Ethernet PC card wired to an office network.
</P>
<P>
   A program called Active Sync keeps a watchful eye on both the
small computer and the big one _ as long as they are connected _
swapping bits back and forth to insure that both share the same
data on contacts, schedules, tasks, e-mail, documents and
spreadsheets.
</P>
<P>
   That makes it easy for the user to coordinate between the
desktop computer and the portable, which illustrates an important
point: a PC companion is just that, a limited partner to a user's
existing desktop or notebook PC, whereas notebooks, despite their
small size, are full-fledged PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Broady acknowledges that the big PC companion's dependency on
desktops may count as a small strike against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure at some point I'll wish I could run a standard PC
program like a game or that I had a built-in floppy drive,'' he
said. He also expressed some concern about the trend toward Web
sites with complex designs that may require features the big PC
companions lack.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Broady is already sold on the devices. He figures that
he can buy the next three generations of Windows CE machines for
the cost of a notebook. ``And since I like to shop for
technology,'' he said, ``that's a big advantage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
