<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANDLING THE DIFFICULT TASK OF EDGING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.
Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
 (bl)  
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many homeowners find it difficult to maintain the borders around
the patio, driveway and sidewalks. Frequently, the lawn overgrows
onto these surfaces, narrowing them and making them look unkempt
and uncared for. The usual way to service these areas is with an
edger that trims and cuts back the grass to form a neat, defined
edge.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, there are other solutions to the edging problem.
Most garden and home centers sell rolls of edging material made of
metal or plastic. This material is economical and easy to install,
but it is flimsy and many need to be replaced every few years.
</P>
<P>
   Well, there are other options. You can, for example, put down
wood or masonry materials to emphasize and define the edges. You
can also put in plants that look good but do not encroach upon the
paved surfaces. All of these solutions require an initial
installation effort but afterward, they will require less upkeep
than a grass edge demands.
</P>
<P>
   Creating a border of wood trim involves implanting rot-resistant
boards into the soil adjacent to the paved surface. Bury them deep
enough so the top surface is flush with the ground.
</P>
<P>
   It's best to anchor the boards so that heaves in the underlying
soil do not pull them away from the pavement. There are two easy
methods of anchoring. You can drill a hole through the boards (one
hole at each end) and drive a 2-foot long, 1/2-inch rebar (concrete
reinforcing bars) through it into the ground. You can also drive a
2-foot-long stake, made of 1 by 2 inch pressure-treated wood, next
to the ends of each board. Secure the stakes by driving nails
through them into the sides of the border boards.
</P>
<P>
   Cedar and heart-redwood are naturally rot-resistant and make
attractive borders. Unfortunately, both are expensive.
Pressure-treated lumber is less attractive but more economical.
</P>
<P>
   Some landscapers use railroad ties to create a rustic border,
but this may not be a good idea because of the preservatives used
to make the ties rot-resistant. Many are treated with creosote,
mercury compounds or pentachlorophenol. These chemicals can leach
toxins into the surrounding ground and damage neighboring plants.
Pressure treated lumber isn't toxic, so it makes an acceptable
edger.
</P>
<P>
   Masonry borders may be made of bricks, concrete edging blocks or
natural stone. These materials are heavy and abrasive, so work
carefully and wear heavy gloves to protect your hands. Regardless
of whether you choose bricks, blocks or stone, they should be
embedded in a shallow trench dug beside the pavement. Ideally, you
should lay down a 2-inch bed of carefully leveled sand before you
position the masonry.
</P>
<P>
   Bricks should be placed on end (masons refer to bricks in this
position as ``sailors''). Bricks are designed with letters, SW, MW
and NW, to indicate their resistance to weathering. Severe
weathering (SW) bricks are the best choice for outdoor
applications. Since standard bricks measure 8 by 3 1/4 by 2 1/4
inches, it is relatively easy to order the amount you will need by
measuring the length of the border to be edged, then dividing that
figure by 3 1/4 (this calculation assumes that the bricks will be
butted against each other without mortar). Obviously, you'll have
to round off any fractions to the nearest whole number.
</P>
<P>
   Natural stones are another option but require more effort
because they are heavier and irregular in shape. In order to fit
them together, you may have to chisel off bumps and projections.
Use a brick chisel and a small sledge hammer for this and always
wear safety goggles.
</P>
<P>
   Ground cover plants create a softer edge than wood or stone
materials, yet they do not require much more maintenance. Talk to
the dealer at your local nursery to find out what plants are best
for your needs; ask how tall, lush and how dense they will grow.
</P>
<P>
   Not all edging problems occur around paved surfaces. It is often
difficult to trim the grass near or under a perimeter fence. Plant
cover may eliminate the need for trimming, but this is not always a
good solution, particularly if the fence is made of wood. The
plants will hold moisture and provide a possible shelter for
insects. Both could affect the fence. A better solution involves
digging a small trench under the fence and filling it with gravel.
The gravel bed will provide drainage so water will not collect, and
it will eliminate the need for hand trimming.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
