A2292 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-STUDENT-FEEDBACK-     06-03 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-STUDENT-FEEDBACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERCEPTION ANALYZER ALLOWS STUDENTS TO GRADE THEIR PERFORMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mich.)   (af)  
 By ADAM BRYANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teachers, of course, make their living grading students. But
with a device known as a Perception Analyzer, students can now turn
the tables (or the lecterns) on their teachers and grade their
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Perception Analyzer has been used for years by
corporations and politicians to test the mass appeal of their
products and messages, Market Strategies, the company that makes
it, is pushing into academia with its system. It includes
dial-mounted handsets that a test group can twiddle to give
real-time feedback to a main computer about their opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Malone, a research psychologist who is with Market
Strategies, a Detroit-based company that, with about 80 clients
worldwide, dominates the market for such systems and the Perception
Analyzer could help teachers get candid feedback from students
about whether they really understood the material being presented.
</P>
<P>
   It is not an easy sell, and not just because a basic system with
12 handsets costs about $10,000. Many teachers, Malone said, wince
at the notion of students rating their talks in real time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faculty hate it,'' he said. ``But if every kid in the class is
having problems, maybe the problem is with the faculty member.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there have been some takers. Portland State University
bought the system to give its professors a way to check whether
students really understand the material being presented.
</P>
<P>
   The Perception Analyzer has proved to be an effective tool in
measuring student responses, said Devorah A. Lieberman, director of
teaching and learning excellence at the university.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, the system is not used by Portland State to evaluate
its professors. Instead, the professors use it to test whether
their messages are getting across clearly.
</P>
<P>
   So instead of students having to admit publicly that they don't
understand something, they can, without embarrassment, turn the
dial of their Perception Analyzer to respond to just about any form
of question the teacher puts to them, including a snap quiz on what
they; have just learned.
</P>
<P>
   The system is also used by students in public-speaking courses.
``I think it's really got an incredible amount of potential,'' Ms.
Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   Given the cost of a college education, Malone said, he expects
that students and their parents will, over time, start insisting on
more accountability for teachers.
</P>
<P>
   After all, he added, power in the marketplace is gradually
shifting to consumers, and there is no reason why the people who
pay for college education _ students and their parents _ should not
be part of that shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``If organizations engaged in any kind of commerce do not meet
consumers' specific requirements, they're toast,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But is education really commerce? At some point, students in a
lecture hall have to do their part and pay particularly close
attention to difficult materal that is not so easily spoon-fed.
</P>
<P>
   Given his line of work, it is perhaps not surprising that Malone
often faces grillings about the Perception Analyzer at dinner
parties and other gatherings. Can't this shift of power to
consumers go too far and lead to a more homogenized society?
</P>
<P>
   Malone counters that, despite the growth of market research, the
breadth and depth and variety of content in American society is
expanding. The role of the Perception Analyzer, he added, is merely
to deliver opinions that are less filtered than if they were voiced
in a group of people who, because of peer pressure, are more likely
to keep their thoughts to themselves or sugar-coat them so as not
to offend.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is absolutely no evidence that greater information in
the hands of decision-makers chokes creativity,'' Malone said.
``The American consumer cannot be manipulated. They are cynical
enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
