<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE FISHIN' OFF THE BACK BURNER, AND SEE WHAT HAPPENS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's been too long since I've fished.
</P>
<P>
   Like most people, I have relied on restaurants to supply my
cooked fish. It's easy enough, sometimes not too expensive, and
always dependable.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the case when I was fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Fishing never was easy. I never lived by a river, where all I
had to do was walk from my home to a secret rock where I could sit
and drop my line deep down to the black home of hungry catfish. I
didn't have a crappie hole where the water boiled with fish. The
lake shore never lapped outside my door.
</P>
<P>
   I always had to GO fishing.
</P>
<P>
   And it wasn't cheap. There was the boat, the motor, the trailer.
Also the depth finder, the tackle, the sunglasses with big elastic
straps, and the vests with a lot of really neat little pockets. Did
you know a fishing license costs $19 these days?
</P>
<P>
   And, I dare say, fishing was never dependable. I was a fair hand
with a rod and reel, but if my casting had to bring in dinner,
there would have been some lean times.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I found out recently that I really miss it.
</P>
<P>
   On the Memorial Day weekend, we went to Lake Nocona, where we
met with my daughter's future in-laws, who are from Bowie. They are
nice people, Bob and Sue Romine. They fish.
</P>
<P>
   Along with several of their friends, they have created a private
camp on the lake. They swim, picnic, boat, relax. Mostly they fish,
and then they eat them.
</P>
<P>
   That was the part I liked best.
</P>
<P>
   The Romines, Sam Williams and Ray Murphy collected a batch of
crappie, sand bass and catfish for the weekend fish fry. None of
the fish came from the grocery store. Most were caught just a few
hundred yards from where they were about to be deep-fried in three
cookers sitting side by side.
</P>
<P>
   I must say that I have become accustomed to farm-raised catfish,
and for the most part, the sweet taste and even size make the farm
variety my favorite.
</P>
<P>
   People argue that the catfish they caught as youths in some
slow-rolling river tasted better, and I don't doubt them. But I
doubt that the rivers are as clean as they once were, and catfish
can bring the taste of the river to the table.
</P>
<P>
   Catfish from the lake, however, are a different matter.
</P>
<P>
   Those big chunks of flaky fish were moist and rich. If
restaurants make a mistake with their much-thinner farm-raised
fillets, it's that they cook them until the ends turn up dark and
brown. They look and taste like a wet shoe left to dry in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   The catfish I had with the Romines tasted fresh and fleshy, with
just a tang from the mustard coating.
</P>
<P>
   The mustard is important. Most catfish recipes just call for the
fillets, or the whole fish for that matter, to be simply rolled in
cornmeal and dropped into the hot oil.
</P>
<P>
   Some call for a milk wash, but the really good ones call for
mustard. Don't dilute it, don't try to make it a fancy spiced
mustard. Just plain old yellow hot dog mustard will do.
</P>
<P>
   Roll the fillets through the mustard, then drag them in a
mixture of half cornmeal and half flour. Salt and pepper should be
added to the mixture. Maybe a little cayenne, too. The standard
recipes don't call for this much flour in the coating; usually it's
either straight cornmeal, or three-to-one cornmeal over flour.
</P>
<P>
   I like the half-and-half better, though. It helps carry the
taste of the mustard, yet it doesn't overpower the catfish.
</P>
<P>
   The Romines do it right, and I hope we get back there soon.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Romine was kind enough to take me fishing for an hour or so
after we ate. We didn't catch anything, but just being out there
was like a rich dessert. It made me feel a part of the whole day,
even though I didn't contribute to the stringer.
</P>
<P>
   I hope to, next time. I've already bought a couple of lures and
a fresh tube of sunblock. I'm working on the vest.
</P>
<P>
   I paid the $19 for the license.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman receives e-mail at: artc\Nstar-telegram.com Web
site: www.startext.net/interact/chapman.htm. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 1538EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2352 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMAN-MONEY-MAVEN-ART     06-03 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMAN-MONEY-MAVEN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SINGLE WOMAN AT 60, FACING UP TO FINANCES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Md.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By ALEX WITCHEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOODSTOCK, N.Y. _ ``I am a woman of 60 with no savings and no
investments,'' Colette Dowling says. ``I have no disability
insurance, but I feel very strong physically and emotionally. All
things being equal, I should work until I'm 75. But who knows if
all things will be equal?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dowling, the author of seven books, including the
best-selling ``Cinderella Complex'' (Summit, 1981) is standing in
the kitchen of her rented house making a salad and telling all.
From 1989 to 1994 she spent her entire $250,000 retirement account
(paying penalties and interest on premature withdrawal) and went
into debt to the IRS for $80,000 in unpaid taxes. She lost
everything she had, including two houses here (and all the
furnishings), an apartment in New York City and the advance she was
paid for her newest book, ``Maxing Out: Why Women Sabotage Their
Financial Security'' (Little, Brown).
</P>
<P>
   Just by the subtitle, you can tell that Ms. Dowling is willing
to court controversy. Not all women sabotage their financial
security _ by a long shot. But Ms. Dowling's theory is that in her
generation particularly, women have been raised with the
expectation that someone else (usually a husband or a father) will
take care of them, or rescue them from having to assume
responsibility for their financial independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that if I took good care of myself, I would always be
alone,'' she says. ``It wasn't conscious. I never in my life was
taught to expect I'd have large amounts of money I'd have to manage
wisely, and when I did, I found it quite frightening and
disturbing. I also didn't think I'd have to support myself for the
rest of my life. My story is dramatic because of the sums involved,
but the process is one with which women are particularly
familiar.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting here in the kitchen of a house heated only by a
wood-burning stove, Ms. Dowling looks out at a living room adorned
with exposed beams and throw rugs. Wind chimes hang on the porch.
The surroundings are warm and cozy, motherly.
</P>
<P>
   But the woman who lives here isn't, quite. She has the edge of
someone who learned her lesson the hard way, but that seems to be a
way with which she is uncannily comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Tall and thin, dressed in black jersey pants and top, and
stylish black sandals, she looks more Soho than Woodstock. And
though she is open and articulate (and makes a beautiful salad)
there is something unsettling about her, a feeling that she is
somehow untamed. Which is a characteristic she seems to have
nurtured.
</P>
<P>
   Raised in a Catholic family in Baltimore, Ms. Dowling was forced
by her father to marry the man by whom she became pregnant _ which
was the last time she seemed to obey anyone. Though she had three
children with her husband, they later divorced and she moved to
Rhinebeck, N.Y., with another freelance writer, a man 10 years her
junior. That relationship lasted 15 years, until 1989, when she
resolved to live alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life has been lived in rebellion against the whole thing,''
she says. ``The father patriarch taking up all the space, the
mother who was subservient to him. I hated it, and I was willing to
sacrifice a lot in order to have something different. There's no
reason why I couldn't have married a doctor or dentist and had a
life more financially predictable, as my mother's was.''
</P>
<P>
   Though when Ms. Dowling wrote ``The Cinderella Complex,'' a best
seller that was translated into 20 languages, her financial future
seemed secure.
</P>
<P>
   ``For so many years I had so little money and no regular
paycheck,'' she says, ``that I felt triumphant just making ends
meet, even though the seeds of my carelessness and of overspending
to fulfill other needs started then.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ms. Dowling's thesis in ``The Cinderella Complex'' was
that, liberation aside, women have a hidden fear of independence.
When she moved to Rhinebeck with the writer, she said she
immediately found herself depending on him to support her and her
children. Needless to say, many women, including those who reviewed
the book, excoriated her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it has to do with the depth of our conditioning as
women,'' Ms. Dowling says, ``which has been a theme of mine all
along. It's hard for some of the academic feminists to understand
how emotional conflict about independence could continue decade
after decade. It's hard for a lot of women to admit that after what
we HAVE done, there are still these issues holding us back.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dowling became aware of her own issues after her
relationship ended. ``Bit by bit, I began mismanaging my money,''
she says. ``I made a decision to buy out his share of the house and
was saddled with a mortgage. I also left 15 years of analysis. I
had a book bomb, called `Perfect Women.' My parents were ill and
died. Menopause hit with a bang. I became depressed.''
</P>
<P>
   To compensate, she made expensive improvements on her house. ``I
built stone walls, planted fruit trees, put in a new foundation for
half the house and raised the roof. I should have put my foot down
when the architect told me he couldn't renovate without doing that,
but there was that self-destructive moment of `the hell with it.'''
</P>
<P>
   She shakes her head. ``And why I thought I should spend my
retirement money to do it, I don't know,'' she says. ``It was the
illusion that I was more in control and had some kind of power I
didn't have. I think now a part of me didn't want to be viewed by
the world as a single woman in her 50s on her own and struggling,
God forbid. This crisis has forced me to change a lot of that.''
</P>
<P>
   What helped her the most, she says, was joining Debtors
Anonymous in 1995. ``I had to sell everything to pay off this
debt,'' she says, ``and I still had other bills, and I thought,
`I'm not going to get through this unless I join a support group.'
It's a very rock bottom feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   But once there, ``there was such a degree of openness,'' she
continues, adding: ``DA gets you past experiencing shame at what
you've done and what's happened to you. And it's practically
oriented from Day One. They asked me to make a wish list of things
I wanted to purchase for myself, and here I was the biggest spender
known to mankind, but I wasn't used to thinking about myself as
deserving of things that I wanted, so I could actually state my
desires and plan to go after them. The spending I had done before
was to meet unconscious needs, unconsciously.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Debtors Anonymous is not only for women, though Ms. Dowling says
in her group she counted 15 women and 3 men. ``This whole money
business is the last arena in which these old but persistent
feelings women have are showing themselves,'' she maintains. ``It's
one thing to be productive, make money and be aggressive in a
career, another to acknowledge in an accepting, open way the
responsibility you have for supporting yourself indefinitely.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last book I wrote, `Red Hot Mamas,' about women in
their 50s,'' she goes on, ``I interviewed 65 women and only two of
them had an investment plan for the future. And I do think it does
still relate to conflicts with dependency. Money savvy is connected
with masculinity in our culture. That leaves women with the feeling
that if they want to take care of themselves and are good at it,
the quid pro quo is they'll never hook up with a relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly, says Jane Bryant Quinn, the financial expert and
author, who recently revised and updated her classic, ``Making the
Most of Your Money'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster).
</P>
<P>
   ``It IS more socially acceptable for women not to manage their
money,'' she said in a telephone interview. ``But the Y chromosome
is not a money management chromosome. In all the studies, if you
control for earnings, age and experience, women are the same as
men. At 23, out in the working world staring at a 401(k) plan, they
are equally confused. But if those women quit working they will
know less and less about finance, while the man, who keeps working,
knows more and more. He will not necessarily be better at it, just
less anxious. It's simply knowledge and experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Quinn has not read Ms. Dowling's new book. ``I would not in
any way undercut her personal experience, because she's obviously
had a bad time,'' she said. ``But it's not because she's female.
Someone else could write a book called `You Could Do It,' based on
65 widows who got out there and learned and drove their advisers
wild.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dowling replies: ``I think that saying money management is
socially acceptable for men is very much more insidious in its
effects on women than she seems to allow for. The question is
whether women understand they HAVE to assume responsibility, and be
equally involved in money, savings, investments, all those
decisions and how they get made. It's not enough to say one of us
is good at this, the other is good at that and we have an equal
marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dowling expects her debt to be paid off next fall when the
sale of her New York apartment is finalized. ``That will be a big
relief,'' she says. She also feels more secure about her own
financial future since joining a women's investment group, which
she recommends to others. ``You are able to learn in an uncritical
atmosphere where you don't feel you're being judged, and there's
something empowering about that,'' she says. ``It seems to take it
out of the arena that only men can do this.''
</P>
<P>
   She does stress that the difficult situation she has found
herself in these last four years has not been all negative. She is
close to her son and daughters, all in their 30s. ``One daughter is
struggling with her finances,'' Ms. Dowling says, ``the other is
beginning an investment plan.'' Their brother owns his own business
in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``For most of my adult life, my mother and I were estranged,''
she says. ``I was so different from her and her expectations. My
mother at 60 had no idea of how to support herself, or structure
things. It was wind-down time. Women now have the latitude to have
a life that goes on productively and adventurously longer than most
of our mothers, certainly. It's almost as if an extra 20 years were
handed to you without having expected it. What to do?''
</P>
<P>
   She plans to write a new book (she won't divulge the topic) and
to appreciate what she has learned. ``The things I care about that
give me quality of life have changed,'' she says. ``I've created a
life in which I have a lot of deeply connected relationships. I
feel supported, not alone. One thing that creates a feeling of
stability is understanding how things work in the world, not to be
so caught off balance as I was when I was younger. It's that
feeling of arriving at some sort of intelligence about the world
and people in it _ not the inner shrinking girl feeling I had for
so many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very big thing to have learned how to come up with
$80,000 to pay off my debt. I have learned to make choices about
how to spend my money. I think now, `Yes, I can deal with it.'''
Her smile is genuine. ``There's some relief in actually feeling
like a grown-up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
