<P>
   CHINA-US (Washington) _ President Clinton urges Congress to
approve his decision to renew normal trade relations with China.
But House Majority Leader Richard Armey says approval will be
tougher to get this year because of questions about U.S. technology
transfers to Beijing and alleged Chinese campaign contributions to
the Democrats. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-TREATMENT (Washington) _ Women and minority men are more
likely than white men to delay seeking treatment for AIDS and tend
to receive less effective care for the deadly disease, according to
a new study by Johns Hopkins University and the University of
California at San Francisco. By EUN LEE KOH.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-DAVIS (San Francisco) _ Lt. Gov. Gray Davis grabbed a
victory few would have envisioned a few months ago, trouncing the
best-financed gubernatorial candidates in U.S. to become the
Democratic nominee for governor. By ROBERT SALLADAY and ZACHARY
COILE.
</P>
<P>
   FISH-ANTS (San Antonio) _ Texas Parks and Wildlife officials
blame fire ants for the death of 22,000 trout in the Guadalupe
River. Fire ants are toxic to fish. During the ant mating season,
the insects fly and mate in the air, then fall to the ground and
die. When they fell in the river, the fish ate them. By THADDEUS
HERRICK.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-US (Mexico City) _ Foreign Minister Rosario Green has
told U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright that Mexico is
investigating charges of illegal activity by U.S. agents in a
money-laundering sting that led to the arrests last month of
several Mexican bankers. Green says Mexico will seek the
extradition of the agents. By PHILIP TRUE.
</P>
<P>
   FRENCH-FOOD (Paris) _ Tourists coming to France this year will
find that local interest in good food has declined and that fewer
luxury restaurants are open. More and more, the French are flocking
to fast-food places, carryouts, and inexpensive Asian restaurants.
Some experts predict that talented French chefs will be forced to
emigrate. By BERNARD D. KAPLAN. (Already filed; also filed in ``d''
and ``t'' categories)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-FINALS (Salt Lake City) _ The world champion Chicago Bulls
take on the Utah Jazz in Game 1 of the NBA Finals. By EDDIE SEFKO.
</P>
<P>
   SOC-WORLD-CUP (Undated) _ Third in an eight-part series of
previews on the World Cup groups focuses on Group C. By JOHN P.
LOPEZ.
</P>
<P>
   RAC-BELMONT (Elmont, N.Y.) _ The field is shaping up for
Saturday's Belmont Stakes, where Real Quiet will be bidding for the
Triple Crown against a field a largely undistinguished horses. By
ALAN TRUEX.
