<HEADLINE>
TWO HORSERACING SYNDICATES FLOURISH ON LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Please note that the word AT in parentheses has been used in
the 6th 
graf instead of the symbol, non-transmittable to many newspaper
systems.)  (JT)  
 By VICTOR MATHER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Horseplayers are by nature second-guessers. So perhaps it is not
surprising that, in 1994, a group of racing fans who had been
second-guessing trainers and owners regularly on an Internet
mailing list decided to see if they could do better. So they pooled
their money and bought a horse.
</P>
<P>
   Racing ownership syndicates are not new. But Virtual Owners
Partnership (http://www.ttinet.com/vop/), formed in September 1994,
and Cyberspace Racing Team (http://www.crt-stable.com), started by
several Virtual Owners members in 1995, have taken the concept
digital.
</P>
<P>
   The two groups are small-time as syndicates go. The best-known
syndicate in the world of horse-racing, Team Valor, has won many
major stakes races, and its runners earned over $1.5 million last
year. By contrast, Cyberspace Racing has owned 13 horses in its
history, and its greatest success has come with Born Wild, who won
a minor stakes race at an Arizona track. Still, buying in is much
less expensive than in a typical syndicate: under Cyberspace
Racing's system, $1,000 buys one-150th of a four-horse ``stable.''
Virtual Owners allows an investment as low as $400.
</P>
<P>
   Many decisions _ excluding training decisions _ are made by
majority rule, with partners weighing in via e-mail, said Toni
Richardson, general manager of Cyberspace Racing. For day-to-day
decisions, like which race to enter a horse in, the partners rely
on their trainers. But before a horse is bought or sold, members
are polled.
</P>
<P>
   Most partners were recreational bettors. Only a few had any
experience in the field, and most were attracted through the
mailing list, a horse racing newsgroup or the groups' web pages.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual Owners Partnership races primarily in Illinois.
Cyberspace Racing Team, which has been racing primarily in Arizona
and California, is expanding into New York with a horse set to run
at Belmont Park.
</P>
<P>
   Even the teams' jockey silks reflect their computer origins.
Cyberspace Racing's sport a big ``(AT)'' sign, a reference to an
Internet address, while Virtual Owners' silks feature the winking
emoticon, ;). (The New York Jockey Club has frowned on the
``(AT),'' and Cyberspace Racing will sport modified silks there.)
</P>
<P>
   For a sport that relies heavily on accurate data, racing has
been slow to embrace online technology. Soon after the introduction
of off-track betting, attendance at tracks fell as bettors started
betting near their homes. Wagering by telephone has also been a big
success. A few hundred fans are taking part in an online betting
experiment at http://www.youbet.com.
</P>
<P>
   Betting on sports like football and baseball on line is illegal
in most of the country, and in March the federal government
arrested several online bookmakers. With betting on horse-racing
legal in most states at the track or by phone, there are few legal
obstacles to online betting on horses.
</P>
<P>
   Data on horses' past performances are now available on some
tracks' web sites, usually for a dollar or two. And results and
race calls are quick and easy to get at many sites. A site at
http://www.racingchannel.com provides real-time odds. Pedigree
information is available, notably at
http://owl.frontier.com/pedigree/.
</P>
<P>
   Race horse ownership is still dominated by the wealthy. But the
online groups have offered the chance for $2 bettors to experience
racing in a new way.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Zorn, a law professor at Pace University and a
Cyberspace Racing partner who has been betting on horses since high
school, said winning as a part-owner is ``much more exciting than
winning a bet.''
</P>
<P>
   Syndicate members say making money is not the object. The cold
truth is that most horse owners at any level lose money.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Zorn said, ``It's a thrill to be in the winners'
circle.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
