<HEADLINE>
MAKING ICONS EASIER TO SEE 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Where can I find the commands to make my screen icons bigger?
</P>
<P>
   A. Since you did not specify whether your computer is
Windows-based or a Macintosh, let's look at the methods for the
current versions of both operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   For a personal computer with Windows 95, go to the Start menu
and select Settings, then Control Panel. The various icons there,
with names like Sounds, Mouse and Keyboard, are for controls that
let you customize the look of your computer.
</P>
<P>
   Double-click on the Display icon, and the Display Properties box
will pop up. Click on the Appearance tab. In the bottom part of the
box, go to the Item pop-up menu and select Icon. In the Size box to
the right, type in a number that is larger than the one you see,
and the icons will become larger. You can also change the font and
font size of the icons' labels in the boxes just below. When
finished, click Apply, then OK.
</P>
<P>
   If you work on a Macintosh running OS 8,look under View in the
Finder's Menu bar. Pick View Options, and click the button for the
icon size you'd like. There are two sizes available for desktop
icons. To change the size of icons that appear in folder windows,
open any folder and repeat the process (there are three icon sizes
to choose from). You can change the font and font size for your
icons with the Preferences option in the Finder's Edit menu. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology by
postal mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West
43d Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
QandA(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
