<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2399 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-KID-WEATHER-SITE-     06-03 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-KID-WEATHER-SITE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOBAL WEATHER PROJECT UNITES STUDENTS ON WEB 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Md., N.Y., Colo.)   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (af)  
 By DEBRA NUSSBAUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In rain, snow, sleet and hail, and even wind that will ruin a
teen-ager's perfect hair, students around the country are trudging
outside daily to gather precise weather data that will be used by
teams of scientists studying the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these students gather their information on Saturdays and
Sundays, and a few have even shown up on holidays to record data on
temperature, cloud cover, precipitation and the pH of rain and snow
for a program called Global Learning and Observations to Benefit
the Environment. As students become more advanced in their
data-gathering skills, they add hydrology, land cover and soil
studies.
</P>
<P>
   After gathering the data, the students enter it on the Globe Web
site (www.globe.gov). Students in more than 4,000 schools in the
United States and 1,000 schools in 70 countries are using the
Internet in this way to report their weather observations.
</P>
<P>
   Nine teams of government and university scientists use the data
from the Globe Web site, which gets 30,000 hits a day from
students, teachers and anyone else who is interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of talking about what scientists do, we are doing what
scientists do,'' said Joe Grande, a teacher and chairman of the
science department at Abington Junior High School in a suburb of
Philadelphia. ``They love to go outside and collect the
information. It gives the kids an ownership of the data.''
</P>
<P>
   The Globe program was started in April 1994 by Vice President Al
Gore as a way to give elementary and high-school students hands-on
science and computer training. Based in Washington, it receives
about $13 million each year from the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration, the National Science Foundation and
National Aeronautics and Space Administration.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, some Republican leaders have tried to cut the
program. Rep. John R. Kasich, R-Ohio, who is chairman of the budget
committee, said in a 1996 speech that the program ``says to
children, `We will give you millions of dollars to measure rainfall
by collecting it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But the program has enough fans in both parties in Congress that
it has been financed for the past three years. The next proposed
budget requests $13 million for the program, said Ann Elise
Hardison, Globe's communications director.
</P>
<P>
   In Grande's seventh-grade science class, students take turns
gathering information for the project. Every day two of them walk
out to a steel box on the school's lawn with a Globe clipboard.
</P>
<P>
   Students need to make their observations within an hour of solar
noon. Checking the instruments in the box, they record the maximum
and minimum temperature in the previous 24 hours (in Celsius, of
course), the amount of rainfall and the extent of cloud cover. If
there has been rain or snow, they measure the accumulation and pH
level.
</P>
<P>
   When the students return to the classroom, they go to the Globe
Web site and record the data on the computerized form. Students can
check data from around the world, call up weather maps and see if
weather predictions matched reality.
</P>
<P>
   Grande's class has also monitored the weather on most weekends.
On Saturdays, Dan Scharle, 12, goes to the weather box to get the
data; his classmate Allison Tausek, 13, does the same on Sundays.
``It's cool to realize that everyone around the world will see the
numbers I give to Grande,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, 300 students from 22 countries who have
participated in Globe will attend a Globe conference in Helsinki,
Finland, where they will get a chance to tell scientists about the
data they are gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Globe's budget is used to support the scientists who work with
the program, to provide free teacher training and educational
material and to maintain the Web site. The schools also spend $400
to $900 apiece for weather-measuring equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest concern about the program early on, Ms. Hardison
said, was whether students could be trusted to collect data. ``That
has been proven,'' she said. ``Students can be counted on to gather
useful environmental science data.''
</P>
<P>
   When Republicans tried to cut the program, many teachers spoke
up to defend it. A teacher in Kasich's district called it the best
science program since the Manhattan Project.
</P>
<P>
   The administration, defending the Globe program, said it gave
students hands-on training. Killing the program would have wasted
the schools' investment in equipment and training for it, officials
added. Most of the cost is carried by the school, although some
federal grants have been available.
</P>
<P>
   A soil scientist, Dr. Elissa Levine, who works at the NASA
Goddard Space Flight Center in Greenbelt, Md., uses the weather
data to see how weather patterns have affected soil
characteristics. Dr. Levine visits schools regularly and exchanges
e-mail with students.
</P>
<P>
   Several times a year, she gets on the Web to tell the students
about her research and give them a chance to ask her questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Web chats are wonderful,'' she said. ``The questions range
all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Students are also able to talk on the Web to students in the
Globe program at other schools. At the Dwight School in Manhattan,
on Central Park West at 89th Street, students in the elementary
division have asked children in Boulder, Colo., about their weather
and have asked children in Finland what their school is like, said
the division's dean, Nancy Burton.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've found kids all over the world live lives that are more
similar than different,'' Ms. Burton said. The school's students
use the data in science and math classes.
</P>
<P>
   They have plotted their numbers on charts and graphs and checked
out Globe's historic weather data on Central Park. Once a month,
the students go down to the 79th Street Boat Basin on the Hudson
River and check the river's temperature and pH level.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the data has been the easiest part for the students,
Ms. Burton said. ``Kids are much more computer-literate than
adults,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   A long-term benefit of the program may be that it will encourage
students to go into the fields of technology and science, Dr.
Levine said. She received a letter from a sixth-grade girl who said
she had wanted to be a doctor or a veterinarian. ``Now,'' Dr.
Levine said, ``she wants to be a soil scientist for NASA.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
