`BULWORTH' BORROWS FROM EARNEST POLITICAL GEMS OF THE '70s 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whatever else you might say about ``Bulworth,'' part of what
makes it exciting and different is that it has reintroduced the
idea of politics in a major studio movie. For those of us who think
movies should be about something, ``Bulworth'' offers ideas: the
corruption of a man's ideals as seen from the eye of the hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   It is a refreshing concept that has mostly disappeared from
movies; empty-headed junk like ``Deep Impact'' and ``Godzilla''
couldn't be less interested in giving audiences something to talk
about.
</P>
<P>
   As the disillusioned senator, Warren Beatty is so eager to give
the movie a political context that ``Bulworth'' seems a little
incoherent, like someone who has so much to say that he rushes
through it all so that we end up with no idea of the point he is
trying to make.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the audacity feels a little worn. Beatty never deals
with the fact that a number of African-Americans don't like rap,
and in fact that's probably the audience segment most likely to be
offended when Halle Berry murmurs to Beatty, ``You know you my
nigga.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also a hint of Beatty trying to have his cake and eat
it, too. By using rap, he connects with both the prime movie-going
audience _ white 12- to 24-year-olds _ and a black audience
underserved by movies in general.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bulworth'' comes at a time when we're seeing more movies about
politics _ ``Wag the Dog'' and ``Primary Colors'' also touch on the
subject _ than we've seen in years. But Beatty's ``Bulworth'' is an
anachronism, a healthy throwback to the old-fashioned political
context that flourished in movies a few years back, a period that
ended about the time of ``Apocalypse Now.'' These days, the only
politics you find in movies is capitalism: getting audiences to
vote with their dollars, so the pictures make a profit.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when politics and movies were so intertwined
that a political subtext was inescapable. Even ``Star Wars'' lifted
the last sequence _ the military procession _ from Leni
Riefenstahl's ``Triumph of the Will'' in order to make a subtle
point about the fascist implications of the Force.
</P>
<P>
   For the longest time, politics had to be sneaked into movies the
way sex was hidden in films before the MPAA ratings came along;
politics was part of the subtext in such films as ``Bonnie &AMP;
Clyde'' and ``Chinatown.'' And I say ``had to'' because the nation
was torn apart by civil rights issues, the Vietnam War and U.S.
involvement in South America. Those issues created a schism across
the country, and filmmakers were proud to get their attitudes into
their films, like the lumnious and insane ``Burn,'' with Marlon
Brando. It was in the '70s that politics had its last flowering as
a subject for movies, when fervor and anger and mistrust boiled
into a potent stew in the national consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   The high point of that cinematic unrest is the little-seen and
not-quite-successful thriller ``The Parallax View,'' with its
merciless paranoia and Beatty starring as a reporter pulled into an
assassination conspiracy. (''Parallax View'' has been acknowledged
by ``X-Files'' creator Chris Carter as an inspiration for that
show's suspicious purview.)
</P>
<P>
   But ``Parallax View'' wasn't the first _ or the best _ of such
movies. The picture that set the tone of fear and powerlessness in
politics happens to be one of the craftiest comedies ever made:
``The Manchurian Candidate,'' based on the novel by Richard Condon.
Essentially a vaudevillian, All-American turn on Graham Greene, in
which a soldier is brainwashed into killing the president,
``Candidate'' was set into motion by Frank Sinatra, who produced
and starred in the film. When John F. Kennedy, Sinatra's friend,
was slain by an assassin's bullet, the heartsick producer withdrew
the movie from circulation.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Bulworth,'' Beatty skimmed off the earnestness that used to
be such a part of the political backdrop in movies, using slickness
as a concession to the audience's need to be entertained. But all
of the other recent movies about politics, like the softhearted
``Dave,'' prize the entertainment factor so highly that they never
really get around to displaying any brains. ``Dave,'' along with
``The American President'' and ``My Fellow Americans'' relinquished
significance in a desperation to inflict pleasantries. They danced
around the issues. ``The American President'' and ``Dave'' were
romantic comedies about how the Oval Office can put a crimp in your
love life. (Which, clearly, isn't a problem for some of its
residents.) MORE &QL; 
.MDNM/ttx-z r ebx nt06 nt07 nt26 &QL; 
rebx &QL; 
BC-BULWORTH-ESSAY-1600(2ndTake)-TEX &QL; 
`BULWORTH' BORROWS FROM EARNEST POLITICAL GEMS OF THE '70s &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED: of its residents.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The other quasi-political movies about the Oval Office have been
thrillers, like the less-than-memorable ``Murder at 1600,'' in
which the president is barely necessary. Clint Eastwood starred in
a pair of them, ``In the Line of Fire''.MDBU/.MDNM/ and ``Absolute
Power,'' movies in which the presidential figure is mostly a
nuisance. In ``Air Force One,'' Harrison Ford turns the chief
executive into a fierce anti-terroristist who must have been
inspired by the old ``Super President'' cartoon series of the '60s,
in which the president was literally the alter ego of a
superpowered being. In ``Independence Day,'' Bill Pullman is a
president who gets his credibility back when he has aerial
dogfights with creatures from another world.
</P>
<P>
   But those films have nothing to do with politics, strictly
speaking. Rather, they are about the contempt that has grown in
most of us for the political process. It's a deeply cynical ploy
for a movie to suggest that, essentially, the only way the most
powerful elected officeholder in the world can show any muscle is
to strap on a gun. When the level of discourse for the president in
most recent films consists of him disarming an alien, it's no
wonder Beatty felt he had to make ``Bulworth.'' At least the
president in Stanley Kubrick's ``Dr. Strangelove'' was supposed to
be a cartoon that no one took seriously. But in most movies, no one
takes politics seriously. There are those who say that Oliver Stone
keeps political debate alive in film, but most of Stone's movie's
are about ... well, Oliver Stone.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe movies about politics, and the presidency in particular,
have sacrificed weight since Watergate and its consequences. ``All
the President's Men'' was the final word that we couldn't trust the
people we voted into office. But some of the most important movies
about politics have a defeated air. ``The Candidate,'' an absorbing
and keenly corrosive satire of young liberal candidate (Robert
Redford) being hustled as a product, ends on a disquieting note. It
amplified, even during an era of hope, the disorder and compromise
that politics cause.
</P>
<P>
   The satires ``Wag the Dog, Primary Colors'' and ``Bulworth''
also end with a bad taste. These are all the visions of major
directors, who felt these movies had to be made and forced the
issue. ``Wag the Dog'' was made by Barry Levinson (''Rain Man)''
quickly and cheaply; ``Primary Colors'' was based on a bestselling
novel and featured major star John Travolta; ``Bulworth'' came
about because Fox contractually owed Warren Beatty a movie and
didn't want to be dragged through the courts.
</P>
<P>
   As a producer, Beatty has used politics as a backdrop more than
anyone, including two of his most interesting movies, ``Reds'' and
``Shampoo,'' which was set during the 1968 presidential election.
Perhaps in an era in which things are good, as they were during the
time before the Depression _ which galvanized filmmakers to make
movies about the state of the world in a way we haven't seen since
_ we don't want to be reminded in movie of just how little we
demand of our politicians.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
