<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2403 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUDSON-HOUSE-TOUR-ART     06-03 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUDSON-HOUSE-TOUR-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR WHO DEFINED 19TH CENTURY ARCHITECTURAL TASTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By PATRICIA LEIGH BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWBURGH, N.Y. _ A river ran through them. Clouds still linger
on the craggy green cliffs overlooking the Hudson River. And if you
stand on the wide Gothic revival verandas of houses that began a
19th-century design revolution here and squint past the
subdivisions, it is possible to feel the kinship that Andrew
Jackson Downing, Calvert Vaux and Frederick Clarke Withers had with
this place. But the story has largely slipped into history's mists.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the most ugly house you can imagine _ really nasty,''
Julian Hogan, a 48-year-old psychologist, said of the hilltop house
she later learned was built in 1857 by a young architect named
Vaux, who would meet Frederick Law Olmsted, a sometime farmer, on
Newburgh's fertile ground and go on to design Central Park with
him. ``But something about the light was amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   After buying it she removed an inch and a half of wire-lathed
stucco _ and uncovered an extraordinary, forgotten legacy. ``I kept
thinking, If people only knew.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon they will know. On June 6 and 7, this scrappy river city,
home to one of the state's largest and most significant historic
districts, will be the host of ``Taste Makers of an Era,'' a
two-day symposium and house tour that will examine the lineage of
four 19th-century apostles of taste _ Downing, Vaux, Withers and
Olmsted _ and the city that nurtured them.
</P>
<P>
   Among the featured scholars at the event will be Francis Kowsky,
whose new book ``Country, Park and City: The Architecture and Life
of Calvert Vaux'' (Oxford University Press) has prompted a
reappraisal of the more silent partner in Olmsted &AMP; Vaux.
</P>
<P>
   Downing, Vaux's mentor and the son of a Newburgh wheelwright and
nurseryman, became the leading taste maker of his generation,
mostly through his writings. He drowned in the Hudson when fire
broke out on a steamboat ferrying him to visit clients. It was
1852. He was 36. Vaux, the ``clever young architect'' Downing had
plucked from obscurity in England and and eventually made his
partner, grimly identified the body. The coffin was laid out in the
library of Highland Garden, Downing's house in Newburgh. ``A
terrific storm burst over the river and crashed among the hills,''
an observer wrote, ``and the wild sympathy of nature surrounded
that blasted home.''
</P>
<P>
   Downing had forged a naturalistic link between house and garden,
a revolutionary idea that _ perhaps forever in America _ threw the
corset of classical formality to the winds.
</P>
<P>
   Frederick Withers, another young English architect discovered
and hired by Downing, would become a leading church designer and
architect of wondrous Gothic revival buildings like the Jefferson
Market Courthouse in Greenwich Village. The last collaboration
between Vaux and Olmsted would be a park in Newburgh in Downing's
memory.
</P>
<P>
   Downing's historical timing was perfect. He appeared at a moment
before the Civil War when a generation of home builders, the new
American middle class, was seeking to define American style. It was
in need of an oracle, an ``apostle of taste,'' in the words of
David Schuyler, an architectural historian.
</P>
<P>
   In popular books and in The Horticulturist, his journal of
``rural art and rural taste,'' Downing set forth his ideas about
picturesque houses and gardens, advocating the Gothic revival
style. He loved the Gothic for its ``artistical irregularity.'' The
variety of its forms, proportions, color, light and shade, Vaux
later wrote, appealed to the eye ``and through the eye to the
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   An architectural evangelist, Downing told America's new middle
class what it yearned to hear: that taste could be learned. At
Highland Garden and other houses in and around Newburgh _ some of
which, designed in partnership with Vaux and Withers, are on the
tour _ Downing put his ideas about landscape into practice. (The
houses were designed by Vaux and Withers; Downing had no formal
architectural training).
</P>
<P>
   From his property on the Hudson's steep slopes, he established a
design firm catering to Newburgh's middle class; Vaux and Withers
would continue the business for three years after his death. The
grounds were poetry, with shadowy pathways, fragrant beds of moss
and thyme and rustic log and bark shelters, so one could ``linger
and quietly communicate with the genius of the place,'' in Francis
Kowsky's words.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Newburgh _ listed as one of the most
endangered historic districts by the National Trust for Historic
Preservation _ has a subculture of homeowners who consider
themselves keepers of the flame. They have inherited french doors,
breezy verandas, side porches, bay windows and quirkily placed
chimneys. Like Downing, they tend to be messianic. This may be the
only city in America where homeowners can quote verbatim from
dogeared editions of ``Cottage Residences,'' Downing's 1852
classic.
</P>
<P>
   Lillie and Dan Hodge live in a house above the river that Vaux
designed for William Warren, treasurer of the Delaware, Lackawanna
&AMP; Western Railroad and deputy comptroller of New York City.
Conceived as a platform for viewing nature, the house is subtly
planned, its public front tall and ornamental, with a simple, more
horizontal back that has a view of the river.
</P>
<P>
   Though Vaux ``didn't invent a style of architecture,'' Kowsky
notes, he had an eye for spatial arrangement, adapting each house
to its location and allowing those who lived there to feel intimate
with the landscape. That talent would be extravagantly expressed
later in Central Park in spots like Bethesda Terrace, where the
views were from naturally elevated areas ``in a manner analogous to
the way Vaux sited his houses,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   The house has been in the Hodge family since 1953. Mrs. Hodge
still has some of Warren's books, including a Bible with a big
silver clasp. Not long ago, the Hodges hired Tom Pope, a house
painter from Chatham, N.Y., to paint the place, which was
originally coated in stucco.
</P>
<P>
   Vaux was drawn to ``soft, quiet tones,'' but because the
exterior had been sandblasted to reveal the brick, Pope felt it was
OK to ``make it jump out a bit.'' He striped the tin canopies,
spruced up the rosettes and chose what he calls ``an Olana theme''
_ an allusion to the painter Frederic E. Church's sensuous Moorish
reverie farther up the Hudson, designed by Church and planned by
Vaux.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Hodges' house now has a whimsical air. Lillie Hodge feels
herself admiring it, especially when cleaning her pair of
ballrooms. ``It's a museum, really _ that's how I see it,'' she
said. ``But it's well lived in. There's no furniture you can't sit
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Downing's romantic presence is palpable even in the driveway
that wends its way to the 23-room Downing-Vaux ``cottage'' owned by
Linda Anderson Henry and Scott Henry. As it turns, the drive
reveals a three-quarter profile of the house, its irregular roof
lines deliberate echoes of the distant hills.
</P>
<P>
   The house was built after Downing's death beside a stream in
what Downing called ``the Rhine style,'' and it has been an object
of passionate _ some might say obsessive _ interest for the couple
since they purchased it in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Henry, a freelance political consultant, and Ms. Henry, a
psychologist, had a ``coming out party'' for their house to which
they invited leading Downing and Vaux scholars. Henry, who studied
architecture at Brooklyn Tech, has made a career out of researching
the history of his property. He speaks grandly of ``classic Downing
effects.''
</P>
<P>
   Though few Downing landscapes survive, there is a strong
suspicion among landscape historians that Henry's and Ms.
Anderson's yard, with its tulip trees, Osage orange trees, European
beeches and native specimens, may be among them.
</P>
<P>
   Newburgh residents who own and love these houses seem determined
not to be intimidated by their illustrious architectural pedigrees.
Though they proudly show off the original drawings of their house,
designed by Withers in 1859, Carla and Robert Decker were bent on
making it comfortable. While they restored the parlor, with its
original gaslight ceiling fixture, they let the rest of the house
``kind of just be 1998,'' as Mrs. Decker put it.
</P>
<P>
   Houses like the Deckers' are testaments to an optimistic era in
which the towns along the Hudson boomed with the river. Recent
history, however, has not been kind to Newburgh, whose depressed
economy and high vacancy rates are taking their toll on the
historic district.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, Morningside, an 1859 Withers house, was in such
disrepair that its Gothic revival library was removed and
reconstructed in the American Wing of the Metropolitan Museum of
Art. (The house, on the June 7 tour, has since been restored.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Poverty is a preserver of sorts,'' said Winthrop Aldrich, the
deputy commissioner for historic preservation in the state Parks
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are signs of a rebound. The National Trust has
recently set up a nonprofit development corporation to create
affordable housing in the historic district. And the 35-acre city
park designed by Vaux and Olmsted in Downing's memory _ finished,
poignantly, by their sons, including one named Downing Vaux _ has
been rejuvenated by the Downing Park Planning Committee. Downing is
buried nearby, beneath a medieval-looking gravestone designed,
naturally, by Vaux.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like having a wonderful painting you scratched and
discovered was a Rembrandt,'' Henry said of the city's uncommon
lineage. ``So what do you do? You keep on scratching.''
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Registration
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, ``Taste Makers of an Era: A Perusal of the
Architectural Works of Andrew Jackson Downing, Calvert Vaux,
Frederick C. Withers and Frederick Law Olmsted,'' takes place in
Newburgh, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A symposium on Downing and his disciples, featuring Francis
Kowsky, David Schuyler and other scholars, will be held on Saturday
from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m., with registration from 9 to 10 a.m., at 189
Montgomery St. (Clinton Street). The cost is $20.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday from noon to 5 p.m., there will be a film and tour of
more than 15 homes and churches designed by the four men in the
Newburgh area. Registration begins at 11 a.m.. The cost is $20.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (914) 561-2585.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
