<SLUG> BC-CIR-NETNAMES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GREAT DOMAIN NAME HUNT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (Eds: Please note subslug for CIR-TONGA)  
 (af)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You filthy-minded little pervert! The Kingdom of Tonga
admonishes you. Now go back and think of another name that you
wouldn't be embarrassed to say to your mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the shame, being scolded by a computer. But more about that
later.
</P>
<P>
   All I wanted to do was to get an Internet domain name of my own.
The problem is that Lewis is a very common name, and lewis.com was
already taken.
</P>
<P>
   So, like millions of Internet users before me, I began looking
elsewhere for a domain I could call home, the Internet equivalent
of 40 acres where I could grow electronic mail, raise a small herd
of Web pages and maybe someday _ this is the Internet dream _ open
a little electronic cottage industry of my own, all with my own
unique electronic brand. Lewis dot something. Lewis dot anything.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be technically difficult for average computer users
to get their own personal, second-level Internet domain names _ the
part of an e-mail address to the right of the ``(AT)'' and the part
of the World Wide Web address that typically follows www. But if
you could figure out how to do it, registering a domain name was
free, and good names were plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   No more. The Internet is now the world's fastest-growing
economy, and the commercialization of the Internet has created a
feeding frenzy for domain names. A combination of greed, government
bureaucracy, technical jingoism and wild consumer speculation has
thrown the Internet addressing system into chaos.
</P>
<P>
   This week, after months of debate and policy wrangling, the
Clinton administration is expected to issue its revised proposal
for turning the management of the Internet domain naming system
over to a private nonprofit international organization. If all goes
according to plan, individuals and businesses alike will find it
easier to register and begin using a domain name.
</P>
<P>
   With 100 million people on the Internet, domain names are
already a precious commodity. After all, an Internet domain name is
not just the computer equivalent of a telephone number and mailing
address but also a status symbol, a powerful marketing tool and a
vanity license plate.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, someone in Texas was reported to have paid $150,000
for the rights to the name business.com.
</P>
<P>
   Although alternatives will soon abound, nearly everyone agrees
that no other Internet address carries the cachet of a personal
``dot com'' domain, the equivalent of a 212 area code for a phone
number or a Fifth Avenue address. It is the largest top-level
domain on the Internet, with more than two million unique secondary
domains (like nytimes.com). More than 100,000 new ``dot com''
domains are added each month.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still good dot-com names available,'' said Doug
Wolford, senior vice president for marketing and sales at Network
Solutions, a for-profit company that for the past five years has
had a virtual monopoly on registering .com domains because of an
early agreement with the National Science Foundation, the original
Internet overseer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people don't get their first choice, obviously they're
going to say all the good names are gone,'' Wolford said. ``But
with a little creativity, there are lots of good names left.''
</P>
<P>
   Network Solutions, known in the industry as NSI, is a case in
point. Someone else nabbed the address nsi.com before NSI did, so
the company took the less intuitive netsol.com. And now, facing the
end of its government-mandated monopoly on Sept. 30, the company
has been marketing itself as ``The Dot Com People''
(www.thedotcompeople.com) and adopting a much more friendly
demeanor to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   I tried to be creative. Peterlewis.com had been registered by a
fire-and-brimstone Christian group in Kansas called the Friend to
Friend Foundation (www.friendtofriend. com) that apparently
finances its ministries by registering Internet domains and
releasing them to others in return for donations.
</P>
<P>
   Pete.com already belongs to a guy named Pete in Hawaii.
Peter.com was taken by a chap named Jimmy in England. Phoenix Home
Life got to my initials before I did, so I had to scratch phl.com.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, lewis.org and lewis.net _ .org and .net being
arguably the two most desirable top-level domains after .com _ had
been snatched already. Lewis.edu belongs to Lewis Middle School in
San Diego, which has a dandy Web site. Lewis.gov or lewis.mil are
available, but since I have neither my own government bureaucracy
nor an army, I don't qualify.
</P>
<P>
   A group of Internet mullahs called the Internet Assigned Numbers
Authority last year proposed adding seven more top-level domains:
.firm, .shop, .web, .arts, .rec, .info and .nom. But those
proposals fell into an electronic limbo in January when the Clinton
administration first proposed its overhaul of the domain naming
system.
</P>
<P>
   And besides, my swifter relatives and an assortment of domain
bandits quickly signed up for lewis.nom, lewis.info and others.
</P>
<P>
   So, like my Irish and Welsh forebears more than a century ago, I
began looking for a virtual homestead in another country.
</P>
<P>
   Using the ``whois'' command (neatly automated for novice
computer users at rs.internic.net/cgi-bin/whois), I quickly
scratched from my list Sweden, Denmark, South Africa, Switzerland,
New Zealand and Australia, all of which had been electronically
homesteaded by Lewises, or pretenders, before I got there.
</P>
<P>
   But the world is a big place, and the Internet is spreading.
More than 200 countries now offer Internet domain registrations
under their own two-letter country codes, like .jp for Japan and
.uk for Britain. The .us for the United States has until now been
used primarily by state and local governments.
</P>
<P>
   It is significant that more than 70 of these 200-plus countries
have no local residence requirement (most require merely some sort
of local presence) and, shall we say, relaxed concepts of trademark
law. Some have policies that allow any paying customer to register
names on a first-come, first-served basis, allowing a swift and
unscrupulous entrepreneur to register microsoft.xx or mcdonalds.xx.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Turkmenistan's country code .tm, might be mistaken for
a trademark notice, which has made it very popular. Turkmenistan is
one of many unlikely countries trying to capitalize on the demand
for Internet domain names and generate some income.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, domain registries have been marketing little
pieces of Bhutan (.bt), the Cocos Islands (.cc), Tuvalu (.tv),
Congo (.cd), Niue (.nu) and American Samoa (.as), among many
others.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 1615EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2408 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-NETNAMES-ART-2NDT     06-03 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-NETNAMES-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: many others.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many of these burgeoning Internet paradises have no meaningful
communications infrastructure, at least in terms of the
big-bandwidth demands of the Internet, so they form partnerships
with Web-savvy companies in major cities like New York, San
Francisco and London. The all-important name-server computers,
which keep track of all the names and addresses of all the clients
in the given domain, are often tethered to high-capacity phone
lines thousands of miles away from the namesake country.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, I was beaten to lewis.tm by just one day, by someone in
England named Jones. Another British rival had registered lewis.cc,
from the Cocos. Even the microscopic island of Niue had already
issued lewis.nu to someone else.
</P>
<P>
   So I raced through the global Internet Packet network to the
South Pacific island of Tonga, only to discover that the same
Jones, who fittingly lives on Robin Hood Street in Gloucester, had
also snatched lewis.to just ahead of me. An information
superhighwayman, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   In frustration, I tried to register the first word that came to
mind _ one that cannot be printed in this newspaper _ prompting the
stinging rebuke from the Tongan computer. Tonga and its Internet
overseer, His Royal Highness Crown Prince Tupouto'a, are extremely
proud of the island's Christian heritage and ban pornography and
foul language.
</P>
<P>
   Turkmenistan recently suspended all new domain registrations
after it discovered that people were registering obscene and unholy
words. At this point I resolved to find the most remote speck in
the ocean, where the fame and prestige of the Lewis clan has not
yet spread. Spinning my globe, I picked a spot almost precisely at
the opposite end of the earth from my home and there found
Christmas Island.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas Island, a territory of Australia, has fewer than 900
residents. Surrounded by sharks, the island is home to one
television station, one AM radio station, one casino and several
million scuttling crabs. It is a veritable crab paradise, with 18
different species, including one so large and powerful that it
cracks coconuts with its pincers.
</P>
<P>
   But to me, the island's most interesting resource was _ at last!
_ an unclaimed spot for lewis.cx. A search of the domain's official
records revealed the welcome news that Christmas Island's domain is
administered by four name-server computers in London, presumably on
robust, crab-tolerant phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   With the end of my search so tantalizingly near, and with no
desire to navigate a foreign technical bureaucracy on my own, I
decided to use a domain name agent. One of the best agents is
Netnames USA (www.netnamesusa.com), which is based in New York and
boasts that it can easily and painlessly, if not exactly
inexpensively, register secondary domain names almost anywhere on
the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Netnames typically charges a onetime fee of $75 to set up each
.com, .net or .org domain and $249 to set up a national domain.
National domains also charge their own registration and annual
fees, which vary widely. The customer can also hire the agent to
administer the domain, in effect renting the use of the agent's
name servers.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement can be temporary (until the domain name is
transferred to a local Internet service provider) or long-term.
Netnames allows the user to set up as many as five e-mail accounts
on the new domain without charge. Mail sent to pete(AT)lewis.cx,
for example, assuming I get the name, will automatically be
forwarded to my preferred e-mail account.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, requests sent to www.lewis.cx would be automatically
forwarded to the humble Web site that my preferred ISP provides
free _ but now I won't have to use a Web address that contains lots
of squiggles and dots and dashes and slashes.
</P>
<P>
   So for the bargain price of $249, I bought a piece of Christmas
Island. My application will be evaluated by the Christmas Island
domain administrator and will be operational as soon as I am
determined to be a good citizen, electronically speaking.
</P>
<P>
   And if I'm rejected, well, there can't possibly be many Lewises
in Antarctica or Tajikistan. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you're interested in getting your own domain name here are a
few helpful hints.
</P>
<P>
   Following are some of commercial registries for top-level
Internet domains, including national two-letter country code
domains. They handle, for a fee, all aspects of registering and
maintaining domestic and international domain names.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.netnamesusa.com/ NetnamesUSA, New York, New York
212-627-4599 or 888-NETNAMES
</P>
<P>
   http://www.idnames.com idNames, Herndon, Va. (a subsidiary of
Network Solutions Inc.) 888-436-2637
</P>
<P>
   http://www.alldomains.com A division of NetCorps, Pleasant Hill,
Calif., 510-685-9600.
</P>
<P>
   For `Do-It-Yourself` Registration through Network Information
Centers (NICs)
</P>
<P>
   Tonga http://www.tonic.to
</P>
<P>
   Niue http://www.nunic.nu
</P>
<P>
   For an expanded list of national NICs:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.yahoo.com/Computers_and_Internet/Internet/Domain_Registra
tion/Network_Information_Centers/
</P>
<P>
   For the full list of official country codes:
http://www.iana.org/in-notes/iana/assignments/country-codes
</P>
<P>
   For information on using the `WHOIS` command:
http://www.rs.internic.net/tools/whois.html
</P>
</TEXT>
