<SLUG> BC-CIR-NOSTALGIA-CAPSULE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOOSE SOME `GOOD OLD DAYS' AND SEE HOW THEY REALLY WERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Want to prove to your wisecracking, history-challenged progeny
that ``Roll Over Beethoven'' _ and not old Ludwig himself _ was all
the rage when you were born?
</P>
<P>
   For an instant dose of personal nostalgia, just beam your Web
browser to the dMarie Time Capsule (dmarie.com/asp/history.asp).
Once there, type in a birthday or other significant date. The Time
Capsule will reward you with a quick recap of the top headlines for
the three months surrounding that date and the sports achievements
and most popular songs from the year.
</P>
<P>
   You can find out other ephemera from that period, including
average income, the prices of a stamp and a gallon of milk, and
Academy Award winners. The site offers specific data for the years
1900 to 1997, although some facts from 1995 to 1997 are not
available yet.
</P>
<P>
   The Time Capsule comes courtesy of dMarie.com, a do-it-yourself
site that lets its users compile and lay out their own virtual
scrapbooks and also features chat rooms, discussion boards and a
poetry database.
</P>
<P>
   ``The information here is to serve as a fun, reminiscent stroll
through past days,'' reads a disclaimer on the Time Capsule page.
``Use it to put together a heritage page for your scrapbook _ NOT
for your school history report!''
</P>
<P>
   While the Capsule provides a soft-focus-lens look at a certain
time, surfing scholars looking for events occurring on a particular
day may need to dig a little deeper. The History Channel's Web site
has an online version of its popular ``This Day in History''
television spot (historychannel.com/thisday).
</P>
<P>
   After selecting a date, users are treated to a page of
historical and pop-culture events that took place on that day. For
instance, on this day in 1939, the first grocery-store shopping
cart was introduced in Oklahoma City. June 4 is also the birthday
of England's King George III (in 1738), and ``Love Me Do'' by his
future countrymen the Beatles was topping the American pop charts
on this date in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo also boasts an extensive list of time-specific tidbits on
its Today in History page. It includes a link to the Library of
Congress' Today in History site, illustrated with items from the
library's collection.
</P>
<P>
   More focused efforts, like the Literary Calender, Mathematicians
Throughout the Year and Today in Movies, also round out Yahoo's
collection (www.yahoo.com/Arts/Humanities/History/TodayinHistory).
</P>
<P>
   The brief synopses these history pages offer _ particularly if
you search, say, on your high-school graduation date _ are enough
to transport you, emotionally at least, back in time. And if you
can't remember all the words to what were your favorite songs, you
might find them at the Lyrics Library Homepage
(web2.kw.igs.net/wgarvin/ lyrics.html). You can find all the words
to ``American Pie'' there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 1617EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
