<HEADER>
A2419 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-SCREEN-SAVERS-NYT     06-03 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SCREEN-SAVERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNING DESKTOPS INTO THEME PARKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(th) 
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only defense I will offer for my recent behavior _ I just
spent hours playing with dinosaurs _ is this: My children made me
do it.
</P>
<P>
   My young daughters are obsessed with dinosaurs. Yours probably
are, too, so I would not be surprised to learn that you have also
been sucked into the vortex of the ``desktop theme'' craze that is
overtaking home computer users.
</P>
<P>
   Theme programs are the next iteration of screen savers; they're
screen savers on speed. Not only do they change the background on
your monitor, but they often use video and sound to transform other
elements of your desktop into, well, a theme park, or, in my case,
a two-dimensional facsimile of Jurassic Park.
</P>
<P>
   PC desktop customizing has come a long way since the old days,
when the definition of a mind-bending screen saver was something
that projected images of tropical fish swimming languidly. Today's
theme programs take various components of your desktop _ the
wallpaper, the screen saver, fonts, icons, sounds _ and repackage
them around a single theme.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the Dinosaurs program written for Windows
computers by Hank Van Winkle, a graduate student at Northern
Illinois University, mutated all the icons on my desktop. The My
Computer icon became a little image of the head of an angry T. rex,
and the Recycling Bin turned into a skeletal version of same. The
background on the monitor was a hungry T. rex rudely mauling an
unlucky triceratops. When I started up my computer, I heard a roar.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and the mouse pointer turned into a claw. That was the part
my daughters liked most.
</P>
<P>
   If you are wondering just how hot the themes trend is, consider
that in the three weeks since Tucows Interactive opened a new site,
www.freethemes.com, traffic to the site has grown to 100,000 views
a day. ``That's what we call popular,'' said Elliot Noss, vice
president of Tucows. ``It's probably because themes allow you to
control the look and feel of your desktop in a way you couldn't
before.''
</P>
<P>
   At www.hotfiles.com, ZDNet's download site, one of the most
requested software programs is a simple shareware utility called
Desktop Themes, which enables the Windows operating system to
recognize and accept themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few months ago, this shareware program didn't even exist,
and now it has become one of the most popular programs in our
library,'' said Preston Gralla, executive editor for the ZDNet
software library.
</P>
<P>
   The reason that themes are proving so popular is that people
identify with their computers. Computers aren't just machines
anymore. They have become little buddies who take us to new places,
introduce us to new activities and claim more and more of our
waking hours.
</P>
<P>
   Most computers look relatively generic _ could you really pick
out a particular Windows box from a lineup? But users want to
invest them with a personality. Remember when all your Macintosh
friends used to give their machines friendly names like Mabel,
Skeezer or Rover? In that same spirit, you can now load a desktop
theme.
</P>
<P>
   And you can choose from thousands of themes: sports themes; pop
culture themes, like Titanic or the Spice Girls or the Rug Rats, or
themes that send alien space invaders scurrying across your
desktop. I even ran across a program titled Kill Them Seagulls,
described rather drily as capable of importing 605 kilobytes of
anti-seagull sentiment to your desktop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cool,'' said Zoe, my 9-year-old. ``Let's get that one next.''
</P>
<P>
   Why not? Putting aside for the moment any fears I had of
inciting the wrath of animal rights activists, installing a theme
on my Windows machine is incredibly easy. Soon, I was enjoying the
spectacle of dozens of seagulls flying across my screen;
occasionally, one is shot and falls from the sky with a strangled
squawk.
</P>
<P>
   And I did not even have to download the Desktop Themes utility
because my computer maker chose to install Microsoft Plus in the
factory. Introduced in 1995 as an enhancement to Windows, Microsoft
Plus is a package of entertainment and utility programs that was,
in fact, responsible for spawning the themes revolution. Plus has a
program in it that hangs, like a hook, off the Windows operating
system. You can, in turn, hang any desktop theme on the hook.
</P>
<P>
   Plus comes with about a dozen themes of its own, including a
Mystery theme that reminds me of the Clue board game, a science
theme and an artsy Leonardo da Vinci theme that displays sketches
and his famous signature on screen.
</P>
<P>
   If you have Plus and want to check out the themes furnished by
Microsoft, look in your Control Panel. Double click on the Desktop
Themes icon to sample them all.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you feeling like Hamlet, trying to decide whether
it is worth the bother to upgrade to the Windows 98 operating
system (``Alas, poor 95! I knew it, Horatio.''), Microsoft is
offering this inducement: more themes! After soliciting feedback
from focus groups, Microsoft decided to upgrade Plus 98 to include
themes based upon favorite characters from the Cathy or Doonesbury
comic strips.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did it because we got a wish list of the things that users
wanted to add to the operating system,'' said Kim Akers, a
Microsoft product manager. ``And this was one of the top things on
the list.''
</P>
<P>
   I doubt that the Dinosaurs theme will linger on my home-office
computer for long. My daughters will soon tire of it, and after
all, it really does not reflect my own personality.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, I do not look forward to the household
discussion about a replacement. Something tells me a Godzilla theme
may be in my future.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   To use desktop themes, you need a computer that runs Windows 95.
If you don't have Microsoft Plus (which costs about $39 in stores),
you can download a shareware tool. Here are some helpful sites:
</P>
<P>
   _ TUCOWS INTERACTIVE: www.freethemes.com
</P>
<P>
   Has themes and a handful of other tools.
</P>
<P>
   _ ZDNET'S DESKTOP THEMES: www.hotfiles.com
</P>
<P>
   Allows you to download theme programs.
</P>
<P>
   _ ZDNET'S CUSTOM THEMES: www.hyperactivex.com
</P>
<P>
   Helps you create a customized theme. You need to run Microsoft's
Internet Explorer browser to use this site, where you can choose
things like screen backgrounds and screen savers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
