<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOM ENDED THE FIGHT OF THE CENTURY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm really not a true boxing fan. Sure, I watched Mike Tyson
bite a hunk out of Evander Holyfield's ear, but other than a few
highly publicized matches, I haven't seen many fights.
</P>
<P>
   So you can take it with a grain of salt or you can suspend
disbelief and roll with me on this, but the best fight there ever
was took place in Fort Worth, 18 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It was a lightweight match between two of the strongest,
meanest, maddest pugilists in Cowtown.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't one of those pretty-boy, celebrity matches where the
fans wear suits and the ring announcer is in a tuxedo. There
weren't any ringside analysts describing the action and recalling
their own days between the ropes.
</P>
<P>
   The media did not cover this event, though goodness knows I wish
I had a video of that match. In fact, this fight wasn't even
announced in advance because it was totally spontaneous. A few of
us just happened to be around when the melee began.
</P>
<P>
   When we heard the loud arguing between the two opponents, we
formed a circle around them and stood there waiting for the
punchfest to begin. We didn't have to wait long, either.
</P>
<P>
   Sherri Bodine said: ``Is that my blouse you have on? Didn't I
tell you not to borrow my clothes without asking?''
</P>
<P>
   Her sister, Terri Bodine, answered: ``So what? I look better in
this blouse than you do anyway; at least that's what your boyfriend
said.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherri's boyfriend, Karl, who had been quietly observing this
exchange, started doing the moonwalk, and he just kept sliding
backward until he was out the door. Luckily for him, school had
just been dismissed so he could retreat to the safety of his home
until the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Sherri was furious for good reason. Terri hadn't borrowed just
ANY blouse. No, this was one of those classic white polyester
blouses with ruffles around the collars and the sleeves. It even
had a big bow in front for no apparent reason. It certainly wasn't
a blouse you would ordinarily wear to school, unless it was picture
day.
</P>
<P>
   To add insult to injury, there was a red ketchup stain on the
front of the blouse and two large wet spots under the arms. I would
have been mad, too, if it had been my blouse.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, they argued some more, and then Sherri pushed Terri. Oh,
it was on after that!
</P>
<P>
   Sherri was jabbing and bobbing like a professional, but Terri
fought like a wildcat. She was doing that windmill thing, where you
just swing your arms furiously and hope you hit something. We were
all laughing and egging them on like the moral and compassionate
teen-agers that we were. At one point, Sherri grabbed a fistful of
the blouse and pulled so hard that one sleeve came off.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, the fans became hysterical. In response, Terri
did a swan dive and grabbed the hem of Sherri's skirt. Both the
skirt and Terri ended up on the floor. The place went wild. We were
enjoying ourselves so much that we were all startled when we heard
a very deep, very familiar, grown-up voice say, ``What is going on
here?''
</P>
<P>
   That stern voice belonged to the last person on Earth any of us
wanted to upset: Mrs. Bodine.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bodine was 6 feet 2 inches in her bare feet. She drove a
truck before it was cool for women to drive pickups. Her arms were
as big as our principal's legs.
</P>
<P>
   As she approached, we parted like the Red Sea. It was so quiet,
you could have heard a gnat sneeze. Mrs. Bodine just stood there a
moment, looking at her daughters and breathing fire. The rest of us
ran like scared rabbits. I zoomed past Karl in the parking lot,
still moon-walking toward the bus. I don't know what happened to
the Bodine girls that day, but they were awfully nice to each other
for the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The other morning, my youngest son came downstairs in his
brother's favorite baggy shorts. He didn't think I noticed. I
didn't say a word as I watched him lace up his athletic shoes for a
game of basketball with some of the neighborhood boys.
</P>
<P>
   When my older son yelled out from his room, ``Mom, I can't find
my JNCOs!'' The little one headed for the door in haste.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tyler, wait!'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, mom?'' he answered with one foot out the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you wearing a good pair of underwear?''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
