<HEADER>
A2442 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-COMPUTER-GAMES-NY     06-03 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-GAMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CALL TO GAME DESIGNERS TO HEAR THE BEAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Entrain,'' Brian Moriarty said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the hundreds of video game designers assembled at the
Computer Game Developers' Conference in Long Beach, Calif., not one
seemed to have the slightest idea what he was talking about.
</P>
<P>
   They had shown up because Moriarty is one of the industry's old
soldiers, someone who wrote early text adventures like Beyond Zork
and has stuck around long enough to oversee an online multiplayer
game network, Mpath Interactive, on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word has its origin in the Middle French verb entrainer,''
Moriarty continued. ``It means to draw along. To induce into a
rhythm. To coax into a flow. Entrainment is a ubiquitous natural
phenomenon. It occurs in the vicinity of any rhythmic expression of
energy. Play a note on a violin, and you'll hear the same note
ringing on an adjacent piano. Rotate a magnet inside a coil of
wire, and the vortex of flux will induce a sympathetic pulse of
electric current. Opera singers use entrainment to shatter glass.''
</P>
<P>
   Games, he argued, produce entrainment effects as well. Look at
someone playing Quake, with the attendant body movements,
breathing, yelps of fear, howls of frustration and grunts of
satisfaction. ``You will find yourself in the presence of a curious
creature: a twitching, blinking, buzzing bundle of nerves deeply
engaged in a frantic conversation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This creature has its own language _ a language with
sentences, paragraphs and all kinds of punctuation. Be still,
observe, and you will notice certain chronic tendencies in the
communications of this creature. It keeps coming back to the same
few subjects, circling around and back, around and back. The image
and sound also manifest a succession of repeating sensations.
There's a regular alternation of shadow and light. A cycle of
action and response.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be still, observe, and you will recognize periodicity.
Periodicity in time, also known as rhythm. And periodicity in
space, which we call patterns. Rhythms and patterns. Every game has
them. Solitaire. Hopscotch. Chess. Quake. Myst. Gemstone. Ultima.
These games and all others can be described as entrainment engines.
Systems designed to coax the behavior of participants into mutually
satisfying rhythms and patterns. As a game designer, you are an
entrainment engineer.''
</P>
<P>
   Viewing computer games through this new lens, it was suddenly
obvious why they are so much fun, and why it is so difficult to
explain the thrill to non-gamers.
</P>
<P>
   Non-gamers cannot see the payoff because they are looking only
at what is on the screen: The graphics. The 3-D architecture. The
cinematic violence. And because they cannot work the controllers,
because, for whatever psychological or generational reason, they
can't participate in the experience, non-gamers see a player
immersed in a video game and think his rapturous attention stems
from the particular qualities of those images. To a critic of video
games, it looks as if the spectacle of cinematic violence is
triggering little outbursts of joy.
</P>
<P>
   After all, that is how other moving images work. They are
stimuli. They trigger a response. The causality is clear. When
non-gamers see people playing Nintendo 64, they see it as analogous
to watching television and movies.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, this analogy is so flawed that it is useless. The
appeal of video games _ the whole point of them, really _ is that
you are not simply receiving a signal. You are a signal. You act,
and the environment responds. And vice versa. It's a channel of
continuous two-way feedback. Playing a video game is not like
watching television. It's like dancing. It's like playing music.
</P>
<P>
   Computer-rendered violence _ the martial arts strikes, the
gunshots, the laser fire _ is appealing not because it looks good
on the screen; it is appealing because it's percussive. It's a
drum. It's a cymbal. If you're going to strike a note, destruction
is satisfying because it makes the loudest bang. Your targets don't
need to be figurative. You could be blowing up beautifully rendered
abstract blobs and it wouldn't make much of a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Critics are obsessed with the esthetics of video game violence.
But the debate about increasing levels of realism in computer games
is a red herring. It is not the visual component of violence that
players find so compelling.
</P>
<P>
   It's the rhythm: Duck. Fire. Duck. Fire. Fire. Reload. Fire.
It's the patterns of action and reaction, patterns that are
spontaneous and jagged and almost entirely dissonant. It makes
perfect sense that most of the people who play violent computer
games are adolescent boys and young men. Look at the music they
listen to. Dissonance is a selling point. And dissonance has its
place. The world has room for punk rock _ or for Stravinsky's
``Rite of Spring.''
</P>
<P>
   But it also has room for other kinds of music, and the
interactive entertainment industry has been loath to fill that
space. Games that prompt reflection rather than survival-related
stress are viewed with some disdain among game designers. They hold
Myst in the same contempt that Bartok aficionados reserve for
Pachabel and Brahms. But Myst continues to outsell Duke Nukem for
the same reason that Bach will always outsell the Polish composer
Krzysztof Penderecki. Dissonance alienates people. Sometimes it
alienates them in thought-provoking ways, but it begs for
justification. Meter and harmony justify themselves. People like to
sing along. They like to dance. They like to join.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do sports fans create and sustain the Wave?'' Moriarty
said. ``Why is it such a joy for 50,000 people to coordinate their
behavior? For the same reason it's such a joy for two people.
Because we are wired for it. Just look at those fans, with their
goofy hats, loud Bermuda shorts and T-shirts stained with mustard.
Tens of millions of them. They are the potential audience for
multiplayer games. They enjoy coordinating their behavior. They
want to play together. The designer who figures out how to reach
these people with the online equivalent of the Wave will be a hero.
A very wealthy hero.''
</P>
<P>
   A roomful of game designers smelled the catnip. They pondered
the challenge. As the lights came up, without the slightest
provocation, the crowd burst into the synchronous cacophony
otherwise known as applause. All those video game designers are
back in their cubicles now, writing code. Let's hope the next
inning of game development produces something worthy of the Wave.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
