<SLUG> BC-SORTERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SORTING OUT YOUR LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By PHIL PATTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is it warm weather that inspires the desire to put household
objects in order? Something that provokes the taking up of arms
against a winter's accumulation, the determination to stem the
relentless tide of miscellany, to put things at last in their
place?
</P>
<P>
   Sorting things implies a greater order in one's life. I'm drawn
by the grids of such order, and fascinated by those tiny sets of
clear plastic drawersthat give nuts and bolts the precision and
randomness of fishing tackle. I'm drawn to cunning Rubbermaid
plastic organizers, to the magazine boxes at Ikea or Sam Flax, to
everything that holds things at Hold Everything and to such pieces
of furniture as the round gridded shelves called RD2 11 displayed
by Lush Life, a Los Angeles design group, at a recent furniture
show.
</P>
<P>
   Many people seem convinced that if they just had the right
closet organizer, kitchen pantry or sorting bins they could get
everything under control at last. It is the furniture equivalent of
the desires that draw people to date-and-address systems like the
Dayrunner or Franklin planner or their electronic equivalents: the
Palm Pilot, the Rex or the Psion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personal organizers,'' such devices are called, are as much
about taking hold of your personality as your personal effects. In
the home, furniture works the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the current fashionable pinnacle of organizing: the
French postal sorting desk, with its 36 square compartments of
metal mesh arranged in a Cartesian gird, with a work surface and
swing-away seat. Cristina Grajales of 1950, a furniture store on
Lafayette Street in Manhattan, sold her first postal sorter seven
years ago. She came upon it in a Paris flea market and later found
a steady French supplier; she now has 50. In 1950 and other stores,
the sorters retail for about $4,000.
</P>
<P>
   Applying some kind of ultimate imprimatur, Martha Stewart uses a
postal sorter she bought from 1950 as a desk. Ms. Grajales sold one
to a fashion designer and another to a photographer, who converted
the work surface into a light table. Susan Orlean, an author and
writer for The New Yorker, uses one to stow her collections of
green pottery and globes, as well as her bills.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by Roux Spitz in the 1930s, the postal sorter remained
in use through the 1960s. Perhaps the fact that it is French
increases its appeal. The French, after all, invented the Cartesian
grid of the pigeonholes and, with their passion for surrealism and
collage, pioneered the sort of meaningful juxtaposition the postal
sorter makes possible.
</P>
<P>
   Many things fit no neat category of pigeonhole or drawer; many
don't fit at all. Ms. Orlean has come up with a high concept
category in her kitchen. ``I have a drawer,'' she said, ``just for
measuring equipment.'' There she keeps not just measuring spoons
but the candy thermometer and the dry-weight scales.
</P>
<P>
   In urban apartments, simply fitting it all in is a challenge.
When hiding things is not possible, displaying them becomes
performance art. Making a virtue of necessity, organizational
furniture can become a means of personal expression, somewhere
between kindergarten cubby and Joseph Cornell box. Laden with
objects of personal meaning _ whether car keys or vacation
souvenirs _ organizer furniture can become a dovecote for flights
of fancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Collector's Cabinet,'' a show at the National Gallery in
Washington, explores the 17th-century tradition of the
Wunderkammer, or cabinet of curiosity, encompassing art, craft and
natural specimens. The miscellany aimed to be encyclopedic and
expressive: Chinese porcelain sat beside a rare shell, beside a
clever sextant.
</P>
<P>
   I think of the miscellaneous collection on my discount
veneer-composite shelves as a modern Wunderkammer. There, bird's
nests and wasp's nests, a mini flashlight, a Super Bowl XXX
matchbook and three microcassettes coexist with a glass insulator
that once held up electric lines.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonders, perhaps, but my own.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
