<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-SPACE-SPCL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENSIONS FLARE ANEW WITH NEIGHBORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DANIEL GOLDEN AND JOHN YEMMA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; When they drew up the guest list for President Clinton's
commencement address Friday at Massachusetts Institute of
Technology , MIT officials remembered the adage, ``All politics is
local.'' So President Charles Vest invited the Cambridge city
council.
</P>
<P>
   But Cambridge's other world-famous university neglected to pay
the councilors the same courtesy. Harvard did not invite them to
its graduation Thursday (June 4) until a Globe reporter asked about
the omission.
</P>
<P>
   Such oversights only inflame the re-emerging tensions between
Harvard and its neighbors. Unlike competitors Stanford and Duke,
which enjoy thousands of acres of elbow room, Harvard is hemmed
into 446 acres in Boston and Cambridge, which has the sixth-highest
population density in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   After a decade in which Harvard sold twice as much Cambridge
property as it bought and renovated rather than built, the
university is expanding. Its ambitions are colliding with a
grass-roots resistance Harvard administrators term ``BANANA,'' _
Build Almost Nothing Anywhere Near Anything.
</P>
<P>
   Unquestionably, town-gown relations have improved since 1956
when former Cambridge Mayor Alfred Vellucci proposed paving Harvard
Yard. Now, a revolving door is replacing the brick wall between
campus and community.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Spiegelman, former assistant Cambridge city manager, heads
Harvard's office of planning and real estate, and former Boston
School Committee member Kevin McCluskey is its liaison to Allston.
Cambridge Mayor Francis Duehay and Councilor Kenneth Reeves are
Harvard alumni, while Councilor Kathleen Born, an architect, has
renovated homes of Harvard officials.
</P>
<P>
   But superficial goodwill masks tensions. ``I hold most Harvard
administrators personally in very high regard,'' Born says. ``But
I'm baffled by some of the decisions coming out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   Born is puzzled by Harvard's plan for a massive home for the
government department on the northeast edge of campus, behind the
Graduate School of Design. The 60,000-square-foot, six-story
building could imperil two historic homes and a tree-lined
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The building would sit just inside the ``Red Line,'' the campus
boundary set by Harvard and Cambridge a quarter-century ago. Local
activists complain that the university is overloading its frontier.
They call for a gradual transition from the campus to the
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the campus has a traditional core, Harvard's path of
least resistance is to push at the edges,'' says John Pitkin,
president of the mid-Cambridge Neighborhood Assocation. ``It's the
neighborhood's job to push harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Cambridge activists pushed so hard that they drove Harvard
across the Charles River into Allston. Taking the neighborhood by
surprise, Harvard announced last year that it had secretly acquired
14 properties totalling 52 acres. Combined with the medical school,
the Allston purchases give Harvard as much land in Boston as in
Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard is likely to use the Allston property for administrative
functions. While many residents are pleased at the upgrade from
auto repair shops and deserted warehouses, they worry about higher
rents _ and becoming a battleground between Harvard and Boston
University. Both are eyeing the Conrail yards on either side of the
turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought my house here 20 years ago and I couldn't afford to
rent here today,'' says Paul Berkeley, who represents Allston on
task forces with Harvard and BU. ``If you're a person of average
means, the universities make it tougher.''
</P>
<P>
   But the price of gentrification must be balanced against the
economic benefits provided by Harvard: 5,000 jobs for Boston and
Cambridge residents; nearly $300 million a year in contracts for
local vendors; and millions of dollars in tourist income for hotels
and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard, which owns 2,300 housing units in Cambridge, sold 100
units to the city last year at one-third of market value to ease
the end of rent control. Harvard pays taxes on commercial property,
including University Place and the Inn at Harvard Square. It makes
payments in lieu of taxes to Boston ($1.3 million) and Cambridge
($1.5 million). By contrast, BU pays Boston $1.6 million, Yale pays
New Haven $1.6 million and MIT pays Cambridge $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   But Cambridge officials aren't satisfied; they also want to tax
Harvard and MIT on now-exempt research facilities that develop
lucrative products.
</P>
<P>
   Many faculty and students volunteer in community service. Law
students represent thousands of low-income clients each year;
medical students help to fight Hepatitis B in Boston's Asian
community; business students act as mentors, tutors, coaches, and
pen pals in a Boston middle school; and undergraduates teach dance
and movement to Cambridge fourth- and fifth-graders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harvard is deeply committed to being a resource in our local
communities, particularly the public schools,'' says Mary Power,
Harvard director of community relations.
</P>
<P>
   But it may not be committed to Stamatis Eliades. For 22 years,
he's run Three Aces Pizza in Cambridge, one of four small
businesses near Harvard Law School. Harvard, their landlord, has
raised their rents nearly 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Spiegelman says Harvard is asking the market rate, but she
acknowledges that the law school will eventually take over the
location. Eliades says the university wants to drive out the
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people are supporting us,' Eliades says. ``They're very
upset with Harvard, what it's doing around here, trying to take
over the city.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 1637EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
