<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2455 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARVARD-INSIDE-SPCL-A     06-03 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-INSIDE-SPCL-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROBLEMS FESTER IN UNCHECKED BASTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DANIEL GOLDEN AND JOHN YEMMA  
 c.1997 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The May edition of Harvard's in-house library journal contains a
glowing tribute to Jeanne T. Newlin, former curator of the Harvard
Theatre Collection, announcing her appointment as honorary curator.
</P>
<P>
   The article fails to mention that this distinction was granted
following the settlement last January of her lawsuit against
Harvard. In it, she alleged that she was fired because a homosexual
administrator discriminated against her as a heterosexual. The case
pitted the university against prominent supporters of Newlin,
including Supreme Court Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg and oil tycoon
Frederick Koch.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute that heated up the climate-controlled library system
illuminates a weakness of Harvard's decentralized governance. Power
struggles and personal animosities fester unchecked in the
subterranean bastions where outsiders rarely stray.
</P>
<P>
   The Theatre Collection melodrama featured a strong-willed
heroine, let go for supposed insensitive treatment of employees,
who then herself claimed to be a victim of a type of discrimination
_ anti-heterosexual _ unrecognized by state law and unprecedented
in Harvard legal history. ``This is unique in my experience,'' says
Anne Taylor, Harvard vice president and general counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Newlin and her attorney, Nancy Shilepsky, declined comment.
Supporters call her a ``superstar,'' as renowned in her sphere as
Alan Dershowitz or Stephen Jay Gould in theirs.
</P>
<P>
   After taking over as curator in 1972, she built the collection
into the nation's most complete archive of theatrical scripts,
photographs, and other memorabilia. Loyal to Harvard and fiercely
protective of her piece of it, she attracted major donations and
bequests. ``Much of the department's current reputation is based on
the commitment Jeanne Newlin devoted to it over the past two and
one-half decades,'' states the article in May's Harvard University
Library Notes.
</P>
<P>
   Her downfall began in 1991, when she discovered that a male
subordinate was violating conflict-of-interest guidelines by
privately collecting documents that Harvard wanted to acquire. She
asked her supervisor to discipline him.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, according to court documents, the supervisor sided with
the employee, who was openly homosexual, and began undermining
Newlin. He downgraded her evaluations, refused to replace departing
members of her staff, and instigated a five-month investigation
into her treatment of employees.
</P>
<P>
   The supervisor's investigation culminated in a June 1994 report
characterizing Newlin as curt to employees and careless about
returning donors' phone calls. That November, a committee of
Harvard library administrators upheld the report, citing a
``serious and longstanding problems with Ms. Newlin's performance
and conduct.'' Five days later, Newlin filed a complaint with the
Massachusetts Commission Against Discrimination, alleging gender
bias.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1995, Newlin was fired. The following month, the MCAD
dismissed her complaint. But she persisted, suing Harvard in
Middlesex Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   This time she contended that her supervisor was bisexual or
homosexual and ``overtly favored gay male employees'' _ including
appointing a ``less qualified bisexual man'' over a ``more
qualified woman'' for a staff position. The supervisor, who has
left Harvard, declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said Harvard does not acknowledge having discriminated
against Newlin, despite settling the lawsuit. ``If we had tried it,
we would have prevailed,'' Taylor says.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor declined to explain why Harvard settled. Insiders point
to Newlin's powerful backers, including Ginsburg and Koch.
Ginsburg, an alumna of Harvard Law School, became close to Newlin
through one of the justice's cousins, the late David Bader, who
co-owned the Wilbur Theater in Boston. His collection of theatrical
treasures was left to Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Sources say Ginsburg, who declined comment, wrote to Harvard
applauding Newlin's honorary appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Koch, a former Harvard and Yale student who has an estimated
$600 million fortune from his family's oil services and refining
firm, is a major art donor and collector. Sources say that as a
protest against Newlin's firing, he threatened to shift a major
gift from Harvard's theater collection to archrival Yale.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Koch has withdrawn his multimillion-dollar
commitment to Harvard, a spokesman declined comment. But, he added,
Koch is ``totally supportive'' of Newlin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 1639EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2457 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEMA-COX &UR; 240&AMP;ADD &UR; FEMA     06-03 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEMA-COX </SLUG>
   240&AMP;ADD  FEMA LAUNCHES PREVENTION PROJECT TO CUT
DISASTER COSTS
 &HT;     By SAMAR ABULHASSAN 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Urging communities to ``learn from past
experiences,'' the federal government's disaster response chief
launched a nationwide project Wednesday that aims to cut the cost
of natural disasters before they strike.
</P>
<P>
   James Lee Witt, director of the Federal Emergency Management
Agency, said communities must take measures to protect their homes
and businesses before a flood, earthquake or hurricane occurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have seen too much devastation and destruction in the last
five years,'' Witt said at a National Press Club briefing. ``We
must end this damage-repair, damage-repair cycle.''
</P>
<P>
   FEMA's Project Impact seeks to reduce federal costs of cleaning
up after natural disasters by encouraging local partnerships
between businesses and government leaders and promoting public
awareness. This can mean buying flood insurance, installing storm
shutters or hosting prevention forums.
</P>
<P>
   Every dollar spent in damage prevention saves $2 in repairs,
Witt said. He pointed to the Anheuser Brewery in earthquake-prone
Northern California, which spent $15 million in the 1980s to
protect its facilities. After a 1994 quake whose epicenter was only
12 miles away, the company estimated it escaped damage that could
have topped $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, the agency launched a pilot program in seven
cities, including Deerfield Beach, Fla. Boasting the success of
these models, FEMA will stretch its resources to a first round of
localities in all 50 states. Each of the chosen communities will
receive from $500,000 to $1 million to implement their initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In the past 10 years, FEMA has spent more than $20 billion to
help communities bounce back after a disaster. That doesn't include
lost jobs and insurance claims, Witt said.
</P>
<P>
   One avenue to reducing FEMA costs, Witt said, is for communities
to take the initiative, such as passing bond proposals. He cited
Austin, Texas, which recently approved a $25 million bond
proposition to build a flood tunnel for Waller Creek. Another $10
million proposition was allocated to protect 175 East Austin homes
from Walnut Creek flooding.
</P>
<P>
   ``They see the difference it makes,'' he said, emphasizing that
areas not chosen for FEMA aid ``can be a part of this.''
</P>
<P>
   For the pilot coastal community of Deerfield Beach, 1992's
Hurricane Andrew was a ``wake-up call,'' said Mayor Albert
Capellini.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a new sense of awareness,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, high school students, Americorps volunteers, and
local leaders began to install hurricane straps on the city's only
high school and hung storm shutters on the homes of elderly
residents. Four homes have been completed, with at least 50 more
expected to be shielded.
</P>
<P>
   Witt emphasized that people need to protect themselves first _
particularly by taking tornado and hurricane warnings more
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing we can do is protect lives and
injuries,'' he said, noting that ``communities can always be
rebuilt.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
