<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2459 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARVARD-INVEST-SPCL-A     06-03 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-INVEST-SPCL-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL REACH RIVALS SCHOOL'S ACADEMIC INFLUENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DANIEL GOLDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Wyndham Anatole Hotel, just outside Dallas, exudes
extravagance. It boasts 240,000 square feet of meeting space, 1,620
guest rooms, 13 restaurants, 10 original Picassos, and a basketball
court that NBA teams practice on. ``You could put the
Marriott-Copley in one of the lobbies,'' boasts vice president and
general manager Marc L. Messina.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the hotel's financial backers isn't a Stetson-wearing
oilman. It's the staid bastion of the eastern Establishment _
Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   Like Harvard's academic influence, its financial tentacles
extend far beyond Cambridge. Although officials declined to
identify individual investments, and the university uses a web of
interlocking companies to ensure secrecy, sources and public
records show that its hidden realm ranges from oil wells to
cosmetics, auto dealerships to Internet search engines, luxury
apartments to subsidized housing.
</P>
<P>
   Since the '50s, when it became the first university to invest
its endowment in the stock market, Harvard has brought an
aggressive, unorthodox approach to financing its future. While most
universities, including Yale, farm out their investments, Harvard
manages most of its money through a downtown Boston subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Although most colleges invest conservatively in domestic
securities, Harvard takes chances on emerging companies and
international stocks. And its prestige, massive resources, and
well-placed alumni bring Harvard opportunities that other colleges
can only dream of. The result: an impressive 18.9 percent annual
return over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have less plain vanilla than the typical institution,''
says Jack Meyer, president of Harvard Management, which has 170
employees and is located in the Federal Reserve building.
</P>
<P>
   Some of its flavors may not satisfy everyone's taste. Like most
universities, Harvard invests to make money, not reform society.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, when Harvard divested its tobacco holdings,
then-president Derek Bok explained that it did not want to be
associated with companies whose products ``create a substantial and
unjustified risk of harm to other human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite that standard, federal filings at the end of last year
show, the university owns nearly $24 million worth of Mirage
Resorts casinos, more than $6 million worth of Seagram liquor
company, and nearly $500,000 worth of Playboy Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playboy is clearly inappropriate for a university,'' says Amy
Domini, who manages a fund that invests in ``socially responsible''
companies as measured by indices such as employee relations and
environmental impact. The fund regularly out-performs the Standard
and Poor's 500 Index.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard treasurer D. Ronald Daniel said that divesting tobacco
stocks, particularly Phillip Morris, hurt the university
financially. Whether to divest from alcohol or gambling companies,
he said, ``gets very complicated. You can write a series of
scenarios that could constrain our investment universe into a very
small one. Automobiles kill people too. Does that mean we shouldn't
invest in automobiles?''
</P>
<P>
   Even when Harvard's own advisory committee recommends a
favorable vote, the university often opposes or abstains from
stockholder resolutions urging firms to stop polluting the
environment or doing business with repressive regimes.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the advisory committee, composed of alumni,
faculty, and students, last year unanimously supported a resolution
by shareholders of Unocal. Harvard has nearly $5 million at stake
in Unocal, an oil and gas exploration company and the leading US
investor in Burma, one of the world's most repressive regimes.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution pushed Unocal to investigate allegations that its
Burmese partner was a conduit for laundered drug money. But the
Harvard Corporation, the governing board overseeing university
finances, abstained from the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel, a member of the corporation committee on shareholder
responsibility, acknowledged that it tends to be ``a little more
cautious'' than the advisory committee. But over several years, he
said, the corporation often comes around to the advisory
committee's viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   While Harvard has only small stakes in Seagram, Unocal, and
other giant corporations, it has a bigger share _ and often a seat
on the board _ of an array of smaller companies. For example, it
owns 15 percent of United Auto Group, which buys and operates car
dealerships, and 5 percent of Immunogen in Norwood, which develops
cancer therapies.
</P>
<P>
   The university was majority owner of National Housing
Partnership, a major landlord of subsidized apartments, before
selling the company last year to Apartment Investment and
Management Co. Harvard retained a 3.5 percent share of AIM. At the
other end of the housing spectrum, it's an investor in a string of
luxury apartments under construction nationwide _ including a
Waltham complex cited last year for safety and labor violations.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard owns nearly 5 percent of Playtex Products, the women's
cosmetics company, whose biggest investor is Boston financier
Thomas H. Lee. That's only one aspect of the close relationship
between Harvard and Lee. Harvard is a limited partner in his
private equity funds. Lee, a 1965 alumnus, gave $22 million to the
university in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of Harvard's gambles pay off. In the early '90s, Harvard
Management wrote off $250 million in poor investments, particularly
in wildcat oil and gas exploration in the Southwest. The
Massachusetts state pension fund, which had followed Harvard's
lead, lost tens of millions of dollars in the venture as well. More
recently, Harvard's 6.6 percent share of Cambridge Neuroscience, a
biotech firm, plunged in value due to the disappointing performance
of an experimental drug.
</P>
<P>
   But winners outweigh losers. Harvard was an early investor in
Kleiner Perkins, a West Coast venture capital firm that has backed
many high-tech start-ups, including Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   The Wyndham Anatole is not Harvard's only hotel. Although the
university sold the Copley Plaza in 1996 for a reported $70
million, it still has an interest in six hotels, several shopping
centers, and 35 office buildings, including Crystal City near
Reagan Washington National Airport. ``We have been trying
vigorously to increase our real estate ratio in the portfolio,''
Meyer says.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard doesn't always have to pay for real estate. Alumni
donate everything from subdivisions to summer homes. In 1992, one
alumnus donated a Colorado ski area for his 50th class reunion.
Harvard unloaded the property for $23 million, much to the athletic
department's consternation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a call from the ski coach saying, `You'd never sell it,
right?''' says Thomas Reardon, vice president for alumni affairs
and development. ``I said, `We're in the education business, not
the ski business.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
