<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2461 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-DIGITAL-IMAGER-AR     06-03 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DIGITAL-IMAGER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHIND MOVING IMAGES, A CURATOR IN STEP WITH THE DIGITAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-1243 or 1927.)  
(gm) 
 By DAVID KUSHNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a Tuesday morning in Queens, two students in baggy
pants prepared to get digitized. As strobe lights flashed in a
small room, they stuck out their tongues and twisted their bodies
in comic break-dance moves as their life-size images were projected
onto the wall in front of them.
</P>
<P>
   Rows of consecutive portraits streamed from a laser printer like
a miniature, moving Warhol poster. With a pair of scissors, the two
teen-agers could cut and paste later the old-fashioned way,
assembling the shots in order into a souvenir flipbook.
</P>
<P>
   This was yet another highlight of a field trip to Oz _ or, as it
is better known, the American Museum of the Moving Image. Behind
the curtain was not an avuncular wizard but a modest 32-year-old
named Carl Goodman, AMMI's curator of digital media and the person
responsible for developing the museum's burgeoning collection of
electronic exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever you do,'' Goodman said as he stepped past the lights,
``don't call me a cybercurator.'' He prefers to call himself the
museum's ``ambassador'' to new media. Since the AMMI matured
alongside Silicon Alley, Goodman has become a popular fixture in
the new media community of downtown New York. Last year, The
Silicon Alley Reporter, a newsletter, called him the ``most
insightful chronicler of media in Silicon Alley.''
</P>
<P>
   For many museumgoers, AMMI is most strongly associated with
motion pictures. Built in Astoria, where Paramount had studios in
the 1920s, AMMI opened on 36th Street at 35th Avenue in 1988 to
offer a behind-the-scenes look at how movies and television shows
were made. ``Behind the Screen,'' the core exhibition, is a
historical journey from a 19th-century zoetrope, which created
moving images by having a viewer gaze at a series of illustrations
through a slotted, spinning spool, to a digital animation station
from the late 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond a demonstration of the gadgetry, the goal of the
exhibitions is to illuminate the human experience of storytelling.
``It's all about the people and the process,'' Goodman explained,
continuing past rows of ancient movie cameras, ``computers are just
another tool.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike curators who spend their time acquiring old pieces,
Goodman collaborates in new interactive projects, conceiving
installations, then hiring freelance designers and programmers who
create magic. Goodman prefers keeping the technology in the
shadows. He said his mission was to present digital arts as part of
the broader evolution of storytelling media, like television and
film. ``The biggest compliment I get is when visitors forget
they're using a computer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One exhibit that uses special software lets visitors dub their
own voices into classic film scenes like Robert DeNiro's ``You
talking to me?'' soliloquy from ``Taxi Driver.'' For an exhibit on
computer editing, Goodman worked with a group of programmers and
designers to develop an interactive station where visitors can
piece together a variety of images.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want someone to sit here doing weatherman-style
tricks against a blue screen,'' Goodman said, as he sat at the
editing station and clicked together a surreal montage of tropical
fish swimming inside a burning television set.
</P>
<P>
   An early 1980s synthesizer was the tool that booted Goodman into
the world of digital media. The keyboard was a gift he received for
his 13th birthday from his parents, both musicians. Later, at
Wesleyan University in Middletown, Conn., Goodman studied
philosophy and music; inspired by the work of the composer John
Cage, he created his own electronic compositions. When he arrived
in New York, he began writing jingles, then wound up as an
executive recruiter on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   One day, he got a call that his friend's mother needed help
setting up the digital audio at a museum she had opened in Astoria.
Goodman has been at the museum, AMMI, ever since, orchestrating the
museum's digital offerings.
</P>
<P>
   His curatorial impulses inspired ``Computer Space 98,'' an
exhibition of video arcade games. Since 1989, Goodman has procured
classic video-game machines like Pong and Space Invaders. In a
downstairs gallery of the museum, game machines line the walls for
visitors to play. Nearby, for context, a bank of computers features
contemporary computer games, like the popular multiplayer shoot 'em
up game Quake.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Goodman said, his head is firmly planted six months
into the future. That is when, with a $1.3 million grant from the
National Science Foundation, AMMI will take an improved version of
``Behind the Scenes'' around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman faces the daunting task of developing a portable
high-tech exhibit that will survive the perils of travel.
Eventually, he would like AMMI's Web site to play a more active
role in the museum's collection (www.ammi.org). He is currently
exploring the possibility for a ``History of the Web'' exhibit on
the site, featuring work from the early era of the medium's
development. ``AMMI to me is both a media museum and a way to
explore the notion of museum as medium,'' he explained via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman makes an effort to maintain close ties with the local
high-tech community. Six times a year, he organizes museum events
that feature digital artists and innovators discussing their craft.
Recent programs have explored the makings of movies that emphasize
special effects, like ``Titanic'' and ``Alien Resurrection.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman uses the word ``cheerleader'' to describe his role in
the community. Goodman makes an effort to support and critique the
innovations made by the countless start-ups struggling to survive.
``I respect and admire these bungee jumpers of digital media,'' he
said. ``I'm excited about how they're always trying new concepts,
even if they fail. They're really the kamikaze pilots of the
industry. I encourage them to keep getting in those planes.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
