<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SIX-DEGRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
6 DEGREES OF NETWORKING 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By SHELLY FREIERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Six degrees of separation, the theory that everyone on the
planet is connected by a chain of only six people, carries the
grace of logic and the tantalizing lure of being impossible to
disprove. The idea of six degrees of separation was advanced by
Guglielmo Marconi, the inventor of the wireless telegraph, and
popularized in the 1990 play of the same name by John Guare.
</P>
<P>
   It has fueled countless conversations pondering connections to
the famous and infamous, the dead and living. It has also come to
the Web in the form of a networking site called Six Degrees
(www.sixdegrees.com).
</P>
<P>
   Six Degrees, which has 675,000 members and adds 3,000 more every
24 hours, uses the standard tools of the Net _ e-mail, bulletin
boards and search engines _ to offer links to friends and friends
of friends. What makes Six Degrees different from other public
online services is that a member has a connection to all the other
people on the site through a series of mutual acquaintances.
</P>
<P>
   A participant can either sign up at Six Degrees' Web site or
join by responding to a member's e-mail invitation. Participants
choose an initial circle of friends (the first degree), and they in
turn recruit their friends (the second degree), who can repeat the
process. Members control who can see their personal information,
and there is a limit to how far into the network a question can be
distributed. Users can communicate via e-mail only within their
first or second degree.
</P>
<P>
   As with similar networking tools at other membership-based sites
like Geocities (geocities.com), Six Degrees offers an opportunity
to ask people with shared interests for information. So, reaching
into a network for a car repair shop, chiropractor or a good place
to go birding in eastern Pennsylvania can yield useful
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   One of the enjoyable features at Six Degrees is being able to
look up the path of acquaintances between yourself and another
member. The resulting ``I know her through Barker at the printing
shop and his cousin Trisha'' list is reminiscent of those
conservations about how you are connected to Warren Beatty.
</P>
<P>
   David Barton, a systems engineer in Stockholm, Sweden, the
country with the highest per-capita membership in Six Degrees,
recruited several members after he joined. ``I use the site to keep
track of my friends and business contacts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of the site, Macroview Communications of New York,
promises not to sell members' names to marketing businesses, though
it does sells banner ads for the site and demographic statistics
based on the site's membership. The company has also formed
partnerships with sites like Job Direct (www.jobdirect.com) and
College Beat (www.collegebeat.com). If a member registers with Six
Degrees through one of these sites, his or her personal information
belongs to both partners.
</P>
<P>
   According to the company, half the site members joined Six
Degrees because friends had registered them, but they never do any
networking. One such member is Derek Whiteside, a software engineer
from Corvalis, Ore., who uses other online sources for getting
advice and parts from owners of American Motors cars, which he
collects. Only two of his friends joined Six Degrees when he listed
them in his initial circle, and he said he is not comfortable
pushing membership. ``The site has the feel of a multilevel
marketing thing,'' Whiteside said. ``Before you can reap the
benefits, you have to get others to join.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
