<HEADER>
A2477 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-COMPUTER-TRAVEL-A     06-03 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-TRAVEL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRTUAL TRAVEL: NO LOST LUGGAGE OR JET LAG 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (af)  
 By SUZANNE MACNEILLE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's 9 a.m. and the streets are packed in Jerusalem's Old City
souk. Middle Eastern pop music blares from boom boxes, shoppers
jostle one another and just ahead of me, a bicyclist nearly crashes
into a 500-year-old wall.
</P>
<P>
   In search of more tranquil surroundings, I head off for the
quieter Via Dolorosa, but on the way have second thoughts. Why not
a cruise down the Seine instead? Or perhaps a trek to Mount
Kanchendzonga in the Himalayas?
</P>
<P>
   By 10 a.m. I've managed to squeeze in all three sites and the
Grand Canyon besides. Yet, even for a virtual traveler, scouring
half the globe in an hour is no small accomplishment. My feet may
not ache, but my head is spinning.
</P>
<P>
   Never has the life of an armchair traveler been so exhausting.
Travel sites crowd the Web. Guidebooks to anyplace with a name and
a scenic overlook jam bookstore shelves.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the Travel Channel, the National Geographic
specials, Michael Palin and his ilk, leaning their heads out of
train windows in Siberia and bobbing around in walrus-skin boats in
Alaska. Who needs to pack a suitcase any more? There are far
cheaper ways to get that exotic view.
</P>
<P>
   The destination CD-ROM is one of those ways. Not to be confused
with practical and popular road-map or trip-planning CD-ROMs,
destination disks are glossy productions with photographic essays,
music and narratives, video clips, historical text, endless
point-and-click opportunities, glossaries and occasionally,
interactive games.
</P>
<P>
   Seldom do they bother with mundane stuff like hotels and
restaurants or how to get from Point A to Point B. While that may
fuel the criticism that destination CD-ROMs have no real practical
use, it also sidesteps the problem of their limited shelf life.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel rates vary. Museum hours change. Restaurants close. So why
not leave details to the guidebooks _ or the Internet, where sites
(if they're any good) are continually updated?
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, destination CD-ROMs steer so far away from modern
events that it is difficult to catch a glimpse of anything that
remotely suggests the 20th century. In EMME Interactive's Countries
of Romance, for example, it is not the real Italy we encounter, the
Italy of summer crowds and screeching tires, but the timeless
Italy, accompanied by period music and enticing graphics of things
that are generally no younger than 200 years old.
</P>
<P>
   What CD-ROMs can give the armchair traveler is depth and
immersion in a virtual experience. Their success, of course,
depends on how well they can persuade their viewers to suspend
their disbelief. While the CD-ROMs reviewed here may not be able to
simulate the bumpiness of a mountain bus ride, say, or the
smokiness of a flamenco club, they all perform very well as
destinations in and of themselves. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COUNTRIES OF ROMANCE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (EMME Interactive; $38.99; Windows 3.1 and 95.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like a lushly illustrated coffee table book, Countries of
Romance is pretty to look at but lacks much detailed information.
The France, Spain and Italy we find in this set of three CD-ROMs
are the idealized versions, presented in broad strokes and caught
in centuries past.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the viewer who will get the most out of this collection
_ which is a perennial in stores _ is the art-history student
planning a first trip to Europe. Produced by EMME Interactive, the
Paris-based company that has also published CD-ROMs on the Louvre,
the Vatican and the Sistine Chapel, Countries of Romance is most
informative and innovative when it deals with art and historic
architecture.
</P>
<P>
   In Spain, three of the five main menu items focus solely on
architecture, including Roman, Islamic, Baroque and Renaissance
styles. A photographic sequence devoted to Antonio Gaudi's
surrealistic Barcelona buildings is especially appealing.
</P>
<P>
   In each of the CD-ROMs, at least one section is devoted to that
country's major artists, like Monet in France, Goya in Spain and
Piero della Francesca in Italy. Biographical texts and lists of
major works and their museum locations are given for each entry, as
is a selection of five or six paintings that the viewer can magnify
and examine.
</P>
<P>
   Photographs, graphics (including lovely but not particularly
useful maps), lots of period music and extensive narration make up
most of the format used here. There is some written text, but not
much.
</P>
<P>
   If you search for them, you will find short video clips on
bullfighting, flamenco, the Palio horse race in Siena, Florentine
football and, surprisingly, the May 1968 student riots in Paris,
the only nod at recent history in the collection.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best features in the entire set is the beautiful and
remarkably detailed graphic of the Grand Canal in Venice. You can
move along the right or left banks and click on a highlighted
building, like the Church of the Scalzi or the Doge's Palace, and
get a close-up photograph of the building accompanied by a brief
narrated history.
</P>
<P>
   The seemingly arbitrary selections of cities and subjects for
each country might make you wonder about what was left out. In
Voyage Through the Wonders of Italy you will find Venice, Rome,
Siena and Florence (albeit of several centuries ago), but you will
have to resort to your Baedeker or Michelin if you are looking for
anything on Milan, Bologna, Naples or the Tuscan countryside.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Voyage in Spain has nothing about Cadiz, Valencia or
the lovely white towns of Andalusia, and the France CD-ROM offers
virtually nothing on French cuisine or wine.
</P>
<P>
   Another element that has been ignored is the late 20th century.
Madrid is a sprawling, largely modern city, but one sees little
beyond the Prado or a nearly empty Plaza Mayor. And is it possible
that I never encountered a single car in traffic-ensnared Rome? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   JERUSALEM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Cambrix Publishing/Multimedia Corp.; $39.95; DOS, Windows 3.1
and 95.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jerusalem is an exhaustive and realistic treatment of a
complicated city and, for the traveler, the most practical of the
CD-ROMs reviewed here. It manages to make good use of multimedia
without a lot of hype and without making you feel, as often happens
with destination disks, that you are about to embark on the journey
to end all journeys.
</P>
<P>
   Given the city's controversial history and politics, that is
quite an accomplishment. The makers of this CD-ROM have pulled off
a balanced yet complex introduction to Jewish, Muslim and Christian
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   This straightforward and thorough product is a good
advertisement for destination CD-ROMs that focus on single cities
rather than entire countries.
</P>
<P>
   The moment you start up this disk, you sense that there is a lot
of information to be gained. Compared with the other CD-ROMs
reviewed here, Jerusalem contains considerably more written text
and more video. The video segments are accompanied by ambient
sounds, like footsteps, conversation and the chattering of birds
rather than a musical score.
</P>
<P>
   There are few graphics. The most elaborate is a map of Jerusalem
on which the viewer can point and click to visit a particular spot.
A browser lists all the photographs and video clips, which is a
convenient option, given the extensive use of both.
</P>
<P>
   As in other destination disks, the narrator's tour-guide manner
and tireless bonhomie can be grating, but he imparts more detailed
information than most hosts of this type of CD-ROM.
</P>
<P>
   There are three main menu entries: Explorations, Religion and
History. Explorations includes the map mentioned above, tours of
the Old City market, the Dome of the Rock and a walk along the
ramparts, as well as scenic views from different vantage points
around the city.
</P>
<P>
   In Religion, you can, for example, visit the al-Aksa mosque at
prayer time, join a Jewish family for a Sabbath meal, walk up to
the Wailing Wall or view the crowded Easter procession on the Via
Dolorosa.
</P>
<P>
   In History, a surprisingly thorough entry, you can visit
different historical periods by clicking on a time line at the
bottom of the screen that starts at 3000 B.C. and runs through the
20th century. Bronze Age Jerusalem, Byzantine Jerusalem, Roman
Jerusalem, Ottoman Jerusalem, the Crusades, the British mandate,
1948, the present day _ no major period is ignored.
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate and explain the various historical periods, there
are videotaped interviews with archeologists, historians and
representatives of the three main religious groups and many photo
sequences, accompanied by written text, with links to other parts
of the disk, including a glossary.
</P>
<P>
   The present-day segment includes interviews with people like
Teddy Kollek, the outspoken former mayor of Jerusalem, and Dr.
Albert Aghazarian of Bir Zeit University in Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
   The attempt to explain the Jerusalem of today is particularly
admirable although it is a nearly impossible task because this
CD-ROM came out late last year. After all, anything published on
Jerusalem even in the last 24 hours would already be outdated. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UP TO THE HIMALAYAS: KINGDOM IN THE CLOUDS (DNA Multimedia
Corp.; $49.95; Windows 3.1 and 95, and Macintosh.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's not hard to be impressed by the fiery red tectonic plates
colliding in a noisy 3-D simulation as you witness the birth of the
Himalayas. It's the background effects _ the pulsating music, the
loud echoing voice of the narrator, the references to ``pure
being'' _ that make you think that the introduction to Up to the
Himalayas is getting way, way over the top.
</P>
<P>
   Once you get past the initial hard sell, however, things settle
down. Most viewers will find quite a bit to keep them entertained
on this 20-hour CD-ROM, produced by DNA Multimedia, based in
Vancouver, as they blithely wander around the small kingdom of
Sikkim (India's 22d state), high in a verdant section of the Indian
Himalayas. Lavish and sometimes showy use has been made of 3-D
animation, and tricks and puzzles are scattered throughout.
</P>
<P>
   The main directory offers a variety of sites to choose from: The
Palace, Mount Kanchendzonga, Gangtok, Caravans in the Clouds (an
explanation of ancient trade routes) and Archery (the national
sport). If you choose a destination, you must choose your mode of
transportation to get there: honking bus, squeaky Jeep, rickety van
or, for impatient Westerners, flying monk.
</P>
<P>
   For those who opt for conventional transportation, a lengthy
video of your vehicular travels along Sikkim's bumpy roads follows.
Though limited in size to less than a quarter of the computer
screen, this video sequence is especially rewarding for those who
enjoy precarious mountain drives, although I was somewhat
disappointed that the same footage was used for every destination.
</P>
<P>
   Up to the Himalayas also includes a relatively complicated
interactive game: you use your growing knowledge to find clues to
the reincarnated whereabouts of the recently deceased Lama Dorje,
whom the narrator calls a ``great Buddhist scholar.''
</P>
<P>
   To aid you, there is a diary where you can save scraps of
information for future reference. There is also a Book of Wisdom in
which you must answer detailed questions about Sikkim's history and
customs.
</P>
<P>
   If you would rather not play, there is also a captivating tour
of the town of Gangtok. Here you can meet food and trinket sellers
or enter buildings, including a dark Buddhist library where you can
flash a spotlight around and spy on the readers.
</P>
<P>
   The barely discernible whispers of a person reading to himself
is an especially nice touch. But a chiding voice telling me that I
must walk on the street ``like any mortal being'' whenever I
clicked on the confusing map of Gangtok was annoying.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Gangtok you will also find the quintessential resting
spot for weary electronic travelers, a terrace at the Hotel Tashi
Delek. You can click through the major phases of the day _ I like
the sunset option _ and enjoy the view of twinkling lights, jumbled
buildings and shadowy valleys before a little six-armed deity at
the bottom of your screen reminds you to reach for the mouse and
continue your journey.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
