<HEADER>
A2480 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASTEROIDS-SCIENTISTS-     06-03 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASTEROIDS-SCIENTISTS-1600(2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS GIVE `DEEP IMPACT' LOTS OF THUMBS-UP
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: yes. Fiction, no. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a rather remarkable job,'' says Helin, of the Jet
Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena, Calif., who was among several
scientists by moviemakers consulted in pre-production. ``I've been
involved for the last 20 or 25 years in these types of productions,
and this by far is the best that's been done.''
</P>
<P>
   `tHE SMOKING GUN'
</P>
<P>
   Until fairly recently, even most of the scientific world
pooh-poohed the danger posed by big pieces of celestial junk. That
began to change in 1980, when geologists first proposed that the
impact of a massive asteroid caused the extinction of the dinosaurs
and most other species 65 million years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That hypothesis was effectively confirmed this decade with the
discovery of a massive crater in Mexico, where scientists believe
an immense space boulder, probably six miles in diameter, crashed
into Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was rather a widespread feeling that this was the
smoking gun,'' says Brian Marsden, a prominent Harvard astronomer.
</P>
<P>
   That discovery caused a collective shudder in the scientific
world. But in truth, Marsden says, evidence of the celestial danger
has been with us on every moon-filled night since the beginning of
man. After all, those aren't acne scars on the moon's tattered
surface.
</P>
<P>
   In 1908, a relatively small asteroid exploded in the atmosphere
above Siberia, flattening trees across an area larger than Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the Shoemaker-Levy 9 comet provided one of history's
most dramatic demonstrations of the threat when pieces of it
smashed into Jupiter. Much of the resulting carnage was visible
through backyard telescopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think we would see anything of the effects of impact
on Jupiter, but it was really quite dramatic,'' Marsden says. ``It
threw a lot of stuff up in big high plumes that were clearly
visible. Then, as Jupiter rotated, there was a dramatic black spot
where the hit occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the Earth, looking at those consequences, knowing that
Jupiter is somewhat larger than the Earth, that would frighten
anybody out of their wits.''
</P>
<P>
   In March, Marsden was the first to predict that a huge, newly
discovered asteroid would pass dangerously close to Earth.
Additional observations and calculations quickly showed that the
original concern was somewhat overstated. But 30 years from now,
Asteroid 1997 XF11 will come closer than any known asteroid of that
size (perhaps as much as a mile in diameter) in recorded history.
</P>
<P>
   Someday, a big one won't miss. Hence the increasingly urgent
call from astronomers for the Earth to get ready. A top priority is
identifying the rest of the 2,000 large, threatening asteroids
still out there, an effort that could take a decade or more, and
cost between $5 million and $10 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Technology must also be perfected to intercept and deflect
heavenly rocks headed for Earth. In the case of comets, that will
be difficult because of the relatively high speed with which they
hurtle across the solar system. Conventional rocketry would be
hard-pressed to keep up. But comets are relatively rare. Asteroids
present a much greater threat and will be easier to deflect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic idea is that you send up a rocket with a nuclear
explosive, an unmanned one, and you set it off about one radius of
the asteroid away,'' Hills says. It can be done. People have
analyzed it, and it looks quite tractable.''
</P>
<P>
   But not overnight, he says, and it's possible that asteroids
could approach with comparatively little warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you start fresh, and just wait until the asteroid is about
to hit us, nothing can be done,'' Hills says.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a congressional subcommittee heard testimony about
the threat and discussed funding to deal with it, but so far
nothing. President Clinton has vetoed funding for anti-asteroid
space missions.
</P>
<P>
   The possible consequences, scientists say, are now playing in a
theater near you.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
