<SLUG> BC-DOUGLAS-MURDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHAEL DOUGLAS DISCUSSES LATEST ROLE IN ``A PERFECT MURDER''
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ask Michael Douglas to play the old acting-class game
of which animal he'd see himself as, and it takes him only a second
to reply, ``A fly on the wall.'' But it never has worked out that
way, especially in his latest film, ``A Perfect Murder,'' opening
Friday. Smiling and checking sports scores in a paper as he settles
into a sofa in an East Side hotel, Douglas says of his new role, as
a raging Wall Street cuckold, ``I guess you'd call me a great white
shark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, there's some dipping back to Gordon Gekko'' _ the part
in ``Wall Street'' for which Douglas won an Oscar _ ``in terms of
this guy's job as a financier and his behavior. I mean, he kind of
eats everything in his way.''
</P>
<P>
   In the film, Douglas simmers at the center of a lethal triangle
with Gwyneth Paltrow as his silk-stocking district trophy wife and
Viggo Mortensen as a painter with whom she's having an affair. ``A
Perfect Murder'' bears little resemblance to the film on which it's
based, Alfred Hitchcock's ``Dial M for Murder.'' Douglas, who says
he hasn't seen most of his own movies because he doesn't enjoy the
experience, says he hasn't seen many of Hitchcock's, either. He
liked ``Rear Window.'' ``Psycho'' _ heading for a remake with Anne
Heche _ is part of his personal history.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my first jobs was as an assistant film editor on
`Lonely Are the Brave,' which is my favorite of the pictures my dad
(Kirk Douglas) did. It was at Universal Studios. Down the hall they
were editing and cutting `Psycho.' In those days they didn't have
commissaries and such. We brought brown bag lunches. So we used to
go down at lunchtime with our brown bags and watch the outtakes of
Janet Leigh in that shower scene in `Psycho.' Then when I came on
board for this picture, I didn't want to go back and see the
original.''
</P>
<P>
   The film he couldn't help thinking back to, Douglas says, was
``Fatal Attraction.'' ``In that picture, I had the role Gwyneth
Paltrow plays here. I was the adulterer in that picture. She plays
an adulteress here. I was surprised how quickly people forgave me
in `Fatal Attraction.' People have been cheering Gwyneth in the
previews. But, you know, adultery is one thing, and attempted
murder is another. So it's just a question of how bad you are. Real
evil roles are relatively easy to play because there's something
unrealistic to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the attraction and fantasy are from the
audience's point of view. We have a big attraction to villains. I
was making comparisons to my dad, who got his first acknowledgment
in `Champion,' where he played a bad guy. I guess whereas most of
us in life are censored in our actions, villains aren't. So there's
that little piece in all of us that loves to watch somebody act out
those things we only think about in our deepest, darkest secrets.
It gives you a freedom. But you have to be unpredictable. A lot of
the appeal with Gwyneth is that she looks as if she has a secret.
So I thought Steven Taylor (Douglas's character) should have a
secret too.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; gfdots &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; sv1,s1,s2,s3,s4 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; dm0,38,14,14,19 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Smooth operator
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el3 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; dm0,v1,v2,v3,v4 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; sv1,0,0,0,0 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   When told that Paltrow, speaking via satellite from London,
described him as smooth, together, and in control, and said she
always felt like addressing him as ``sir,'' Douglas laughs. ``She
should! I've known her mother, Blythe Danner, since we both
auditioned for Lincoln Center in 1968, and I met her father, Bruce,
soon afterward. I remember Gwen as a girl in high school. This guy
I play, well, yeah, there's a slickness to him. He's really a kind
of coverup guy, trying to act more charming and looser than he
really was.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to create sympathy for your character, by showing his
rags-to-riches story played against his wife's inherited money and
position. Yeah, there was an anger to him. Yet in the first act,
you want to create sympathy for him because he was the one being
cheated on. Like, awwwww, Mikey, awwwww. What he didn't give his
wife, though, was passion and time. I mean, usually what happens
when you go into affairs, somebody's giving you something you're
not getting. I think her life is pretty much focused on his
attention. Then all of a sudden, here's somebody who's focusing all
of his energies and expertise on her,'' says Douglas, 54, recently
single after the end of his own marriage.
</P>
<P>
   The buzz around the film centered largely on a reshot ending.
Douglas minimizes its importance, saying the differences between
the two endings weren't nearly as divergent as the two wrap-ups of
``Fatal Attraction.'' In the first ending of ``Attraction,'' Glenn
Close's angry spurned lover frames Douglas's adulterer for murder.
In the one the public saw, he got off and returned to his family.
The two resolutions of ``A Perfect Murder,'' Douglas says, without
giving away the outcome, have to do with a final killing. In one
ending, it's done in self-defense. In the other, it's coldblooded.
``Which one you prefer depends on how dark and sick you are,'' he
says, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas says he hadn't planned to do ``A Perfect Murder,''
especially on the heels of ``The Game,'' in which he portrayed a
San Francisco millionaire plunged into a terrifying loss of control
over his life. ``The last thing I was looking for was another
Prince of Darkness role, after `The Game.' But it was what was
ready, and I make choices based on lack of comfort. It's exciting
when there's an element of danger, and the fun here was to make
this guy more than a two-dimensional villain. Comedy is not
something that comes naturally to me. But I liked doing `American
President,' and I love dark comedy, like `War of the Roses.' My
next role will be a heroic one, a good commander of a World War II
submarine, called `U-571,' so that will be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the project Douglas says he must do, the one
alongside his father, now 82. ``It's coming along,'' he says of
``Songs for David.'' ``It's getting closer. It's a tough one to do
right. We both feel we don't wanna do it unless it's done right.
And we only have one shot at it. It's a father-son piece involving
the construction business in New York. It's about a retired
chairman of the board, and his son is taking over, and the
struggles and dilemma and ultimate resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; gfdots &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; sv1,s1,s2,s3,s4 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; dm0,38,14,14,19 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A low-key star
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el3 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; dm0,v1,v2,v3,v4 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; sv1,0,0,0,0 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Oedipal resonances between the story and Michael Douglas's
relationship with his father are obvious. Douglas's parents
divorced early. He was raised by his mother, and he sidled into
acting in low-key fashion. ``In my father's generation, movie stars
were larger than life,'' he says, explaining the difference. ``In
my movies, people kind of relate to me. I mean, most people feel,
`that could be me up there. I could play that part. I could be that
person.'''
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Douglas tended toward the flamboyant. Michael Douglas,
Prince of Darkness roles notwithstanding, has been a readily
identifiable beleaguered Everyman in films ranging from ``Falling
Down'' to ``Disclosure.'' Anger is a part of his persona, too, but
in more layered, less immediately apparent ways. His on-screen
identity has also been influenced by wearing two hats
interchangeably over many years: actor and producer. Years after
his father's play, ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest,'' flopped on
Broadway, Douglas bought the screen rights and made his father rich
from the Oscar-winning film starring Jack Nicholson. Douglas has
successfully produced some of his own films, ranging from ``The
China Syndrome'' to ``Romancing the Stone.'' Yet he says he can't
stand producing films he acts in.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one was a pleasure. Just acting is cool. At the end of
the day, you go home. `Bye-bye, see ya. The dailies were great last
night? Glad to hear it!' Doing both is contradictory. I mean,
acting is about being selfish. It's about what's in front of you.
You are the most important thing in the world. Most really good
actors are very self-involved. You almost have to have a degree of
selfishness to be so much in demand of attention for yourself.
Producing is about being involved in everything that's going on
around you. If I'm producing, I'm watching all the other actors,
and seeing if I think they're fulfilling not only their
responsibility to the scene, but to the picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would I direct? It's beginning to be of more interest to me.
It's been starting to haunt me a little bit as we get into
reshooting endings like this. Certainly, I've been accused by
enough directors of meddling. But my acting career didn't really
take off until `Wall Street' and `Fatal Attraction.' So it's only
been about 13-14 years. Producing keeps me busy too. But I'm
recently single, my son is an adult, and I've got a lot of free
time on my hands. I better stay busy. I'm not good with a lot of
time on my hands. I like sporting events because you never know
what's going to happen until the end. In the movies, usually 20
minutes into the picture you kind of guess where it's going to go.
I'd love to get involved in a picture about sports. And my golf
game is getting good. I hope to make the Senior Tour one of these
days!''
</P>
</TEXT>
