   Which might be good news for ``Deep Impact,'' but bad news for
civilization as we know it. The movie chronicles the attempts of
earthlings to deal with a massive comet racing toward a collision
with our planet. Suffice it to say that they are not completely
successful. A large piece of comet lands just off the Atlantic
coast and spawns a tidal wave 100 yards high. Moviegoers observe as
New York City and Washington, D.C., are quite believably
obliterated.
</P>
<P>
   Thus goes the latest in a spate of celestial disaster dramatics.
In last year's ``Asteroid'' TV miniseries, Dallas got creamed.
Coming soon is ``Armaggedon,'' in which space hero Bruce Willis is
dispatched to save the world by taking on an asteroid the size of
Texas. (Scientists roll their eyes at this.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep Impact'' they say, is easily the best of the lot. What
happens in the movie could happen in real life. That and worse.
It's not likely any moment soon, perhaps, but planetary experts say
the risk posed by asteroids and comets justifies far more concern
than is currently exhibited by politicians and the general public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the threat is real,'' says Jack Hills, an
asteroid specialist with Los Alamos National Laboratory in New
Mexico. ``It doesn't happen very often, which is fortunate in one
respect. But in many ways it's unfortunate, because we won't do
anything before the next one comes.''
</P>
<P>
   And the consequences of such inaction should a huge piece of
space junk be headed our way?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're toast,'' Hills says.
</P>
<P>
   AN UNIMAGINABLE DEATH TOLL
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers have charted 120 asteroids more than a kilometer in
diameter whose orbits intersect with Earth, and the number grows
almost monthly. So far, calculations show that none poses a real
threat. But scientists estimate that 2,000 space rocks of that size
(the terms ``asteroid'' and ``meteor'' are essentially
interchangeable) zip about the solar system, most of them as yet
unseen.
</P>
<P>
   Should one that size strike land, dust and vapors thrust into
the stratosphere by the impact would plunge Earth into darkness for
months, killing off much plant and animal life. The human species
probably would not be entirely lost, but the death toll would be
unimaginable.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a huge celestial object slamming into the Atlantic
Ocean would produce ``a tsunami that goes all the way up to the
Appalachian Mountains in the upper two-thirds of the United
States,'' Hills says. ``In Europe, the coast of the Iberian
peninsula, Spain and Portugal, is basically wiped out, and the
(seacoast) of France. So it's quite severe.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists put the odds of such a catastrophe happening this
year at about 1 in 300,000, considerably greater than those for
drawing a royal flush in poker (1 in 649,000). Odds for a lesser
but still disastrous collision are much greater, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably about 1 in 3,000 or 1 in 5,000,'' Hills says.
``That is, something large enough to devastate many kilometers of
coastline. It would certainly be devastating regionally.''
</P>
<P>
   So it is a mistake to dismiss ``Deep Impact'' as science
fiction, as many have done. Science, yes. Fiction, no. MORE &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
