<HEADER>
A2487 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARVARD-III-SPCL-ART-     06-03 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-III-SPCL-ART-3RD </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... on Limerick.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few challenge Harvard's verdict. The university conciliates some
tenure victims, such as Berkowitz, with an extra year on staff;
others fear being blackballed if they complain. One exception was
Clare Dalton, who sued after being denied tenure by the law school
in 1987. Harvard settled the case in 1993 by paying $260,000 to a
domestic violence institute she heads at Northeastern University. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Junior faculty need not apply &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was, junior faculty members agreed as they listened to their
elders discuss fringe benefits a decade ago, classic theater of the
absurd. The tenured historians on the Committee to Improve Junior
Professorships were trying to patch the roof while the foundation
was collapsing.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, someone dared to ask Professor Bernard Bailyn, who
chaired the committee, why the department had not offered tenure to
a junior Americanist since 1959.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bad luck,'' Bailyn replied.
</P>
<P>
   Bailyn, the great historian of colonial America, knew better. He
and post-World War II contemporaries such as Oscar Handlin, had
themselves risen through Harvard's ranks to tenure, and forged its
pre-eminence in American history.
</P>
<P>
   Then the upheavals of the '60s reshaped the field. Ambitious
books devoted to entire eras, such as Arthur Schlesinger Jr.'s
``The Age of Jackson'' (1945), gave way to narrow studies of
oppressed groups _ women, blacks, Native Americans.
</P>
<P>
   To Harvard's elders, interest-group politics had supplanted
scholarship. In a 1970 jeremiad, Handlin lamented the ``erosion of
the basic skills, atrophy of familiarity with the essential
procedures, dissipation of the core fund of knowledge.'' Promotions
and appointments, complained Handlin, ``rest on strategic or
ideological considerations rather than on merit.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe elsewhere, but not at Harvard. Its wise men pulled up the
drawbridge against an entire generation. Then, in 1986, Brinkley
came knocking. A magnetic teacher, he turned down offers elsewhere
because he had been assured of breaking the Harvard impasse. But at
a key department meeting, sources say, several senior Americanists
voted against him, on the grounds that his scholarship was too
shallow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The university should have stepped in and said, `We can't have
this,''' says Donald. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Entrenched historians ignore committee's advice &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the administration blinked. Although Brinkley had won a
narrow majority in the department vote, A. Michael Spence, then
dean of arts and sciences, quashed his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard has occasionally placed departments paralyzed by
factional disputes over appointments, such as sociology in the
1980s, in a kind of academic receivership. But it did not confront
the entrenched historians. And while the visiting committee for
history, part of a system that monitors all Harvard departments,
urged a more welcoming attitude toward junior faculty, its advice
went unheeded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their reputation in American history has suffered,'' says one
scholar who has served on the committee, and requested anonymity.
``It was once the place to study American history. It's still good,
and they've got some fine historians. But I don't think it's at the
very top any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Brinkley's ouster particularly upset students and junior
faculty. The number of undergraduate history majors, which then
stood at 497, plunged immediately and has never recovered; there
are currently 260. Junior faculty took refuge in gallows humor.
They joked that the Dunwalke Chair in American history, held by
Brinkley and other untenured associate professors, was aptly named:
When they were done, they walked.
</P>
<P>
   They referred to their pot luck suppers as ``Dinners of the
Ephemeral Faculty.'' And they held an annual get-together marking
the anniversary of the last book by Professor Donald Fleming, who
specializes in American intellectual history.
</P>
<P>
   Junior faculty say Fleming blocked one candidate after another,
citing insufficient publications. Yet Fleming has not authored a
book by himself since 1954.
</P>
<P>
   At 74, Fleming remains a popular teacher. He barely avoided
mandatory retirement, turning 70 soon after the policy was
abolished in 1993. In a telephone interview, he defended the
rejections of junior faculty, but added that some of them should
have been ``brought back'' later on.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1954, Fleming said, he has written several monographs and
edited and contributed to scholarly volumes. Then he said, ``I take
it you'll turn this into a personal attack,'' and hung up. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Restoring the luster to American history &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After nearly two decades with hardly any new blood in US
history, Harvard in recent years has tried to restock from outside
_ only to see most of its offers rejected. ``We have too few
Americanists, period,'' acknowledges William Kirby, the department
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The hiring of Ulrich, a Pulitzer Prize-winning specialist in
women's history, from the University of New Hampshire in 1995
signaled a long-awaited glasnost. In 1996, she and Kirby invited
several luminaries _ including the previously exiled Limerick _ to
a brainstorming session. The topic: How to restore Harvard's luster
in American history.
</P>
<P>
   Their advice eventually translated into three offers of tenured
positions. Lizabeth Cohen, a widely-respected 20th-century
historian at New York University, accepted, but the other two
outsiders declined.
</P>
<P>
   Richard White, a specialist in western US history from the
University of Washington, opted for Stanford. And Pulitzer
Prize-winner Alan Taylor decided to stay at the University of
California's Davis campus because his wife, a classics professor,
was on track for tenure there. At Harvard, she would have no such
expectation.
</P>
<P>
   In US News and World Report's 1998 rankings of graduate
programs, Harvard stood sixth overall in history, and seventh in
modern US history. ``Harvard is within striking distance of making
the claim that they're as good as any American history
department,'' Taylor says. ``They need more hires and to build the
morale of junior faculty....It's a harder task to turn around a
luxury liner than a more modest craft.''
</P>
<P>
   By rejecting Fitzpatrick, Harvard missed an opportunity to
reverse the liner's course, and end a 39-year drought. Now at the
University of New Hampshire, she articulates the blighted hopes of
all those young scholars discarded in the name of excellence by a
harsh and, at times, capricious system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite all the evidence to the contrary, it's difficult not
to begin to think that you can be the exception,'' Fitzpatrick
says. ``You get on the hamster wheel, and you start spinning.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Kera Ritter of the Globe staff contributed to this article.)
</P>
</TEXT>
