<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2497 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARVARD-III-SPCL-ART-     06-03 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-III-SPCL-ART-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... of performance.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It's a snare and a delusion,'' Rudenstine says. ``If you don't
want a bitter person on your hands, sooner or later you're going to
make them a professor even if you've made a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   But sticking to its principles puts Harvard at a competitive
disadvantage. Some of its best junior faculty leave for tenured
positions elsewhere years before they would come up for tenure at
Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real issue is that Harvard does not tenure at the
associate professor level,'' Ulrich says. ``Everyone else does. So
people who would fully qualify for tenure at any other university
in the US are forced to compete for a full professorship with a
kind of star system.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Harvard historian emeritus David Donald: ``If you have a
young person coming along who you would really like to keep, who
will reshape the field, but has only published a PhD thesis,
somebody else will steal him off.''
</P>
<P>
   Although competitors such as Stanford have elevated the
importance of teaching in tenure verdicts, Harvard adheres to the
aphorism, ``Publish or perish.'' Officials contend that the
judgment of a candidate's peers is more meaningful than that of
easily-impressed undergraduates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the scholarship, you're just not going to remain a
part of the community,'' Rudenstine says. ``It's miserable for
someone who's totally outclassed in his department to be going
around knowing they're not a major scholar and almost everyone else
is. You can be a good teacher at the undergraduate level, but when
you move to the graduate level or faculty colloquia, you either
have it or you don't, and it's very obvious right away.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Competition is fierce for world's best minds &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Harvard faculty of the future takes shape every Wednesday
morning in a conference room in University Hall. Under a portrait
of architect Charles Bulfinch, Knowles and his staff take stock of
their courtships of the world's best minds.
</P>
<P>
   In an era of two-career couples, they realize that recruiting
isn't as simple as it used to be. Have they helped find a job for
one scholar's spouse, a school for a second's children, a
low-interest mortgage for a third? Are they offering enough lab
space to a scientist, enough graduate students to a humanist?
</P>
<P>
   Such perks only sweeten what is still one of the most desirable
jobs in academia. According to Knowles, nearly 70 percent of
Harvard job offers are accepted. Tenured Harvard professors enjoy
brilliant colleagues and students, vast libraries, six-figure
salaries supplemented by consulting work, a bully pulpit on talk
shows, op-ed pages, and Congressional committees, and near-total
job security. They may be fired only for ``grave misconduct or
neglect of duty.'' No wonder Harvard professors rarely quit, not
even economist Robert Barro, who wavered this spring before
rejecting a lucrative offer from Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing more important than drawing here the very best
faculty we can identify,'' Knowles says.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, junior faculty at Harvard earn half as much as
senior colleagues and live on borrowed time. The winnowing starts
after four years, when assistant professors may be promoted to
associate _ or not. If promoted, they receive a letter from the
department assessing their tenure prospects. A negative letter is a
signal to start job-hunting.
</P>
<P>
   But if an associate professor has written a prize-winning book
or two, he or she may be considered for tenure in three years. The
ordeal starts with a unique Harvard ritual _ blind letters, which
ask outside experts to assess six or more scholars in a given
field. They are called blind because they don't identify which
scholar Harvard is interested in hiring.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1990 amicus curiae brief to the US Supreme Court defending
the confidentiality of tenure, Harvard offered a rare glimpse into
the blind-letter process. ``The conscientious evaluator must be
specific, searching, and blunt in his or her appraisals,'' Harvard
wrote. ``He or she must have the intellectual honesty to say that
Professor A is no longer doing prime research, or that Assistant
Professor B's work is largely derivative of others in the field, or
that Professor C, although pursuing innovative concepts, has been
erratic, and that only Professor D, though not widely known, has
the creativity, discipline, and potential that characterizes a
truly innovative and influential thinker at the threshold of a
distinguished career.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the ideal. But in reality, critics say, the outside
experts are often unfamiliar with little-known, brilliant Professor
D from the junior faculty, and instead opt for the older,
established professors A, B and C.
</P>
<P>
   More and more, Harvard faculty regard blind letters as an
anachronism. Starting next year, letters from the economics
department will name its candidate. ``Blind letters are silly,''
says Jeffrey Williamson, the economics chairman. ``The rumor mill
works so fast that Berkeley knows in a few minutes who we're
interested in.''
</P>
<P>
   After reading the evaluations, the department's tenured faculty
vote at a meeting closed to junior faculty. The candidate needs a
favorable consensus; any substantial opposition spells doom.
</P>
<P>
   If the candidate prevails, the department forwards the name to
Knowles, who presides over another Harvard wrinkle. Each tenured
member of the department must write a confidential letter about the
candidate to the dean. It's an invitation to frank evaluation _ or
backstabbing.
</P>
<P>
   The dean may deny tenure. More often, he proceeds, selecting a
committee of three outside experts and two Harvard professors in
related departments. The ad hoc committee, a Harvard innovation
dating back more than half a century, gives the president veto
power over appointments to stop departments from becoming cliques
for friends and proteges.
</P>
<P>
   Chaired by Rudenstine, who has read each candidate's file at
least twice, the committee gathers in Massachusetts Hall. Over a
morning, it typically hears testimony from four people: the
candidate's chairman, two supporters, and an opponent. The
committee caucuses over lunch at the Faculty Club before leaving
Rudenstine to ponder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll read the file again afterward if I feel I need to do any
further checking,'' Rudenstine says. ``I'll make some phone calls
or whatever. Just to make sure my instincts are right. And then
I'll decide the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past five years, Rudenstine has rejected 15 percent of
candidates considered by ad hoc committees. He doesn't have to
follow the committee's recommendation; indeed, Bonnie Honig
reportedly was reportedly favored, 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   Although outside candidates are supposed to jump through the
same hoops as in-house candidates, the system sometimes bends for
them. Rudenstine waived the ad hoc committee for an organic chemist
Harvard wooed from the California Institute of Technology in April.
</P>
<P>
   Rejected applicants are rarely given a reason. Limerick learned
that she would not be promoted when she walked into the otherwise
sparse office of the history chairman and saw three words written
on a legal pad: ``No on Limerick.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
