<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-III-SPCL-ART-3 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SEARCH FOR BEST, BRIGHTEST, RISING STARS ARE LOST 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DANIEL GOLDEN AND JOHN YEMMA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Ellen Fitzpatrick, a well-regarded scholar and teacher of
modern US history, was denied tenure by Harvard University last
November, it extended a streak unparalleled in academia.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1959, when Dwight Eisenhower was president and Fidel
Castro assumed control over Cuba, Harvard has not tenured any
junior faculty members in US history, rejecting such standouts as
Alan Brinkley, a National Book Award winner, and Patricia Limerick,
recipient of a MacArthur ``genius'' grant. Once one of Harvard's
signature strengths, US history has become its version of the
Shaker religion, which died out because it forbade having children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's vital to change the perception out there that coming to
Harvard as a junior faculty member is a dead end,'' says Harvard
historian Laurel Ulrich. ``Creating a more flexible tenure system
is the wave of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Harvard's reputation for excellence rests largely on the
quality of its faculty, administrators regard the granting of
tenure, or lifetime appointment, as their most important decision.
To prevent mediocrities from sullying its ranks, Harvard has
established the nation's strictest tenure process. At a time when
other universities are rethinking tenure, or placing teaching on a
par with research, Harvard clings to a trial-by-fire system that
anoints a select group of scholar-kings, and consigns everyone else
to also-ran status.
</P>
<P>
   Yet its decline in US history offers a stark example of the
price Harvard sometimes pays for its lofty standards: poor morale
and intellectual stagnation. US history, a specialty within the
history department, is one of several fields suffering from what
Henry Rosovsky, the former dean of arts and sciences, has called
the ``classic pathology'' of being unable to find anyone worthy of
joining its ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for Harvard to reconsider its tenure process,'' says
Harvard Law Professor Charles Nesson. ``We've had a long history of
embarrassment with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, Harvard has farmed out junior faculty _ untenured
assistant and associate professors _ to other schools, confident
that it can hire them back if they set the world on fire. Like a
wealthy baseball team, it recruits expensive free agents instead of
promoting promising minor leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   The risks of this approach are familiar to sports fans: internal
dissension, bidding wars, and an aging roster past its prime. And
because federal law has abolished mandatory retirement, the
``extinct volcanoes,'' as one Harvard official privately calls
them, can stay as long as they want, denying slots to talented
newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tenure plus no retirement age presents big problems,''
Rosovsky says. ``Older people are inevitably very influential. I'd
like to see people gain more of a voice at a younger age.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, many junior faculty, including some Harvard would like
to retain, are so intimidated that they give up and leave early.
Even as Fitzpatrick appointment was being torpedoed last year, two
other associate professors in US history left for tenured jobs
elsewhere rather than run the tenure gantlet at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Being a junior faculty member at Harvard, recalls Limerick, now
at the University of Colorado, ``was a little like being a
terminally ill child. People were very nice to me since I wasn't
going to be around very long.''
</P>
<P>
   Under President Neil Rudenstine, prospects for junior faculty
have brightened somewhat, particularly for women and minorities. Of
111 junior faculty hired from 1987-1990, the most recent group to
be considered for tenure, about one in five survived the long
march, compared to one in 10 for earlier colleagues, according to
Harvard statistics. Thirty-eight percent of the 406 tenured
instructors in the Faculty of Arts and Sciences were appointed from
within _ still far less than competitors such as Princeton (50
percent) and Columbia (60 percent).
</P>
<P>
   This progress doesn't impress the casualties _ or their
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Rudenstine stirred up the campus by rejecting two
junior faculty in the government department, Bonnie Honig and Peter
Berkowitz. Fifteen women faculty signed a letter supporting Honig,
now tenured at Northwestern University. Nesson flouted Harvard's
policy of confidentiality by publishing Berkowitz's tenure
documents on the World Wide Web. Nesson also invited private
detective Terry Lenzner to investigate whether Harvard had violated
its own tenure rules.
</P>
<P>
   Rudenstine, who left Harvard as an assistant professor in 1968
for a tenured position at Princeton, now spends 25 18-hour days a
year judging tenure cases _ much more time than the average
university president spends on the issue. ``If there is a doubt, it
is better to resolve the doubt in terms of not promoting than
promoting,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you find yourself looking for reasons for tenure, then you
have to stop and say, `Wait a minute, we're supposed to be over the
bar, not creating a ladder to climb up and over.' I don't want to
sound negative, but if that is not the standard, then you're not
going to have the Harvard faculty.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not all appointments are treated equally &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The tenure process at Harvard is as decentralized as other
administrative functions. The powerful schools of law, business,
and medicine choose faculty with little presidential scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Yet all appointments are supposed to meet Harvard's tenure
standard, the most rigorous in American education. Tenured
appointments are made ``only if the candidate is among, or shows
promise of joining, the very best scholars in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The selection process of the Faculty of Arts and Sciences,
Harvard's largest school, is designed to fulfill this boast. ``If
no one is ever turned down, there's no point in having a process,''
says Jeremy Knowles, the dean of arts and sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike competitors such as Stanford, Harvard has no tenure track
that assures junior faculty will be considered. ``There's never any
guarantees,'' says Theda Skocpol, professor of government and
sociology, who was denied tenure in 1980 but filed a successful sex
discrimination grievance. ``There's a million stages where you can
lose your tenure fight right up to the end. This system is more
likely to make the mistake of not appointing an excellent person
than of appointing a second-rate person. The sins are of
omission.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard is virtually the only major university in America that
never gives tenure to associate professors _ the middle rung on the
academic ladder of assistant, associate, and full professorships.
</P>
<P>
   Other universities do award lifetime jobs to associate
professors, while still dangling promotion to full professorship as
an incentive. Harvard used to. As an associate professor, Ernest
May was the last junior faculty member tenured in US history in
1959. But Harvard stopped giving tenure to associate professors in
1968 because it found that departments would eventually promote
them regardless of performance.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
