<SLUG> BC-SKIN-CANCER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANCER SURVIVOR CRUSADES TRIES TO WARN SUN GODS AND GODDESSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ When a doctor diagnosed Harry Livingston with a
type of skin cancer known as melanoma three years ago, the New York
man figured it might be a death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my doctor, when the odds are a million to one, I'll be
the one,'' Livingston said.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston is lucky. His cancer was detected early, when the
chance of survival is as high as 95 percent. The key is early
detection. This year, about 7,300 Americans will die from melanoma,
which left untreated can spread.
</P>
<P>
   Melanoma is a growing problem. Since 1973, the incidence of
melanoma has increased 4 percent each year, with white people at
greatest risk.
</P>
<P>
   At this time of year, with warm temperatures and sunny skies,
Livingston, who celebrated his 64th birthday Tuesday, encourages
people to take heed.
</P>
<P>
   While working at Victory Lane Speedway in his hometown of
Schodack, N.Y., he proselytizes for sunscreen and hats while
helping customers into their Go-Karts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see these young girls come in and you can tell they're sun
worshipers. I try not to become a fanatic and scare them away.''
Instead, this born-again cancer survivor hands out pamphlets and
shows off a scar on his back. ``It looks like two craters on the
moon because the skin grafts fell off.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors also are busy this time of year getting out the message
that skin cancer kills. Many are trying to counter a recent study
that questioned the effectiveness of sunscreens.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of skin type, they suggest using a sunscreen with a
sun protection factor (SPF) of at least 15.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell Singer, a dermatologist in Schenectady, N.Y.,
recommends a facial sunscreen with moisturizer ``and wear it on
your face and arms from Memorial Day to Labor Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Research shows we get up to 80 percent of our lifetime sun
exposure before we turn 18, so Dr. Singer is adamant about
discouraging teen-agers from basking by pools or in tanning salons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I scare the hell out of them. I show them somebody with half
their face missing,'' Singer said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, protecting yourself from the sun has never been easier.
Besides sunscreens and sun blocks, there is a new line of
protective clothing approved by the Food and Drug Administration
and manufactured by Sun Precautions in Everett, Wash. For
information, call 800-882-7860.
</P>
<P>
   Those most at risk for melanoma include anyone who has had a
blistering sunburn, a family history of the disease, more than 20
moles or an outdoor occupation.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston isn't taking any chances. Since his wife first
spotted the cancerous moles on his back, he examines himself
frequently for any skin changes. Two years ago, he spotted a woman
in a sleeveless shirt with a growth on her shoulder. He encouraged
her to see a doctor, who diagnosed cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``She comes in and gives me a hug and a kiss, she tells people,
`I do this to Harry because he saved my life.'''
</P>
<P>
   Livingston blames his malignant melanoma on too much surfing in
Baja California as a teen-ager. While he wears sun blocks, hats and
protective clothing, he isn't giving up on summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``In life, you've got to have some pleasure without killing
yourself doing it,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
