<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2510 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FISH-ANTS-HNS &LR;      06-03 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISH-ANTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRE ANTS TO BLAME FOR 23,000 DEAD TROUT IN GUADALUPE RIVER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By THADDEUS HERRICK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ They have killed birds, toads, rats _ even fawns.
They have obliterated native ant populations. And, of course, they
have caused endless frustration _ and much pain _ to folks across
Texas and the South.
</P>
<P>
   Now the venom of the dreaded ``Solenopsis invicta,'' otherwise
known as the fire ant, has claimed another victim: the rainbow
trout.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Texas Parks and Wildlife Department say winged
fire ants that landed in the Guadalupe River following an airborne
mating ritual are to blame for the death of at least 23,000 trout
just north of New Braunfels.
</P>
<P>
   The kill occurred late last week along a well-stocked, 15-mile
stretch of the river that provides the state's only year-round
trophy trout fishing, a spot known to anglers for cool water, deep
pools and not a few keepers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a blow to our trout program,'' said Steve Magnelia, a
fisheries biologist for the parks and wildlife department.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say the ravenous fish gobbled up the venomous ants as
they fell in the water, in some cases consuming as many as 500 of
the dreaded insects. Though some trout were more than a foot long,
the majority of the dead fish were 3 inches to 5 inches and had
been released only within the last 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know their stomachs were packed with fire ants,'' said
Magnelia. ``There was nothing wrong with the water quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Though parks and wildlife officials cannot recall a fire-ant
fish kill of this magnitude, they say the incident is not the
first. The same thing has happened annually along the Guadalupe
since 1994, officials said, always triggered by a spring or summer
rain storm that sends the winged ants into the air.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the ants may be to blame for fish kills that date even
farther back, though state officials paid little attention before
the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Once airborne, the thousands of mating ants are attracted to
shiny surfaces, which is why they end up in swimming pools, pick-up
trucks and trout streams. Parks and wildlife officials found a
number of dead frogs and sunfish along the Guadalupe, also victims
of the ants.
</P>
<P>
   The reddish-brown ants, which make their homes in large mounds
and are known to sting when disturbed, are believed to have been
mistakenly imported to the United States from South America in the
1930s in ships carrying earth to stabilize their loads.
</P>
<P>
   Fire ants are quarantined in at least nine states. The scourge
of animal and plant life, their attraction to electricity has also
led them to chew through insulation, triggering blackouts and
fires.
</P>
<P>
   The trout that swim the Guadalupe apparently made easy victims
because of their tendency to snap up anything that floats on the
water's surface.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the fire ants actually stung the fish internally is a
matter of debate. Bart Drees, an entomologist who heads the Texas
A&AMP;M Imported Fire Ant Research and Management Plan, theorized that
the females (the only gender capable of stinging) had done just
that killing the fish.
</P>
<P>
   Parks and wildlife officials, on the other hand, were operating
on the assumption that the fire ants were dead when they were
consumed and that the fish succumbed to the insects' toxicity.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the state agency's divers found piles of trout
lodged behind boulders at the bottom of pools of 4 to 5 feet of
water. Because trout have small air bladders, they tend to fall to
the bottom instead of floating when they die. Still, the scene
along the Guadalupe was plenty grim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-three thousand fish is a sizable kill,'' said Jack
Ralph, a member of the parks and wildlife team that investigates
``kills and spills.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't compare to the 21 million that went down in the red
tide, but it's sizable.''
</P>
<P>
   State parks officials had recently finished stocking the
Guadalupe near New Braunfels with about 250,000 3- to 5-inch trout,
of which they expect to lose at least 10 percent with the latest
kill.
</P>
<P>
   The area below Canyon Lake is the only stretch of Texas river
that stays cool enough to provide trout fishing year round. Its
trophy trout designation, meaning anglers stand a good chance of
catching a big fish, attracts fly fishermen from around the state.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
