<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESCUING OUT-OF-PRINT BOOKS, INTERNET ADDICTION, HIGH-TECH GIRLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Ill., Tenn., Cal., Wash.) (js) 
 By KATIE HAFFNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
 A High-Tech Rescue For Out-of-Print Books 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ At the Book Expo America show in Chicago this week,
the most popular attraction by far was a new technology for
on-demand book printing. Print Lightning, a division of the book
wholesaler Ingram, hauled its entire operation to Chicago to
demonstrate the new process, which uses state-of-the-art IBM
printing equipment and software.
</P>
<P>
   When a title goes out of print or demand for a book falls so low
that publishers hesitate to reprint it, in steps Lightning. ``Books
really never have to go out of print again,'' said Larry Brewster,
Lightning Print's general manager. ``For $100 to $150, you set the
book up in the digital library, and books can be printed as
booksellers order them.'' A 300-page book costs about $5 to print
after the initial setup, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Once Ingram receives an order for even one book from a
bookseller, Lightning prints the book at the Ingram headquarters in
La Vergne, Tenn., and ships it to one of three major distribution
centers.
</P>
<P>
   A 300-page book takes about 30 seconds to print, and the books
are printed in no particular order. Out comes Freeman Dyson's
``Disturbing the Universe'' one minute, and ``The Collected Stories
of Phillip K. Dick'' the next.
</P>
<P>
   The books are expected to cost $15 to $20 apiece, Brewster said.
</P>
<P>
   At the book show, people were taken with the quality of the
books, especially the covers. ``Unless you were in the production
business, you'd have a very difficult time telling the difference
between these covers and offset printing,'' Brewster said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Lightning system prints only paperbacks, but
Brewster said the company hoped to offer hardcover editions as well
by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Lightning recently finished a pilot project with 150 titles from
three dozen U.S. publishers, like Random House and Princeton
University Press. The company plans to have 10,000 titles in its
digital library by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A New School for Girls Aims To Make High-Tech Seem Phat &LR;
</P>
<P>
   For the past three years, Kathleen Bennett, a high-tech
businesswoman in Silicon Valley and former middle school teacher,
has been on a mission to give adolescent girls a better chance at
becoming technical stars. In September, she will open the doors of
the Girls' Middle School, a private school for sixth through eighth
grade in California that will focus on math, science and
technology. Ms. Bennett said she believed that the school would be
the first of its kind in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   According to a report by the Commerce Department, men were three
times more likely to choose computer science as a field of study
than were women in 1994. Ms. Bennett believes that an all-girl
environment will give students the confidence they need to nurture
an interest in the sciences at an age when the pressure to be cute
and popular can be overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Silicon Valley is engineering-driven,'' Ms. Bennett said.
``It's not OK to have paradigms where the men are the technologists
and the women do everything else because that means the men are
going to go make the technology decisions for the next
millennium.'' The school's first class, sixth grade only, will have
36 students.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bennett has raised $1 million so far and hopes to raise an
additional $7 million. At first, the school will share space with a
church in Mountain View, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bennett has still more ambitious plans, including
after-school and summer programs. ``We want to take what we learn
and reach out into our communities,'' she said. ``We're trying to
be the beginning of a place in Silicon Valley that will grow to be
a center that provides young women and girls with a positive
experience with math, science and engineering.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Can the Internet Be Addicting, Or Is the Problem Elsewhere? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The results of a small, new study cast some doubt on the notion
of Internet addiction as a psychiatric problem. The report,
presented earlier this week at the annual meeting of the American
Psychiatric Association in Toronto, suggests that people who seem
unable to curtail the number of hours they spend on the Internet
may suffer from a raft of other psychiatric disorders.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, at the University of Cincinnati, interviewed 14
people who had spent so much time on line that they were facing
problems like broken relationships and job loss. The most striking
finding of the survey, the researchers said, were the other
psychiatric problems that turned up. Eleven of the 14 people had
been diagnosed with manic-depression.
</P>
<P>
   The study's authors said it was unclear whether the Internet
problem should be considered an addiction; a symptom of something
else, like manic-depression; a disorder caused by faulty impulse
control, similar to compulsive shopping or trichotillomania (a
compulsion to tear your hair out).
</P>
<P>
   The small number of study subjects has generated skepticism.
``Based on 14 cases, I don't know that we'd conclude much of
anything,'' said Malcolm Parks, an associate professor of speech
communication at the University of Washington. ``The question is,
could you find 14 people equally weird who didn't use the
Internet?''
 &UR; Delay of the New Intel Chip Won't Affect Consumers Much &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturing problems that have set the delivery of Intel's
next-generation chip back by at least six months mean a blow to
Intel, but for the average personal computer user, the impact of
the delay is likely to be imperceptible.
</P>
<P>
   Code-named Merced, the powerful new chip is designed primarily
for servers and work stations. It processes 64 bits of data at a
time, rather than the 32 bits handled by Intel's current crop of
microprocessors. The new chip was expected to be available late
next year, but now the company doesn't expect to deliver commercial
quantities of the chip until the middle of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   For consumers, the chip will eventually mean more sophisticated
computer games, with more realistic images and further advancements
toward virtual reality. For corporate users, the chip's
computational power will help with the manipulation of huge
databases.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say that consumers will not see the benefits of
Merced for at least five years. ``It's a much longer ramp than
we've seen before because Merced is so different and so high end,''
said Rob Enderle, an analyst with Giga Information Group.
</P>
<P>
   Intel stockholders, on the other hand, are feeling the impact of
the announcement. Intel is already suffering from razor-thin profit
margins on low-cost chips. The popularity of PCs costing less than
$1,000 has altered the economics of the computer chip marketplace,
increasing the importance of more profitable high-end sales. Since
the announcement of the delay, and the news last week of an
imminent antitrust suit by the Federal Trade Commission against
Intel, the company's shares have fallen.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Praise for an Ayatollah  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Internet already has a smattering of unofficial tributes to
the revolutionary leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini. Now Iran
plans its own electronic homage. On Monday, an Iranian official
said the ayatollah's 210 works in Persian and 107 of his texts,
translated into 16 languages, would be made available on the Web,
but it did not specify when.  &QL; 
 &UR; Taking Traffic's Pulse &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Seattle is a relative newcomer to traffic madness, but it's one
of the first clogged metroplexes to come up with an innovative
solution to the problem: a Weather Channel for traffic. Traffic TV,
a new University of Washington cable television channel, broadcasts
real-time, rush-hour traffic updates. The channel provides live
video footage of various traffic choke points around Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
