<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
  
 TOBACCO LOBBY WILL FAIL TRYING TO MAKE McCAIN SAY ``UNCLE'' 
(For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Mayday! Mayday! Tiger Two to Naval Command. I'm taking flak
from my left and heavy ack-ack from my right. Fuel is low, and I'm
out here alone. The bad guys just winged me. Looks like I'm going
in. Mayday! Mayday!''
</P>
<P>
   The last time John McCain was in a similar pickle, he was shot
down over Vietnam and landed in pain, in prison, and in the hands
of torturers. Now, Big Tobacco is trying to do what the North
Vietnamese prison guards couldn't do in six years of trying: make
him say ``Uncle.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator from Arizona is on the receiving end of the torture
treatment from the tobacco executives. The Big Tobacco companies _
undoubtedly represented in the 401(k) plans and mutual funds of
many Americans who sympathize with McCain _ are spending big money
to smear the chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee. The Bully
Boyz of the Burley Biz are spending what some estimate as upwards
of $50 million on advertising that is designed to demoralize
Congress and demonize McCain. It is not pretty.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco companies are buying air time and running broadcast
and print ads in lots of places, including Arizona and the two
early presidential testing ground states, Iowa and New Hampshire,
to turn public opinion against McCain.
</P>
<P>
   So low have they gone in their desperate attempt to stop tobacco
legislation that they are trying to destroy the political future of
one of the only Republicans in Washington with the gumption to
stand up to the most free-spending lobby of them all.
</P>
<P>
   The nicotine peddlers are worried that McCain's peculiar
combination of hero status and his committee chairmanship in the
Senate may give him the unique kind of outside-inside clout that
will decide the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   For the tobacco company chiefs, a lot rides on their struggle
with the onetime US Navy pilot who was shot down in Vietnam and
offered early release by his captors for propaganda purposes.
McCain's father and grand-father were Navy admirals who had ships
named after them. But McCain foiled North Vietnam's propaganda aim
by refusing to go home ahead of his turn, and he was roughed up
considerably by his torturers.
</P>
<P>
   Now the torture is the electronic kind _ death by a thousand
negative ads. McCain is thinking of running for president. At 61,
as a conservative hero to many Americans across the ideological
spectrum, the 2000 election is his last shot. He's earned his right
to have a go.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no free pass in politics, war hero or no. They all
get the same kind of flak. And what shot him down over North
Vietnam is a lot deadlier than the gimmicky junk fired off by the
greasy tobacco lobby.
</P>
<P>
   From the left, Teddy Kennedy hammers at McCain for not wishing
to impose a $1.50-per-pack tax on the evil weed. From the right,
Newt Gingrich denounces him as an apostate advocating ``a
big-government liberal tax-and-spend'' philosophy. Senate majority
leader Trent Lott, always the chief water-carrier for Big
Tobaccycq, undermines McCain's $1.10-per-pack tax, saying it'll
break the cigarette barons, harm the farmer, and weaken America's
moral fiber: ``Greed has just gone hog wild here,'' cautions the
greediest PAC-money porker of them all.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has come to terms with the Clinton White House _
something remarkable in this toxic waste dump called D.C. _ by
agreeing with Erskine Bowles, Clinton's chief of staff, to trim the
tobacco package in the direction of curbing youth smoking. With
3,000 kids daily initiating the smoking habit, McCain and Bowles
have settled on their version of a deal.
</P>
<P>
   But the cancer-stick lobby seeks to sow fear and dissent among
our lawgivers. And all the fire their millions can buy focuses on
McCain. The message to more cowardly congressmen? If we can savage
McCain, imagine what we can do to you, Senator, or you,
Congressman.
</P>
<P>
   Fear of saddling millions of teens with inevitable lung cancer
runs a poor second to fear of losing campaign cash from Tobacco Row
or, worse, having all that boodle go to your opponent next fall. So
stakes are huge, and McCain is in their gunsights, just like the
day his Navy fighter was knocked from the sky.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is a real hardhead, as the North Vietnamese learned. He
does not flinch. He takes on the TV networks, the piggish interests
of the anticampaign-finance-reform coalition, the wealthiest
lobbies in America, and now Big Tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco propagandists misread their man. You cannot break
McCain's will. You cannot make him quit. You cannot coerce him with
threats, bribes, bluster, or 30-second attack ads. He is a stranger
to the Tobacco Boys, because the senators they know are craven,
boot-licking, lily-livered, cash-sucking, yellow-bellied political
warblers. McCain has been in tougher spots than having Big Tobacco
blackmail him in Iowa or New Hampshire. If his fellow senators
abandon him on this one, they deserve the craven reputation they
have earned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
