<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLD TILTED THE COUNTRY WESTWARD
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ A few tiny nuggets of bright metal discovered
at Sutter's Mill in January 1848 tilted this continent westward,
brought in people and wealth, and made California a restless
nation's destination. The state is celebrating for the next three
years because were it not for the Gold Rush, California today would
be a place of stunning geography, a large, peaceful, sylvan ``Baja
Oregon.''
</P>
<P>
   In June 150 years ago, a Massachusetts native, Thomas O. Larkin,
wrote to the secretary of state ``of the most astonishing
excitements and state of affairs now existing in this country.''
Larkin, US consul general when Mexico ruled the West, told James
Buchanan that the gold ``is situated on public land.'' Forget it,
Uncle Sam. This gold would not be federalized but instead became a
symbol of frenzied opportunity and the basis of fortunes that still
rule California today.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the celebration, the California Historical Society
has published a double issue of its magazine, lavishly depicting
pregold California, ``The Contested Eden.'' At the Oakland Museum
of California, ``Gold Fever!'' has attracted crowds to its art,
artifacts, and photography. The exhibit moves this summer to Los
Angeles, then Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1840s, Isaac Wallace Baker prospered in Beverly, Mass.,
as an illustrator. But after he came to the California diggings,
his drawings and daguerreotypes of life in Murphy's Camp, on
display here, enthralled America. The search for gold intensified
divisions between the East's smugness and the West's suddenness,
between ingenuity and adventure, between pluck and luck.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1850s, California's population swelled by 245 percent, as
documented in J.S. Holliday's book, ``The World Rushed In.'' Larkin
warned that when ``the whale ships visit San Francisco, I think
they will lose most all their crews.'' Excavations for modern
skyscrapers confirmed his prediction, finding whole ships buried in
muck.
</P>
<P>
   California became synonymous with luck and hope until, as the
phrase went, things ``didn't pan out.'' Mark Twain and Bret Harte
arrived, their stories enriching the American imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone cheered. ``The recent rush to California,'' wrote
Henry David Thoreau in 1852, ``appears to me to reflect the
greatest disgrace on mankind.'' The sage of Walden Pond derided
``the lottery of gold-digging,'' as did his neighbor, Ralph Waldo
Emerson: ``I do not think very respectfully of the designs or the
doings of the people who went to California in 1849. It was a rush
and a scramble of needy adventurers, and, in the western country, a
general jail delivery of all the rowdies of the rivers.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowdy they were, and are. With human nature in thrall to Mother
Nature, an outlaw romantic image evolved, one that enlivened the
self-image of the state long after it entered the Union in 1850.
``A truly Homeric number of homicides fills the literature of the
Gold Rush, a catalogue of slit throats, gunshot wounds, and crushed
skulls,'' the historian Kevin Starr writes in ``Americans and the
California Dream,'' the first of his multivolume history. ``Murder,
especially from the latter part of 1850, through 1851, became a way
of life.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1860, Emerson declared, ``In America, the geography is
sublime, but the men are not,'' meaning that ``events so grand as
the opening of California'' prove that ``most of the great results
of history are brought about by discreditable means.''
</P>
<P>
   An untidy randomness is California's heritage, as real as ``the
blowing dust'' of gold seen by another New Englander in his youth.
Robert Frost was born in San Francisco after his father joined the
Gold Rush. In the 1870s, gold was still in the air and the memory,
as he later wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``Such was life in the Golden Gate:
</P>
<P>
   Gold dusted all we drank and ate.
</P>
<P>
   And I was one of the children told,
</P>
<P>
   ``We all must eat our peck of gold.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 1703EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
