u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-03 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK CHURCH ATTACKED FOR ALLEGED BIAS AGAINST HOMOSEXUALS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rev. Irene Monroe, a doctoral candidate at Harvard Divinity
School, is exploring, as she describes it, the ``relationship
between misogyny and homophobia in the black church and in the
Nation of Islam.''
</P>
<P>
   Monroe is rapidly becoming a prominent figure on the Boston
religious scene, and is not shy about expressing her views. Her
blunt style and academic credentials have made her increasingly
popular on the lecture circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe's growing renown comes from a willingness to do what few
others with her educational and theological pedigree dare to do _
publicly attack the black church.
</P>
<P>
   Within the black community, the church is viewed as the
foundation of the civil rights movement and the institution
unequaled for providing spiritual and physical comfort in times of
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But Monroe, a lesbian who lives with her partner in a row house
near Cambridge's Inman Square, is outspoken in her criticism of the
black church and the Nation of Islam for their treatment of women
and homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   In historically black Baptist and African Methodist Episcopal
churches, homosexuality is rarely mentioned. And if it is,
homosexuality is usually treated as a sin against God.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to speak out every opportunity I get because black
lesbians and gay men are virtually invisible in our churches and in
society,'' says Monroe, a youthful-looking 43-year-old who is also
a teaching assistant for the Rev. Peter Gomes at Harvard Divinity
School.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of the treatment of women is equally troubling to
Monroe. While black women are the backbone of most African-American
churches, they are often relegated to second-class status and
forced to take a back seat to male clergy. ``It's an entrenched
patriarchy,'' Monroe says.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe traveled a long, hard road to make it to the citadel of
academic excellence on the banks of the Charles River. She was
abandoned in a Brooklyn, N.Y., park as a baby, where she was found
by garbage collectors. She was reared by abusive foster parents.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe recalls one of her foster mother's favorite putdowns:
``You come from nothing. You are nothing. You'll be nothing.'' She
found refuge in a Brooklyn public library and in the sanctuaries
inside black churches. Monroe won a scholarship to attend Wellesley
College and went on to earn a master's degree at New York's Union
Theological Seminary.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, she became increasingly aware that the black
church was not always a welcoming place for women or gays. The bias
against gays and women extended to other black religious
institutions, Monroe said, in particular, the Nation of Islam.
</P>
<P>
   She wrote an essay titled ``Louis Farrakhan's Ministry of
Misogyny and Homophobia'' for a recent anthology on Farrakhan that
also included contributions from Henry Louis Gates Jr., Michael
Eric Dyson, Stanley Crouch, and other noted black intellectuals.
</P>
<P>
   The black church's attitude toward homosexuality is not solely a
question of civil rights, Monroe believes, but also involves
serious public health issues.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their views on homosexuality, many black churches
have been reluctant to talk about AIDS, which has ravaged the black
community, says Monroe, who will be a grand marshal for the Gay
Pride parade on June 13. The following day she is scheduled to
preach at Old West Church in Boston as part of Gay Pride Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Among blacks, and especially among many black clergy, Monroe
says ``there is a hierarchy of oppression. Being black is at the
top of the hierarchy and everyone else, women, queers, Latinos,
Asians are below. We need to realize that we don't have a patent on
oppression.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Monroe describes herself as a ``public theologian''
moving between academia and ``the streets'' to challenge
traditional black religious institutions to become more
egalitarian.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who are secure in themselves and in their faith don't
go around preaching hate, they preach love and acceptance,'' she
says. ``The only way to change the dynamics of the black religious
experience is to educate people.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HDfgc,s5,14 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Religion Notes
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _While it might be premature for most people, Pope John Paul II
has already released his schedule for the year 2000. John Paul, the
most traveled pope in history, is planning to stay in Rome to
welcome the hordes of visitors expected to visit the Vatican to
mark Christianity's third millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The only possible change to the pontiff's agenda might be a trip
to the Holy Land, a pilgrimage John Paul has long been eager to
make. So far, the politics and complexity of such a trip have made
it impossible to coordinate.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 million people _ triple the usual number _ are expected
to visit Rome during 2000 and the Vatican hopes to spread the
number of visitors by scheduling different events throughout the
year. The Vatican has set aside specific days to honor
entertainers, refugees, health workers, journalists, farmers and
police, among others.
</P>
</TEXT>
