<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-PERSPECTIVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCULPTOR SALLY FINE PUTS BROKEN CROCKERY AND GLASS TO USE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Broken crockery and glass have been important, if unexpected,
materials for art making throughout the 20th century, from the
mosaic exteriors of buildings by turn-of-the-century Catalan
architect Antoni Gaudi to the plate-encrusted, Gaudi-inspired
paintings Julian Schnabel started making in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Gaudi and Schnabel use broken china more for texture than
meaning; the Boston sculptor Sally Fine uses the same material for
both reasons, to suggest people, usually women, who have been
broken apart and partly reassembled. In Schnabel's work, there's a
macho tone to the Humpty-Dumpty breakage; in Fine's, it seems more
important to put the pieces back together.
</P>
<P>
   Fine calls her new show at Boston Sculptors at Chapel Gallery in
West Newton ``Happenstance,'' a nod to the random, chance aspects
of life. An artist known in the past primarily for work in tree
branches and bark _ there's a prime example in a prime spot near
the new entrance of the DeCordova Museum in Lincoln _ she's now
expanded her materials and emotional range.
</P>
<P>
   All the Chapel Gallery works, both small and large, are in some
sense figurative. A couple of the smallest are under bell jars that
protect but also suffocate: There's a parallel in Sylvia Plath's
novel ``The Bell Jar,'' where the glass dome is a metaphor for the
depressed person's isolation from the rest of the world. One of
Fine's bell-jar pieces, ``Sounding Stone,'' shows a child's hands
rising out of rock, with a spiny shell delicately balanced on the
fingertips. The upward thrust of the piece suggests optimism about
the possibility of escape.
</P>
<P>
   Several works are female torsos, covered in broken china or, in
the case of ``Wasp's Nest,'' in birch bark with fungi sprouting
from it and a ruff of bright green moss around the neck. The
whiteness of the bark recalls a Victorian lady's skin, but the
markings suggest the skin has been flayed. The torso is installed
facing the wall, so you see its back, a gaping hole lined in black
velvet that makes the depth of the space unreadable. Inside is a
lyrically bending twig with a wasp's nest clinging to it, stand-ins
for arteries and a heart. Hung inside another torso, called
``Property,'' are a variety of house keys with at least two
meanings: women locked away, and women's role as keeper of domestic
stores.
</P>
<P>
   The most glorious works in the show are the largest, including
``Blue Glass and Pen Shells,'' a neck-to-knees female figure hung
by a metal rod through her shoulders. A baroque extravaganza of
voluptuous shells and jagged, dangerous spikes of aqua glass, the
figure is lit from within, but only at womb level, as if that were
the only part of her that counted. One of her breasts wears shell
armor; the other one is missing, a void. The literal-minded might
see this as a mastectomy. But it also suggests images of strength:
a mythical Amazon warrior cutting off her breast so it won't
interfere with her archery; the icon that conflates Artemis and
Apollo into a single potent person, half woman, half man.
</P>
<P>
   Fine's ``Birch Maiden'' suggests a female crucifix, with
additional references to classical mythology and Native American
craft. Frontal and hieratic, the maiden hangs in the center of a
wall in front of the apse of this gallery, which used to be a
chapel. Behind her flares a skeletal fan of metal (actually a
dismembered satellite dish). The maid is made of birch bark, like
an American Indian basket, and her head and arms are replaced by
wayward, antlerlike twigs, which makes her seem a sister to Daphne
turning into a laurel. Hung off the floor, powerless to move, she
may be a sacrifice _ but she's a potent one, with her own magic.
</P>
<P>
   The only complete figure in the show, ``Winged Jardiniere,'' is
also the only male. While the fragmentary women are covered with
floral or lacy china patterns, this guy gets more masculine solids
or stripes. He also gets a cute little teapot spout for a penis.
(It's tempting to read this as some sort of size-does-matter
comment.) He seems poised for takeoff, hanging from rusty, thick
chains, with only the toes of one foot still touching the floor,
his satellite dish wings jutting behind him. Yet this Man of Action
looks weighty and awkward. His attempt to soar seems as doomed as
that of Icarus, or those of the flying machines of Leonardo and
Vladimir Tatlin.
</P>
<P>
   Sally Fine's ``Happenstance'' is at Boston Sculptors at Chapel
Gallery, 60 Highland St., West Newton, through June 21. Gallery
hours are Wednesday through Sunday, 1-5:30 p.m. The show's opening
reception is Sunday 2-5 p.m. Fine gives a gallery talk on June 14
at 11:15 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; gfdots &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Carl Belz, Princeton basketball star, rock music chronicler,
and, for nearly a quarter-century, director of the Rose Art Museum
at Brandeis University in Waltham, is retiring early from that
post, at the ungracious request of a university administration that
wants a fund-raiser in the job. It was Belz who built what has
become the largest collection of contemporary art in New England,
and who brought more high-level contemporary shows to this region
that any other curator or director has. That's his most visible
achievement. Belz was also a whiz at explaining art, and not only
to grown-ups. The Rose never patted itself on the back for its
school programs _ that's not Belz's style _ but area teachers and
students remember them as masterful introductions to
sometimes-challenging work. And Belz was a tireless visitor to
artists' studios, tracing careers over years, even decades.
</P>
<P>
   A great many people in the Boston art community have reason to
be grateful to Carl Belz. They'll have a chance to say thanks in
person Sunday, when Brandeis and the Rose overseers host a
reception in his honor inside the museum and on its grounds.
Everyone's invited. Hours are 3-5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the end of Belz's presence on the Boston scene. He's
agreed to be the guest juror for the Triennial at the Fuller Museum
of Art in Brockton next year. The Triennial is the region's largest
regular contemporary art pulse-taking: Selecting its participants
is an appropriate assignment for a man with such extensive
knowledge of the art community. And, on a national level, Belz has
been approached about contributing to the catalogue raisonne of
Robert Motherwell's paintings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
