<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, June 4, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, residents of Rapid City, S.D., awakened to a
record low temperature of 32 degrees as a push of unusually cold
air poured southward from Canada. This pool of cool air will remain
over a large section of the Northern states Thursday, stretching
from the northern Rockies to the Great Lakes and onto New England.
</P>
<P>
   Milder winds gliding over the cold air will cause chilly rains
to fall from eastern Wyoming to South Dakota and Nebraska. Snow is
likely in some of the higher elevations of the Front Range, mainly
above 6,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of showers and strong thunderstorms will occur from the
lower Mississippi Valley to the Southeast coast as sultry winds
from the south intercept a nearby stationary front.
</P>
<P>
   Later Thursday, a jet stream disturbance will pass over the
front, causing a few of these storms to become severe. Winds
changing direction and increasing speed with altitude will impart
rotation to a few of these storms. These rotating thunderstorms,
known as supercells, are capable of spawning tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, uncomfortable heat and humidity will persist from
southern Texas to southern Georgia and Florida. Elsewhere, isolated
strong thunderstorms will erupt Thursday afternoon in west Texas as
a front separating dry air from humid air advances east through the
region.
</P>
<P>
   Brisk winds from the northwest will direct very cool air into
the eastern Great Lakes and Northeast. A disturbance rotating
around low pressure over eastern Canada will bring chilly showers
to portions of northern New England. The remainder of the region
will have a mixture of clouds and sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific states will be dry and sunny, though patchy clouds
will shroud sections of the California and Oregon coasts. Much of
California will continue to be seasonably cool.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: JUNE SNOW
</P>
<P>
   As a meteorologist at the National Weather Service at Rapid City
ventured outside to prepare for a weather balloon launch, he was
met with a surreal scene. With heavy snow falling from a lightning
illuminated sky, water sprinklers rhythmically swayed across a
newly whitened lawn earlier parched by hot, dry weather. By early
Wednesday, three inches of snow had fallen, the city's second
greatest June snowfall. June snow is rare. Since records began in
1888 at Rapid City, it had previously snowed twice in June _ 0.5
inches on June 13, 1969, and 3.6 inches on June 1, 1951. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
