<HEADER>
A2607 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-SALMON-NAT     06-03 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-SALMON-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     
 &HT;    
 &HT;      SALMON GROWERS, LAWMAKERS ON CHILEAN OFFENSIVE
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Paul Kane  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, June 3 -- Maine's lawmakers and fishermen argued
Wednesday that the state's Atlantic salmon industry is ``a shadow
of what it could be'' because of heavily subsidized Chilean imports
eating away at Mainers' profits.
</P>
<P>
   In a hearing before the International Trade Commission, the
delegation laid out a case for the alleged harm done to the salmon
industry caused by Chile's imported salmon, noting the decline in
Maine salmon producers from 19 companies to 10.
</P>
<P>
   But the Maine industry faced off with a well-financed opponent,
backed by Chile's salmon growers and various U.S. industries that
benefit from the imports of cheap salmon.
</P>
<P>
   For a hired gun, the opponents have brought in retired Senate
Majority Leader Bob Dole, who is a partner at the high-powered
Washington lobbying firm of Verner, Liipfert, Bernhard, McPherson
-- which is also the legal home of George Mitchell, the retired
majority leader from Maine. Mitchell, however, has not been
involved in the salmon case.
</P>
<P>
   Dole did not appear at Wednesday's hearing because he was in
Arizona for the funeral of Barry Goldwater, but in prepared
testimony he contended that ``there is no injury to the domestic
salmon industry caused by Chilean imports.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The imposition of tariffs (against Chile) would do far more
harm than good,'' added Dole, who was representing American
Airlines, United Airlines and the National Restaurant Association,
among others. The airlines benefit from flying Chile's salmon cargo
from South America up to Florida, where most of it is processed,
and the restaurants prefer buying cheap salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the high-profile opposition, Maine's position received a
boost Tuesday from a U.S. Commerce Department final ruling that
found 38 companies from Chile did indeed ``dump'' its salmon on
U.S. markets at prices below market prices.
</P>
<P>
   It was not as widespread an indictment of the Chilean salmon
industry as Maine's fishermen would have liked, but that ruling set
in motion the process that could lead to anti-dumping duties
imposed on Chilean salmon, anywhere from $2.24 to $10.91 for every
$100 of salmon sent to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   For that to occur, the ITC must issue a ruling, due by July 15,
that the U.S. salmon industry has in fact been harmed by the salmon
dumping, otherwise the prices will remain the same despite the
Commerce decision.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Maine's representatives tried to hammer home
the point that the industry has suffered greatly from Chilean
dumping. ``I just can't go toe to toe with them,'' said Eric
Swanson, president of Trumpet Island Salmon Farm. ``It's important
to send a message out: you have to play fairly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This threat is very real, and deadly, to our industry,'' said
Sen. Olympia Snowe, R-Maine, whose comments were echoed by Sen.
Susan Collins and Rep. John Baldacci.
</P>
<P>
   All three lawmakers noted that the salmon industry is the second
largest form of acquaculture in Maine, worth $44 million a year in
revenue, accounting for about 960 jobs in the economically
challenged Downeast counties of Washington and Hancock.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a place where good jobs are few, the salmon industry has
indeed been a blessing,'' Collins said, adding, ``This illegal
dumping makes the industry a shadow of what it could be.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Baldacci: ``The deck is stacked and the Chileans have the
stronger hand.''
</P>
<P>
   While demand for salmon has risen 100 percent this decade,
profits have fallen for U.S. salmon growers, 13 of which have
closed the past three years in Maine and Washington, the two states
that produce salmon.
</P>
<P>
   But Dole and other supporters of Chilean salmon say the domestic
industry focuses on producing whole salmons, while Chile focuses
sales on salmon filets, the product most responsible for boosting
U.S. demand for the fish. The domestic industry, they contend,
cannot keep up with the demand for filets, and Chilean salmon
growers should not be punished for finding a niche market.
</P>
<P>
   Further, Dole says there are 1,400 jobs in southern Florida
alone, 7,600 nationwide, directly related to distributing,
transporting and marketing Chilean salmon. Any duties imposed on
Chilean salmon would endanger those jobs. ``It would create
significant injury to other sectors of the U.S. economy, injury
that is far out of proportion to any beneficial impact derived by
(Maine salmon growers),'' Dole said.
</P>
<P>
   But Snowe disputed her former colleague, saying Maine's salmon
is just as good and could be easily substituted for Chilean filets
to meet the rising demand -- if everyone was on equal footing.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, we must ask: Who is winning, and at
whose expense?'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
