NYT-06-03-98 1725EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2615 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARLEM-SHOWHOUSE-ART-     06-03 0220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARLEM-SHOWHOUSE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A' TRAIN TO SHOW HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-1243 or 1927.)  
(gm) 
 BY MITCHELL OWENS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Show houses in New York are generally not racially or
ethnically diverse, from the designers for whose works they are a
showcase to the ticket buyers who come by to gawk and sometimes
hire. The first Harlem United Show House, which opens Saturday and
will remain on view through July 3, however, aims to change that
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to show what we've been doing for all these years,''
said Roderick Shade, an interior decorator, who organized the show
house to raise funds for the Harlem United Community AIDS Center
and also to raise the visibility of African-American designers.
</P>
<P>
   Staged in an imposing brick and limestone 1906 town house at 459
West 141st Street, between Columbus and Amsterdam avenues, the show
house will present the work of 24 African-American designers. They
include Shade himself, who is paving a guest room's walls with
rough mosaic tiles, and Patsy Johnson, whose romantic roof garden
design employs Oriental motifs.
</P>
<P>
   For directions and information, the number is (212) 531-1300,
extension 415.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
