<HEADER>
A2627 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      06-03 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Please note that the word AT within parentheses has been used
in the Internet address in the last graf instead of the symbol,
which is non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(th) 
 By LESLIE LAND   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE `MAGIC NUMBER'
</P>
<P>
   Q. I tried to grow sweet corn several years ago and failed
miserably. I have heard that you need a certain minimum of plants
so that they can cross-pollinate, a necessity for the plants to
yield corn. Is this true? What is that minimum number? Is it too
late to plant this year?
</P>
<P>
   A. No, it's not too late at all. Corn does best when planted in
warm soil and grown in hot weather. Then, ideally, just as the
ripening starts, nights will begin to cool off. Heat is great for
vegetative growth, but the plant will produce ears that have more
carbohydrates (including sugars) when temperatures are moderate.
</P>
<P>
   As far as pollination goes, your informant is on the right track
but not great on the specifics. Cross-pollination between varieties
usually results in starchy, bland corn, so different strains should
be separated, either by large distances or staggered ripening
times.
</P>
<P>
   Yet pollination itself is essential, and though each plant is
both male and female, corn plants don't fertilize themselves
because the two parts reach sexual maturity at slightly different
times. The ear is the female part. Each corn kernel on it is
attached to a strand of silk. A grain of pollen from a tassel, the
male part, must fall on it in order for that kernel to develop. The
pollen is shed over a period of several days, but each grain is
only viable for about four hours. So the trick is to be sure those
grains get a good wide distribution.
</P>
<P>
   You can't call in the bees for help; corn is pollinated by a
combination of wind and gravity, and that's where the ``minimum
number of plants'' comes in. It's not so much a matter of numbers
as it is of how they're arranged _ they should be in blocks rather
than single rows.
</P>
<P>
   You should have at least four rows 36 inches apart. That means
that a block will be nine feet on a side. So the plants should be
about 10 inches apart, with a total of 10 or 11 plants per row.
That may sound like a lot, but since two ears per stalk is average,
there isn't much point in planting less.
</P>
<P>
   GREENERY VS. TOXINS
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have read that certain houseplants are particularly
effective at removing toxic substances from the air. (Those
mentioned include the spider plant, English ivy and dracaena.) Is
there any truth to this?
</P>
<P>
   A. The most impressive tests of this hypothesis were conducted a
decade ago by NASA scientists. They put plants and pollutants
together in sealed containers and measured marked reductions in
gases, including formaldehyde, benzene and carbon dioxide.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the sealed environment is central to the effect.
Open a window, and the impressive results fly out of it. As
skeptics, including Robert Axelrad, senior policy adviser in the
indoor environments division of the Environmental Protection
Agency, have pointed out, it would probably take hundreds of plants
to refresh the air as well as proper ventilation does.
</P>
<P>
   Indoor air pollution is in large part caused by ``outgassing,''
the release of toxic substances by a host of common products. From
plywood to permanent-press fabrics, the synthetic rug to the
ceiling tiles, many furnishings of daily life constantly exude
chemicals like formaldehyde, xylene, toluene, ammonia and benzene.
Plants can remove small quantities of these from the air, but they
cannot stop the outgassing itself; so control at the source should
not be ignored. Score another point for natural fibers.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. B.C. Wolverton, an environmental engineer who worked on the
NASA studies, has retired from the space agency but continues his
research under the sponsorship of the nonprofit Plants for Clean
Air Council in Davidsonville, Md., an organization supported by the
houseplant industry.
</P>
<P>
   His enthusiastic but regrettably footnote-free ``How to Grow
Fresh Air'' (Penguin, 1996) lists 50 houseplants recommended for
their air-cleaning ability. He gives high marks for chemical vapor
removal to the Areca palm (Chrysalidocarpus lutescens), the rubber
plant (Ficus robusta) and the Gerbera daisy (Gerbera jamesonii), as
well as English ivy (Hedera helix) and a couple of dracaenas. The
spider plant is also in the book, but rather low on the list.
</P>
<P>
   EDIBLE OR POISONOUS?
</P>
<P>
   Q. If I plant edible plants like herbs next to plants that are
listed as poisonous, will the edible one still be safe to eat?
</P>
<P>
   A. Toxins being formed by growing plants don't migrate through
the soil and wouldn't be taken up by the neighbors even if they
did. And plants of different species do not cross-breed naturally.
So the short answer is sure, no problem.
</P>
<P>
   But there are a couple of things to watch out for:
cross-contamination, in which toxic plant parts fall on the
innocents next door, and skin rashes, known to doctors as contact
dermatitis.
</P>
<P>
   Cross-contamination is seldom a problem, since most poisonous
plants must be eaten _ or made into tea and drunk _ before they can
hurt you. But a few, including angels' trumpet (Datura), foxglove,
oleander and some lobelias are potentially so virulent you could be
sickened just by nectar or sap that fell on an adjacent edible and
didn't get washed off.
</P>
<P>
   Contact dermatitis is a lot more common. It would be so easy to
brush against an ornamental as you reach for the food. Allergic
reactions to plants vary widely, but many people get rashes from
such garden stalwarts as comfrey, spurge and feverfew, and I can
personally vouch for the devastating effects of the beautiful
blue-flowered Phacelia parryi.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I'd say all bets are off if small children will be
visiting the garden. They might easily come to the wrong
conclusions if they saw pretty poison in the vegetable patch, and
they're a lot more likely to be seriously hurt if they make a
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to Garden Q&AMP;A, The New York Times, 229 West
43rd St., New York, N.Y. 10036, or by e-mail to
gardening(AT)nytimes.com. Those of general interest will be
published. Unpublished questions cannot be answered individually. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
