<HEADLINE>
FAN WANTS HARTMAN THE PLANET FOR PHIL THE STAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill O'Reed of Lancaster, Ohio, thinks the world of Phil
Hartman, the late comedian-actor.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, O'Reed wants a world named for the former ``Saturday
Night Live'' performer who died a week ago in a murder-suicide.
</P>
<P>
   O'Reed's Phil Hartman Tribute (www.maggie-roo.com/phil) asks
that visitors to his site write to their congressional
representatives and suggest ``Phil'' or ``Hartman'' as names for a
planet recently discovered by the Hubble Space Telescope.
</P>
<P>
   The planet, known as TMR-1C, was officially announced May 28,
the day Hartman was found dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be coincidence, but the planet was found near the same
time a star dimmed on Earth,'' O'Reed said. ``It may sound quirky,
but it would be a great tribute.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Reed's page is one of several sites official and unofficial
that pay tribute to Hartman and his work.
</P>
<P>
   A rundown of some of the others:
</P>
<P>
   Chip Howland's Phil-Hartman-izer
(www.skypoint.com/members/howland/hartman.html) translates any text
into coded swear words that Hartman made up as a child.
</P>
<P>
   Brian LeBail's The Phil Hartman Show
(www.geocities.com/Hollywood/6422/hartman.html) features sound
files of Hartman from ``NewsRadio'' and ``SNL.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Hartman, Man of 1,000 Voices and Faces
(members.aol.com/kathster1) has an image gallery and an online
guest book.
</P>
<P>
   Hartman fans can get a biography and a collection of his work on
these sites, or they can turn to official sites set up by NBC's
``NewsRadio'' and ``SNL'' or Fox's ``The Simpsons.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Reed's site might be the most complete Hartman tribute, with
images, sound files, links, guest book and chat options. O'Reed
said he admired Hartman's talent and character.
</P>
<P>
   ``I design Web pages for many different people, and this time, I
designed one from the heart _ for Phil,'' O'Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   ( Tommy Cummings receives e-mail at dragon\Nstar-telegram.com
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
