<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KAYAK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KAYAKING IS FOR THE PHYSICALLY, FINANCIALLY FIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE NEWBERG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) - Peter Zwagerman staggered from the river and
collapsed in a heap.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when I just started trembling,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ``post-adrenaline syndrome'' of kayaking had spent his
energy that day in 1986, when Zwagerman experienced the Santa Rita
Hole on the Animas River in Durango, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to exit the hole _ an area formed by water rushing over a
rock or obstruction _ by turning upside down and putting his paddle
into the current rolling downstream didn't work. Zwagerman
eventually managed to escape by rocking back and forth, and finally
out of the raging current.
</P>
<P>
   Zwagerman is no amateur when it comes to kayaking. As the owner
of Tempe's Permagrin Canoeing and Kayaking School, he knows the
thrill and the risk of running white water. He coined the term
``post-adrenaline syndrome'' after experiencing the rush of
kayaking and the letdown that follows.
</P>
<P>
   This year was especially good for the sport after El Nino rains
fed Arizona waterways, notably the upper Salt River.
</P>
<P>
   ``The upper Salt River Canyon is probably one of the premier
river runs in the Southwest. It's absolutely beautiful,'' said Paul
Tuohy, president of the Central Arizona Paddlers Club.
</P>
<P>
   Another prime kayaking spot in Arizona is the Verde River near
Camp Verde, where the white-water season usually runs from February
to April.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of fun. Boy, it's fun,'' Zwagerman said.
</P>
<P>
   When Arizona's rivers become too shallow, many kayakers chase
white water around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of boaters who live for the river. They're going
from river to river,'' said Nancy ``Kanu'' Kaplan, owner of
Phoenix's Canyons &AMP; Coastlines Kayak School.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the season on the upper Salt River is winding to a
close, kayakers' next big event is Animas River Days on June 27 and
28 in Durango.
</P>
<P>
   Other kayaking destinations are the Green River in Utah, the
Lochsa in Idaho, the Kern in California and the Rio Grande in New
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Kayakers do all that traveling for one reason: The sport is too
much fun to pass up.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Murbach of Scottsdale, Ariz., lives in a small house and
drives an old car so she can spend her money on kayaking trips.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kayaking is a blast,'' Kaplan said.
</P>
<P>
   What makes white water such a rush is playing in the water in
the highly maneuverable boats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier to do the trick moves in a shorter, flatter
boat,'' Zwagerman said.
</P>
<P>
   Those moves might include surfing a wave or standing the boat
vertically in the current.
</P>
<P>
   White-water kayaking presents a physical and mental challenge
for its practitioners.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm out on the water, I don't think about anything else.
It's very intense, but not in a dangerous way. It's intense in a
stimulating way,'' Zwagerman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's challenging. It's a place where I can enjoy myself and
benefit from the rewards of being challenged.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides running fast water, kayakers can choose touring or sea
kayaking. Touring is peaceful paddling that takes boaters along a
lake's shoreline or on relatively flat river water. Sea kayakers
have to reckon with waves and swells.
</P>
<P>
   Training is important in all types of kayaking, but it's
imperative with white water. A river can kill a kayaker.
</P>
<P>
   Water is rated from Class 1 to Class 6, ranging from flat water
easily navigated to water that is unrunnable and could mean death
for anyone who tries. Kayakers who run Class 5 rapids push the
envelope.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of rapid would likely contain ``hydraulics'' that can
suck in kayaks and not let go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rivers have all kinds of hazards,'' Kaplan said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those are visible, such as when a horizon line suddenly
appears. That means a drop is ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pull over and look at it. An everyday Joe will just run it
and get into trouble,'' Kaplan said.
</P>
<P>
   About a year of hard work and training is required to become
proficient at paddling, Tuohy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the hardest thing is developing the mental end of it,
knowing that you can roll back up when you flip over,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Flipping over and having to execute an Eskimo roll to right the
craft is an inevitable part of white-water kayaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know you're going to get flipped over eventually,'' Tuohy
said. ``It's not a bad thing. It's kind of fun, especially when
it's hot out.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning white-water kayakers should start with at least 15
hours of flat-water training, learning moves such as the Eskimo
roll and basic strokes. Then they can move up to slow moving water
to learn peel outs, eddy turns, ferrying, and side and bow surfing,
Zwagerman said.
</P>
<P>
   How to read and swim moving water, basic river safety and
running a river with a group of people are other must-learn topics.
</P>
<P>
   Intermediate instruction takes kayakers to Class 3 white water.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's certainly a large level of skill involved,'' Tuohy
said.
</P>
<P>
   Having the right equipment is another requirement. Kaplan
remembers one man running the upper Salt River who strapped a
mixing bowl to his head and called it a helmet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I'm not going to pay no $65 for a helmet,' '' she
said. ``We see the wacko-est people up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting started in kayaking will cost about $1,000 to $1,500 for
a boat, paddle, spray skirt, life jacket, wet suit and helmet.
</P>
<P>
   A life jacket is a critical piece of equipment, Tuohy said, and
a kayaker needs to have one that can be depended on to float.
</P>
<P>
   ``Always buy a new life jacket,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 1736EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
