<HEADER>
A2646 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      06-03 0362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (pr) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Thursday, June 4. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (212-556-1927).
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-RAILCRASH (Eschede, Germany) _ A high-speed passenger
train roaring through northern Germany ploughs into a concrete
bridge pillar at 125 mph, spins from the tracks, and kills at least
80 people, possibly including children on a school excursion. By
Alan Cowell. 1,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-ELECT (Los Angeles) _ A look at what Tuesday's primary
says about California, its demographics and the key role played by
the Hispanic vote in defeating the referendum on bilingual
education. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-LABOR (Los Angeles) _ In an impressive assertion of
organized labor's political might, California voters on Tuesday
dealt conservatives a major setback by rejecting a measure that
would have pinch the flow of money to Democratic candidates and
causes. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR-ASSESS (Washington) _ News analysis: Monica
Lewinsky's new legal team, Plato Cacheris and Jacob Stein, spend a
good part of the day familiarizing themselves with the case in
preparation for possible new settlement talks with independent
counsel Kenneth Starr. But the lawyers also make clear that they
have not been hired to strike any deal, and they are prepared to
contest any charges if they are filed. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   With: LEWINSKY-LAWYERS (Washington) _ Profiles of Plato Cacheris
and Jacob Stein, Monica Lewinsky's new lawyers. By Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN-MOLE (Washington) _ The case of an intelligence official
in another country who was accused of being a spy for the Russians
but was then exonerated and reinstated, is raising concerns about
the security of American secrets. By James Risen. 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-VACCINE (Undated) _ The Food and Drug Administration has
given a California company approval to conduct the world's first
full-scale test of a vaccine to prevent infection with the AIDS
virus. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
</TEXT>
