u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-PRAYER-COX &UR; 450     06-03 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-PRAYER-COX </SLUG>
   450&AMP;ADD  CHRISTIAN COALITION CAMPAIGNING
HARD FOR SCHOOL PRAYER AMENDMENT
 &HT;     By EUNICE MOSCOSO 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With a vote scheduled Thursday on a constitutional
amendment to guarantee school prayer in public schools, the
Christian Coalition has stepped up its campaign in favor of the
measure.
</P>
<P>
   The religious organization this week distributed hundreds of
thousands of church bulletins urging constituents to call their
leaders in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, they are targeting 50 congressional districts with
phone calls, radio ads and 150,000 postcards _ some of which accuse
opponents of religious bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   Arne Owens, spokesperson for the Christian Coalition, said the
amendment is one of the group's highest priorities because
intolerance of religion is spreading throughout society, not just
in schools.
</P>
<P>
   Owens cites a case in which a judge was not allowed to display
the Ten Commandments in a courtroom, and another in which a menorah
was not allowed as a decoration on a government building's lawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see it all over,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents say a constitutional amendment is a first step in
changing the social climate.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, introduced by Rep. Ernest Istook, R-Okla., states
that ``the people's right to pray and to recognize their religious
beliefs, heritage or traditions on public property, including
schools, shall not be infringed.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's vote will be the first of its kind in 27 years. A
similar amendment fell 28 votes short of the needed two-thirds
approval in the House in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the measure _ including President Clinton _ say
voluntary prayer is already allowed in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, many fear that the amendment would lead to a
majority religion being imposed on schoolchildren, and to
government intervention in religious activities.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the opposition in the House is Rep. Chet Edwards,
D-Texas, whose district includes Baylor University, one of the
nation's leading Baptist colleges.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of his stance, Edwards has been the topic of one of
the coalition's mail campaigns. In a postcard sent this week to his
constituents, the coalition accuses him of trying to silence people
of faith.
</P>
<P>
   The postcard states: ``The Edwards bigotry directed at
Christians and other people of faith is outrageous and must be
stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said the postcards are ludicrous and hateful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect the Christian Coalition's right to support an
amendment, but their tactics of accusing Istook opponents of
religious bigotry smacks of old-time McCarthyism,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows how far the far right has gone when it is now
anti-American to defend the Bill of Rights,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Many members said Wednesday they remained undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said he is not surprised at that, because the measure is
politically sensitive. He said several of his colleagues have told
him they would vote for the measure because they know it won't
pass.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In Edwards' district, more than 100 pastors are involved in the
public awareness campaign to support the amendment, according to
Joe Carbajal, who works with the Christian Coalition in central
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Carbajal, pastor of the non-denominational Mighty Wind Worship
Center in Waco, said the amendment will ensure that children won't
be punished for practicing their religion at school.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents say motives behind the measure are not
ideological, but political. They say it will give the far right a
chance to paint their opponents as ``voting against God.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote will be featured on the Christian Coalition's voting
scorecard, which will be distributed to members later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said the tactics are backfiring.
</P>
<P>
   On the postcard distributed to Edwards' district, the coalition
says ``his attitudes have no place in Texas or anywhere in
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said this kind of intolerance is exactly why he opposes
the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've made my point,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
