<SLUG> BC-KAYAK-SIDE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STEEP CREEKING' TAKES SPORT TO NEW EXTREME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE NEWBERG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) - Brian Tuten could easily be classified as an
extremist. He runs waterfalls in a kayak.
</P>
<P>
   There's a term for this move, and it's not crazy, suicidal or
nuts. It's called ``steep creeking.''
</P>
<P>
   Waterfalls are a bit more than steep creeks, especially when the
tallest Tuten has run is 38 feet, at Little River Canyon in
Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Not many steep creeks exist in Arizona, though there is talk of
the ``Monsoon Warriors,'' a group of kayakers that runs washes
during summer rains.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's more a legend than anything,'' said Peter Zwagerman,
owner of Arizona's Permagrin Canoeing and Kayaking School.
</P>
<P>
   Steep creekers do their sport with a wide kayak that carries
more air than smaller models. That extra buoyancy coupled with
rounded ends on the bow and stern make landing relatively safe.
</P>
<P>
   Note the word ``relative.'' Tuten is an expert kayaker who has
built skills to enable him to do such moves in a tiny boat. He
still runs the risk of broken legs, ribs or worse every time he
does it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the thrill of running waterfalls draws him to the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing the steep creeking is the ultimate adrenaline rush,''
Tuten said. ``You can never know too much. I'm always learning.''
</P>
<P>
   Landing perfectly at the bottom in super-aerated water is ``like
landing on a pillow,'' Tuten said.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Murbach of Scottsdale, Ariz., recently returned from a
trip to Mexico where she ran waterfalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was one that was 23 feet. That was the highest one,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Proper waterfall-jumping technique includes keeping the paddle
up and away from the face, leaning back slightly to keep balanced
in the boat and putting the boat into the water at 45 degrees.
Landing flat could result in back injuries, Murbach said.
</P>
<P>
   After landing, the kayaker could get caught in the flow at the
bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one that we did on the bigger river, the hydraulic was
interesting because it took you under water and spun you around a
little,'' Murbach said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
