<SLUG> BC-SERRA-HOLOCAUST-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN ARTIST LEAVES GERMAN HOLOCAUST PROJECT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ The American sculptor Richard Serra has
abruptly pulled out of a project to design a massive and
much-debated Holocaust memorial in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Serra, who had teamed up with the American architect Peter
Eisenmann to submit a design that was strongly favored by Germany's
Chancellor Helmut Kohl, said he had quit for ``personal and
professional reasons'' that ``had nothing to do with the merits of
the project.''
</P>
<P>
   The surprising announcement by Serra, whose giant abstract works
have both enraptured and infuriated people for the last several
decades, was yet another twist in the tortuous efforts by German
leaders to build a memorial to Jewish victims on land at the heart
of Hitler's Third Reich, almost on top of the line where the Berlin
Wall once stood.
</P>
<P>
   Though Kohl and other German leaders had hoped to build a
memorial to the Holocaust in Berlin by the time the city resumes
its role next year as the capital of the reunited Germany, the
project has been bedeviled by philosophical and political battles
at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   Though German leaders have not officially decided on a design,
the proposal by Serra and Eisenmann, one of four competing designs,
has been the clear favorite of Kohl and of the nonprofit
organization that has led the decade-long effort to build a
memorial.
</P>
<P>
   As envisioned by the two Americans, the memorial would feature a
forbidding labyrinth of 4,000 huge pillars that would sprawl over
an area of 180,000 square feet. It would be located between
Berlin's Brandenburg Gate and Potsdamer Platz, the huge new
commercial and office complex being built on what used to be the
no-man's-land between East and West Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Much like the years of debate in the United States over building
the memorial to Vietnam veterans in Washington, the proposed Berlin
memorial has engendered endless argument and infighting over both
details and fundamental philosophical issues.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, German leaders almost selected an entirely separate
design for the memorial that consisted of a huge tilting slab of
concrete that was to have been covered with the names of 4.2
million known victims of the Holocaust. Kohl vetoed that design in
1996 and a new competition led to the selection of the four
competing designs, including that of Serra and Eisenmann.
</P>
<P>
   But the arguments did not end. Many critics argued that the
design should include names of victims, as well as the numbers of
people killed and the places where the killings occurred. Several
months ago, a group of leading German intellectuals, including
Germany's best-known writer, Guenter Grass, argued that the
monument should be abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   The opponents of a memorial argued that no artistic monument
could faithfully represent the full horror of the Holocaust, and
that the new monument would be an ``abstract installation of
oppressively gigantic proportions'' that would be ``neither a
witness to the past nor a sign to the future.'' The letter said the
memorial should include other groups persecuted by the Nazis, such
as Gypsies, homosexuals, Soviet prisoners of war and the disabled.
Others are proposing that instead of building a monument, Berlin
should rename Potsdamer Platz ``Juden Platz'' or ``Jews' Place.''
</P>
<P>
   It remained unclear on Wednesday whether Serra's unexpected
withdrawal would lead to further delays in the memorial. In a
statement issued by Serra's dealer, the Gagosian Gallery in SoHo,
the sculptor said he continued to support the design. Eisenmann
said he would proceed on his own and that the design was nearly
complete.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``As far as we're concerned, the project is more than either
Richard Serra or Peter Eisenmann,'' the architect said. ``In 50
years, nobody will remember who the artist and the architect
were,'' Eisenmann added, dismissing the matter as ``a tempest in a
teapot.''
</P>
<P>
   Lea Rosh, head of the nonprofit organization that has lobbied
for a Holocaust museum since 1988, said Serra's decision would not
cause a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is important is that Eisenmann stands by his proposal and
that his design is finally put on display,'' Ms. Rosh said on
Wednesday
</P>
<P>
   A decision on the memorial has already been delayed for several
months, and proponents are now hoping to reach a final agreement by
the end of June. But Kohl is still insisting on numerous changes,
though Eisenmann has indicated he can accommodate the requests.
</P>
<P>
   Berlin's mayor, Eberhard Diepgen, remains opposed to all of the
final four designs and is supposed to have a say in the ultimate
decision. Diepgen, who has been lukewarm about the project all
along, recently questioned whether any monument could ``deal with
this horror artistically.''
</P>
</TEXT>
