A2649 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARLOW-HARVARD-BOS &LR;      06-03 1718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARLOW-HARVARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYBERSPACE GURU JOHN PERRY BARLOW GOES TO COLLEGE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE _ John Perry Barlow is walking slowly and almost
daintily along John F. Kennedy Street near Harvard Square, as if
his black cowboy boots are too tight. ``Have you ever had a sake
hangover?'' he asks, his sandpaper voice a few grades coarser than
normal.
</P>
<P>
   When his companion allows as how he can't remember, Barlow
scowls darkly. ``If you'd had one,'' he announces, ``you'd
remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is life in meatspace, which is how Barlow, the 50-year-old
Internet guru and techno-libertarian who used to raise cows in
Wyoming and write songs for the Grateful Dead, refers to the
nonvirtual world. Lately much of his own time in meatspace  &UR; xr &LR; has
been spent at Harvard University, where he recently completed an
associate fellowship at the Kennedy School of Government's
Institute of Politics before landing a similar gig at the Harvard
Law School's Berkman Center for Internet and Society. ``If I'm not
younger, smarter, and better-looking by the time I leave here, I
haven't taken advantage of the situation,'' he muses.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't feel this way a few months ago. ``He expected people
here to be closed-minded and arrogant,'' says Berkman Center
professor Lawrence Lessig, a cutting-edge scholar on cyberspace and
the law. ``But he didn't find that at all.''
</P>
<P>
   What he found instead was that he could wander into a place like
Grendel's Restaurant &AMP; Bar in Harvard Square for dinner, make some
new friends among the graduate students hanging out there, and
repair to a dorm room for some long hours of conversation while
knocking back a few glasses of that sake.
</P>
<P>
   ``My preconceptions of Harvard students, based on visits here
during the 1960s and '70s, are no longer valid,'' Barlow says.
``The culture has changed considerably. It's a true meritocracy
now. The reason people are here is because they're smart and
they're diligent in applying their intelligence, not because eight
generations of their forebears came here and they know exactly how
to get their clothes fitted at Brooks Brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; if,,.07l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In addition to this glowing report card, Harvard is getting what
Lessig _ who is also the court-appointed ``special master'' in the
US government's antitrust suit against Microsoft Corp. _ calls ``a
towering figure in the first generation of thinking about how to
deal with cyberspace.'' The university is also experiencing what he
terms a ``Wyoming/Republican character,'' something of a Robert
Preston look-alike who rides a motorcycle while spitting out the
word ``government'' as if it were an unexpected chicken bone.
</P>
<P>
   Ironic, isn't it, that Barlow this year found himself holding
court at one of the country's foremost schools of government? ``Oh,
there's plenty of irony there,'' answers the cofounder of the
Electronic Frontier Foundation, a group that promotes freedom of
expression in digital media and has been major thorn in the side of
the US government whenever it has tried to put a leash on
cyberspace. ``But I love irony. I mean, I'd like to dramatically
reduce the number of lawyers in the world and here I am at a school
of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Here he is indeed, dressed typically in black _ invariably
including a scarf _ a cyberitic Paul Revere riding to warn the
populace of the danger of those redcoats down in Washington. (He
usually votes for ``one wing nut or another'' in national
elections, he says.) In the course of several conversations, the
self-described ``old hippie,'' registered Republican, and divorced
father of three daughters comes across as insightful, combative,
articulate, grandiose, charming, holier-than-thou, egotistical, and
self-effacing. At one moment he declares, ``I think I have the same
sense of inevitability that Marx must have had all the time because
I'm so certain I'm right about a lot of this stuff.'' But remember
that he's also &UR;  &LR; been known to refer to what he does as ``cyberspace
jiving.''
</P>
<P>
   And listen, you want irony? One of America's most wired
individuals _ this high-profile writer, lecturer, and consultant on
digital media _ often scribbles messages to himself not on a
personal digital assistant (PDA) but on the palm of his hand.
``This is the original PDA,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Barlow's rants and raves are nothing if not strongly felt. He
rants against television, suburbia, and especially government
regulation of communications. (The only way in which the federal
government should possibly mess with the Net, he says, is by wiring
public libraries.) Meanwhile, he raves about the value of
close-knit communities, whether they exist in cyberspace or
meatspace. Regarding this particular belief he is likely to fall
back on Friedrich Nietzsche, declaring solemnly that ``sin is that
which separates.''
</P>
<P>
   But he can also sound like Hunter Thompson, particularly when he
declares, say, that the US government is no longer a democracy but
has become ``government by hallucinating mob, driven mad by
television.'' There's some Timothy Leary in there too: ``I've been
trying to expand consciousness by whatever means are available to
me, whether it's writing Grateful Dead songs or trying to wire the
consciousness of the planet with the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   To borrow from a Dead song Barlow didn't write, ``What a long
strange trip it's been.'' ``When I was growing up, one could
imagine being a fireman or a businessman or a movie star, or
whatever,'' he says. ``One could not have imagined being an
Internet guru.''
</P>
<P>
   The only child of third-generation Wyoming cattle ranchers,
Barlow was a devoted Mormon until the age of 14, whereupon he lost
his faith and found a motorcycle. His father, who was president of
the state Senate and also ran the powerful statewide cattle
association, was so unimpressed that he shipped the boy off to prep
school in Colorado. Young Barlow later majored in comparative
religion at Wesleyan University in Connecticut, avoided the
military draft by forging a letter from a doctor, wrote poetry, and
spent a year in India. He then set off for San Francisco to become
what he calls, borrowing from a Rolling Stones song, ``an under
assistant West Coast promotion man'' in the recording business.
</P>
<P>
   He never got there. The 7,000-acre Bar Cross Land &AMP; Livestock
Co., his family's spread in tiny Pinedale, Wyo., (population: about
1,200) was having management difficulties, so he decided to spend
six months straightening matters out. He stayed 17 years. He not
only raised cows and calves, but also, as he puts it, ``developed a
reputation as a place where you could send your highly potentiated
but basically miscreant kid'' to work. (John F. Kennedy Jr., he
says, came for a while in 1978.) He became county chairman of the
Republican Party and lost a race for state Senate by a single vote.
He also began writing tunes with an old prep school buddy, Bob Weir
of the Grateful Dead. Over a two-decade period, he would co-write
more than a dozen songs that would be recorded by the Dead, the
best known _ and his personal favorite _ being ``Cassidy.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Barlow sold the Bar Cross in 1987, he'd found
cyberspace. He landed there after learning that hard-core Grateful
Dead fans, a.k.a. Deadheads, were communing together on ARPANET,
later known as the Internet. He'd purchased an early Compaq
computer that ``looked like a sewing machine,'' and when he first
went on line he was astounded by what he found:
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to myself, `Whoa, this is like a small town. This is
like a restoration of everything I care about. This is not
televisionland. This is not suburbia. This is the beginning of
another future.' That's what I thought. And I was right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't misunderstand. It's not like it's a substitute for a
community. I mean, it ain't no Amish barn-raising. But it is a
means to a real connection, so that people can come together in
cyberspace and break through the tension of separation. See, my
purpose in life is to connect everything to everything else, to
make people understand that we are one and that there is no such
thing as being alone.''
</P>
<P>
   There was something else that attracted Barlow to cyberspace,
something more practical. ``I felt,'' he says, ``that I could
become as much an expert on it as anyone, and pretty quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   So he did. He became a writer, lecturer, consultant, and
pontificator. He was the first person to popularize the term
``cyberspace'' to refer to the nexus of computer and
telecommunications networks. (Although science fiction writer
William Gibson apparently coined the word.) He helped fire up the
Electronic Frontier Foundation. He wrote the much-circulated
``Declaration of the Independence of Cyberspace,'' thereby
declaring a new ``civilization of the mind.'' He gained a
reputation as a Net hypester as well as a Net hipster, someone who
saw limitless good in cyberspace. It's an estimation of himself he
finds inaccurate. ``To say that the Internet is going to bring
nothing but good is like saying the weather is going to bring
nothing but good,'' he fusses.
</P>
<P>
   At Harvard's Kennedy School earlier this semester, he taught a
weekly study group called Cyberspace vs. Meatspace and participated
eagerly in the social aspects of a fellowship program one staff
member described as ``an intellectual Club Med.'' (His duties at
the Law School have yet to be defined by the administration.
Yesterday Barlow himself declared his title to be ``Emissary and
Gadfly.'') He talked, as he often does, about the inevitable fall
of the world's federal-level governments, about the rise of a kind
of libertarian Net Nation, and especially about how the new
information economy will totally renegotiate the planet's current
power relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, look at the relationship between men and women,''
he says. ``Traditionally, women have been economically unempowered.
But women are naturally advantaged (in cyberspace) because they
know about relationships and consensus-making. They aren't
physically disadvantaged, because strength doesn't matter. And they
aren't threatened, because they're separated physically. So I think
women will do pretty well in cyberspace.''
</P>
<P>
   So will John Perry Barlow. He already has.
</P>
</TEXT>
