<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-DAVIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS DEFEATS BIG MONEY, FACES LUNGREN IN BIG FOR GOVERNORSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY and ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Lt. Gov. Gray Davis grabbed a victory few would
have envisioned three months ago, trouncing the best-financed
gubernatorial candidates in U.S. history to win the Democratic
nomination and the chance to take on the Republican candidate,
Attorney General Dan Lungren.
</P>
<P>
   Dismissed by political insiders as too dull, Davis ran a steady
campaign built on a powerful slogan _ ``Experience money can't
buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bland ambition defeated two wealthy Democratic challengers,
former Northwest Airlines co-chairman Al Checchi and U.S. Rep. Jane
Harman.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Davis campaign spent about $12 million, nearly a
record, Davis didn't come close to his rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The race for California governor has cost an astonishing $64
million so far, with five months to go before the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning at the Biltmore Hotel in Los Angeles, the
losing candidates joined Davis to promise a united front against
Lungren.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a strong, united party that is headed for victory in
November,'' Davis said. ``I'm very proud to head a strong ticket
that's going to win from top to bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   Harman said, ``Gray, you won a stunning victory yesterday. You
are going to lead our state to prosperity in the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Checchi praised Davis' ``wealth of experience, intelligence and
tenacity.'' But when asked whether he would support Davis
financially, Checchi responded curtly, ``Next question.''
</P>
<P>
   He later stormed out of the hotel, declining to answer
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, after the outcome was clear, Davis told a
cheering crowd of supporters, ``My friends, this is truly an
experience money can't buy.''
</P>
<P>
   During his expensive campaign, Checchi promised dramatic change,
but his message failed to resonate in a state experiencing
prosperity. Harman ran as the only woman in the race, but her
reliance on gender politics seemed dated.
</P>
<P>
   Davis sold his government experience, and it seemed like the
right message in this state of 33 million.
</P>
<P>
   Davis captured 35 percent of the vote, while Checchi received
almost 13 percent and Harman 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren, the Republican, tallied 34 percent. Tuesday's primary
was the first in which California voters could cast a ballot for
any candidate, regardless of party affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Gov. Pete Wilson, who has served two terms, was
barred from seeking another term.
</P>
<P>
   It was a remarkable victory for the Bronx-born Davis, who
survived the removal of a benign brain tumor 14 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Just three months ago, Davis looked destined for political
obscurity, after a solid but uninspired 24-year career as state
assemblyman, controller and, since 1995, lieutenant governor.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime Democrats didn't take his fund-raising calls, reporters
largely ignored him and early in the campaign, he didn't have
enough money to run television commercials. He was behind in the
polls. Even former California Republican Chairman John Herrington
was encouraging Republicans to vote for Davis so Lungren would face
a weak opponent in November.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his two well-financed Democratic opponents, Davis
captured a higher percentage of the popular vote Tuesday than
Lungren, who ran nearly $5 million in biographical commercials who
faced only token opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``You defied the experts,'' Davis told jubilant supporters at
the Biltmore. ``You proved the pundits wrong, and you know what? I
think we're gonna win again in November!''
</P>
<P>
   An exit poll conducted by the Los Angeles Times found Davis also
benefited from the $20 million effort to defeat Proposition 226,
which would have restricted the use of union dues for political
lobbying.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever an anti-226 phone bank worker called up a potential
voter during the past few weeks, the campaign worker also reminded
people to vote for Davis. The AFL-CIO produced a campaign brochure
for Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Checchi bet nearly $40 million that he could win the nomination
by appealing to the state's surging numbers of independent voters,
moderate Republicans and Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, voters went for the familiar _ a longstanding liberal
Democrat and a conservative Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Although Davis and Lungren both plan breaks, the November
campaign is expected to begin right away. In some ways, it already
has.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren is anxious to associate Davis with the last Democratic
governor, Jerry Brown, who was elected Oakland's mayor Tuesday.
Davis worked as Brown's chief of staff, and he has repeatedly
mentioned his old boss on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``He obviously thinks it's important to be identified with Jerry
Brown,'' Lungren said. ``If that's what he wants, then fine. I'll
be happy to acknowledge that.''
</P>
<P>
   Each candidate carries enough political baggage from a combined
44 years of public service that the campaign could get ugly.
</P>
<P>
   While Lungren paints Davis as a bleeding-heart liberal aligned
with Jerry Brown, Davis will hit Lungren for his anti-abortion
stand and for questionable enforcement of the state's
assault-weapons law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have an honest, straightforward debate on the
issues,'' Lungren told cheering supporters in Newport Beach. ``We
will show two visions of California. ... Let's make sure that we
have a campaign that's based on issues, that talks about what the
people of California want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Lungren already has asked for a series of debates with the
Democratic nominee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
