<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERYMAN-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EVERYMAN': MORALITY MADE JUST A BIT TOO PRECIOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-1243 or 1927.)  
(Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(js) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the Royal Shakespeare Company's revival of
``Everyman,'' the 15th-century morality play, Beauty wears one red
high heel, Strength sports a weight lifter's belt and Goods flashes
a wad of bills.
</P>
<P>
   They are among the allegorical figures who meet up with Everyman
on his journey to death, characters on whom the directors, Kathryn
Hunter and Marcello Magni, can't refrain from bestowing modernist
touches. Sometimes, the embellishment gets carried away, and it
appears as if the ghost of ``Godspell'' has arrived. ``This matter
is wondrous precious,'' a character observes, and given some of the
sillier bits of business _ like having Everyman's relatives speak
with Italian accents _ you think you know exactly what she means.
</P>
<P>
   Although the tinkering is, on the whole, restrained, it's too
bad that the company felt the need to toy at all with ``Everyman,''
which is being presented through Sunday at the Brooklyn Academy of
Music's Majestic Theater. What's best about the piece, popular with
college theater groups and medievalists alike, is its stark
simplicity; the primitive directness puts you in mind of a
children's play.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the work, believed to have been written around the time
Columbus discovered the New World, was unusual among the English
morality plays of the period, like ``The Castle of Perseverance''
and ``Mankind,'' because it did not require the kind of elaborate
costume or scenery changes to which audiences 500 years ago had
grown accustomed.
</P>
<P>
   This version works well whenever the company takes its cue from
the past, and plays it straight. ``Everyman'' is a poignant story
about that task that puts us all on equal footing, coming to terms
with mortality. Upon receiving news of his fate from Death,
portrayed enchantingly by Josette Bushell-Mingo as a kind of virgin
deceiver, Everyman (Joseph Mydell) sets off on the adventure during
which he must undergo various trials and sacrifices before he can
achieve the state of grace.
</P>
<P>
   The play is mostly taken up with Everyman's struggles with
actors posing as embodiments of abstract concepts (Confession, Good
Deeds, Five Wits) who are either aids or impediments in his quest.
Often, the actors are encouraged not to trust the text, and they
search inappropriately for moments in which they can turn up the
volume. Some of their inventions are effective: Everyman's
back-slapping friend, Fellowship (the excellent Edward Woodall), is
accompanied by a two-piece band, and God (Paul Hamilton) is drolly
conjured as a stringy-haired curmudgeon.
</P>
<P>
   At other times, however, the conceits can seem transparent, Rosa
Maggiora's parched set places ``Everyman'' on the plateau of a
timeless, sunbaked sierra, where the minimal adornments include a
woodshed and, wholly unnecessarily, a Jesus figurine. (Yup, it's
about religion, we get it.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is enough of the sweetly unvarnished framework of
the play to sustain this ``Everyman'' as a humbly inviting
experience. The cast is uniformly nimble; Mydell is a dignified,
though at times a bit affected, Everyman. And despite the
late-20th-century padding, the play remains an absorbing window
into a creative mind of the late Middle Ages.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `EVERYMAN'
</P>
<P>
   The anonymous 15th-century morality play. Directed by Kathryn
Hunter and Marcello Magni; sets by Rosa Maggiora; lighting by Chris
Davey; music director, Ben Livingstone; movement, Toby Sedgwick;
sound by Tim Oliver; sound re-creation by Martin Slavin. The Royal
Shakespeare Company presented by the Brooklyn Academy of Music,
Bruce Ratner, chairman of the board; Harvey Lichtenstein, president
and executive producer. At the Majestic Theater, 651 Fulton Street,
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   With: Joseph Mydell (Everyman), Josette Bushell-Mingo (Death,
Kindred, Knowledge and Charlatan Priest), Paul Hamilton (God,
Goods, Strength and Charlatan Priest), Myra McFadyen (Nin, Good
Deeds and Charlatan Priest) and Edward Woodall (Fellowship, Five
Wits, Angel and Charlatan Priest). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 1745EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
