<HEADER>
A2660 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT &LR;      06-03 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FICTIONAL' WAR OF THE SEXES 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why can't a woman write like a man? Or perhaps more precisely,
why is it perceived that in serious fiction male writers have
grander thoughts and crisper styles? Why do so many reviewers and
editors act as if male and female literary writers have genetically
staked out their own neighborhoods of vocabulary and concerns, like
street gangs?
</P>
<P>
   These questions were the talk of book publishing last week
because of a critical essay in the June issue of Harper's magazine
by Francine Prose which asked, ``Are Women Writers Really
Inferior?''
</P>
<P>
   That question has passionately concerned serious female writers
since they began publishing their work. Hence, the male pseudonyms
George Sand and George Eliot.
</P>
<P>
   For female writers of literary fiction, the implications of the
question whiz by dangerously, as Ms. Prose pointed out. Perhaps
most important historically was, who is doing the judging of
literature in general? Which led naturally to, who decided that the
subjects women mostly wrote about (before their breakout in the
workplace) and still often write about _ domestic issues, love _
are of less consequence then the depth of thought produced by male
writers?
</P>
<P>
   In short, who determined the difference in importance between a
woman's inner or outer life and a man's? The answer, until recently
at least, has been men.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Prose attacked the perception that there is a discernible
womanly prose style, which is emotional and sentimental, for
instance, as opposed to the more muscular cadence of sentences by
men.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Galassi, editor-in-chief at Farrar Straus &AMP; Giroux,
which publishes much literary fiction, tends to agree that often
such generalizations about writing style are nonsense. ``There's
all those male weepers out there writing, who tend to be very
sentimental about themselves,'' he said. ``When you read Pat
Barker'' _ the award-winning English fiction writer _ ``you can't
tell her gender unless you have the title page in front of you. A
great author is usually recognized as great.''
</P>
<P>
   Why is all this important other than as a cerebral exercise?
Because it all gets back to what is important in any business,
including that of making books: cash.
</P>
<P>
   The success of a literary novel most often depends on the high
wire of reviews, which in turn helps feed word-of-mouth. So good
reviews for a first novel can mean that the writer will more easily
get a second novel published with a higher advance. From that seed,
a career can be born that can make money for both the author and
the publisher. (Literary prizes also help, and Ms. Prose feels
women get shorted on those too.)
</P>
<P>
   Book publishing at the editorial level is largely dominated by
women. And The New York Review of Books has a woman co-editor, and
the editors of The Washington Post and Chicago Tribune weekly book
review sections are women.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, despite this woman power, Ms. Prose had statistics
to show that more literary fiction written by men was reviewed than
that written by women, and that indeed more actual reviews of books
in the weekly journals were written by men than by women.
(Moreover, she was critical of The New Yorker and Harper's magazine
for printing many more short stories written by men than women.)
</P>
<P>
   All this criticism despite the fact that most people in
publishing believe that more literary fiction is still written by
men than women. The evidence, however, is largely inferential.
</P>
<P>
   The Harper's essay was particularly critical of The New York
Times Book Review and The New York Review of Books for the
discrepancy between the number of books of literary fiction written
by men or women and the number that were actually reviewed, and by
the disparity between the number of reviews written by men compared
to the number by women. The Times was also criticized for not
giving serious fiction by women enough prominence in its ``editor's
choice'' selections.
</P>
<P>
   This Sunday The Times Book Review is reviewing seven works of
fiction, five by men and two by women. Three of the seven books are
reviewed by women, including the cover review, which was written by
Ms. Prose. Three of the four books topping The Times's hardcover
fiction best-seller list this Sunday were written by women,
including Anna Quindlen's ``Black and Blue'' (Random House), which
is No. 4 and decidedly literary fiction. Last Sunday The Times
reviewed six works of fiction, three by women. Three of the
reviewers were women.
</P>
<P>
   But that's two weeks in many, and Charles McGrath, editor of The
Times Book Review, said that the number of women reviewers ``is
roughly in proportion to the number of women writers, not that we
say a woman has to review a woman writer's book.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that ``we are aware of what appears to be a pattern of
more male reviewers, and we don't think it's a good one and we are
trying to examine our decisions to be sure we are not falling into
the pattern.'' He added that ``when we pick the best books we try
to judge them on their merits.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Epstein, co-editor of the New York Review of Books, said
that ``I hate to comment. I like Francine. To refute it would take
many hours of work.'' Repeated attempts over nearly three days to
get comment from her co-editor, Robert B. Silvers, failed. But the
June 11 issue had 16 contributors, five of them women. There were
26 reviews and articles, with eight of them reviews of books
written by or articles about women. Included was a review of the
Nobel laureate Toni Morrison's ``Paradise'' (Knopf). In the issue
dated May 28 all 12 contributors were men.
</P>
<P>
   If Ms. Prose is correct, is it because of prejudice or even lack
of attention? No to the first, perhaps yes to the second. Nina
King, editor of The Washington Post Book World, said: ``I think we
are guilty but not intentionally. It's probably a very complicated
psychological predilection, coming from our whole culture. There
are still more men in power and influence and it probably trickles
down to what we review and who reviews.'' She said that several
years ago her review conducted an ``informal count of male versus
female, of blacks, of all minorities, and females were way
under-represented as authors and reviewers. We decided the only way
to correct it was to be more conscious of the problem, and I hope
we succeeded.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite such good intentions, many women authors of
serious fiction are outraged at what they perceive to be their
treatment in book review journals, and one woman connected to a
most prestigious review weekly said that she was sure there
remained in reviewland the attitude toward women that the Jack
Nicholson character expressed in the movie ``As Good as It Gets.''
The actor, playing the part of a grumpy writer, when asked by a
literary groupie how he managed to write so knowingly about women
replied: ``I think about a man, and I take away reason and
accountability.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 1747EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2662 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROUDABOUT-THEATER-2TA     06-03 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROUDABOUT-THEATER-2TAKES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROUNDABOUT'S RED INK GIVES WAY TO A HEALTHY GLOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-1243 or 1927.)  
(gm) 
 By RALPH BLUMENTHAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ These are sweet times for the Roundabout Theater
Company, the comeback kid of Off Broadway and Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years after filing for bankruptcy, 15 years after voting
to close its doors only to escape extinction by a last-minute gift,
a company that staged its first plays in a supermarket basement
with 150 seats has become a producing powerhouse, the nation's
second biggest nonprofit theater after Lincoln Center's.
</P>
<P>
   It has three hits on Broadway, many new productions in the
wings, an annual audience of 400,000 and a blanketing presence at
this Sunday's Tony Awards ceremony, much of which is credited to a
management-trained artistic director whose only performing
experience was the title role in a P.S. 6 kindergarten version of
``Mary Poppins.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically I'm incredibly insecure and don't take myself
seriously as an artist,'' said the director, Todd Haimes, 42, in a
recent series of interviews. ``But somehow my taste seems to match
up with what the public wants.''
</P>
<P>
   The Roundabout formula now includes a growing number of new
works by successful contemporary playwrights like Beth Henley and
Paula Vogel as well as offbeat musical revivals like the coming
``Little Me,'' along with the theater's more predictable repertory
of classic drama _ Shaw, Ibsen, Strindberg, Williams and Miller.
The Roundabout has also courted a younger audience, with
subscriptions at prices about half those on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   With three big revivals on Broadway _ ``Cabaret,'' ``1776'' and
``A View From the Bridge'' _ the Roundabout has also just begun
previewing a new play, ``Side Man,'' on one of its two stages at
Criterion Center on Broadway at 45th Street, where two other
productions recently ended their 12- and 15-week runs.
</P>
<P>
   Three new productions _ the Henley and Vogel plays and a new
Harold Pinter play _ and three revivals are to follow over the next
year. The company is also planning a move in the fall of 1999 to a
new home in the refurbished 1918 Selwyn Theater on West 42d Street,
down the block from two entertainment behemoths, Disney and Livent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cabaret,'' playing to sellout crowds in a dissolute
mock-Berlin Kit Kat Klub on West 43d Street, has become perhaps the
hottest ticket on Broadway, a celebrity rendezvous where Roundabout
subscribers find themselves knee to knee at cafe tables with the
likes of Steven Spielberg, Madonna, Mel Brooks and Anne Bancroft,
Mikhail Baryshnikov and Walter Cronkite. (Baryshnikov and Cronkite
were pulled up onstage on different nights to dance with the
raunchy master of ceremonies, played by Alan Cumming.)
</P>
<P>
   And now come the Tonys. Crowning what has been its most
commercially successful season since its debut in 1966,
Roundabout's three Broadway productions have been nominated for 17
Tony Awards in 14 of the 21 categories, including best play and
musical revivals, best direction and best leading and featured
actors and actresses. The winners will be announced on Sunday in a
televised ceremony at Radio City Music Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm jealous of them _ don't quote me,'' said Bernard Gersten,
executive producer of Lincoln Center Theater, which has three
nominations this year, for ``Ah, Wilderness!'' and ``Ivanov.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' he said, ``you can quote me.'' (In 1988, three Lincoln
Center productions were nominated for 18 Tonys, winning four, for
``Anything Goes'' and ``Speed-the-Plow.'')
</P>
<P>
   The Roundabout's $17 million annual budget is exceeded only by
Lincoln Center's $21 million theater budget. Of the $17 million, a
full 80 percent is covered by ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   While the Roundabout has had its share of flops and missteps _
it recently yanked a scheduled musical, ``What the World Needs
Now,'' with songs by Burt Bacharach and Hal David, substituting
``Side Man'' _ and it has never sought distinction as a
particularly experimental theater, its rebound has drawn interest
and envy in a struggling industry where success stories stand out.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've done a very good job of identifying their audience,''
said Rocco Landesman, president of the Jujamcyn theater chain, who
admitted to mixed feelings about competing for Tonys against
nonprofit theaters aided by public funds.
</P>
<P>
   The Roundabout also appears to exemplify a trend toward a firmer
business hand at the controls. Some leading nonprofit theaters,
Lincoln Center's and the Manhattan Theater Club among them, have
divided the directorship into artistic and management components.
</P>
<P>
   In the Roundabout's case, it comes down to the same person, the
soft-spoken, hard-driving Haimes, whose background _ his title of
artistic director notwithstanding _ is more in business than in
art.
</P>
<P>
   A liberal arts graduate of the University of Pennsylvania who
went through the Yale School of Management, Haimes is widely
credited with stanching the flow of red ink and blending a
repertory that draws audiences and by and large commands critical
respect, if not always raves. He does this over long days and
nights, time spent away from his wife, Alison, a neuro-radiologist,
and their daughter, Hilary, 11, and son, Andrew, 9.
</P>
<P>
   Associates say Haimes's personable manner has won him strong
staff and artist loyalty. Rob Marshall, the co-director, with Sam
Mendes, and choreographer of ``Cabaret,'' who has been nominated
for two Tony Awards and is directing the theater's fall ``revisal''
_ a combination revision and revival _ of the Neil Simon and Cy
Coleman musical ``Little Me,'' said Haimes had given artists a
great sense of freedom and support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Todd takes characters and actors and puts them in a room and
says, `Go play,''' Marshall said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   In the past, some critics have faulted the Roundabout as overly
tried-and-true, an indictment that Haimes challenges as no longer
applicable, if it ever was.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take enormous risks,'' he said, citing plays like ``London
Assurance'' that ``if we don't do, are not going to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Had `1776' flopped, it would have devastated us,'' he said. In
fact, it became the theater's biggest success, with ticket sales of
$2 million in 17 weeks before moving to Broadway. That show and ``A
View From the Bridge'' have been licensed to commercial producers
for their Broadway runs; the Roundabout is itself presenting
``Cabaret'' in space subleased from a nightclub that has taken over
the Henry Miller Theater, a location that took Haimes four years to
find. Yet, he said, with the capacity limited to 500 seats,
``Cabaret'' would have to sell out for a year and a half before the
costs are recovered.
</P>
<P>
   For all the luster of the theater's prospects today, they were
bleak indeed when Haimes arrived as managing director in 1983, at
age 26, from two years of managing the Hartman Theater in Stamford,
Conn.
</P>
<P>
   The Roundabout _ founded in 1965 by a director, Gene Feist, and
his wife, Elizabeth Owens, an actress, and installed first in the
basement of a supermarket on West 26th Street, then in an RKO movie
house on West 23d Street _ had filed for bankruptcy in 1978. By
1983 it had run up a $2.5 million deficit, the equivalent of a
year's budget. Two weeks after Haimes arrived, the directors voted
to shut down altogether. That day, too, his mother died.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew they were in Chapter 11,'' Haimes recalled. ``I didn't
know they were completely out of money.'' The only bright side, he
said, was that things were so bad they were ready to take a chance
on a neophyte like him.
</P>
<P>
   At the last minute, the chairman of the Roundabout board,
Christian Yegen, who ran a leasing and insurance business in New
Jersey, donated $100,000, allowing the company to continue
operating. But then the Roundabout lost its lease to its 299-seat
theater in the movie house. The following year, 1984, Haimes found
new quarters in the former Tammany Hall on 17th Street and Park
Avenue South, then owned by the International Ladies Garment
Workers Union.
</P>
<P>
   While renovations went on, the Roundabout, still in bankruptcy,
rented the Haft Theater at the Fashion Institute of Technology,
where it presented ``Joe Egg,'' with Jim Dale and Stockard
Channing. The production moved to Broadway, winning Tony Awards and
other prizes.
</P>
<P>
   By 1985, the company had moved into the 17th Street theater that
is now the Union Square Theater and emerged from bankruptcy, with
the help of a general manager, Ellen Richard, whom Haimes recruited
from his former Stamford theater. In 1989 Feist retired, and Haimes
became artistic director.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping a tight rein on expenditures, he instituted zero-base
budgeting. ``We started each year with zero and had to prove that
every expense was justified,'' he said. The deficit began to
shrink, and subscribers signed up, attracted by revivals like ``The
Crucible'' and ``The Subject Was Roses.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1990 the lease expired on 17th Street, and the company was
facing homelessness again. Haimes found new quarters in the
Criterion Center on Broadway, signing a 20-year lease on a 499-seat
theater.
</P>
<P>
   The 1992-93 season offered mixed blessings. There was an
acclaimed ``Anna Christie'' starring Natasha Richardson and Liam
Neeson, who met there and later married. (Ms. Richardson is up for
a Tony for her current role in ``Cabaret.'') There was also a
widely derided ``Hamlet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a learning curve,'' Haimes said.
</P>
<P>
   Promotionally, however, he scored with innovative marketing
programs and earlier curtains to draw after-work audiences. It took
10 years, but by 1993 the deficit was erased.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994 a second performance space opened up inside the
Criterion, and a 399-seat theater was built, affording
opportunities to present new plays as well as revivals. Between
1989 and 1995, the number of subscribers nearly doubled, to 35,000,
where it has leveled off. But with the clamor for ``Cabaret''
tickets, the Roundabout is unashamedly using the demand to woo new
subscribers and benefactors. With every seven-play package, a
subscriber can buy one ticket to ``Cabaret'' at 25 percent off.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Roundabout began discussions about moving into the
Selwyn Theater, a prospect that took on some immediacy last year
when the owner of the Criterion Center, Charles B. Moss Jr.,
reacting to rapidly rising real estate values in Times Square,
invoked a provision in the lease to prematurely terminate the
Roundabout's tenancy.
</P>
<P>
   Haimes said, however, he was grateful that the Roundabout has
been allowed to remain there for now. He said he couldn't face
another move just yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
