<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2667 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-FESTIVAL-ART-2T     06-03 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-FESTIVAL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY TONGUES EXTOL GOD IN ONE VOICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (af)  
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FEZ, Morocco _ Upraised, passionate voices sang the names of God
in Arabic, Latin, Hebrew, French, Greek, Spanish, Turkish, Hindi,
Italian, German, Gaelic, Farsi and English during the fourth Fez
Festival of World Sacred Music, presented here during the last week
of May.
</P>
<P>
   Under the giant keyhole arch and the crenellated ramparts of Bab
Mekina, one of the gates into this 1,000-year-old city, and in the
courtyard of the Batha Museum, a former sultan's palace, musicians
from four continents gathered to perform devotional songs, setting
aside doctrinal differences to praise the divine.
</P>
<P>
   On opening night, an American opera singer, Barbara Hendricks,
sang spirituals, sharing a bill with Monajat Yulcheva from
Uzbekistan, performing songs rooted in the Sufi tradition of
mystical Islam. The final two concerts, on Saturday, were given by
a Javanese gamelan group and whirling dervishes from Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   In between were performances of Greek Byzantine chants,
Andalusian Jewish songs, Indian ragas, medieval cantigas from
Spain, Celtic Christian music and songs from various traditions of
Sufism.
</P>
<P>
   Fez was founded by a Sufi saint and is considered the spiritual
heart of Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   It was a festival, by and large, of contemplative music,
centered in meditative drones and finely detailed improvisations.
The music kept returning to the human voice and the glides and
quavers that are shared by cantorial singing, Koranic chant and
plainsong; in Fez, the sound of praise was the sound of the
melisma, a single syllable sustained through many notes. And for
some performers, contemplation led to joyous release.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammed Soussi, performing under the ruins of a Roman arch in a
concert at Volubilis, 30 miles outside Fez, sang classical Arabic
poems called qasidas in music that gradually accelerated from
stately call and response to ecstatic hand-clapping rhythms and
blasts from six-foot-long trumpets.
</P>
<P>
   The Fez Festival of World Sacred Music is so unworldly that it
doesn't even offer a souvenir T-shirt for sale. But it was created
in response to a distinctly earthbound event: the Persian Gulf war
of 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, all the cultures were in great conflict because
of the media,'' said Dr. Faouzi Skali, the festival's general
director. ``I was convinced it was important to have a direct
meeting between people, not through the media.''
</P>
<P>
   His first effort was an international film festival in Fez in
1992; he called it Desert Colloquium as a direct answer to the
Desert Storm military campaign. The festival also included some
concerts of Sufi music, and the response convinced Skali that
``music could be a very good medium,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With film, there is the problem of language. But with music
there is a direct connection that can be larger and deeper. It's
not a question of what you think and don't think. It is a direct
experience of the Other.''
</P>
<P>
   So he decided to make his next gathering a music festival. He
chose sacred music, he said, because, ``It is a crossroads of so
many questions about our time.'' He added: ``It is about values,
about spirituality, about the future, about the connections between
cultures and about the identity of a culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Held in 1994, 1996, 1997 and 1998, each sacred-music festival
has drawn larger audiences. This year, bus loads of New Age
tourists from the United States and Europe sat alongside Moroccans
from across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have begun to discover what we are losing without
spirituality,'' Skali said. ``Progress has given us computers and
global markets, but no feeling, no passion, no flavor of life. Then
when we discover the beauty of spirituality and the traditions of
the sacred, it's just so strong and so deep that it reminds us of
what we have lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is impossible to live spiritually now the way people lived
many years ago, when you grew up in a tradition and it was your
universe. Now, with media and travel, we don't have that. We have
to discover a new culture of living spirituality: to be yourself
but to be aware of what's around you and to recognize the worth of
the other person.''
</P>
<P>
   The music this year came from udaism, Christianity and Islam.
(Although the Indian musicians, Begum Parveen Sultana and Ustad
Dilshad Khan, were playing in a style generally associated with
Hinduism, they adapted song texts to make Islamic references.)
</P>
<P>
   The festival also included films and academic symposiums on
subjects that included the cultures of India and Borobodur, the
great Buddhist monument in Java. But religions from Shinto to
santeria also have remarkable music associated with them, and for
the Fez festival in the year 2000 Skali hopes to have an even more
ecumenical lineup, what he called ``a great meeting of all
traditions.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The festival is devoted to styles that date back through the
centuries. ``These are ancient forms that have traveled through
time,'' said Gerard Kurdjian, the festival's artistic director, who
chooses the musicians each year. ``We live in a society in which
time is understood as an obstacle. We want to make more things in a
shorter time; we want to communicate instantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``But these forms of music are full of time. They are old forms,
but they are absolutely up-to-date. They express something coming
from the heart of the performer and from the heart and mind of a
culture, society and social group. And whether you are talking
about Sufism, Christianity or even Buddhism, they correspond to
something that crosses time and goes across all cultures.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the music at the festival was not liturgical music used
directly in religious rituals but concert music with songs about
God. ``Ritual aspects have to be performed in specific places,''
Kurdjian said. ``When you take them out of those places, they lose
their meaning. But the sacred is something much larger than the
liturgical and ritual. The thread that links them is the emotion
that all these musics provoke in the heart of the listener.''
</P>
<P>
   The festival's lineup might have been designed to argue that all
sacred styles meet in the Middle East. The Byzantine Choir of
Greece bridged Gregorian chant and Middle Eastern singing.
</P>
<P>
   Performing in a Greek Orthodox tradition that survives at the
monastic Mount Athos, the group sang in the pure-toned unison of
European plainsong, but soloists' voices took on the rougher
timbres and microtonal turns of Arabic music.
</P>
<P>
   Another European-Arabic link emerged when Begonia Olavide and
the Mudejar Ensemble, a medieval-music group from Spain, performed
cantigas written 400 to 700 years ago; the music moved between
European polyphony and the stark single lines of Arabic music,
backed by clay drum and oud.
</P>
<P>
   Laude Novella, a medieval- and Renaissance-music trio from
Sweden, performed ``In Stadio Laboris,'' a song from ancient
seminaries, with triple-time Middle Eastern-flavored rhythms; Ute
Goedecke, its singer, used a nasal delivery akin to the sound of
the oboelike ghaita used in Morocco's jajouka music. It was a
musicological coincidence; Ms. Goedecke said she had not heard
jajouka before arriving in Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   Anuna, from Ireland, used the courtyard of the Batha Museum for
antiphonal effect, deploying singers all around the audience. Its
arrangements of ancient songs, which used Far Eastern
throat-singing for drones and sometimes added strangely jazz-tinged
harmonies, were probably anachronistic, but the purity of the
voices imbued the music with reverence.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Bouhadanna, a cantor from Morocco who now officiates at a
synagogue in Paris, performed in a tradition called piyyout that
was preserved by Jews in Morocco after they were expelled from
Spain in the 15th century. Working with the Arabo-Andalusian
Orchestra of Fez, conducted by Mohammed Briouel, he sang with a
genteel intricacy in both Hebrew and Arabic.
</P>
<P>
   But the most spectacular singing came from performers in the
Sufi tradition. For many Westerners whose only exposure to Sufi
music has been the serene melodies of Turkish dervishes and the
driving, flamboyant improvisations of the late Nusrat Fateh Ali
Khan, here were other points on the spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein al-Azami, whose trip from Iraq to Fez began with a long
taxi ride from Baghdad to Amman, Jordan, brought a rich,
magisterial tone to classical Iraqi maqams, groups of songs with
plenty of room for melodic ruminations.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Yulcheva, the Uzbek singer, has taken up a repertory
formerly reserved to men; her voice was suffused with a thoughtful
tenderness, almost turning Sufi poetry into intimate revelations.
Alim Kassimov of Azerbaijan hurled his voice skyward, in grand arcs
that merged fervor and control, making every delicate ripple or
soaring phrase sound momentous.
</P>
<P>
   It was a festival of music by believers, but not for believers
alone. As virtuosity met devotion, the pleasure of music was
inseparable from the profundity of faith.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
