<HEADER>
A2673 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNIONS-IMPACT-COX &UR; 580     06-03 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIONS-IMPACT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEASURE CHEERS NATIONAL REFORMERS
</HEADLINE>
   580&AMP;ADD  CALIFORNIA VOTE AGAINST UNION-DUES &HT;     By ANDREW MOLLISON 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal campaign reformers Wednesday cheered the
defeat in California of Proposition 226, which would have reduced
the political power of unions.
</P>
<P>
   By about 53 to 47 percent, voters in the nation's most populous
state on Tuesday rejected a measure that would have required unions
to obtain permission annually from each union member before using
any part of that person's dues for political purposes.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leaders had hoped that the proposal would be
``so popular that House members would be forced to vote for it'' as
an amendment to any campaign finance bill, said Ann McBride. She is
president of Common Cause, which leads a coalition of national
advocacy groups that support a bipartisan federal bill.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's results ``really take this off the table as a
potential poison-pill amendment'' that would keep House Democrats
from voting for a bipartisan bill, said McBride, whose organization
was neutral on Prop. 226.
</P>
<P>
   The House Rules Committee will try Thursday to streamline the
House debate by agreeing on a way to eliminate some of the
record-setting 600 amendments proposed by members to 11 rival
bills.
</P>
<P>
   The fight over the California initiative was itself a prime
example of big-money politics, even though many California business
leaders stayed aloof. Some executives didn't want to pick a fight
with unions and others didn't respond as enthusiastically to
appeals from the measure's chief fund-raiser, California Gov. Pete
Wilson, as they used to before he was a lame duck.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of us (outside California) who thought it was
overblown to begin with,'' said Bernadette Budde of the
Business-Industry Political Action Committee (BIPAC), which
conducts political research for hundreds of businesses. ``Labor has
a lot more sources of political money than dues.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson did obtain some $6 million to $8 million in help from his
fellow Republicans, some tax-exempt groups and businessmen as far
away as Georgia and Pennsylvania. House Speaker Newt Gingrich of
Georgia and other Republican leaders endorsed the proposal as well.
</P>
<P>
   But exit polls showed that support for the proposition, measured
at 71 percent among union and non-union voters alike in polls last
February, slid to a statistical even split among non-union voters
and 29 percent among union voters by Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   The proposition was rejected because opponents ``spent a lot of
money and they lied about what it was about,'' said Mary Mead
Crawford, spokeswoman for the National Republican Congressional
Committee, which gave $145,000 to the losing side.
</P>
<P>
   Unions from as far away as Washington and Boston, some
tax-exempt organizations and Democrats _ who get the bulk of union
contributions _ spent about $17 million opposing the proposal, and
President Clinton and other Democratic leaders spoke out against
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the defeat of Prop. 226 will also send a message to the
United States Congress that working families and our unions are fed
up with phony campaign reform schemes and ready for the real
thing,'' AFL-CIO President John Sweeney said Wednesday afternoon.
``That means passing campaign finance reforms outlawing soft money
and slamming the lid on what contributors can give, what candidates
can spend and what political parties can accept and spend.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined to be pinned down on whether organized labor would
settle this year for a less sweeping bill sponsored by Reps. Chris
Shays, R-Conn., and Martin Meehan, D-Mass., and endorsed by the
coalition led by Common Cause.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We are monitoring the debate on campaign finance and assessing
various bills (and) amendments that are going to be introduced,''
Sweeney said. ``We will see which is going to be the best from the
point of view of the AFL-CIO.''
</P>
<P>
   McBride said that, regardless of labor's stand, she expected
House Democratic leaders to continue to round up votes for ``an
unamended Shays-Meehan bill.''
</P>
<P>
   However, several attempts at bipartisan reforms have been killed
in recent years by an unlikely alliance of Democrats who wanted
more restrictions and Republicans who wanted fewer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For use by clients of The New York Times News Service &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
