r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-SPICE-AZR &LR;      06-03 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SPICE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITHOUT GINGER, SPICE GIRLS FANS FACE BLAND FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Last Sunday won't exactly go down in history as the
day the music died. Instead, think of it as the beginning of the
end of one of pop music's fluffier chapters.
</P>
<P>
   In a tersely written statement, Geri Halliwell _ Ginger Spice to
millions of fifth-graders and ``Penthouse'' readers _ said farewell
to her bandmates and announced plans to launch a solo career.
</P>
<P>
   The thought of Gingerless Spices isn't exactly heart-wrenching.
Sure, that was her screaming ``tell me what you want, what you
really, really want!'' on the irrepressible ``Wannabe'' to assure
her place in history.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of personality among the Spices, Ginger wins hands
down. She's the cheeky one who always was carping about girl power,
the same one who gave Prince Charles a pinch on the bum. That may
not make her the John Lennon of the group, but she was the
brightest light among some pretty dim bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this is the Spice Girls. It's cotton candy. It's
marshmallows. It's helium-filled balloons with big smiley faces
painted on them. The loss of Ginger isn't akin to Diana Ross
leaving the Supremes or Stevie Nicks walking away from Fleetwood
Mac. It isn't even ABBA without Agnetha Faltskog.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, the Spice Girls was a manufactured product.
This wasn't a bunch of women who discovered they could harmonize
while hanging out in a coffee shop, no matter what image the
big-screen ``Spice World'' portrayed.
</P>
<P>
   Even the women's names _ Posh, Sporty, Scary and Baby are the
Spices that Ginger is leaving on the rack _ came from a British
teen magazine. Musical ability was not key: ``No singing or dancing
experience necessary'' read the ad that announced auditions for the
group.
</P>
<P>
   When the fivesome exploded in 1996 with its spritely
choreography, big hair and chipper personalities, it was a fully
formed phenomenon. The end result was a live-action version of
Josie and the Pussycats with flame-haired Ginger serving as a buxom
Josie.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing wrong with man-made groups. The Monkees made
some pretty sublime pop at their best before they began to splinter
apart. The Bay City Rollers? Purists may carp, but their version of
``I Only'' Want to Be With You'' was a heckuva lot more fun than
Dusty Springfield's. Even the New Kids on the Block had their
moment in the sun with the stuttered ``oh-oh-oh-oh-oh'' hook of
``(You Got It) The ``Right Stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The thing with manufactured pop is that it tends to be
imminently disposable. Little Debbie products usually have a longer
shelf life. Kids outgrow the music. The groups splinter and die,
becoming increasingly uninteresting as personnel changes occur. By
the time the Monkees were down to a trio in 1969, hardly anyone
cared.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have been predicting the end of the Spice Girls ever
since ``Wannabe'' fizzed and popped its way to No. 1. Their other
singles _ the percolating Latin rhythms of ``Spice Up Your Life,''
the dreamy make-out ballad ``2 Become 1'' _ were fine and fluffy,
just as pop should be.
</P>
<P>
   By that point, the Girls already seemed to be beating the odds.
But you can only outrun the inevitable for so long. With Ginger's
goodbye, the final act has started to begin.
</P>
<P>
   And, strangely enough, the loss of Ginger probably will cause
more damage than if any other Spice left.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Adams plays the Gucci-loving Posh Spice, the same way
the childlike Baby is a role that Emma Bunton fills. You could
replace them, the same way one mustachioed biker easily takes over
for another in the Village People. But Geri Halliwell actually is
Ginger, a chirpy, chattering British bird.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Randy Cordova can be reached at The Arizona Republic, P.O. Box 2245
NF-19, Phoenix, AZ 85002; or at randy.cordova(at)pni.com via
e-mail &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
