u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMILY-POST-STAMP-2NDT     06-03 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMILY-POST-STAMP-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
 &HT;     
 STAMPS AND POP CULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 UNDATED: be found.)  
 &HT;    The shift toward user-friendly images, of which the Elvis stamp
is still the apogee, began with the Postal Reorganization Act of
1972, which established the U.S. Postal Service as a
quasi-government agency with no taxpayer support. In the late 1970s
the Postal Service, under the aegis of the Citizens' Stamp Advisory
Committee, issued its first decorative package: a solid block of
butterflies and owls.
 &HT;    ``People went wild,'' said Mary Anne Owens, a leading collector
who recently retired from the committee. ``Before then, stamps were
primarily historical, mostly anniversaries, depending on who got
talking to their congressman,'' she said, adding, ``The post office
said, `Well, this is what the public wants.'''
 &HT;    Lighthouses, puppies and Elvis followed (the postal pelvis has
had greater retention than any U.S. stamp _ 38 million in its first
1{ years). ``It didn't take them long to realize that revenue from
stamps retained and not used was money in the bank,'' said Michael
Laurence, the editor and publisher of Linn's Stamp News.
 &HT;    ``That's how Tweety Bird and Sylvester have come to displace
George Washington and Abe Lincoln, much to the dismay of old-fogy
stamp collectors like myself.''
 &HT;    Virginia Noelke, a historian and the chairwoman of the citizens'
advisory group, said that Looney Tunes and other commercial images
raise ``serious questions'' but that the Bugs Bunny stamp is
``historically defensible.'' Bugs ``is an early bit of Americana,''
she said. ``The notion is the greater good _ to get young people
back to stamp collecting.''
 &HT;    Future stamps are likely to contain more colorful and complex
images, with a greater emphasis on photography and illustration.
Advances in printing will also affect design: Last year saw
star-shaped perforations and the first American triangle stamps.
Controversial subjects, like war, will in all likelihood continue
to be treated generically. (A 1994 proposal to depict the 50th
anniversary of the bombing of Hiroshima and Nagasaki with a
mushroom cloud aroused such furor that it was replaced by the image
of Harry S. Truman announcing the war's end.)
 &HT;    Stamps continue to be symbols of broad cultural approval,
Brinkley said. ``You won't find too many radical uneven figures,''
he said. ``You'll get Rosa Parks but probably not Stokely
Carmichael or Abbie Hoffman. The twist and Barbie dolls were not
going to undermine the status quo.'' He thinks Bob Dylan will make
his way onto a stamp and, if Al Gore becomes president, possibly
the Grateful Dead. Think of the joint marketing ventures.
 &HT;    At the recent Metropolitan Stamp Show in New York, where grown
men huddled over lamps with their magnifying glasses, the country's
fate seemed to hang in balance over the question of what is to
become of philately. ``If Tweety is what it takes to interest kids
in stamp collecting, absolutely,'' said Jeff Fishman, a dealer from
Arlington Heights, Ill. ``We're competing with high exciting things
like Nintendo and the Internet. But we wouldn't have half the
problems we have if kids stayed home and collected stamps.''
 &HT;    There were signs that Bugs might eventually endear himself to
collectors. Recently, an imperfection _ the philatelists' reason
for living _ was found on the Bugs sheet. On the decorative half of
the pane, a single stamp is inserted next to a blown-up image of
Bugs. On some sheets, however, it appears that the Postal Service
forgot to perforate that stamp. So much for being cutting edge.
 &HT;    News of the flawed Bugs has swept swiftly through the
beleaguered world of philately. ``It's much rarer than the
others,'' said Ken Lawrence, a columnist for The American
Philatelist, with a twinge of rapture, noting that imperforate
Bugses are already selling for about $150 a pane.  By BARTH HEALEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Popular culture has been a dominant international theme in
stamps for 20 years. Chad honors Einstein, Mongolia honors the
X-Men comics. When it comes to pop postage, America is way behind
tiny Antigua, where 220 stamps have been designed by Walt Disney
Co. with images ranging from Donald Duck to Sleeping Beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Disney has yet to design a stamp for the American market, but
then, the Inter-governmental Philatelic Corp., a private stamp
marketer, has Disney sewed up. That's why the Postal Service went
with Warner Brothers' Tweety and Sylvester.
</P>
<P>
   Among Inter-governmental's coups: giving the Grenadines its own
James Dean stamps, as part of a series honoring ``100 Years of
Cinema.'' Inter-governmental, founded in 1957, saw its fortunes
blossom in 1979, the United Nations International Year of the
Child, when Inter-governmental asked Disney to design appropriate
stamps. In the usual deal, said Lonnie Ostrow, the company's
director of marketing, the company collects a basic fee and a
percentage of sales of stamps outside the country producing them.
Ostrow declined to estimate the company's annual income.
</P>
<P>
   So it goes: The company has arranged Elvis Presley stamps for 36
countries (Graceland got royalties). It arranged for five countries
to mark the 20th anniversary of ``Rocky'' with Sylvester Stallone
(who, Ostrow said, got such a kick out of seeing the stamp that he
did not charge royalties). There are philatelic souvenirs of Barbra
Streisand's 1993 tour.
</P>
<P>
   Is there any cultural logic to such stamps? Yes, Ostrow said.
For example, in each country honoring ``Rocky'' _ Ghana, Gambia,
Uganda, Grenada and St. Vincent _ the film had been a big
box-office grosser. On the other hand, Inter-governmental helped
both Antigua and Lesotho issue stamps with Disney cartoon
characters celebrating the Lunar New Year.
</P>
<P>
   Ostrow insists that two regulations of the Universal Postal
Union be met in order to have the stamps declared legal tender:
that the stamps be of high quality, and that a certain number be
available in the country of issue.
</P>
<P>
   For many countries, stamps are crucial for foreign-exchange
earnings. The numbers are startling: In the 38 years since
independence, Antigua (population 65,000) has issued 2,016 stamps;
during this period, the United States (population 268 million) has
issued 2,018.
</P>
<P>
   What this has done, however, is to deny foreign countries their
patrimony. In some countries that are clients of Inter-Continental,
only half of the stamps issued honor local culture. The rest borrow
from American pop culture or present weirdly eccentric
juxtapositions.
</P>
<P>
   Once, stamps, with their engraved monochrome images of national
leaders and famous events, taught history. But there is not much
history to be learned from a handful of James Deans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
