<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MTV-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MTV MOVIE AWARDS: HONORS WITH A WINK BUT WITH NO DICAPRIO (LIVE) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.)  
 (bl)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Leonardo DiCaprio didn't show up for the Oscars ceremony
this year (some said because he hadn't been nominated as best actor
for his role in ``Titanic''), there was a little public grumbling.
</P>
<P>
   When DiCaprio didn't show up for the MTV Movie Awards last
Saturday but thanked the voters on tape for his best male
performance award, the producers followed his thank you with ``The
Making of the Leonardo DiCaprio Acceptance Speech.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The 1998 MTV Movie Awards,'' taped in Santa Monica and being
shown Thursday night, specializes in parodies. Between the awards
presentations this year, there were also takeoffs on the taxi chase
scene from ``Godzilla'' (with Christopher Lloyd in character as Jim
Ignatowski from the series ``Taxi''); ``Dawson's Creek,'' WB's hit
show about articulate teen-agers with physical needs (featuring the
series' real stars), and a pitch meeting for a ``Titanic'' sequel,
in which Ben Stiller tells James Cameron not to worry if they can't
``get Leo.'' ``You put Buddy Hackett on that boat, you got a
billion dollars, OK?'' Stiller tells him.
</P>
<P>
   This year's show isn't as consistently inspired as last year's,
but it's still a shining example of what other awards shows should
be.
</P>
<P>
   MTV starts with some unorthodox categories. John Travolta and
Nicolas Cage, for instance, were named best on-screen duo for
``Face Off.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam Sandler and Drew Barrymore received the best kiss award for
a scene in ``The Wedding Singer,'' a movie that advertised itself
as nostalgia for 1986. In his acceptance speech, Sandler thanked
his sixth-grade girlfriend for having given him kissing tips.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Myers won two awards for a dual role: as best villain in
``Austin Powers: International Man of Mystery'' and for best dance
sequence _ Austin's mod, mod London street sashay _ in the same
film.
</P>
<P>
   Only 15 awards are presented during the two-hour show, and the
MTV audience voters have definite tastes of their own. Neve
Campbell received the award for best female performance this year
for her role in Wes Craven's horror sequel ``Scream 2.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, ``Titanic'' was named best movie, in a rare
case of agreement with the Academy Awards. In the past, MTV had the
good sense to honor ``Pulp Fiction,'' when the Oscars passed it
over for ``Forrest Gump.'' (In the MTV Awards' first year,
``Terminator 2: Judgment Day'' was named best movie.)
</P>
<P>
   The MTV show's musical numbers are a lot better than those at
the Oscars, maybe because they have nothing to do with the actual
nominees for best song. This year's numbers included the
Wallflowers, with Jakob Dylan sounding particularly Dylanesque,
doing ``Heroes,'' from the ``Godzilla'' soundtrack, and Natalie
Imbruglia singing ``Torn,'' which isn't even from a movie.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Carrey, who is having an especially good week (a brilliant
turn on the ``Larry Sanders Show'' finale last Sunday and the
opening of his film ``The Truman Show'' tomorrow), received the
best comedic performance award for ``Liar Liar.'' Accepting the
award, Carrey went into character from that film, forced to tell
the truth about his own greatness. Nobody was arguing.
</P>
<P>
   The lifetime achievement award went to Clint Howard, Ron
Howard's brother and an unsung but recognizable actor specializing
in nerd roles. Previous recipients include Chewbacca, Godzilla and
Jackie Chan.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast notes:
</P>
<P>
   1998 MTV MOVIE AWARDS
</P>
<P>
   MTV, Thursday night at 9
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Gowers, director; Joel Gallen, producer; Rick Austin,
co-producer; Salli Frattini, executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Cameron Diaz, Matthew Broderick, Neve Campbell, Chris
Rock, Heather Graham, Matt Dillon, Anne Heche, Robert Downey Jr.,
Vince Vaughn, Rupert Everett, Jennifer Lopez, Jamie Lee Curtis,
Kenneth (Babyface) Edmonds, Jennifer Love Hewitt, Denise Richards
and Christina Ricci, presenters. The Wallflowers and Natalie
Imbruglia, performers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
