<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBS-CHIVES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIVES ADD ONIONY ZIP TO SALADS, MAIN DISHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROL NUCKOLS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABCs: These onion relatives have cylindrical, green, mildly
onion-flavored leaves and bluish-purple flowers. Clumps reach 12
inches in height. These perennials are native to Greece, Sweden,
the Alps regions and northern Britain; they are widely cultivated.
</P>
<P>
   Growing conditions: Rich, moist, well-drained soil and full sun
(can take some afternoon shade). Grow from transplants in early
spring or fall. Apply fish emulsion, manure or compost regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Companion plants: Roses, carrots, comfrey.
</P>
<P>
   Food pairings: Poultry; eggs; fish; vegetables; potato, chicken,
tuna and vegetable salads; salad dressing; butter; bread.
</P>
<P>
   Caveats: Slug and snail damage; may attract aphids away from
roses.
</P>
<P>
   GRILLED LAMB CHOPS WITH ORANGE-CHIVE SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   Sauce:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon canola oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped shallots
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup brandy
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced fresh chives
</P>
<P>
   1 cup orange juice
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons raisins
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons arrowroot (See note)
</P>
<P>
   Chops:
</P>
<P>
   12 loin lamb chops, each about 3/4 inch thick (about 2 pounds)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup canola oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced fresh chives
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Note: Some groceries carry arrowroot; look on the spice shelf.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare sauce, heat oil in a small skillet over medium heat.
Add shallots and cook, stirring, for about 4 minutes, or until
soft. Add brandy and chives and cook until almost all the liquid
has evaporated. Add orange juice and simmer until reduced by half.
Add raisins and cook for 3 minutes, or until plump. Mix water and
arrowroot in a small bowl and stir into skillet. Stirring
constantly, cook until sauce is thickened. Keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the grill or heat the oven broiler. Combine orange
juice, oil, chives and pepper in a small bowl. Brush both sides of
each lamb chop with mixture, and grill or broil for about 4 minutes
on each side until medium-rare. Serve with sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 413 calories, 27 grams fat, 13
grams carbohydrates, 26 grams protein, 98 milligrams cholesterol,
78 milligrams sodium, 60 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Herbal Palate Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   by Maggie Oster and Sal Gilbertie
</P>
<P>
   (Storey, $29.95)
</P>
<P>
   SPINACH AND POTATO CASSEROLE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6
</P>
<P>
   4 to 5 medium potatoes, cooked and mashed
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Dash pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   1/4 to 1/2 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons chopped chives
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon dill seed
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cooked, well-drained spinach
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup grated Cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Combine potatoes, sour cream, salt,
pepper, sugar and butter. Add enough milk to make a fluffy mixture.
Stir in chives, dill seed and spinach. Place in a greased
casserole. Sprinkle with cheese. Bake 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 293 calories, 22 grams fat, 21
grams carbohydrates, 6 grams protein, 16 milligrams cholesterol,
697 milligrams sodium, 66 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Potato Casserole''
</P>
<P>
   by Janet Reeves
</P>
<P>
   (Pelican, $14.95)
</P>
<P>
   CHEESE-CHIVE BISCUITS
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 24 biscuits
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup vegetable shortening
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup grated Cheddar or other sharp cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped fresh chives
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons (1/4 stick) butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 450 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, mix flour, baking powder and salt with a fork.
With a pastry cutter, cut in shortening until the mixture resembles
coarse crumbs. Stir in cheese and chives. Add milk and stir just
until mixture forms a soft dough that pulls away from side of bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Turn dough out onto a lightly floured surface. Knead quickly to
mix dough thoroughly. Roll dough out until it is 1/2 inch thick.
Cut out biscuits with a floured biscuit cutter and place on an
ungreased cookie sheet. Brush tops with melted butter and bake
until golden brown, 12 to 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 84 calories, 5 grams fat, 8
grams carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, 8 milligrams cholesterol, 219
milligrams sodium, 51 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cooking With Herbs''
</P>
<P>
   by Emelie Tolley and Chris Mead
</P>
<P>
   (Potter, $24)
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
