<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: NEW MUSIC; BENEFIT FOR JACOB'S PILLOW; AUCTION OF
P.G. WODEHOUSE PAPERS; SHORT STORY AWARD
</HEADLINE>
  (ja)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORKS IN PROGRESS
</P>
<P>
   New music by Augusta Read Thomas, Pierre Boulez and Wolfgang
Rihm is being commissioned by the Chicago Symphony Orchestra and
the Berlin Philharmonic Orchestra. The first of the works is a
piano concerto by Rihm, a German composer; Daniel Barenboim will be
conductor and soloist at its premiere next May at the Berlin State
Opera's new Mozart Festival Berlin. Barenboim, the music director
of the Chicago Symphony and the Berlin State Opera, took the
initiative in bringing the two orchestras together. The Berlin
Philharmonic will present the new festival in cooperation with the
Berlin State Opera. The composition by Ms. Thomas, the Chicago
Symphony's composer in residence, will receive its premiere at the
festival in June 2000. And the work by Boulez, the Chicago
Symphony's principal guest conductor, will have its premiere in
2001. Each work will receive its second performance in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   CELEBRATION ON TAP
</P>
<P>
   The Oscar, Grammy, Emmy, Tony and Golden Globe award-winning
composer Marvin Hamlisch will be among the performers when the
Jacob's Pillow Dance Festival opens its 66th season with a benefit
on June 20 on the festival grounds in Becket, Mass. Other
performers include Mark McVey of ``Les Miserables'' and principal
dancers from Ballet Hispanico. The occasion will also celebrate the
renaming of the Studio/Theater as the Doris Duke Studio Theater in
recognition of the $1 million gift to Jacob's Pillow this year by
the Doris Duke Charitable Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   FOR LAUGHS
</P>
<P>
   He created Stiffy Byng, Stilton Cheesewright, Pongo
Twistleton-Twistleton and, of course, Bertie Wooster, Jeeves and
the Empress of Blandings. He was none other than P.G. Wodehouse.
Now novels, autograph manuscripts, letters, theatrical memorabilia
and other items associated with the prolific British humorist, who
published more than 90 novels and short stories and wrote lyrics
for musicals in collaboration with Guy Bolton, Jerome Kern, Cole
Porter and the Gershwin brothers, is coming up for auction on June
26 at Sotheby's New York. More than 6,300 items in 150 lots from
the estate of James Heineman, a New York publisher, are to be sold.
</P>
<P>
   A FACT OF FICTION
</P>
<P>
   The $30,000 Rea Award for the Short Story goes this year to John
Edgar Wideman, 56, whose collections include ``Damballah'' (Avon,
1981), ``Fever'' (Henry Holt, 1989), ``The Stories of John Edgar
Wideman'' (Pantheon, 1992) and ``All Stories Are True'' (Vintage,
1993). The Rea Award was established by Michael Rea in 1986 to
honor a living U.S. or Canadian writer who has made a significant
contribution to the short story form. Wideman, whose previous
honors include a PEN/Faulkner Award for fiction and an American
Book Award for fiction, is an English professor at the University
of Massachusetts, Amherst.
</P>
</TEXT>
