<HEADLINE>
YOUTHFUL R&AMP;B ACT ON THE ROAD TO STAR DOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Only one word can capture the feeling of having a No.
1 single on the ``Billboard'' charts, touring with Boyz II Men and
having a video in heavy rotation on MTV all at the tender age of
22.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blessed,'' says Tweety, one-third of the R&AMP;B act Next.
</P>
<P>
   Next, which also includes R.L., 21, and Tweety's brother T-Low,
23, is one of the opening acts for Boyz II Men's current
three-month tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like family,'' Tweety says of the tour, which also
features Uncle Sam and K-Ci &AMP; JoJo. ``Everybody embraces each other
on the tour.''
</P>
<P>
   The masses also have been quick to embrace Next, whose single
``Too'' ``Close,'' from the album ``Rated Next,'' was just recently
certified platinum. Fresh from the Twin Cities, the trio croons
``sensual R&AMP;B'' with sometimes explicit sexual content.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a stamp on there that lets you know that some of the
songs are built with explicit content,'' Tweety says.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we try to make an album that, no matter who you are,
you'll like at least one thing on the album.''
</P>
<P>
   While some may be attracted to the lyrical content, others may
be interested in the fact that Naughty By Nature deejay Kay Gee
handles most of the production work on the album _ which was a
stroke of luck for the members of Next.
</P>
<P>
   Tweety recalls the meeting for probably the hundredth time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how they say . . . it was just being in the right
place at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   While hanging out at the Foot Locker in the Mall of America
outside Minneapolis, Tweety and T-Low spotted Naughty By Nature,
which was in town for a tour stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was like, `I know them from somewhere,' but I couldn't
really place it because it happened so fast,'' Tweety says.
</P>
<P>
   Although his brother dissuaded him from saying anything, Tweety
told himself that if he saw them again, he was going to approach
them and talk to them about their group.
</P>
<P>
   And wouldn't you know? Tweety eyed them again.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I stopped and told him our name, and he said, `Yeah, I
heard of you guys.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Tweety stopped in his tracks, amazed that a group with national
prominence had heard of them. The next night at the concert,
Tweety, T-Low and R.L. gave Kay Gee, who heads the Divine Mill
record label, a demo tape, and ``he called us back and, God bless
him, we're here today.''
</P>
<P>
   Next was the first group signed to Kay Gee's Divine Mill label,
a subsidiary of Arista Records.
</P>
<P>
   But Next has not relied solely on luck. The guys are more than
pretty faces dancing in unison on a video. They wrote nine out of
the 14 tracks on ``Rated Next,'' giving the group little worries
about being a flash in the pan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sing about what's going on around us or what we've
experienced,'' Tweety says. ``We won't have to date back years and
years and we won't get lost in the shuffle with time, because we
talk about the times.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as being young, I think that's a good thing. We're
still able to use our creative minds, and we'll only get stronger
as the years go by.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the guys have handled fame like true gentlemen, leaving
little time to act like 20-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do have to watch what you do in public because you never
know who's watching you,'' Tweety says. ``I was in a Kmart in Los
Angeles and a little boy recognized me, and as soon as I told him
who I was, he just ran off, `Mom! Mom!' I met his mother, I met his
little sister. I never thought I'd go in Kmart and be
recognized.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
