<SLUG> BC-SHEHORI-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORDECAI SHEHORI: A RECITAL INTERRUPTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mordecai Shehori, a pianist who has developed a
considerable reputation among connoisseurs, found himself unable to
finish his recital on Tuesday evening at Merkin Concert Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Shehori began the program with Beethoven's Fantasy in G minor,
playing with his typical searching intensity though experiencing
difficulty in passage work. Then he started Schumann's Fantasy in C
but fell to a halt in the fiendishly difficult second movement.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief attempt at a restart, he stood and spoke to the
audience. ``I am not feeling well,'' he said. ``I cannot continue
to play like this.'' He left the stage, but the audience stayed for
a time to applaud.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did something very stupid,'' Shehori said from his home
Wednesday, explaining that he had not taken his medication for high
blood pressure. ``It dulls my senses,'' he added, ``and I wanted to
play explosively.'' The demanding program consisted entirely of
fantasies, including Chopin's F minor Fantasy and
``Polonaise-Fantaisie'' and Balakirev's ``Islamey.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I blacked out,'' said Shehori, who is 52. ``My left hand was
not going to the right place.''
</P>
<P>
   Although nothing like this had ever happened to him before, he
said, he is haunted by the awareness that his father, an actor,
died onstage, as did one of his piano teachers. His father was 62
at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was basically saving my life,'' Shehori said.
</P>
<P>
   Shehori was born in Israel but studied at the Juilliard School
and lives in New York. His annual recitals here have a small but
committed following.
</P>
<P>
   His playing is prized by many for its individuality,
thoughtfulness and poetry despite its occasional unevenness in both
expression and technique. He has made fine recordings for
Connoisseur Society and, more recently, his own label, Cembal
d'Amour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will do this another time,'' Shehori said from the stage,
adding that ticket money would be refunded. But any future recital
plans, he said Wednesday, would have to await a clean bill of
health from his doctor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
