<SLUG> BC-AIDS-TREATMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN, MINORITIES DELAY AIDS TREATMENT, GET LESS EFFECTIVE CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EUN LEE KOH  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Women and minority men are more likely than white
men to delay seeking treatment for AIDS and they tend to receive
less effective care for the deadly disease, according to a new
study released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from the Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore and
the University of California at San Francisco found that a larger
proportion of women and minorities than white men sought treatment
for HIV, the virus that causes AIDS, after their immune system had
already broken down.
</P>
<P>
   According to the study, 36 percent of women, 42 percent of
blacks and 43 percent of Hispanics waited until their T-cell count
dipped below 500 to seek treatment while 27 percent of white men
did. T-cells are white blood cells that protect the body against
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Health and Human Services recommends treating
AIDS patients before their T-cell count dips below 500, but many of
the patients who delayed treatment had T-cells below the
recommended level. Healthy people have more than 1,000 T-cells per
one milliliter of blood.
</P>
<P>
   The study did not examine the causes for the disparity, but
researchers suggested that economics probably played a large role
in the difference in the quality of AIDS treatment that patients
receive.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Volberding, professor of medicine at UC San Francisco, said
poorer patients tend to put off treatment to avoid early medical
costs until they begin experiencing symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Women and minorities infected with HIV are generally poorer than
infected white men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early in the disease, there's almost no physical change to the
body,'' Volberding said. ``Patients mistakenly believe that just
because they seem healthy, they don't need to be treated right
away.''
</P>
<P>
   In order to slow the breakdown of the immune system, Volberding
said a patient should seek treatment immediately after being
diagnosed with HIV.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that 76 percent of women, 68 percent of
blacks and 65 percent of Hispanics infected with HIV sought care
from physicians who did not specialize in AIDS treatment, compared
to 54 percent of white men who did.
</P>
<P>
   John Bartlett, chief of infectious diseases at the Johns Hopkins
University medical school, said physicians with little experience
in AIDS treatment tend to offer their patients ``second-best''
treatment options.
</P>
<P>
   Again, researchers blamed the trend on economics.
</P>
<P>
   Volberding said physicians who specialize in AIDS treatment cost
more than those who have little or no AIDS background and are less
accessible to poor patients.
</P>
<P>
   A telephone survey of 476 physicians around the nation who had
treated at least one AIDS patient showed that doctors with minimal
AIDS background waited longer to begin treatment for their patients
and prescribed fewer medications than recommended by the U.S.
Department of Health and Human Services, according to the study,
</P>
<P>
   HHS recommends fighting HIV with at least three different types
of medicine to slow the virus in its attack of the immune system.
But some doctors in the survey said they have prescribed only one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The disparity in the treatment of HIV, especially for
particular populations, signals an urgent need to educate
physicians and patients more aggressively,'' Volberding said.
</P>
<P>
   Volberding said delayed treatment can lead to earlier death
because the disease becomes harder to treat once it develops into
full-blown AIDS and the immune system starts breaking down. There
is no cure for AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Although the federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
in Atlanta reported last January that, over-all, AIDS-related
deaths are declining for the first time since the beginning of the
epidemic in 1981, women and minority men have experienced the least
amount of decrease in AIDS-related deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC reported that the estimated number of deaths among women
fell by 13 percent in 1996 from the previous year, while among
minorities the number went down by 19 percent. The number of deaths
among white men, however, plummeted by 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A follow-up study will be conducted later this year by the two
universities to determine causes for the disparity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
