<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIREVIEWS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews of the latest sounds
 &HT;    By Eileen M. Drennen, Shane Harrison, Al Levine, and Sonia
Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Dark and Hell Is Hot''
</P>
<P>
   DMX. Def Jam Music Group.
</P>
<P>
   19 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Granted, ``anticipated'' is an overused adjective, but here it
applies. The momentum created by DMX's guest appearances on
underground tapes and the No. 2 rap single by the Lox (``Money,
Power, Respect'') had retailers ordering 800,000 copies of this
debut _ meaning that it shipped gold (500,000 copies or more). Even
better, all that dues paying says that it hit the shelves sealed in
that intangible of street credibility, a key factor in hip-hop in
these times. A line from ``Crime Story'': ``Put the harness on the
dog / Load up the weapons / Murder's on my mind / No half
stepping.'' Well, that's not necessarily true. Like Master P and
his ``ugghhhs,'' DMX barks too much. His bite is in his emotional
storytelling _ detailing nightmares as clear as day.
</P>
<P>
   -- COUNTRY
</P>
<P>
   ``Wish You Were Here''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Wills. Mercury. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   They should package a large box of tissues with this album. Mark
Wills has uncovered two of the best weepers to come out of
Nashville in years. In the title track, the woman gets her man's
postcard with just the word ``heaven'' on it right after the call
telling her that his plane has gone down. ``Don't Laugh at Me''
brings you lower. ``I lost my wife and little boy when someone
crossed that double line. / The day we laid them in the ground is
the day I lost my mind, / and right now I'm down to holding this
cardbard sign.'' But there's enough upbeat stuff on the second
album from the former house singer at the Buckboard to make this a
solid sophomore effort.
</P>
<P>
   -- DANCE / ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Mezzanine''
</P>
<P>
   Massive Attack. Virgin. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Something's afoot in Bristol, England. Massive Attack was the
originator of trip-hop, an atmospheric, fluid style that takes
hip-hop's innovations to exotic musical locales. Fellow Bristolians
Portishead and Tricky followed the Attack's lead and have created
some of this decade's most vibrant music. Now, with this third
outing, Massive Attack reasserts dominance over the competition.
Cocteau Twin Elizabeth Fraser lends her ethereal voice to three
tracks, including the gorgeous first single, ``Teardrop.'' This is
a fiercely original piece of work that's an early entry in the race
for album of the year.
</P>
<P>
   -- POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Beautiful World''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Carrack. ARK 21. 10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   With a shiny-happy keyboard backdrop that brings Bruce Hornsby
to mind, Paul Carrack and company have crafted a radio-friendly mix
of rhythmic pop that should get constant airplay at Star 94. Not
that there's anything wrong with that _ if you like that sort of
thing. Perched at the programmed end of the blue-eyed-soul
spectrum, Carrack _ best known for his vocals with '80s pop outfits
Squeeze, Ace and Mike + the Mechanics _ is at his best on the
strutting ``You Give Me Something'' and the gospel-powered
``Beautiful World.'' Actually, this is perfect for the gym.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
