<SLUG> BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN:`Big doings': Colorful days at the Capitol
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 7: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Channel 8, the Georgia Public Television station, has been a
favorite of mine since Gene Moore used to run a book show there.
Gene read the books, which is not true of every television
interviewer, and when he invited me out to the studio, then on
Stewart Avenue, I knew we were in for a lively discussion. Now the
station has moved to 14th Street, and I don't believe they have a
book program by an erudite, well-read commentator, as they had in
Gene's day.
</P>
<P>
   But they do have some staffers who are knowledgeable and
enthusiastic about the state Capitol building. Rosy Bailey, a tall,
thin man who grew up in Georgia, and his photographer sidekick,
Wayne Baumgardner, have been covering the restoration of the
Capitol. They've spent many hours interviewing people about it and
standing by when the workers come out at night to scrape paint and
repair plaster in the House or Senate chambers.
</P>
<P>
   They invited me to meet them over there and talk about so-called
``old days'' in the Capitol. I was delighted to accept because I
have always loved the old building and have seen some interesting
and exciting times there. Just to walk through the near-deserted
halls filled me with nostalgia and a sadness for so many people who
are there no longer. The swearing in of Ellis Arnall as Georgia
governor was my first assignment over there, and I was hooked. I
wanted to be there when things happened.
</P>
<P>
   Rosy asked me how you can get the public interested in that
building, and I was surprised. How can the public not be
interested? It's the heart of the state, where people from all the
counties assemble once a year, and it's wonderfully colorful and
exciting and sometimes disgraceful.
</P>
<P>
   When senators dressed up in togas and drank quantities of
whiskey on adjournment day, even a fan like me couldn't call it
statesmanlike behavior. I did think it was funny when House Speaker
Georgie L. Smith and Reps. Frank Twitty and Jack Ray put on Beatles
wigs and marched into the chamber in defiance of some editorial
criticism of them from the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   And I loved it when Mr. H.P. McGibbony, the old peanut man who
sold his wares outside the House chamber, warned me that ``big
doings'' were going on inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you know, Mr. Mac?'' I asked. His cart was outside, and
he plainly couldn't hear the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's big controversy, they eat lots of peanuts,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The aisle was ankle-deep in peanut shells. The debate was on the
hot rural-roads question.
</P>
<P>
   It probably takes too much explaining to convince kids that the
Capitol is a fascinating place. They may never have heard of the
stormy January when we had two governors vying for the office and
one in the wings, waiting for a nod from the state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   They may not sense the bigness and the diversity of the state
just sitting in those rather grand chambers and hearing the
arguments of representatives of the people _ say cotton or tobacco
growers. It may not amuse them that the man from a tobacco county
always tried to put a new tax on Coca-Cola to retaliate for the tax
on tobacco products.
</P>
<P>
   When they are older, I can tell them about the day a prostitute
visited the House or the woman patient from the mental hospital,
who sang and played the piano in impersonation of Sophie Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   But you can't really explain the kindness and helpfulness of
workers in all those big offices, or the aide who had a hollow
walking stick filled with little vials of whiskey for adjournment
night. And I didn't explain much to the men from Channel 8.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
