<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Platform sandals flatten the competition
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 7: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Size matters. Don't let anybody tell you differently.
</P>
<P>
   Keep that two-word truism in mind and you won't make a bad shoe
purchase all summer long.
</P>
<P>
   These days, ``summer'' is just another word for ``blockbuster.''
</P>
<P>
   And the platform sandals that look so right for this season have
blockbuster stamped on their soles.
</P>
<P>
   The sold-out signs are already flashing above some of the 2- to
4-inch-high sandals stores brought in. And there's good reason why
this style's so popular.
</P>
<P>
   Platforms accentuate legs and elongate physiques just about as
well as stilettos _ without the clear and present danger of pain or
injury.
</P>
<P>
   That's one thumb up.
</P>
<P>
   And they basically put women on pedestals.
</P>
<P>
   That's two.
</P>
<P>
   So, it's settled then. Size matters. Women who think otherwise
this summer are only selling themselves short.
</P>
<P>
   Some sandal styles this summer:
</P>
<P>
   Lucite wedge sandal ($420) by Gucci. At Bob Ellis Shoes.
</P>
<P>
   An airy multi-colored thong ($20) by Mixed Blues. At JCPenney.
</P>
<P>
   Linen-soled sandal ($370) by Prada. At Bob Ellis Shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Leopard print sandal ($20) by Mixed Blues. At JCPenney.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
