A2710 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NOTES04-COX     06-03 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NOTES04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    South Carolina scandal turns into a book
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, James Kilgo was presented with a tantalizing
story that no writer could resist. A cousin told him about a murder
and suicide in 1918 that left two brothers dead and a South
Carolina county scandalized. At the center of the tragedy was a
distant relative, a mixed-race woman who was loved by one brother
and lusted after by the other.
</P>
<P>
   Kilgo's re-creation of the story led him through years of
research into family secrets. One of his best sources was an older
family member who had been in his teens at the time. The man gave
Kilgo much of the background, but left out the part about the
woman. Then, a few weeks before his death, he revealed the woman at
the heart of the story and gave Kilgo a picture of her.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Kilgo faced a dilemma of either telling the true
story and hurting some family members or casting it as a novel. He
took the fictional route.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I started working on it,'' Kilgo says, ``the characters
started talking to each other, and that's when I really got excited
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is ``Daughter of My People'' (University of Georgia
Press, $24), Kilgo's debut novel, which early reviews have
described as ``sad, vivid, and haunting.'' Kilgo's earlier works
were two books of essays, ``Deep Enough for Ivorybills'' and
``Inheritance of Horses.''
</P>
<P>
   While the two brothers in the real-life story wound up dead, the
woman at the center of the tale lived into the 1960s. Kilgo wasn't
able to locate her burial site, but he knows that she married and
was around 85 at the time of her death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to tell a story that evokes its time and place,''
Kilgo says, ``and I wanted to write a book that would touch and
move people.''
</P>
<P>
   -- RIDING HIGH: Georgia novelist P.T. Deutermann has just signed
a $500,000, two-book deal with St. Martin's Press. The former naval
commander has been slowly building a readership with military
thrillers such as ``Sweepers'' and ``Official Privilege,'' both of
which have been optioned for movies. Wesley Snipes is scheduled to
star in ``Official Privilege.'' Deutermann's next book, ``The
Trainman,'' is about a Unabomber-like terrorist.
</P>
<P>
   -- CHRISTMAS GIFT: Sometimes it pays to start small. Utah
legislator Richard Siddoway's first novel, ``The Christmas Wish,''
was published by Bookcraft, a small Utah press. Now Harmony Books
has bought the novel for repackaging, and CBS will air an
adaptation as a Sunday-night movie, starring Debbie Reynolds and
Neil Patrick Harris, in December. The story is about a man who
returns to his home in upstate New York after his grandfather dies
to discover how important the old man was to the town.
</P>
<P>
   -- WINNERS: The American Booksellers Association has selected
Charles Frazier's ``Cold Mountain'' as the 1998 Book of the Year in
the adult category. Jan Brett's ``The Hat'' won in the children's
category. The award honors titles that independent booksellers most
enjoyed recommending to their customers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
