<HEADER>
A2711 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRAWFISH-RECIPES-COX     06-03 1474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRAWFISH-RECIPES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Uncovering the tale of a good etouffee
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 7: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Breaux Bridge, La.--Ailene Champagne Guidry died a couple of
years ago, but people in Cajun country will never forget the mother
of crawfish etouffee.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't create the most famous crawfish dish; people from
Baton Rouge to Lake Charles had long been cooking something like
it. She did, however, make an early version of it and give it a
name. And that's why her sepia-toned portrait hangs in a place of
honor in the Cafe des Amis, a restaurant on the main street of
Breaux Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   As the cafe's Dickie Breaux tells it, Miss Ailene learned the
recipe from two sisters who ran a hotel, and she served it when she
opened her own restaurant, the Rendezvous. One day in the
mid-1940s, a visitor from Lafayette asked her how she made the
dish, and she answered with a literal description in French: She
cooked it ``smothered'' (etouffee), meaning that she left the lid
on the skillet.
</P>
<P>
   ``She used to come in here and talk about how she'd catch the
Landry boys (competing restaurateurs) peeking in her window to see
how she did it,'' Breaux says. ``But she didn't really consider it
her dish. It was everybody's.''
</P>
<P>
   Cafe des Amis Etouffee
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 servings Preparation time: 30 minutes Cooking time: 45
minutes
</P>
<P>
   This is a simpler, kitchenized version of the Cafe des Amis
etouffee. ``It's not the same as the original,'' says Cynthia
Breaux. ``The original had more crawfish and a thinner sauce. Most
etouffees have thicker sauces these days.''
</P>
<P>
   STOCK:
</P>
<P>
   3quarts water
</P>
<P>
   24boiled crawfish heads
</P>
<P>
   (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon creole
</P>
<P>
   seasoning
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   BLOND ROUX:
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup (1 stick) butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   SAUCE:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) butter
</P>
<P>
   1cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup chopped green pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup chopped celery
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon white pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2teaspoons granulated garlic
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon chicken base (found in spice sections of
well-stocked supermarkets)
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons paprika
</P>
<P>
   2pounds crawfish tail meat
</P>
<P>
   Stock: Place water, crawfish heads, creole seasoning and cayenne
in 8-quart stockpot. Bring to boil and simmer 15 minutes. Strain
and reserve 6 cups stock. Keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Roux: Melt 1 stick butter in 12-inch frying pan. Gradually stir
in flour; cook and stir 5-6 minutes over medium-low heat, or until
roux has a blond color. Cool slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Sauce: Melt butter in 10-inch frying pan. Add onion, green
pepper and celery and cook until softened. Add cayenne, black and
white pepper, garlic, chicken base and paprika. Stir until
well-blended. Reheat roux over medium heat. Gradually add 6 cups
crawfish stock to roux, stirring to blend. Add sauce mixture to
roux, then add crawfish. Cook over low heat until slightly
thickened. Serve over rice or crawfish corn bread.
</P>
<P>
   Note: If you haven't boiled crawfish and don't have heads, make
a seafood stock with fish bouillon or shrimp.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 295 calories, 19 grams protein, 20 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 60), 11 grams carbohydrates, 166
milligrams cholesterol, 937 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Crawfish Corn Bread
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings Preparation time: 30 minutes Cooking time: 1
hour
</P>
<P>
   The Cafe des Amis serves several other crawfish dishes,
including this rich corn bread.
</P>
<P>
   2eggs
</P>
<P>
   2cups yellow cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   3teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   28 1/2-ounce cans
</P>
<P>
   creamed corn
</P>
<P>
   1cup milk
</P>
<P>
   4tablespoons melted butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4pound grated
</P>
<P>
   cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   1pound crawfish tail meat
</P>
<P>
   Mix the eggs, cornmeal, baking powder, salt, creamed corn, milk,
butter, sugar, cheddar cheese and crawfish in a large bowl. Pour
into a greased 13-by-9-by-2-inch baking pan. Bake at 375 degrees
for 1 hour. Serve by itself or topped with crawfish etouffee or a
piece of grilled fish.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 230 calories, 12 grams protein, 10 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 38), 24 grams carbohydrates, 91
milligrams cholesterol, 633 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to etouffee, the classic crawfish dishes are bisque,
boiled crawfish, crawfish pie and fried tails known as ``Cajun
popcorn.'' The Louisiana Crawfish Board doesn't want you to stop
there; there are 72 crawfish recipes, from dips and salads to
breads and casseroles, in its promotional booklet (available by
calling 1-800-522-4742). We liked this rice salad.
</P>
<P>
   Crawfish Rice
</P>
<P>
   With Coconut and Peanuts
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings Preparation time: 30 minutes Cooking time: 45
minutes
</P>
<P>
   4tablespoons cooking oil
</P>
<P>
   2cups white rice
</P>
<P>
   3 3/4cups water
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon minced onion
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup grated, unsweetened coconut
</P>
<P>
   1pound crawfish tail meat, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup chopped salted
</P>
<P>
   peanuts
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon curry powder
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons minced
</P>
<P>
   parsley
</P>
<P>
   y
</P>
<P>
   In a heavy pot, combine oil, rice, water, onion and salt. Stir
once, and bring to a boil. Reduce heat to low, cover and cook 25-30
minutes or until water is absorbed and rice is cooked. Do not lift
cover or stir while cooking. Melt butter or margarine in skillet.
Add coconut and cook, stirring, until lightly browned. Stir in
crawfish, peanuts and curry. Add parsley. Combine half of
coconut-crawfish mixture with cooked rice. Place in serving dish
and sprinkle remaining coconut-crawfish mixture on top. Serve warm
or at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 254 calories, 10 grams protein, 12 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 42), 27 grams carbohydrates, 43
milligrams cholesterol, 495 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   The crawfish boil is a rite of spring and early summer in
Louisiana. But if you didn't grow up with the little critters, as
most of us in Georgia didn't, it can all seem mysterious. Here's
what you do.
</P>
<P>
   Live crawfish are available through July at major farmers
markets such as DeKalb and Harry's. Keep them alive, cool and moist
(but not submerged in water). Before boiling, you'll have to clean
them well (they're ``mudbugs,'' after all). The easiest way is to
take them outside and douse them thoroughly with a sprayer hose on
a screen or old sweater rack. Look for the few that have died and
discard. Plan on cooking 4 or 5 pounds for every person.
</P>
<P>
   After boiling comes the intricate part: peeling and picking out
the tail meat. Take the crawfish with both hands and twist it apart
in the middle. If you want, suck the head to taste the juices and
the dab of yellow liver that's as buttery as foie gras. To eat the
tail, peel off the top ring of shell, hold the tip of the tail
between thumb and forefinger and squeeze the meat into your mouth.
If you pinch it right, the vein _ the crawfish's digestive canal _
will pull out along with the tail armor.
</P>
<P>
   When live crawfish season is over, you can get frozen, cleaned
tail meat year-round. The folks in Breaux Bridge would appreciate
it if you looked for the ``Product of Louisiana'' label.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the crawfish boil recipe we improvised over Memorial Day
weekend. At outdoor boils, crawfish are usually cooked in large
kettles or trash cans over a propane flame. We cooked them in small
batches at a kitchen stove, using the largest pot we had _ a
5-gallon canning steamer. Same taste, better air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   Boiled Crawfish
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 30 minutes Cooking time: 30
minutes
</P>
<P>
   3gallons water
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup salt
</P>
<P>
   1package seafood boil
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon creole seasoning
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon granulated garlic
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon white pepper
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   6pounds live crawfish
</P>
<P>
   In a large pot, place the water, salt, seafood boil, creole
seasoning, cayenne, granulated garlic and white and black pepper.
Stir and bring to a rolling boil. Pour in live crawfish. Boil for
10 minutes. Turn off heat and allow crawfish to soak up spices for
another 15 minutes. Strain out crawfish. If you're cooking more of
them, put them in an ice chest and sprinkle creole seasoning over
each new batch. Change the water and seasonings after two boils.
</P>
<P>
   Many Louisianians also boil vegetables in the crawfish water.
Tradition calls for new potatoes, whole onions and ears of corn.
Cook as much as you want by putting them into the water before the
last batch of crawfish. Then pour in the crawdaddies and let the
veggies soak up the flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 262 calories, 54 grams protein, 3 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 11), less than 1 gram carbohydrates,
388 milligrams cholesterol, 789 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
