<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-RAP04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Master P's `Last Don' puts reality on record
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remarkably, Master P has stormed the charts with some pretty
simplistic music. But now, as the rapper, filmmaker and owner of No
Limit Records focuses on his obviously numerous outside interests,
he uses his double-CD farewell to tell a multidimensional story of
a hustler.
</P>
<P>
   First, he's a hustler. So he spends a good deal of this record
(like his others) basically yelling hustler mottoes in the guise of
songs: ``Get Your Paper,'' ``Ride,'' etc. Second, this is gangster
rap, so the language used is often harsh and the scenarios can be
violent (``Let's Get Em'').
</P>
<P>
   But unlike many in this subgenre, Master P does a good job of
explaining why those components have to be a part of ``Da Last
Don.'' They are a part of his life. And it's made easy to
understand that, after the violent loss of a younger brother and
two of the ghetto heroes (Tupac Shakur and the Notorious B.I.G.)
whom you may very well replace, if you want to be honest on record,
it might not always sound happy.
</P>
<P>
   But Master P doesn't wallow in the losses, either. He ends many
of these same graphic tracks with admonitions such as ``The
ghetto's got us crazy, but we've got to overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Moving even further beyond the expected and the limitations of
some pretty unremarkable production, Master P uses his husky chants
to reveal his vulnerabilities. ``I'm a thug, but still mama's
baby,'' goes the chorus of ``Mama Raised Me.'' And the kinetic
``Thug Girl'' is directed to certain women with love. Then, on
``Black and White,'' he charges designer Tommy Hilfiger with
discrimination while assailing blacks for not supporting their own
retail outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Rapper Jay-Z once said that the better a rapper is, the closer
he can bring you to his experience. Here, Master P makes his
reality so clear that much more than his signature grunt resounds
in your ear long after the record goes off.
</P>
<P>
   ``MP Da
</P>
<P>
   Last Don''
</P>
<P>
   Master P. No Limit Records.
</P>
<P>
   29 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Master P saves his best for ``Da Last Don.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
