<HEADER>
A2718 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEOS-MINIREVIEWS-CO     06-03 0424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEOS-MINIREVIEWS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini views of latest videos
 &HT;    By Steve Murray and Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- ``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil'' (R) _ Director
Clint Eastwood did the unimaginable with the screen version of John
Berendt's fact-based book: He made it into an overlong, unfocused
bore. You can't argue with the ways the film compresses or alters
parts of the book; Berendt himself juggled the facts a little
cavalierly. But 30 minutes into the movie, renamed hustler ``Billy
Hanson'' (Jude Law) has been gunned down by Jim Williams (the
ill-used Kevin Spacey), and the film spins its wheels for the next
two hours. It hinges on a crime it can't convince us we should care
about. What we get is a tepid murder trial with sidebar excursions
into the eccentricities of Savannah. Even in his better work,
Eastwood's direction has been marked by flat, uninflected scenes.
That describes this whole movie. Eastwood keeps pulling the Lady
Chablis into the frame to liven things up. But it's more than one
hard-working girl can do. Grade: C -
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Home Alone 3'' (PG) _ The latest installment in the most
successful film franchise ever to center on child neglect.
Confident and precocious, Alex D. Linz is a more than adequate
replacement for Macaulay Culkin. He has at least a sequel in him
before the cuteness wears off. It's the central gimmick of these
movies that has become problematic. Like the first two, this was
written and produced by kiddie king John Hughes, and his knack for
figuring out ways to strand children without their parents is
getting kind of creepy. The series' cartoonish violence is at a
crowd-pleasing peak here, with the bad guys experiencing cranial
trauma, testicular bruising, hypothermia and electrocution.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B -
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Fall'' (R) _ If you're looking to replace your
``Showgirls'' tape for guilty-pleasure midnight viewing, you're in
luck. If you thought writer-director-producer-star Eric Schaeffer's
last flick, ``If Lucy Fell,'' was a vanity production, oh baby,
wait. He made out with Elle Macpherson in that one; this time
around he angles for sex scenes with Amanda De Cadenet. She plays a
married supermodel who falls (oh yeah, right) for Schaeffer's
cabdriver. He writes bad poetry and _ I swear, this is in the movie
_ inspires her to, um, maximum excitement by talking dirty to her
in the kitchen. It gets worse. Fabulously worse. Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
