<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEOS-OSCARandLUCINDA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The sure bet rides on `Oscar &AMP; Lucinda'
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Oscar &AMP; Lucinda'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   You have every reason to expect this period drama to lift you
away. After all, it stars smoldering Brit heartthrob Ralph Fiennes
(``The English Patient'') as the first half of the titular couple
and up-and-coming Australian actress Cate Blanchett (``Paradise
Road'') as the second.
</P>
<P>
   It's directed by Gillian Armstrong (``My Brilliant Career'') and
based on an award-winning contemporary novel. Set in the 19th
century, the film introduces us to our heroes by degrees _ Oscar, a
gawky British minister; Lucinda, an unexpected Australian heiress,
who funnels her money into a glassworks. What they have in common
is a love of gambling, at the time as scandalous a pursuit as
anything Pamela or Tommy Lee might have done.
</P>
<P>
   As the movie unfolds their kind-of-almost love story, the
old-fashioned frame of the narrative gets peppered by modern
notions of fate, chance and plain old miscommunication. The result
is like the glass Lucinda loves: ravishingly beautiful, but chilly,
distant and brittle. Grade: B -
</P>
<P>
   Other films by Armstrong: ``Starstruck,'' ``High Tide,'' ``Mrs.
Soffel,'' ``The Last Days of Chez Nous.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
