<HEADER>
A2720 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXCURSION-DANCE-REVIE     06-03 0376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXCURSION-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EXCURSION FARE': SUCH HAPPY FEET, TAP, TAP, TAPPING
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
 (js) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Manhattan Tap took a trip around the world in
``Excursion Fare'' on Tuesday night at the Joyce Theater. And with
this imaginative new show, the company comes close to bridging the
gap between old- and new-style tap, with dancing that is intimate
and as intimately involved with the music as any tap soloist and
instrumentalist.
</P>
<P>
   It was an inspired idea to join Manhattan Tap with the
Crosspulse music ensemble. The six dancers and five musicians are
equal as performers in this program. One duet is a whispered
conversation between the dancing feet of Heather Cornell, director
of the dance company and of ``Excursion Fare,'' and the soft
percussive tapping of sticks manipulated by Keith Terry, director
of the musicians. It soon becomes clear that the dance and the
music are two ways of using the body to make music.
</P>
<P>
   Terry also performs the old ``patting Juba'' or ``hambone'' folk
style of slapping the body. And Jackeline Rago nearly steals the
show in a maraca solo whose hushed beat magically fills the
theater. The accent throughout the evening is on quiet pleasures,
enhanced by the subtly shifting color that fills the stage space,
designed by Stephan Quandt. The choreography is by Ms. Cornell,
Germaine Ingram, Michael Minery and Terry.
</P>
<P>
   The staging is sleek but a little cute at times and the music
and dance can come perilously close to sheer appropriation of other
cultures.
</P>
<P>
   But a flamenco number, performed by Olivia Rosenkrantz, is
typical of the richly textured footwork of the entire dance
company, which also included Charon Aldredge, Maria Bostwick,
Parris Mann and Minery.
</P>
<P>
   The similarly textured, burnishing music was performed on
everything from guitars and drums to the Balinese gamelan and South
Indian solkatu. The Crosspulse ensemble was completed by Edgardo
Cambon, Claudia Gomez and Raymond Graham. ``Excursion Fare'' will
be performed through Sunday at the Joyce, 175 Eighth Avenue, at
19th Street.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
