<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-PUMPKINS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smashing Pumpkins try new route, but its a dead end
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why do potentially potent rockers equate maturity with
diminished energy and growth with, well, not rocking? It happens
all too often: Your favorite artist describes the latest opus as a
``more serious, more adult work.'' Then you go out and buy the
thing and find it as limp as overcooked linguine.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Corgan is the latest rock hero to succumb to
mature-artist-itis. The front man and primary visionary for the
Smashing Pumpkins, Corgan has signaled in recent interviews that
he's moving away from their signature sound (loud, layered guitars
and mucho screeching). Rumor had it that the follow-up to 1995's
sprawling smash ``Mellon Collie and the Infinite Sadness'' would be
an acoustic set, but it's not so much that as it is muted.
``Adore,'' the Pumpkins' fourth album, begins with a whisper _ the
tepid ballad ``To Sheila'' _ and never rises above a dull roar
(emphasis on the ``dull''). Keyboards and cheesy electronic
percussion sub for guitars and ex-member Jimmy Chamberlain's
much-missed drumming. Corgan's pinched vocals, always their best at
full scream, flirt with wispiness.
</P>
<P>
   The album is not without low-key charms. ``Ava Adore,'' the
synth-driven first single, is a canny impression of Depeche Mode.
``Behold! The Night Mare'' lifts the disc's second half out of its
torpor with a lovely, Brian Wilson-inspired melody. But, overall,
the mournful motif feels forced. It's as if Corgan took the
``Infinite Sadness'' part of the previous album's title to its
literal extreme. And, coming from one of rock's last angry young
men, that's a crying shame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adore''
</P>
<P>
   Smashing Pumpkins. Virgin.
</P>
<P>
   16 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Even hard-core fans may not adore the Pumpkins'
largely languid latest.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
