<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARREY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Truman' lets Carrey `Show' his stuff
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's time for the question. The question that has put Jim Carrey
on the cover of Time, Movieline, New York and Entertainment Weekly
in recent days. The question he's facing all over as he talks to
journalists about his new film, ``The Truman Show,'' opening
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the question comes out something like this: How does
Jim Carrey, the movies' bona fide premier funny guy, make the
transition to bona fide premier funny guy ... and more?
</P>
<P>
   ``I already have,'' he replies simply in a telephone interview.
``I made the movie. Whether it comes together financially is out of
my hands.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``comes together financially'' is a guarded reference to
1996's ``The Cable Guy,'' the first _ and thus far, only _ disaster
in a foolproof career built on such foolishness as the two ``Ace
Ventura'' flicks, ``Dumb and Dumber'' and ``The Mask.'' ``The Cable
Guy'' was supposed to introduce moviegoers to a ``different''
Carrey. A ``darker'' Carrey. Just how a script written originally
for the now-late Chris Farley was supposed to do that was never
quite clear. But the film bombed, and Carrey took the brunt of the
criticism for trying to be ``different'' and ``darker.''
</P>
<P>
   Now comes ``The Truman Show,'' which has also been tagged with
those ``d'' words. But this is no Chris Farley discard. Directed by
Peter Weir (``Witness,'' ``Gallipoli''), it's a complex, funny,
multileveled meditation on matters ranging from the pervasiveness
of our TV nation mentality to theological questions filtered
through a camera lens.
</P>
<P>
   Carrey plays Truman Burbank, an insurance salesman who, without
knowing it, is actually the star of a hugely successful
long-running TV series. Everyone in his life is an actor, from his
pert wife (Laura Linney) to his loyal best friend (Noah Emmerich).
</P>
<P>
   Linney, for one, isn't surprised by her co-star's range.
``There's always more to someone than just one thing. And when
you're really talented, you want to be able to explore that,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Carrey puts it this way: ``This is an opportunity for me to show
more colors. But there was no master plan. No telling my agent, `Go
out and find me a drama!' It simply came my way and I chose to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean he'll never talk through his butt again, as he
did in ``Ace Ventura, Pet Detective.'' ``It's not like I never want
to do that stuff again. But I absolutely want to have a career
where you make'em laugh and make'em cry. It's all theater. ''
</P>
<P>
   It's a career that sounds a lot like, oh, say, Tom Hanks'. It's
a comparison he's heard before. He says of Hanks: ``He's had an
incredible career. He's really done it right.''
</P>
<P>
   But here's one he hasn't heard: With his leading man good looks
and his funny man reflexes, could he be a Danny Kaye of the '90s?
The reply is unintelligible, like Robin Williams channeling Michael
Jackson. Say what? He laughs. ``Oh, that's just how `Wonderful
Copenhagen' (a song in Kaye's ``Hans Christian Andersen'') sounds
in my head.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is, Carrey simply doesn't want to be stuck in a
rut. He points out, ``In a lot of ways, that's what `Truman' is
about, a man who feels repressed and trapped. But every day he puts
a smile on his face and goes out the door.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, Hollywood's $20 million man knows a thing or two
about being trapped. He watched his father, a Canadian businessman,
put a smile on his face and go out the door every day to a job he
loathed. Then, at age 51, after 30 years with the company, he was
laid off. Carrey and his siblings had to quit high school and take
menial jobs at a tire factory. At one point, the family was living
out of a VW van.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps those hard times gave Carrey his Silly Putty
resiliency; it took him 15 years to become an overnight sensation.
Up next is ``Man on the Moon,'' in which he plays Andy Kaufman, the
cutting-edge comic who died of lung cancer at 35. Then it's back to
the dumb 'n' dumber stuff in ``The Incredible Mr. Limpet,'' a role
originated, if that's the word, by Don Knotts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lineup is really exciting.'' Carrey says. ``It's amazing
the things I've tripped into. But you can't settle for things.
You've always got to try doing something different. You've got to
have a choice.''
</P>
<P>
   He laughs again. ``I could do `Ace Ventura 6,' but the fact is,
you'd get tired of me a lot quicker than you think.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
