</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARREY-LIST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EVOLUTION OF A CAREER: JIM CARREY
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- ``Ace Ventura, Pet Detective'' (1994). A gunshoe goofball is
born. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Mask'' (1994). The actor shows some depth. Carrey plays
a mild-mannered clerk who flips out and comes off as sweet as he is
manic. Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Dumb and Dumber'' (1994). Road trip. The most lowbrow, and
possibly the funniest, of Carrey's 1994 ``Doofus Trilogy.'' Grade:
B+
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Ace Ventura: When Nature Calls'' (1995). The sequel has the
same winning combination as the original: idiotic plot, inspired
Carrey. And that scene inside the rhino. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Batman Forever'' (1995). As the Riddler, Carrey is the
film's best special effect _ leering, prancing and spouting his
riotous nonsense. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Cable Guy'' (1996). A horror, but not one of Carrey's
making. Its signals are so disastrously scrambled that not even its
hard-working $20 million star can rescue it. Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Liar Liar'' (1997). A selfish Carrey goes over the top,
wears out his welcome. Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Truman Show'' (1998). Carrey loses the silliness and
gains an even brighter future. Grade: A.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Man on the Moon'' (Release TBA): With his next film, Carrey
may well complete his transformation to dramatic leading man with
the bitter-funny biopic of comedian Andy Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
