<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2724 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNN-NEWSSTAND-COX     06-03 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-NEWSSTAND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CNN Newsstand finally hits the air on Sunday
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sunday night, for the first time in 17 years, James Earl Jones
will not intone ``This is CNN.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he'll say, ``This is CNN NewsStand.''
</P>
<P>
   That brief but telling break with tradition is the network's way
of signaling that ``NewsStand'' is not news as usual. The new
magazine series, a co-operative venture with Time, Fortune and
Entertainment Weekly, is CNN's biggest initiative ever, an attempt
to get viewers to think differently about the network.
</P>
<P>
   Another sign of the importance of ``NewsStand'' within CNN: In
President Richard Kaplan's office, the photos on the shelves behind
his desk are all of his family, save one. It's an 8x10 publicity
photo of the five ``NewsStand'' anchors in a silver frame.
</P>
<P>
   And yet Kaplan knows the hard truth of starting a TV
newsmagazine show.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is all magazine shows start in the dumper almost,
or at least they start off needing fixing,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``NewsStand'' is CNN's most extensive attempt to fix its largest
problem: the peaks and valleys of Nielsen ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have these enormous (ratings) spikes when something
important really hits the fan,'' says Tom Johnson, chairman of the
CNN Newsgroup and Kaplan's boss. ``But when that news environment
becomes more calm, people go back to watching sports or movies or
soap operas.''
</P>
<P>
   So Kaplan, aided by more than 100 CNN staffers over nine months
of brain-storming, development, prototypes, a three-month delay,
new hires and incessant on-air promotion, is bringing forth
``NewsStand'' with the idea that it will evolve into what TV
executives call ``appointment TV.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal, if I may put it modestly,'' says anchor Jeff
Greenfield, ``is to be a place where people know that at 10 o'clock
at night, they might find something interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Greenfield, who left ABC to come work for CNN and
``NewsStand,'' will be Bernard Shaw for the Time and CNN shows.
Willow Bay and Judd Rose, also defectors from ABC (where Kaplan
worked for years) will anchor ``CNN &AMP; Entertainment Weekly,'' and
Bay and CNN veteran Stephen Frazier will anchor ``CNN &AMP; Fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to overstate how much work has gone into
``NewsStand,'' although the results remain to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trying to translate a magazine to television is incredibly
hard,'' says Teya Ryan, executive producer of ``CNN &AMP; Fortune.''
``They are fundamentally such different mediums, and there are just
infinite details.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The tough job is to find the right stories,'' says Rose.
``Very smart, serious, edgy stuff that I don't see a lot of on
television.'' He says ``EW,'' like the magazine it's based on, will
be much more in-depth than CNN's ``Showbiz Today'' or the
syndicated ``Entertainment Tonight,'' more about the business of
show business than the latest movie premiere.
</P>
<P>
   ``NewsStand'' will be the only network newsmagazine show
actually based on magazines. Time, EW and Fortune are all owned by
Time Warner Inc., which also owns CNN. To insiders, this represents
smart synergy. To outsiders, it may look more like cross-promotion
from a network that values its credbility.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Time Warner chairman) Gerald Levin and Ted Turner took an
attitude of 'If you can work it out, great, if you can't, fine. We
don't want to push people into unnatural relationships,' '' says
Kaplan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judge us by what we do,'' Greenfield says of the corporate
co-operation.
</P>
<P>
   The show enters a TV marketplace already saturated with network
newsmagazines. ``Dateline NBC'' expands to five nights a week in
the fall, ABC pushes ``20/20'' to three times a week, and CBS's two
hours (``60 Minutes,'' ``48 Hours'') make 10 hours a week of
network newsmagazines, plus the four ``NewsStands.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The clutter doesn't really concern me,'' says Kaplan. ``When
shows like 'PrimeTime Live' (which Kaplan produced at ABC) or
'Public Eye With Bryant Gumbel' come on, people wonder: What is it
about? Everybody knows what Time, Fortune and Entertainment Weekly
are about, so defining ourselves is not an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, CNN is expecting what Pat Mitchell, president of CNN
Productions, calls ``a very slow build.'' Advertisers have been
told to expect no increase (fewer than 500,000 homes watching) at
first in the ratings over the regular newscasts ``NewsStand'' is
replacing. ``These shows don't do well when they premiere,'' Kaplan
says.
</P>
<P>
   They also run the risk of being dramatically re-worked at the
last minute in the event of breaking news. The shows are all taped,
but the anchors will be on stand-by to go live if needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will throw out the show to go to breaking news,'' says
Mitchell. ``'Cause that's what CNN does.''
</P>
<P>
   TV PREVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``NewsStand: CNN &AMP; Time''
</P>
<P>
   10 p.m. EDT, Sunday and 10 p.m. EDT, Monday on CNN. Bernard Shaw
and Jeff Greenfield, anchors.
</P>
<P>
   ``NewsStand: CNN &AMP; Fortune''
</P>
<P>
   10 p.m. EDT, Wednesday on CNN. Stephen Frazier and Willow Bay,
anchors.
</P>
<P>
   ``NewsStand: CNN &AMP; Entertainment Weekly''
</P>
<P>
   10 p.m. EDT, June 11 on CNN. Judd Rose and Willow Bay, anchors.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 1812EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
