<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0310 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2725 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNN-SIDE-COX     06-03 0344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-SIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``NewsStand'': a closer look
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Each ``NewsStand'' hour will have three major stories and lots
of smaller bits, the briefest of which are called
``interstitials.'' ``Dateline NBC's'' Timeline feature is an
example of an interstitial.
</P>
<P>
   But each show will reflect the elements of the magazine it's
based on:
</P>
<P>
   -- Time: Sunday's premiere will feature a Peter Arnett report
that CNN is keeping under wraps. It involves a new disclosure of a
secret U.S. operation inside Laos. Each show will end with an essay
called ``The Looking Glass,'' similar to Time's back page, with
Jeff Greenfield doing several. His first, on Sunday, will be on the
responsibility of the TV viewer for much of what's wrong with TV
news coverage. Bits will include People and Milestones.
</P>
<P>
   -- Fortune: Wednesday's premiere will look at ``Face Reading,''
a business consultancy that says it can tell bosses whom to hire
based on facial features. A weekly spot will be Coolest Office,
going inside the offices of famous and not-so-famous business
leaders. Bits will include Techno-File, From the Pages Of (editors
and writers' column), Fortune Investor (news-you-can-use help).
Upcoming stories: Michael Jordan's endorsement empire, Magic
Johnson's movie chain and an agent who represents Silicon Valley
software designers.
</P>
<P>
   -- Entertainment Weekly: The June 11 premiere will have an
interview with Sean Lennon and a look at Hollywood spin doctors.
One of readers' favorite features, Jim Mullen's Hot Sheet (a
broader-based, funnier version of Letterman's Top 10), will be an
interstitial, with an animated Mullen. (The real one wasn't very
telegenic.) EW's critics and editors will do a weekly roundtable,
and Encore (the where-are-they-now back page) will be a weekly
feature. Upcoming stories: How focus groups sometimes change the
endings of movies, a look at TV's ``The X-Files'' and Burt
Bacharach's comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 1812EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
