<SLUG> BC-POOL-SAFETY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fences not enough; other protective measures for pool safety
recommended
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA--It requires more than just a big fence to prevent
children from drowning in pools. Although that helps, keeping a
close eye on children and using other protective measures are more
effective, health experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Drowning is the third-leading cause of death in children under
5. In Georgia, 241 people younger than 19 drowned between 1990 and
1994, according to the Injury Control Section in the state
Department of Human Resources. The most recent occurred Sunday in
metro Atlanta, when 6-year-old twins drowned in a residential
swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year we hear about drownings. The horrible thing is that
they are preventable,'' said pediatrician Karen Dewling of the
Emory Clinic.
</P>
<P>
   To help prevent drowning accidents, Dewling advises parents and
caregivers to watch young children at all times when they are near
any body of water.
</P>
<P>
   Children who are good swimmers also should be supervised,
Dewling said, because they could have muscle cramps or other
physical problems while swimming that could lead to an accident.
Children can drown in as little as 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The Centers for Disease Control recommends that residential
pools be surrounded on all four sides with a fence and
self-latching gate, in addition to having a fence around the yard.
</P>
<P>
   If it is possible to walk from inside the house or yard directly
to the swimming pool, ``you don't have appropriate prevention
strategies to prevent small children from gaining access to the
pool,'' said Christine Branche, director of the Division of
Unintentional Injury Prevention at the CDC's National Center for
Injury Prevention and Control.
</P>
<P>
   But pool fences alone are not enough to prevent the majority of
drownings in children. Only 19 percent of the fatalities might have
been prevented with proper fencing, according to a CDC study of 584
children who drowned in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Laws in Georgia regulating residential swimming pools vary by
county. For example, in Fulton County pools must be surrounded by a
5-foot fence. However, one side of the barrier can be the house.
The fence can be wrought iron, wooden, aluminum or chain link, and
the links must be set closely together to prevent climbers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to adequate fencing, Branche recommends that
homeowners use pool covers or alarms when the pools are not in use.
A cover would conceal the water, making it less appealing to a
child. An alarm would send off a warning that an object, such as a
toy or a child, had broken the surface of the water.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
