<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: EVEN BRAVE THEATERS MUST COURT THEIR BACKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PETER APPLEBOME   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK: Last month, before his play `Corpus Christi'' was
canceled and then reinstated, the playwright Terrence McNally gave
a luncheon speech to a theater group in Manhattan listing the nine
things every playwright needed to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Write plays that matter,'' he said, getting to No. 7 on the
list he read to the New Dramatists on May 12. ``Raise the stakes.
Shout, yell, holler, but make yourself heard. It's time for
playwrights to reclaim the theater. We do that by speaking from the
heart about the things that matter most to us. If a play isn't
worth dying for, maybe it isn't worth writing.''
</P>
<P>
   The chill that swept the theater world when McNally's play was
canceled after the Manhattan Theater Club received telephoned death
threats was precisely about the fear that raising the stakes can be
particularly risky at a time of raw political and religious
sensitivities and when serious drama is increasingly dependent on
revenue from image-conscious contributors.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of ``Corpus Christi,'' the Catholic League for
Religious and Civil Rights threatened to wage war against anyone
who staged the play, which features a gay Jesus-like figure who has
sex with his disciples offstage.
</P>
<P>
   The Manhattan Theater Club, one of the most respected theatrical
groups in the city, last Thursday agreed to reinstate McNally's
play after announcing a week earlier that it was removing it from
its fall schedule following the threats. The Catholic League
disavowed knowledge of the calls and said it condemned the threat
or use of violence.
</P>
<P>
   The theater club said its decision to withdraw the play was
based solely on security. But beyond the threats, much of the alarm
occasioned by the incident stemmed from the recognition among
theater people that serious drama depends in large part on outside
donors, like politically sensitive corporations, and how vulnerable
that can leave theater groups seeking both adventurous fare and a
broad audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Funding for the arts is becoming more and more difficult for
those out there chasing money,'' said Jim Nicola, artistic director
of the New York Theater Workshop, one of the city's major nonprofit
theaters, which also include the Roundabout and Lincoln Center
Theaters. ``There's very little fortitude among the funders for any
scent of scandal or controversy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The interesting thing to me about `Corpus Christi' was TWA's
withdrawal of its support,'' he added. ``What this really showed
was that if we're going to proceed, we need partnerships and
funders with courage and reliability, and that's getting harder and
harder to find.''
</P>
<P>
   Some theater people said the incident was a reflection of just
how intimidating the current political atmosphere can be.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very conservative time for the arts,'' said the
playwright Tony Kushner. ``You have the dismantling of the National
Endowment for the Arts, the defunding of arts organizations and the
increasing timidity of corporate sponsors. It has arts groups
running scared. Everyone's trying to be brave and hold the line,
but they remember how debilitating the debacles with the NEA were
and they're afraid to go through it again.''
</P>
<P>
   But the courts have created an environment hostile to outright
censorship of the arts, Kushner said. And other theatrical veterans
said that for all the ruckus, they did not find the current
political environment much more daunting than in the past,
certainly not more daunting that the McCarthy era of the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Producers are still willing to break their necks to put good
material onstage, and we have playwrights who are afraid of
nothing,'' said Alexander Cohen, a longtime Broadway producer.
``But plays of this kind of substance are essentially going the way
of the dodo bird, because the money is going to grand spectacles
featuring special effects. So we turn to our nonprofit theaters for
these kind of adventurous productions.''
</P>
<P>
   To many experts, that's the real difference between a
controversy that inflames public passions now and those in the
past, like the one surrounding ``The Deputy,'' by Rolf Hochhuth, a
German playwright. It created a furor in 1964 with its message that
Pope Pius XII was morally bankrupt in not denouncing Hitler and the
Nazi death camps.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, controversial fare essentially had to depend on the
interest and support of theatergoers and investors. Now the vast
majority of truly challenging fare is presented by nonprofit
theaters. And they are dependent for their money on more than box
office and traditional investors.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, tickets sales provided about $4.3 million, or less than
half the Manhattan Theater Club's $10 million budget. Private and
government grants accounted for just over $3 million, and the rest
came from special events, royalties and subsidiary rights and other
sources.
</P>
<P>
   Jed Bernstein, executive director of the League of American
Theaters and Producers, said that in the end both for-profit
theaters and their nonprofit sisters faced pretty much the same
pressure: the need to attract audiences. In that sense, a boring
noncontroversial production sometimes can be just as lethal as one
that is deemed offensive.
</P>
<P>
   But the comparison with ``The Deputy'' may still be instructive
in other ways.
</P>
<P>
   In his review in The New York Times, Howard Taubman wrote, ``Our
theater rarely touches on moral issues of this magnitude,'' both a
tribute to the play and a commentary on how rare truly
groundbreaking theater, at least on Broadway, was then and is now.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest difference, several people in the theater said, is
that the potential for violent protest or genuine terrorism is much
more on people's minds now. They said that left less room for
second-guessing the sincerity if not necessarily the wisdom of the
Manhattan Theater Club's initial decision to back away from the
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy for the sideline sitters to be judgmental, but when
you have 11-year-olds committing massacres, you look at these
things differently than you used to,'' said Emanuel Azenberg,
another veteran producer.
</P>
</TEXT>
