<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio teams get ready for upcoming State rivalry
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ They are on the banks of San Francisco Bay at
Candlestick Point, but some can't help but let their minds drift
toward the shores of Lake Erie.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the Cincinnati Reds finish their chores with the San
Francisco Giants, they return home to hopefully play ungracious
hosts to the Cleveland Indians over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Taubensee, Jeff Shaw, Danny Graves and Scott Winchester _
all former Indians _ admit their anticipation rivals Christmas Eve
when they were greedy-minded kids. For Taubensee, the spike is on
the other foot. He played briefly for the Indians in 1991 _ 105
losses, dreary Cleveland Municipal Stadium, manager John McNamara.
</P>
<P>
   ``McNamara got fired and Mike Hargrove was hired,'' Taubensee
said. ``They were beginning their transition period . . . and I was
part of the transition. They made me a transaction.''
</P>
<P>
   After the 1991 season, Taubensee and pitcher Willie Blair were
traded to Houston for Dave Rohde and some character named Kenny
Lofton.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, the Reds had just won the World Series (1990), so
everybody said Cincinnati had the great organization,'' Taubensee
said. ``Now that the Indians are winning, everybody says that's the
great organization. That's the definition of a great organization .
. . a winning organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Taubensee is looking forward to the three-game set in Cinergy
because the stadium will be packed, even though he realizes the
majority will be Cleveland fans who can purchase tickets in
sold-out Jacobs Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's fine,'' he said. ``Maybe we can win some of them over.
Hopefully we don't lose some of our fans to them. But we're
defending state champions. We beat them two of three in Cleveland
last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw carries an ingrained dislike for Hargrove and general
manager John Hart. He was Cleveland's No. 1 draft choice in 1986,
but he remembers the day in late 1992 when Hargrove called him into
his office and told him, ``You'll never pitch in the major leagues.
You aren't good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   That stuck in Shaw's craw like a chicken bone and to this day he
says, ``Every time I get a save I hope Hargrove picks up the paper
and sees it. I never got a fair shake there and I can't care if you
are a No. 1 draft pick or a No. 100 draft pick you don't treat
people that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers Graves and Winchester are recent-vintage former
Indians, from the successful days, acquired last July in the trade
that sent John Smiley to Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Winchester, a starter, won't face the Indians _ but wishes he
were.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be kinda fun,'' he said. ``You like to face a team
that signed you (14th, 1995) and it would be a great challenge with
that lineup and those hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Winchester calls the two organizations, ``Two teams going in
different directions. The Indians are trying to win the World
Series and utilize their minor leaguers (in trades) to put them
over the top. Cincinnati operates right now by using veteran
major-league players to get young minor-league players . . . the
two organizations are in two different points of time _ the Indians
trying to win now, the Reds trying to win later.''
</P>
<P>
   Graves is full of anticipation at the possibility of facing his
former team out of the bullpen and has been since last winter when
he told his wife, Andre, ``I hope I'm in the big leagues with the
Reds when they play Cleveland.''
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that I think they made a mistake trading me, but you
always want a chance to show your old team you can pitch in the big
leagues,'' he said
</P>
<P>
   Difference in the two organizations? Plenty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the young and cheaper development stage,'' Graves
said. ``Over there, they're ready to win the World Series. The
situation for young players is better with the Reds. The Indians
don't have time to develop players at the major-league level. The
Reds do and that's better for young players. You can't learn to
pitch in the minors watching major-league games every night on
SportsCenter. You learn by pitching in the majors.''
</P>
<P>
   And Graves hopes part of his education advances this weekend
against the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
