<SLUG> BC-FUTURE-BATES&AMP;WALKER04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Futures of Bates, Walker unsure
 &HT;    By Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Two of the most popular football players in
Dallas were absent when Cowboys coach Chan Gailey introduced
special teams at Tuesday's minicamp.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bates and Herschel Walker, two of the league's best
special-teams players, have not been offered contracts for 1998 and
are not eligible to attend camp. It's unclear whether either player
will be offered a contract before the start of summer camp on July
16.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said Bates and Walker have not been forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for Herschel, we're still in the decision-making process
with that,'' Gailey said. ``Right now we have that on hold. Bill
Bates is in the same situation. We're trying to evaluate where we
are as a football team.''
</P>
<P>
   Bates and Walker are unrestricted free agents, meaning they are
free to negotiate with any team. Both, however, are hoping to
extend their careers with the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of the three-day camp at Valley Ranch is to install
special teams and ``rehash'' the offense Gailey installed earlier
this spring. After Tuesday's practice Gailey said the players have
been taught 85 percent of the offense.
</P>
<P>
   No player has benefited more from Gailey's offense than Billy
Davis, who is No. 2 on the depth chart at wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to put myself on a pedestal but, at the same
time, I'm not going to put myself on any lower step than someone
else,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey has installed four- and five-receiver sets. At times the
Cowboys line up three receivers on one side of the field. Gailey
stopped short of calling it a ``gimmick'' offense, saying he wants
to have a run-pass balance.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are expected to keep six receivers _ Davis, Michael
Irvin, Stepfret Williams, Ernie Mills, Macey Brooks and newcomer
Jimmy Oliver.
</P>
<P>
   On defense, veteran defensive end Tony Tolbert remains with the
team but no one is certain how much longer he'll be around. Chronic
knee problems have hurt Tolbert, who counts about $3.4 million
against the salary cap. The Cowboys would save $2 million against
the cap if they cut him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that a healthy Tony Tolbert would help this
football team,'' Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: Nate Newton reported to minicamp at 293 pounds, an
all-time low for the 13-year veteran who weighed nearly 380 last
season. Strength Coach Joe Juraszek wants Newton to gain 25 pounds
of muscle by training camp. ... Center Clay Shiver weighed in at
285 pounds, an increase of 20 pounds from last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have a tentative scrimmage set against New Orleans
on Aug. 11 in Shreveport. ... Wide receiver Michael Irvin, after
learning that the temperature in Wichita Falls has hovered near the
100-degree mark for weeks, said, ``As soon as Deion (Sanders) heard
that, he decided his ankle started to hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Troy Aikman said he recently encouraged Denver's
John Elway to return for his 16th NFL season. ``Selfishly, I wanted
him to come back. He's great for the NFL. I have a lot of respect
for John in the way he handles himself. He's a goodwill ambassador
for the game, and you hate to see the league lose guys like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Cowboys Coach Barry Switzer attended minicamp Tuesday,
talking about his new movie ``Varsity Blues,'' which was filmed in
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
