<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Test Drive: Tweaking pays off for new Accord
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Face it. Mainstream family sedans -- both domestics
and imports -- don't get much glory.
</P>
<P>
   They're like washing machines in the sense that they only get
attention when they're not working properly. But Honda set out to
change that with the '98 Accord, and it's paid off for the
Japanese-based manufacturer and buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Billed as the ``All-American'' because it's built in Marysville,
Ohio, with Japan supplying only 15 percent of its parts, this
Accord really is new. The badging is the same, but the 22-year-old
Accord's other characteristics are new or carefully improved. It's
no head-turner, but it is better looking, drives and rides
noticeably smoother, and has moved up to midsize status.
</P>
<P>
   To settle behind the wheel is to notice that the seats are a
touch larger and supportive in a non-sporty way, the instruments
are easier to read, controls have been moved up and about, and the
view is remarkably unimpeded.
</P>
<P>
   Take it to the road, and things get better. The 200-horsepower
V-6 engine, although not hushed, is keenly responsive, the
automatic four-speed generally glides through the gears, and the
Accord handles docilely and adroitly. It's no sports sedan, but it
will mimic one, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   But here's what many of the 300,000-plus expected to buy Accords
this model year will seize on: The prices are virtually unchanged.
Critics can't miss this because Honda's elaborate press kit --
football-themed and with a hidden noisemaker that produces the roar
of a crowd when it's opened -- comes with a price list red-shirted
from '97.
</P>
<P>
   What that means is the test Accord LX sedan is base-priced at
$21,550, as it was last year. The bottom line is $22,024, with
floor mats adding $79 and destination charges totaling $395.
</P>
<P>
   It's that way all up and down the line, which includes DX and EX
sedans and a coupe whose exterior shares only headlights with the
sedan and is available in LX and EX trim. Prices range from about
$15,000 for the base sedan to about $24,000 for decked-out sedans
and coupes.
</P>
<P>
   Engine choices, in addition to the 200-horsepower V-6, are a
150-hp, 2.3-liter four-cylinder and a 135-hp four-banger. (A
four-cylinder that meets California's Low Vehicle Emission standard
is available nationally.)
</P>
<P>
   A five-speed manual is offered on four-cylinder Accords, while
the automatic four-speed is standard on V-6-powered Accords and
available for the four-cylinder cars.
</P>
<P>
   Move past the base cars, and the Accords have most of the
amenities covered, making options passe. Sure, some may whine about
the lack of ashtrays and lighter and rear-seat drink holders, but
there's little else to invoke protest, other than the engine and
road noise that penetrates the cabin and the automatic transmission
-- sometimes the shifts make it seem it's adapting to driving
style, and other times it seems to be a slacker.
</P>
<P>
   At the end
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
