<SLUG> BC-MECHANIC04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beware of bad air-conditioning retrofits
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- With summer approaching and temperatures climbing
higher, more air-conditioning systems will require servicing. As
the price for R-12 -- or Freon, the most common but now banned
refrigerant -- continues to escalate, owners of older vehicles with
A/C systems that use this refrigerant will become the prime targets
for the retrofit hawkers.
</P>
<P>
   These are shops that will encourage you to switch your air
conditioning system over to a money-saving, alternative
refrigerant.
</P>
<P>
   Beware! While there are legitimate circumstances where a system
should be retrofitted, there are many instances where minor repairs
and a recharge will suffice. It's still legal to use R-12 in
systems that already are using it; it's the manufacture of more
R-12 that's outlawed because of the damage it does to the Earth's
upper-atmosphere ozone layer.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, steer clear of shops using refrigerants other than
R-12 or 134-A, the approved replacement for R-12. Although the
other ``accepted'' refrigerants may work well and their price is
attractive, it could prove to be a nightmare when needing future
service.
</P>
<P>
   Most reputable shops recommend retrofitting an A/C system only
when the situation warrants it, such as compressor failure or the
need to replace multiple components. Major repairs of this sort
require that the entire system be flushed out with a cleaning
chemical that removes all traces of debris, old refrigerant and
lubricating oils. This, in turn, provides the best possible
environment for the 134-A replacement, along with the new oil,
neither of which are compatible with R-12.
</P>
<P>
   The end result is a system that is environmentally friendly,
less expensive to maintain (the cost of the refrigerant in the
event of future repair) and, most importantly, uncontaminated by
residue from old R-12.
</P>
<P>
   There are claims and plenty of arguments throughout the industry
that ridding the system of the old chemical is unnecessary and that
it is acceptable simply to ``evacuate and recharge'' using the
replacement refrigerant and oil. However, the use of refrigerant
identifiers is uncovering a flaw.
</P>
<P>
   Greg, a mechanic friend of mine, told me about a customer whose
car needed some air-conditioning repairs, including a compressor
and 134-A retrofit. She declined the work at that time but returned
sometime later with a knocking compressor. While inspecting the
system, Greg noticed the old R-12 service fittings had been
replaced with new 134-A type, indicating the system had been
serviced elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   When he ``sniffed'' the system with his identifier, it confirmed
that the refrigerant had indeed been replaced with 134-A and also
contained contamination from a little of the old R-12. He could
neither recover nor dispose of the contaminated refrigerant, so he
closed the hood and sent her and her knocking compressor on their
way.
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to think that the shop that ``retrofitted'' her system
didn't knowingly contaminate it. The fact they were using the
industry-accepted 134-A instead of one of the other replacements
gives them some credence. I'm more inclined to believe that the
R-12 was residual. Unfortunately, it was a costly mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps she'll find a shop that won't identify the contaminated
refrigerant. In turn, that refrigerant will be recovered and
recycled and find its way into another system, maybe yours.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
