<SLUG> BC-SHARP-DRIVING04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Journalists test Dodge Neons with a 'race within a race'
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- There are a lot of ways to test a vehicle, but none
is more fun than on a racetrack. Over Memorial Day weekend, I did
just that with a Dodge Neon at Lime Rock Park in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the Memorial Day program included two Dodge Neon
Challenge races. The Neon Challenge is a series of events where
Sports Car Club of America racers have the opportunity to compete
for prize money.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the program, Dodge invited three journalists to
compete in the event: Car &AMP; Driver's Steven Cole Smith, Popular
Science's Dan McCosh and me. For McCosh, it was his first outing.
Smith has spent some time on dirt tracks in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   And I've made a lap or two on tracks for some 20 years. I missed
all the practice sessions, so my weekend began with qualifying.
Smith qualified fastest of the three of us. I was second and McCosh
third.
</P>
<P>
   When the green flag dropped, I passed Smith going into the first
turn and led for 19 laps of the 20-lap event. On the final lap, I
moved over to let the guys by who were racing for the money. The
leader cleared with no problem, but the second-place car bumped me
in the turn. Smith went by while I was spinning in the weeds.
</P>
<P>
   The second race began from our finishing positions from the
first. Smith was ahead of me. He had also mastered the art of
blocking. This time it took five laps for me to get by.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the race, I was some six seconds ahead of Smith.
He claimed he ``let me by'' and was ``planning to make his move on
the last lap.'' Fact is, we were 27th and 28th in a 34-car field.
</P>
<P>
   Steve rationalized that our stock Dodge Neon ACR's, which had
only safety equipment as extras, were 100 pounds heavier than the
club race cars, had smaller tires and that the rear wing caused
more drag. He finally got Dodge to concede that there was at least
a two-second difference in the cars' performance.
</P>
<P>
   That says a lot for a stock Neon compared with one with about
$10,000 worth of preparation.
</P>
<P>
   The Lime Rock Dodge Neon Challenge will be broadcast July 5 at
12:30 p.m. and July 11 at 6 a.m. on ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
