   NETWATCH _ ATLANTA _ For those of you who know nothing about
soccer, the World Cup is the best place to learn. One way for
clueless Americans to bone up on World Cup news is on the Web.
(Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED 6/2. (f, l)
</P>
<P>
   TESTDRIVE _ ATLANTA _ Face it. Mainstream family sedans -- both
domestics and imports -- don't get much glory. But Honda set out to
change that with the '98 Accord, and it's paid off for the
Japanese-based manufacturer and buyers. (DeVault, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MECHANIC _ ATLANTA -- With summer approaching and temperatures
climbing higher, more air-conditioning systems will require
servicing. As the price for R-12 -- or Freon, the most common but
now banned refrigerant -- continues to escalate, owners of older
vehicles with A/C systems that use this refrigerant will become the
prime targets for the retrofit hawkers. Beware! (Carter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SHARP-DRIVING _ ATLANTA _ There are a lot of ways to test a
vehicle, but none is more fun than on a racetrack. Over Memorial
Day weekend, I did just that with a Dodge Neon at Lime Rock Park in
Connecticut. Dodge invited three journalists to compete in the
Dodge Neon Challenge races: Car &AMP; Driver's Steven Cole Smith,
Popular Science's Dan McCosh and me. For McCosh, it was his first
outing. Smith has spent some time on dirt tracks in Texas. (Sharp,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
