<HEADLINE>
MANY CALIFORNIANS CROSSED PARTY LINES IN STATE'S FIRST OPEN
PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIN McCORMICK and DIANA WALSH  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It was a day to abandon the party line.
</P>
<P>
   In California's first open primary election, voters were allowed
to try on new political hats and choose primary contenders from any
party.
</P>
<P>
   There appeared to be plenty of side-switching in Tuesday's
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people voted all over the map,'' said Kim Alexander,
director of the nonprofit California Voter Foundation. ``A lot of
voters thought it was fun to cross party lines and vote on the
other side.''
</P>
<P>
   It appeared that people from all political parties flocked to
vote in the most exciting contest going _ the Democratic primary
race for governor among Lt. Governor Gray Davis, millionaire Al
Checchi and U.S. Rep. Jane Harman.
</P>
<P>
   While in other races only about 48 percent of the voters chose
Democrats, in that race 61 percent of the voters chose a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would indicate that a lot of Republicans voted
Democrat,'' said pollster David Binder. ``It might be because of
the race's visibility. The Democratic campaign attracted so much
attention that Republicans decided to cross over.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To have Republicans selecting the Democratic nomination and
vice versa is kind of weird,'' said Simon Brown of San Francisco,
who said he enjoyed voting in the open primary anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Some voters said they used the open primary to attempt sabotage
by casting a vote for the opposing party's weakest candidate.
</P>
<P>
   With Attorney General Dan Lungren facing only token opposition
for the Republican nomination for governor, former California
Republican Party Chairman John Herrington saw it as a chance to
throw a wrench into the workings of the Democratic machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I voted for Gray Davis, because I believe Lungren can beat him
better than any other candidate,'' said Herrington, who added that
Jane Harman was the candidate his party feared most. ``I voted that
way and I urged my friends to do it too.''
</P>
<P>
   But Herrington and a number of political pundits said they
doubted that such sophisticated cross-voting was used by many
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that will happen in six or eight years when people get
the hang of the open primary,'' said Garry South, campaign manager
for Gray Davis, who won the Democratic nomination. ``But now there
are frankly not that many voters who are aware of the change.''
</P>
<P>
   Deciphering exactly how the open primary affected the vote may
take days or weeks. But clearly it added to both the confusion and
the excitement of Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   Voters were faced with one of the most imposing ballots in state
history, with a long list of candidates not separated by party. The
election was the first time that independent or non-partisan voters
could participate in a primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good,'' said Ray Murray, a Noe Valley independent who
cast his vote for the first time in a primary Tuesday. ``I've
always had a concern about the primary and I've considered signing
on with a party just so I could vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Others found the system long-winded and perplexing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ballot's so vague. You can't tell who's who,'' said Bernal
Heights voter Teresa Taylor, who said she sat with her four grown
daughters for an hourlong ballot study session before even
venturing to the polls. ``Just getting ready to vote was
time-consuming.''
</P>
<P>
   The open primary, approved by voters in 1996, was designed to
increase turnout and give moderate candidates a better chance.
</P>
<P>
   Long before voters ever went to the polls, the system was making
profound changes in the way campaigning is done in California.
</P>
<P>
   With the new format, primary candidates could no longer focus
solely on members of their own political party. They had to cater
to independents and moderates in the other parties as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has increased campaign costs,'' said Herbert Alexander, an
emeritus political science professor at the University of
California at Los Angeles. ``One state senator told me it used to
cost him $100,000 to send mailers to the people on his mailing
list. Now it costs him $250,000 because he has to mail to
independents and members of the other party as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The open primary also meant that candidates who had no
challengers in their own party couldn't just sit out the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The open primary forced Dan Lungren to spend $4 million in the
primary,'' said Bob Mulholland, campaign adviser to the Democratic
Party.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren complained that the open primary is one more thing
making it more expensive to run for office.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those who were selling the idea of these open or blanket
primaries as being better for the public, I think they ought to
take another look at that,'' he said. ``This ups the ante, this
causes the entry fee to run for political office, raises it
tremendously.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
