<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-US-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID PROTESTS, CLINTON SEEKS TRADE STATUS RENEWAL FOR CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``f'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton triggered the annual battle over
U.S. trade relations with China on Wednesday but this year's fight
quickly became ensnared with questions of Chinese government
political contributions and U.S. technology transfers to Beijing,
in addition to the usual criticism of China's human rights
policies.
</P>
<P>
   In defending his decision to grant China ``most favored nation''
trading status, Clinton described China as the linchpin of U.S.
strategic interests in Asia that are now under challenge by the
nuclear testing of India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   The president promised to ``deal forthrightly'' with China on
what had been the main area of contention between Washington and
Beijing: human rights. But he made clear that human rights would
take a back seat to strategic concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to renew (China's trading status) would be to sever our
economic and .... strategic relationship with China, turning our
back on a fourth of the world at a time when cooperation for world
peace and security is especially important,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Congress now has 90 days to disapprove Clinton's decision to
renew ``most favored nation'' trading status for China. Because the
president could veto such a resolution of disapproval, a two-thirds
vote of the House and Senate would be needed to override such a
veto and cancel the administration's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Absent that, U.S.-Chinese trade relations would continue
uninterrupted for another year.
</P>
<P>
   Reaffirmation of China's most favored nation trading status puts
China at the same level as virtually all U.S. trading partners in
terms of import tariffs, normally in the four to six percent range.
</P>
<P>
   The president stressed the role that China plays in the U.S.
economy. U.S. exports to China have more than tripled in the past
decade to $12.8 billion and an estimated 170,000 U.S. jobs depend
on these exports, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship is no one-way street; China exports $62 billion
annually to the United States, according to the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce, thus creating a huge trade imbalance in favor of China.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's bid for renewal of China's trading status drew
skepticism from some members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a tough vote,'' said House Majority Dick
Armey, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in both the House and Senate are launching
investigations of a complicated web of allegations involving New
York-based Loral Space &AMP; Communications Ltd. and its chairman,
Bernard Schwartz, who has contributed $1.3 million to Democrats in
the six years since Clinton's election.
</P>
<P>
   Last February, Clinton granted a waiver to Loral to launch a
satellite atop a Chinese rocket even though the Justice Department
was investigating whether Loral in 1996 gave China missile
technology with military applications.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the Justice Department is probing allegations by
former Democratic fundraiser Johnny Chung that he funneled
large-dollar contributions to Democrats from Chinese aerospace
executive Liu Chaoying, daughter of a retired prominent Chinese
Army commander.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame that President Clinton has endangered a strong,
bipartisan trade policy by his slow reaction to serious national
security questions raised by the questionable transfer of sensitive
technology to China,'' said Rep. John Boehner, R-Ohio. ``To ensure
that we can continue our free trade approach, the president must
come clean right away and offer complete, forthright answers to
these serious questions.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House has defended the Loral waiver, saying it came
only after assurances by the Pentagon and State Department that no
sensitive technology would be compromised.
</P>
<P>
   In previous years, an alliance of liberal Democrats and
conservative Republicans on Capitol Hill has cited Chinese human
rights violations in their unsuccessful efforts to derail the
annual renewal of China's trading status. The renewal process has
become a yearly ritual in which all aspects of America's often
testy relationship with China bubble to the surface for
re-examination.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, some Democrats on Capitol Hill again cited human
rights as a reason to oppose Clinton's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must not reward the Chinese Communist government for its
continuing political repression and tyranny,'' said House Minority
Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., said she was ``disappointed once
again'' with Clinton's decision. Pelosi accused China of providing
nuclear technology to Pakistan, running a $63 billion trade surplus
against the United States and continuing to hold political and
religious dissidents in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Since November, China has released two prominent dissidents,
Wang Dan and Wei Jingsheng. But according to Amnesty International,
at least 250 others involved in the 1989 democracy protests in
Tiananmen Square in Beijing are still in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday marks the ninth anniversary of the Chinese government's
crackdown on the Tiananmen Square protesters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, representatives of human rights organizations
downplayed the significance of the trade issue as a wedge against
China on human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Renewal of China's trade status ``doesn't serve as an effective
instrument on human rights'' because Clinton declared in 1994 that
U.S. trade policy toward China would not be affected by human
rights issues, said Xiao Quiang, executive director of the New
York-based organization, Human Rights in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``The release of the dissidents is a significant achievement and
the administration deserves credit,'' he said. ``But that's not
enough. We need a consistent policy (in which the administration)
exerts pressure on the Chinese government.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Jendrzejczyk, Washington director of the Asia division of
Human Rights Watch, said his organization is focusing on Clinton's
summit meeting in Beijing later this month and using China's desire
to join the World Trade Organization as a wedge to improve human
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``MFN (most favored nation trading status) has become much more
routine,'' he said. ``Joining the World Trade Organization is a
much bigger carrot to the Chinese.'' Admission to the World Trade
Organization would help China open markets and lower trading
barriers around the world, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Chamber of Commerce praised renewal of China's trading
status. ``There's been tremendous progress in China on human
rights, and that's because of the U.S. policy of engagement,'' said
Myron Brilliant, manager of the chamber's Asia division. Cutting
off Chinese trade would be ``shooting U.S business in the foot,''
he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
