<HEADER>
A2756 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERB-ROSEMARY-1500(2T     06-03 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERB-ROSEMARY-1500(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDITERRANEAN FLAVOR ADDS FLAIR TO YOUR SUMMER TABLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROL NUCKOLS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABCs: Rosemary is a tender perennial (some varieties are
hardier). A native of the Mediterranean countries, Portugal and
northwestern Spain, this evergreen shrub is widely cultivated.
Upright varieties may reach 6 feet in height, prostrate varieties
12 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Growing conditions: Full sun; well-drained alkaline soil. Do not
overwater. Plant from transplants. Benefits from occasional foliar
sprays of seaweed solution and light feedings of fish emulsion.
Mulch well to protect from frost.
</P>
<P>
   Companion plants: Sage, dill, cabbage. Flowers attract bees.
</P>
<P>
   Food pairings: Lamb, chicken and other meats and poultry,
potatoes and other vegetables, breads, butters, cheese spreads,
tomato-based pasta sauces.
</P>
<P>
   Caveats: Subject to some spider mite or webworm damage in the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   CRISP UNFRIED CHICKEN
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6 to 8
</P>
<P>
   Zest (colored part of peel) from 6 lemons, removed with a zester
and minced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh lemon juice (from about 6 lemons)
</P>
<P>
   8 garlic cloves, peeled and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup chopped fresh rosemary
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 chickens (about 7 pounds total), each in 8 serving pieces, all
visible fat removed, see Note
</P>
<P>
   2 cups fine dry bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup grated Parmigiano-Reggiano cheese
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   In a food processor, combine lemon zest and juice, garlic,
rosemary and olive oil. Process until fairly smooth.
</P>
<P>
   In a shallow, nonreactive dish, combine lemon mixture and
chicken. Cover and refrigerate overnight, turning once or twice.
Return chicken just to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Position a rack in the middle of the oven and preheat to 425
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In a wide, shallow bowl, stir together bread crumbs and cheese.
Remove chicken pieces from marinade and season lightly with salt
and pepper. One at a time, dredge chicken pieces in bread-crumb
mixture, coating thoroughly. Transfer chicken to a jelly-roll pan.
Bake until chicken is crisp, golden brown and just cooked through
but still juicy, about 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serve hot or warm.
</P>
<P>
   Note: If desired, substitute boneless chicken breasts or thighs;
shorten baking time by about half.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 398 calories, 23 grams fat, 5
grams carbohydrates, 39 grams protein, 120 milligrams cholesterol,
208 milligrams sodium, 53 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Pamela Morgan's Flavors'' by Pamela Morgan and Michael
McLaughlin (Viking, $29.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ROSEMARY MILLET CAKES WITH SUN-DRIED TOMATOES
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 (makes 8 cakes)
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, peeled and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons finely chopped fresh rosemary
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups homemade chicken stock or reduced-sodium canned
chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup millet, rinsed, see Note
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   8 oil-packed sun-dried tomatoes (16 halves), drained and
coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   In a medium saucepan over low heat, warm 2 tablespoons of the
olive oil. Add garlic and cook uncovered, stirring occasionally
without browning, for 3 minutes. Add rosemary and cook, stirring,
for 1 minute.
</P>
<P>
   Add stock and salt and bring to a simmer. Stir in millet, cover
and adjust heat to low. Cook undisturbed until millet has absorbed
all the liquid and is tender, about 25 minutes. Remove from heat
and let stand, covered, for 5 minutes. Cool to room temperature.
Millet can be prepared up to a day in advance. Cover tightly and
refrigerate. Return to room temperature before using.
</P>
<P>
   In a food processor, combine half the millet and the eggs and
process until smooth. Stir puree into remaining whole millet. Fold
in tomatoes and season generously with pepper. Form mixture into 8
2 1/2-inch cakes.
</P>
<P>
   In a large skillet over medium-high heat, warm remaining 3
tablespoons olive oil until very hot, but not smoking. Gently set
cakes in oil. Lower heat slightly and cook, turning once, until
crisp and golden brown on both sides, about 10 minutes total.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Millet is available in health-food stores.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 376 calories, 25 grams fat, 27
grams carbohydrates, 12 grams protein, 239 milligrams cholesterol,
1,014 milligrams sodium, 59 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Pamela Morgan's Flavors''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ROSEMARY-FIG CHUTNEY
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 6 cups
</P>
<P>
   4 cups fresh orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds dried Calimyrna figs, tough stems removed, figs
coarsely chopped, see Note
</P>
<P>
   1 cup golden raisins
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup apricot preserves OR orange marmalade
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup apple cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon crushed red pepper
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons minced fresh rosemary
</P>
<P>
   In a large, heavy, nonreactive pan, combine orange juice, figs,
raisins, preserves, sugar, vinegar, salt and red pepper. Set over
medium heat and bring to a simmer, skimming any foam that may form.
Stir in rosemary, then cook partially covered, stirring
occasionally, until figs are tender and mixture is thick and shiny,
20 to 30 minutes. Remove from heat and cool to room temperature.
Cover and refrigerate at least overnight. Return to room
temperature before serving. Chutney will keep for 1 month. Serve
with pork, lamb, chicken or beef. MORE &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
