<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2785 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-GOLD-RUSH-2TAKE     06-03 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-GOLD-RUSH-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. MONEY MANAGERS HOPE TO STRIKE GOLD IN JAPAN 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(dc) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The Great Japan Money Rush is on.
</P>
<P>
   With $9 trillion in private savings up for grabs, international
banks and money managers are hurtling into Tokyo to stake their
claims. Japan's ``big bang'' market liberalization, which began in
April, is breaking down the barriers and luring the likes of
Travelers Group , which this week bought a 25 percent share of
Nikko Securities, the country's third-largest brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. and General Electric Capital have already
picked up ailing Japanese institutions or their branches and are
now trying to rescue them with Western-style management and
marketing techniques. And still other American companies will be
making a giant push over the next few months, in part because by
December foreign institutions will be allowed for the first time to
sell mutual funds in partnership with Japanese banks.
</P>
<P>
   In their struggle to win a larger share of the market in the
world's second-biggest economy, the Americans are redrawing the
rules of the financial playing field here and sending shock waves
down the halls of their Japanese competitors. And though foreigners
have stumbled in the dark for years in Japan, this time the prize
is too big to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any other opportunity in the world
three, five, 10 years from now that's a larger opportunity than
Japan in the asset management business,'' said John R. Alkire, a
managing director who heads Morgan Stanley Asset Management in
Japan, a unit of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``If you want to stake
out your house in this gold rush, you want to make sure you get
your pegs out there as far as you can.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not just the Americans who are rushing in; the Swiss Bank
Corp., for example, has formed an asset management venture with
Japan's Long-Term Credit Bank. But while other Western institutions
are also prospecting here, it is the Americans who have put down
the most claims.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is a chunk of the savings of people like Megumi Narita,
a young training consultant who keeps her money in a neighborhood
bank _ earning less than 1 percent interest. The Japanese are
enormously conservative investors, leaving the bulk of their
savings in banks and the postal savings system, but young people
like Miss Narita are increasingly fed up with the dismal interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I often see middle-aged men on the train reading the stock
market tables in the newspaper, and I want to buy, too,'' Miss
Narita said the other day, discussing investments with friends.
``But as a young woman, I've always been a bit embarrassed to do
so. And I never can figure out what the tables say anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for the Americans will be to persuade Miss Narita,
and millions more like her, to take the first step and actually
make new investments. Indeed, the money management and insurance
landscape has proved to be a minefield for starry-eyed foreign
companies in the past. For years, foreign companies banged on doors
here, trying to break into this intensely clubby, closed and
secretive market.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch opened three branches in the late 1980s and 1990,
only to close them in 1993. Fidelity Investments, the giant mutual
fund arm of the Boston-based FMR Corp., has had an office here
since 1969, but its sleepy business did not get very far, until
recently. Likewise, after winning its first pension management
account in April 1990, Mercury Asset Management Japan Ltd., a unit
of Merrill Lynch, had to wait two years before it got a second.
</P>
<P>
   What is different now is that Japan's big bang is liberalizing
the arcane rules that have fettered the financial industry. Under
international pressure to revive its sinking economy and its rigid
markets, Japan seems willing to let foreign companies acquire its
institutions, or pieces of them, to gain a place on an inside
track.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the Americans are now knocking on doors that the
Japanese government appears eager to open.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last 50 years, we have been relatively isolated,
insulated from the rest of the world in terms of information
technology and finance,'' said Eisuke Sakakibara, vice finance
minister for international affairs. ``That has to change.''
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, American companies are betting, as they roll
out their new marketing strategies, that profits will pile up.
After all, many of them remember just how well they did after
London's big bang in 1986 and New York's May Day liberalization in
1975. Those efforts led to a broad restructuring of the financial
markets in Britain and America, and now Americans and Japanese
alike are hoping that the liberalization will do the same for
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Japanese companies are also petrified by what they call the
Wimbledon phenomenon: since Britain opened up its national tennis
tournament to foreigners, few Britons have won the title.
Similarly, while Britain's big bang made London a major
international financial center, British companies wound up playing
only a minor role.
</P>
<P>
   It is far too soon to say that the same thing will happen here,
but one trend seems clear: American companies are competing with
Japanese institutions on their home turf and, in the process,
changing the way the market works.
</P>
<P>
   ``Foreigners have been a catalyst for change in Japan,'' said
Clifford J. Shaw, president of Mercury Asset Management Japan.
``Whatever way it happens, we are going to get from here to there.
We are going to get a more efficient financial system.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Japanese and American companies have been tying the
knot in droves through alliances, partnerships and cooperative
ventures in asset management and insurance. Bankers Trust New York
Corp. is forming a business arrangement with Nippon Credit Bank,
for instance, while American International Group is interested in
acquiring Aoba Life Insurance. And in discussing his company's deal
with Nikko, Sanford I. Weill, chairman and chief executive of
Travelers, said that a similar arrangement with a Japanese
insurance company might be next.
</P>
<P>
   Other American companies are increasing their marketing efforts,
and the response has been promising. When Fidelity ran color
advertisements in Japanese newspapers last December, telephone
inquiries came tumbling in, even though the first ads did not
include a phone number. When Fidelity did display its number this
spring in two more ads, there was a flood of several thousand
calls.
</P>
<P>
   For several companies, business is already rolling in, along
with nice fees. Goldman, Sachs Investment Trust Management Japan
Ltd., a unit of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., began selling investment
trusts just over two years ago, and now it has $6 billion under
management. Similarly, within four months from opening its first
trust in December last year, Merrill Lynch brought in $2.5 billion
and had to slow sales. Alliance Capital Investment Trust Management
Inc. has gathered $5 billion in 17 months.
</P>
<P>
   The competition, of course, is going to become extremely fierce,
the profit opportunities are likely to shrink and not everyone,
including the operations run by foreigners, may survive. For now,
though, there should be enough business to go around, especially
because there are so few formidable players.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And while the rules have already been relaxed in pension
management, regulations will soon allow companies to offer new and
varied kinds of trusts that are similar to American-style mutual
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese investors are wary of their own stock market, which has
been depressed since the early 1990s, so they have shied from
Japanese investment trusts, which tend to put money in domestic
stocks and bonds. But many Japanese are now flocking to foreign-run
trusts that invest in overseas stocks and bonds because they
believe _ sometimes mistakenly _ that the foreign managers have
more expertise and better results. Indeed, in April, foreign
companies for the first time sold more investment trusts here than
the Japanese did.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear that Japanese customers fully understand what
they are getting into, for foreign investments often carry a
currency risk, namely that a rising yen will wipe out profits
earned abroad. It could take just one bad wave _ a turn in exchange
or interest rates _ and the Japanese might go running back to their
friendly local brokers, who have visited them in their homes for
years and worked hard at forging strong relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Nomura Securities was caught in a financial scandal
and some of its businesses were suspended for up to five months.
Commercial customers fled to other underwriters, including Merrill.
But now Nomura has recovered and nearly all of that newly won
business has disappeared, Merrill says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't underestimate the value of relationships that
Japanese banks have had for many, many years,'' said John P.
Sievwright, the new president of Merrill Lynch Japan Ltd. ``They
don't fall apart overnight, and they certainly won't fall apart
because of big bang.''
</P>
<P>
   But those relationships are at least fraying, and the American
companies are jockeying for position to catch the stray cash.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill is taking over 33 branches and 2,000 employees from
Yamaichi Securities, a fraction of the operations of Japan's
fourth-largest brokerage firm, which filed for bankruptcy last
fall. Merrill estimated that it would incur net costs of $125
million for leases, furniture, salaries, technology and market
development this year. This summer, Merrill will operate the
largest non-Japanese brokerage-firm network in the country, though
it says its branches will look pretty much the same as when
Yamaichi was running them.
</P>
<P>
   There will be important differences, though, aside from new
products and the absence of uniforms that female employees had to
wear when Yamaichi was in charge. Merrill's employees will be
trained as financial planners to offer advice to customers, rather
than merely act as brokers. Still, when it opens its doors this
summer, Merrill is counting mainly on the old Yamaichi customers to
provide business.
</P>
<P>
   As for Fidelity, it is taking a different approach, one much
like its direct strategy at home: reliance on the telephone. In
addition to a small phone center it has already set up, Fidelity
may use land it recently purchased on the outskirts of Tokyo to
build a larger telemarketing operation. So far, it has gathered
nearly $3 billion to manage, up nearly 40 percent from the end of
1997.
</P>
<P>
   GE Capital spent $575 million to take over 500 sales offices and
the new business of the Toho Mutual Life Insurance Co. _ without
the debt and other demons from the Japanese company's past _ and
has already hung its signs on the doors. Analysts hailed the deal
as a smart way to gain entry.
</P>
<P>
   But General Electric is wary of overconfidence, and it says that
to win business it will simply have to do a better job than its
Japanese counterparts. It brings with it a few ideas to lower
costs, like centralizing the back office processing activities and
standardizing credit decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't come here and find we can walk all over them, by any
means,'' said K. Ronnie Baldwin, president of GE Capital Japan.
``The fact is that Japanese companies have an enormous capability
to improve and change. When challenged, they have been historically
able to rise to the occasion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
