<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CHINA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TAKES STEP TO RENEW CHINA'S TRADE STATUS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton moved Wednesday to renew most
favored nation trade status with China, saying the United States
must continue to engage the Asian giant.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton cited China's cooperative role in trying to contain the
escalating nuclear arms race between India and Pakistan and its
economic importance to the United States in making the annual
renewal.
</P>
<P>
   His decision immediately was condemned by members of Congress
who have 90 days to try to pass legislation blocking the MFN trade
status. Clinton may face a battle with lawmakers from both parties
in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to renew would be to sever our economic and, to a large
measure, our strategic relationship with China, turning our back on
a fourth of the world at a time when our cooperation for world
peace and security is especially important in light of the recent
events in South Asia,'' Clinton said in a Rose Garden event.
</P>
<P>
   But House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., said, ``I
oppose the president's actions. We must not reward the Chinese
Communist government for its continuing political repression and
tyranny.''
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, said, ``It is going
to be, I believe, a tough vote, and I believe it will be in fact
now a tougher vote than it was a year ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met early Wednesday with Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, who left for Geneva, where the United States has convened
the foreign ministers of the five permanent United Nations Security
Council members. China will chair the session intended to craft a
united response to the India-Pakistan crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important example of how our engagement with China
serves America's interest: stability in Asia, preventing the spread
of weapons of mass destruction, combatting international crime and
drug-trafficking, protecting the environment,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, we continue to deal forthrightly with China
on those issues where we disagree, notably on human rights; and
there clearly have been some concrete results as a result of this
engagement as well,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, appearing with Clinton in the Rose Garden, said, ``It
is very clear that the better the relations are between the United
States and China and the United States and Russia, the better we
can protect and serve the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright also sounded dire warnings on the state of play between
India and Pakistan, rivals who conducted underground nuclear tests
and threatened to deploy nuclear weapons aimed at each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing both sides can do is to cool it and
take a deep breath and to begin to climb out of the hole they have
dug themselves into,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The five permanent Security Council members _ the United States,
Russia, China, France and Britain _ also are the only five nations
with declared nuclear capability, and Albright said they intend to
keep the number limited to five.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (nonproliferation treaty) will not be amended to
accommodate either country,'' she declared of India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Albright pledged to do her best to craft an international
response to the crisis. However, she added, ``But do not make a
mistake: the risks of the moment are high and, for the moment, the
key choices will be made in New Delhi and Islamabad.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials have praised China for its
behind-the-scenes effort to contain the arms race. India's five
underground tests also were intended to rattle China, its neighbor
who has been allied with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   China first received MFN status in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton noted, despite the name, the status does not provide
special privileges but extends the same tariff treatment provided
to almost all other nations.
</P>
<P>
   China's trade status has sparked an annual battle since 1989
when the communist government massacred pro-democracy student
demonstrators in Tiananmen Square and cracked down on a growing
dissident movement.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt, the House's top Democrat, said he and other opponents
again would move to block the trade status. Last year, they drew
only 173 of the 218 votes needed to overturn Clinton's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt said, ``Human rights is a principle that can not be
allowed to fall prey to politics. America must stand for more than
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., however, said he expected the Senate
to endorse the trade renewal because ``on balance, it is in the
best interest of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Three Republican House members _ Speaker Newt Gingrich of
Georgia, Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill Archer of Texas and
Phil Crane of lllinois, wrote Clinton a letter saying: ``We welcome
the determination you made today to recommend the renewal of MFN
trade status for China, and we pledge to work with you in a
bipartisan manner to preserve our long-standing policy of
commercial and diplomatic engagement with the Chinese.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, however, there are additional controversies
enveloping China, and the three Republicans pledged in their letter
that the House would continue its investigation of those issues.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic donor Johnny Chung recently alleged a portion of the
money he gave to the Democratic Party came from a Chinese
corporation owned by the military there. His accusations continued
to spur an investigation into whether the Chinese government
attempted to influence the 1996 U.S. elections.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also came under fire for granting a waiver allowing a
satellite company owned by a major Democratic contributor to send
its satellite into orbit aboard a Chinese-launched rocket. The
company was under investigation by the Justice Department for
passing along sensitive rocket technology to China following a
previous rocket explosion that destroyed one of its satellites.
</P>
<P>
   The House, where critics charged that Clinton endangered
American security, voted overwhelming to ban U.S. companies from
launching satellites aboard Chinese rockets.
</P>
<P>
   The escalating Chinese controversy comes just weeks before
Clinton plans an official state visit to the country. Republicans
have called on him to cancel the trip until they investigate the
campaign finance allegations, and other critics have assailed him
for planning to attend an official greeting at Tiananmen Square. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
