<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2791 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILMED-COX &UR;  &UR; ByJEFFNES     06-03 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILMED-COX </SLUG>
     By JEFF NESMITH 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate next week is expected to take up a bill
seen by supporters as an initial step toward allowing retired
members of the military to enroll in the federal government's
civilian health care plan.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would establish a ``demonstration program'' under which
some retired military personnel who are eligible for Medicare would
be permitted to enroll in the Federal Employee Health Benefits Plan
(FEHBP), with the Defense Department paying 72 percent of their
premiums.
</P>
<P>
   The House of Representatives last week passed a similar plan
with only one dissenting vote.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing all retired members of the armed services to opt out of
the military's TRICARE health benefits plan in favor of FEHBP would
be a move that the Pentagon warns could have ``drastic
consequences'' for the military medical care system.
</P>
<P>
   But veterans groups and other organizations that have been
lobbying in recent years to allow retirees to leave TRICARE hail
the bills as a move toward opening FEHBP to their members.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first step (toward) providing America's military
retirees guaranteed access to quality health care, as they were
promised many years ago,'' said John Moon, commander-in-chief of
the Veterans of Foreign Wars.
</P>
<P>
   Both the House measure and the Senate bill, introduced by Sen.
Max Cleland, D-Ga., would be limited to retired military personnel
who are covered by Medicare, either because of disabilities or
because they have reached age 65.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department has long opposed shifting any retirees to
FEHBP _ even though its TRICARE program provides no health care
benefits to retirees who are eligible for Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have strong concerns about proposals allowing military
retirees to enroll in the FEHBP, particularly under-65 retirees who
already have TRICARE,'' Defense Secretary William Cohen said in an
April 30 letter to House National Security Committee Chairman Floyd
Spence, R-S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen noted that the Congressional Budget Office has estimated
that requiring the Defense Department to pay FEHBP premiums for
over-65 retirees would cost the government $1.4 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expanding FEHBP enrollment to retirees under age 65 would
increase these costs drastically,'' Cohen wrote. ``Requiring the
department to bear these additional costs would have drastic
consequences for the military health system.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those who are the most unhappy with TRICARE are military
retirees who are covered by Medicare, because as soon as they
become eligible for that plan, they are dropped from TRICARE by the
Defense Department.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill would require the Pentagon to use funds it
receives from selling surplus stockpiles of chromium, industrial
diamonds, paladium and platinum to pay FEHBP premiums for up to
70,000 Medicare-eligible retirees, a cost estimated at up to $100
million a year, depending on how many chose to enroll in the plan.
</P>
<P>
   The retirees could then use the FEHBP coverage to supplement
their Medicare benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Cleland's bill would provide for a smaller demonstration group
but would also require the Pentagon to extend TRICARE to
Medicare-eligible retirees and to set up a test program to provide
mail-order prescription drugs to retirees who do not live near
military hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The measure was approved in April by the Senate Armed Services
Committee as an amendment to the Defense Authorization Bill for the
next fiscal year. The authorization bill is expected to be voted on
as early as Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the Defense Department Office of Health
Affairs have warned that requiring the department to fund FEHBP
participation for some retirees will force it to reduce benefits it
currently provides in military hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   That could motivate others to opt out of TRICARE and into FEHBP,
creating a ``slippery slope'' that could wreck the military health
care system, Gary Christopherson, acting assistant secretary of
defense for health affairs told a House subcommittee in April.
</P>
<P>
   But Retired Army Col. Chuck Partridge, legislative affairs
director of the National Association for the Uniformed Services,
disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have this slash-and-burn policy of cutting back on
military health care,'' Partridge said. ``If these retirees could
get into military hospitals, they wouldn't even want FEHBP.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For use by clients of The New York Times News Service &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
