<SLUG> BC-GOLF-TECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLF'S RULE MAKERS CONSIDER CRACKDOWN ON EQUIPMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ja)  
 John Strege covers the golf equipment industry for Golf Digest and
Golf World magazine.  
 By JOHN STREGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was, perhaps, inevitable that the friction between tradition
and technology in golf would spark a controversy and set it ablaze.
The question confronting the industry now is how to control it
before it does irreparable harm to the game.
</P>
<P>
   On the side of tradition is the U.S. Golf Association, which has
been preparing to address its concern that technological advances
in equipment enable players to hit the ball with greater distance
and accuracy, in the process imperiling the integrity of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our franchise is to preserve and protect the game's ancient
and honorable traditions,'' said F. Morgan ``Buzz'' Taylor Jr., the
USGA president, and its point man on the technology issue. ``I
intend to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was installed as the USGA president in January, Taylor
suggested in his inaugural address that an influx of better
athletes armed with high-tech equipment ``combine to threaten
obsolescence of many of golf's historic venues.''
</P>
<P>
   On the side of technology are equipment manufacturers, who are
aggressively defending the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's inconceivable anybody would want to make the game
tougher,'' said Ely Callaway, founder and chairman of Callaway
Golf, the world leader in the sales of golf clubs.
</P>
<P>
   The approaching millenium has given the USGA pause to consider
further legislation on several fronts, among them whether to roll
back advances on the golf ball, limit the lengths of drivers and
putters, limit the minimum and maximum lofts of clubs, and whether
a 14-club limit is too many.
</P>
<P>
   But the most highly charged issue the USGA is confronting
involves woods, specifically whether thin-faced titanium woods
produce what commonly is called a trampoline effect. Such an effect
is in violation of 4-1e in the Rules of Golf, which states that the
clubface cannot ``have the effect at impact of a spring.''
</P>
<P>
   A trampoline effect occurs when the face of a clubhead deforms
at impact with a ball, then rebounds to its original position, in
theory propelling the ball farther than it would have gone had the
clubface been rigid. The expanded surface of a titanium clubface is
said to contain more elasticity than a smaller face, in much the
same way that the membrane of a larger drum would have more give
than it would on a smaller drum.
</P>
<P>
   The USGA has concluded from its tests that a trampoline effect
indeed exists in titanium drivers, according to Richard
Helmstetter, chief of new products for Callaway Golf. The USGA has
not publicly revealed the results of its tests, but it has informed
Helmstetter of its testing methods and what they demonstrate.
</P>
<P>
   According to Helmstetter, the USGA took an air cannon and fired
a golf ball at the center of a titanium plate at 160 feet per
second and measured the rebound speed of the ball. It used all
different thicknesses of plates, he said. ``They're charging that
some of the plates, the thinner ones, have a rebound speed that was
faster than it was on the thicker ones,'' Helmstetter said.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturers are concerned that the USGA is preparing to
declare that some of their clubs do not conform to the Rules of
Golf and at some point in the future will be declared illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not beyond logic to conclude that they'll take some
action with the drivers they're concerned about, maybe saying that
they're OK now, but as of a certain date they'll be
nonconforming,'' said Wally Uihlein, president of Titleist and
FootJoy Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The USGA's alternative is to grandfather in all existing
equipment, but to establish a standard that in the future will
limit the distance a club can hit a ball in testing procedures
established by the USGA. Such a standard would effectively curtail
technology advancing unabated as it has in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   David Fay, executive director of the USGA, recently said he
believes ``there will be some announcement beyond `we're looking at
it''' at the U.S. Open, scheduled for the week of June 15 at the
Olympic Club in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are substantial and conceivably include the USGA's
ability to retain its role as the governing body of the game in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Callaway Golf has sold conservatively upward of 5 million
drivers in its Big Bertha line. A USGA declaration that existing
woods do not conform to the Rules of Golf would mean that those
golfers who continue to use them would in essence be using illegal
clubs.
</P>
<P>
   In the event they ignored the USGA's edict and continued to use
these woods in violation of the rules, the USGA's relevance as the
governing body of golf in the United States might be dramatically
diminished.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturers' argument is that the millions of titanium
drivers in play around the world, purchased at costs upward of
$300, had already been judged by the USGA to conform to the rules.
By reversing its position regarding the conformity of the woods,
the USGA almost certainly would invite lawsuits from manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   The USGA is almost certain to rewrite its Overall Distance
Standard for golf balls, tightening tolerances that have existed
since 1976. The Overall Distance Standard currently states that a
ball ``shall not cover an average distance in carry and roll
exceeding 280 yards plus a tolerance of 6 percent (an additional
16.8 yards).''
</P>
<P>
   Said Fay, ``A promise we made when we introduced the Overall
Distance Standard in 1976 remains unfulfilled, that once we got
better testing procedures, we'd tighten up the tolerances.''
</P>
<P>
   The net result of proposed legislation would be diminished fun,
Callaway said, adding that by nullifying technological advances
that have made the game more enjoyable for millions might
ultimately drive them from the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, cooler heads will prevail,'' Callaway said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
