<HEADLINE>
BOEING TO HALT MD-11 OUTPUT, LAY OFF SOME WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Utah, Ark., Toronto)   (bl)  
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boeing Co. announced Wednesday that it would stop producing the
MD-11 wide-body jet late next year and lay off some workers because
of slumping demand for the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, based in Seattle, said the move would not result in a
special charge against earnings, as many analysts had feared. But
it will reduce second-quarter earnings, though the company declined
to specify by how much.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing inherited the MD-11 last year when it bought McDonnell
Douglas Corp. for $16.3 billion. In November, Boeing announced that
it was phasing out the MD-80 and MD-90, two narrow-body jets
produced by what is now called Boeing's Douglas Products division.
</P>
<P>
   Executives had hoped that they could continue to sell the
three-engine MD-11, which has a passenger capacity ranging from 233
to 410, primarily as a freighter. But the financial crisis in Asia
has forced many airlines there to shed older wide-body planes,
which are expensive to operate, creating a large number of
passenger jets that can be converted into cargo planes at a
fraction of the cost of a new MD-11.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite our best marketing efforts,'' said Ronald B. Woodard,
president of Boeing's commercial aircraft division, ``it became
clear to us that there simply was not enough customer interest in
either the passenger or freighter versions of this airplane to
justify keeping the production line open.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing said it had commitments for 22 more MD-11s and planned to
deliver the last plane in February 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement leaves only the 717, a 100-seat, twin-engine
jet formerly called the MD-95, as the remaining Douglas model in
the Boeing stable.
</P>
<P>
   About 3,000 workers at the former Douglas plant in Long Beach,
Calif., now build the MD-11. An additional 600 workers build the
plane's wings in Toronto along with 75 workers each in Salt Lake
City, Utah, and Melbourne, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Boeing announced it would eliminate 6,200
jobs in Long Beach, most of that the result of phasing out
production of the MD-80 and MD-90. But the company has more
recently transferred some work on a new version of the 737, a
narrow-body passenger jet, to Long Beach and is considering opening
a line to assemble the 737 there.
</P>
<P>
   Woodard said Boeing would do its best to find new jobs for the
workers, adding, ``But ultimately we will have to lay off employees
for whom we do not have work.''
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian Press quoted Boeing Canada president George Capern
as saying that the Toronto wing plant, which employs about 2,000,
would be phased out unless additional work was found.
</P>
<P>
   But Sean O'Donnell, a Boeing spokesman, said: ``We are looking
to place additional temporary work in Toronto.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
