A2795 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     06-03 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KUDOS FOR NEWT, PRAISE FOR HOPE, FOOT-TAPPING FOR STARR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Random comments on people in the news:
</P>
<P>
   NEWT GINGRICH: The speaker of the House is taking all kinds of
heat because he committed the unthinkable faux pas of speaking out
on behalf of Israel. Seems that the speaker sided with Israel on an
issue or two that are points of contention in the ongoing sham
known as the Middle Eastern peace process and suddenly found
himself under attack by the Palestinians and their apologists.
</P>
<P>
   Israel, the best and most reliable friend the United States has
in today's dangerous world, is perfectly willing to negotiate a
peace agreement _ but not at the expense of its national security.
The Clinton administration, which ought to be siding with America's
loyal and trusted ally, is instead cozying up to the Palestinians
and their terrorist-loving leader, Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Good for Newt for reminding the Israelis that they still have
friends in high places.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN KASICH: John ``who?'' OK, John Kasich may not be a
household name just yet, but the chairman of the House Budget
Committee is gearing up for a compelling arrival on the national
political scene. The 46-year-old congressman from Ohio is
reportedly laying the groundwork for a run at the Republican
presidential nomination in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, of course, is the runaway favorite to
head the GOP ticket _ and if he runs, he'll win.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush doesn't run, however, the race will be wide open, and
rank-and-file Republicans might just be in the market for a new
face to lead their party into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Kasich has a solid record of achievement _ he's as responsible
as any politician in Washington for steering the nation toward a
balanced budget _ and he has energy and charisma to spare. If
nothing else, Kasich would be an excellent running mate for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   PRESIDENT CLINTON: Is the president feeling distracted and
defeated by independent counsel Ken Starr's relentless
investigation of Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky? Or is
Slick Willie going about his business, unflappable and secure in
the certainty that no mere prosecutor can trip him up?
</P>
<P>
   Hard to say. As soon as one of the so-called experts tells
Geraldo Rivera that Starr has stripped the gears of the Clinton
presidency, another tells Larry King that Clinton is doing just
fine and is cruising comfortably toward January 2001 and the
second-term finish line.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is probably in between: Clinton is distracted, but
he's not defeated. Not by a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   KEN STARR: It's way past time for this guy to put up or shut up.
If he has evidence of lawbreaking by Clinton or others, let's see
it.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's critics are convinced that he has nothing, or next to
nothing, and that he's dragging out his investigation to embarrass
Clinton and disrupt his presidency. Starr's fans believe that he's
methodically closing in on a guilty Bill and is simply being
careful to dot every legal ``i'' and cross every ``t.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. Legions of just-plain-Americans who have no strong
feelings about either Starr or Clinton are ready for all this to
end. If the president broke the law, he must be held accountable;
if he didn't _ or if Starr can't prove that he did _ then Clinton
should be allowed to get back to the business of running the
country.
</P>
<P>
   BOB HOPE: We always seem to wait until some legendary figure
dies to praise him to the heavens. The tributes to Frank Sinatra
are still coming in _ and some of them are coming from people who
never said a kind word about the Chairman of the Board before he
kicked the bucket. Well, Bob Hope turned 95 the other day, and I've
decided not to wait.
</P>
<P>
   Hope is the greatest comedian who ever lived. He virtually
invented the art of stand-up comedy, paving the way for all the
Carsons, Lenos, Lettermans and Seinfelds. He was cracking wise
about politicians when most comics wanted no part of political
humor. And he made the Academy Awards worth watching, year after
year.
</P>
<P>
   Here's hoping that Hope knows how much the world appreciates
him.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
