<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-GEORGIA-YOUTH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODERN GEORGIA'S YOUNG FOUNDING FATHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add art note)  (Foreign Journal) 
(ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(js) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TBILISI, Georgia _ Sitting in his Manhattan office in the spring
of 1995, Mikheil Saakashvili had every reason to look forward to a
lucrative career as a big-city lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Only 26, he had attended schools in Kiev, Strasbourg and
Florence, held a degree from Columbia Law School and was winning a
reputation for diligence and legal talent. After nightfall he was
likely to be found either at the Metropolitan Opera or cheering for
the New York Knicks at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is a superstar of Georgian politics, hugely admired and
widely viewed as having unlimited potential.
</P>
<P>
   Saakashvili is among the most prominent of several dozen bright
and energetic young people who are playing important roles in
building a new post-Communist order here. The president of the
central bank, Mikheil Chkuaseli, was a swiftly rising 27-year-old
business manager when he was tapped for his new post last year.
More recently, a 30-year-old World Bank official, Irakli Managadze,
was named finance minister.
</P>
<P>
   Youth is on the rise not only in government but also in hundreds
of private groups that support causes ranging from organic farming
to protection of homeless children.
</P>
<P>
   Many organizers of these groups admire the new breed of
politician, but complain that while President Eduard Shevardnadze
encourages them, he refuses to purge older loyalists with whom he
worked in his days as Georgia's Communist boss when the republic
was part of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not what he does that bothers us, but what he doesn't
do,'' complained Levan Ramishvili, a 26-year-old human rights
advocate who works for a group called the Liberty Institute. ``He
talks a lot about democracy, but when people around him are proven
to be corrupt or to violate human rights, he keeps them on as long
as possible because he values their loyalty. The reformers are
always having to fight the bad guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Saakashvili's transformation from freewheeling New York lawyer
to someone seen as a crusading hero of a struggling democracy began
when an old friend, Zura Zhvania, arrived at his New York office
with a remarkable offer. He said he had been sent by Shevardnadze
to recruit talented young Georgians to enter politics. The desired
qualifications were intelligence, energy, idealism and no
connection to the old Communist elite.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia was then in chaos, staggering under the weight of
corruption, separatist wars in breakaway provinces, deep poverty,
pressure from a resentful Russia, and criminality so severe that
few people dared to walk the streets after dark. Saakashvili
quickly succumbed to his friend's appeal and went with his
Dutch-born wife to Tbilisi, the Georgian capital.
</P>
<P>
   When Georgians voted in national elections in December 1995,
both Zhvania and Saakashvili won seats in Parliament. Since then
they have helped shape their country's resurrection and transition
to democracy. Zhvania, now 34, is the president of Parliament.
Saakashvili, 29, is chairman of a powerful committee charged with
creating a new electoral system, an independent judiciary and a
non-political police force.
</P>
<P>
   In public opinion surveys Saakashvili often rates as the second
most popular person in Georgia, trailing only Shevardnadze. A panel
of journalists and human rights advocates named him the country's
1997 ``man of the year.'' Some foreign diplomats are already
treating him as a future president.
</P>
<P>
   ``He drives the older politicians crazy,'' said Zurab Karumidze,
editor of a new English-language magazine. ``They're used to the
Soviet style, and suddenly they have to deal with this completely
Western-oriented guy. It's not just his beliefs that are Western,
but his style and his whole approach to politics and life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's smart and full of ideas, and it's really amazing what
he's accomplished in two years,'' Karumidze said. ``But we still
don't know what kind of a politician he'll make over the long term.
It's a jungle here.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his parliamentary office, where a Georgian flag hangs
above a copy of the 1789 Declaration of the Rights of Man,
Saakashvili obviously relishes his role as one of modern Georgia's
founding fathers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, there are still people in positions of power here who
were brought up in the old regime, and they have a certain
suspicion of us,'' he said in rapid-fire, idiomatic English. ``They
accuse us not only of being radical, but also pro-Western. We admit
it. For us being pro-Western is not a matter of tactics but of
values.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to make Georgia a model democracy for the whole
region, a stable country that will be successful internationally.
America taught me that you can go from nowhere to somewhere. I had
a lot of problems at the beginning, but in just a few years I had a
good job and an apartment on Central Park West. That shows a
society that's open and rewards work and merit. If we can
transplant those values here, our place in the history of this
country will be secure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
