<HEADLINE>
HINGIS MOVES TO SEMIFINALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Since the French Open is conveniently located in Paris,
Venus Williams already had a Plan B in mind after top-seeded
Martina Hingis robbed her of the opportunity to activate Plan A and
join the elite group of four who will square off at Roland Garros
on Thursday for a spot in the women's finale on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I have all the time in the world, again, to shop; I
wish it weren't so,'' said the 17-year-old Williams, whose
quarterfinal finish in 1998 was a marked improvement on the
second-round exit she made here last year in her slam debut. But it
wasn't good enough to close the gap that separates her from the
17-year-old Swiss avenger who won every slam except this one in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   So while Williams is off scouring the Champs Elyses for fresh
beads and baguettes on Thursday, Hingis will be trying to improve
her imposing career record against Monica Seles to 6-0, and Arantxa
Sanchez Vicario, a two-time French Open champion, takes a 6-2
career edge against second-seeded Lindsay Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   Though Davenport is a first-time semifinalist at Roland Garros,
she was thrilled to reach her third consecutive slam semifinal, a
spot she claimed by dethroning the defending champion, Iva Majoli.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I never would have imagined I'd be in the semifinals
here; I'm not far from the finals,'' said Davenport, who has never
before survived a slam semifinal and whose fondness for clay has
yet to be proven.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's improving: instead of trying to slow her game down and
do her fair share of eternal rallying, Davenport has decided to
treat clay like a hardcourt and play the kind of game that comes
most naturally. Davenport is well aware that she's unlikely to win
a war of clay court attrition against the fourth-seeded Spaniard.
</P>
<P>
   ``She loves playing here, she's the clay court player, and I
feel like I'm probably the underdog,'' said Davenport, who hasn't
faced Sanchez Vicario on clay since 1994. ``But since the last time
I played her on clay, I'm a little faster, a little smarter. I'm
going to try to beat her playing my game.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the same tactic Seles, who owns three French Open titles
among her collection of nine slams, will use. She's been unable to
muster the necessary concentration level over the past two years as
she coped with the terminal illness of her father, Karolj. But she
vowed this year's Seles is a more determined Seles than the weary
competitor who ran out of steam against Hingis in this same round
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's coming back,'' Seles said of her focus. ``For the
past two years, I haven't the chance for my mind to be there as it
was when I was number one; since I was six, seven years old I had
that. I wish that it would come back in one match. But I really
expect myself to beat every single player when I step on the court,
whether it's the 100th-ranked player or number one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
