<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-PRESSURE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESSURE COOKERS HAVE COME A LONG WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BY LISA CARY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Remember diving for cover every time your mom or
grandmother was cooking with a pressure cooker? You always feared
that the ``chtt, chtt, chtt, chtt'' noise was signalling an
eruption.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure cookers have come a long way since then. The newer
versions are safer, quieter, and increasingly popular. And, when
the weather turns hot, pressure cooking doesn't heat the kitchen as
oven or stovetop cooking would.
</P>
<P>
   Before microwave ovens became as commonplace as a toaster in the
kitchen, home cooks used the pressure cooker for fast, hot meals. A
pressure cooker can cook a soup or stew in minutes, a boneless
chicken breast within five minutes and is the fastest method for
preparing dried beans and peas, making them popular with
vegetarians.
</P>
<P>
   A wide variety of foods can be pressure-cooked, from hearty
stews to soups to cheesecake. Clam chowder takes five minutes to
cook and another 10 to simmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It keeps your kitchen virtually cool,'' said Melanie
Northfield, who is an associate sales and marketing manager for
Fagor, a pressure-cooker manufacturer based in Spain. ``It's an all
season houseware product.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Florida Times-Union'' reported last year that an estimated
1 million pressure cookers are sold in the United States each year,
and the number has been increasing over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   The recent interest in pressure cookers can probably be
attributed to nostalgia and health concerns, said Robin McKenzie,
marketing vice-president for Kuhn-Rikon, a Swiss manufacturer of
pressure cookers. ``We've found all over the United States sales
are going up.''
</P>
<P>
   JoAnne O'Gara, home economist/consumer service coordinator for
National Presto Industries, a long-time American manufacturer, said
that an older age group was buying pressure cookers five to 10
years ago to replace the ones they had for years, but today, a
younger generation is also buying them.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, there's still a fear factor for people who are in
their mid-30s and older because they remember the pressure cooker
generation of old with the jiggler valves,'' O'Gara said.
</P>
<P>
   Those older than baby boomers used pressure cookers, but
children of the boomers never used them.
</P>
<P>
   However, people who are getting educated about them are buying
them, O'Gara said. ``The proper training is really starting to pay
off. People are becoming more knowledgable.''
</P>
<P>
   Northfield said the pressure cooker never lost popularity in
Europe, where it continued to develop into what it is today. ``Most
people own two to three cookers in Europe. They're on their stoves
night and day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pressure cookers today are very fast to use, they save up to
70 percent in cooking time. So it's great for anyone working,
either a woman or a man. No one seems to have time to cook healthy
these days and that's really the way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   National Presto Industries introduced the first saucepan-style
pressure cooker in 1939 and gave it the trade name ``Presto,''
which soon became synonymous with pressure cooking. In 1949 the
Duromatic pressure cooker was developed by Kuhn Rikon in
Switzerland. More companies have emerged including Fagor, Mirro and
T-Fal, among others.n Pressure cookers aren't cheap, ranging from
$70 to $340, but if you're constantly on-the-go and don't have a
lot of time to spend in the kitchen, one can be worth the
investment.
</P>
<P>
   Cooks who are new to this cooking method are encouraged to
attend classes and demonstrations, and check out pamphlets,
booklets and video tapes to learn how to use the pressure cooker so
it won't sit on the shelf.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
RECIPES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate Mousse Cheesecake &QL; 
(From ``Recipes for the Pressure Cooker,'' by Joanna White) &QL; 
1/2 cup chocolate wafer crumbs
</P>
<P>
   Pinch cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces semisweet chocolate
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   16 ounces cream cheese, softened
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons unsweetened cocoa powder
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   Grease an 8-inch springform pan that will fit inside the
pressure cooker. Mix chocolate crumbs and cinnamon together, and
sprinkle on the bottom of springform pan, pressing gently. Melt
chocolate and butter together and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   With a food processor or mixer, process cream cheese until
smooth. Add chocolate mixture and process until mixture is well
mixed and uniformly colored. Add cream, vanilla, sugar and eggs,
beating well. Sieve cocoa powder over batter and pulse or mix on
low speed until cocoa is thoroughly incorporated. Pour mixture over
crumbs in pan. Cover cake with a piece of waxed paper. Cover entire
pan with aluminum foil, sealing the edges well. Add water to
cooker. Place pan on the trivet in pressure cooker. Seal cooker,
bring up to 15 pounds (high) pressure, reduce heat to stabilize
pressure and cook 45 to 50 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Remove cooker from heat and let the pressure drop on its own.
Remove cheesecake from cooker and let cool to room temperature in
pan on a rack. Remove cheesecake from pan and refrigerate for 8
hours before serving. If desired, garnish with confectioners' sugar
or whipped cream and sliced strawberries.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings. &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 596 calories, 44 g fat, 152 mg
cholesterol, 48 g carbohydrates, 297 mg sodium, 63 percent calories
from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Hearty Beef Stew &QL; 
(From ``Quick Cuisine: The Art of Pressure Cooking``) &QL; 
 &QL; 
2 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds lean beef stew meat, cut into 1-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, peeled and diced
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups beef broth
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon dried basil
</P>
<P>
   3 medium carrots, peeled and cut into 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 rib celery, cut into 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   4 red skinned potatoes, unpeeled and cut into 1-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup tiny frozen peas, thawed
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Dijon-style mustard
</P>
<P>
   Combine flour, salt and pepper in a paper or plastic bag. Add
meat and shake until well coated with flour mixture. In a 4-quart
or larger pressure cooker, heat 1 tablespoon of olive oil over high
heat. Add half of the beef and cook until browned on all sides.
Remove beef with a slotted spoon and set aside. Heat remaining oil
and brown the remaining beef. Remove and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Add red wine vinegar to pan and stir to loosen any brown bits
that may be sticking. Reduce heat and add onion. Cook until
translucent, stirring often. Add beef, broth, tomato paste and
basil and stir until food boils. Close lid and bring to 15 pounds
(high) pressure. Adjust heat to stabilize and cook for 15 minutes.
Remove from heat and set the pressure cooker aside so pressure will
drop on its own. Add carrots, celery and potatoes. Close lid and
bring to 15 pounds (high) pressure. Adjust heat to stabilize and
cook for 5 minutes. Remove from heat and set the pressure cooker
aside so pressure will drop on its own. Stir in peas,
Worcestershire and mustard. Serve immediately or freeze for later
use.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings. &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 759 calories, 44 g fat, 171 mg
cholesterol, 33 g carbohydrates, 1,388 mg sodium, 52 percent
calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
New England Clam Chowder &QL; 
(From ``The Official Presto Pressure Cooker Cookboo'') &QL; 
4 slices bacon, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chopped onions
</P>
<P>
   4 cups cubed potatoes
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   2 cans (8 ounces each) minced clams
</P>
<P>
   1 quart light cream
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   Saute bacon and onions in 4- or 6-quart pressure cooker. Add
potatoes, salt, pepper and water. Close cover securely. Bring to 15
pounds of pressure and cook for 5 minutes. Remove from heat and let
pressure drop on its own. Drain clams into a measuring cup and
reserve liquid. Slowly add clams, 1 cup clam liquid, cream and
butter. Stir constantly. Simmer 10 minutes in open pressure cooker.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings. &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 456 calories, 38 g fat, 149 mg
cholesterol, 15 g carbohydrates, 735 mg sodium, 74 percent calories
from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Italian Risotto with Vegetables &QL; 
(From ``The Pressure Cooker Cookbook,'' Toula Patsalis) &QL; 
2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound pancetta or bacon, cut into 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   6 green onions, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 garlic cloves, crushed
</P>
<P>
   1 small carrot, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 cup arborio rice
</P>
<P>
   2 3/4 cups chicken broth or stock
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup tomato sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon white pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried rosemary
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   1 cup frozen peas
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup grated Fontinella or Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   I n a pressure cooker, heat oil. Add pancetta, green onions,
garlic, carrot and parsley and saute in hot oil 3 minutes. Stir in
rice and cook 1 minute, stirring. Add broth, tomato sauce, lemon
juice, brown sugar, salt, pepper, rosemary and bay leaf. Stir well.
Secure lid. Bring to 15 pounds of pressure (high) and maintain for
13 minutes. Release pressure immediately by holding cooker under
cold running water. Remove lid. Using a wooden spoon, stir rice
mixture well. Stir in peas. Cook, uncovered, over medium-high heat
1 minute. Ladle rice into a serving bowl and sprinkle with cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 to 8 servings. &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 314 calories, 13 g fat, 17 mg
cholesterol, 35 g carbohydrates, 1,271 mg sodium, 37 percent
calories from fat. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
