<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2810 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EPHEDRINE-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      06-03 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EPHEDRINE-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EPHEDRINE PROPONENTS ADMONISH TEXAS BOARD OVER PROPOSED
REGULATIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Optional trim included) 
 
By KATHY WALT 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It was supposed to be a public hearing on a
proposal to restrict the sale of diet supplements and other
over-the-counter products containing ephedrine.
</P>
<P>
   But a hearing Wednesday before the Texas Board of Health _ which
has proposed classifying ephedrine as a dangerous substance and
prohibiting sales without a prescription _ sounded more like a
daylong infomercial for dietary supplements containing the
controversial substance. Ephedrine has been linked to depression,
psychosis, high blood pressure and death in some cases.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, hour after hour, though, physical therapists,
doctors, body-builders and businessmen and women from around the
country trooped to a lectern to give testimony to the weight-loss
and energy-boosting properties of the ephedrine-containing products
_ and to admonish the board that the proposed measures would have
dire financial implications not only on the Texas economy but also
on their personal lives.
</P>
<P>
   Ephedrine, an amphetamine-like stimulant, is an ingredient found
in many dietary supplements and so-called energy boosters. But
ephedrine also is a central ingredient in the illegal drug
methamphetamine, known as speed, and another illegal drug known by
the street name ``ecstasy.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of those criticizing the proposed regulations are
distributors either for Wellness International Network Ltd. or
Metabolife, two companies whose products would be regulated, under
the health board proposals.
</P>
<P>
   While many states already have regulated sales of
ephedrine-containing products, Texas health officials did not act
until after getting more than 1,200 complaints of adverse effects
dating back to 1993. Eight Texas deaths have been linked to
ephedrine in the past four years, state health officials said, and
many adverse reactions occurred in children and teen-agers. Those
reactions included headaches, high blood pressure, seizures,
strokes and death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it's an economic issue disguised as a health
issue,'' Philip Sindler of Dallas told commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   Individual distributors whose incomes are based on product
sales, he said, would lose out and profits would be shifted to
greedy, global pharmaceutical companies if the products become
available by prescription only.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a health issue,'' he added. ``It's an issue of where
are the profits from the sales of the products going to go.''
</P>
<P>
   What he didn't tell commissioners was that he and his wife are
among Wellness International's top money earners, with commissions
of $55,000 during a one-month period, according to an Internet site
for the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Board of Health is concerned about public safety,'' said
Health Department spokesman Doug McBride. ``They do not have a
responsibility to see that someone does make money or does not make
money.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the regulations, if adopted, would be among the toughest
in the nation. The board first proposed the rules earlier this
year. It will continue to take public comment through June 29, and
is scheduled to vote on the regulations at its September meeting.
If the regulations are passed, they would take effect in October at
the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new rules, current over-the-counter products like
Ripped Fuel, Thermajetics, Formula One, Herbal Ecstasy, Cloud 9,
Mini Thins (now sold as Mini Two-Way Action) and MaxBrand (formerly
sold as MaxAlert) would be available by prescription only under
their current formulation.
</P>
<P>
   Over-the-counter asthma products, like Primatene, would not be
affected by the proposed rules, although they contain ephedrine.
</P>
<P>
   No one at the hearing testified about the dangers of ephedrine,
however.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this really is a dangerous product, where are the
supporters of this legislation?'' asked Andy Sikora, a product
distributor who did not identify his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the medical experts who criticized the proposed
regulations was Theodore M. Farber, a toxicology consultant from
Maryland, who said most of the data that the federal Food and Drug
Administration has collected is anecdotal and does not support
limitations proposed by the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA has proposed labeling diet aids to warn consumers not to
take the product for more than seven days and to warn that taking
more than the recommended amount could lead to heart attack,
stroke, seizure or death.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Ketchen of Dallas, another ephedrine product distributor,
told commissioners that he had struggled with obesity all of his
life, his weight like a roller coaster _ losing 30 pounds and then
gaining it back, losing 40 pounds and then gaining that back.
</P>
<P>
   He started taking an ephedrine product about a year ago and
within five months had lost 56 pounds ``without all the pain and
suffering'' normally attributed to dieting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't take away my hopes and put me on that ugly roller
coaster I'd been on all my life,'' he pleaded.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
