<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2812 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-YELTSIN-NYT &LR;      06-03 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-YELTSIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRISIS CALLS A DIMINISHED YELTSIN TO ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also RUSSIA-ECON)  
(ja) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ There is nothing like a crisis to propel Boris Yeltsin
into action, and the bottoming out of Russia's financial markets in
recent weeks did the trick once again.
</P>
<P>
   Night after night, the 67-year-old president has been shown on
television, filling the airwaves with proof of a crisis-packed
schedule, meeting in turn with media chiefs, bankers and government
officials, threatening and cajoling each group with his familiar
bluster.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in a long time, he teamed up squarely with
his own government, placing calls to foreign leaders on its behalf
and taking upon himself the politically difficult task of selling
its package of painful budget cuts at a special meeting of
parliamentarians planned for late June.
</P>
<P>
   The financial panic that hit Russia was Yeltsin's second crisis
this spring. The first, in March, was self-inflicted when he fired
his long-time prime minister, Viktor S. Chernomyrdin, and muscled
his young nominee, Sergei Kiriyenko, through a recalcitrant
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   For a leader with a record for short days, long absences and
uncertain attention span _ problems that are only partly explained
by his heart surgery in late 1996, Yeltsin's recent performance has
convinced many here and abroad that he is back on the job _ maybe
not to the extent that his appearances are intended to suggest, but
enough to prove that he is still in command. The question once
again is: How much longer he can keep it up?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the evidence over the past several weeks, it
seems more and more certain that he is not giving any serious
consideration to retirement,'' noted one Western diplomat.
``Running for a third term is something that is very definitely on
his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   With Russia's next presidential elections two years away, the
jockeying for political position has already begun, and not only in
the Kremlin. The bankers and business executives who assembled
around Yeltsin's table on Tuesday were there not only to help sort
out Russia's finances, but to resume a relationship that will be
crucial if Yeltsin chooses to run again. So far, he has given mixed
signals; the most recent signal came in March, when he said he
would not run again.
</P>
<P>
   Much has changed since the 1996 election, when Yeltsin was able
to summon the near-unanimous support of business tycoons and their
news media. Several of those tycoons _ including Vladimir Gusinsky,
a media mogul who was at the Kremlin meeting, and Boris Berezovksy,
a powerful financier who was not invited _ have stated that they
are looking for alternative candidates to back.
</P>
<P>
   But Yeltsin, whose career has been a string of remarkable
comebacks, can not be counted out, particularly now that he has no
obvious political heir. And his performance over the last few
months offers evidence that he is keeping his options open, hoping
his new government will give him a record he can defend before the
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He strongly believes that Mr. Kiriyenko and his young team
will promote economic growth,'' said Sergei Markov, director of the
Institute of Political Studies. ``That is why he chose them. Also
because they are young: That way his rivals do not know whether to
accuse him of being too old, or the government of being too young.
As for himself, he wants to create an image of a president who is
not a sleeping lion.''
</P>
<P>
   As the father figure of a new government, Yeltsin had no choice
but to commit the power and prestige of his office to the all-out
effort to dig Russia out of its latest crisis.
</P>
<P>
   That in turn has required him to adopt the government's economic
goals, and terminology, as his own, abandoning the ambiguous
phraseology of his last prime minister, whose views and experience
as a Soviet-era manager had acted as a brake on the reformers.
</P>
<P>
   The president's task has been helped by the performance of
Kiriyenko, who comes across as a sober-minded, clear-spoken
technocrat, in stark contrast with Chermomyrdin, whose tortured
language had made him a favorite target of spoofs.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews published Wednesday in the newspaper Kommersant,
several of the executives who met with Yeltsin complemented him on
his performance during the one-and-a-half-hour talk _ though some
noted that he appeared to tire towards the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have met with Yelstin several times,'' Gusinsky noted in
Kommersant. ``For the first time I saw that the president was
completely involved with economic problems. He does not listen to
opinions, but has his own position. That is a big difference. This
position is absolutely adequate to the real situation. ``
</P>
<P>
   Aleksandr Smolensky, head of the SBS-Agro bank, suggested that
Yeltsin's main purpose in calling the executives together was to
``share responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps,'' he said, ``it is the system of checks and balances
that the president is so fond of _ as in, here sits the prime
minister but I keep the right to consult with others.''
</P>
<P>
   But those present also acknowledged that it is mostly Kiriyenko
who provided answers to questions. Someone would propose something,
said Vitali Malkin, president of Russian Credit Bank, and
``Kiriyenko said he agreed, did not agree, we are going to do that,
we have already done it, we are going to pass this or that law.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeltsin understands nothing about economics,'' said Markov,
recalling how Yeltsin's support swung in the early 1990s from
Russia's first team of economic reformers to the more protectionist
policies of Chernomyrdin. ``Now he has the next wave of new
reformers. He has to trust them, because he chose them. Mr.
Yeltsin's job is to keep power, and to run the country. He is good
at the first, and not so good at the second, so he chooses the
people who will run the country on his behalf.''
</P>
<P>
   And while he has embraced the Kiriyenko government and its
deficit-cutting program, there is nothing to stop Yeltsin from
distancing himself if the results are not successful, Markov noted.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Yeltsin geared up for his latest crisis, there were
signs of the unsteadiness that has often puzzled Kremlin watchers.
His speech seems slurred at times, his facial grimaces almost
grotesque. And there were veiled suggestions from some people at
the meeting that he was not registering everything they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time we saw him engage in real dialogue in public
dates back to the election campaign,'' noted the Western diplomat.
``Those problems are still out there, and no one really knows what
is wrong with him.''
</P>
<P>
   But the recent crisis has again demonstrated that Yeltsin's role
at the helm of the Russian state is already a prescribed one.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have to be very active to function,'' the diplomat
said. ``What he needs to understand is a limited number of
things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
