<HEADLINE>
PRESSURE COOKER BASICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LISA CARY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - The concept of a pressure cooker is quite simple.
Because a pressure cooker is airtight, pressure builds up inside as
the liquid inside comes to a boil. The trapped steam causes the
internal temperature to rise beyond what it would be capable of
doing under normal room pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure limit for a cooker is 15 pounds or 250 degrees. At
that point, if the heat is not turned down, the pressure cooker
will release steam so it won't explode. In older cookers the
pressure could build up and the steam would literally shoot the
regulator to the ceiling. After that, food could be propelled
through the vent.
</P>
<P>
   The new pressure cookers have at least two backup safety vents
and the lids must be locked into place before the pressure will
even rise. An expanding rubber gasket inside the lid prevents the
lid from being removed or unlocked until all the pressure has been
released.
</P>
<P>
   In a worst-case scenario, if the pot is left over heat for an
extended amount of time, it will not explode. All the steam will
eventually escape, the liquid will evaporate and the pot will burn.
</P>
<P>
   There is a a wide range of pressure cooker sizes and features,
and for the money you will spend, it pays to shop around. Most
kitchen stores, home accessory stores and even department stores
now carry them.
</P>
<P>
   T-Fal makes a version (the Safe 2 Visio Cooker) with a glass lid
so you can see the contents cooking. It retails for $139.99.
Kuhn-Rikon's ``Cadillac'' version has a nonstick waffle-bottom and
a glass lid that can be used in the oven up to 350 degrees. It
retails for $289.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure cookers are constructed of either aluminum,
enamel-coated carbon steel or stainless steel. Aluminum is best
known for heat conduction, but the stainless steel and
enamel-coated carbon steel has no interaction between the metal and
the food being prepared. Look for a pressure cooker of heavy-gauge
metal with an easy to clean interior and surface.
</P>
<P>
   Also look for a heat-resistant handle with a helping handle on
the other side for easier lifting.
</P>
<P>
   Soem pressure cookers can't go in the oven, although you do
brown foods in some recipes on top of the stove before pressure
cooking commences. Some kinds won't go in the dishwasher. The
rubber gaskets that help keep the lid airtight may need to be
replaced from time to time if you use the cooker often. Fagor
recommends replacing its cookers' gaskets every year.
</P>
<P>
   Other utensils that may be needed are a steam basket for
vegetables and fish, and a heat diffuser that comes in handy with a
gas stove. Some recipes call for a cake pan or a pudding mold and a
trivet.
</P>
<P>
   Look for an 800 help line, which most of the manufacturers have,
as well as websites where consumers can e-mail questions. For
preliminary research or materials, contact:
</P>
<P>
   Fagor at 1-800-207-0806 or email at fagoramerica(at)deccanet.com
</P>
<P>
   Presto at 1-800-368-2194 or email at contact(at)presto-net.com
or website at www.presto-net.com
</P>
<P>
   Kuhn Rikon at 1-800-662-5882 or website at www.kuhnrikon.com
</P>
<P>
   T-Fal at 1-800-395-8325 or website www.t-fal.com
</P>
<P>
   There's also several websites that offer pressure cookers for
sail over the internet. These include: IQVC, Cybershop, Crescent,
Cendant and the Virtual Kitchen Store.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
