<HEADLINE>
FURNISHING WITH NATURAL FIBERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS.: Zendoow is cq.)  
 (ja)  
 By MARIANNE ROHRLICH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In summer, furniture made with natural fibers is as welcome as a
cool breeze. This year, designers are returning to the basics _
straw, hemp, string, paper, reeds, even banana leaves _ for
furniture, rugs and textiles. Because many pieces are handmade,
they may be expensive, despite the humble materials.
</P>
<P>
   1. A wood bar stool wrapped with fiber string is $135 at
Interieurs, 114 Wooster St. The Italian Tulle chair has a chromed
steel frame. The back and seat are of a strong linen rope
originally used for fishing nets; $560 from New York Works at Out
of Time Architects, (212) 206-0642.
</P>
<P>
   2. Ralph Lauren's Alcade club chair is woven of banana tree
fibers. The cushion, in plaid wool, is available in other fabrics
or in leather; $6,765 at Polo Ralph Lauren, 867 Madison Ave.
</P>
<P>
   3. An Alexander Calder straw rug, 56 inches by 82 inches, has
the artist's initials and the date '74 woven into the design. It
will be auctioned on June 10 at Phillips New York, 406 E. 79th St.,
which estimates the rug will bring $3,000 to $5,000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4. A ``floor'' with a trompe l'oeil wood-grain design is
actually an Aleman/Moore straw rug called Zendoow. The imported
straw is hand-dyed and hand-sewn by two former milliners. The
6-by-9-foot rug, made in Greenpoint, Brooklyn, is $7,425 at
Innovations (to the trade) in the D&AMP;D Building, 979 Third Ave.
Other Aleman/Moore rugs begin at $800.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Louis XVI might cringe if he saw one of his dining chairs
upholstered in woven leaves. The Hermina chair by a Filipino
designer, Antonio ``Budji'' Layug, has a Louis XVI frame of South
Pacific rosewood, but the seat and the back are woven of the outer
peel of the rattan palm; $1,925 from Niermann Weeks (to the trade),
232 E. 59th St.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5. Lloyd Looms introduced its first collection of woven kraft
paper furniture in 1922. Now, Lloyd/Flanders makes indoor-outdoor
furniture in 13 colors, including light green. The Reflections
rocker, which has a protective polyurethane finish, is $696 at
Gracious Home, 1220 Third Ave.
</P>
<P>
   6. A decorative centerpiece of paper twine by Ritva Puotila, a
Finnish artist, is $400 at the American Craft Museum Store, 40 W.
53rd St.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   7. A desk and dining table, named Louis XV, has hand-forged iron
legs and a top of woven Italian straw. Thirty-six inches wide by 72
inches long, it's $3,600 at Modern Stone Age, 111 Greene St.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Place mats of straw, bamboo and banana leaves cost $15 to $48;
natural straw coasters, $4. All from Kitchen Classics, (800)
251-2421. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hemp twill, which can be used for upholstery or draperies, comes
in 15 colors and costs $20 to $25 a yard at Hempinstead, 353 W.
47th St.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
