<HEADER>
A2822 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRANKFURT-ARTS-3TAKES     06-03 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANKFURT-ARTS-3TAKES-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CULTURAL WARD OF THE STATE BECOMES AN ORPHAN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 7) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANNE MIDGETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Picture a society that has world-renowned
architects design spacious, beautiful museums, open to its citizens
free of charge; that spends millions renovating buildings into
concert halls and theaters; that goes out of its way to found new
institutions dedicated to the experimental and the avant-garde;
that invites performing artists from around the globe to come and
work, and gives them spaces in which to display their work when
they're done.
</P>
<P>
   Now picture a society that has no money for the arts: where the
museums charge steep admission fees for shows that in some cases no
one wants to see, where the opera can afford to give only a handful
of performances each month, where dance companies close and visual
and performing artists leave town because they're no longer able to
do their work.
</P>
<P>
   The first society is Frankfurt 10 years ago. The second society
is Frankfurt today. And the transformation illustrates all that's
best and worst about the German system of government-subsidized
culture _ a system that in today's economic landscape is facing the
prospect of significant structural change whether it wants it or
not.
</P>
<P>
   Frankfurt is an extreme case. Frankfurt is broke. Germany's
banking center, styled ``the city of the euro,'' is $4.5 billion in
debt. The city is a fine example of the perils of living beyond
one's means: it tries to support all of the amenities of a major
metropolis, from a subway system to its generously proportioned
cultural life, with the tax revenues from a mere 650,000 citizens
and with very little support from the state.
</P>
<P>
   In the Federal Republic of Germany, public arts financing is
borne primarily by the states, not the national government. The
states had to cut back support to their cities after they were
compelled to start ``solidarity payments'' to help finance German
reunification in the early 1990s, and they tend to give state
capitals the biggest share of their subsidies in any case.
</P>
<P>
   Munich, for example, one of Germany's wealthiest cities, has two
state opera houses, two state theaters and two state museums: 51
percent of its cultural financing comes from the state of Bavaria.
But in the state of Hessia, it is Wiesbaden, not Frankfurt, that is
the capital, and Frankfurt receives only 6 percent of its cultural
budget from Hessia; Frankfurt's cultural institutions are municipal
rather than state (the Stadtische Buhnen, or City Theaters, rather
than the Staatsoper, or State Opera).
</P>
<P>
   So a city half Munich's size, with only a fraction of its
resources, is trying to compete with the Bavarian capital and other
German cities as well. Small wonder that when the crunch hit in
1993, Frankfurt found itself so strapped that it started dimming
its street lights after 9 p.m. to save on its electric bill.
</P>
<P>
   In its heyday, however, Frankfurt put itself on the German
cultural map. In the 1980s, it had both the money and the
initiative. Hilmar Hofmann, who ran the city's cultural scene for
two decades as cultural adviser, did his best to use his power to
create an artistic utopia.
</P>
<P>
   From the late 70s to the early 90s, 12 major museums were built
or completely renovated. The Alte Oper, the bombed-out old opera
house that had sat in ruins since the war, was painstakingly
restored and reopened as a concert hall in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   At the Stadtische Buhnen, the conductor Michael Gielen led
operas staged by avant-garde directors like Ruth Berghaus and Hans
Neuenfels; the Playhouse (Schauspiel) erupted with scandals over
works by the filmmaker Rainer Werner Fassbinder and the theater
director Einar Schleef; and the choreographer William Forsythe
arrived in 1984 to take over the ballet company and transform it
into the critically applauded blend of ballet and modern
Tanz-theater that it is today.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller institutions opened, too, and flourished: the
experimental Theater am Turm, or TAT, presented cutting-edge
companies from around the world (the Wooster Group was one); the
Mousonturm, with a similar program, also cultivated in-house groups
like Rui Horta's innovative dance company, SOAP. At its height,
12.5 percent of the city's annual budget went to support culture.
</P>
<P>
   Like New York's &UR;  &LR; in a long bull market, Frankfurt's overspending
had a certain manic quality. ``We knew it couldn't last,'' says
Martina Aschmies, the Mousonturm's communications director. ``But I
think it's good that Mr. Hofmann created such a flourishing
cultural landscape. All you can do is set it up and hope it has the
strength to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   The question now is what will survive. When the $4.5 billion
deficit first became evident in 1993 (it has held steady since), it
was clear that arts support would have to be reduced, although
cultural spending still represents some 8.5 percent of the city
budget.
</P>
<P>
   How to implement cuts was less clear. Any cut was bound to raise
howls of pain from Frankfurt arts administrators. In Frankfurt's
continuing cultural crisis, the politicians have been so roundly
criticized, so often derided as philistines, that one might think
they were willfully making senseless cuts on a whim, rather than
reacting to a financial crisis so severe that Hessia at one point
threatened to take away Frankfurt's financial autonomy altogether.
</P>
<P>
   It takes the objectivity of a resident foreigner like Forsythe
or Christopher Hunt, the recently departed director of the Alte
Oper, to note that ``the politicians' position is impossible; there
is no money,'' as Hunt puts it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Being democratic, the politicians opted for evenhanded
reductions across the board. The Mousonturm's Ms. Aschmies, and
most other cultural administrators in Frankfurt, object to what
they call ``the lawn mower principle'' of reducing financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was needed were concepts,'' says Ms. Aschmies. ``If there
had to be closures, they should have been made decisively, not just
these small cuts every year so the whole thing withers away.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Aschmies feels that the Mousonturm has been penalized for
its willingness to cooperate and work within the tighter budget,
that the politicians' attitude is, well, if you can work so well
with that little money, we'll trim off a bit more.
</P>
<P>
   The conductor Sylvain Cambreling, who took over as Artistic
Director of the Frankfurt Opera in 1993, just as the crisis struck,
watched his budget dwindle, too, until he left in disgust in 1997.
``It's like taking a three-star gourmet restaurant and turning it
into a McDonald's,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of across-the-board cuts question the authority of
politicians to make what amount to judgment calls, the
pronouncement that one arts institution ``deserves'' to survive
while another must close.
</P>
<P>
   An unspoken reason for Germany's generosity and decentralized
largess in its public-arts spending has been a desire to avoid what
happened when a previous national government took an aggressive
role in arts policy: book burnings, exhibitions of ``degenerate
art'' and the like.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians all over Germany are also restrained by what a
Frankfurt City Councilman, Felix Semmelroth, describes as ``the
German fear of closing down an existing institution.'' This was
demonstrated in Berlin when the Schiller Theater closed in 1993.
Never mind that the theater, however long and glorious its
tradition, was playing to about 50 percent of capacity; never mind
that reunified Berlin was and is bursting at the seams with the
glut of institutions resulting from joining two separate cities.
</P>
<P>
   Every newspaper in the country rose up to beat on the same drum,
attacking the philistinism and ignorance of politicians depriving
the city of a national treasure. Few politicians want to repeat the
experience by actually closing something down in Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians are also hampered by the entrenched nature of the
system. Most year-round spoken and operatic theaters in Germany _
and there are more than 150 of them _ are not only
government-supported but also entrenched bureaucracies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The City Theaters are Office No. 46,'' says Semmelroth. ``I
have to approve the Intendant's application when he wants to go on
a business trip.'' All of a theater's employees _ singers, actors
and musicians as well as administrative staff _ are technically
government officials, with full benefits, paid six-week vacations
and total job security.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, a theater's budget is allocated in certain ways:
staff can't be laid off, and, says Forsythe, ``if you need an extra
20,000 for sets and you have it in costumes, you can't trade it
in.'' Because of this, a theater's fixed operating costs are not
negotiable, which means if the budget is cut, the money has to come
out of the sum that goes toward actually mounting productions.
</P>
<P>
   This fact has been very evident in Frankfurt in months when the
opera house staged a mere seven or eight performances, rather than
playing every night.
</P>
<P>
   An alternative to this system is the GMBH (company with limited
liability, or incorporated), exemplified by the Mousonturm. Still
relatively new in Germany in its application to cultural
institutions, such privatization gives an institution the autonomy
to decide how to allocate its subsidies for itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why pay year round for 20 seamstresses I use for 15 days a
year when I can hire 5 tailors for 2 weeks?'' asks Forsythe, who
explored turning his ballet company into a GMBH in his contract
negotiations this spring. But as the Mousonturm also illustrates,
the drawback of an incorporated company, from the point of view of
German arts administrators, is that the government then has no
legal obligation to maintain the subsidy.
</P>
<P>
   In general, Germany, an essentially conservative country,
doesn't take well to change. Suggestions regarding the virtues of
private arts financing on the American model were received with the
polite but firm opinion that it could never work in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Now in Frankfurt, after some years of much-touted and undeniable
crisis, you can actually hear people talking about the necessity
for change.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we want to save our culture at all,'' says Dr. Martin
Steinhoff, business director of the Frankfurt Opera, ``we have to
be prepared to change our structures.'' Administrators and
politicians are adopting a quasi-capitalist vocabulary from the
American-style model: incorporated structures, private foundations,
corporate sponsorship (the latter still in its infancy here).
Semmelroth even talks with feeling about ``trying to convince
museum directors to open museum shops.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't think that way,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   While no one wants to relieve politicians of the obligation to
pay for culture, cultural administrators in Frankfurt can now
regard public arts support as something other than their God-given
right.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous to say, I need this much money or I can't
operate,'' says Michael Hocks, director of the Alte Oper. ``You
have to say, `I have this much; now, what can I do with it?' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 1859EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
