u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-SPOT-SPI &LR;      06-03 0398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPOT-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Thursday, June 4, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Tina May at (206) 448-8355.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MFN (Washington) President Clinton urges Congress to
renew normal trade benefits for China, saying good relations with
Beijing are especially important in light of fears of a nuclear
arms race in South Asia. Congress will debate the issue amid
investigations of technology transfers to China and questionable
campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Paulson. (story will move in the ``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-MD11 (Seattle) The Boeing Co. will end production of its
MD-11 aircraft in the year 2000 because of insufficient demand for
the triple engine, long-range jet, the company said Wednesday.
Boeing said that demand for the aircraft has declined since
November and that as of April 30, it had only 22 order commitments
for the MD-11. Boeing's decision affects about 3,750 employees who
work in its MD-11 program. These include 3,000 workers at a Long
Beach, California, facility, 600 who make MD-11 wings at a Toronto,
Ontario, plant, 75 employees in Salt Lake City and 75 employees in
Melbourne, Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   By Karen West. (story will move in the ``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS (Seattle) Mariners vs. Anaheim, Kingdome, with
Randy Johnson scheduled to pitch for Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   By Dan Raley. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-RANDY-JOHNSON (Seattle) The scene surrounding Randy
Johnson's appearance after 10 days of trade reports. With comments
from fans gathered in stands near the warmup mound as Johnson
prepares for the game, and quotes after the game from Johnson about
his reception.
</P>
<P>
   By Angelo Bruscas. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-SONICS (Undated) Sonics president Wally Walker is in Chicago
at the NBA predraft camp. But while he's looking at players, he's
also scouting for a coach. Walker says his short list is six, and
he wants to have it down to two in the next week. Paul Westphal
apparently tops the list, and Lenny Wilkens probably isn't on it.
</P>
<P>
   By Ronald Tillery. (story will move in the `` '' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-COLUMN-THIEL (Salt Lake City) From the NBA finals, Jazz vs.
Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   By Art Thiel. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 1859EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0354 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2827 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRANKFURT-ARTS-3RDTAK     06-03 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANKFURT-ARTS-3RDTAKE-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
  
 FRANKFURT: with it?'''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hocks represents what could be a new breed of German Intendants.
On Jan. 1, he took over a hall whose subsidy has fallen by half
since it opened in 1981, from $14 million to $7 million, and is
slated to drop a further $2 million by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than wringing his hands, Hocks exudes a confident
optimism: the Alte Oper, recently plagued by financial difficulty,
is in his view still the ``flagship'' of Frankfurt's culture. The
Alte Oper is a GMBH, so it's been able to streamline, reducing its
personnel from a high of 400 to the current 30: concessions are
rented out and technical staff brought in from outside for big
productions.
</P>
<P>
   Hocks plans to restructure the subscription series, building on
the hall's standing relationships with the Ensemble Modern or the
Chamber Orchestra of Europe while continuing a program of visiting
groups that already extends from the Bavarian Radio Orchestra to
James Taylor to touring productions of shows like ``West Side
Story.''
</P>
<P>
   Hocks is perhaps abler than any other German administrator to be
flexible about state support: he comes to the Alte Oper after a
decade at the Hoechst Jahrhunderthalle (Century Hall), a private
facility run by the chemical company Hoechst: a virtually
unparalleled example of corporate arts financing in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   For all the gloom and doom about Frankfurt's situation _
headlines on Frankfurt's crisis have become standard on German
newspapers' arts pages _ there are signs that the city's cultural
life is, collectively, getting its second wind.
</P>
<P>
   As Hocks gets the Alte Oper on its feet, William Forsythe is
about to take over the TAT, which he hopes to build up into the
kind of avant-garde center it used to be under Tom Stromberg in the
1980s (with, of course, a special emphasis on dance). While some
museums struggle, others, like the Museum for Modern Art under
Jean-Christophe Amman, continue to attract attention.
</P>
<P>
   And the opera, which fell back on a regimen of ``greatest
hits,'' from ``Carmen'' to ``La Boheme,'' after Cambreling's
departure, is also continuing its commitment to the modern.
</P>
<P>
   In March, a mini-festival called ``Henze Days'' surrounded a new
production of ``Boulevard Solitude'' by Hans Werner Henze, a living
composer whose works tend to appeal to audiences; the critic
Gerhard Rohde described this Frankfurt attempt to be ``a little bit
modern'' as a link with ``the good old days'' of Gielen and
Cambreling. And next season, the composer Wolfgang Rihm arrives to
head a new, permanent workshop for contemporary opera.
</P>
<P>
   Germany's state support of the arts has allowed the development
of a performing arts culture unequaled in the world, supporting
progressive developments in stage direction, in musical
performance, in contemporary composition.
</P>
<P>
   But the generosity has also supported a certain level of
mediocrity, as institutions become overly comfortable and their
structures increasingly unwieldy. Germany's industry is pulling out
of the recession of the early 1990s, but the arts continue to
struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Like the lumbering vessels of the Spanish Armada, the
established city and state arts institutions are proving less
maneuverable than other models, and people are beginning to
question whether there is really need for four opera houses within
a 50-mile radius of a city like Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
   The best argument against closing an institution is probably
still the presence of vital, high-quality art. And events in
Frankfurt may be demonstrating not the hopeless incompetence of
politicians but the fact that change doesn't have to mean the end
of the world, that ``crisis'' can serve as a wake-up call.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bad years are behind us,'' says the opera's Steinhoff.
``The other German cities, those which have more money, still have
their bad years ahead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 1859EDT &QL; 
