<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2828 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-REVIEW-CENTURY-SPI     06-03 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-REVIEW-CENTURY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PEOPLE OF THE CENTURY' IS A HALF-HEARTED EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Go figure. Maybe it's because of Time magazine's
affiliation-by-merger with CNN, but if ever there was a
half-hearted special on TV, it's CBS's ``People of the Century: CBS
News/Time 100 _ Artists and Entertainers'' Thursday night. (Check
local listings.)
</P>
<P>
   What could have been a riveting two- or even three-hour look at
some remarkably talented, inspirational and just plain weird people
is instead a one-hour rush job that seems to have produced as an
afterthought. Not that it's badly done. The editing, in fact, is
laudable. Try cramming 20 people (24, actually) into a 60-minute
format (about 45, after commercials) and see what you can come up
with.
</P>
<P>
   But if everyone on this list of the century's top
arts-and-entertainment types were to get equal time, we're talking
roughly two minutes per listee. Instead, CBS chose to do
mini-profiles of a handful _ Lucille Ball, Louis Armstrong, Jim
Henson, Steven Spielberg, Marlon Brando, Aretha Franklin and Frank
Sinatra among them _ and had to reduce most of the others to less
information than is contained in this paragraph. So Charles-Edouard
Jeanneret, the Swiss architect and design guru known more widely as
Le Corbusier, gets about as much air time as a deadbeat cellphone
customer.
</P>
<P>
   What's odd is that the list is not just a parroting of something
conceived by Time magazine. CBS clearly had input; Mike Wallace,
who hosts tonight's special, even persuaded Time's managing editor,
Walter Isaacson, to yank Elvis Presley off the arts/entertainment
Top 20 _ can you say ``Return to Sender''? _ and replace him with
Sinatra. Wallace's argument was that, in terms of their influence
on personal style, the Chairman of the Board had more sway than the
King.
</P>
<P>
   I could quibble with that, but I'm 47 years old. Mike Wallace
hasn't seen 47 since the Johnson administration, and generational
differences are what help to make these list-making endeavors so
enjoyable. And frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the ``Artists and Entertainers'' top 20, with the
Beatles and Rodgers &AMP; Hammerstein each counting as one entry, are:
Lucille Ball, Oprah Winfrey, Jim Henson, Louis Armstrong, Igor
Stravinsky, James Joyce, T.S. Eliot, Pablo Picasso, Steven
Spielberg, Marlon Brando, the Beatles, Bob Dylan, Aretha Franklin,
Richard Rodgers/Oscar Hammerstein, Martha Graham, Le Corbusier,
Coco Chanel, Charlie Chaplin, Frank Sinatra and Bart Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Bart Simpson. Never mind that he's fictional. Wallace, or
at least Wallace's script, says Bart is ``as funny as Lucy, as
angry as Dylan, as deep as Joyce.''
</P>
<P>
   Ay, carumba!
</P>
<P>
   We could argue all day about who isn't on the list, which, not
surprisingly, centers on people who made their names in the United
States, with the remainder all hailing from Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Such wasn't the case with the first list, ``Leaders and
Revolutionaries,'' which Time published (and CBS aired) in April.
Along with the likely suspects _ Churchill, Lenin and Roosevelt
(Theodore/Franklin/Eleanor) _ there was a smattering from outlying
precincts, such as Gandhi, Mandela, Mao Zedong, Ho Chi Minh and the
``unknown rebel'' who stood in front of the column of tanks near
Tiananmen Square in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   If you're wondering why someone like Muhammad Ali isn't on the
latest list, it's because sports figures _ entertainers in my book
_ will be included in the ``Heroes and Adventurers'' segment next
year. Also still to come: ``Builders and Titans,'' slated for
December, ``Scientists and Healers'' next year, and a final special
exploring the life and impact of the CBS/Time Person of the
Century.
</P>
<P>
   With six episodes committed to this one project on ``the 100
most important people of the 20th century,'' it's easy to see why
CBS is condensing each subcategory of 20 individuals into a
60-minute box. Too bad. In the hands of A&AMP;E or Discovery, this
could have been a wonderfully enriching, seasonlong series of
biographical specials.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Time insisted that CBS not steal too much of its
thunderWhatever the case, CBS tonight offers viewers a good reason
to seek out this week's edition of Time or visit the magazine's Web
site (www.pathfinder.com/time/). Don't bother with CBS's Web site
(www.cbs.com). You'll only find information on the people mentioned
in the mini-profiles. Nothing on Le Corbusier. Or Bart, for that
matter.
</P>
<P>
   When TV sets and computers are totally wired and we're all
nauseatingly interactive, a lip-service approach like tonight's
won't matter much. We'll just click on the remote and go barreling
off to a site that provides more ``stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   But as we wait for that time to come along, CBS would do well to
remember that information was power to the people of this century.
It will be in the next, too.
</P>
<P>
   John Levesque is the P-I's television critic. Call him at
206-448-8330 or send e-mail to: tvguy(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 1859EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2832 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-PAKISTAN-COX- &UR; -600     06-03 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-PAKISTAN-COX- </SLUG>
   -600&AMP;ADD 
 &HT;     CLINTON WARNS INDIA, PAKISTAN AGAINST `ARMS RACE;' RENEWS
FAVORED TRADING STATUS FOR CHINA
 &HT;     By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hoping to press India and Pakistan to ``reverse
course and to avoid a dangerous arms race,'' President Clinton
dispatched his top diplomat Wednesday to Geneva to huddle with the
envoys of four other major powers over how best to reduce mounting
tensions on the Indian subcontinent.
</P>
<P>
   Standing beside Clinton at the White House, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright vowed to ``do my very best,'' in Geneva, but
warned that there were stark limits to U.S. influence in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risks of the moment are high, and, for the moment, the key
choices will be made in New Delhi and Islamabad,'' she said,
referring to the Indian and Pakistani capitals. ``We must all hope
and pray those choices are the right ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton praised the efforts of China, which will chair
Thursday's meeting in Geneva, and said such cooperation underscored
the importance of renewing most favored nation trading status with
Beijing, a step the president took Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said one goal in Thursday's meeting is to try to bring
India and Pakistan together to discuss the single most contentious
security issue between them: the fate of Kashmir, seat of four
decades of sectarian strife that has left tens of thousands dead.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan has sought U.S. assistance in addressing the subject,
but India's government has insisted that third countries stay out
of the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Indians have not wanted it to be discussed,'' Albright
told reporters at a State Department briefing shortly before she
left for Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither side is blameless,'' in the complicated conflict,
Albright said. ``The bottom line here is, they've got to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has been wrestling for weeks over
escalating tensions and a series of nuclear tests by India _ which
detonated five nuclear devices last month _ and neighboring
Pakistan _ which responded by detonating six last week.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, Clinton had tried to use diplomacy, including
several personal phone calls to Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif, to head off the tests.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of both countries, however, said their own national
security concerns outweighed the pleadings of the American
president, who insisted Wednesday that both countries refrain from
further tests, agree to not attach nuclear weapons to delivery
systems such as missiles and join in a dialogue to allay
longstanding tensions between them.
</P>
<P>
   ``India and Pakistan are great nations with boundless potential,
but developing weapons of mass destruction is self-defeating,
wasteful and dangerous. It will make their people poorer and less
secure,'' Clinton told reporters gathered in the Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``The international community must now come together to move
them to reverse course and to avoid a dangerous arms race in
Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright's mission to Geneva is aimed at coordinating a broader
response that might better make use of the influence that Russia
has on India and China has on Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting Thursday of top diplomats from the five permanent
members of the United Nations Security Council _ the United States,
Britain, China, France and Russia _ is being chaired by the
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   China stands accused of clandestinely assisting the Pakistanis
in developing long-range missiles and other potentially offensive
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, though, who plans to visit Beijing later this month,
praised the Chinese, saying they were playing a constructive role
in global non-proliferation efforts and calling for improved ties
between the two giant Pacific powers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is further evidence of the important role China can play
in meeting the challenges of the 21st Century,'' Clinton said.
``This is an important example of how our engagement with China
serves America's interests _ stability in Asia, preventing the
spread of weapons of mass destruction, combating international
crime and drug trafficking, protecting the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Engagement is the administration's term for working closely with
the Chinese government and the Chinese people, as opposed to
isolating Beijing or imposing trade and economic sanctions _ as is
U.S. policy toward Cuba, which, like China, is a one-party
communist state infamous for widespread human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Buttressing his engagement policy, Clinton renewed China's most
favored nation trading status, or MFN, on Wednesday, the day before
the annual June 4 deadline for doing so, according Chinese products
the same low tariffs in this country as the exports of most U.S.
trading partners.
</P>
<P>
   The president's renewal of MFN will stand unless it's overturned
by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Some representatives oppose MFN for China, claiming that the
country should be denied favorable trading terms with the United
States unless and until it improves its human rights record. Others
have raised concerns over Clinton's decision last year to allow the
transfer to China of sensitive satellite technology, which critics
maintain Beijing could use for military purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said, however, that the best way to work for change in
China is to improve relations and build common ground, not punish
Beijing with sanctions that most of rest of the world would not
match.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to renew (MFN) would be to sever our economic, and, to a
large measure, our strategic relationship with China, turning our
back on a fourth of the world,'' Clinton said. ``This policy
clearly is in our nation's interests, and I urge Congress to
support it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For clients of the New York Times News Service &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 1902EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0357 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2833 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-AD-COLUMN-NY     06-03 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: INTERNET AD DEALS PICK UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (dc) 
 By COURTNEY KANE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The pace of deals involving interactive advertising accelerated
Wednesday as three acquisitions and affiliations were announced.
</P>
<P>
   In one deal, 24/7 Media Inc. in New York acquired Cliqnow Sales
Group, the Internet advertising sales representation division of K2
Design Inc. in New York, for $1 million in cash and $3 million in
convertible preferred stock of 24/7.
</P>
<P>
   Cliqnow, which K2 started in 1996, has 10 employees who handle
ad sales for 75 Web sites including those of The Associated Press,
PR Newswire and the Women's Forum. Cliqnow will operate as an
autonomous unit of 24/7 with sales staffs in Chicago, Los Angeles,
New York and San Francisco, and the Cliqnow sub-networks, offering
computer users content on topics like finance and travel, will
operate separately from the 24/7 network.
</P>
<P>
   Though Cliqnow has been successful, said Matthew de Ganon,
president at K2, ``we need to focus specifically on our core
interactive advertising and media business.'' The sale, he added,
would enable K2 to concentrate on that ``and pursue aggressive
growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Paternoster, 32, president at Cliqnow, and Joe Apprendi,
31, executive vice president, will continue in those roles and also
become senior vice presidents at 24/7.
</P>
<P>
   The second deal involved Double Click Inc. in New York, an
interactive advertising network, and Ad Knowledge in Palo Alto,
Calif., which provides tools for Internet media planning and buying
and campaign management. The two companies have formed a strategic
partnership; financial terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the affiliation is to integrate the technologies of
the two companies to create standard industry platforms for Web ad
management that would help make buying and selling online
advertising more efficient and effective. Ad Knowledge will now
focus primarily on operations intended to help advertisers and
agencies buy ads on the Internet while Double Click will support
the Ad Knowledge operations focused on selling ads on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, customers of Click Wise, the Ad Knowledge Web site
ad management software, will now be about to use the Double Click
DART service, a proprietary technology offering ad server,
reporting and tracking abilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the online ad industry continues to expand, there is
significant benefit to creating uniform standards for site
publishers and advertising agencies,'' said Kevin O'Connor,
chairman and chief executive at Double Click. ``With the
standardization that this partnership represents, we believe that
online advertising will improve industry-wide. And, by
consolidating our efforts with Ad Knowledge, we believe we can
expand DART's reach and market penetration.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Kauffman, president and chief exective at Ad Knowledge
said, ``We believe DART provides the best solution for Web site
publishers and we are confident our Click Wise customers will
benefit tremendously from the power of Double Click advanced
technology.'' Both Kauffman, 41, and O'Connor, 37, will continue in
their respective roles.
</P>
<P>
   The third deal involved Interactive8, an online marketing agency
in New York, which acquired Tuckett/Parshall Interactive in New
York, a specialist in interactive advertising aimed at black
consumers. Financial terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Tuckett/Parshall, which will be renamed as the TPI division of
Interactive8, has estimated billings of $500,000 from clients like
Essence magazine, Motown Records and Morgan Stanley, Dean Witter &AMP;
Co. TPI will be headed by Lawrence Tuckett, 43, founder and partner
at Tuckett/Parshall, who also becomes creative director, and
Michael Waite, 30, partner, who becomes executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition ``puts us at the forefront of urban online
marketing and will greatly benefit companies expanding into the
African-American consumer demographic,'' said Bill Markel, partner
at Interactive8. Interactive8 has 37 employees and estimated
billings of $4.9 million from clients like AT&AMP;T Corp., the Citibank
unit of Citicorp and the M&AMP;M/Mars unit of Mars Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The quickening pace of deal-making in cyberspace is echoing the
frenzied deal-making among traditional agencies as well as
reflecting how the dynamics of interactive advertising and
marketing are changing rapidly as the industry grows.
</P>
<P>
   Other Internet-related deals in the last month included two
acquisitions by Agency.com in New York; the purchase of Digital
Cafe, a digital media agency in St. Paul, by Campbell Mithun Esty
in Minneapolis, which is majority owned by the Interpublic Group;
the acquisition of Circle Interactive in Boston by Arnold
Communications, a unit of Snyder Communications in Boston, and the
expansion of the online career services of TMP Worldwide in New
York through the purchase of two Web sites, About Work and Student
Center, from Ivillage in New York for $1.7 million in cash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 1902EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0358 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2834 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-PAKISTAN-COX- &UR; -600     06-03 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-PAKISTAN-COX- </SLUG>
   -600&AMP;ADD 
 &HT;     CLINTON WARNS INDIA, PAKISTAN AGAINST `ARMS RACE;' RENEWS
FAVORED TRADING STATUS FOR CHINA
 &HT;     By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
