the Chinese government and the Chinese people, as opposed to
isolating Beijing or imposing trade and economic sanctions _ as is
U.S. policy toward Cuba, which, like China, is a one-party
communist state infamous for widespread human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Buttressing his engagement policy, Clinton renewed China's most
favored nation trading status, or MFN, on Wednesday, the day before
the annual June 4 deadline for doing so, according Chinese products
the same low tariffs in this country as the exports of most U.S.
trading partners.
</P>
<P>
   The president's renewal of MFN will stand unless it's overturned
by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Some representatives oppose MFN for China, claiming that the
country should be denied favorable trading terms with the United
States unless and until it improves its human rights record. Others
have raised concerns over Clinton's decision last year to allow the
transfer to China of sensitive satellite technology, which critics
maintain Beijing could use for military purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said, however, that the best way to work for change in
China is to improve relations and build common ground, not punish
Beijing with sanctions that most of rest of the world would not
match.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to renew (MFN) would be to sever our economic, and, to a
large measure, our strategic relationship with China, turning our
back on a fourth of the world,'' Clinton said. ``This policy
clearly is in our nation's interests, and I urge Congress to
support it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For clients of the New York Times News Service &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
