<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ECONSCENE-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC SCENE: IMF'S RX FOR RUSSIA RAISES CONCERNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RUSSIA-ECON, RUSSIA-YELTSIN) 
(mk) 
 By PETER PASSELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yet another emerging-market economy has been forced to the brink
by financial panic. And yet again the International Monetary Fund
is riding to the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   Only this time around the economy at risk is Russia, which is
far more feeble yet far more important in geopolitical terms than
the Asian Tigers. And the drumbeat is growing from critics of the
IMF, which places an enormous premium on stabilizing currency
exchange rates, sometimes at very high costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia is being asked to crush the opportunity for economic
growth in the name of short-term market stability,'' said Jeffrey
Sachs, the director of Harvard's Institute for International
Development.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, in a world of capital markets that can move
billions at the stir of a rumor, the alternatives to the IMF
prescription seem almost as problematic.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin gets a passing mark on economic reform
only if you grade on a curve. True, much of the economy's
industrial base has been privatized. Inflation is down to single
digits. And though the budget deficit in the first quarter of this
year _ at 4.6 percent of gross domestic product _ was high by
Western standards, it was right on the track set by the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   What has not been done, though _ or has been done badly _ haunts
the government. Sachs, for one, makes a big distinction between its
rapid privatization of manufacturing and its sale of natural
resources, notably oil and gas reserves.
</P>
<P>
   The former was a step forward, since the only hope for
modernizing Soviet enterprises was to introduce free market
incentives. But the ``virtual giveaway of hundreds of billions of
dollars in natural wealth deprived the state of desperately needed
revenues and created a powerful class of robber barons,'' Sachs
argues.
</P>
<P>
   The search for revenue has compounded Moscow's problems,
suggests Richard Medley, a New York adviser on financial risk
management. Under pressure from the IMF, tax rates were set high _
``so high,'' Medley said, ``that no one can afford to pay them.''
As a result, tax evasion has become the norm and, in the
time-tested fashion of politicians seeking to shed blame, Yeltsin
has ousted the tax collector.
</P>
<P>
   While the proximate cause of the financial panic of the last few
weeks was the failure of the government to sell off the Rosneft oil
enterprise for some $2 billion, no one doubts that the stage was
set by the financial troubles in Asia. And to some, the Asian
Tigers' continuing wobble suggests that the IMF has prescribed the
wrong medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Wade, a visiting scholar at the Russell Sage Foundation,
argues that the high interest rates and tight fiscal policy that
the IMF has demanded as a means of restoring confidence in the
Asian currencies is destroying indebted, but otherwise healthy,
businesses. ``The IMF spends too much effort defending old
orthodoxies _ not to mention the interests of Asia's foreign
creditors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For such skeptics, the big question is whether the IMF is again
applying flawed priorities and policies in Russia. Over the last
three years, Russia's domestic inflation has outpaced the
depreciation of the ruble by about 35 percent, Sachs noted,
attracting the attention of speculators even before Asia caught the
currency flu. Yet the IMF is encouraging the Yeltsin government to
use its dwindling credibility and foreign currency reserves in a
last-ditch defense of the exchange rate.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sachs is convinced the effort will ultimately fail. But even if
it does not, struggling Russian businesses could be shattered by
the exorbitant interest rates the government is paying to hold the
line on the ruble. This week, the government raised more than $1
billion in a debt sale that included one-week bills yielding just
under 40 percent. To service this debt, the government will have to
shift some resources that otherwise could have gone to keeping
pensioners fed and coal miners paid.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, the major alternative, a sharp depreciation of the
ruble, would also inflict a blow to the feeble Russian economy from
which it would not easily recover. With Russian banks and
enterprises owing roughly $30 billion on securities coming due in
the next year, Rudi Dornbusch of the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology reckons that letting the ruble go would ruin the banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``One way or another, Russia faces a big balance-sheet
problem,'' Dornbusch said: Either it will be devastated by high
interest rates, or debtors will face huge liabilities in dollars
they probably will not be able to repay.
</P>
<P>
   Dornbusch prefers the high-interest-rate devil he knows to the
collapse-of-the-ruble devil he doesn't. And that view will almost
certainly prevail for a while longer, since the West is apparently
committed to sustaining the exchange value of the ruble.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a lesson here, it is that short-term capital is no
friend to emerging economies. Russia's anarchic capitalism may have
little in common with the highly organized cronyism of Asia. But in
both cases, ``hot money'' has proved an Achilles' heel, magnifying
the impact of more fundamental institutional weaknesses and
immensely complicating rescue efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Genuine reforms, ranging from changes in the tax system to
application of the rule of law, are surely necessary to get the
Russian economy moving. As long as Russia depends on the good
opinion of international capital markets, though, those reforms may
not be sufficient.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
