<HEADER>
A2840 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMANY-RAILCRASH-ART     06-03 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-RAILCRASH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT LEAST 80 DEAD IN HIGH-SPEED TRAIN WRECK IN GERMANY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphics are being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ESCHEDE, Germany _ A high-speed passenger train roaring through
northern Germany crashed into a concrete bridge pillar at 125 mph
Wednesday, spun from the tracks and killed at least 80 people,
possibly including children on a school excursion. Hundreds more
were injured.
</P>
<P>
   German Railways officials called it the worst crash in post-war
German history and the worst in Europe in decades. The crash
stunned Germany, which prides itself on the safety and speed of the
aerodynamic silver-and-red Inter-City-Express system.
</P>
<P>
   Rail officials said the final toll could exceed 100. Wednesday
night, huge cranes were still trying to lift debris from two
crushed railroad cars in which anyone still living, a medical
official said, had only a ``minimal'' chance of surviving.
</P>
<P>
   Inter-City-Express 884 crashed just south of the small station
in Eschede, a town of 6,000, 35 miles north of Hanover. As it
approached the station, on its 500-mile journey from Munich to
Hamburg, it had been right on time at 10:59 a.m. The bullet-nosed
locomotive pulling a 13-car train sped under a road-bridge as the
carriages behind it twisted out of control, according to accounts
by rescue workers, police and railway officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw nothing on the tracks as I went under the bridge,'' said
the driver, who survived unharmed. His name was not immediately
released. ``Then there was a vibration. Then the automatic brakes
came on,'' he told German television.
</P>
<P>
   The brakes came on, railway officials said, because the
locomotive had been severed from the rest of the 1,200-foot-long
train. It sped alone unscathed for hundreds of yards along the
tracks until it came to a halt. Only at that point, said Gisel
Lunig, an official investigator, did the driver realize what had
happened.
</P>
<P>
   The first two carriages immediately behind the locomotive seemed
to have remained crookedly on the tracks. But others behind them
careened over a leafy embankment, leaving their iron wheels in
place as the carriages sheared away.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the bridge came crashing down, burying two cars full of
people as five or six more cars folded together like playing-cards,
creating a sculpture of horror that rose up where the road-bridge
had once been.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a loud noise, like a helicopter, a crashing, and
then there were railway carriages in front of my door,'' said a
woman living near the tracks, who asked not to be identified by
name.
</P>
<P>
   Then, for a moment, all was quiet. ``There was the silence of
the dead,'' said Gerhard Bleyl, a former mineworker, who said he
was among the first to arrive at the wreck. ``Then we saw about 20
or 30 people who had managed to escape. Noone said anything. Then
we heard whimpering and screams.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There were legs, arms, from adults and children, men and
women,'' said one rescue worker who lives near the tracks and who
asked not to be identified by name.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could hear children crying for their mothers,'' said
Bleyl, whose home is also close to the tracks. ``This is the worst
thing I have ever seen,'' said a fire service officer, Andreas
Koch. ``It is the worst thing anyone has seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Seats and suitcases had been thrown clear of the train along
with splinters of metal and chunks of concrete from the bridge.
Some passengers smashed their way out of the windows.
</P>
<P>
   Railway officials and police said they believed two groups of
school-children may have been been aboard the train and were
possibly in the cars trapped under the debris of the collapsed
road-bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Medical workers set up a field-hospital to perform emergency
surgery on survivors while others were taken by helicopter to
hospitals in Hamburg, Hanover, Bremen and elsewhere. Hearses queued
to take the dead away.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, around 1,200 rescue workers _ both civilian and
military _ were drafted into the battle to locate survivors from
the 759-seat train. ``There was one woman. She was injured herself.
But all she could do was scream for her three-year-old child,''
said Barbel Joachim, a rescue helper, ``So I went to look for the
child and she was injured.''
</P>
<P>
   Railways officials and police originally said around 300 people
were injured in Wednesday's crash. By Wednesday evening, nine hours
after crash, German television said that more than 100 bodies had
been pulled from the wreckage, but police did not confirm this
figure.
</P>
<P>
   The ICE trains can travel at speeds of up 175 mph on special
tracks and routinely travel at 125 mph on the stretch where the
accident happened, railway officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The train is regarded as the safest in Germany,'' a German
Railways spokesman said. Since the ICE trains came into service in
1991, none of the 104 trains in the fleet had been involved in a
fatal accident, he said. The ICE trains have airline type seats,
restaurants and telephones.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday night, there was no clear explanation of why the
train had derailed and struck the central pillar supporting the
road-bridge. Police and railways officials said they could not
confirm early reports that a car atop the road-bridge had somehow
swerved through safety barriers to land on the tracks in the path
of the train or on the train itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the cause of this accident is concerned, we are
still in the area of speculation,'' said Joachim Lindenberg, a
police spokesman. He confirmed, however, that the ruins of a car
had been found in the wreckage, but said it was unclear whether the
car finished up there after the bridge collapsed when the train
ploughed into it.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl cut short a visit to Italy to return to
Germany. His challenger in September's election, Gerhard Schroder,
called off a political rally in Hanover. The authorities in Bonn
ordered that flags be flown at half-staff on public buildings. ``I
am lost for words to comfort the bereaved,'' Kohl said.
</P>
<P>
   The worst previous rail disaster in western Germany in the past
53 years was just after World War II when a U.S. transport train
loaded with tanks collided with a trainload of German war
prisoners. The disaster claimed 102 lives.
</P>
<P>
   Europe's worst rail crash in recent decades was in 1974 when a
train traveling from Belgrade to Germany derailed in Croatia,
killing 153 people
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
