<SLUG> BC-CALIFORNIA-HISPANICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISPANIC VOTE MAY DECIDE CALIFORNIA ELECTIONS, ANALYSTS SAY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Growing Hispanic political activism in California
could be decisive in key elections this year, analysts said
Wednesday after primaries moved Latino candidates into almost half
the statewide races.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're ready for a breakthrough,'' Sherry Bebitch Jeffe, a
political scientist at Claremont Graduate University, said of the
fastest-growing segment of the California electorate. ``Whether or
not it will come is another question.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats especially are counting on Hispanic voters to help
them retake the California governorship after 16 years of
Republicans holding the top job in the nation's most populous
state.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans, aware they have alienated some Hispanics with
strong backing for ballot initiatives that have been labeled
anti-immigrant, promised a strong effort in the minority community.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the parties' efforts will be gubernatorial candidates
who emerged from the primary Tuesday: Democrat Gray Davis, the
lieutenant governor, and Republican Dan Lungren, the state attorney
general. They seek to succeed Republican Gov. Pete Wilson, who must
leave office because of term limits.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren, in a calculated public break with Wilson and other
Republicans leaders, and Davis opposed the anti-bilingual education
proposition that was overwhelmingly approved by voters Tuesday.
Proposition 227 would allow most students one year of intensive
English instruction before requiring a return to regular classes.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican American Legal Defense and Educational Fund said it
filed suit Wednesday in U.S. District Court in San Francisco
seeking to have the measure thrown out, contending it would deny
equal educational opportunity to English-deficient students.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic leaders Wednesday attacked Lungren for his support of
two earlier initiatives that have drawn the ire of Hispanics, the
1994 measure to deny almost all state services to illegal
immigrants and the 1996 proposition scuttling the state's
affirmative action program. Davis opposed both measures.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats hope they have a magnet for Hispanic voters in their
lieutenant governor nominee, Cruz Bustamante, the first Hispanic
speaker of the California Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Bustamante, whom operatives in both parties regard as an
effective campaigner, said Wednesday he would fight to ``keep my
party in the center _ where I think the heart of my party is.''
</P>
<P>
   Lungren countered by signaling he will try to portray Davis,
whose first governmental experience was as chief of staff to
Democratic Gov. Edmund G. ``Jerry'' Brown Jr. in the 1970s and 80s,
as a classic liberal.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, whose last political ventures were failed presidential
races, returned to elective life Tuesday, winning the mayor's race
in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats outlined Lungren's ``troubles,'' leading off with his
opposition to abortion _ an issue that separates the Republican not
only from Davis but also from incumbent Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   In seeking to appeal to Hispanics, Republicans have turned to
San Mateo County Supervisor Ruben Barrales as their candidate for
state controller. Barrales is one of only three Hispanic
Republicans in California holding an office with a countywide or
larger constituency.
</P>
<P>
   Bustamante and Barrales are two of four Hispanics in the nine
major statewide races. Democrat Diane Martinez, daughter of Rep.
Matthew G. Martinez, D-Calif., is running for insurance
commissioner. Gloria Matta Tuchman, a Republican who supported the
anti-bilingual initiative, is challenging an incumbent Democrat who
opposed the measure, in a race for the post of superintendent of
public education.
</P>
<P>
   Only one Hispanic has made it to the statewide general election
ballot in modern California history, political operatives and
analysts said. Former state Sen. Art Torres, now the state
Democratic chairman, ran for insurance commissioner in 1994 but
lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really have a history to go on'' of whether Latino
candidates draw fellow minorities to the polls, said Mark
Baldassare of the Public Policy Institute of California. ``This
ballot is going to be a real test of that issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Baldassare estimates that one in six California voters is
Hispanic, ``so they can definitely make the difference in a close
election _ which is what I expect in the gubernatorial and U.S.
Senate races.''
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. House contest in Orange County may serve to re-enforce
any Hispanic discontent with Republicans. The primary set up a
rematch of the bitter 1996 race between former GOP Rep. Robert
Dornan and the Democrat who defeated him two years ago, Rep.
Loretta Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
   In another U.S. House race of note, Republican Rep. Jay Kim, the
only Korean-American in Congress, became the first incumbent to be
defeated this year. Kim is currently under house arrest in
Washington on a campaign finance conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Matt Fong, the state treasurer, won the Republican
nomination to challenge Sen. Barbara Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
