<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-TELECOMMUNICATIONS-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINT CORP. RAISES CURTAIN ON NEW TELECOMMUNICATIONS TECHNOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 1997 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sprint Corp. staged a full-scale Broadway production
this week to showcase technology that could radically change the
way telecommunications services are delivered, what they cost and
how customers are billed for them.
</P>
<P>
   The presentation _ featuring actors, a stage set and a
supporting cast of Sprint executives _ played to a full house of
securities analysts, corporate customers and reporters Tuesday at
the Richard Rodgers Theater.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the show was a radical new network design
that Sprint calls the Integrated On-demand Network, or ION.
</P>
<P>
   Basically it's a $2 billion upgrade to the company's fiberoptic
long-distance network. But more important, experts say, it's a
technological advance that could vault Sprint into the lucrative
market for local phone services and breathe new life into
futuristic communications services such as videoconferencing, video
on demand and ultrafast Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint released the outlines of the integrated network Monday.
In the Broadway presentation Tuesday, Sprint executives stressed
that the technology was not some pipe dream in a laboratory but was
set for delivery to businesses and consumers in the next year and a
half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other companies may have bits and pieces of this,'' said
Sprint Chairman William T. Esrey, ``but only Sprint has it all. And
only Sprint has it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprint may be the first to the market with such a system,
analysts said, but other phone companies are working on similar
networks.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, Sprint intends to replace the current telephone
system, which relies on a 100-year-old technology of copper lines
and electronic switches, with a digital-age network that can handle
the exploding audio, video and data traffic generated by the
Internet, corporate intranets and wide-area networks.
</P>
<P>
   By modern standards, the existing system is a hugely inefficient
user of calling capacity. From the time you make a call to when you
hang up, the system opens a dedicated end-to-end circuit. And as
any frustrated Web surfer or parent of teen-agers can attest, while
that call is in progress, the line cannot be used for anything
else.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the tangled patchwork of facilities pieced together by
most large phone companies is full of traffic bottlenecks and being
rapidly overloaded by the demands of a digital age. The time needed
to send most audio and video over standard phone lines makes them
practically useless for those applications.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, Sprint intends to abandon dedicated-circuit
switching in favor of a vastly more efficient network that dices up
traffic into digital bits and bytes, sends them at light speed over
many parallel avenues to their destination and reassembles them
there.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint already operates one of the most efficient networks in
the business, a web of fiberoptic rings that it began building in
1984 and marketed for its ``pin drop'' call clarity.
</P>
<P>
   By overlaying high-speed switches, routers and proprietary
software, the company says, it can generate almost unlimited
capacity while reducing the cost of a long-distance call by up to
70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The company also plans to extend its fiberoptic network to 60
cities by the end of 1999, which will allow it to bypass local
phone companies and push its high-tech services directly to
business and residential customers.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to run its lines directly into most large
businesses. To provide high-speed service to smaller companies and
residential customers, it plans to employ cable modems, wireless
systems or technology that will allow it to send high-speed digital
signals over copper lines. That technology is known as XDSL.
</P>
<P>
   ``This announcement marks Sprint's entry into the local
market,'' said Ronald LeMay, the company's president. ``Where I
come from, that's called killing two birds with one stone.''
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate how the ION network will work, Sprint executives
compared it to an electric utility that delivered as much power _
or in this case communications bandwidth _ as a customer needed at
any moment, through a single connection.
</P>
<P>
   Residential customers would have to buy a $200 box that
allocates capacity and meters usage. Through the box, they would be
able to control their own bandwidth use, adding phone lines, fax
machines or Internet connections at will, just as they can switch
on lamps and run the dishwasher and a hair dryer at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   For example, people in the same household could simultaneously
conduct a videoconference, surf the Internet, download a video and
send a fax using the same line.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses, however, are slated to be the first customers for
high-bandwidth service, and the potential benefits are enormous.
Sprint's network promises to facilitate telecommuting, distance
learning for employees, real- time desktop collaboration and
electronic commerce. It could also alleviate the pressure on
businesses to maintain dedicated technical support staff to deal
with the endless problems on their networks.
</P>
<P>
   At Tuesday's presentation, actors on an elaborate stage
portrayed the contrast between the old and new phone systems as
envisioned by Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   In the first act, four members of a fictional family vied for
control of the single line running into their home, which resulted
in a high-volume family feud and a cacophonous systems crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think that was bad, imagine what it's like at a
business,'' Esrey said as he stepped back into the footlights. That
led into a similar demonstration of pandemonium as three business
colleagues tried to collaborate on an on-line marketing
presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Both acts were followed by idyllic depictions of what would have
occurred had they been using the new network. MORE
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ the new network.
</P>
<P>
   The company also mounted several live demonstrations in which
employees put some prototype residential equipment through its
paces.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the realization that Sprint's famed guerrilla
marketers had reached their zenith in terms of corporate theater,
typically skeptical analysts and customers were impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the real deal,'' said Kenneth McGee, an industry
analyst with the Gartner Group. ``We think this vision is terrific.
It's clearly where every carrier has to head.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also warned that Sprint would soon face competition
from other phone companies building similar networks.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Sprint still has a way to go before it totally realizes
its vision. It said it expected to spend about $400 million in the
next two years as it rolled out its network.
</P>
<P>
   The company and two strategic partners _ Bellcore and Cisco
Systems _ are still working on upgrades to the network and software
that will ensure reliability and functionality, which are critical
to persuade customers to adopt the service.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to say you've entered the market, and another
for customers to believe it's safe to use the network,'' McGee
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another big hurdle that analysts foresee is Sprint's ability to
strike deals with local carriers to gain access to small-business
and residential customers using their copper lines. To do that,
Sprint must lease space in the local companies' switching centers
and install their own equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the amount of bandwidth that Sprint can provide to
some customers may be limited by the condition of the copper lines
that run to most homes and small businesses. In some cases, those
lines may be incapable of carrying high-speed service.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Brauer, president of Sprint's national integrated services
division, said the company was ``close to an agreement with a
couple of the regional Bell companies.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he said, the company's research shows that 70 percent of
households are capable of receiving some level of broadband
service. For those that aren't, he said, the company has other
options, including wireless technology or cable modems.
</P>
<P>
   One of the immediate effects of Sprint's move will be on the
$250 billion market for telephone equipment and software. By
abandoning a circuit-switched network, Sprint is pushing aside
traditional suppliers in favor of new partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the investment community has figured that out
yet,'' McGee said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
