r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      06-03 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEALTH TAX INCREASES DO LITTLE TO REFORM SOCIAL SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: When The Kiplinger Washington Letter recently advised
its business clients to anticipate a boost of the Social Security
taxable wage base to as high as $71,700 next year, it raised a
question of why this method of increasing the payroll tax
continues.
</P>
<P>
   The question is pertinent because Social Security is overtaxing
Americans to no good purpose except to provide bigger and bigger
windfalls for Washington. A recent fund-raiser from United Seniors
Association Inc. sought support for proposed legislation that would
minimize Social Security's cash cow function. The letter estimated
that this year's payroll tax would generate $80 billion more than
is needed to fund benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The money, as usual, will be spent on general budget outlays and
Social Security's trust fund will get an IOU. While the public is
starting to become increasingly aware of this scam, the practice of
enhancing Social Security receipts by expanding Social Security's
taxable wage base remains largely overlooked. And even if there
were more awareness there probably wouldn't be all that much
breast-beating because these tax increases hit only the highest
wage-earners.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the point, though. While there may be a convincing
case to be made for removing the cap from Social Security's taxable
wage base, this is something apart from Washington's yearly
practice of milking more revenue at the margin to create more
spendable income.
</P>
<P>
   Those interested in true reform can claim a righteous cause only
if a substantial expansion of the taxable wage base is accompanied
by relief for taxpayers at the bottom rungs of the wage scale.
Social Security is the most regressive tax ever devised because of
the way it hits low-wage workers much harder than high-wage
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, in theory at least, lack of means-testing means the
taxes of workers earning less than poverty-level wages could be
funding the benefits of millionaire Social Security recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, the practice of expanding the taxable wage base each
year benefits nobody but Washington's big spenders because the
so-called trust fund doesn't exist except as markers issued by
Uncle Sam. Since excessive Social Security taxation was mandated in
the early 1980s to prevent the system's insolvency, the Treasury
has taken in about $630 billion in excess taxes and spent the
money.
</P>
<P>
   The wage base expansions aren't small potatoes, either. They
affect both employers and employees, and an increase next year to
$71,700 would be an increase of 40 percent for the wage base this
decade. For those lucky enough to have earned the maximum
throughout the 1990s, the combined employee-employer Social
Security tax bill has risen substantially.
</P>
<P>
   This might be defensible if Social Security needed the money,
but it doesn't because the system is overfunded.
</P>
<P>
   The point man for the bill being pushed by United Seniors is
Rep. Mark Neumann of Wisconsin, who seeks to force the Treasury to
invest Social Security's surpluses in real financial assets with
market value. The IOUs being deposited in the trust fund are
nonmarketable securities and thus have no practical value except as
a future claim on the Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Both Neumann's reform and the efforts to privatize the system
are worthy goals, but the time has come to stop the annual stealth
tax increases imposed by automatic expansions of the taxable wage
base.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 1915EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0368 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2849 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-03 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: ENTER THE SUPREMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Next Monday, the Supreme Court _ acting swiftly,
even in a jam-packed June with more than 30 decisions to be handed
down _ will hear argument on whether a dead man can be forced to
tell his tale.
</P>
<P>
   It stems from the abuse of power known as (1) Travelgate. Just
before Vincent Foster committed suicide, he unburdened himself to
his lawyer, presumably including Hillary Rodham Clinton's role in
the firing and smearing of seven government employees.
</P>
<P>
   For two years, Ken Starr's grand jury has been trying to get the
three pages of notes taken that day by Foster's lawyer to make the
case that Hillary lied about this. The lawyer, James Hamilton,
argues that attorney-client confidentiality should continue after
the client's death.
</P>
<P>
   Although lawyers have often been examined about the intentions
of dead clients in wills, most people assume that what they tell
their lawyers remains privileged forever. So did a trial judge, but
an appeals court reversed, holding that death protected the client
from prosecution and the need to do justice outweighed the need for
confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   This case is what learned counsel call a toughie, but that's why
we have a Supreme Court. As a privacy nut, I hope the justices
decide to extend the privilege beyond the grave _ but in criminal
cases, to allow a judge to examine a lawyer in camera to see if
such testimony is essential for a grand jury to do justice to the
living.
</P>
<P>
   The Supremes will not have to decide President Clinton's claim
of (2) executive privilege to shield his PR aide Sidney Blumenthal
because when Starr went eyeball-to-eyeball with the White House on
this, Clinton blinked. I think the president knew this claim on a
matter unrelated to national security was a loser all along, but
made it in lower court to run down the clock. Smart; it bought him
four months.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal, lest we forget, may be Colson Revisited. Watergate
buffs will recall that Nixon counsel Charles Colson pled guilty to
disseminating derogatory information from Daniel Ellsberg's FBI
file to influence the outcome of the Pentagon Papers leaker's
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Especially coming from a federal official, such defamation was
obstruction of justice; Special Prosecutor Leon Jaworski wrote on
June 12, 1974, that Colson's Section 1503 conviction was ``of great
national significance in helping to insure the sanctity of the
judicial process with respect to cases involving controversial
defendants.'' I suspect Starr will charge that a defamation
conspiracy is obstruction whether aimed at defense or prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Though Clinton has fled the field at least temporarily on
stretching executive privilege, he hopes the Supremes will not take
action on (3) government attorney-client privilege, which he has
claimed to keep his notorious consigliere, Bruce Lindsey, from
testifying.
</P>
<P>
   Should the high court review this now, as Starr urges, or wait
till next year, thereby easing Clinton past the midterm elections?
The 8th Circuit Court of Appeals has already agreed with Starr in
deciding a similar case, ordering White House lawyers to testify
about two Hillary debriefings; the Supremes refused a Clinton plea
to review. Because the latest White House maneuver aims strictly to
delay, the court should sink its teeth into this ripe tomato
forthwith.
</P>
<P>
   And to be consistent, it should deal expeditiously with
Clinton's most egregious reach, bypassing the legislative branch to
assert a royal prerogative: (4) the see-no-evil bodyguard
privilege. The White House pretends to have nothing to do with the
claim that turns the Secret Service into the Silent Service _ as if
the Treasury Department, represented in this by Clinton Justice,
were independent of the executive branch.
</P>
<P>
   Bodyguards need to stick close to a president when he is in
crowds or in potential danger, not when he is in the Oval Office or
speaking tete-a-tete to an adviser or visitor who has been
electronically scanned. The notion that he would push away
protection while exposed in a crowd is ludicrous. The court should
tell the agents they can maintain their tradition of discretion
without seeking special privilege through judicial fiat.
</P>
<P>
   I realize all this burdens the justices in their busiest time,
but then they can hit the beaches until the first Monday in
October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
