</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ECON-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN BOND SALE JUDGED A MODERATE SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RUSSIA-YELTSIN, RUSSIA-ECONSCENE) 
(th) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's unsteady economy survived a critical test
Wednesday as the government sold nearly $1 billion in treasury
bills without paying the colossal interest rates that the bonds
traded at just a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Anxious foreign investors, fearing the treasury bill auction
would fail to draw enough investors, breathed a sign of relief.
While the auction did not raise all the money the government
sought, it was judged a moderate success. Stock prices rose in
Russia for a second day. A more skeptical bond market pushed prices
lower.
</P>
<P>
   Russia also sold $1.25 billion in long-term bonds, so-called
Eurobonds, to international investors mostly in Europe and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday's auction also illustrated Russia's economic
predicament. Since the government did not raise all of the money it
needed to cover debts that are coming due it will be forced to dip
into its reserves.
</P>
<P>
   And the auction raised the question of how long Russia will be
able to stagger on without billions of dollars in additional
financing from the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have done well so far,'' said Al Breach, an economist at
the Russian-European Center for Economic Policy. ``But this has
been a very hairy week, and each week is going to be hairy until
investors have more confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Another 5.5 billion rubles in Treasury bills, or about $900
million, comes due next week. The following week treasury notes
worth another 8.1 billion rubles, or $1.3 billion, mature. That has
led many investors to argue that billions of dollars in additional
loans from the IMF and other international organizations are needed
to help Russia keep its currency stable and restructure the cost of
its short-term debt.
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday's auction, the interest rates ranged from 40
percent to 54 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Russia depends on the sale of treasury bills to finance its huge
budget deficit, which last year was 6.1 percent of the country's
gross domestic product. The goal is to reduce the deficit to 5
percent of GDP this year through a combination of spending cuts and
tax increases.
</P>
<P>
   Reducing the deficit is a crucial goal because interest payments
on the debt amount to about a third of total spending, more than
double the level in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russian government cannot carry on paying 50 percent
interest rates for a long period of time,'' said Breach. ``It will
kill the budget.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As Russia's financial markets have been pounded by the global
economic crisis, the Yeltsin government has been desperately trying
to reassure investors both at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Foreigners own about about a quarter of the treasury bills,
making Russia's financial stability vulnerable to the calculations
and whims of far-off investors who have a tendency to abandon a
distressed country just when the money is needed most.
</P>
<P>
   Russia had been making progress pushing down the interest rates
of the treasury bills when the currency crisis in Asia erupted. As
investors lost confidence in emerging markets, however, rates began
rising as they began cashing in Russian treasury bills for rubles.
</P>
<P>
   The investors had contracts with Russian banks that allowed them
to convert the rubles into dollars, creating a surplus of rubles
and weakening the value of the ruble value against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's auction followed several failed attempts to raise
enough money to pay short-term maturing debt. The auction actually
involved three types of treasury bills known as GKOs: One type
matured in 343 days, another matured in 126 days and the third was
a seven-day bill, the shortest treasury bill Russia has ever
issued.
</P>
<P>
   To stir up demand, President Boris Yeltsin summoned Russia's 10
leading businessmen and financiers to the Kremlin on Tuesday and
told them they had a duty to invest in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   In selling the bills, the Finance Ministry was determined to
hold down its borrowing costs. It was operating on the expectation
that investors will soon regain confidence in the market or that
less costly interest rates will become available after the monetary
fund leads a bailout.
</P>
<P>
   It sold the seven-day bills with an average interest rate of 40
percent. The other bills had an average interest rate of 54
percent.
</P>
<P>
   While those rates are very high for an economy in which
inflation is running at about 11 percent or 12 percent, they are a
far cry from the 80 percent and 90 percent interest rates of last
week. They are even a bit lower than the interest rates paid
Tuesday by the secondary market in treasury securities.
</P>
<P>
   But holding down interest costs also meant that the Russian
government did not sell all the bills it offered. The Finance
Ministry, for example, was ready to sell 2.5 billion rubles worth
of seven-day bills. It sold half a billion rubles worth.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Wednesday's auction raised 5.83 billion rubles, or
about $950 million. That meant that the Finance Ministry had to dip
into its reserves to pay 2.58 billion rubles, or about $420
million, to redeem treasury bills that matured Wednesday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 1919EDT &QL; 
