<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAHRAIN-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAHRAIN'S LEADER IN U.S. TO COURT INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In his first visit to the United States in seven
years, the Emir of Bahrain came not to buy U.S. military hardware
or ask for more protection against Iraq's Saddam Hussein, but to
woo American investors. Quietly.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Sheik Isa bin Salman al-Khalifa doesn't like to
play rainmaker.
</P>
<P>
   The emir did not stop by New York's citadels of capitalism the
way Chinese President Jiang Zemin did last year, when he visited
the New York Stock Exchange and IBM. Instead, during his stopover
in New York, the emir chose to recover from jet lag and meet
privately with the U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
   The man who has been Bahrain's monarch for 36 years did not give
one speech, grant one interview or hold one news conference during
his stay.
</P>
<P>
   Bahrain has loyally acted as host to the U.S. Navy's 5th Fleet
for decades and even accepted more U.S. troops and equipment during
the recent crisis with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   But the emir did not demand a state dinner, with flags flying
along Pennsylvania Avenue and a 21-gun salute on the White House
lawn, as a payoff. He settled for the less lofty ``official'' visit
instead, which at least gave him lodging at Blair House, the
official residence across the street from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   For most countries, the art of commercial diplomacy is to get
out and tell your story. And if Bahrain had more oil, perhaps the
emir's reticence wouldn't make much of a difference.
</P>
<P>
   But Bahrain is the smallest, the least wealthy and the most
densely populated of the six monarchies on the Persian Gulf.
Seventy percent of its population is under the age of 27.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years it has survived by building itself up as a
service-based economy, the banking center of the Persian Gulf and
an oasis for Saudi-based Westerners who can drive across the
causeway from Saudi Arabia to relax and drink alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Now it wants to diversify beyond oil and aluminum.
</P>
<P>
   So why not tell your story?
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with the Bahrainis is that they just don't have
the PR gene,'' said an American businessman with long ties to the
country. ``They don't understand how to project their image. Poor
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The emir did rub shoulders with corporate America at a dinner
given by six corporations _ Caltex, Turner Broadcasting System
Inc., Lockheed Martin, Citibank, Chevron and Leo Daly _ at the Four
Seasons Hotel on Monday night. He made a few opening remarks, but
left it to his finance minister to give a speech on why Bahrain is
such a good place for American investors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 1920EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0371 </DOCNO>
