<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2859 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ERITREA-ETHIOPIA-ART-     06-03 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ERITREA-ETHIOPIA-ART-576&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHTING BREAKS OUT BETWEEN ERITREA AND ETHIOPIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY JR.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASMARA, Eritrea _ Heavy fighting broke out early Wednesday
morning between Ethiopian and Eritrean troops along the common
border of their two countries, dealing a serious blow to diplomatic
efforts to avert a full-scale war between the former allies,
Eritrean officials and witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   Eritrea said the Ethiopian troops crossed the border and mounted
an attack at 5:30 a.m. on Eritrean positions in the Ambesete Geleba
region just west of the border town of Zala Ambessa, about 60 miles
southeast of this capital.
</P>
<P>
   The Ethiopian troops used tanks and heavy artillery in the
assault, a spokesman for the Foreign Ministry, Amdemicael Kahasai,
said. The fighting continued into the late afternoon, but by
nightfall the guns where silent, Eritrean officials said. No
casualty figures were available, and it was unclear where the
battle lines stood.
</P>
<P>
   ``This attack represents a new and dangerous escalation of the
crisis between Eritrea and Ethiopia,'' Amdemicael said.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate confirmation of the fighting from the
Ethiopian government. Instead, the Ethiopian Foreign Ministry
issued a statement saying Eritrean forces had tried once again to
take the towns of Alitena and Ayga, which lie about 15 miles west
of Zala Ambessa and were the focus of another clash last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting has dampened hopes for a peaceful settlement to the
crisis, diplomats said. An American team of diplomats who were
trying to bring the two sides to the negotiating table remained in
the Ethiopian capital, Addis Ababa, Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The two countries had been close allies since Eritrea became
independent in 1993, but until recently they had disagreed
peacefully about their common border.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia asserts that it has jurisdiction over a number of areas
that used to be part of the Ethiopian administrative province of
Tigray, but Eritrea claims those regions are now within its
territory and has cited turn-of-the-century treaties between the
Italian colonizers and the Ethiopian emperor as proof of their
claims.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute turned violent on May 6 when Eritrean troops clashed
with Ethiopian forces near the border town of Badame, about 90
miles southwest of Asmara. Both sides accuse the other side of
invading.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, both governments have sent tens of thousands of
soldiers, backed by tanks and artillery, into the disputed regions,
while American diplomats and regional leaders have shuttled between
the capitals in an attempt to find a peaceful solution to the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   But Ethiopia has insisted that Eritrea withdraw its troops from
what it considers Ethiopian territory before talks can begin.
Eritrea has refused to withdraw, asserting that its soldiers had
never crossed what it says is the border.
</P>
<P>
   Eritrea has also said its troops in Badame only took back land
the Ethiopians had occupied last year. For more than nine months,
Eritrean officials said, Ethiopian officials in Tigray have tried
to extend their influence northward by sending settlers into the
Eritrean territory and setting up administrations.
</P>
<P>
   A full-scale conflict would be disastrous not only for the two
countries, which are still trying to rebuild after decades of civil
war, but also for the stability of the entire region, diplomats
say.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Wednesday, Amdemicael said the clash was
the fifth occasion in the last week that Ethiopian troops had
attacked Eritrean positions along the border.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Three of these attacks, he said, took place in the region around
Badame last week. The most recent occurred on Sunday near the town
of Alitena, about 15 miles east of Wednesday's fighting.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's clash, Ethiopian officials say Eritrean troops
crossed the border and fought Ethiopian militiamen at the town of
Dal Geda. The militia later withdrew. Ethiopian troops then engaged
the Eritreans and pushed them back into Eritrea, these officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Eritrea's version of the clash near Alitena is radically
different. Eritrean military officials deny invading Ethiopia and
maintain it was the Ethiopian troops who penetrated nearly 12 miles
into Eritrean territory.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the renewed fighting Wednesday, Amdemicael said Eritrea
remained committed to finding a peaceful solution. He said Eritrea
is still calling for both countries to pull their troops back from
the border and create a demilitarized zone. Eritrea has also called
for a third country or for the United Nations to arbitrate the
dispute and demarcate the border once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the Ethiopian government persists in its
intransigent position of launching a full-scale war unless Eritrea
withdraws unconditionally from territories that are indisputably
Eritrean,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews this week, Ethiopian officials said the Eritrean
actions around Badame and Sheraro amounted to an invasion and that
to start negotiations before Eritrean troops withdraw would be to
surrender Ethiopian sovereignty over the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you draw the line here, nobody will be able to know
what the Eritreans might do tomorrow,'' the deputy foreign minister
of Ethiopia, Tekeda Alemu, said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Eritrea has a regular army of about 35,000 men, most of them
battle-hardened veterans from the 30-year war for independence that
ended in 1991 with the defeat of Ethiopia's Marxist dictator,
Mengistu Haile Mariam. In recent days, it has also called up at
least 10,000 reservists, many of them former guerrillas, and sent
them to the frontier.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Ethiopia has about 120,000 men under arms, though
it is unclear how many of them are in Tigray. Many of the top
commanders and enlisted men in the Ethiopian army are former rebels
from the Tigray region who fought hand in hand with the Eritrean
rebels to overthrow Mengistu. Some were even trained by the
Eritrean rebel movement that now controls the country.
</P>
<P>
   Both armies have experience fighting conventional battles in the
region they are now fighting over, military experts said. Both have
artillery and tanks as well as small air forces.
</P>
<P>
   In the Eritrean capital Wednesday, the mood was muted as news of
the fighting spread through town. Many people said they cannot
believe the border dispute is on the verge of exploding into
another war, yet many also expressed a grim determination to defend
their territory whatever the cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fighting is no solution,'' said one taxi driver, Habte
Frezghy, who is a former rebel. ``They need to sit down at the
table and talk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
