A2867 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPRINT-TELECOMMUNICAT     06-03 0438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-TELECOMMUNICATIONS-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ the new network.
</P>
<P>
   The company also mounted several live demonstrations in which
employees put some prototype residential equipment through its
paces.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the realization that Sprint's famed guerrilla
marketers had reached their zenith in terms of corporate theater,
typically skeptical analysts and customers were impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the real deal,'' said Kenneth McGee, an industry
analyst with the Gartner Group. ``We think this vision is terrific.
It's clearly where every carrier has to head.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also warned that Sprint would soon face competition
from other phone companies building similar networks.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Sprint still has a way to go before it totally realizes
its vision. It said it expected to spend about $400 million in the
next two years as it rolled out its network.
</P>
<P>
   The company and two strategic partners _ Bellcore and Cisco
Systems _ are still working on upgrades to the network and software
that will ensure reliability and functionality, which are critical
to persuade customers to adopt the service.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to say you've entered the market, and another
for customers to believe it's safe to use the network,'' McGee
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another big hurdle that analysts foresee is Sprint's ability to
strike deals with local carriers to gain access to small-business
and residential customers using their copper lines. To do that,
Sprint must lease space in the local companies' switching centers
and install their own equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the amount of bandwidth that Sprint can provide to
some customers may be limited by the condition of the copper lines
that run to most homes and small businesses. In some cases, those
lines may be incapable of carrying high-speed service.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Brauer, president of Sprint's national integrated services
division, said the company was ``close to an agreement with a
couple of the regional Bell companies.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he said, the company's research shows that 70 percent of
households are capable of receiving some level of broadband
service. For those that aren't, he said, the company has other
options, including wireless technology or cable modems.
</P>
<P>
   One of the immediate effects of Sprint's move will be on the
$250 billion market for telephone equipment and software. By
abandoning a circuit-switched network, Sprint is pushing aside
traditional suppliers in favor of new partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the investment community has figured that out
yet,'' McGee said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
