</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEALTH TAX INCREASES DO LITTLE TO REFORM SOCIAL SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: When The Kiplinger Washington Letter recently advised
its business clients to anticipate a boost of the Social Security
taxable wage base to as high as $71,700 next year, it raised a
question of why this method of increasing the payroll tax
continues.
</P>
<P>
   The question is pertinent because Social Security is overtaxing
Americans to no good purpose except to provide bigger and bigger
windfalls for Washington. A recent fund-raiser from United Seniors
Association Inc. sought support for proposed legislation that would
minimize Social Security's cash cow function. The letter estimated
that this year's payroll tax would generate $80 billion more than
is needed to fund benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The money, as usual, will be spent on general budget outlays and
Social Security's trust fund will get an IOU. While the public is
starting to become increasingly aware of this scam, the practice of
enhancing Social Security receipts by expanding Social Security's
taxable wage base remains largely overlooked. And even if there
were more awareness there probably wouldn't be all that much
breast-beating because these tax increases hit only the highest
wage-earners.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the point, though. While there may be a convincing
case to be made for removing the cap from Social Security's taxable
wage base, this is something apart from Washington's yearly
practice of milking more revenue at the margin to create more
spendable income.
</P>
<P>
   Those interested in true reform can claim a righteous cause only
if a substantial expansion of the taxable wage base is accompanied
by relief for taxpayers at the bottom rungs of the wage scale.
Social Security is the most regressive tax ever devised because of
the way it hits low-wage workers much harder than high-wage
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, in theory at least, lack of means-testing means the
taxes of workers earning less than poverty-level wages could be
funding the benefits of millionaire Social Security recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, the practice of expanding the taxable wage base each
year benefits nobody but Washington's big spenders because the
so-called trust fund doesn't exist except as markers issued by
Uncle Sam. Since excessive Social Security taxation was mandated in
the early 1980s to prevent the system's insolvency, the Treasury
has taken in about $630 billion in excess taxes and spent the
money.
</P>
<P>
   The wage base expansions aren't small potatoes, either. They
affect both employers and employees, and an increase next year to
$71,700 would be an increase of 40 percent for the wage base this
decade. For those lucky enough to have earned the maximum
throughout the 1990s, the combined employee-employer Social
Security tax bill has risen substantially.
</P>
<P>
   This might be defensible if Social Security needed the money,
but it doesn't because the system is overfunded.
</P>
<P>
   The point man for the bill being pushed by United Seniors is
Rep. Mark Neumann of Wisconsin, who seeks to force the Treasury to
invest Social Security's surpluses in real financial assets with
market value. The IOUs being deposited in the trust fund are
nonmarketable securities and thus have no practical value except as
a future claim on the Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Both Neumann's reform and the efforts to privatize the system
are worthy goals, but the time has come to stop the annual stealth
tax increases imposed by automatic expansions of the taxable wage
base.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 1935EDT &QL; 
