<HEADER>
A2875 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-03 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE SKY DIDN'T FALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BOB HERBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finally the benefits of the nation's long-running economic
expansion are reaching the folks at the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   It was an article of faith not too long ago that an unemployment
rate of 6 percent or less was bad news, a harbinger of runaway
inflation and all the ills that accompany it. (Not surprisingly,
this was never a doctrine advanced by the unemployed. It was a
belief most fervently held by well-fed professors with tenure.)
</P>
<P>
   Well, in April the jobless rate fell to 4.3 percent, the lowest
level in nearly three decades, and the sky hasn't fallen with it.
The numbers for May are not yet out, but over the past year or two
there has been reasonably good news across the board for low-wage
workers, and without a hint of accelerating inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Jared Bernstein, an economist with the Economic Policy Institute
in Washington, noted that from 1996 to 1997 the hourly wages of the
bottom 20 percent of workers increased by 3.2 percent in real
terms. That compared with a 1.5 percent increase in the top 20
percent of wage and salary workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an example not only of strong wage growth, but stronger
at the bottom than at the top,'' said Bernstein. ``You couldn't
find a 3.2 percent increase at any point in this recovery for
workers at the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``That said, these workers are in such a deep hole that these
conditions would have to persist for a long time if they ever hope
to make up their two decades of wage declines.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein and others have cited three principal reasons for the
recent wage growth: tight labor markets, continued low inflation
and increases in the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, when Bob Dole was running for president, it was
an article of faith among conservative Republicans that an increase
in the minimum wage would result in job losses for low-wage
workers. According to this doctrine, large numbers of employers
would rather let workers go than give them a modest raise.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Armey, the House majority leader and holder of a Ph.D. in
economics, denounced the Democratic proposal to hike the minimum
wage by 90 cents an hour as ``a cruel hoax on the least-advantaged
workers in the system.'' He said the minimum wage should be
abolished.
</P>
<P>
   William Niskanen, chairman of the conservative Cato Institute,
told a House committee, ``It is hard to explain the continued
support for increasing the minimum wage by those interested in
helping the working poor.''
</P>
<P>
   Return with us now to reality. Bernstein is the co-author, with
John Schmitt, of a rigorous study of the impact of the 1996-97
minimum wage increase. It found that the increase raised the wages
of nearly 10 million workers, most of them adults and more than
half of them women, without causing job loss.
</P>
<P>
   The study said: ``The benefits of the increase
disproportionately help those working households at the bottom of
the income scale. Although households in the bottom 20 percent
(whose average income was $15,728 in 1996) received only 5 percent
of total national income, 35 percent of the benefits from the
minimum wage increase went to these workers. In this regard, the
increase had the intended effect of raising the earnings and
incomes of low-wage workers and their households.''
</P>
<P>
   I am still waiting for Armey, Niskanen and their brethren to
explain how this is a bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about the way things are lining up,'' Bernstein
said. He noted that even the groups facing the most difficult
employment hurdles, including young and less-well-educated
African-Americans, are experiencing some improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 20 percent unemployment rate is still a Depression-level
number,'' he said. ``But it's better than 25 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge now is to keep the economy moving in a way that
benefits everyone, not just those at the top. It won't be easy.
When the April unemployment numbers were released, the inflation
hawks got their usual jitters. Was it time to raise interest rates
and curb this spreading prosperity? Were workers making 10 or 15
grand a year becoming a threat to the nation's millionaires?
Wouldn't it be prudent, at least, to jack up the jobless rate?
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
