</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-VIOLENCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL SHOOTINGS PROMPT A LOOK AT STATISTICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We had barely gotten over the carnage in Jonesboro, Ark., when a
young gunman sprayed a high school cafeteria with a barrage of
bullets in Springfield, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   When he was done, 24 students had been hit. Two died. Police
have accused 15-year-old Kipland Kinkel of killing those students,
and his parents, who were shot earlier.
</P>
<P>
   And so the speculation begins anew. What is this world coming
to? Why are kids so violent? And why aren't we doing a better job
of socializing them?
</P>
<P>
   But despite what appears to be a wide and growing tide of
violent juvenile crime, statistics show declines at the local,
state and national levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are horrible events that shock us, and should shock
us,'' said Alfred Blumstein, professor of operations research and
public policy at John Heinz School of Public Policy and Management
at Carnegie Mellon University. ``But a few incidences a year,
however distressing, are still short of a tide.''
</P>
<P>
   A study released in January by the Texas Criminal Justice Policy
Council bears that out, showing a significant drop in violent
juvenile crime.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, violent and weapons offenses by Texas juveniles dropped
12 percent, despite a 1.4 percent rise in the juvenile population.
</P>
<P>
   And in May, the Department of Public Safety reported a 2.4
percent drop in juvenile arrests statewide last year, the first
decrease since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Violent offenses such as homicides, aggravated robbery and
sexual assaults have been declining in Tarrant County for the past
several years, said Carey Cockerell, director of Tarrant County
Juvenile Services.
</P>
<P>
   Cockerell attributed the local decline to better community
programming, such as the Tarrant County Advocate Program, YMCA,
Boys and Girls Clubs, community policing and efforts that ``put
resources with kids and their families in their neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   If children are more violent, he said, it is because ``we
haven't provided the right skills for kids to deal with conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm convinced that a lot of adolescents do not have
appropriate role models who care about them enough to set limits,''
he added.
</P>
<P>
   Cockerell and others blame the media for the growing negative
perception of juveniles and say that media coverage might encourage
juveniles to commit crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What never gets conveyed is, we're still talking about a very
small minority of kids that commit the most heinous crime,'' said
Judy Briscoe, chief of staff at the Texas Youth Commission.
</P>
<P>
   At least one major newspaper _ the ``Chicago Sun-Times'' _
agrees that teen-agers are influenced by the news they see and
read, and accordingly opted to change the way it covered the
Springfield shooting. Instead of running the story on the front
page, Editor in Chief Nigel Wade decided to play it on Pages 2 and
3. On the front was a message to readers explaining the newspaper's
``concern that more prominent coverage might harm or frighten
vulnerable children.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some children see only the front page of a newspaper, in a
box, on the street, on the porch or over the breakfast table,''
Wade said in a ``New York Times'' column. ``I did not want to take
the risk that another front-page story about another school
shooting might cause some unbalanced 15-year-old to add one more
disaster to the recent series.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, Briscoe says, children do seem more violent
than they were 20 years ago. But so are adults, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1973, when I got into this business, the predominant
offense for which kids were committed was stealing and then
disobedience (running away,)'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, 35 percent of our kids are committed for violent
offenses, but children aren't doing anything adults aren't doing.
Our youth violence is a microcosm of what's going on in society.''
</P>
<P>
   Blumstein, however, is not convinced that youths are more
violent. They just have more access to lethal weaponry, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the access to the weaponry that results in the tragic
consequences, because youth have always fought with each other,''
he said. ``But when it's a battle with fists, the dynamics run much
more slowly. With a gun it evolves very rapidly, too fast for a
third party to intervene. That also raises the stakes and
encourages others to arm themselves, thereby triggering a
pre-emptive strike: `I better get him before he gets me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Although schools have been the focal point of much of the
tragedy, a survey of major North Texas school districts shows that
few weapons were confiscated from students this past year.
Arlington had the highest number, with five. Fort Worth officials
confiscated four, and none was found in the Hurst-Euless-Bedford
district.
</P>
<P>
   Cecelia Speer, director of student affairs, said the Fort Worth
school district has seen a dramatic drop in the number of guns
confiscated. The district has gone from a high of 69 guns in
1991-92, to 39 guns in 1992-93, to 24 in 1993-94, and down into the
single digits. The number crept back up to 10 during 1996-97, but
dropped again this year to four (one of which was confiscated from
a nonstudent).
</P>
<P>
   What is most shocking is the number and power of the guns
students have been using in their crimes, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Jonesboro shooting, investigators found 22 spent shell
casings in the copse of trees from where the suspects _ a
13-year-old boy and an 11-year-old boy _ are believed to have shot
at their schoolmates. Five casings were from a .30-06 rifle.
Fifteen were from a .30-caliber rifle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that I find astonishing is not that a 13-year-old
kid is angry at his girlfriend,'' said Blumstein, ``but that he has
access to the arsenal that he is reported to have had.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would favor some type of punishment _ civil or
criminal _ for people who give children access to guns, just
bartenders are liable for letting someone become drunk if that
person commits vehicular homicide.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
