<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TICKET SALES SAG FOR THE HOLYFIELD-AKINWANDE BOUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (dc) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If Evander Holyfield chops down the 6-foot-7-inch
Henry Akinwande on Saturday night at Madison Square Garden and
there is no one around to hear it, will it make a sound?
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield doesn't care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has this thing that they like to feel like they're a
draw,'' Holyfield said. ``I'd love to see the place packed. That
inspires me. But if it's just me, Henry and the referee, that would
be OK. I just want to know that I'm better.''
</P>
<P>
   Ticket sales have been sagging for the heavyweight championship
bout, the first at Madison Square Garden since Riddick Bowe fought
Michael Dokes in 1993. The reasons are as varied as ticket prices
(from $1,000 for ringside to $100 for the least expensive seat),
another major sporting event in the area on the same day (the
Belmont Stakes) and the spring weather that invites outdoor
activities. As of Wednesday afternoon, just over 7,000 tickets had
been sold for the fight, which will be broadcast live on
pay-per-view by Showtime Event Television ($39.95).
</P>
<P>
   The promoter Don King set the ticket prices, which are expensive
even by New York standards. By comparison, tickets are priced
between $350 (ringside) and $30 for Oscar De La Hoya's WBC
welterweight title defense against Patrick Charpentier at the Sun
Bowl in El Paso on June 13, a bout for which more than 50,000
tickets have been sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening in New York is a disservice to Evander
Holyfield,'' said Bob Arum of Top Rank Boxing, De La Hoya's
promoter and a rival of King. ``He's a great champion. But the
price of the tickets means that even though people would like to
see Holyfield fight, they can't afford it. It's ludicrous.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for flagging sales might be that true boxing fans
view the bout between Holyfield and Akinwande as a stinker.
Akinwande, who was disqualified for excessive clutching in his last
title fight, against Lennox Lewis, is suspect as a quality
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket sales have never been a question for Holyfield because in
the last 10 years he has fought only twice outside a
casino-sponsored venue in Las Vegas, Lake Tahoe and Atlantic City.
He fought Bert Cooper at the Omni in Atlanta on Nov. 23, 1991, and
he fought Bobby Czyz at Madison Square Garden on May 10, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield and his lawyer, Jim Thomas, say they don't believe
they're involved in a bad show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think you are discounting how good a fight this could
be,'' Thomas said. ``You've got a guy who is big and skilled.
Evander brings out the best in his opponents. I think you'll see
the best Akinwande you've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has kind of shamed the guy by telling him he doesn't
deserve the fight,'' Holyfield said of Akinwande. ``The man has
been listening to that for eight weeks. This guy is coming here
with something to prove to himself and everybody who says he
doesn't have a chance. You know he's going to work hard and be at
his very best. He feels like he doesn't have anything to lose. He's
going to try to prove a point to the whole world that he's worthy
even if he doesn't win the fight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an interesting fight from a pay-per-view standpoint,''
said R. Thomas Umstead of Multi-Channel News, a weekly trade
publication that follows the pay-per-view industry. ``You know
Akinwande doesn't bring anything to the table, because he has no
name recognition. You don't know what Holyfield brings to the
table. He hasn't fought in a while, so there will be interest to
see him fight. I think it's going to do anywhere between 300,000
and 500,000 buys. It's going to do less than Holyfield-Moorer.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield's last bout, against Michael Moorer, did 550,000 buys.
</P>
<P>
   Although Holyfield has been involved in four of the top five
boxing pay-per-view shows (two with Tyson and one with George
Foreman), he is not in the same class as Tyson when it comes to
attracting an audience. Tyson has been involved in 7 of the top 10
boxing pay-per-view shows.
</P>
<P>
   But Holyfield discounts the fact that Tyson has a certain
mystique that makes him an attractive draw.
</P>
<P>
   Said Holyfield: ``A man comes out of jail and the whole world
watches him come out. `Oh, he's dangerous!' People came to see if
he's going to hurt the guy. People are into the hurt business to
the point where if you say we're going to kill a chicken and we're
going to cut his head off, people are going to come out and see
somebody kill the chicken.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as the crowd at the Garden is concerned, Holyfield
believes that the die-hard boxing fans are going to show up, if for
no other reason than to see him lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come out and say, `Well, he's a nice guy, but I've got
to see him get whupped,''' he said. ``They like to see how I
respond if I get whupped good. They'll be waiting a long time for
that. I've already took all my whuppings from my mom.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
