r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-TRAILS-LADN     06-03 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-TRAILS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC INVITED TO HELP CLEAN AREA TRAILS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The saw and pickax. The scythe and Pulaski. As
many varieties of hoes, shears and shovels as are forged.
</P>
<P>
   These are the tools that scratched out the countless miles of
pathways crisscrossing the nation. The same tools are depended upon
to maintain those trails that are beaten by more than 47 million
Americans who hike at least once a year.
</P>
<P>
   But tools alone don't make a trail. It takes a strong back and
steely will. The American Hiking Society is looking for both
Saturday during its sixth annual National Trails Day, an event
organizers expect will draw at least one million people to more
than 3,200 trail-work and celebratory activities planned across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to let people know that they have ownership of their
local trails and to take pride in them,'' said Gwyn Fletcher Hicks,
spokeswoman for the Silver Spring, Md.-based American Hiking
Society, founded in 1976 to establish, maintain and protect
trekkers' corridors. ``National Trails Day was created to promote
trails and public appreciation for them, and this is our way of
getting people to take the next step and get them involved in trail
initiatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Initiatives that would free up funding to help ensure that
trails are not engulfed by development or left so idle that
disrepair makes them obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about awareness of the fragility of trails _ the fact
that they don't maintain themselves and are encroachable,'' said
Bob Ballou, executive director of the Pacific Crest Trail
Association. ``When you take away trails, you take away
recreational opportunities, you take away wildlife and open space,
and you contribute to the uglification of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to build a constituency for trails and have that
constituency make its feelings known to Congress (and state
governments).''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of local events on the National Trails Day
registry slated for Saturday. Volunteers are asked to wear long
pants and layered clothing and bring work gloves, their own lunch,
at least two quarts of water, a hat, sunglasses, sunscreen and bug
repellent. Tools are provided, though attendees are welcome to
bring their own. No previous trail-work experience is required.
</P>
<P>
   Backbone Trail: The project will restore a section of the
pathway in Malibu's Upper Solstice Canyon damaged by El Nino-fueled
storms.
</P>
<P>
   Take Pacific Coast Highway (1) to Corral Canyon Road (3.75 miles
east of Kanan-Dume Road and 2.35 miles west off Malibu Canyon
Road). Drive north 5.5 miles to its terminus and park. Parking
spaces are limited and carpooling is recommended.
</P>
<P>
   The event runs from 8:30 a.m. to 3 p.m. To participate,
volunteers must be at the parking lot by 8:30. However, they are
welcome to leave at any time. About 140 people are expected.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (818) 222-4531, (805) 370-2301 or (310) 473-4574,
ext. 3011.
</P>
<P>
   Vasquez Rocks County Park: The day will feature maintenance
along the Pacific Crest Trail through the Agua Dulce parkland and a
celebration marking the renewal of official Pacific Crest Trail
Association partnerships with the Bureau of Land Management, U.S.
Forest Service and National Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   The trail work takes place from 7:30 a.m. to 2 p.m. No parking
fee will be charged for volunteers; all others must pay the
customary $3 charge. Take the Golden State Freeway (5) north to the
Antelope Valley Freeway (14) east, exit at Escondido Canyon Road
and turn left. Turn left again at Agua Dulce Canyon Road.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the day's activities are designed for PCTA members, but
the public is welcomed to most, including the following:
</P>
<P>
   _A day hike and a fund-raising ``poker hike run'' through the
Sierra Pelona section of the Angeles National Forest, 9 a.m. to
noon. Meet at the Mint Canyon Road Trailhead, intersection of Agua
Dulce Canyon Road and Sierra Highway.
</P>
<P>
   _Two one-hour guided nature hikes through Vasquez Rocks County
Park, 9 to 11 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   _Education and speaker's program, noon to 3 p.m., Agua Dulce
Women's Club, 33201 Agua Dulce Canyon Road.
</P>
<P>
   _Public remarks, recognition and press conference, 3 to 4 p.m.,
Agua Dulce Women's Club.
</P>
<P>
   _Barbecue dinner, 5 to 6:30 p.m., Central Agua Dulce. Cost: $4
adults, $2 children; beverages $1.
</P>
<P>
   _Cowboy campfire, 7 to 10 p.m., Vasquez Rocks County Park.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers expect about 250 participants. Parking will be
limited, so plan on carpooling. Information: (888) 728-7245.
</P>
<P>
   TRAILS TRIVIA
</P>
<P>
   Facts and figures from National Trails Day '97:
</P>
<P>
   Number of events: 3,200.
</P>
<P>
   Participants: More than 1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Miles hiked, ridden or run: 18,000.
</P>
<P>
   Trail miles maintained: 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   New trail miles dedicated, opened or built: 2,500.
</P>
<P>
   Source: American Hiking Society.
</P>
</TEXT>
