<HEADLINE>
FISH FREE AND GET HOOKED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As altruistic as Free Fishing Day might sound, the
Department of Fish and Game has ulterior motives behind its
biannual event.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, while fishing licenses are required for anglers 16 and
older 363 days a year, none is needed Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   And, sure, no charge is asked at various fishing events slated
around the state to enlighten novices and first-timers.
</P>
<P>
   But you just know there's a ... hook.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who enjoy the experience are more likely to become
licensed anglers or supporters of Fish and Game programs,'' said
Jack Edwards, a DFG spokesman at the state office in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the rub, and surprisingly revealing. Using a comp day on the
water as the carrot, tyros are lured into the department's web,
compelled to buy a license to satisfy their newfound lust for
another outing, and another and another.
</P>
<P>
   Simply ingenious, for the plan benefits everyone. The funds are
employed to plant more fish, increase the number of available
loaner rods and reels and develop additional free fishing clinics
to teach anglers the finer points of fish biology, tackle,
technique, safety, ethics and fish handling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives the public recreational opportunities that they might
not have otherwise,'' Edwards said. ``And it's a great way to spend
time with your kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Bravo, DFG, bravo. Your scheme is sound and sincere.
</P>
<P>
   Free Fishing Day is scheduled the first Saturday in June and the
last Saturday of September to correspond to National Fishing Week
and National Hunting and Fishing Day, respectively. The DFG program
started in 1991 on the approval of the State Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Free Fishing Day participants never buy a license or
fish again, the knowledge they gain in a single morning or
afternoon can go to a greater benefit. A learning experience for
greenhorns, a chance to share their wisdom for graybeards, a
confidence boost for all involved. And Mother Nature gets some of
the trickle-down.
</P>
<P>
   ``People increase their knowledge of the aquatic habitat and
become more interested in caring for the environment, building
stewardship,'' said Jackie Kourassis, coordinator of the DFG's
Fishing in the City program for Los Angeles and Orange counties.
</P>
<P>
   So try your luck Saturday at any of a number of bodies of water.
</P>
<P>
   Four area urban lakes will be stocked with catfish for the
event:
</P>
<P>
   _Peck Road Park, 5401 N. Peck Road, Arcadia; (626) 334-1065.
</P>
<P>
   _Santa Fe Dam, 15501 E. Arrow Highway, Irwindale; same phone as
above.
</P>
<P>
   _Puddingstone Lake, 120 E. Via Verde, San Dimas; (909) 599-2667
or (909) 599-8411.
</P>
<P>
   _Downey Wilderness Park, 10999 Little Lake Road, Downey; (562)
904-7131.
</P>
<P>
   The DFG is planning one free local event, at Santa Fe Dam. It
will include fly-tying and fly-casting instruction and five
learning stations operated by volunteers. Some loaner rods and
reels will be available; ID is required. For more information, call
the facility or the DFG at (562) 590-4835 or (562) 590-4824.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous creeks, rivers and reservoirs are regularly stocked
with trout and/or catfish, including these in Los Angeles and
Ventura counties: Big Tujunga Creek, Bouquet Canyon Creek, Casitas
Lake, Castaic Lake and Lagoon, Elizabeth Lake, Little Rock Creek
and Reservoir, Matilija Creek, Piru Creek and Lake, Rancho Simi
Park Lake, Reyes Creek, San Gabriel River (all forks) and Rose
Valley Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   See the Fishing Report on page 11, call the DFG's 24-hour Fish
Stocking Information at (562) 590-5020 or visit the department's
Web site at http://www.dfg.ca.gov to determine which were to be
stocked this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
