<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-DEMONSTRATE-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS DEMAND HABIBIE'S RESIGNATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Singing, chanting, blowing kisses, waving
flags, Jakarta's students were out in force again on Wednesday in
motorcades of buses and cars that wove through the city demanding,
in the happiest manner possible, the downfall of the government.
</P>
<P>
   Bursting with the energy of youth, flush with their recent
victory in helping to oust President Suharto, the students seemed
to have become an unstoppable force, maintaining momentum for
democratic change.
</P>
<P>
   They rejected the slow, deliberate constitutional procedures
outlined on Tuesday by President B.J. Habibie, who said in an
interview that he could not transfer power to a new leader before
the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Habibie must go!'' they shouted. ``Reform now!''
</P>
<P>
   And many of their elders seemed to agree. A number of opposition
figures whom Habibie is consulting _ notably the pro-democracy
leader Amien Rais _ are demanding new elections this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look happy but inside we are sad,'' said Hermanjosef, a
24-year-old student studying psychology. ``We are sad about the
government. It is not the same as our inner voice.''
</P>
<P>
   The military turned out in force along the students' route,
blocking key intersections with cordons of soldiers armed with
metal staffs and automatic weapons. Though they exchanged smiles
and thumbs-up signals with the students, the soldiers were a
reminder that demonstrations can turn violent and deadly.
</P>
<P>
   In another reminder, the country's leading human rights group
said Wednesday that at least 1,188 people had died in Jakarta in
the riots that swept the city from May 12 to May 15 after at least
four students were shot dead in a demonstration on the campus of
Trisakti University. This death toll is more than double the
initial estimate by the military.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, the toll is believed to be much higher. Devastating
riots broke out in many cities as weeks of mostly peaceful student
demonstrations were suddenly transformed into a chaos of rioting
and looting.
</P>
<P>
   The rights report did not say how the deaths occurred, but
evidence in Jakarta suggests that the overwhelming majority of the
victims were looters trapped in stores that were set on fire by
rioters who drove around the city hurling gasoline bombs.
</P>
<P>
   In one hospital in Jakarta where nearly 200 bodies were
collected, all but a handful had burned to death. A small number
had been shot or stabbed by unknown assailants.
</P>
<P>
   An uncounted number of those burned to death were also ethnic
Chinese trapped inside shops or homes that were attacked by rioters
in a familiar pattern here in this overwhelmingly Muslim and ethnic
Malay nation. ``One of the targets of the unrest was the ethnic
Chinese group, which in reality is an inseparable part of the
Indonesian society,'' the rights group said.
</P>
<P>
   The group, the National Commission on Human Rights, blamed the
armed forces for failing to contain the damage and death.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``When the unrest took place, there was no visible evidence of
serious efforts from the security forces to prevent it,'' the
report said. ``The security forces did not adequately anticipate
the strong possibility that the unrest could have broken out.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the deaths, the report tallied an extraordinary
swath of devastation in the capital, saying 40 large shopping
centers, 4,083 shops, 1,026 private homes, 383 offices and 1,119
automobiles had been attacked, burned or looted.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing many accounts, the commission said unidentified
``organized groups'' had been involved in some of the burning and
vandalism. Witnesses reported seeing men in trucks or on
motorcycles traveling through the city identifying Chinese-owned
homes and businesses or handing out gasoline bombs.
</P>
<P>
   The city is filled with theories about these groups, and it
remains unclear whether they involved thugs, representatives of
radical organizations or provocateurs from some branch of the
security forces.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, which is financed by the government but has
earned a reputation for independence, called on Habibie to
``thoroughly investigate'' the security forces for ``not preventing
or immediately dealing with the riots.''
</P>
<P>
   The military said on Wednesday that 10 low-ranking officers
would go on trial on Saturday in the shooting deaths of the
university students, the incident that led to the rioting.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were 10 people who did the shooting without orders,''
Chief of Military Police Maj. Gen. Syamsu said in a report on
Wednesday in the Indonesian Observer, a newspaper. ``They were
soldiers and noncommissioned officers.''
</P>
<P>
   His exoneration of higher officials was greeted with skepticism
by students. The newspaper reported that some students at Trisakti
University said they had received threats and had been told not to
come forward with information about the deaths. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
