<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH-PIOLINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIOLINE CRASHES AN ALL-SPANISH FINAL FOUR
</HEADLINE>
  (With TEN-FRENCH-OPEN)  
(ja) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Cedric Pioline was commanding full attention on the
wind-whipped center court at Roland Garros today, working a big wad
of gum and pretending to be pluckier than he felt. He was one game
from winning a five-set epic with the acrobatic Hicham Arazi, one
game from reaching his first French Open semifinal after a decade
of disappointment at his hometown Grand Slam tournament.
</P>
<P>
   As the Moroccan Arazi, in deep trouble at 2-5 in the final set,
scuffed toward the baseline to try to stave off disaster with his
serve, Pioline's frenzied fans began a vehement version of the
wave. Around and around the jammed stadium it went, picking up
momentum with each revolution until, by the fourth go-round, it had
turned into a tidal wave. At the behest of the chair umpire, the
wave faded away. But the 24-year-old Arazi did not: he held his
ground with an annoying ace, forcing Pioline to serve out the match
and earn his accolades honestly.
</P>
<P>
   Pioline, who turns 29 on June 15, seemed close to collapse. But
he delivered a desperate seat-of-the-pants volley at 0-15 while
tumbling to the clay, saved a break point with a bullish backhand
approach and converted his first match point for a 3-6, 6-2, 7-6
(8-6), 4-6, 6-3 victory when Arazi fluffed a forehand long.
</P>
<P>
   Chic or not, the place went ballistic. Even the typically stoic
Roland Garros groundskeepers could not refrain from clapping as
they hustled to prepare the net for a doubles match.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'm going to jump into the Seine River, commit
suicide,'' Arazi said after converting only 4 of the 21 break
chances Pioline gave him. ``If I compare myself with Cedric, he
looked very tired, but he was much more aggressive than I was,
really moved up to the net and made quite a few volleys. Instead of
running to the net only to shake his hand at the end, I should have
been more to the net before that.''
</P>
<P>
   The valiant performance by the 17th-ranked Pioline earned him a
semifinal match against 14th-seeded Alex Corretja of Spain, who
advanced with relative ease by trouncing Filip Dewulf of Belgium,
7-5, 6-4, 6-3. Pioline, the only Frenchman to reach the finals of
two different Grand Slam tournaments in the open era _ the 1993
U.S. Open and last year's Wimbledon _ is the only non-Spaniard, and
the only unseeded player, to reach the semifinals here this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is history in our tennis, but I hope the people
in Spain don't believe this is really easy,'' said Corretja, who
joined 12th-seeded Carlos Moya and 15th-seeded Felix Mantilla in
the semifinals. ``We've been practicing on clay through our life,
and now is the moment to forget about the small tournaments and go
for the big one, as we did here.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time three Spaniards have reached the
semifinals of a Grand Slam event. Four times in Grand Slam history,
representatives of a single nation have filled the semifinals, most
recently at the Australian Open in 1995, when an all-American crew
of Pete Sampras, Andre Agassi, Michael Chang and Aaron Krickstein
reached the final four.
</P>
<P>
   Pioline crashed this final four by refusing to cave in during
his 3-hour-43-minute quarterfinal. He saved a set point against him
in the third set with a second-service ace that helped force a tie
breaker, in which he saved another set point with a high backhand
volley that pulled Arazi off the court and produced a forehand
error. Once Pioline broke Arazi for a 4-2 lead in the fifth set, by
outlasting him in a junkball rally in which the impatient Arazi
netted a backhand at break point, he scraped his way through for
the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I could have gone on,'' said Pioline, who
needed nearly two hours of restorative treatment, including
intravenous rehydration, after the ordeal. It was his third
five-setter of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MATCH POINTS  &LR;  The only American left in the junior boys'
competition, 17-year-old Taylor Dent, reached the quarterfinals
Wednesday with a 6-4, 7-6 (7-2) defeat of Guillermo Coria of
Argentina. . . . The Grand Slam committee announced that the French
Open's 1997 champion, Gustavo Kuerten, who lost in the second round
in singles and was disqualified from his doubles quarterfinal
Tuesday night for hurling his racquet at the umpire Bruno Rebeuh,
will be fined just $7,000 rather than his approximately $40,000 in
winnings. The devastated Kuerten, who will also lose the 22 ranking
points he earned here, said he deeply regretted the incident and
hoped it would make him become ``a more mature person.''
</P>
</TEXT>
