<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUILDING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nostalgia _ but with gadgets _ next trend in home building
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Cozy but high-tech Tudor houses on tree-lined streets
could replace multi-gabled suburban mini-mansions with two-story
foyers and Palladian windows as America's next dream homes.
</P>
<P>
   That's what some 5,000 architects and designers will be told as
they gather today through Saturday for the fifth annual Southern
Building Show. A longing for simpler days, a changing family and a
computer in every home will be among themes discussed at the event,
held at the Cobb Galleria Centre.
</P>
<P>
   The show is not open to the public. It showcases new products,
the latest software and forward-looking design trends for members
of the building trades.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Reimer, president of Omaha, Neb.-based Design Basics,
thinks people are looking for ways to recapture memories of
friendly, grandmotherly houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``People live in the suburbs, but they are starting to want the
feeling of a smaller community, one with lampposts, where you can
walk at night,'' said Reimer.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want places to sit and visit _ like porches. And inside
of the house, they want very flexible room spaces _ a dining room
now but a library after the kids leave home.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with Boca Raton, Fla., architect Quincy Johnson, Reimer
will talk today about other features she believes will sell in the
cutting-edge housing market:
</P>
<P>
   Airy, light rooms are no longer limited to Florida but are
showing up all over.
</P>
<P>
   Bigger bathrooms and wider doors for walkers or wheelchairs for
a time when the owners grow older or their parents move in.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of storage space in the garage.
</P>
<P>
   Computer niches, where users can sit for a few minutes at a
time, replacing ``computer rooms'' or computer set-ups in family
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   New products will include vinyl flooring that looks like wood,
ceramic or stone; windowpane films that block ultraviolet rays and
diminish nighttime reflections; and maintenance-free exteriors with
siding and fencing that needs no painting. Baby boomers have
neither the time nor the inclination to toil over maintenance, said
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the largest group of home buyers in the free world,''
he said. ``Even though it is a diverse group ranging in age from 34
to 52, it is interested in lifestyle. The first-move-ups continue
to be status seekers, wanting the most impressive houses their
money can buy . . . but others are developing a
been-there-done-that attitude about big houses with big yards.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
