u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAPORTA-COLUMN04-COX     06-03 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAPORTA-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woodruff Arts corporate support is second only to Lincoln Center
 &HT;    By Maria Saporta
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The Woodruff Arts Center's annual corporate campaign
has passed the $6 million mark for the first time in its history.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Franklin, chairman of the campaign and president of
Georgia Power Co., will announce the campaign's success at a
reception today hosted by Gov. Zell Miller and his wife, Shirley.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign surpassed the $5.9 million goal. The corporate
campaign now is the second largest corporate arts fund in the
nation behind New York's Lincoln Center. The fund benefits the
Woodruff Arts Center and its four divisions _ the Alliance Theatre
Co., the Atlanta College of Art, the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra and
the High Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the campaign raised $5.7 million, a $500,000 increase
over the year before.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things we wondered about after last year's dramatic
increase was whether it could be sustained this year,'' Franklin
said. ``Happily, we were able to sustain it and bump it up another
notch.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest donors were: Georgia Power ($100,000); Community
Foundation for Greater Atlanta ($100,000); Cook Family Foundation
($100,000); Primerica Financial Services ($100,000); United Parcel
Service ($50,000); Crawford &AMP; Co. ($30,000); and the Katherine and
John Murphy Foundation ($25,000).
</P>
<P>
   Franklin attributed part of the growth to the addition of 15 new
members to the Patron Circle of Stars, companies that give $10,000
or more: General Electric Power Systems ($25,000); ING North
America Insurance ($25,000); Premiere Technologies ($25,000); and
Miller Industries ($15,000).
</P>
<P>
   Next year, the campaign will be led by James R. Lientz Jr.,
president of NationsBank-Georgia, followed by Roger Kintzel,
publisher of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Despite strong corporate response to the Woodruff Arts Center
campaign, arts leaders recently have grumbled it does not receive
enough support from the Atlanta community.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly see the business community taking a leadership
role,'' said Shelton G. Stanfill, president of the Woodruff Arts
Center, ``where Atlanta is lacking is in individual giving. Not to
take anything away from the individuals who are giving, overall, it
would not begin to match what people are giving in Washington, San
Francisco, Denver, New York, Minneapolis and Chicago. Corporations
give more here than in most other cities I just named.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Woodruff Arts Center board held its annual
meeting Wednesday afternoon. John W. Spiegel, CFO of SunTrust Bank,
is chairman of the board, succeeding G. Joseph Prendergast,
chairman of Wachovia-Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Newly named to the Woodruff Arts Center board was M. Douglas
Ivester, chairman and CEO of Coca-Cola Co.
</P>
<P>
   Women's Fund strong
</P>
<P>
   Come July 1, the Atlanta Women's Fund will become a stand-alone
foundation _ emerging from under the umbrella of the Community
Foundation for Greater Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we have achieved our womanhood and maturity as an
organization,'' said Stephanie Davis, executive director of the
Atlanta Women's Fund, which will become the Atlanta Women's
Foundation.``We are practicing what we preach for women and girls,
which is autonomy, independence and self-sufficiency.''
</P>
<P>
   For 12 years, the women's fund has been part of the Community
Foundation, where it has been able to give more than $1.2 million
for organizations dealing with the homeless, domestic violence and
other needs of women. It also has built up $1.1 million in endowed
funds, which will continue to be managed by the Community
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are really enthusiastic about this,'' said Alicia Philipp,
executive director of the Community Foundation, whose board
approved the change Wednesday. ``We see our foundation as a
nurturer of goals.''
</P>
<P>
   The two organizations also were taking diverging paths. The
Community Foundation attracts significant givers for its endowment
funds, and then it makes donations based on the proceeds of its
endowment. The Atlanta Women's Fund has become known for its
widely-attended receptions hosted by its partners (such as Women in
Finance, Women in Law and Medicine, Women in Media and Commercial
Real Estate Women). Those funds are doled out to organizations
supporting women and girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are considered one of the fastest-growing women's funds in
the country,'' Davis said. ``We now have 3,000 donors. Numerically,
that is more than the Community Foundation. But financially, it's
nowhere close.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation will relocate to its own offices on the same
floor of the Hurt Building as the Community Foundation. It also
will have its own governing board, largely made up of members from
its existing advisory board.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth T. West, advisory board chair and partner at King &AMP;
Spalding, also was excited about the change, saying, ``We want to
show the power of women in a way that's very imaginative, very
aggressive and fully on our own.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: msaporta(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
