 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   The gains of Spain &QL; 
are plain in Paris
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PARIS _ The, uh, Spanish Open?
</P>
<P>
   France's Cedric Pioline finds himself surrounded on his own
turf. The heroic homeboy, he of the daily five-set Houdini gig, has
the Roland Garros garrison overwhelmingly in his corner, but in
truth, it's he who has been cornered at the French Open.
</P>
<P>
   They're everywhere, the Spaniards. Basques. Andalusians.
Catalans. Tall ones. Short ones. Drop-dead gorgeous ones. Long
hair. Short hair. Weird hair. They constitute a late-20th-century
Armada, a swarm of baseline-hugging dirt-ball maestros who swarmed
through the Pyrenees to settle their internecine differences on
French soil, the burnt-amber terre battue.
</P>
<P>
   The reign of Spain looks pretty sunny. The Americans had their
day, as did the Germans, the Swedes and, of course, the
once-dynastic Australians. But of late, tennis has begun to acquire
an Iberian tilt, certainly on red clay.
</P>
<P>
   The ATP season began with 16 Spaniards ranked among the top 100,
six more than the American contingent, which was hanging in second,
one ahead of Germany. The Roland Garros semifinals, however, will
habla espaol, save for Cedric.
</P>
<P>
   Six of Spain's hombres reached the final 16, half of whom
advanced to the quarters, each of whom then stormed
unapologetically into the semis.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Corretja would be the latest, whipping Belgian upstart
Filip Dewulf on Wednesday. Carlos Moya and Felix Mantilla had
already achieved the penultimate round the previous afternoon, the
former knocking out the favorite to win the tournament, Marcelo
Rios.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone surprised
</P>
<P>
   Also, old-timer Arantxa Sanchez Vicario continues to pursue a
third women's title. She's a likely finalist _ sorry, Lindsay
Davenport _ meaning Spain could be front and center on Court
Central for the whole weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Corretja, having almost flawlessly disposed of the Dewulf in
sheep's clothing, was asked if he has been surprised by the
dominance of his cadre of compadres.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am only surprised,'' he replied, ``that we aren't four in
the semifinals.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a sore leg muscle might have prevented Alberto
Berasategui from beating Pioline's worthy Wednesday foil, Hicham
Arazi, in the round of 16. Berasategui, no stranger to success on
the terre battue, had himself been a finalist in 1994, losing to _
naturally _ another Spaniard, Sergi Bruguera.
</P>
<P>
   Bruguera was the point man, the fellow who announced the
gathering Spanish invasion to the world by conquering Paris
back-to-back in 1993-94. Now, Sergi's just another among many faces
in the Spanish crowd, and a lesser light at that.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish are so omnipresent that one of them, rising star
Julian Alonso, has even discreetly become Martina Hingis' secret
amor. Not bad for a country that could fit into Arizona with little
spillover.
</P>
<P>
   You probably wonder what's going on here. There have been a
smattering of Spanish champions through the years, most notably the
two Manuels _ Santana and Orantes. But they have never arrived in
waves like this.
</P>
<P>
   Close-knit countrymen
</P>
<P>
   The secret of their toasting France is a no-quarter work ethic
and a mutual support structure that lets them draw strength from
each other. These guys are friends in every sense of the word.
</P>
<P>
   ``On court, we are fighting hard,'' explains Moya, who reached
the Australian Open final last year and appears to be the best of
his class by a slim margin. ``But off the court, we are doing
everything to help each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Same as Connors and McEnroe used to, right?
</P>
<P>
   If any of the trio wins Sunday _ you tend to like the odds _ the
two who don't will nonetheless feel better about themselves.
They're a team, a concept foreign to tennis since the Aussies'
Golden Age, although the Edberg-era Swedes briefly had a similar
chemistry, if not the same camaraderie.
</P>
<P>
   From widely disparate backgrounds and locales, the Spaniards
have gravitated to Barcelona, where they live, train and party
together.
</P>
<P>
   Corretja, heretofore most famous for losing a memorable five-set
U.S. Open quarterfinal to an upchucking Pete Sampras, has been as
high as No. 4 in the world. Moya rose to fifth in the rankings in
1997 and established himself as an international heartthrob.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Corretja nor Moya, however, is currently in the top 10 _
nor is the yellow-haired Mantilla _ and they won't receive their
full due until they accomplish elsewhere what they have done en
masse at Roland Garros.
</P>
<P>
   Wimbledon's lawns remain a particularly treacherous adversary
for the Spaniards, treating them no more hospitably than the
British navy did the original Armada.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need somebody who can play well just once on grass,''
Corretja says. ``Then, the others will think they can as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Caramba! Today Paris, tomorrow todo el mundo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
</TEXT>
