<HEADLINE>
LETTUCE NOW CONSIDER THE RICHES OF THE FIELDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tired of biting into mushy tomatoes or rock-hard cantaloupe?
Here are a few hints on choosing the best fresh fruits and
vegetables. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WATERMELON
</P>
<P>
   In the store: I hate to break it to you, but thunking, floating
or balancing a watermelon is useless. Instead, look for an attached
stem that is discolored and shrunken; that's a good sign. If the
stem has fallen off, the watermelon is over the hill and will be
mushy and dark red. The melon should be heavy for its size. The
underside should be pale or creamy yellow, and the rind should have
a healthy sheen.
</P>
<P>
   At home: Store watermelon in a cool place (but not the
refrigerator), away from sunlight. Depending on the temperature,
and the condition of the melon, it can keep for a week. Cut melon
should be wrapped tightly in plastic wrap and refrigerated. It
should last a day or two in the refrigerator, but the texture can
become mushy.
</P>
<P>
   CORN-ON-THE-COB
</P>
<P>
   In the store: Choose fresh-looking ears with tight, green husks
and a sweet smell. The kernels should be plump and juicy and packed
closely on the husk. Color of kernels varies by variety, from white
to buttercream to crocus-hued. Big, tough kernels can indicate
over-the-hill corn that will be more starch than sugar.
</P>
<P>
   At home: Cook as soon as possible. (There's an old adage that
you should start boiling the water as you head out the door to pick
the corn.) If dinner isn't imminent, store in refrigerator. Don't
store corn longer than two days.
</P>
<P>
   CANTALOUPE
</P>
<P>
   In the store: Select melons that are slightly oval with a golden
background under the netting. Sniff the stem end to find melons
with a distinct aroma, and look for tiny cracks at the stem end:
Both indicate ripeness.
</P>
<P>
   At home: Store melons at room temperature. A cantaloupe should
last a couple of days on the counter. If you want the fruit
chilled, place in refrigerator shortly before serving.
</P>
<P>
   OKRA
</P>
<P>
   In the store: Look for bright green pods that are 2 to 4 inches
long. Larger pods can be tough. The pods should snap easily.
</P>
<P>
   At home: Refrigerate in a brown paper bag or in a plastic bag
lined with paper towels. Don't store longer than two days.
</P>
<P>
   PEACHES
</P>
<P>
   In the store: Don't pinch the peaches. Instead, let the
background color of the fruit be the key. It should be
cream-colored or yellow. Unripe peaches will ripen at room
temperature; they won't get sweeter, but they will get juicier.
Don't buy peaches that have a green undercast; they won't ripen.
</P>
<P>
   At home: Refrigerate fully ripe peaches, but only for one or two
days. Otherwise, leave them on a counter.
</P>
<P>
   TOMATOES
</P>
<P>
   In the store: Looks can be deceiving when it comes to tomatoes.
Although winter tomatoes look nicely shaped, smooth and firm, they
have no flavor. Instead, choose tomatoes that are heavy for their
size and still have stems attached (they'll stay fresher longer).
And smell _ a good tomato smells like a tomato. Greenish tomatoes
will turn red eventually, but the redder the farm-stand tomato, the
more ready it is to eat.
</P>
<P>
   At home: Keep tomatoes out of the refrigerator. Instead, store
on a counter top away from heat and moisture. Some tomatoes will
keep for a day, some for a week.
</P>
<P>
   GREEN BEANS
</P>
<P>
   In the store: Days were when green beans needed to be strung of
their string. No longer. Now the strings have been bred out of
beans. But the snap remains. Look for beans that are small to
medium with a velveteen texture and bright green color. If you can
chew the bean uncooked, it will be just as tender out of the pot.
</P>
<P>
   At home: Refrigerate unwashed green beans in a paper bag or
unsealed plastic bag for no more than one or two days.
</P>
<P>
   CHILE PEPPERS
</P>
<P>
   In the store: Jalapenos, serranos and any other chile pepper
should be crisp, with no sign of wilting or bruising. Peppers with
woody striations have usually been water-deprived and/or
heat-stressed, and can be hotter than the norm.
</P>
<P>
   At home: Store peppers in the crisper for no more than a couple
of days. Left at room temperature, peppers will go limp quickly.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
