<HEADLINE>
MEXICO DENOUNCES U.S. ROLE IN MONEY-LAUNDERING STING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHILIP TRUE  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Foreign Minister Rosario Green said Mexico was
``obligated'' to investigate, charge and seek the extradition of
U.S. agents who violated this country's sovereignty during a recent
money-laundering sting operation.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of a three-year investigation that the U.S. Justice
Department last month termed the largest of its kind in American
history, at least 22 Mexican bank officials were enticed to the
United States, then arrested on charges of laundering money
allegedly belonging to Mexican drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   But Mexican judicial authorities have said that at least some
undercover aspects of ``Operation Casablanca'' took place on
Mexican soil, without knowledge or consent of Mexican officials,
violating anti-drug agreements and Mexican sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is one line to which we Mexicans are obligated: There
was a series of violations of Mexican law, and this will be pursued
officially,'' Green told Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a very precise instruction from (President Ernesto
Zedillo) that we will not desist ... we are going to insist on ...
the investigation of the crimes and that arrest warrants be issued
... to solicit extradition,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   He said American officials ``must be educated (to understand)
that other legal systems exist in other parts of the world, just as
solid as theirs, and that they have to respect them.''
</P>
<P>
   Green spoke with Albright privately at a meeting of ministers of
the Organization of American States in Caracas, Venezuela, earlier
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Their conversation was revealed by the foreign minister in a
radio interview here on Tuesday, and a transcript of the interview
was released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials could not be reached for comment on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   During the investigation, U.S. agents masqueraded as drug
sellers. Their contacts then put them in touch with Mexican
bankers, who were allegedly willing to participate in
money-laundering schemes.
</P>
<P>
   The bankers, mostly mid-level managers, were lured to Nevada
with the promise of attending the opening of a gambling casino.
</P>
<P>
   Green said U.S. undercover agents had themselves committed
money-laundering violations punishable under Mexican law while
entrapping the bankers and usurped Mexican authority because they
acted without notification of the Mexican government.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo and top Mexican anti-narcotics officials have emphasized
national sovereignty and multilateral cooperation in the
international drug fight, a position strongly backed by Barry
McCaffrey, the White House drug policy director.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
