<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE FUTURE IS A STEAMROLLER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; F &UR; aith Popcorn &LR; , widely quoted expert on cultural trends and
future fads, makes several fearless predictions in the latest issue
of Biography magazine. Among the ``trends Popcorn sees taking shape
in our everyday lives'':
</P>
<P>
   Clanning (``spending time with those who share your values'');
Pleasure Revenge; Egonomics (``customized, individual products and
services as an antidote to feeling depersonalized''); Being Alive;
and Down-Aging (``nostalgia for carefree childhood days'').
</P>
<P>
   In other words, xenophobia, selfishness, greed, breathing and
Alzheimer's.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WINNING FORMULA: ROMANCE + DISASTER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The huge financial success of the movie ``Titanic,'' where an
artificial romance was combined with a real-life tragedy to attract
an army of teenage girls to the theater, has spawned the idea for
``1906,'' in which similar elements will tell the story of the
Great Quake of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Publishers Weekly says that a treatment by  &UR; James Dalessandro &LR; 
reportedly has been optioned by Warner Bros. and  &UR; Barry &LR; 
 &UR; Levinson &LR; 's Spring Creek Productions. The author and his manager
are said to be looking for a book deal to match the movie.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; _ It's unclear whether  &UR; Meg Ryan &LR;  laid down the law, or the
filmmakers decided among themselves, but the British Press
Association reports that Ryan will be the only blonde in the
forthcoming movie ``You've Got Mail.'' According to the PBA, one
blond actress was made to wear a dark wig; a blond actor was told
to put gel on his hair to make it darker; and a blond child was
given a knitted hat to wear.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Laura Spillis &LR;  exchanged the soup ladle she had bought as a
birthday gift for  &UR; Paula Pinsky &LR;  after she noticed that it was
scratched. A few days later Pinsky gave Spillis a soup ladle as a
graduation present; it was the ladle with the scratch on it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Double entendres, double indemnity, double features: &UR; Tessa &LR; 
 &UR; DeCarlo &LR;  is struck by the marquee on the Uptown theater in Napa,
which regularly combines the two movies playing: ``Grease My
Giant'' was playing a few weeks ago, replaced by ``Titanic Object
of My Affection.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Episcopalian was the one speaking in Hebrew when Rabbi
 &UR; Stephen Pearce &LR;  of Temple Emanuel and the Episcopal Diocese's
Bishop  &UR; William Swing &LR;  performed a double invocation at the Koret
Prize Foundation luncheon in San Francisco. The luncheon's honorees
were  &UR; Youn-Cha Shin Chey &LR; ,  &UR; Cecil Williams &LR; ,  &UR; Stephen &LR; 
 &UR; Zipperstein &LR;  and  &UR; Michael Luckoff &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _ For the record, the band on ``Mermaid Avenue,'' that
collection of new songs composed around  &UR; Woody Guthrie &LR; 's lyrics,
is  &UR; Jeff Tweedy &LR; 's Wilco.
</P>
<P>
   _ The latest weight-loss gimmick, says Living Well, is habitEX,
a $399 system that includes ``a programmable interactive wristwatch
that emits a sound or vibration at a specified time to help keep
you on track when you're most likely to be experiencing a food
craving.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The U.S. Lunar Prospector, which is supposed to crash on the
moon later this year, includes an ounce of the cremains of lunar
geologist  &UR; Gene Shoemaker &LR; , who was killed in a car accident last
year. Because the moon is considered sacred by many cultures,
American Indians ``have expressed outrage'' about the choice of a
final resting place for part of Shoemaker, says the Earth Island
Journal.
</P>
<P>
   _ The asparation looks like a cross between broccoli and
asparagus but in fact is an entirely new vegetable with a silly
name, says Food &AMP; Wine magazine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE PHOTO IN THE AD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; That photograph described herein earlier this week, in which
 &UR; Johnny Cash &LR;  was flipping the bird, was taken by rock photographer
 &UR; Jim Marshall &LR;  at San Quentin in 1969 and appears in his new book,
``Not Fade Away; The Rock and Roll Photography of Jim Marshall''
(Little, Brown; $50).
</P>
<P>
   Marshall said that while the creators of the Billboard ad
criticizing country music stations got his permission to use the
image, the editors of Harper's magazine, who reprinted the ad,
didn't bother. Irked, he called to complain; when one call was
answered by a woman who refused to take a message and insisted on
putting him on voice mail, his irritation turned to rage. ``I'm
letting my attorneys deal with it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``I do try to have a thought in my head, so that it's not like
a blank stare.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The hardest part about being a supermodel. Cindy Crawford
responding to Allure magazine's question: What goes through your
mind when they take your picture?
</P>
