</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-KEOWN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY TIM KEOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  
Giants Are Showing They're Experts at Winning  c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Cincinnati are a chalk outline of a ballclub, one of a
growing number of anonymous teams that filter in and out of town
without leaving a single memory in their wake. To the Giants, teams
like the Reds come carrying bouquets. Teams like the Reds are the
very best guests.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants have made a living off these teams the past two
seasons. They dispatch them and move on to the next day. When
you're looking to separate teams that will contend throughout the
season from those that might, you could do worse than use games
like Tuesday night's as your guide.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants won their fifth in a row. They're 11 games over .500
_ ahead of last season's pace. They're now 11/2 games behind the
Padres in the National League West. They're showing the same kind
of stubborn professionalism they showed last season.
</P>
<P>
   Not that long ago, it seemed the Padres were going to run away
like a bunch of steroid-enhanced sprinters, never to be seen again.
</P>
<P>
   It's all great stuff, but it would be more noticeable if it
didn't seem so inevitable. The Giants have established a routine:
They win the ones they should win and then move on. They're experts
at winning games that are forgotten before the exhaust lifts from
the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   And with the way the National League shapes up this year, with a
lot of teams like the Reds and Diamondbacks finding their way onto
the schedule, it's the best way to ensure an interesting summer.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night was the perfect night to think about nights to
come. There were about 10,000 people in the stands, and the crowd
had the knowledgeable nastiness unique to Candlestick. They gave
Danny Darwin a standing ovation when he walked off after 62/3
innings of four-hit ball, making it clear they understand what it
takes for him to keep it together that well and that long. They
gave Darryl Hamilton a standing ovation after his tremendous
running catch at the wall in the eighth inning. They harassed Reds
left fielder Chris Stynes, just because he was there.
</P>
<P>
   And if you're really insistent upon looking ahead, you could say
the Giants are a power-hitting right fielder and one late-season,
rent-an-ace starter away from taking this to the ultimate level.
</P>
<P>
   On that front, the latest round of Randy Johnson-to-the-Dodgers
rumors drifted through the clubhouse around 5:30 Tuesday night, and
there wasn't a concerned look in the place. The talk was later
silenced by both sides, but the feeling among the Giants was
exemplified by Brian Johnson, who said, ``If it happens, it'll make
this all a lot more fun.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen if this is the way for this team to win
the division _ the same M.O. worked last year _ but it appears to
be the way to ensure a spot in the race for the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Darwin was out there inning after inning, flicking the ball up
there toward the nearest available corner. Just as Bill Mueller
drops off, J.T. Snow shows his most significant signs of awakening.
But most of all, Tuesday night was Hamilton's game.
</P>
<P>
   He made a diving catch to end the top of the first. He singled
and scored in the bottom half. He homered to lead off the fifth.
Then, to beat all, he made the running catch of an Eddie Taubensee
liner at the wall in left-center to save a run in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton had a great time out there. After the eighth-inning
catch, he smiled at the fans in the bleachers, laughed with Barry
Bonds and then took a quick look over his shoulder to watch the
replay on the big screen.
</P>
<P>
   Attempting to describe his team's attitude, Dusty Baker said,
``We play everybody. Everybody is in on our victories. Everybody
contributes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, whether valid or not, see themselves as the
outsiders in the National League West. It's an odd identity for a
defending champion to adopt, but it's the same one that worked last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants get a lot of credit for playing hard and playing with
intensity, and Baker rightfully gets considerable credit for
instilling those qualities. But there's another way to think about
this: Why wouldn't this particular group play hard and with
intensity?
</P>
<P>
   This seems to cut to the root of their success. Aside from Barry
Bonds and now Robb Nen, this isn't a group that can afford to be
comfortable. The mix is young guys attempting to prove themselves
star-worthy (Bill Mueller, Shawn Estes), established veterans who
constantly push to prove themselves (Darry Hamilton, Charlie Hayes,
Kirk Rueter, Brian Johnson), borderline guys who are getting the
chance of a lifetime (Rich Rodriguez, Rich Aurilia, Chris Jones)
and old guys who are here because they like the atmosphere and want
one more chance to win (Orel Hershiser, Danny Darwin).
</P>
<P>
   It's not the Orioles or the Dodgers, which means the team
doesn't come equipped with the violent mood swings of the teams
that are predominantly ego-driven.
</P>
<P>
   Put it another way: They're as blue-collar as a room filled with
millionaires can be.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
