<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2924 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-GIANTS-SFCHRON &LR;      06-03 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GIANTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURGING GIANTS LOOKING MORE LIKE '97 EVERY DAY 
BY HENRY SCHULMAN
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
   Reds catcher Eddie Taubensee hit a two-run homer off Danny
Darwin of the Giants in the first inning Tuesday night. Thus, the
Giants had the Reds right where they wanted them.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's uncanny how the Giants seem willing to spot their opponents
runs at the outset the way kindergarten teachers hand out milk
tickets, only to come back and win. It happened in Monday night's
16-3 rout, it happened in Tuesday night's 4-2 victory and it's
happened several times before. The Giants have won 35 games this
year. Seventeen have been comebacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't like getting behind, but certainly it happens,''
Giants manager Dusty Baker said. ``These guys don't worry when they
get behind, especially early. This team is really positive in that
respect.''
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to be positive when the offense is working like it
should.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Bonds had two hits and an RBI, and Jeff Kent had a single
and an RBI. But Tuesday night's game was marked by production from
unlikely sources, a hallmark of last year's division-title team.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Hamilton hit his first homer of the season to tie the
game 2-2 in the fifth inning after reading in the paper that no
other Giants regular has gone longer without one. Later in the
inning, J.T. Snow ripped a two-out single to right that drove in
the go-ahead run, a positive sign in his bid to reach .200.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds' run-scoring single in the sixth, scoring Brent Mayne, who
had doubled, produced the 4-2 final. The Giants won their fifth in
a row, improving to 5-1 on a homestand that ends today, took their
14th in the last 17 games at home and moved within 11/2 games of
the first-place San Diego Padres, the closest they have been to the
division lead since April 9.
</P>
<P>
   The key Tuesday night was the ability of Darwin (5-3) to shut
down the Reds after allowing the two first-inning runs. After that,
he blanked them for 52/3 innings, even surviving rare back-to-back
errors by himself and Kent that put two Reds on to start of the
fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Reed, Rich Rodriguez and Robb Nen, who earned his 15th
save, also kept Cincinnati off the board, Rodriguez benefiting from
Hamilton's fine running catch of a long drive to center that robbed
Taubensee of an RBI in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing good baseball,'' Baker said. ``Despite the three
errors we made, we put pressure on them and came away with the
victory.''
</P>
<P>
   While Tuesday night's game was certainly more sanguine than
Monday night's 16-3 carnival, it did not start out that way as the
Reds scored twice in the first on Taubensee's homer and the Giants
got a run back on Hamilton's single, a Bill Mueller grounder that
pushed him to second and Kent's single through the left side of the
infield.
</P>
<P>
   Darwin and Reds starter Scott Winchester then engaged in a
standoff until Hamilton's leadoff homer in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton had gone 190 at-bats without a homer, going back to
last September 19, a fact he read in yesterday's paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice after all the pressure that's been on me the last
few days,'' he said. ``Everybody had one and I didn't have one. I
almost felt left out. I wasn't brought here to hit home runs. I was
brought here to get on base and score runs. I know my job is not to
hit home runs, but it's fun to hit one.''
</P>
<P>
   While Winchester gave, Darwin did not. He pitched a scoreless
sixth and left in the seventh with two out and a runner on second.
Darwin looked more like the pitcher who had a 16-inning scoreless
streak last month than the one who was shelled for seven runs in
each of his two previous starts. His trip back to Texas to watch
his daughter graduate from high school on Saturday must have done
him some good.
</P>
<P>
   And, at 42, Darwin proved that his reflexes are still OK when he
speared a wicked liner through the box by Willie Greene to end the
sixth inning. As Darwin walked off the field, the pitcher who was
drilled in the knee by a line drive in spring training and in the
breadbasket during his first start of the year simply said,
``Wow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' he said later, ``might have hurt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
