<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
49ERS ARE IN NO RUSH OVER RICE THIS TIME 
BY IRA MILLER
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ Jerry Rice is finding his second comeback
taking longer than his first, and he is anxious to speed it up. In
the long run, though, he might be better off because he is taking
it slowly.
</P>
<P>
   Although Rice and 49ers coach Steve Mariucci insist they have no
regret over Rice's rush back to the field last December, just 31/2
months after major knee surgery, they are pursuing a much more
measured pace with his rehabilitation from the second operation.
</P>
<P>
   It is now nearly six months, and even in a no-pads, no-contact
minicamp like the one the team is holding this week, Rice runs his
pass patterns mostly against the air. He is held out of full team
drills, just running his routes and working on timing with the
quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to do a little more, but Steve is being very
cautious, and he's really driving me crazy, too, because I believe
in practicing and getting yourself ready,'' Rice said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci says he is handling it that way because there is no
urgency: The season does not begin for more than three months. Left
unsaid is that, as remarkable as it was for Rice to return during
the 1997 season, it became somewhat of a hollow accomplishment when
he was reinjured before halftime in his first game back.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, even Rice says now, ``I wouldn't change that for
the world, just to be able to run back on that field again. That
night, the atmosphere was unbelievable.'' And Mariucci says he
won't second-guess the decision, either.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, it is clear there is a different plan. Rice has
the entire offseason to get ready, and the 49ers are making sure he
uses it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no choice,'' he said. ``Steve's controlling everything.
If it was left up to me, I would probably take the same approach
(as last time). But everything is going to work out. I feel like
I'm getting stronger day by day and it's just a matter of time
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice has been running _ and running fast, but he acknowledges
his surgical left knee is not yet at full strength. He said it
feels good, especially since two irritating screws were removed in
a procedure last month. But he admits he still does not have full
confidence in the knee and needs to strengthen the muscles around
it.
</P>
<P>
   Until last September, Rice never had suffered a major football
injury. Now he has gone under the knife three times: the two
operations and the screw-removal procedure which, while technically
minor, Rice called the most painful of them all because he did it
under only a local anesthetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you sustain an injury like that, you have a tendency to
favor that injury,'' Rice said. ``Basically, I'm going to try to
fight through that. I think it's all about confidence. If you can
gain confidence in that knee again, you're not going to think about
it; you just go out there and react.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I'm looking forward to that first hit, and
hopefully I can jump up from it and go back to the huddle.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been expected Rice will be ready when training camp
begins for the veterans on July 21. With five exhibition games,
however, Mariucci might continue to hold Rice back until sometime
in August. As usual, Rice wants to play as much as he can. He is so
anxious to do more than he is doing that, at one point, he lined up
on defense and ran step-for-step down the field with wide receiver
J.J. Stokes.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, it is clear the 49ers are counting on Rice's return
for the season. Mariucci and quarterback Steve Young talk of making
frequent use of three-wideout formations, not just on third down.
Young wants to see the 49ers' offense become more aggressive,
especially on first downs.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Young said he expects Rice will be 100 percent by September
``because I don't know how else to think about him.'' But he
strayed from the company line on another topic. With the hindsight
of history, Young questioned the wisdom of Rice's rapid return last
year, saying, ``Everybody got really hyped up about the moment, but
clearly, probably, should have used a little more time.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, Rice is using the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any reason why I can't come back and do the things
I'm accustomed to doing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; Doleman Absent: &LR;  Defensive end Chris Doleman, who agreed
to a restructured contract last month, is absent from the minicamp.
That was one of his conditions for accepting the deal.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  ``He had some golf plans, I think,'' said vice president
Dwight Clark.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Money Matters:  &LR; The 49ers are about $870,000 under the salary
cap limit, so they'll need to clear about $1.4 million more to sign
their draft choices. The 49ers' rookie salary pool is $2,294,831,
although they do not have to spend it all. Negotiations with the
draft choices have not started yet.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; Ailing:  &LR; Jamie Brown, the recently acquired left tackle,
strained a calf muscle while working out last week, so he's not
practicing in the mini-camp. Two other veteran linemen, Harris
Barton and Frank Pollack, still are on the mend from surgeries. So
is defensive end Gabe Wilkins, an offseason acquisition, and free
safety Merton Hanks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
