<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-TRIAL-325&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APARTHEID-ERA CRIMINAL TESTIFIES AT BOTHA TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GEORGE, South Africa _ One of apartheid's most notorious killers
took the witness stand Wednesday to say he was rewarded with rare
medals and congratulated by generals and at least one Cabinet
minister for his work in killing political opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The former police colonel, Eugene de Kock _ who is serving two
life sentences and 212 years for six murders and a host of other
crimes, most of which he says he committed under orders _ testified
in the contempt trial of former President P.W. Botha, who says he
never sanctioned such activities.
</P>
<P>
   Botha is on trial for ignoring subpoenas to appear before the
Truth and Reconciliation Commission, which is investigating South
Africa's brutal past. The 82-year-old Botha has called the panel a
circus, saying he will answer only to God for his deeds.
</P>
<P>
   But if he hoped to avoid political theater he appears to have
miscalculated. While the issue may be whether Botha is compelled to
appear before the commission, the prosecution has offered a small
parade of witnesses in the last three days who have made the horror
and pain of the government's covert operations come to life.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the prosecution has concentrated on Botha's role
in the bombing of a church building in Johannesburg in 1988, an
attack that injured 21 people. One of Botha's former Cabinet
ministers has said that Botha personally ordered him to destroy the
building. The prosecution has called victims of the explosion and
de Kock, who carried out the assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Botha's lawyers have objected to the testimony as irrelevant.
But the judge, Victor Lugaju, has allowed it, saying it was
important that information about the bombing of the church
building, known as Khotso House, be heard.
</P>
<P>
   Botha, who sits on a special padded seat outside the dock
because of hip replacement, appeared to clench his jaw at times
during de Kock's testimony, and to studiously avoid eye contact
with him.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Tuesday, a security guard who was sucked into the basement
during the blast described his terror as the walls crumbled around
him. And the Rev. Peter Storey told how elderly and mentally
disabled residents of the building across the street staggered from
their rooms bleeding from glass and other shrapnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a scene out of hell,'' said Storey, whose church owned
the apartment building. ``Utter devastation. I've never seen
anything like it.''
</P>
<P>
   De Kock testified that as a specialist in covert operations he
was called in by a police general to blow up Khotso House after a
local police effort failed. Local police had tried to use land
mines but apparently the grocery bags carrying the explosives to
the underground parking garage burst and the mines rolled down the
street.
</P>
<P>
   De Kock was experienced in blowing up buildings. He had blown up
a building belonging to the African National Congress in London in
1981. For that, he received a medla, the Star of Excellence, which
was usually given only to generals and which required the approval
of Botha.
</P>
<P>
   De Kock described how his men planted the mines and intended to
kill anyone who got in the way, including, if need be, other police
officers who stumbled on to their operation. He cleared this with
his commanding officer, he said.
</P>
<P>
   De Kock testified that he believed low-level operatives like
himself had been ``hung out to dry'' by politicians such as Botha
who have repeatedly maintained that they knew nothing of ``dirty
tricks'' operations. During Botha's period in office between 1978
and 1989, thousands of political activists and family members were
tortured or killed by security forces.
</P>
<P>
   But many former Cabinet members have said that terms like
eliminate, neutralize and remove permanently from society _ phrases
that have been found in policy documents approved by Botha and his
inner circle _ did not mean kill. De Kock said such assertions were
nonsense. Politicians who said such things ``want to eat lamb but
don't want to see blood and guts,'' he said. ``They're cowards.''
</P>
<P>
   The head of the Truth Commission, Archbishop Desmond Tutu, also
took the stand Wednesday to deny Botha's claim that he ever made a
deal allowing Botha to avoid a public appearance before the
commission in exchange for answers he gave in writing to commission
questions. Ignoring usual court protocol, Tutu began by making a
statement that he was pained to find himself in court. ``I stand
here with the greatest possible reluctance and filled with
considerable distaste,'' Tutu said.
</P>
<P>
   Tutu, in often passionate tones, testified that he had gone out
of his way to accommodate Botha and show him that he would be
treated with dignity if he came before the commission, but to no
avail. Tutu said he would still be willing to ask the prosecutor to
drop the charges if Botha changed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not seeking to humiliate him and I am not seeking to set
him up,'' the bishop said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
