<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2929 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-REALQUIET-SFCHRON     06-03 1259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-REAL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGEND OF SECRETARIAT'S TRIPLE CROWN RUN REVIVED BY REAL QUIET'S
BID 
BY DAVID EINSTEIN
</HEADLINE>
 QUIET-SFCHRON   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Belmont Stakes on Saturday will generate more than ordinary
interest, because one of the horses, Real Quiet, has a chance to
become the first Triple Crown winner since Affirmed in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   But for me, and I suspect for many, many others, the race will
be run in the shadow of what happened 25 years ago, when the great
Secretariat turned the Triple Crown into a tour de force and won
the Belmont by an unheard-of 31 lengths.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, 1973 was a lousy year. The Vietnam War was
essentially over, but the wounds it had inflicted on the American
psyche still festered. Five original defendants in the Watergate
break-in pleaded guilty and began to spill the beans on Nixon.
Spiro Agnew resigned the vice presidency and pleaded no-contest to
tax evasion. Israel and its Arab neighbors duked it out in the Yom
Kippur War, and the Arabs retaliated against American support for
Israel with an oil embargo that plunged us into an energy crisis.
</P>
<P>
   When I look back on 1973, however, the picture that emerges is
of a chestnut colt in blue- and white-checkered blinders thundering
at 38 miles an hour and blowing the bad memories aside like autumn
leaves in Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came around when we needed him,'' one observer wrote in an
America Online message board set up last month for the silver
anniversary of Secretariat's Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   The son of Bold Ruler out of Somethingroyal, Secretariat seemed
predestined to become the monarch of the sport of kings. By the age
of 2, he was the size of a 3-year-old, with a barrel chest and
perfect legs. Naturally they called him Big Red.
</P>
<P>
   If he was breathtaking standing still, Secretariat left people
gasping when he ran. Combining power and poetic rhythm with a an
irrepressible joie de vivre, he fashioned a record of 16 victories
in 21 starts that put him in the company of Citation and Man O'War.
Many call him the greatest horse of all.
</P>
<P>
   How impressive was Secretariat on the track? The late
sportswriter Red Smith once asked Charlie Hatton, the trainer, how
Secretariat had done in his morning workout. ``The trees swayed,''
Hatton replied.
</P>
<P>
   Secretariat, who had been named horse of the year after his
first season in 1972, won the 1973 Kentucky Derby in record time,
and nearly set a record in winning the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   In the Derby, he came from last place to take the lead in the
stretch. Astonishingly, he ran each quarter-mile faster than the
previous one. In the Preakness, he pulled off a risky maneuver by
passing the pack wide at the first turn and never looked back.
</P>
<P>
   Those performances in the first two legs of the Triple Crown
captured the public's imagination. In one week, Secretariat
appeared on the covers of Time, Newsweek and Sports Illustrated,
and the Belmont Stakes _ the final leg of the Triple Crown _ was
anticipated more as a coronation than a contest.
</P>
<P>
   With nearly 70,000 fans in attendance at Belmont Park and
millions more watching on TV, Secretariat broke lackadaisically
from the gate on the afternoon of June 9. Ron Turcotte, who rode
him in 18 of his 21 races, including all three in the Triple Crown,
said it was not necessary to push him. ``He was a good breaker,''
the jockey said. ``I never tried to make him lead. I just gave him
time at the start to get his legs under him.''
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the back stretch, Secretariat made his move, and
you could see Sham, the only horse in the five-horse field given
any chance against him, sag visibly. The race was over, and all
that was left was for Secretariat to gallop into the realm of myth.
</P>
<P>
   Coming around the final turn Big Red pulled away handily, and
down the stretch he widened the lead with every stride. He put the
length of a football field between himself and the field and was
still gaining at the end.
</P>
<P>
   A famous photo shows Turcotte turning his head to look back as
he crosses the finish line. ``I just had to turn around,'' he said.
``I kept hearing the announcer saying how far ahead we were, and I
had to look for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Turcotte, who won 3,033 races in his career, including 14 aboard
Secretariat, did not need much expertise for this race.
Essentially, he was just along for the ride, never once using his
whip. ``He was running on his own,'' Turcotte said. ``If I asked
him to go harder through the stretch, I don't know how fast he
would have gone.''
</P>
<P>
   It was arguably the greatest two-plus minutes in the history of
sports, rivaled perhaps only by Joe Louis' first-round knockout of
Hitler's Aryan standard-bearer Max Schmeling at Yankee Stadium in
1938.
</P>
<P>
   Secretariat's winning time of two minutes and 24 seconds still
stands as a record for a 11/2-mile dirt track. Sham, who might have
achieved glory in a different year, finished fifth and never raced
again, his spirit shattered.
</P>
<P>
   The impression left by Secretariat's magnificent performance was
considerable _ the sort of once-in-a-lifetime experience you relate
to your grandchildren with a faraway look in your eyes and a lump
in your throat. Some 5,300 winning tickets went unclaimed, becoming
souvenirs and proof that their holders had been there.
</P>
<P>
   Secretariat would run six more races, winning four. At his final
appearance, in the Woodbine Canadian International, the track
announcer, departing from the traditional call of ``Ladies and
Gentlemen, the horses are on the track,'' said instead, ``The horse
is on the track.''
</P>
<P>
   Syndicated for more than $6 million, an astronomical figure for
the time, Secretariat was retired to stud at Claiborne Farm in
Paris, Ky. There he sired 663 offspring, 46 percent of whom won
races. One, Risen Star, took both the Preakness and the Belmont in
1988.
</P>
<P>
   Even in retirement, Secretariat remained a star. More than 8,500
people visited him each year at Claiborne, watching him frolic and
perhaps having the chance to pet him or give him a handful of grass
_ the horse-world equivalent of getting an autograph.
</P>
<P>
   ``People loved to come see him, it was exciting,'' said Gus
Koch, longtime assistant manager at Claiborne. ``The horse had such
presence. He was the king and he knew it.''
</P>
<P>
   Koch recalls one time a car pulled up late in the afternoon with
a family who had come to see Secretariat. Koch told them visiting
hours were over, but they persisted. ``They said they'd driven all
the way from Michigan,'' he said, ``so I told them, OK, come on,
let's go see him.''
</P>
<P>
   Turcotte visited Claiborne once just before the Kentucky Derby
in 1977. The following year, he would be paralyzed in a fall at the
Belmont and confined to a wheelchair. Today he lives in a little
town in New Brunswick on the east side of his native Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stood at the fence and called to him, saying `Come over
here, Big Red,''' Turcotte recalls. ``It seemed as if he recognized
me. He put his head on my shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretariat was euthanized in October 1989 at the age of 19,
victim of an incurable hoof disease. The autopsy revealed that his
heart was twice normal size. That didn't surprise anybody.
</P>
<P>
   A true measure of greatness is the ability to transcend
generations, and Secretariat has that magic. Folks still place
flowers on his grave, and youngsters who were not alive at the time
marvel at the power and the beauty he conveyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could have been born earlier,'' said one young fan on
AOL's message board. ``I would have given anything to see that
horse run.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
