A2932 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELLSOUTH-CABLE-COX     06-03 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-CABLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth today offers an option to cable, satellite
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- BellSouth Corp. today will launch a wireless
television service that will serve much of metro Atlanta, a
160-channel, digital offering that pits the phone company against
established cable providers.
</P>
<P>
   The service, beamed from four towers in and around the city, is
available immediately to 700,000 households _ about half the
households in metro Atlanta _ with plans for expansion in the
months to come, said John Hartman, vice president of BellSouth
Entertainment, the unit offering the service.
</P>
<P>
   The move makes Atlanta one of the few cities in the nation where
consumers can choose between rival cable television providers. But
some entrenched cable companies are planning their own
counterattack by upgrading their networks. Moreover, MediaOne has
started offering phone service in some parts of Atlanta and
Norcross, challenging the phone monopoly held by BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   The wireless offering can be seen as a pre-emptive strike by
BellSouth, since cable company upgrades are time-consuming and
costly, requiring construction and visits to new customers.
BellSouth only has to send technicians to a customer's home or
apartment to install wireless cable. They will put a receiver on
the roof or in a tree, then run a cable into the home and to its
televisions.
</P>
<P>
   MediaOne, the largest area cable provider with 540,000
customers, is spending $400 million to add broad-band service while
awaiting the entry of BellSouth, said company spokesman Dave Wood.
``We are certainly ready to meet them head on. I think we've had
more time in the business with a proven technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone in metro Atlanta can receive wireless service.
Homes blocked from transmission by hills or large buildings, and
even homes that are too close to broadcast towers, will not get the
service. On the other hand, the service can be delivered to
isolated homes that would be expensive to serve with wired cable.
BellSouth has a license to provide service within a 35-mile radius
of the NationsBank building in Atlanta, where one broadcast tower
is placed.
</P>
<P>
   Other towers are in Peachtree City, Stone Mountain and Sweat
Mountain in Marietta. BellSouth decided to limit the service's
availability at first, largely because the company fears being
faced with demand it cannot meet. Even so, BellSouth expects a slew
of orders and has hired several hundred technicians, Hartman said.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for company and customers alike, the areas where
the service is available at first do not follow a neat geographic
pattern. BellSouth said it cannot precisely describe which homes
can sign up for the service _ setting the stage for some consumer
confusion.
</P>
<P>
   About 75 percent of Atlanta households now receive television
either by cable or satellite broadcast. Hartman declined to say how
much of the market BellSouth expects to capture, except to say,
``We expect to be a very major player in the home entertainment
business.''
</P>
<P>
   He agreed that 30 percent of the market would make BellSouth a
major player, representing more than 200,000 households and annual
revenue of well over $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on which plan a customers chooses, BellSouth's service
costs between $60 and $200 to install and $40 a month for basic
service to two televisions.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth intends to lure customers not with price but with the
promise of a the crystal clear picture of a digital broadcast and
an array of choices, including up to 50 pay-per-view channels _
features far beyond what most cable companies offer. And while
satellite offers high-quality pictures and a variety of channels,
it has no local programming. BellSouth will deliver local broadcast
channels.
</P>
<P>
   Few consumers connect the BellSouth name with television, but
the company hopes to capitalize on its reputation as a dependable
provider of phone service. By contrast, cable companies have
struggled to overcome a legacy of customer dissatisfaction. More
than anything else, BellSouth must overcome the tendency of
consumers to stick with whatever they do now for television _
whether cable, satellite or rabbit ears, Hartman said. ``From my
perspective our largest competitor is inertia.''
</P>
<P>
   Several thousand people _ mostly BellSouth employees _ are
already testing the service. But one tester is telecommunications
analyst Jeff Kagan, who said he found the service ``awesome'' but
challenging. Accustomed to an old-style remote, Kagan said it took
some time to learn how to use the controls needed for to customize
directories, block inappropriate shows for children and order
pay-per-view. ``Moving to the BellSouth entertainment remote from a
cable remote is like moving from a dashboard of a Geo Metro to an
F-14 fighter jet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth now offers wireless cable in New Orleans, competing
with an established cable operation run by Cox Communications,
which is majority owned by Cox Enterprises, owner of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. Later this year, BellSouth plans to offer
wireless service in Dayton, Jacksonville and Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
