<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BULLS-JAZZ-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINALS IS REMATCH OF AGE, WISDOM 
BY DAVID STEELE
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Salt Lake City _ The teams are the same, and most of the names
are the same. The question now, as the NBA Finals begin Wednesday
night, is whether the games will be the same.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Bulls and Utah Jazz meet again to decide the
championship _ the 11th rematch in Finals history and the first
since 1988 and '89, when the Lakers defeated the Pistons and lost
to them the following year. The major players have not changed
since last year, when the Bulls defeated the Jazz in six games. The
featured performers are still Michael Jordan, Karl Malone, Scottie
Pippen, John Stockton, Dennis Rodman and coaches Phil Jackson and
Jerry Sloan. The home-court advantage belongs to the Jazz this
time, which means the first two and last two games (if necessary)
will be at the Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   However, this year is not like last year. Both teams, among the
most experienced (a kind euphemism for ``old'') in the NBA, are a
year older. The Jazz are no longer newcomers to the increased
pressure and heightened attention from fans and media the Bulls are
accustomed to.
</P>
<P>
   And in several major areas, the Jazz are more intact from last
season. The Bulls are missing two key players whose absence will be
felt greatly. Center Brian Williams and forward Jason Caffey were
far from All-Stars; they were not even starters. But they were big
bodies who could help defend Malone and keep him from running wild
inside.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping Malone in check is as critical to the Bulls' chances as
controlling Jordan is to the Jazz's. Now the Bulls are left with
Luc Longley _ whom Jackson said Tuesday is his first choice _ and
Rodman, who once again has the potential to be more sideshow than
solid contributor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis will be matched up with him at times, but that's out of
necessity. Our main guy has always been Longley,'' Jackson said.
``Dennis takes the also-rans and does the help defense and the
rebounding.'' That comment could be just another tactic to prod the
flighty Rodman, but based on Rodman's disinterested, distracted
performance in last year's Finals, it holds a germ of truth.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Rodman griped again about officiating and Jackson's
decision to bring him off the bench in the previous series against
Indiana. ``It's just very difficult to play when you can't play.
You get into foul trouble, you come off the bench, you're back on
the bench, come off the bench,'' he said. ``Hopefully, this year
will be a lot different for me in the Finals.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, a late-season pickup last year, was the inside
presence at both ends that the Bulls needed to neutralize Malone in
the Finals; however, with the Bulls limited in what they could
offer him to retain him as a free agent, he left for substantially
more money with the Pistons last summer. Caffey played only 17
minutes total in the Finals last year but probably would have
played more this time around _ except that general manager Jerry
Krause inexplicably traded the free-agent-to-be to the Warriors in
February for two second-round picks and David Vaughn, whom they cut
a week later. Asked late in the season why he thought the Bulls
would give him away like that, Caffey shook his head and said,
``You tell me. I don't understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz, meanwhile, come in with the same players playing the
same roles as last June. Once again, small forward Bryon Russell
(11.9 points, 49.5 percent shooting) and center Greg Ostertag (4.6
rebounds, 2.57 blocked shots a game in just 20 minutes) have
stepped up in the playoffs after mediocre regular seasons. Shandon
Anderson (who missed most of the Finals last year after his father
died) and Chris Morris also have turned in strong performances off
the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I see it as a lot better than last year,'' Russell
said, comparing the Jazz's two Finals berths, ``because we're
getting more support, not just from me but from everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Most important, the Jazz are a year older but a year wiser about
the Finals experience. ``Last year we came in and were too happy.
This year we're more relaxed,'' Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   Malone agrees, about his team and himself. He admitted he might
have pressed too much last year after winning the Most Valuable
Player award; his bad free-throw shooting all but sealed the Jazz's
losses in games 1 and 6 in Chicago. ``I don't know what kind of
attitude I have; it's not an excitement attitude, and it's not an
`I don't care' attitude,'' he said. ``It's kind of in the middle,
and sometimes I feel like I play my best when I have that feeling
or that kind of attitude.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
