<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-A'S-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWINS JUMP ON A'S EARLY IN ROUT 
BY STEVE KETTMANN
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Minneapolis _ The Minnesota Twins made their 10-3 win over the
A's look so easy, it wouldn't have been surprising to see Twins
third baseman Brent Gates trot onto the field wearing a big pink
bubble-gum bubble stuck to the top of his batting helmet.
</P>
<P>
   During Monday night's game, TV cameras had shown Gates strolling
around the Twins dugout, unaware that a mischievous teammate had
stuck a bubble to his cap. The gag might have helped Gates, a
former A's second baseman. He tied a career high Tuesday with four
hits _ three in the first three innings when the Twins scored eight
runs off starter Tom Candiotti _ and lifted his average 40 points
to .181.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who did it yet,'' Gates said of the gag. ``You
have to have fun. We have a great bunch of guys here. I got off to
a slow start this year. It's just something I think will turn
around.''
</P>
<P>
   The A's were having a bad enough day even before reliever Dave
Telgheder sprained his knee fielding Otis Nixon's little nubber in
the fifth. Telgheder's spikes caught in the turf enough to put
unusual stress on the knee. Depending on the results of an MRI
today in Oakland, he's likely to go on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those freak things, I guess,'' Telgheder said.
</P>
<P>
   Candiotti (4-6) has been a good addition to the A's staff this
year, but lately he's been struggling. The Twins clobbered him for
eight runs in just 22/3 innings, the second-worst showing of
Candiotti's 15-year big-league career. In his worst, he gave up 10
runs in four innings against the Giants at Candlestick in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Since May 1, Candiotti has just one win against three losses. He
has an 8.51 ERA in those games and has lasted five innings or less
in four straight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to find a way to get him turned around,'' A's
manager Art Howe said. ``I don't know what we can do. This is the
second time he had extra time between starts and he wasn't sharp. I
was told in warm-ups he had a good knuckleball going. It seemed
like everything fell in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Twins piled up eight hits against Candiotti, but it wasn't
as if they were all rockets. Nixon led off the first with a bounder
up the middle that second baseman Scott Spiezio gloved, but he had
no chance to get the speedy Nixon. All it took after that for the
Twins to throw up three runs in the inning was a Gates single
followed by a Paul Molitor double and three groundouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like they were just trying to make contact,''
Candiotti said. ``You look at the lineup they put out there. Otis
Nixon is a perfect example of a guy who just tries to put the bat
on the ball and run.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Candiotti isn't concerned. But at 40, he knows
that shrugging off a bad stretch is a big part of turning it around
on the field. The ups and downs are what get to you, especially
when you're young.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go bad, you can just mentally kill yourself,'' he
said. ``The results to me haven't been good. But my approach isn't
going to change. I'm sure if this were my first year or two in the
big leagues, my confidence might be affected. But when I go good, I
go good, and when I go bad, I go extremely bad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
