<HEADLINE>
IN THE BANKBOSTON DEAL, MONEY WAS EVERYTHING FOR SANDY 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK VEVERKA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
Sandy Robertson's 11th-hour negotiations to stay aboard the
BankBoston gravy train produced a higher contract offer, but it
wasn't enough to keep him in the deal.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sources close to the talks between BankBoston and the investment
bank that Robertson co-founded say his proposed ``personal
side-deal'' threw a wrench into the works shortly before the buyout
was slated to be finalized.
</P>
<P>
   Around 4 a.m. last Friday, BankBoston announced that it agreed
to buy Robertson Stephens from BankAmerica for about $800 million.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a story leaked to the Wall Street Journal published
Thursday that raised hackles at BankBoston headquarters, sources
say. The Journal reported that BankBoston was buying the investment
bank and also revealed that Sandy Robertson, instead of remaining
with the firm after the sale, was going to start his own investment
bank.
</P>
<P>
   More important, perhaps, was the story's suggestion that
Robertson Stephens might fetch a lower price because Robertson was
no longer going to work for it.
</P>
<P>
   To their chagrin, BankBoston's board of directors saw their deal
exposed in the paper before getting to sip their Thursday morning
coffee. Later that day, they were scheduled to give a thumbs-up to
the bank's tentative agreement to buy Robby Stephens.
</P>
<P>
   Sources contend that Robertson, or associates of his, hoped the
story in the Journal would squeeze more money and authority for
himself out of BankBoston. At that point in the negotiations,
Robertson had been offered$5 million over three years, and he was
asking for $15 million, sources say. Robertson denies that he
planted the story.
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, the BankBoston directors and officers weren't
thrilled that their buyout plans had been spilled to the papers.
But &UR;  &LR; the board told BankBoston Vice Chairman Paul Hogan and
President Henrique Meirelles to go ahead and ``work out their Sandy
deal,'' a source says.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; So with their marching orders in hand, they hopped on a plane
for San Francisco immediately after the board meeting adjourned
Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Later that day, a meeting was held to announce the buyout to
Robertson Stephens employees.
</P>
<P>
   But bankers on both coasts continued to work through the night
to iron out the Sandy deal.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Sandy Robertson rejected BankBoston's final offer.
He would not reveal the size of it, but sources say it was around
$10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson says the Journal article ``did precipitate a very
generous offer from (BankBoston). It was a huge offer. But it was a
different kind of offer'' than the original one presented to him by
Meirelles early last week.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson, who is 67 and hasn't been running the investment bank
for a few years, says he plans to ``do some kind of offshoot'' but
wouldn't call it an investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Robertson has a no-compete clause with BankAmerica,
but as most lawyers in this state will tell you, they are difficult
to enforce in California.
</P>
<P>
   NO. 2 REDUX
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco is playing second fiddle to Charlotte ... again.
First, it was the battle for the corporate headquarters of the
merged NationsBank-BankAmerica. Now, it's the right to host a
global economic gabfest, er, business conference.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that the North Carolina metropolis beat out our
fine city as the location for next year's Trans-Atlantic Business
Dialogue conference. The news was released (where else?) yesterday
at NationsBank headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Topping the guest list is President Clinton. But I don't see
what the big deal is. It seems like the president is in the Bay
Area every other week passing the fund-raising hat for somebody.
</P>
<P>
   CORRECTION
</P>
<P>
   The leveraged buyout of Northwest Airlines led by Gary Wilson
and Al Checchi occurred in 1989. Monday's column incorrectly stated
the year as 1987.
</P>
<P>
   And as for whether Mr. Checchi should receive credit for turning
around the airline, that could be debated at length.
</P>
<P>
   But airline analyst Michael Boyd in Golden, Colo., makes this
point: Checchi and Wilson hired current chief executive John
Dasburg, who has successfully recast Northwest into a profitable
and successful carrier. ``They did one thing: They brought in
someone who could run the airline,'' Boyd says.
</P>
