<SLUG> BC-WORLD-RELIGIONS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS WEEK:OLD ORDER AMISH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JIM JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One in a series or articles on religions of the world.
</P>
<P>
   OLD ORDER AMISH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MEMBERSHIP: about 80,000 in 22 states, Canada and Central
America. Most Old Order Amish live in Pennsylvania, Ohio and
Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   HISTORY: The Amish sect began as part of the Mennonite movement,
which arose in Europe in the 1500s. Differences arose regarding
church-state relations and infant baptism, and in 1693, Jacob Amman
broke from the Mennonites. His followers became known as the Amish.
The two groups still share beliefs regarding nonresistance and
basic Bible doctrine, but they differ in their views on technology,
dress and forms of worship. The Old Order Amish represent the most
conservative of the Amish and Mennonite groups.
</P>
<P>
   BELIEFS: The basic doctrine differs little from orthodox
Christianity: faith in God through Jesus Christ, belief in the
Bible as the inspired word of God, a conviction that faith should
be reflected in a lifestyle of good works and discipleship.
However, the Old Order Amish emphasize the teaching of Romans 12:2
and other verses that encourage believers to separate themselves
from the world. Therefore, Old Order Amish forgo electricity,
television, radios, automobiles and public schools because of the
connection these things create with the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   DAILY LIFE: Most Amish are trilingual, speaking a German dialect
called Pennsylvania Dutch at home, High German in worship services
and English with outsiders. Amish children receive an education
through the eighth grade in one-room private school buildings. A
1972 Supreme Court ruling upheld the group's right to operate its
own schools and deny its children a high school education.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation is limited to horse-drawn buggies. However,
members may hire a car and driver for specific tasks, and they may
use other modern conveniences such as bottled gas for light, heat
and refrigeration.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: National Committee for Amish Religious Freedom;
Pennsylvania Dutch Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau; Handbook of
Denominations in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones covers religion for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 2021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
