<SLUG> BC-KOMAG-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Komag to Cut 10% Of Workers   By Jon Swartz  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
The personal computer glut claimed another victim yesterday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Komag Inc., a maker of platters used in computer disk drives,
said it will slice its 4,800-person workforce by 10 percent and
take a one-time charge of up to $185 million in its second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The struggling San Jose company _ the latest components
manufacturer to be sideswiped by an oversupply of PCs _ did not
disclose how many jobs would be affected in the Bay Area, where it
employs 2,000. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A company spokesman said the job cuts would be ``across the
board'' and ``throughout the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Komag said it will close one of its two San Jose plants by July
1999, but it declined to say how many jobs would be eliminated.
Nearly three-fourths of Komag's manufacturing capacity is outside
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials are predicting a second-quarter loss on par
with its first-quarter loss of $58.2 million ($1.10 a share).
</P>
<P>
   Komag is forecasting that sales in its second quarter ending
June 28 will be $75 million to $85 million, significantly lower
than the $100 million to $125 million it expected earlier. In the
same quarter a year ago, Komag reported revenues of $175.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The disk supplier warned that it does not expect to be
profitable until the first half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been swept up by adverse conditions in the PC
market,'' said analyst Jim Porter of Disk/Trend Inc. in Mountain
View. ``Management will need to hunker down over the next year and
survive a difficult period.''
</P>
<P>
   Komag joins a growing list of companies in the disk-drive
industry who have recently made cutbacks to offset dwindling market
share and oversupply problems caused by a softening PC market.
</P>
<P>
   Seagate Technology Inc. and Quantum Corp. already have slashed
workforces this year, and Western Digital has warned of
disappointing earnings. The stocks of all three companies have
plummeted in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Komag made the announcement after the close of trading. Shares
of Komag dipped 44 cents, to a 52-week low of $9.19.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 2021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
