<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Forbes Names New Publisher, Bay Area Base   By David Einstein  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Forbes Inc. named a new publisher for its flagship business
magazine yesterday _ a 43-year-old technology booster who will
preside from a West Coast headquarters in Silicon Valley.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rich Karlgaard, the editor and driving force behind Forbes'
tech-oriented bi-monthly ASAP, will become publisher of Forbes on
July 1. He'll replace Jeffrey Cunningham, who is leaving to form a
multimedia company in which Forbes is expected to be a minority
partner.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes is the latest East Coast media power to relocate its
nerve center to Silicon Valley, bowing to the growing influence of
technology in the U.S. economy. Newspaper chain Knight Ridder,
publisher of the San Jose Mercury News, is moving its headquarters
from Miami to San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Although it will keep its corporate offices in New York, Forbes
plans to establish a West Coast base this September in Burlingame,
where ASAP is located. The company will consolidate ASAP's staff,
an expanded Forbes editorial bureau and advertising and sales
personnel on the top floor of a new five-story building.
</P>
<P>
   Karlgaard's appointment signals Forbes' intent to put greater
emphasis on technology coverage _ a strategy embraced by its rival,
Fortune. Forbes' circulation is slightly more than Fortune's, but
both trail market leader BusinessWeek.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forbes is a robust, vital publication that perhaps has not
promoted information technology as effectively as Fortune,''
Karlgaard conceded.
</P>
<P>
   It's uncertain whether Karlgaard will imbue Forbes with the
refreshing irreverence that characterizes the writing in ASAP. But
Steve and Tim Forbes, who run the Forbes family empire these days,
made it clear they expect Karlgaard to bring a new voice to the
staid publication that began life 81 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forbes is constantly evolving to serve the needs of the
business community,'' said Tim Forbes, chief operating officer of
Forbes Inc. ``Rich's selection as publisher reflects a new phase in
the magazine's commitment to technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, the sometime-political candidate who serves as
Forbes' chief executive, hailed Karlgaard as ``a forward-looking
original thinker who understands the information needs of top
executives in the new economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Karlgaard co-founded Upside magazine, another opinionated
technology publication, in 1989. In 1992 he left to help Forbes
start ASAP.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights of his tenure there included the week he spent
following Bill Gates around the clock. He also came up with the
idea for an annual issue in which noted writers like Thomas Wolfe
and Kurt Vonnegut are asked to weigh in on a major technology
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Karlgaard, a 1976 Stanford graduate who lives in Los Altos with
his wife and two young children, called Forbes' decision to let him
stay in California a bold move.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes a lot of sense and gives Forbes great balance with a
lot of eyes and ears on Silicon Valley and the Pacific Rim,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In his new job he plans to be ``a chief evangelist for the
digitally driven economy.'' He'll write a column for Forbes every
other week and spend a good deal of time giving speeches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
