<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAKEWEB-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 `Stealth' Web pages feed off addresses   By Jon Swartz  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
When a congressional staffer recently went surfing for information
on the White House, what he stumbled across was hardly
presidential.
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the infamous Whitehouse.com Web site, the flummoxed aide
encountered a digitally enhanced caricature of Hillary Rodham
Clinton _ resplendent in black leather and whip _ leading the
president by a dog leash, and a banner cooing, ``Our nation's young
teens, hot lesbians and hardcore nymphomaniacs all gather here to
serve you and serve their country.''
</P>
<P>
   The aide's boss, U.S. Senator Lauch Faircloth, R-N.C., was not
amused.
</P>
<P>
   ``It upsets the senator that children can punch up `White House'
and look at this stuff,'' said Jim Hyland, Faircloth's legislative
director.
</P>
<P>
   The bait and switch (the official Oval Office Internet address
is  &LR; www.whitehouse.gov &LR; ) has driven Faircloth to draft legislation
that would put a lid on some ``stealth'' Web sites. It prohibits
private parties from using government agency names for commercial
Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Hyland said the proposal is being crafted as a stand-alone
bill or as an amendment to pending legislation from Indiana Senator
Dan Coats. The latter legislation, which is scheduled for a Senate
vote this month, would require operators of commercial sites
``harmful to minors'' to put up barriers to prevent access by
anyone under 18.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  But industry insiders and legal experts say Faircloth's bill
_ in whatever form _ is a blatant affront to the First Amendment. &LR; 
 &LR; They say the law won't clear up the murky realm of online
trademarks, nor will it arrest an onslaught of &UR;  &LR; stealth Web sites
that promote everything from adult-oriented businesses to political
parodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many sites with misleading names, (the bill)
would be difficult to enforce,'' said Shyla Welch, a spokeswoman
for Enough is Enough, a Fairfax, Va., nonprofit organization that
supports Coats' bill.
</P>
<P>
   Enterprising Web operators are increasingly invoking the
monikers of government agencies and well-known companies to mask
their content and get extra attention among an estimated 1 million
online sites.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Steamy Web sites have excelled at the digital diversion to
reach a large commercial audience _ and the results can be jolting
to unsuspecting Web surfers.
</P>
<P>
   _Those expecting to get Internet services by typing
 &LR; www.yahhoo.com &LR;  instead are getting an eyeful of a nude Pamela Lee
Anderson with breathless promises of ``See Pamela f--- Tommy Lee.''
</P>
<P>
   A Yahoo spokeswoman said the Santa Clara company (real site:
 &LR; www.yahoo.com &LR; ) is aware of the site &UR;  &LR; but that the firm's lawyers
have not contacted it.
</P>
<P>
   _NASA officials (real site: &LR;  www.nasa.gov)  &LR; thought they had rid
themselves of an embarrassing situation when they invoked the
National Space Act of 1958 _ which makes it illegal for a private
group to identify itself as NASA _ to shut down the X-rated site &LR; 
www.nasa.com &LR;  last year.
</P>
<P>
   Not entirely. Now there is  &LR; www.nassa.com &LR; , which also features
eye-popping nude photos.
</P>
<P>
   Although Faircloth's bill would ban such misappropriation of
government names, it does not tackle the scores of Web sites that
mask their content with corporate names or well-known phrases. For
example, dumbfounded nerds looking for free shareware software are
surprised to find pornographic images at  &LR; www.sharware.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Faircloth's ire, however, is directed squarely at
Whitehouse.com.
</P>
<P>
   After plunking down $10,000 to buy the rights to
 &LR; www.whitehouse.com &LR;  in May 1997, Dan Parisi of Secaucus, N.J.,
started the site as a ``pure parody of U.S. politics,'' but few
cared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was losing $10,000 a month until I discovered how popular
adult sites are,'' Parisi said.
</P>
<P>
   The site's traffic also has surged to 50,000 visitors per day
from just 100 daily a year ago. Even with all those visitors,
Parisi said he's just now breaking even, but he expects to turn a
profit soon.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials aren't amused, however.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``We object to your use of the names and images of the White
House, the President and the First lady on that Website to sell
memberships in an adult video club,'' presidential counsel Charles
Ruff stated in a curt December 1997 letter. ``We too believe in the
First Amendment _ and in humor, although we see nothing humorous in
your use of the White House domain name to draw children and other
unwitting Internet users to your website.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the warning, the site is still up. It includes the
disclaimer: ``We are in no way endorsed by or associated with the
U.S. government. You must be 18 years or older to enter this
site!''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are plenty of other companies with Web sites that
contain the words `White House,''' Parisi said. ``I have just as
much right to that name as they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Many agree with Parisi that legislation is not the answer.
</P>
<P>
   Industry observers argue that the Clintons are public figures,
making the parody of them _ no matter how distasteful _ legal. And
the site's other content is protected under the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a huge encroachment of free-speech rights, &UR;  &LR; which allow
for parody and conflicting opinions,'' said Wayne Rash, senior
technology editor at InternetWeek magazine in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Trademark lawyers, meanwhile, are divided on whether the White
House should receive the same protections as NASA and Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are federally mandated super trademark protection for
Olympics, Girls Scouts and Daughters of the American Revolution,''
said Carl Oppedahl, an intellectual-property attorney in Frisco,
Colo. ``I'm sure Congress could do the same to White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Sally Abel, a Palo Alto attorney and board member of the
International Trademark Association in New York, said the Internet
industry is trying to ``hash out'' its role in online-naming
rights. &UR;  &LR; She said victims of stealth sites have three options: They
can lobby domain-name dispenser Network Solutions to protect their
trademarked name online, sue the offending party or ``grin and bear
it.''
</P>
<P>
   If legislators don't get their way, they might get an assist
from cybersquatters _ people who register Web addresses that
include the names of companies, celebrities or products, with the
intent of reselling them at a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Parisi and others routinely pay $100 to $1,000 to buy the legal
rights to domain names. Some cybersquatters say they are wary of
being misled into selling their names to hard-core Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will absolutely not sell the rights to `teens.com' so
someone can slap nude photos on a Web site,'' said Martin Turnbull,
a 57-year-old grandfather and domain-name speculator in Colorado
Springs, Colo. ``I'm sick and tired of being abused by those
people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
