<SLUG> BC-AUTO-SALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTOS POST BEST SALES MONTH IN 12 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
 (dc) 
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ May was the best month for car and truck sales since
September 1986 for the nation's auto industry, with sales totaling
1,511,661 cars and trucks, a 12.1 percent increase from May 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, fueled by hefty price discounts, the seasonally
adjusted annual selling rate for light vehicles reached 16.3
million cars and trucks last month, the highest level since October
1987. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sales of both cars and trucks increased though truck sales
showed a higher rise. Car sales totaled 793,066 units, up 6.9
percent; light truck sales topped 718,575 units, up 18.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamentals of the economy are very strong,'' said
Michael DiGiovanni, the chief forecaster at General Motors Corp.
``A lot has been written about the industry slowing down, but
frankly it's hard to see that happening because of low
unemployment, low interest rates and high consumer confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales, however, were buoyed by attractive incentive programs.
Automakers spent as much as $1,600 a vehicle on incentives in May,
up from about $1,100 a year earlier, according to analysts. In
mid-April, G.M. sent certificates worth $500 to $1,000 to previous
buyers of G.M. products to use toward the purchase of 50 different
models, above and beyond other cash rebate and low-interest loan
incentives.
</P>
<P>
   The program was an effort to rebuild GM's market share in the
United States, which had dropped to below 30 percent early in the
year. In May, G.M.'s share of the U.S. car and truck market rose to
32.5 percent. Ford Motor and Chrysler Corp. matched G.M.'s Loyalty
First program with their own customer loyalty plans and agreed to
accept GM certificates. GM did not agree to take Ford and Chrysler
coupons. The loyalty programs run through July 2.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors said Wednesday that it sold 487,151 cars and
trucks in May, an increase of 12.4 percent over May 1997. GM's
truck sales increased 19.2 percent, to 229,097 vehicles, the third
consecutive month GM has set a record for truck sales, pushing G.M.
well ahead of Ford in truck sales. GM's car sales also increased,
up 7 percent at 258,054 units.
</P>
<P>
   Ford reported Wednesday that it sold 353,693 cars and trucks in
May, up 1.2 percent from May 1997. Car sales totaled 139,622, down
5.5 percent; truck sales were 214,171, up 6.2 percent from last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler said Tuesday that it had its best month ever in May,
selling 250,031 cars and trucks, a 27 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   Also reporting higher sales this week were Honda, Mitsubishi,
BMW, Volkswagen, Audi, Land Rover, Kia, Mercedes-Benz and Subaru.
Nissan sales, which include sales for its Infiniti luxury division,
were off 12 percent at 52,992 cars and trucks. Volvo, Mazda and
Hyundai also reported lower sales.
</P>
<P>
   Based on May's strong performance, GM and Ford said they
expected sales for the full year to come in at the high end of
their original forecasts, about 15.2 million cars and trucks. G.M.
and Ford had predicted full-year sales would total 14.7 million to
15.2 million cars and trucks.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While automakers and analysts predict a healthy year for vehicle
sales, the quick pace of spring sales may have borrowed sales from
the second half of the year. ``The terrific numbers in May aren't
sustainable,'' said David Healy, an auto analyst with Burnham
Securities Inc. in New York. ``The coupons are bringing in car and
truck sales from the second half into the spring. But at some
point, the auto makers will have to start paying the piper.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the highly competitive vehicle market is likely to keep
the level of consumer incentives relatively high throughout the
year, analysts said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
