<SLUG> BC-RETIRE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 More People Thinking About Saving   By Laura Castaneda  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
The number of Americans who have attempted to calculate how much
money they may need for retirement jumped from 32 percent in 1996
to 45 percent this year, according to a new survey.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bad news, though, is that despite a booming economy, 36
percent of Americans still aren't saving for retirement, primarily
because they believe they are burdened with too many financial
responsibilities, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
   The findings, which were released yesterday, are part of the
eighth annual Retirement Confidence Survey, which gauges the views
and attitudes of working and retired Americans regarding a wide
range of retirement issues.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; This year's survey also included for the first time a Small
Employer Retirement Survey and a special analysis of the retirement
views of African Americans, Latinos and Asian Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of the survey is to provide information to
public-policy makers, entrepreneurs and average citizens about
retirement issues and barriers to saving.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hope is that these findings have an impact on a grass-roots
level and motivate people to take action,'' said Paul Yakoboski, a
senior research associate for the Employee Benefit Research
Institute, a co-sponsor of the survey.
</P>
<P>
   Among both savers and nonsavers, more than 50 percent said in
the survey they believe they could save an extra $20 every week for
retirement, the study found.
</P>
<P>
   That would give each person $1,040 per year of extra savings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can (save this amount) for decades, we're talking about
potentially hundreds of thousands of dollars, especially if you
factor in starting early, increasing the amount you save, and
getting an employer match (with a 401k) plan,'' Yakoboski said.
</P>
<P>
   The findings were released to coincide with the 1998 White
House-Congressional National Summit on Retirement Savings tomorrow
and Friday in Washington, D.C., which will focus attention on a
number of retirement issues.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The small employer survey noted many reasons why small
businesses don't offer retirement plans to their employees,
Yakoboski said.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 percent said one major reason is that employees would
prefer higher wages or other benefits.
</P>
<P>
   About 51 percent cited uncertain revenue; 45 percent said
required employer contributions are too high; 35 percent cited
excessive government regulations; and 35 percent cited the expense
of starting and administering a plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``You combine all of these factors, and you see real barriers
for small employers when it comes time to think about offering a
retirement plan,'' Yakoboski said. ``We have to work on addressing
employer concerns and making this a priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning to the analysis of minorities and retirement, the survey
said 62 percent of Asian Americans indicate they've begun saving
for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, 52 percent of African Americans and 62 percent of
Latinos indicate they're not currently saving any money for
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, 32 percent of Asian Americans aren't confident that
they'll have enough money to support themselves in retirement, no
matter how long they live, compared to 43 percent of African
Americans and 43 percent of Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   Yakoboski said there's been a heavy emphasis on the importance
of saving for retirement. But that message is not getting across to
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This quick snapshot raises questions about whether there are
better ways to reach out to different parts of the working
population. Does one size really fit all, or do we have to rethink
our approach a bit?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   The survey is co-sponsored by Employee Benefit Research
Institute, the American Savings Education Council, and Mathew
Greenwald &AMP; Associates, a market research firm. All are based in
Washington D.C.
</P>
<P>
   For more survey results go to the institute's Web site at
 &LR; www.ebri.org/rcs &LR;  and click on ``1998 Findings.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
