<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 PCs Will Bring Personal Touch to Political Campaigns   By Tom Abate  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Former political technology guru Dan Jones helped me see the silver
lining inside another election clouded by big money and negative TV
ads.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jones, now with an Internet startup in San Francisco, said that
when he started doing political work for the Democrats in the
1970s, it took a mainframe computer to run a door-to-door campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, a PC can do it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Schweitzer, a Republican tech specialist from Washington
state, said the idea is to build a database of ``swing'' voters _
people not loyal to either party. The high-tech campaign tries to
reach these voters with direct mail or other appeals.
</P>
<P>
   So why do the major candidates throw all their money at the Boob
Tube? San Francisco State University professor Gary Selnow, author
of several books on campaign technology, blames inertia.
</P>
<P>
   ``TV has a long history of success in politics, and politicians
go with what they know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Selnow thinks that database techniques, combined with
Internet delivery, could revolutionize campaigns, replacing
mass-media appeals with one-on-one tactics that grassroots groups
could employ as readily as the rich.
</P>
<P>
   Net campaigns will start by using e-mail and Web sites to reach
supporters, and graduate to sending video clips that cost far less
than TV ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think a new generation of techniques is arising that
will, to some extent, bring back the type of person-to-person
campaign we haven't seen for a while,'' said Elisabeth Provinse, a
Washington, D.C., political expert since 1970.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Reality check &LR; : Whatever their future, Net campaigns ain't all
ready for prime time _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   When the pro-226 campaign bought a modest $5,000 banner ad on
the Hotmail Web site, the Net-heads and politicos had a tiff over
the meaning of GIF.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Hotmail) called us and said, `You need to get a jiff
(file),''' said campaign spokesman Mitch Zak. ``I said, `What's
that ... peanut butter?'''
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; S.F. confidential: &LR;  The e-mail marked ``confidential'' should
never have reached my in-box.
</P>
<P>
   But Alexander Communications goofed and sent me an in-house
message, in which a staffer at this high-tech PR firm blasted
writer and PR critic Michael Wolff.
</P>
<P>
   Wolff is the author of ``Burn Rate,'' a kiss-and-tell book about
an Internet publishing company he founded in the mid-'90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Burn Rate'' is Wolff's account of how he lost control of his
startup and got screwed by former associates _ like his PR firms.
</P>
<P>
   Writing ``Burn Rate'' apparently wasn't cathartic enough for
Wolff, now a columnist for the Industry Standard in San Francisco.
In the magazine's May 4 issue, he took a shorter swipe at PR firms.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``I'm mad because I didn't get my name in the paper enough''
after spending tens of thousands of dollars on PR fees, Wolff
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   That column provoked one Alexandrian to e-mail her colleagues _
and by accident, me. Wolff's startup stiffed Alexander for $48,869
in unpaid PR fees, she said, to let colleagues ``know the kind of
character we're dealing with here.''
</P>
<P>
   I phoned Wolff, who didn't deny the deadbeat-client claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hire these PR people to get your name in the paper and
they don't,'' he said. ``My position finally was: No ink, no
money.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Political ink: &LR;  Alexander, which wants to be the PR firm that
marries tech to politics, has been helping TechNet bring Republican
lawmakers through Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's guest was Representative Michael Oxley, the Ohio
Republican who will play a key role in passing a bill banning
``frivolous'' lawsuits in state courts.
</P>
<P>
   I asked Oxley why the recent GOP interest in what has been
Clinton-Gore country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might have given up on Hollywood,'' he said. ``All the
Republicans out there are dead. Hell, we lost John Wayne, Frank
Sinatra. But we're not giving up on Silicon Valley. The way they
give out stock options, a lot of these companies are turning
employees into capitalists, big time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by
phone, (650) 961-2689, fax (650) 961-5023 or e-mail abate(at
sign)sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
