<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   HMO Bankrolled By Physicians Fails  
   
 By Sabin Russell  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
The California Medical Association has pulled the plug on its
two-year venture into the the world of managed care.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oakland-based California Advantage Inc., which set out to prove
that organized physicians can compete against commercial HMOs, will
file for bankruptcy today and lay off most of its 30 employees.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, California Advantage had signed up fewer patients
than it had doctor investors. The roughly 7,000 subscribers to the
CMA's health plan had 7,600 physician investors to choose from.
Another 30,000 doctors were available to treat the patients who, in
effect, never showed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very sad and distressing event for us,'' said Jack
Lewin, chief executive of the California Medical Association. The
venture ran up a deficit of $10 million, most of it absorbed by
7,600 doctors who each ponied up $1,000 to get the health plan off
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   But California Advantage lacked one advantage even its founders
recognized they needed from the start: money. To make the health
plan work, the CMA figured they would need to sign up twice as many
doctor investors as they eventually did.
</P>
<P>
   The health plan was unable to market itself effectively and
couldn't guarantee that it would remain in business for more than a
year _ not a strong selling point to insurance brokers. California
Advantage charged more than typical HMO's because it allowed
members to opt out of the care provided by plan doctors for partial
coverage of any doctor in the state. Patients would have to pay
more out-of-pocket for out-of-plan service.
</P>
<P>
   As a consequence, Lewin acknowledged, the health plan attracted
a somewhat sicker population of customers whose health care costs
were higher.
</P>
<P>
   But Lewin was hopeful that a partnership the CMA was building
with the California Hispanic Health Care Coalition and a
physician-owned malpractice insurance company would solve the
problems. The group was poised to cover 30,000 low-income patients
under Governor Wilson's Healthy Families program, but last week the
effort collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the problem was money. California Advantage needed
$3 million to pass a state solvency test in order to participate in
the Healthy Families program. The capital-raising effort came up
short.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 2025EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
