</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-REAL-QUIET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL QUIET ARRIVES AT BELMONT TO A WINNER'S WELCOME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN.: Ky.)   (ja)  
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like a king who has been proclaimed but not yet
crowned, Real Quiet arrived in New York on Wednesday amid
movie-star fanfare and with an entourage that declared him ready to
win the Belmont Stakes and become the 12th horse in racing history
to sweep the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   The extravaganza, staged with comic touches, began at 8 o'clock
in the morning when Real Quiet left Churchill Downs in Louisville,
where he won the Kentucky Derby four and a half weeks earlier. It
reached a peak when his cargo plane landed at Kennedy Airport two
hours later, the wing door swung open and the chief members of the
cast stood there with index fingers over their mouths, signifying
``real quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   Then they let the horse leave the plane, and everybody headed
for nearby Belmont Park, where Real Quiet joined most of the
expected 11 contenders who will try to foil him on Saturday. It was
the second such trip in two years for Baffert, who led Silver Charm
into town last June after victories in the Derby and the Preakness.
That story had an unhappy ending when Silver Charm lost in the
final strides to Touch Gold. But for Kent Desormeaux, Real Quiet's
jockey, this trip was novel and exciting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hair-raising, it gave me chills,'' he said after they
had reached Belmont Park. ``I felt like a throwback to the early
part of the century when the winners would get on the train and
travel to the next city.''
</P>
<P>
   But would Real Quiet supply the desired ending? After all, 13
horses have won the Derby and Preakness but failed in the Belmont,
and they included some great ones like Carry Back, Northern Dancer,
Spectacular Bid, Alysheba and Sunday Silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will say I'm 98 percent sure of winning,'' Desormeaux said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just that so many things have to go right. I mean, you
could stumble in the gate. So, I won't guarantee victory. But I am
very, very confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert was asked to comment on suggestions that Real Quiet
might be considered below standard as a Triple Crown winner because
so many rivals had dropped out of contention with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's going to be answered Saturday,'' he said. ``He
has to win before we can think about things like that. And if we
don't win, we're still going to love him.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert has become the first trainer to win the Kentucky Derby
and the Preakness two years in a row, but he is 0 for 7 in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet will test the Belmont track Thursday morning but
won't hold any formal workout. He worked five-eighths of a mile
Tuesday at Churchill Downs in 1:00 4/5, and Baffert pronounced the
team's theme, which he repeated after arriving in New York: ``He's
ready. We're ready.''
</P>
<P>
   The draw for post positions will be held Thursday, and Belmont
Park will stick to tradition and make it a random draw. Both
Churchill Downs and Pimlico switched this year for the Derby and
Preakness, in the interests of TV ratings, and held a draw that
decided an order of selection, rather than post positions. The
owners then chose their post positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why change something that's been done for 200 years?'' asked
David Cross, who trains Classic Cat, third in the Preakness. ``It
doesn't matter where you draw, you've got a mile and a half to
overcome any problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the horses in the Belmont confined themselves to walking
or jogging for exercise Wednesday, but Hanuman Highway held a full
workout that also served to test his new shoes. The colt went four
furlongs in 45 3/5 seconds and galloped out five furlongs in 58
seconds, prompting his trainer, Kathy Walsh, to say, ``We're very
happy with the shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   The shoes were glued onto the hooves of Hanuman Highway after a
high nail from his regular shoe had caused an irritation and heat
in his right front foot.
</P>
<P>
   One bit of intrigue was prolonged: Grand Slam, who won the
Futurity and the Champagne at Belmont Park last fall and the Peter
Pan last week, was likely to be entered in the Belmont Stakes. But
the final decision on running him may not be made until later by
his trainer, D. Wayne Lukas, who spent Wednesday flying from his
home in Los Angeles to New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
