<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIND BLOWING IN GOOD NEWS FOR TROJANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. _ The weather has turned here at the College World
Series - it's downright cold.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, from a pitcher's standpoint, the wind is suddenly
blowing in. At least it was during Wednesday night's game, and it's
expected to continue that way this afternoon (Thursday) when USC,
facing elimination, tackles two-time defending champion Louisiana
State, which is still unbeaten.
</P>
<P>
   The first time the Trojans took on LSU, it was hot and humid,
and the wind was blowing out - Gorilla Ball weather. The result:
LSU pounded USC All-American Seth Etherton for six of its
CWS-record eight home runs on the way to a 12-10 victory.
</P>
<P>
   After that game, USC coach Mike Gillespie, citing the
conditions, remarked, ``The wind's blowing out, it's a small
ballpark and the bats are nuclear.''
</P>
<P>
   And now?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a small park,'' he said Wednesday, smiling, ``and
the bats are still nuclear.''
</P>
<P>
   But he'll take that two-out-of-three anytime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're capable of playing with anybody,'' Gillespie said
shortly after the Trojans knocked Mississippi State out of the
tournament on Tuesday night. ``It's no upset for us to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans are 46-17 for the season. They've also had
experience working through the loser's bracket. USC lost its
opening-round game in the East Regional at Clemson, S.C., to
Virginia Commonwealth, 14-4, then won three games in a row, the
final two by one run, to earn its record-19th trip to the College
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   In the Trojans' first-round game at the CWS against LSU they
owned a 10-5 lead after six innings, thanks to Robb Gorr's grand
slam in the sixth. Then came the explosion. LSU tied the score with
a five-run seven, then broke the tie an inning later.
</P>
<P>
   Etherton, back down off Cloud Nine following his first-round
selection by the Angels in Tuesday's draft of eligible amateur
players, is again Gillespie's choice to start the rematch with LSU.
</P>
<P>
   It's not like Etherton didn't have success the first time around
against one of college baseball's most powerful lineups. He struck
out 10 in six innings, and he scattered nine hits. Trouble is, six
of them were scattered among the fans in the left and right field
seats.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, USC has rebounded impressively. The Trojans knocked
out top-seed Florida, 12-10, in 11 innings on Monday night, then
bounced Mississippi State, 7-1.
</P>
<P>
   For the Trojans to reach the College World Series championship
game for the 14th time - but first time in 20 years - they'll have
to whip LSU twice. And the Tigers have won 10 consecutive CWS
games, including their first two this year.
</P>
<P>
   But after three games, USC is the No. 1-hitting team in the
tournament, average-wise, at .352. The Trojans' Jason Lane and Brad
Ticehurst are 1-2 in total hits, with eight and seven,
respectively, and the Trojans lead in runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   LSU, though, has powered 14 home runs, twice as many as USC, and
in one fewer game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 2040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
