<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CHINA-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS HE WILL RENEW CHINA'S TRADING PRIVILEGES
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton announced on Wednesday that he
would renew China's trading privileges, signaling that he would not
back away from his policy of engagement despite the rising
congressional clamor over whether the Chinese government illegally
contributed to his campaign and used protected American technology
to improve its missiles.
</P>
<P>
   In a Rose Garden ceremony, Clinton argued that links with China
supported a range of American economic and security interests. And
he called trade ``a force for change in China, exposing China to
our ideas and our ideals, and integrating China into the global
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   While Congress is expected ultimately to approve China's trade
status after the president returns from a visit there later this
month, Republicans made clear on Wednesday that they intend to
exact a high political price. The House and Senate have 90 days in
which to reject Clinton's formal recommendation of what is known as
``most-favored-nation status'' for China.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of revoking the status _ the benefit that the United
States grants to almost every country in the world except those it
regards as terrorist states _ is one of the main instruments
Congress has used to show its displeasure with China over human
rights abuses and other problems. The threat has been raised
repeatedly through the Bush and Clinton administrations, although
the United States has never actually revoked the status.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the majority leader, has said he
is reconsidering his long-held support for extending the trade
status. Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, the House majority leader, said
on Wednesday: ``I think the current circumstances make this a very
difficult vote. While most of us embrace trade as something that's
healthy for the peoples of all countries, we really have a serious
group of national security concerns before us.''
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich threw his support behind renewing
China's trade privileges. ``Seeking to keep China open to the West
has proven to be the most effective way to advance our democratic
values in this turbulent region of the world,'' Gingrich wrote in a
letter to the president on Wednesday that was also signed by two
other Republicans, Reps. Bill Archer of Florida, the chairman of
the House Ways and Means Committee, and Philip Crane of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as they pledged to work with Clinton in a ``bipartisan
manner'' on China trade, the three congressmen indicated that they
would make the most of charges against him. Rehearsing what they
called disturbing accusations, they promised full investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have accused Clinton of risking American security by
permitting the Chinese to launch satellites for an American company
that contributed heavily to the Democrats. As a result, they argue
the Chinese may have been able to obtain technology that permitted
them to improve their missiles. Congressional committees and the
Justice Department are investigating whether the Chinese government
illegally contributed money to the Democrats during Clinton's
re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   As a candidate, Clinton derided the policy of engagement with
China, but as President he came to accept and then embrace it. On
Wednesday, he praised it as a means of assuring American security.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our engagement with China serves American interests,'' Clinton
said, citing ``stability in Asia, preventing the spread of weapons
of mass destruction, combatting international crime and drug
trafficking, protecting the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that cooperation with China had become even more
important in light of the nuclear standoff between India and
Pakistan. He appeared in the Rose Garden on Wednesday with
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who was preparing to depart
for a meeting in Geneva among five nuclear powers to discuss the
situation in South Asia. The meeting is to be chaired by China.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Warning that developing nuclear weapons would make the Indian
and Pakistani people ``poorer and less secure,'' the president
said, ``The international community must now come together to move
them to reverse course and to avoid a dangerous arms race in
Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, in a briefing at the State Department, Ms. Albright
acknowledged past Administration concern that the Chinese helped
Pakistan develop its nuclear capability. But she said that ``in
recent years they have changed their behavior vis-a-vis the
Pakistanis'' and ``are not providing any assistance to
unsafeguarded projects.''
</P>
<P>
   In their one-day meeting, the five nations _ the United States,
Britain, China, France, and Russia _ hope to draw up joint
proposals concerning India and Pakistan. The administration wants
to persuade both nations not to arm missiles with nuclear warheads
or to engage in more provocative rhetoric or military activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the most important thing both sides can do is to
cool it and take a deep breath and to begin to climb out of the
hole they have dug themselves into,'' Albright said in the Rose
Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Every president has renewed normal trade status with China since
it was first extended in 1980, and Congress has always gone along.
</P>
<P>
   American trade with China now amounts to about $75 billion a
year, with China vying with Japan as the nation contributing the
most to the American trade deficit. While the United States
imported $62.5 billion in goods from China last year, it exported
only $12.8 billion in goods.
</P>
<P>
   But American companies are jostling for a foothold in China in
hopes of exploiting its vast market, and they have put heavy
pressure on Congress to support the president's stance. American
business groups, such as the U.S. Chamber of Commerce and the
National Association of Manufacturers, were quick to support
renewing China's trade privileges on Wednesday. On the other side,
unlikely allies have coalesced, including labor unions and
conservative supporters of religious freedom and human rights.
</P>
<P>
   The China issue divides both political party. On Wednesday, Rep.
Dick Gephardt of Missouri, the House Democratic leader, declared
that he would once again oppose most-favored-nation status for
China.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must not reward the Chinese Communist government for
continuing political repression and tyranny,'' Gephardt said in a
statement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
