<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2971 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARCHDEACON-COLUMN04-C     06-03 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHDEACON-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Akinwande says ''I must do whatever is necessary to win``
 &HT;    Editors: This is Tom Archdeacon's column for Thursday's paper.
It replaces the column on the Cox budget slugged DONKING.
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK CITY _ It was like that old Wizard of Oz request: ``Pay
no attention to the man behind the curtain.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Henry Akinwande was being asked to do at a Madison
Square Garden training session for his heavyweight title fight
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The problem Wednesday afternoon was that Evander Holyfield was
the guy behind the curtain. The champ _ encamped in a sea of
television lights just 40 feet from the boxing ring in which
Akinwande was to spar _ was doing an hour's worth of national
satellite interviews and the TV folks didn't want him disturbed.
Worse, the lights around the ring had been shut off to assure an
appropriate background.
</P>
<P>
   To appease Akinwande's complaining manager, panicked Madison
Square Garden officials quickly erected a flimsy curtained barrier
near the ring and then tried convincing the challenger to train in
the dark. And that's about the time a Frenchman approached and
asked Akinwande to autograph a photo.
</P>
<P>
   As Akinwande began to sign, he noticed the image. It showed him
desperately clutching Lennox Lewis in the heavyweight title fight
last July where he was disqualified for excessive holding. It was
the lone _ but monumental _ stain in his career. He was hooted out
of the Nevada ring and back in England, headline writers who had
tagged him ``Henry the First'' changed it to ``Henry the Worst.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's reminder of that soured him even more. And the final
straw came while he was sparring. Looking up from a clinch, he saw
Holyfield _ already a 7-to-1 favorite _ peeking around the curtain
and laughing. By the time Akinwande's training was done, he was in
no mood to talk and let new trainer Emanuel Steward serve as his
mouthpiece:
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the pictures the guy could have handed him, it was from
that Lewis fight. Henry is upset because that's all people want to
talk about. So now he won't talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Akinwande did talk. ``People say I have no guts, that I
have no heart,' he said in a quiet voice steeped with a Nigerian
accent. ``They do not know what I've been through in my life. If
they did ,they would know how much I love this game, how much I've
sacrificed.''
</P>
<P>
   As the 6-foot-7 challenger told his story, you couldn't help but
like him _ as a person, not a guy about to pull a heavyweight
upset. Still, that's not saying he hasn't beaten the odds before.
He did with his dad.
</P>
<P>
   Akinwande was born in Dulwich, England, but his father _ whose
lucrative import-export business afforded the family a pair of
Mercedes Benz autos and college opportunities for the kids _ moved
the family back to Lagos, Nigeria when Henry was seven.
</P>
<P>
   Dad's plan was that Henry would go to college, then take over
the family business. Instead, when Akinwande was 14, he became
fascinated with boxing and secretly began working out. ``When my
dad found out, he nearly killed me,'' he said. ``He tried to have
the trainer arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Africa, the father says everything. It doesn't matter if
you're 30, 35 years old, if he says sit, you sit. No questions
asked. When I told him that I was not giving boxing up, that it was
the one place where I found peace, he told me I was no longer his
son. That's when I left home and when he told me not to come
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Akinwande went back to England and a rough part of south London.
He joined a boxing club and for a while lived in abandoned
buildings while subsisting on a loaf of bread a day. He got a job
at a fast food restaurant, then - donning the traditional green
uniforms and Dr. Suess stove pipe hat _ he manned an oversized
broom as a Trafalgar Square street sweeper.
</P>
<P>
   With a sculpted body, an unmatched 86-inch wingspan and a
noteworthy left jab, he began to make his mark in boxing. He made
the British Olympic team for the 1988 Games in Seoul, though he
didn't medal. Turning pro, he won his first 18 fights before Axel
Schultz managed a disputed draw in Germany. After that he
dispatched of the likes of Jimmy Thunder, Schultz in a rematch,
Tony Tucker, Jeremy Williams for the lesser known WBO heavyweight
crown, and Columbus' Alexander Zolkin.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, family friends stepped in and spoke to his
father. They convinced Joseph Akinwande, who hadn't seen his son in
five years, to relent. ``They told him, 'Look he's proved you
wrong. He's doing what he loves and making more money than those
people who studied to be doctors and engineers,''' Akinwande said.
``We got back together and now we talk like gentlemen. We're
friends, though my father still hates boxing and doesn't come to my
fights.''
</P>
<P>
   It's just as well his dad wasn't there for the failure against
Lewis in Lake Tahoe. After issuing repeated warnings for clutching
rather than fighting, referee Mills Lane had enough and
disqualified Akinwande, who could barely catch his breath and was
being heartily booed in the fifth round.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward Akinwande's trainer Don Turner _ who also co-trains
Holyfield _ was at a loss to explain his heavyweight's actions.
Since then some in Akinwande's camp has blamed his demise on the
altitude and neglect from Turner, whom they claimed treated the
challenger as a second-class citizen with Holyfield in the same
stable.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Lagos _ where Akinwande owns a home as he does in London
and Orlando _ he said friends waited for him in front of his home:
``They were crying. They were sure I was drugged.''
</P>
<P>
   With Turner committed to Holyfield for this fight, Akinwande has
spent the past seven weeks with Steward, who toughened him up at
his fabled Kronk Gym in Detroit. Although he said Steward has
taught him a lot, Akinwande said his best lesson came in the Lewis
fight:
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned I am not invincible, that I must do whatever is
necessary to win. If that means fight naked, that's how I'll do it.
That's how we did it when we were kids in Lagos. It's mental
tactics. You do what you have to to survive. On the streets I'd
take my shirt off and the guy might think I was crazy and run. And
if that didn't work, I'd take my pants off. And when they start
seeing your panties, they usually do run. Saturday I will do
whatever it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Which means the Madison Square Garden folks might want to keep
that portable curtain near the ring.
</P>
<P>
   CONTACT Tom Archdeacon at 225-2156 or by e-mail at
tom_archdeaconcoxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
