<HEADLINE>
PANEL NAMED TO URGE REFORMS IN ULSTER POLICE FORCE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN _ Responding to complaints from the Irish government,
Britain Wednesday announced the creation of an expanded commission
that will recommend reform of the Royal Ulster Constabulary,
Northern Ireland's police force.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen M. O'Toole, the Massachusetts secretary of public
safety, is one of the members of the commission which was created
by the Northern Ireland political settlement and which will be
chaired by Chris Patten, the last British governor of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   But the formal announcement of the commission and its members
was delayed for several days after the Irish government complained
that its list of candidates had been ignored. In response, the
British government added Gerald Lynch, an academic from John Jay
College in New York, who had been recommended by the Dublin
government.
</P>
<P>
   The British also decided to hold off from announcing the
commission's formation on Tuesday at the annual conference of the
Royal Ulster Constabulary, after Dublin suggested that doing so
would undermine nationalist confidence in the commission's
independence.
</P>
<P>
   But while the British added Lynch to the commission they also
added Peter Smith, a Belfast lawyer and a prominent Protestant
unionist who would be seen as sympathetic to the Royal Ulster
Constabulary, bringing the commission's membership to eight.
</P>
<P>
   Other commission members include Maurice Hayes, the former
Northern Ireland ombudsman; Lucy Woods, the chief of British
Telecom in Northern Ireland; Clifford Sheering, a criminologist at
the University of Toronto, and John Smith, former deputy
commissioner of the Metropolitan Police in London.
</P>
<P>
   Reform and restructuring of the nearly 13,000-member police
force is considered essential to cementing the political settlement
and helping to end 30 years of sustained sectarian and political
violence.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Ulster Constabulary is 93 percent Protestant, and the
biggest challenge facing administrators is how to downsize a force
that was just 3,000 when violence erupted in 1968 while also
increasing Catholic representation on, and confidence in, the
force.
</P>
<P>
   In no other area is the gap between Catholic nationalists and
Protestant unionists in Northern Ireland more evident than in
attitudes toward the RUC. Protestants strongly support the RUC and
are deeply suspicious of attempts to reform it.
</P>
<P>
   Many Catholics, however, have had negative experiences with the
RUC. Some Catholics want the RUC disbanded. But even those who
think disbanding the force is unrealistic want it reformed and want
its ranks to more closely reflect the 43 percent of the population
that is Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   The April 10 accord acknowledged the need to change the RUC, and
established an independent commission to recommend how to ``ensure
that policing arrangements, including composition, recruitment,
training, culture, ethos and symbols, are such that in a new
approach, Northern Ireland has a police service that can enjoy
widespread support from, and is seen as an integral part of, the
community as a whole.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
