<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAM BAFFERT ARRIVES, READY TO WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEBBIE ARRINGTON  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. &UR;  &LR; _ With a full police escort worthy of VIPs, Team
Baffert rolled into Belmont Park late Wednesday morning, ready for
its assault on the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet, the convoy's most important passenger, took the pony
paparazzi in stride as he walked confidently off the horse van
before some 150 reporters and photographers. With his dappled coat
gleaming like bronze, the bay colt looked fresh and ready to
rumble.
</P>
<P>
   After a two-hour flight from Louisville, Real Quiet looked happy
to be back on the ground and in a barn. The Kentucky Derby and
Preakness champion playfully tried to kick trainer and co-passenger
Bob Baffert before being led into a stall.
</P>
<P>
   Also making the flight aboard the chartered 727 were owner Mike
Pegram and jockey Kent Desormeaux. ``We're just along for the
ride,'' joked Pegram.
</P>
<P>
   Jockeys usually don't arrive days early, even for a race as
important as Saturday's Belmont, when Real Quiet will attempt to
win the first Triple Crown in 20 years. And they certainly don't
travel with the horse. But Pegram convinced Desormeaux that the
occasion was special enough to make the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Mike gave me the invitation, he told me that no jockey
had ever realized that, the opportunity to arrive with the horse,''
said Desormeaux, who had never flown on a horse plane before. ``I
felt like we were back in the early 1900s when the whole clan jumps
on the train to ride to the next town.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Baffert and Pegram suffer from severe allergies and riding
in a plane decked out in hay for the horse didn't help. ``The horse
took the flight a lot better than I did,'' said Pegram, who could
barely talk. ``I lost my voice, but he didn't turn a hair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What a nerve-wracking experience!'' added Desormeaux. ``And
the horse -- his ears rubbed the roof the entire flight. It's not a
natural situation for him. Somehow he managed to keep his balance
during turbulence.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert flew the whole trip in the cockpit to get away from the
hay. ``Real Quiet is a cool customer,'' he said. ``Nothing bothers
him. He acted like a big kid, looking around. But he looks like 5
million bucks.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the size of the bonus, kicked in by Visa, that goes with
winning a Triple Crown. On Wednesday, Desormeaux sported a new
button: ``Go Fish for $5 million!'' Baffert dubbed the
narrow-framed Real Quiet the Fish shortly after he got him.
</P>
<P>
   Jockey Gary Stevens guaranteed the media last year that he'd win
the Triple Crown aboard Silver Charm, but finished just short of
that goal.
</P>
<P>
   Desormeaux wouldn't make that same claim, but came close. ``I'm
98 percent sure we'll win,'' he said. ``So many simple things can
go wrong. He could stumble leaving the gate. There's no guarantee,
but I am extremely confident. I just want to be in that winner's
circle with Mike and Bob and get that bonus for these two guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet will be ready to do his part, assured Baffert. ``He's
healthy and happy. He's ready to run.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Team Baffert waits for its Saturday date with
destiny. Some 200 family members and guests - including about 50
Bafferts -- were expected to arrive by Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   While Baffert supervises the horse, the family are headed to
Broadway to see Disney's stage version of ``The Lion King.'' Friday
night, Baffert will take time out for the kids and a Yankees game,
where he'll throw out the first ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``My oldest son Taylor is really excited about that,'' said
Baffert, who had the same honor last year. ``He tells me, `Dad,
people think I'm a celebrity now, too.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 2042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
