<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0439 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2975 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXCLUSIVE-RUSSIAN-MOL     06-03 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXCLUSIVE-RUSSIAN-MOLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASE OF ACCUSED MOLE STRAINS RELATIONS BETWEEN CIA AND GERMANY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EXCLUSIVE; 10:45 p.m. ET EMBARGO for print media; 12:01 a.m. ET
EMBARGO for electronic media.) 
(mk) 
 By JAMES RISEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When messages filtering out of Russia reached the
headquarters of German intelligence earlier this year, alarm bells
began to sound throughout the upper reaches of the German
government. Russian intelligence sources had delivered shocking
news: The German official charged with rooting out spies was
himself a Russian spy _ Moscow's leading mole in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Volker Foertsch, was subjected to a prolonged
investigation. His home was searched and a video camera placed in
his office. Later he was put on annual leave. After the
investigation, German prosecutors concluded that they did not have
enough evidence to charge him with espionage.
</P>
<P>
   The 63-year-old Foertsch _ a widely-respected career
intelligence officer known by his alias, ``Fleming'' _ resumed his
duties as head of counter-intelligence in May, and the German
government pronounced him exonerated.
</P>
<P>
   But that finding has not put an end to the controversy
surrounding the Foertsch matter in either Germany or the United
States, where the case has raised troubling new questions at the
CIA about the possible betrayal of U.S. secrets.
</P>
<P>
   CIA officials have been left to wonder if German intelligence,
which was regularly compromised by communist agents during the Cold
War, is once again being infiltrated by Moscow. CIA officials say
Russia has never stopped spying on the United States and European
countries despite the collapse of the Soviet Union, and may be
rebuilding its spy network for the post-Cold War period.
</P>
<P>
   German intelligence officials acknowledge that they are
continuing to investigate a series of unexplained failures of
German intelligence operations and that they are convinced that
material from its spy agency has been handed over to Moscow,
according to recent German press accounts.
</P>
<P>
   With so much intriguing, if contradictory, bits of information,
the truth behind the Foertsch affair now appears lost in the
wilderness of mirrors that so often bedevils major espionage cases.
U.S. intelligence officials trying to fathom the case must try to
determine whether Foertsch is indeed a Russian mole or the innocent
victim of the vicious internal politics that have long plagued
German intelligence. The German decision to allow Foertsch to
return to his job relatively quickly has only added to the mystery
surrounding the case.
</P>
<P>
   Foertsch's supporters in German intelligence believe the
allegations against him were without merit and expressed anger that
the case was ever referred to German prosecutors, according to
recent German press accounts. They have speculated that he has
either been vicitimized by political adversaries or has been
targeted by a sophisticated Russian disinformation campaign
designed to paralyze the German spy service.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is that if Foertsch is not a mole, then
someone else at the agency, known as the BND, mght be handing over
information while attention is focused on Foertsch.
</P>
<P>
   Foertsch returned to his job on May 18 after prosecutors in
Karlsruhe were unable to develop any solid evidence to substantiate
the charges leveled against him, German officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials were reluctant to discuss the
case publicly. A State Department spokesman stressed that the case
is an internal German matter, adding that it is premature to
determine whether it will have any impact on U.S.-German relations.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. intelligence officials also refused to discuss publicly
either the nature or the extent of their discussions with the
Germans about the Foertsch case. But the CIA has a longstanding
liaison relationship with German intelligence, and if the
allegations of a high-level penetration of the BND prove true, old
fears will be revived in Washington about the dangers of trusting
Germany with American secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Cold War, the Stasi, the East German secret
service, along with the KGB in the Soviet Union, feasted on West
Germany, recruiting spies from among its military, intelligence and
political officials. Those German spies sometimes gave the Soviet
Union valuable insights into NATO, but American intelligence
officials learned early on in the post-World War II era to be wary
about which secrets they could share with the Germans. The BND has
``a history of penetration, and the truth is we have never really
taken them too seriously as an intelligence organization,'' said
one American intelligence official.
</P>
<P>
   Such American fears began to recede in the post-Cold War era,
once the CIA and German intelligence obtained the old files of the
Stasi, enabling the German government to eliminate old communist
moles.
</P>
<P>
   But the Foertsch controversy is the latest in a series of recent
incidents that have begun to place new strains on the relationship
between the German and American intelligence services.
</P>
<P>
   While Germany's sieve-like security has long concerned the CIA,
Germany has begun to tire of its traditional role as a playground
for American spies fighting Russia and other adversaries. Just last
year Germany ordered a CIA officer to leave the country after being
caught trying to recruit a German government official as an
American spy. The German action came after years of quiet reminders
by Bonn to Washington that the Cold War was over and that it was
time for the CIA to reduce its presence in the country.
</P>
<P>
   But even given such problems in their relationship, Germany
remains one of the CIA's most important bases of operation for
American espionage. Now, however, the CIA uses Germany not as a
staging area for spy attacks on Eastern Europe, but against
post-Cold War adversaries in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   American officials say that one of the CIA's largest overseas
bases is in Frankfurt, Germany, where agency officials supervise
clandestine espionage operations targeted against countries like
Iran, Iraq and Libya.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 2044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
