<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0441 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2981 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONSANTO-MARKETPLACE-     06-03 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONSANTO-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: CUISINART OF PHONE TECHNOLOGY FAILS TO WHIP UP
ENTHUSIASM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Pa., Calif., N.J.) (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(af) 
 By REED ABELSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Call it the mystery of the vanishing premium.
Typically, when a company is taken over, shareholders get a fat
premium over the current stock price in order to entice them to
sell.
</P>
<P>
   But this week, shareholders of the Monsanto Co. were offered a
mere 19 cents a share over Monsanto's stock price of $55.375 to
fall into the arms of American Home Products, the big
pharmaceuticals company. Though another bidder may emerge, and a
shareholder suit was filed Tuesday seeking to block the deal,
investors seem likely to go along.
</P>
<P>
   Acquirers are rarely tightwads. The average premium paid,
calculated before the target company's stock price reflects some
speculation about a possible deal, is about 30 percent, according
to Houlihan Lokey Howard &AMP; Zukin, an investment banking firm in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Only three of the 25 largest combinations in the United States
have involved no premium to the current stock price, according to
the Securities Data Co. of Newark. In addition to the
Monsanto-American Home Products deal, Nationsbank's proposed
acquisition of BankAmerica, announced in April, and Bell Atlantic's
takeover of Nynex two years ago were for prices at or below the
market values of the companies the day before the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   For these companies, it seems, the premium is not missing but
simply misplaced. All three stocks had been driven up by investors
who guessed that a deal of some nature was in the works.
</P>
<P>
   In some instances, shareholders agree to accept little or no
premium because they do not have other options, and the executives
of the acquiring companies, who are using their own high-priced
stock to pay for these deals, may be reluctant to pay more for fear
of putting their own shares in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The higher the premium, the more risk you build in,''
explained Mark L. Sirower, a professor at New York University, who
has written a book on acquisitions. By paying a higher premium, a
company incorporates even more of investors' performance
expectations into its current stock price. If the deal does not
work out, the stock is likely to drop sharply.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Monsanto, for example, the stock had already run
up significantly by the time the deal was announced, according to
Donald V. Smith, a senior managing director of Houlihan Lokey. If
one calculates the premium before the move up last year, American
Home Products' bid represents a premium of roughly 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Both BankAmerica and Nynex had also benefited from investors'
expectations that a deal might be in the offing. BankAmerica had
traded in the low 60s in January before shooting up to the $86.50
Nationsbank offered, and Nynex had seen its shares increase almost
7 percent in the four months before Bell Atlantic announced its
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Surging stock prices over all have helped bring premiums down,
according to Smith. In the late 1980s, his firm calculates that
shareholders were paid premiums that averaged 50 percent or more
when their companies were taken over. Investors in RJR Nabisco
received nearly twice the value of their stock in 1988, for
example.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, shareholders may simply not be able to get anything
more for their stock. The company may be in some difficulty or need
to combine. In the case of Nynex, one of the regional Bell
operating companies, it was clear that no other bidders were
waiting in the wings willing to pay more, according to Harbir
Singh, a management professor at the University of Pennyslyvania.
What's more, both companies would have been worse off without the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Monsanto, the company and its board may have
decided that American Home's bid was the highest it would receive
even if it was somewhat below the stock's recent high of nearly
$59.
</P>
<P>
   ``Premiums are only a reflection of what people are willing to
pay on an absolute basis,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   But the lack of a premium does not necessarily indicate that the
acquiring company is getting a bargain. Monsanto, despite its
promising ventures in biotechnology, was hardly a cheap stock,
trading around 118 times its trailing earnings for each share.
</P>
<P>
   The management of American Home ``could not have afforded to pay
a higher price,'' said Tom Burnett, the director of Merger Insight,
a New York research firm. Even without a premium, the deal is
already expected to dilute American Home Products' earnings by as
much as 15 percent the first year and somewhat less the following
year.
</P>
<P>
   And even when companies don't pay a premium, the transaction can
be a disaster, Sirower of New York University noted. He cited the
Quaker Oats acquisition of Snapple, the iced-tea and juice company,
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Though Quaker did not pay a premium for the company, Snapple
lost $100 million in 1995 and continued to struggle. Last year,
Quaker sold it for $300 million, about $1.4 billion less than it
had paid for it.
</P>
<P>
   How investors react to the news on the day of the announcement
is a good indication of whether the acquiring company is
overpaying, according to Sirower. When SBC Communications paid a 27
percent premium for the Pacific Telesis Group two years ago, for
example, SBC's stock sank about 5 percent, signaling that the price
was too high.
</P>
<P>
   What about the Monsanto deal? American Home Products' stock
barely moved, gaining less than $1 to close on Monday at $49.25.
The company may not have paid a premium, but investors were in no
hurry to conclude that American Home was getting a steal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
