A2980 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUELINGEVANGELISTS-TE     06-03 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUELINGEVANGELISTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVANGELISTS PREACHING TO EVANGELISTS IN SALT LAKE CITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Consider it a theological shootout between two of the country's
most avidly evangelical faiths.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, thousands of Southern Baptists armed with books
and videos challenging Mormon beliefs will sweep into Salt Lake
City to combine their annual convention with a door-to-door blitz
seeking to convert Mormons.
</P>
<P>
   The Mormons, secure in their own religious heartland, plan to
welcome the Baptists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to do everything we can do to make them feel at
home. These are our brethren and sisters,'' said Gordon B. Hinkley,
the Mormon president and highest prophet of the 10 million-member
church.
</P>
<P>
   The Baptist blitz will come before and during the Southern
Baptist Convention, to be held June 9-11 in the city where half the
residents say they are members of the Church of Jesus Christ of
Latter-day Saints.
</P>
<P>
   Anson Shupe, a well-known writer on American religion and a
sociology professor at Indiana University-Purdue University in Fort
Wayne, said some wonder why Southern Baptists would venture into
the Mormon stronghold.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a bunch of mongoose going into cobra territory,''
Shupe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a symbolic face-off of sorts,'' he said. ``But I think
Mormons will be polite hosts. It's their chance to show how
Christian they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Baptists, he said, will have their say and come away feeling
good about having made their point. And they won't be converted by
the devout Mormons they meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baptists aren't going to suddenly see the light and soften
their beliefs,'' Shupe said. ``Neither will the Mormons.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Crossover Salt Lake City'' evangelism effort is expected
to draw more than 3,000 Baptists _ including 500 college students _
for door-to-door witnessing, block parties, special musical events,
dramas and sports programs planned to entice converts, said the
Rev. Mike Gray, a Salt Lake City Baptist pastor and one of the
local coordinators.
</P>
<P>
   Baptist TV spots, billboard messages, newspaper ads, offers of
religious literature and a free Jesus video will be a part of the
mix.
</P>
<P>
   Hinkley urged his fellow believers to prove themselves to the
visiting Baptists.
</P>
<P>
   ``They accuse us of not being Christian,'' he said. ``I hope
that our people will try to show them, by the very manner in which
they act, that they are truly disciples of the Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray, pastor of the 1,400-member Southeast Baptist Church, the
largest Baptist church in Utah, said the influx is catching the
attention of the state where Mormons are predominant.
</P>
<P>
   An editorial cartoon in a Utah newspaper recently proclaimed:
``The Baptists Are Coming _ The Baptists Are Coming,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like the 15.9 million-member Southern Baptist denomination, the
Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints focuses on winning
converts.
</P>
<P>
   The Latter-day Saints, nicknamed Mormons because they hold as
sacred the teachings of ``The Book of Mormon,'' have 58,000 young
male and female missionaries who witness door-to-door worldwide.
The latest Mormon reports say the church averages 950 new members a
day.
</P>
<P>
   One reason that Southern Baptists say Mormons are not Christian
is because they do not rely solely on the Bible as their standard
of faith.
</P>
<P>
   Mormons base their faith on the Bible and other religious
writings, such as the ``The Book of Mormon,'' which is held to be
another testament of Jesus Christ as translated by church founder
Joseph Smith from gold tablets he said an angel revealed to him.
</P>
<P>
   Two other books, ``The Pearl of Great Price'' and ``The Doctrine
of the Covenants,'' are also used in Mormon teachings.
</P>
<P>
   One of the big differences between the Mormon doctrine and that
of some other Christian denominations is that Latter-day Saints
believe God still speaks to human prophets, just as he did in
ancient Israel, said Stephen D. Posey, president of the
Euless-based office for Mormon missionaries who work in the Fort
Worth area, far West Texas and parts of New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Heavens are not closed,'' Posey said. ``God spoke to
Joseph Smith and each successive prophet of the church, even Gordon
B. Hinkley.''
</P>
<P>
   Baptists and Mormons agree on many lifestyle and social issues;
both decry the drinking of alcoholic beverages and oppose abortion
and pornography.
</P>
<P>
   Shupe said the excursion to Salt Lake City is part of a trend in
recent years in which the Southern Baptist denomination has chosen
convention sites where they could make a symbolic statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They even met in Las Vegas,'' where they marched through ``The
Strip'' gambling district, Shupe said. ``If Sodom and Gomorrah
still existed, you can bet Baptists would book a convention
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Baptists decided several years ago to meet in Salt Lake City as
a means of boosting what they call their ``pioneer'' work in the
western states. The ``crossover'' campaigns have been held along
with national conventions for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Baptists say they are just following biblical commands to share
their faith.
</P>
<P>
   Mormons ``are not Christian as we see it,'' said the Rev. Claude
Thomas, pastor of the First Baptist Church of Euless and president
of the Southern Baptist Pastors Conference. Thomas said more than
100 volunteers from his church will be working in the evangelism
push.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said the Mormons shouldn't be offended.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have missionaries proselytizing all over the world. I
would think they would give us the same latitude.''
</P>
<P>
   The Southern Baptists started pointing toward the Salt Lake City
convention last year at their convention in Dallas with the first
showing of ``The Mormon Puzzle,'' a video that has been sent to
about 40,000 Baptist churches.
</P>
<P>
   It quotes Mormon leaders' statements about their beliefs but
adds commentaries from Southern Baptist leaders saying that Mormons
are not true Christians.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, R. Philip Roberts, , director of the Interfaith
Witness Division of the Baptist North American Mission Board in
Alpharetta, Ga., has written ``Mormonism Unmasked.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts contends that Mormons try to deceive people into
believing they are orthodox Christians. His book is filled with
advice to Baptists on how to approach Mormons.
</P>
<P>
   ``In seeking to win Mormons to Christ, don't get involved in
discussing temple undergarments or secret handshakes or the hidden
and sordid secrets of the life of Joseph Smith,'' he writes.
``Sharing the gospel must take priority over all other elements of
discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   He ends his book with the paragraph: ``Keep lovingly pointing
Mormons to the Christ of the Bible's gospel. In him they will find
the salvation that eludes them and yet is so near.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 2047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
