<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0443 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2982 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-ELECT-500(2TAKE     06-03 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-ELECT-500(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIANS SELECT EXPERIENCED CANDIDATES, REJECT BILINGUAL
EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CALIF-LABOR) 
(th) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Despite record spending by a handful of wealthy
candidates, Californians embraced the established political order
in their primary election on Tuesday, and set the stage for a fall
contest between two conventional career politicians, Democratic Lt.
Gov. Gray Davis and Republican state Attorney General Dan Lungren.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the signs of contentment with the status quo, voters
sent a powerful signal of discontent with the once renowned
California public schools, decisively passing a ballot measure to
curtail three decades of bilingual instruction.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative was opposed by President Clinton and much of the
state's educational establishment, and Wednesday a coalition of
civil rights groups announced that they had filed suit to block it
as unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the overwhelming message was one of relative satisfaction
in a state that has rebounded sharply from economic and natural
disasters, with two-thirds of voters saying California was
generally moving in the right direction, according to surveys of
voters leaving the polls by The Los Angeles Times and CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Davis defeated his richer Democratic rivals, who drew heavily on
their personal fortunes to make their campaigns, by a margin of
nearly 3 to 1, and even ran just slightly ahead of Lungren, who
faced no real opposition for his party's nomination Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A similar dynamic emerged in the race for the Republican Senate
nomination, where State Treasurer Matthew Fong staved off a
self-financed $10 million challenge from Darrell Issa, a
multimillionaire car alarm manufacturer, to win the right to
challenge U.S. Sen. Barbara Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think collectively Californians are saying, `Don't rock the
boat,''' said Mark DiCamillo, director of the statewide Field Poll
in San Francisco. ``They do want to make some changes in the
direction of the state, but pretty much they're not looking for
radical change this year, and that has a lot to do with the health
of the state's economy after years of problems. Cautious optimism
is the byword now.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a striking comeback for Davis, 55. Just months ago his
candidacy was dismissed by many party insiders and pundits, who
argued that he could not hope to compete against Al Checchi, a
multimillionaire businessman who was making his first run for
elective office and spent some $40 million of his own money, the
U.S. record for a non presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   That worked out to about $59 a vote for Checchi, compared to
about $5 a vote for Davis, who still managed to at least tie the
old record of $9 million for spending in a gubernatorial primary
here. Ms. Harman spent about $16 million, most of it her own money,
for about $24 a vote.
</P>
<P>
   But Checchi's campaign was Wednesday widely viewed as a
cautionary tale about the limits of seemingly limitless spending,
and the danger that by attacking one candidate in a three-candidate
field, as he did with Ms. Harman, an opening is created for the
third candidate to emerge unscathed _ i.e., Davis.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the state, it was mostly a day of triumph for
familiar faces, including former Gov. Jerry Brown, who won 59
percent of the vote to become mayor of Oakland without a runoff,
and for former Rep. Robert Dornan of Orange County, who easily
defeated two Republican rivals to win the nomination to challenge
Rep. Loretta Sanchez, the Democrat who defeated him in 1996 by just
984 votes.
</P>
<P>
   The sole incumbent to lose his seat was Rep. Jay Kim, a
Republican from Diamond Bar, who pleaded guilty last year to
accepting illegal campaign donations and had to campaign
long-distance from Washington, where he must wear an electronic
surveillance device. He was defeated for the nomination by state
Assemblyman Gary Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amateur hour is over,'' Mark Mellman, a veteran Democratic
pollsters, said of the voters' preference for experienced
politicians over untried newcomers, a sharp contrast with the
zeitgeist of the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   With 99 percent of precincts reporting in unofficial returns,
Davis had 1,880,030 votes, or 35 percent of the total cast in the
state's new open primary, in which the names of all candidates
appeared on the same ballot regardless of party.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren had 1,830,591 votes, or 34 percent, with Checchi
trailing with 682,012, or 13 percent, just ahead of another
self-financed millionaire, Rep. Jane Harman of south suburban Los
Angeles, who drew 663,151 votes, or 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' strikingly strong finish could be a bad omen for Lungren,
51, a former conservative congressman from Long Beach who enjoys
support from the state's Republican establishment, but could not
manage to muster stronger turnout in the primary, despite spending
some $4 million, most of it on television advertising, in an effort
to establish a presence against the Democrats' early attacks.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, surveys of voters leaving the polls showed
that nearly two-thirds think it is time for a change in control of
the governor's office, which has been held by Republicans for the
last 16 years, and for 24 of the past 32 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am overwhelmed by the vote last night,'' Davis told
supporters at a brief Democratic unity rally Wednesday morning in
downtown Los Angeles, at which Checchi and Ms. Harman both pledged
their support in the fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But he added: ``I'm under no illusions. This will be a real
challenge and we'll be tested time and again.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate race, Fong, 43, the state treasurer since 1995,
defeated Issa by a margin of 22 percent to 19 percent, or 1,158,391
votes to 1,028,682. Boxer, the Democratic incumbent, drew more
votes than both her rivals combined, or 2,322,517 for 44 percent of
the total.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, according to the voter surveys, Democrats appeared to
turn out in disproportionately higher numbers than Republicans,
with nearly four in 10 voters belonging to union households,
according to The Los Angeles Times/CNN survey.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats were apparently energized by the campaign against the
union dues ballot measure, in contrast to the last statewide
gubernatorial primary, in which both parties turned out equally.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just extraordinary union turnout,'' said Bill Carrick,
a veteran Democratic strategist who worked for Ms. Harman this year
and said he did not believe labor had turned out in such force here
since a right-to-work measure was on the ballot 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' strategists, taking a gentle victory lap at the party
rally Wednesday morning, said their surveys had repeatedly shown
throughout the year that Davis' 23 years' experience in state
government _ beginning as chief of staff to Brown _ would resonate
with voters once he got his own message (``Experience Money Can't
Buy'') out over the blizzard of Checchi's television commercials,
many of which harshly attacked Ms. Harman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was what the voters were looking for,'' said Davis' media
consultant, David Doak. ``Sometimes voters just get in a mood, and
I told him months ago, `They're in the mood for you.'''
</P>
<P>
   The one thing voters seemed determined to change was the
existing system of bilingual education, in which non-native English
speakers are taught basic subjects in their native tongue while
also learning English.
</P>
<P>
   The program, a legacy of the civil rights movement of the 1960s,
has been widely denounced as ineffective in preparing a huge new
generation of immigrant children for the job market, and
pre-election polls had shown majorities of all ethnic and racial
groups supporting it, despite the opposition of much of the state's
political leadership, including all four gubernatorial candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The measure won 61 percent to 39 percent in unofficial returns,
though black and Hispanic support for it fell below 50 percent.
According to The Los Angeles Times/CNN survey, fewer than four in
10 Hispanic voters backed the measure, and just under half of
blacks, while nearly six in 10 Asian voters and nearly seven in 10
whites supported it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won a tremendous victory against overwhelming obstacles,''
said Ron Unz, a multimillionaire software entrepreneur from Silicon
Valley who sponsored the measure, which would essentially limit
non-English speakers to one intensive year of instruction. ``The
California immigrant population has also won a victory.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday morning, a group of Hispanic and civil rights
groups announced that they had already filed suit in San Francisco
to block the measure as unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Litigation has become a routine tool against many of the ballot
measures passed in the state in recent years, with some of them,
like Proposition 187, the 1994 measure that cut off benefits for
legal immigrants, still tied up in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents, including immigrant parents, should have the right to
make basic choices about their children's education,'' said Deborah
Escobedo, a lawyer with Multicultural Education, Training and
Advocacy, one of the groups that sued Wednesday. ``All children,
including immigrant children, should have the right to learn
academic English and have access to science, math and history.
Proposition 227 takes away these basic rights.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
