<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMENDMENT-RELIGION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE VOTES ON AMENDMENT TO ALLOW PRAYER IN SCHOOLS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Reflecting House Republicans' promises to promote
legislation important to conservatives, the chamber will vote
Thursday on a constitutional amendment that would reverse decades
of Supreme Court rulings defining the separation of church and
state.
</P>
<P>
   The Religious Freedom Amendment is expected to fall far short of
the two-thirds majority, or about 290 votes, needed to pass. But
supporters Wednesday hailed Thursday's vote as a significant step.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased. We're very excited about this,'' said Jeff
Taylor of the Christian Coalition. ``If we don't get the
two-thirds, we'll bring it up again and build on the momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   This will be the first vote in 27 years on a school prayer
constitutional amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment would make it easier for public school students to
participate in voluntary prayers, and would allow the display of
religious symbols on public property and the use of public money to
pay for religious school education. Opposing the measure are
President Clinton and a coalition of civil liberties and religious
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in his radio address on Saturday, called amending the
constitution ``the wrong way'' to go.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Richard Armey, Republican of Texas, said
Wednesday, ``Any time you are trying to amend the Constitution, you
might expect to have to vote more than once before you get the
two-thirds.'' He said the amendment is being brought up for a vote
despite the long odds of success to generate ``a serious national
discussion'' on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Americans United for Separation of Church and State, a
Washington-based group, said it had solicited 185 firm ``no'' votes
on the amendment, enough to keep the amendment well short of
passage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's appalling,'' said the Rev. Barry W. Lynn, director of the
group, ``that congressional leaders would allow TV preacher Pat
Robertson and other Religious Right extremists to attempt a radical
rewrite of the Bill of Rights.''
</P>
<P>
   But Representative Ernest J. Istook Jr., an Oklahoma Republican
and author of the measure, said a constitutional amendment is
needed to ``correct'' Supreme Court decisions that he blamed for a
deterioration of moral standards in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``As prayer has gone out of school, guns, drugs, and gangs have
gone in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carman, a popular Christian singer, presented Istook Wednesday
with 32 cardboard boxes containing 1 million signatures gathered
from fans at his concerts in support of the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we took God out of the classroom, we had to put metal
detectors at the doors,'' said Carman, a Trenton, N.J., native who
fills football stadiums on his evangelical crusades.
</P>
<P>
   He said the first Supreme Court ruling that banned a school
prayer in New York in 1962 coincided with an increase in divorce,
adultery, sexually transmitted diseases, unwed mothers, sexual
abuse of children, and violent crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like something supernatural took place,'' he said.
``Something is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote is one of a variety of steps taken by Republican
leaders to appeal to social conservatives, who make up a critical
part of the GOP base in a congressional election year.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, Republican leaders formed a Values Action Team
headed by Pennsylvania Representative Joseph Pitts to coordinate
legislative strategy with conservative groups that included the
Christian Coalition, the Family Research Council, and the National
Right to Life Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The school prayer amendment was one of three top priorities. The
others were abolishing the National Endowment for the Arts and
outlawing the medical procedure that critics call ``partial-birth
abortion.'' Clinton vetoed the abortion ban last year, and an
override vote is scheduled later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must never forget this country was founded by forefathers
who were seeking freedom of religion, not freedom from religion,''
Pitts said Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
