<HEADLINE>
JERRY BROWN WINS OAKLAND'S MAYORAL PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CALIF-ELECT, CALIF-OAKLAND) 
(af) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ When the moment came, Jerry Brown's reaction
was every bit as unusual as both his candidacy and the al fresco
victory celebration that concluded it, which featured 500 pounds of
sizzling barbecue and a performance by a rock band called the Naked
Barbies.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a strangely blank expression, Brown refused to
acknowledge his election as Oakland's next mayor, even though
three-quarters of the precincts had reported and he had received
close to 60 percent of their vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really looks good,'' Brown deadpanned as the clock ticked
past midnight into the first minutes of this morning. ``I wouldn't
bet against me.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, pressed by reporters to declare victory in the
time-honored fashion, he replied: ``That's an old ritual. We're
trying to break new ground in Oakland.''
</P>
<P>
   Never one to conform to expectations, Brown was not about to
start doing so early Wednesday, when it became clear that he had
capped one of the oddest acts of political resurrection in many
years by capturing so much of the vote in the mayoral primary here
that he did not have to face a November runoff against any of his
10 opponents.
</P>
<P>
   His unusual demeanor at an unusual street party underscored that
Edmund G. Brown Jr., former two-term governor of California and
three-time presidential candidate, will be a mayor unlike any that
Oakland, the state's seventh-most-populous city, has ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks and days leading up to the primary, voters said
they wanted a mayor with visibility, someone who could tug Oakland
out of San Francisco's shadow and attract national attention.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's schedule Wednesday suggested that Oaklanders might be
getting exactly that. He awoke at 3:35 a.m. for an appearance on
``Good Morning, America,'' followed by interviews with CNN, MSNBC
and CNBC.
</P>
<P>
   It was an itinerary worthy of a new governor or senator, and an
echo of the way Brown's political celebrity allowed him to dominate
news coverage of the mayoral race from the moment he announced his
candidacy in November.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his opponents said they never really had a chance, so
intrigued were reporters by Brown's surprising courtship of Oakland
and so flattered were Oaklanders by his entreaties.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was so much noise, the rest of us were never heard,''
said Ed Blakely, an urban planning professor, who finished second
in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Blakely's campaign coordinator, Laura Ingram, put it more
succinctly: ``This has been like running against Elvis.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown won 58.7 percent of the vote, four times Blakely's 14.9
percent. Under the rules of Oakland's nonpartisan mayoral primary,
a candidate needed more than 50 percent to avoid a runoff in
November.
</P>
<P>
   By easily clearing that hurdle to become the first white
candidate to win a mayoral race here in two decades, Brown
demonstrated just how frustrated Oaklanders were with their city's
persistent problems and troubled image and how willing they were to
put their faith in a relative newcomer.
</P>
<P>
   Along with several friends and associates, Brown moved into a
three-story tin-shelled loft opposite the Amtrak station in
downtown Oakland just three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Elihu Harris, the city's current mayor, who did not seek
re-election, said he worried that Oaklanders were expecting a quick
fix from Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are looking for a change that is so rapid as to
perhaps be unrealistic, that all of a sudden you can heal the sick,
educate the illiterate, that all those things can happen simply by
electing a mayor,'' Harris said late Tuesday night when he stopped
by the noisy party outside Brown's loft to congratulate him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to have to deal with the nitty-gritty reality of a
city with resource problems and very complex demands,'' Harris
warned.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, 60, who will take office in January, said he understood
that. ``It's very daunting,'' he acknowledged early Wednesday
morning, when he finally had to own up to his resounding victory.
</P>
<P>
   He added that there was nothing harder than tackling entrenched
urban problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a reason why the major politicians in the country stay
out of the cities and deal with globalization and Pakistan and all
these other issues,'' he said. ``Because they're easier.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, while his close aides milled in the loft's
downstairs near a large red circle on the floor that signifies
unity, hundreds of people outside gobbled pork ribs and hot dogs. A
large stage accommodated not only the Naked Barbies, who sang a
dirge about the special agony of losing a dog, but also several
follow-up acts, including a troupe that performed West African
dance and a rap group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry Brown _ it's all love, it's all support, it's all
positive!'' one of the rappers shouted. ``Grass roots, baby!''
</P>
<P>
   Brown shooed away questions about whether, as his opponents
sometimes contended, the Oakland mayoralty was simply a way for him
to get back into the political game after 15 years out of elective
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's putting the horse before the cart,'' Brown said. It was
unclear whether he was bungling the order of the words or being
mischievous.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
