<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2990 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TIMBER-SUBSIDIES-500&AMP;     06-03 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMBER-SUBSIDIES-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE REPUBLICANS AGREE TO END A TIMBER SUBSIDY 
</HEADLINE>
  (dc) 
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After years of bitter debate over logging on public
lands, House Republican leaders have agreed to end one of the
federal government's longstanding subsidies for the timber
industry.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, timber companies that harvest logs from national
forests have been able to offset the costs of roads that they first
must carve into the woods. In compensation for those road-building
expenses, the Forest Service has given the companies credits that
have been used to reduce the price for trees taken from public
lands.
</P>
<P>
   For years, environmental advocates and opponents of government
subsidies for businesses have fought the practice as economically
wasteful and ecologically foolhardy.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement, which linked logging and road building in a
rebate system in which money spent on roads could be counted as
partial payment for timber, was seen by environmental advocates as
reinforcing two activities that wreak compound damage on forests.
Quite apart from the logging, the forest roads break up wildlife
habitat and promote erosion that scars the land and fills clean
streams with sediment, environmental groups say.
</P>
<P>
   Republican lawmakers on both sides of the debate have decided it
was time to concede victory to the industry's opponents and to
accept the Clinton administration's proposals to end the subsidy
program, which is known as the timber purchaser road credit.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the compromise, which aides said was endorsed by
House Speaker Newt Gingrich, the two sides agreed not to propose or
support any other amendments relating to forestry when the annual
spending bill that pays for the Forest Service's operations comes
to the floor this summer.
</P>
<P>
   This tactic is designed to foreclose an effort by
environmentalists to cut other road-building programs from the
agency's budget.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed accord among Republicans brings together some of
the logging industry's most loyal allies and some of its persistent
adversaries, as well as chairmen of the House committees that deal
with forest policy. Thus, it could effectively snuff out the forest
debate.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the deal has nonetheless upset some environmental
advocates who oppose all forms of federal support for logging and
have been working for broader reductions in logging on public
lands, especially in areas without roads.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was pushed mainly by Rep. John Edward Porter,
Republican of Illinois, and it demonstrated the continuing
influence of a bloc of some 30 to 50 moderate Republicans with
pro-environment leanings. It also suggests that the House
leadership has little stomach for divisive environmental debates in
the last few months before Congress adjourns for elections this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congressman Porter regards this as a major victory for
environmental common sense as well as a fiscally sound change in
policy,'' said Dave Kohn, Porter's spokesman. ``This is a major
victory for the environmental wing of the party.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Among the Republicans who met last Thursday in Gingrich's office
to shake hands on the agreement, aides said, were Reps. Don Young
of Alaska, the chairman of the Resources Committee; Helen Chenoweth
of Idaho; Ralph Regula of Ohio, chairman of the appropriations
subcommittee on the Interior; Sherwood Boehlert of upstate New
York; James Saxton of New Jersey; George Nethercutt of Washington,
George Radanovich and Wally Herger of California and James
Greenwood of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Although only Republicans have endorsed the deal, it appears
likely that they have the numbers to prevail in the House, even if
some Democrats object. The Senate would have to agree, as well, for
the plan to become law.
</P>
<P>
   Last year a spirited debate on the issue split the House and the
Senate in two narrow floor votes, with the industry barely
prevailing to protect the road-building program.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials contend that the program is not a subsidy at
all, in the sense that without the road credits loggers would
simply offer to pay less for the logs they remove.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purchaser road credit has created a lot of controversy,
and I think it is unnecessary controversy,'' said James English,
president of Idaho Forest Industry Inc., which runs sawmills in and
around Coeur d'Alene, Idaho. The company has about 500 employees
and annual sales of about $180 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not a big company, and it will cost us some money up
front, but over all the important thing is to be able to get into
the federal forest to get the timber,'' English said. ``If we can
eliminate this environmental conflict, pitting the environmental
movement against us and using the road credits to do it, then I
think it is best to get rid of them.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his company used to get almost a third of its timber
from Forest Service land but it now gets only about 5 percent, as
the Forest Service has cut back its sales in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The Forest Service says the dollar value of the credits program
has declined in recent years. In 1996 it was worth $41 million. In
that year, timber companies bid $450 million for logs from the
agency's forests.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement does not, however, mean that no more roads will be
built to haul timber from public lands. The Forest Service
continues to have its own budget for building and maintaining
roads. And timber companies will still build roads, using their own
money, to take logging trucks and other equipment into the woods.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce H. Hamilton, national conservation director for the Sierra
Club, said the Republicans are ``cutting an unfortunate deal which
is bad for the forest.'' He said the environmental group would work
with Democrats to make deeper cuts in the logging budget.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
