<SLUG> BC-CHARITIES-BANKRUPTCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL LETS CHARITIES KEEP MONEY OF BANKRUPT GIVERS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Utah)  (ja)  
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress made it easier Wednesday for churches and
charitable organizations to keep donations made by people who have
filed for bankruptcy and also for those debtors to continue making
charitable donations.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate passed the bill unanimously last month and the House
passed it unanimously on voice vote Wednesday. It is on its way to
President Clinton, who is expected to sign it.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current tax code, a person's donation to a church or
charity within a year of filing for bankruptcy is considered an
attempt to hide assets and therefore a fraudulent transaction.
</P>
<P>
   The bill says that even if a donation was made shortly before a
person filed for bankruptcy, creditors cannot seek repayment from
the church or charity. It also allows the debtor to continue giving
up to 15 percent of income to a church or charity for one year
after declaring bankruptcy. A bankruptcy court would determine if
the donation was consistent with the debtor's practices of giving
before going bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   The bill stemmed from a 1992 court case in Minnesota that
allowed a bankruptcy trustee to recapture thousands of dollars in
past tithes from a church. Lawmakers said they feared that the
ruling would prompt creditors across the nation to ransack the
offering plates of churches in order to recoup their losses from
people who are insolvent.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ron Packard, R-Calif., a Mormon and the chief sponsor of
the measure in the House, said that his own church _ the Church of
Latter Day Saints in Salt Lake City _ had 100 suits filed against
it.
</P>
<P>
   The measure was avidly sought by members of the religious right,
initially to protect churches. But its sponsors realized it would
not pass constitutional muster if it limited its benefits to
churches.
</P>
<P>
   An objection came from members of the National Bankruptcy
Conference, lawyers and judges who handle bankruptcy cases. Stephen
Case, a spokesman for the group, testified in February: ``Congress
should not slice up our fraudulent transfer laws with special
interest exceptions, no matter how deserving the special interest
groups may be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
