<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-YOUTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ATTENDS CONVENTION OF YOUTH VOLUNTEER GROUPS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Seven years after he visited participants of
Boston's City Year program, President Clinton came to the
youth-volunteer organization's national convention Wednesday to
praise its good work and urge members to strive for both national
service and racial reconciliation in the spirit of Robert F.
Kennedy, who was slain 30 years ago this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can finish the work that was done when I was your age by
the people you saw in that video,'' Clinton said, referring to
footage before his speech that featured Robert Kennedy, John F.
Kennedy, and Martin Luther King Jr. ``Your generation will have a
chance to make that the history of the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   In linking national service to racial reconciliation, Clinton
was in essence confronting two major presidential initiatives he
has touted with mixed results.
</P>
<P>
   His volunteerism summit last April in Philadelphia hardly
produced an army of volunteers fanning across the country doing
good deeds, as it was designed to do. And his race initiative,
which is a year old this month, has, by most accounts, fallen short
of sparking the kind of candid conversation about race in America
that smashes stereotypes and helps eliminate racism.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't keep Clinton from promoting the two in his
speech to about 1,000 cheering national youth service corps
volunteers from Boston, where City Year started in 1988, and eight
other cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that the key to solving a lot of our racial tensions
in America is to make sure we keep living together, working
together, learning together, and in some ways, most important of
all _ serving together, giving together,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton visited Boston in 1991 and held a roundtable
discussion with five young people who were serving as City Year
Corps members, he was a little-known candidate for president.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did he become president, but the program grew from one
city to nine. A Seattle program will start this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went to City Year in Boston, the lights came on in my
mind and I said, `This is what I want to do,''' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Of that 1991 visit, Clinton joked: ``I was there as a candidate
for president with about a 1 percent name recognition in
Massachusetts. And so I had a lot of time on my hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I spent the better part of the day, as I recall, talking
to the young people in City Year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One of those young people was Stephen Spaloss, who told Clinton
how his life had been transformed through service. Spaloss had
taken the City Year sweat shirt off his back and given it to
Clinton. Clinton said he still has the sweat shirt and wears it
while jogging.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Spaloss, who has since been named co-executive
director of the City Year program in Philadelphia, presented
Clinton with the group's ``Lifetime of Idealism Award'' and a City
Year baseball cap.
</P>
<P>
   City Year, founded in Boston as a private, nonprofit
organization, operates the national service corps for 17- to
24-year-olds who exchange a year of community service for a weekly
stipend and an education award from AmeriCorps, of which City Year
is a member.
</P>
<P>
   Corps members perform a variety of services: running
after-school programs, tutoring and mentoring children, teaching
HIV and violence prevention, and turning vacant urban lots into
community gardens.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks ago, about 600 corps members wrote Clinton asking
him to come and speak during their four-day convention, which ends
tomorrow, at John Carroll University in a Cleveland suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's event was part high-school pep rally and part
political campaign, as corps members _ dressed in khaki pants,
white T-shirts, and red jackets _ celebrated the end of their year
of service.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also used the occasion to drum up support for national
tobacco legislation among young people.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some in Congress who seem determined to stall, stop
or kill the tobacco bill,'' the president said. ``I hope you will
help me send a loud message back to Washington, D.C., to act and
act now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
