<SLUG> BC-WEBSITE-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUN FOR YOUR LIVES, VIRTUAL PETS!
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Godzilla always seems to be fighting someone: King Kong, Mothra,
Bambi, and for the past two weeks, Ferris Bueller ...
</P>
<P>
   Get ready for Godzilla vs. Tamagotchi.
</P>
<P>
   Kristen Brennan of Berkeley, Calif., created a site
(www.jitterbug.com/gvt/gvt.shtml) that pits the high-maintenance
virtual pets against the big lizard in a Shockwave-powered online
battle.
</P>
<P>
   If you've seen the 1969 film short ``Bambi Meets Godzilla,'' in
which Bambi meets a grisly end, then you're prepared for Godzilla
vs. Tamagotchi.
</P>
<P>
   In Brennan's game, tiny cyberpets wander across a screen on a
Tamagotchi egg, mocking players with their cuteness. Players score
points by crushing the digital creatures into a pulp by clicking
buttons that activate Godzilla's foot. The more pets you smash, the
more points you score.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it sounds brutal, but it must be OK, because it was
developed by a former Tamagotchi owner.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan, who is editor of an online humor e-zine called
Jitterbug Fantasia, came up with the game after one of her
Tamagotchi pets died.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the best way to revenge oneself on a Tamagotchi for
breaking your heart?'' Brennan said. ``Obviously, to recruit
Japan's other major export, Godzilla, to crush the little (toy)
into bits.''
</P>
<P>
   Brennan gained notoriety on the Internet after developing Loving
Henry, a Shockwave-powered digital comic book. Using Shockwave,
readers can turn the virtual pages of the online comic book, which
follows a woman's love for her husband, a bug-eyed alien.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to Brennan's Godzilla-Tamagotchi game has been
positive, she said. Apparently, no one seems offended at seeing
cuddly cyberpets smashed like bugs.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ``kids write that they love the `thumb-candy' aspect of
the game,'' Brennan said. ``Parents write that their kids'
Tamagotchi toys have been driving them crazy, and they're happy to
work out some aggression online.''
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, no one gets hurt _ except for a few cyberpets.
</P>
<P>
   ( Tommy Cummings receives e-mail at dragon\Nstar-telegram.com
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 2058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
