<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0455 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2996 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SECURITY-ONLINE-NYT &LR;      06-03 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECURITY-ONLINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE SUBSCRIBERS ANGERED BY MARKETING MIX-UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By LISA NAPOLI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the 35,000 subscribers to the online version of Advertising
Age checked their e-mail this week, they found an unsolicited _ and
some would say alarming _ piece of mail from TheGlobe.com, an
online ``community.'' The message invited recipients to sign on to
the service, and it included a preselected user name and password.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was that the passwords no doubt looked familiar;
they were the same ones subscribers had used to gain access to the
Advertising Age Web site. Nor did the message mention any
relationship between the two companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you accessed your new FREE e-mail account yet?'' asked
the e-mail come-on. It also pointed users to an Internet address
where they could find these new accounts.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Advertising Age issued an apology, also by e-mail,
explaining that what appeared to be a security breach was really a
marketing mix-up. The apology said that the trade publication was
beginning a new chat community, which it had commissioned
TheGlobe.com to build, and it wanted to make signing up to
participate as easy as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ad Age people merged their data base with ours so people
wouldn't get a second password, to create a seamless introduction
to the community,'' said Esther Loewy, a spokeswoman for
TheGlobe.com. ``That's pretty standard in terms of business
alliances.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Loewy said that she had received a flurry of electronic
messages and calls on Tuesday from people who seemed ``unnerved''
by receiving a private password in an unsolicited e-mail. The
Advertising Age apology explained that the first note should have
come from them, not from TheGlobe.com.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Loewy and officials from Advertising Age said their
companies' respective mailing lists would never be sold. This was a
case of a business alliance, they said, not a violation of privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't sell the passwords or the names, never have, never
will,'' said Edward Erhardt, vice president and publisher of Ad Age
Group. ``There was no intention on our part to give the password
out.'' Merging Ad Age's data base with TheGlobe.com's, he said, was
simply the easiest way to put the message out about the new chat
area.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the mistake raised eyebrows among those concerned
about Internet security. Mailing lists like the World Wide Web
Artists Consortium and other Internet-focused publications were
buzzing with discussions about the subject, said Regina Joseph, a
senior analyst at Jupiter Communications. ``It should alert people
to the privacy issues that are at stake,'' she added, commenting
that such alliances could lead to electronic mailboxes filled with
unwanted promotional material. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It means some people could, based upon whatever mistakes or
errors are made by a service provider, wind up overburdened with
unwanted e-mail. It could lead to people thinking twice before they
registered.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
