u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALBANIA-SERBIA-NYT &LR;      06-03 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBANIA-SERBIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANIA FEARS A SERB INCURSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(dc) 
 By CHRIS HEDGES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ Albania, reeling under an influx of thousands
of refugees from Kosovo, in Serbia, warned Wednesday that the
Serbian army may be preparing to enter Albania to hunt down rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Any such incursion would immediately draw Albania into the
conflict in Kosovo. There is widespread sympathy here for the
ethnic Albanian separatists in Kosovo who are challenging Serbian
rule in the province.
</P>
<P>
   As the fighting in Kosovo intensifies, it also threatens to draw
in Macedonia, where an ethnic Albanian minority also supports the
separatists. Diplomats fear a new Balkan war as destructive as the
one in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs have been manufacturing so-called evidence to say
that Albanian territory is being used to launch terrorist
attacks,'' Prime Minister Fatos Nano said Wednesday in an interview
in his office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had several reports of incursions into our territory
by Serb commando teams that appear to be scouting the area,'' he
said. ``When you look at what the Serbs are attempting to do, to
create a security belt along the border, you soon realize it is
impossible in such a mountainous area. The next step is to try and
enlarge the area under fire, an enlargement that would push the
conflict into Albania.''
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister, who sent an urgent appeal to NATO commanders
Wednesday asking for troops to secure the border area, conceded
that it was impossible to monitor the rugged terrain.
</P>
<P>
   He insisted, however, that any arms shipped into Kosovo from
Albania were being sent without his government's knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic, has deployed
thousands of special police and soldiers along the border, and they
have been pounding villages with heavy artillery, witnesses report.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 10,000 ethnic Albanians have fled since Sunday and
the flow is increasing. The refugees, many of whom walked for two
or three days to reach Albania, said that entire villages had been
reduced to rubble under the Serbian artillery fire, and that
hundreds of families are hiding in the woods.
</P>
<P>
   The sweep by Serbian troops under Milosevic's command is the
latest attempt to crush the Kosovo guerrillas fighting for
independence. Of the 2 million people in the province, about 90
percent are ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington the State Department raised the possibility of
tighter international sanctions against Yugoslavia for provoking
the flood of refugees. ``One does feel like the movie called
`Ethnic Cleansing' is replaying intself,'' said the department's
spokesman, James P. Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia, which now has just two republics, Serbia and
Montenegro, tried a more limited operation to end the rebel
movement in March. That campaign left villages in central Kosovo in
rubble and 80 dead, most of them women, children and the elderly,
witnesses reported.
</P>
<P>
   The attack in March only served to ignite the population and
swell the ranks of the rebel force. Weapons and volunteers, many
from the 600,000 ethnic Albanians living in Switzerland and
Germany, began to pour into the region, crossing into Kosovo from
Albania, according to Western diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Nano said there were also indications that
Islamic groups are interested in aiding the ethnic Albanian
Kosovars, most of whom are Muslim, in the battle against the Serbs,
who are Orthodox Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian government is still trying to clean up after the
collapse of fraudulent investment schemes last year and the
widespread looting and rioting that followed when thousands lost
vast sums of money. The chaos left lawless areas beyond the reach
of the police and the military, especially along the border with
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Nano said 70 former military warehouses scattered around Albania
still held stockpiles of weapons inherited from the preceding
Communist government, and he warned that continued unrest could set
off a new round of pillaging.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are over 2,000 tons of weapons and explosives sitting
out there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   During the confusion that swept Albania last year, an estimated
650,000 weapons were taken by mobs from military and police
warehouses and barracks. Many of the weapons ended up in Kosovo,
Western diplomats say.
</P>
<P>
   The government in Tirana, which has supported the international
community in calling for a negotiated settlement in Kosovo, has
begun issuing much more ambiguous statements. The prime minister
referred to the resistance in Kosovo, for example, as ``self
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These are Albanians who want to protect their kids, their
lives and their homes,'' he said. ``They have these armed groups to
fight the Serbs because they have been attacked.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``We desperately need intervention, the establishment
of mechanisms such as `no fly' zones to halt these attacks. The
situation is deteriorating. We do not want another Bosnia.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
