<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2998 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-LABOR-350&AMP;ADD-N     06-03 1276
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-LABOR-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIONS DEFEAT EFFORT TO RESTRICT POLITICAL ACTIVITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CALIF-ELECT, OAKLAND-ELECT, BILINGUAL-EDUC) 
(th) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In an impressive assertion of organized labor's
political might, California voters on Tuesday dealt conservatives a
considerable setback by rejecting a measure championed by
Republicans that would have pinched the flow of money to Democratic
candidates and causes.
</P>
<P>
   The ballot initiative had posed one of the greatest political
threats to labor in years: It would have choked off a vital source
of money for Democrats, who largely champion labor's issues, by
requiring unions to get annual written permission from each member
before using dues for political purposes.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat, 53 percent to 47 percent, represented a stunning
comeback for labor. Early polls had indicated that the referendum
would prevail by more than a 2 to 1 margin. As recently as late
last week, a senior White House official who has closely monitored
the campaign here predicted, unhappily, that the initiative would
win.
</P>
<P>
   Most proponents blamed the result on lopsided spending on the
issue. Labor poured an estimated $20 million into the drive
compared to a few million spent by supporters of the referendum.
The outcome set off a round of recriminations and soul-searching
Wednesday among Republicans who had thought passage was well within
their grasp.
</P>
<P>
   Grover Norquist, the director of Americans for Tax Reform in
Washington, who campaigned aggressively for the referendum,
predicted that the outcome here will mean that only about five
states will approve proposals to restrict unions dues within the
next year instead of the anticipated 10 that might have been swept
up in the excitement of a victory here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been helpful if we had won _ there would have
been more momentum,'' Norquist said in an interview. ``But when
you're competing with a bottomless pit _ the ability to raise union
dues, it's a little tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Grossman, national chairman of the Democratic Party
responded: ``Grover Norquist and his merry band of extremists
clearly had in mind jump-starting a national campaign _ and
California was the centerpiece of their strategy. That strategy
lies in ruins.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   From here to Washington on Wednesday, labor leaders hailed their
triumph, saying that beyond the money there was an extraordinary
effort by hundreds of thousands of volunteers who made phone calls
and walked precincts in recent days to draw people to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Another unexpected beneficiary, they said, was Gray Davis, who
won the Democratic gubernatorial nomination. Davis has long been an
ally of unions, and the turnout by labor for the ballot measure
also delivered more votes to his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The labor leaders predicted that the California victory will
embolden their efforts to reject similar initiatives in other
states _ and will spur greater grassroots participation by unions
in the November midterm elections. In the next year or two, nearly
a dozen other states are considering similar union measures, either
through their legislatures or the initiative process.
</P>
<P>
   ``A modern political miracle,'' declared John Sweeney, president
of the AFL-CIO, at a news conference in Washington. ``We gained new
strength and momentum for a pro-working family agenda heading into
the fall elections. More than 24,000 new union member political
activists emerged in California in the course of the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The reverberations were felt far beyond California and marked a
disquieting reversal for leading conservatives, including House
Speaker Newt Gingrich, who had vigorously pressed for the measure
and hoped its passage would embolden similar so-called ``paycheck
protection'' drives around the country.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome was also a serious personal rebuke to Gov. Pete
Wilson of California, who had championed the referendum and had
hoped its passage would give him a vehicle on which to base a
campaign for president in 2000 _ and leave conservatives who favor
the measure in his debt.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, expecting victory, had prevailed upon Gingrich to
postpone votes on campaign finance legislation that would have
called for restrictions similar to those in the California measure.
Wilson had thought approval of the referendum, known here as
Proposition 226, would help Republicans gain momentum for a similar
effort in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters after an appearance at a Republican
``unity breakfast'' in Newport Beach on Wednesday morning, Wilson
castigated unions for their role in defeating the proposal,
asserting, ``The more they rip off peoples' pay checks, the more
money they have in their warchests. And they will be just as
arrogant and high-handed as they can get away with.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor brushed aside a question about how the outcome will
affect his White House aspirations, saying, ``You pick your fights
because you think it's the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Surveys showed that while Democrats overwhelmingly rejected the
initiative, so did a sizable segment of voters who identify
themselves as Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the second-guessing and finger-pointing Wednesday was
among Republicans who blamed one another for mounting a feeble
campaign: Supporters in California attacked the Republican National
Committee for not channeling significant resources into the drive.
</P>
<P>
   Republican officials in Washington criticized the backers in
California for bickering over how best to pitch the initiative. And
supporters everywhere criticized major California business
organizations for their refusal to take on labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people thought it was a sure win,'' said Mark Bucher, a
business executive from Tustin, an Orange County community south of
Los Angeles, who was prompted to write the initiative with two
friends after a teacher he knew groused that her union was backing
school board candidates that she opposed. ``So they turned away
their attention and gave their money elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The unions pumped millions of dollars into television
commercials that said the referendum was the brainchild of a
``foreign lobbyist'' _ a reference to Norquist _ and that it
threatened everything from Medicare to education. They asserted
that it would hinder charities that use payroll deductions to raise
money.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents launched their television campaign only a few weeks
ago. They sought to counter the opponents ``scare stories'' and
referred disparagingly to ``union bosses'' amassing great sums of
money.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Mellman, a Democratic pollster who worked with labor to
oppose the measure, said his side was all the more aggressive
because it was spurred on by the early poll findings showing that
it would pass. As for the opponents, he said, ``They were misled by
their own hubris.''
</P>
<P>
   Norquist, whose group contributed about $500,000 to the
referendum campaign, did not dispute that point, saying some
possible donors were reluctant to contribute because they did not
think the referendum was in trouble. ``That hurt us on fund
raising,'' he said. ``That one of the reasons business didn't
contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the critics who blame the Republican National Committee
for barely putting any money into opposing the referendum, Clifford
May, the party's communications director, explained that candidates
are a higher priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as we supported this, our job is to elect Republicans
in November,'' he said. ``Our job is not to match the unions and
have less left over for November.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
