<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3000 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DRUG-STORES-NYT &LR;      06-03 1557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DRUG-STORES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME DRUG STORES SHUN MANAGED-CARE CUSTOMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ja)  
 By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Martin Keane has spent two decades refining his skill
at mixing custom-made prescriptions, helping customers sort through
the maze of medications and making sure they get Feldene for their
arthritis and Seldane for their hay fever, not the other way
around.
</P>
<P>
   But that expertise and dedication have barely kept his
struggling pharmacy on the Upper East Side afloat, buffeted as it
is by the proliferation of chain drugstores and the relentless
cost-cutting permeating every aspect of health care. Keane and his
partner have tried everything they can think of. Pushing the $70
scented candles and $500 French magnifying mirrors they stock in
the front of the store. Renting breast-milk pumps to working
mothers. They've even considered mixing veterinary medicines for
their customers' pets.
</P>
<P>
   But their latest strategy is the most drastic step yet. Like a
handful of other independent pharmacists in New York City, Keane is
rebelling against the whole managed-care system. His store, the
venerable Newton-Timmermann Pharmacy at Lexington Avenue and 62nd
Street, has stopped accepting insurance cards for managed-care drug
plans, saying that the reimbursements are so small that pharmacists
are losing money or skimping on service to their customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Managed care was costing us all of our profit,'' Keane said.
</P>
<P>
   Facing similar strains, many independent pharmacies have
specialized, focusing on a particular niche overlooked by the Rite
Aids and Duane Reades.
</P>
<P>
   Some pharmacists provide services for AIDS patients or develop a
special expertise in chronic problems like diabetes or respiratory
ailments. Some feature homeopathic medicines. Others try to adapt
to their neighborhoods _ for example, serving immigrant customers
in their own language and understanding their medical traditions.
</P>
<P>
   A pharmacy in Ridgewood, N.J., has even begun asking
managed-care customers to pay a voluntary $3 surcharge on each
prescription so the store, Town and Country Pharmacy, does not have
to reduce its level of service. About half the customers asked have
agreed, said John Herr, a pharmacist.
</P>
<P>
   Keane and his partner, Steven H. Hurowitz, are also looking for
niches to fill and new services and products to offer. But by
banishing managed-care plans _ and losing about 250 of their 5,000
regular customers in the process _ they are staking their survival
primarily on an old-fashioned style of service befitting a store
that traces its roots to 1869.
</P>
<P>
   They made the switch in March after concluding that they were
actually losing money on prescriptions and barely breaking even on
the business over all. Reimbursements from the insurers have been
dropping in recent years even as the percentage of customers using
them has grown, squeezing profits and forcing Newton-Timmermann to
lay off two of 11 workers and not replace a third employee.
</P>
<P>
   In an average day, Keane said, three pharmacists at
Newton-Timmermann fill a total of about 75 prescriptions, well
below the average workload for a single pharmacist at many stores.
Keane, an affable man of 41 with a knack for putting people at
ease, often emerges from behind the counter at the rear of the
narrow store and spends as long as 15 minutes with a customer who
needs instructions for taking a new medication. People come in to
get post-surgical advice for a fresh face lift or simply to banter
about Viagra; some customers seem to view him almost as a stand-in
for their doctor.
</P>
<P>
   As Keane sees it, the managed-care companies have threatened the
traditions he values and put so much pressure on druggists that the
danger of slip-ups has increased. Pharmacists are forced to act
more like salesmen than medical professionals, he said, because
they are rewarded or penalized based on whether they can persuade
doctors to substitute a cheaper drug for the one that was initially
prescribed.
</P>
<P>
   Subscribers in the plans typically pay about $10 per
prescription. The insurer then reimburses the pharmacist according
to a formula based on the wholesale cost of the drug, plus $2.50
per prescription intended to cover his costs and profit margin. But
with his high rent and other costs, and his relatively low volume,
Keane said he ended up losing $12 or more on many prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   And in a further blow to the pharmacists, the managed-care
companies are increasingly encouraging subscribers with chronic
conditions to order their medications by mail.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the managed-care companies _ and many
non-managed-care customers reeling at the high cost of prescription
drugs _ see things differently. The companies say they are trying
to bring down the high cost of health care for their clients, who
include employers, trade unions and other insurers. ``We compete in
a marketplace for customers,'' said Kevin Colgan, a spokesman for
Merck Medco Managed Care, the parent company of Paid Prescriptions.
``They select us based on our ability to provide high-quality,
affordable prescription drug plans. Everybody in health care is
under pressure to compete _ to improve quality and reduce costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in affluent parts of New York City, where residents are
often passionate about their neighborhood stores, independent
pharmacies are rapidly disappearing. Recent casualties include
Downing Chemists and Calvin Berger on the Upper East Side and the
Last Pharmacy on the Upper West Side. According to the Hayes
Directory, which compiles statistics from state pharmacy boards,
New York state lost 612 independent pharmacies and gained 513 chain
drugstores from 1992 to 1997, mirroring the national trend.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, when Keane sold a pharmacy he had owned in the South
Bronx neighborhood where he grew up and bought a half-interest in
Newton-Timmermann, only about 7 percent of the prescriptions were
reimbursed through managed care. In six years, that proportion has
grown to 33 percent, he said. Nationwide, the proportion of
prescriptions paid by managed-care companies has risen to 60
percent, from 28 percent in 1991, according to IMS America, a
health-care information company.
</P>
<P>
   Since Newton-Timmermann clamped down on managed-care coverage _
joining several other independent stores in the city that never
took the cards _ some customers have defected to the Pasteur
Pharmacy a block away, where the cards are accepted. ``Their not
taking the plans really helped us,'' said Amy Schimmel, a co-owner
of Pasteur.
</P>
<P>
   Keane is hopeful that his loyal longtime customers, many of whom
have charge accounts, will see him through.
</P>
<P>
   And many customers say they are willing to pay extra for the
service and expertise at Newton-Timmermann. ``They're very
expensive, but I trust them,'' said Diane Papert, a retired
copywriter.
</P>
<P>
   Keane, who lives in Suffolk County with his wife (also a
pharmacist, at a Genovese chain store) and three children, did not
anticipate catering to the carriage trade when he settled on a
career. At 15, he worked part time as a stock boy in a drugstore
near his home in the Highbridge section of the Bronx to help pay
his tuition for parochial school. Pharmacy seemed an ideal field
for him, combining his interest in biology and chemistry, his knack
for business and his desire to work in a helping profession, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, after a five-year pharmacy program at St. John's
University, he was contemplating going on for his doctorate when he
was offered the chance to buy a half-interest in the tiny Weldon
Pharmacy, where he had worked as a teen-ager, for a mere $1,000.
The opportunity was too good to pass up.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, Keane said, it was easy for a pharmacist to do
well because the price of drugs was rising at a steady clip. ``That
protected a lot of pharmacies,'' he said, ``because without really
doing anything, the value of your inventory was going up 12 or 13
percent a year consistently through the '80s. So you were making
real money just standing there. That's why a lot of places that
were less than efficient were able to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   The South Bronx business grew rapidly, eventually handling 275
prescriptions a day, most of them Medicaid reimbursements. Even
with the help of a second pharmacist, Keane said, it was impossible
to give his customers more than minimal individual attention.
``That was one of the things I had originally gone into pharmacy
for,'' he said. ``I missed that.'' He decided to sell and set up
his business elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   In his six years at Newton-Timmermann, Keane has found himself
handing out his business card to hotel concierges to let them know
he can rent wheelchairs to their guests. He has expanded the enema-
and suppository-preparation service for which the pharmacy has long
been known. He has started putting out a newsletter to inform his
customers about new research on vitamins and nutrition supplements.
And he has sought to expand the pharmacy's reach by signing up
several corporate medical offices and a child-care agency.
</P>
<P>
   Keane said he hoped his protest against managed care would give
him the breathing room he needed to keep building the business. ``I
think that in five years there will be very, very few pharmacies
left,'' Keane said. ``I'm hoping that I'll be one of them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
