<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FROM SOUTH KOREA, BOEING TO GET $1.35 BILLION ORDER
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Asian economic crisis and declines in airline
passenger traffic in the region, Korean Air plans to announce an
order next week for 27 new Boeing 737 passenger jets valued at
$1.35 billion. The order is good news for Boeing, which only last
week said that weakening demand from Asia would force it to cut
production of the 747 jumbo jet next year. Boeing will stop
producing the MD-11 wide-body jet and lay off some workers because
of reduced demand for that plane.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS FALL ON TECHNOLOGY SLUMP
</P>
<P>
   Declines among technology shares, led by a 4.8 percent drop in
the price of Intel on fears of lower earnings, helped push the
stock markets lower. The Nasdaq composite index fell 1.1 percent,
to 1,742.31. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 87.44 points and
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 10.49 points.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury prices rose in slow trading. The yield on the 30-year
bond fell to 5.78 percent, from 5.79 percent on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   TEST OF AIDS VACCINE IS APPROVED
</P>
<P>
   The FDA gave VaxGen Inc. of South San Francisco approval to
conduct the world's first full-scale test of a vaccine to prevent
infection with the AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
   Approval was also given to a combination of two antiviral drugs
to treat liver-destroying hepatitis C. The treatment, known as
Rebetron, is made by Schering-Plough.
</P>
<P>
   A TALENT MANAGER FOR LAS VEGAS
</P>
<P>
   Some lavishly produced shows in Las Vegas, like those including
Siegfried and Roy's $50-million-a-year live-animal act, are
obviously successful. But Steven Wynn, chairman of Mirage Resorts,
wants to alter the type of entertainment seen in the gambling
resort city. He has hired a top talent manager, Sandy Gallin, to
start new theaters, arenas and cabarets, hoping to create shows
that will end up on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   QUICKENING PACE ON MADISON AVE.
</P>
<P>
   The pace of deals involving interactive advertising accelerated
with the announcement of three acquisitions and affiliations
involving five New York firms and one in Palo Alto, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   SOME SIGHS OF RELIEF IN MOSCOW
</P>
<P>
   Russia's economy survived a critical test as the Government sold
nearly $1 billion in treasury bills without paying the colossal
interest rates it settled for just a week ago. Anxious foreign
investors breathed a sigh of relief.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics wonder if the IMF is applying flawed priorities and
policies in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON VOW ON CHINA TRADING RIGHTS
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton announced that he would renew China's trading
privileges, signaling that he would not back away from his policy
of engagement despite the rising Congressional clamor over whether
the Chinese Government illegally contributed to his campaign and
used protected American technology to improve its missiles.
</P>
<P>
   CIENA AND POWER OF THE MARKETPLACE
</P>
<P>
   Solid relationships with big customers represent one factor
driving Ciena's acquisition by Tellabs Inc. The company has very
good technology but was starting to feel as if doors were closing.
</P>
<P>
   MORE AT&AMP;T MANAGERS RETIRING
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T said it would take a larger charge than expected in the
second quarter because more managers than predicted are taking
early retirement. But expecting the charge to be more than offset
by gains from the sale of businesses, the company chairman, C.
Michael Armstrong, called the results good news.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
