<HEADER>
A3006 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHAPTER-AND-VERSE-TEX     06-03 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPTER-AND-VERSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF CHRISTIAN BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOOK REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Four Views on the Book of Revelation''
</P>
<P>
   Edited by C. Marvin Pate
</P>
<P>
   Zondervan, $16.99
</P>
<P>
   Confused by the last book of the Bible? Well, the line begins
over there, and it's a lengthy line indeed. But a recent
installment in Zondervan's ``Counterpoints'' series may provide
direction of some sort.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Four Views on the Book of Revelation,'' four scholars _
Kenneth L. Gentry Jr., Sam Hamstra Jr., C. Marvin Pate and Robert
L. Thomas _ outline their respective interpretive schemes. The
choices are preterist (the prophecies were basically fulfilled
centuries ago), idealist (the book is a symbolic lesson, with no
particular connections to history), classical dispensationalist
(almost all of the book deals with the future ``last days'') and
progressive dispensationalist (a modified version of the last).
</P>
<P>
   The book may be most helpful to those who are already with the
Bible but are at a loss about where to begin with Revelation.
There's still plenty to disagree about (Hamstra sees the first
horseman of the Apocalypse as Christ, whereas Pate sees him as
Antichrist), but ``Four Views on the Book of Revelation'' at least
helps set the stage for the discussion.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Alan Cochrum
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``(Pages of Life) Chapters I &AMP; II''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Hammond &AMP; Radical for Christ
</P>
<P>
   Zomba Recording Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Size, the ads for ``Godzilla'' keep telling us, matters.
</P>
<P>
   But more is not always better.
</P>
<P>
   And to understand this fully, the best place to go is ``(Pages
of Life) Chapters I &AMP; II,'' the new two-CD set by Detroit-based
modern-gospel favorite Fred Hammond &AMP; Radical for Christ.
</P>
<P>
   Hammond, who has toured frequently with Kirk Franklin and
Yolanda Adams, has become one of the leading lights of the
crossover/urban gospel movement, fusing stories straight out of the
Bible with deep beats and '70s-redolent funk.
</P>
<P>
   And Hammond and Radical for Christ (10 vocalists, six musicians)
are very good at what they do, no question about it. But here, they
just try to do too much of it _ or, perhaps more accurately, do it
for too long.
</P>
<P>
   This new set's two ``chapters'' are basically one CD (16 songs)
of studio recordings, and one CD (13 songs) of live recordings.
What hamstrings the project, however, and ultimately makes it less
effective than it might have been, is its sheer bulk. The first CD
is clearly the keeper, full of excellent songs, such as the deep
funk of ``I Wanna Know Your Ways, I Will Bless His Holy Name'' (on
which PamKenyon Donald and Frederick Purifoy II contribute some
strong lead vocals) and the truly lovely ``You Were Much Closer.''
The second CD is, well, a lot of the songs from the first CD, done
in louder and longer (but not necessarily better) versions, all
recorded Nov. 29, 1997, at the Straight Gate Church in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Here, again, there are positives: Hammond and the vocalists are
in good form, and there are moments that are exactly what a gospel
music show should be. But did we really need an additional eight
minutes of ``I Wanna Know Your Ways?'' An additional 12 minutes of
``Jesus Is All?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, frankly, no, we didn't, and Hammond should have let the
original versions on the first CD stand alone.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Dave Ferman
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
