<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3007 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKEES-HERNANDEZ     06-03 1294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-HERNANDEZ-ART-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REALIZING A DREAM, `EL DUQUE' MAKES FIRST MAJOR LEAGUE START 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: See also BBA-YANKEES-DEVILRAYS; an updated version of this
story will move a half-hour after conclusion of game) 
(ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1027.) 
(sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Before throwing his first pitch for the New York
Yankees on Wednesday night, Orlando Hernandez stood behind the
mound and stared around the outfield at Yankee Stadium. These were
moments to remember for Hernandez, the realization of a lifelong
goal and the culmination of a harrowing journey that began six
months ago with a risky escape from Cuba and ended Wednesday night
on baseball's grandest stage.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, forbidden to play baseball in Cuba by officials who
feared that he would defect, survived that trip in a make-shift
sailboat last December and signed with the Yankees this spring. He
performed so well in the minor leagues that he was promoted to
pitch at Yankee Stadium on Wednesday night, against the Tampa Bay
Devil Rays. The crowd roared when he was introduced, cheered him
when he walked to the mound, and burst with more cheers when he
struck out the game's first hitter, Quinton McCracken.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees called up Hernandez on Tuesday as a contingency, in
case David Wells, bothered by shoulder soreness, couldn't pitch.
Wells was able to start, but it just so happened that David Cone,
another Yankee pitcher, had been bitten on the pitching hand by his
mother's dog. The Yankees decided to rest Cone and activate
Hernandez for one game; they intend to return him to the minors on
Thursday, and then call him again up later this season.
</P>
<P>
   But for Hernandez, one day was enough. He ate spaghetti on
Wednesday afternoon, his favorite pregame meal, and arrived at
Yankee Stadium around 3:30, cheered enthusiastically by fans
waiting outside, some waving Cuban flags. Hernandez strolled into
the Yankees clubhouse, wearing blue jeans and a denim jacket,
appearing not the least bit nervous or anxious. In a sense, he'd
been preparing for this day for years.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, known as El Duque, was a star on Cuba's national
team. As a child, Hernandez has said, he rooted for the Yankees and
hoped he could play in Yankee Stadium. His younger half-brother,
Livan, defected from Cuba in 1995 and signed with the Florida
Marlins. Livan was a World Series hero for the Marlins last
October.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez is the latest of a handful of defectors from Cuba who
are slowly making an impact in the major leagues. Rey Ordonez, the
shortstop of the New YOrk Mets, won a Gold Glove Award last season
for his defensive brilliance, and Rolando Arrojo of Tampa Bay has
been one of the American League's best pitchers this season.
</P>
<P>
   After his brother's defection, Cuban authorities suspected that
Orlando would also try to defect. So even though he was a star
pitcher, they banned him from life from Cuba's national team in
October, 1996. Other players who had defected, such as Livan
Hernandez and Rey Ordonez, had walked away while the team was
playing in other countries. Orlando Hernandez would not get that
chance.
</P>
<P>
   After he was banned, Hernandez, who is 32 by some accounts and
28 by his own, worked briefly in a psychiatric hospital, making
less than $10 a month, according to his account. He said that
before Christmas of 1997, state officials visited him and warned
him against taking any embarrassing action, because the pope was
due to visit Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   With that, Hernandez determined to leave Cuba. On the morning of
Dec. 26, he and seven others, including his wife Norris Bosch,
obtained a 20-foot sailboat made of scraps, carrying only several
cans of Spam, some fresh water and sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez and his group landed on a small island, Anguilla Cay,
that is part of the Bahamas. After living under a sail and
surviving on seaweed and conch for three days, they were spotted by
a U.S. Coast Guard helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez was offered a visa by the United States, but he
established residence in Costa Rica, instead. Had he taken the
offer of residence from the United States, he would have been
subject to the amateur draft. Living in Costa Rica, he was a free
agent and could field offers from all teams. The Yankees signed
Hernandez on March 7 to a four-year, $6.6 million contract, more
than twice what executives with other bidders said they had
offered.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hernandez worked out with the Yankees for the first time March
21, but the Yankees weren't sure what kind of physical condition he
would be in. After all, he had been out of organized baseball for
more than a year and had struggled to make a living in his final
months in Cuba. But he shocked them: A team doctor said Hernandez
was in the best condition of any athlete he had ever examined.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre, the Yankees manager, saw Hernandez's broad shoulders,
the flexibility in his movements and his pitching mechanics, and
decided then Hernandez had a chance to pitch in the big leagues. He
just looks like an athlete, Torre said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Broad-shouldered at 6-2 and 190 pounds, Hernandez is a
right-hander who throws many different pitches from different
angles, much like Luis Tiant, another Cuban-born pitcher, did. He
draws his left leg upward, standing for an instant on one leg like
a flamingo, left knee almost touching his left cheekbone.
</P>
<P>
   Teammates were taken immediately with his enthusiasm, his
outward joy. At the end of a fielding drill on his first day,
Hernandez bounced around the infield to pick up baseballs, like a
newly hired batboy, his glove overflowing. He was incredulous at
the food and equipment made available to the players _ and at a
Jerry Springer videotape the players watched. Hernandez walked
away, grinning, spinning a pointed finger at his head: Loco.
Welcome to America.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the awkward assimilation of the Japanese-speaking pitcher
Hideki Irabu last season, Hernandez seemed to fit in the with the
Yankees right away, due, in great measure, to his own effort. When
he first went to David Szen, the team's traveling secretary, to
receive his allotment of meal money, Hernandez attempted to speak
only in English. Hernandez shivered in the relative cold of Florida
in March, but refused to buy any warmer clothes; he needed to
adjust, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He always seemed so happy, other players noted. But during
batting practice one day, Jorge Posada, the Yankees' catcher, stood
alongside Hernandez in the outfield and asked him about his trip in
the leaky sailboat. Posada remembered on Wednesday that in
responding, Hernandez spoke quietly, his eyes turned downward.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear about the people who make it on the boats,'' said
Posada, who grew up in Puerto Rico. ``But there are so many who
don't. You wonder, how bad is it over there that they just want to
get away. It's sad.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He left all his friends behind,'' Posada said. ``He had to
some of his family behind. That's pretty tough.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Hernandez's agent, Joe Cubas, authorities in Cuba
incarcerated one of the pitcher's brothers for a few days.
Hernandez's phone calls to his two daughters, 7-year-old Yahumara
and 2-year-old Steffi, are monitored. ``Duque's life is incomplete
until he has his kids next to him,'' said Cubas.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez continued his preparation at the Yankees' training
complex in April, before pitching in a Class A game April 16; just
11 days later, he struck out 10 in five scoreless innings for
Triple-A Columbus. He continued to pitch well, compiling a 6-0
record and a 3.83 era for the Clippers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
