<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0463 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3009 &Cx1f; tth-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MFN-SPI &LR;      06-03 1296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MFN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON RENEWS CHINA'S TRADE STATUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton Wednesday said he will renew
normal trade status for China, saying that an open relationship
with China is particularly important now that India and Pakistan
appear headed toward a nuclear arms race.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's decision launches the annual debate over U.S.
relations with China, a debate that is likely to be particularly
rancorous this year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the perennial concerns about China's poor record
on human rights and arms proliferation, many in Congress are
concerned about allegations that China tried to influence the 1996
presidential election in this country and then gained access to
secret information about satellite technology from a top Democratic
contributor.
</P>
<P>
   Trade relations with China are particularly important to
Washington state, where many businesses, most notably Boeing, are
heavily dependent on trade with China. An estimated $8.7 billion
worth of goods heading to or coming from China passed through the
ports of Washington state in 1996, making mainland China the
state's third largest trading partner, according to the state
department of Community, Trade and Economic Development.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has 90 days in which it could overturn Clinton's
action, but any chance of that seemed seriously diminished
Wednesday when House Speaker Newt Gingrich, a vocal Clinton critic,
signed a letter to Clinton supporting the president's position on
normal trade relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   Although the trade status is called most favored nation, it
allows China the same tariff treatment as most other nations
trading with the United States. Only six countries _ Afghanistan,
Cuba, Laos, North Korea, Serbia-Montenegro and Vietnam _ are not
accorded the status.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to renew would be to sever our economic and, to a large
measure, our strategic relationship with China, turning our back on
a fourth of the world at a time when our cooperation for world
peace and security is especially important, in light of the recent
events in South Asia,'' Clinton said in remarks at the White House
Rose Garden Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews Wednesday, eight of the 11 members of the
Washington state congressional delegation said they support
renewing China's trade status. Only Rep. Linda Smith, R-Wash.,
opposed the president's position, while Rep. George Nethercutt,
R-Wash., said he is undecided, and Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash.,
declined to be interviewed on the topic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be fairly economically devastating to the Pacific
Northwest if we were no longer allowed to do business with China,''
said Rep. Adam Smith, D-Wash. ``And it's not only Boeing _ a number
of small companies in my area are interested in selling products
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington state last year exported $1.9 billion worth of goods
to China, the vast majority of which came in the form of Boeing
airplanes. Boeing expects China to spend $125 billion over the next
20 years on new airplanes, making the country its largest potential
overseas market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trade with China has helped our nation's economy stay strong
and has meant steady jobs for thousands of Boeing families,'' the
Seattle-based aerospace company, which employs 237,500 people, said
in a statement. ``It has long been our position that trade between
the United States and China is a positive force in the overall
relationship between our two countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Most favored nation status was first extended to China on Feb.
1, 1980, and has been renewed annually by every president since
then.
</P>
<P>
   The trade relationship has been particularly controversial since
1989, when the Chinese leadership massacred pro-democracy
protesters in Tiananmen Square. In 1992 President Bush twice vetoed
measures passed by Congress to revoke China's trade status.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ran for president in 1992 accusing Bush of coddling
China's leaders, but in 1994 he dramatically changed his position,
declaring that his administration would no longer link trade and
human rights decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our exports have tripled over the last decade and now support
over 170,000 American jobs,'' Clinton said Wednesday. ``But just as
important, trade is a force for change in China, exposing China to
our ideas and our ideals and integrating China into the global
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the trade argument, Clinton, joined by Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright, argued that good relations with China
will help U.S. security in light of the looming threat of nuclear
confrontation between India and Pakistan. China is chairing a
meeting Thursday in Geneva of foreign ministers from the five
permanent United Nations security council members on the situation
in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important example of how our engagement with China
serves America's interests: stability in Asia, preventing the
spread of weapons of mass destruction, combating international
crime and drug-trafficking, protecting the environment,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, we continue to deal forthrightly with China
on those issues where we disagree _ notably, on human rights; and
there have clearly been some concrete results as a result of this
engagement as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Those arguments were echoed by Gingrich, who co-signed a letter
with House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas,
and Rep. Philip Crane, R-Ill., the chairman of the Ways and Means
Subcommittee on Trade.
</P>
<P>
   They outlined their concerns about alleged illegal Chinese
contributions to U.S. political campaigns and lax enforcement of
U.S. laws against transfers of missile technology. But they said
those issues should be separated from the debate over most favored
nation status for China, which they support.
</P>
<P>
   ``We welcome the determination you made today to recommend the
renewal of MFN trade status for China, and we pledge to work with
you in a bipartisan manner to preserve our longstanding policy of
commercial and diplomatic engagement with the Chinese,'' they
wrote. ``Seeking to keep China open to the West has proven to be
the most effective way to advance our democratic values in this
turbulent region of the world _ a policy we are committed to
maintaining.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Thomas Daschle, D-S.D., also supported
renewing China's trade status.
</P>
<P>
   But opposition to Clinton's policy quickly emerged from the left
and the right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I oppose the president's actions,'' said the House Minority
Leader, Richard Gephardt, D-Mo. ``We must not reward the Chinese
Communist government for continuing political repression and
tyranny.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the AFL-CIO said the labor union will oppose
renewal of the trade status.
</P>
<P>
   ``The egregious human rights violations and violations of
democratic principles have not been addressed,'' said Thea Lee,
assistant director of public policy for the AFL-CIO. ``We also
don't see that China has lived up to its obligations to provide
reciprocal access to its market, and the imbalance of our
relationship is of concern to us as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, the president of the Family Research Council and an
influential voice for the religious right, also opposed renewal of
normal trade relations with China, calling it ``part of an overall
abandonment of the president's previous commitment to get serious
about China's flagrant disregard for human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``China systematically violates agreements on human rights and
weapons transfers, aggressively builds up its military in an
attempt to dislodge the United States from the Pacific, seeks to
tamper with the U.S. electoral system, yet the president does
virtually nothing in response,'' Bauer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 2116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
