<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI-SYRIAN FORUM CALLED `PRODUCTIVE' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Filed in ``a'' and ``i'' categories) 
 
By JERRY URBAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Israeli and Syrian officials on Wednesday ended three
days of closed meetings designed to explore ways to restart peace
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The officials were joined at Rice University's Baker Institute
for Public Policy by officials from the United States and public
policy experts from around the world, institute director Edward
Djerejian confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Among the participants were Uzi Arad, diplomatic adviser to
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, and Walid Al-Moualem,
Syria's ambassador to Washington. Also present was Martin Indyk,
U.S. assistant secretary of state for Near Eastern affairs.
</P>
<P>
   James A. Baker III, the honorary chairman of the institute and
former U.S. secretary of state, didn't participate in the forum but
interacted with the group at a working dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Peace talks between Israel and Syria have been frozen since
February 1996. Netanyahu has rejected Syrian demands they be
resumed on the basis of an Israeli agreement in principle to return
the occupied Golan Heights in exchange for a peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Djerejian, who formerly held U.S. ambassadorships to Israel and
Syria, said the meetings didn't constitute negotiations. He said
the institute invited officials and experts to Houston to attend a
public policy forum designed to analyze conditions and search for
ways to restart the negotiations between Israel and Syria, as well
as to move the peace process along.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a unique gathering of people,'' Djerejian said. ``The
forum was productive.''
</P>
<P>
   The meetings were closed to the public to ``maintain
confidentiality,'' Djerejian said. ``They were closed so people
could speak their minds.''
</P>
<P>
   The institute, designed as a place to help resolve public policy
issues, will publish a report on the policy recommendations and
findings of the forum.
</P>
<P>
   Also among the people taking part were Israel's former military
intelligence chief Uri Sagie, and former Israeli ambassador to
Washington Itamar Rabinovich.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
