<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0465 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3011 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-BELMONT-JOCKEYS-2     06-03 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-JOCKEYS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERACTION BETWEEN JOCKEY AND RACEHORSE: AN INSIDE VIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds, see also RAC-REAL-QUIET)  
 (bl)  
 By JAY PRIVMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ From the time the horses burst out of the starting
gate in Saturday's 130th Belmont Stakes until the finish two and a
half minutes later, an extraordinary collaboration will take place
between every horse and jockey.
</P>
<P>
   Through subtle cues with their hands and legs, each jockey will
attempt to communicate with a dance partner who outweighs him by
900 pounds and does not have a steering wheel. In the case of the
colt Real Quiet and the jockey Kent Desormeaux, their artistry
could earn them the sport's 12th Triple Crown and a $5 million
bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Stevens, the jockey who last year narrowly failed in his
attempt to capture the Belmont Stakes and with it the Triple Crown
aboard Silver Charm, is back this year, but his role is reversed.
He will ride Victory Gallop, who finished second to Real Quiet in
the Kentucky Derby and Preakness Stakes and is considered the colt
with the best chance of an upset Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Belmont Stakes is the last and longest leg of the Triple
Crown. It is a demanding mile and a half around sprawling Belmont
Park. Stevens, 35, will call on years of experience to prepare for
the race and carry him through the long run of strategy and danger.
</P>
<P>
   Already over the last five weeks, Stevens, a riding prodigy and
Hall of Fame jockey who grew up the son of a horse trainer in
Idaho, has dealt with the tactics and tensions of the Triple
Crown's first two legs. He has monitored his weight, gauged the
quirks and undiscovered strengths of his mounts, and learned, as he
says, something new with each ride.
</P>
<P>
   Aboard the favored Indian Charlie in the Kentucky Derby, for
instance, Stevens said he could tell his horse was a likely loser
before he even walked into the gate. Indian Charlie finished third.
Then, after Indian Charlie was held out of the Preakness, Stevens
climbed aboard Victory Gallop, a horse he had never touched before.
Honoring the code among jockeys, Stevens did not consult with the
rider he had replaced. Instead, he studied a videotape of the Derby
and relied on his instincts.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews before and after the Derby and Preakness, Stevens,
along with Jerry Bailey, another Hall of Fame jockey, pulled back
the curtain to reveal a bit of the little-understood world of
jockey and race horse, allowing a glimpse into a modern version of
an ancient art, the communication between man and beast.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the gifts I feel I have is that I can get acquainted
with a horse in the 8 or 10 minutes of the post parade,'' Stevens
said. ``They're comfortable with me, I'm comfortable with them.
They gain my trust. I want to know their quirks, their
idiosyncrasies.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A jockey's preparation begins the night before the race, with a
weight-conscious meal. In the morning, the jockey reads The Daily
Racing Form to assess his mount's chances and the running styles of
the other horses. During the post parade, he begins the process of
reading his horse's body language: are his ears swirling like a
radar dish, alert to his surroundings? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once the race starts, the jockey balances himself on the balls
of his feet in the stirrups (he does not sit in the saddle),
hunches forward to grab the reins just behind the horse's neck and
guides his mount through a maze of flying hooves and dirt. He
steers the horse, often moving as fast as 37 miles an hour, with
tugs on the reins, which are attached to the bit, a piece of metal
that fits in the horse's mouth. The jockey must make split-second
decisions to get through holes that could close instantly, all
while fighting the temptation to move too soon, which could leave
his horse weary for the stretch drive. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I ride high in the saddle early on,'' Stevens said. ``As the
race progresses, and I get more physical _ it's like a locomotive.
You should be strongest the last eighth. In the stretch, you use
your forearms, your shoulders, your whole upper body more or
less.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey said he keeps tension in the reins, using them ``like a
fishing line.'' ``You let the reins run through your fingers,''
Bailey said. ``You give him his head. You pick up the bit, then
push with your arms.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To stay fit, jockeys strike a balance between strength and
weight. In most races, horses carry about 117 pounds, which
includes the saddle and the jockey's silks and boots. In Triple
Crown races, horses carry 126 pounds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to be able to wake up and go climb on a horse,'' said
Stevens, who now stretches before races. ``I'm as flexible as I was
before, but I have to work on it now.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bailey's diet is typical of a jockey's, but seems more suited
for a supermodel. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have coffee in the morning, with some toast, or a bagel,
or a muffin,'' he said. ``During the day, maybe I'll have an apple,
or a banana, or a candy bar, but not much. It's important for me to
eat dinner early. I can eat the same thing at 8 or at 6, but if I
eat late I'll weigh a pound more the next day. At special events,
like charity balls, I eat before I go, then get dressed up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Triple Crown began with the May 2 Kentucky Derby. Stevens
was riding Indian Charlie, the Santa Anita Derby winner, and
Bailey, 40, was on Cape Town, the Florida Derby winner. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned to expect the unexpected in the Kentucky Derby,''
Stevens said before the race. ``Even though you feel you know what
is going to happen, you don't take it for granted. Indian Charlie
hasn't been the greatest actor in the starting gate. I want to keep
him relaxed, yet alert. It's important to get a good break. This
race, nothing can go wrong. Everything has to be perfect. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This horse is difficult the first 100 yards,'' Stevens said.
``He pulls. But once he relaxes, I slide my hands back down to his
withers. That's where he seems comfortable. I don't want to pull
back, but I want to keep the bit in his mouth, secure.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the first turn, Stevens said, ``You assess who's in front of
you and who's behind you. If someone you expect to be in front of
you is not, you're smiling, because you know he's been taken out of
his game plan.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``On the backside,'' he added, ``you're assessing the time and
the pace and how much horse you've got. You assess the horses in
front of you and decide, Do I need to press or sit where I'm at? I
do it on instinct. You can't go in with a set game plan. You have
to adjust instantly and have a horse that can adjust instantly.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The morning of the Derby, Bailey arrived at the track just after
8, spent 15 minutes in the sauna and watched television. But he was
eager to ride in the early Churchill Downs races. It had rained
much of the week, and Bailey wanted to determine if the racecourse
had any biases _ was the inside drier, the backstretch deeper?
</P>
<P>
   Indian Charlie started from Post 8, just outside Favorite Trick,
a slot Stevens himself had selected. Both horses have early speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A race like this, with the tactics involved, I'd rather be
outside the other speed,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indian Charlie was undefeated going into the Derby, but Stevens,
a three-time winner of the race, saw signs, unseen by others during
the post parade, that shook his confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very, very quiet,'' he said of Indian Charlie.
``Usually he's active and full of himself. When they sing `My Old
Kentucky Home,' you know there's going to be an eruption from the
crowd at the end, so I grabbed some of his mane, but there was no
reaction from him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He broke clean,'' Stevens said. ``He relaxed real well off the
pace. He hit the three-eighths pole and got to the lead without
encouragement, but as Real Quiet moved toward me, I knew I didn't
have enough horse to put Indian Charlie into a drive at that point
and still finish in the top five. Midway around the turn, I knew I
was running for second money.''
</P>
<P>
   Indian Charlie did not hold on, finishing third behind Real
Quiet and Victory Gallop. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stevens said a tired horse feels ``like a car engine that's out
of gas. It's misfiring. There's no fuel. It would be like you
running five miles. After four, your legs might feel like Jell-O.
That's what it's like, like  &QC; Jell-O under you.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stevens used his whip on Indian Charlie, but not as extensively
as he did on Silver Charm in the stretch drive of their 1997 Derby
victory. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Silver Charm, I got after him a lot, but I wasn't striking him
hard. I was in rhythm with him. This horse,'' Stevens said,
referring to Indian Charlie, ``responds more to my hands. He's more
alert to what I want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Cape Town, meanwhile, started from Post 11. On the final turn,
``I got a thrill,'' Bailey said. ``Cape Town grabbed the bit and
followed Real Quiet to the quarter pole without me asking him a
lot. He was keeping up on his own. Real Quiet went on by Indian
Charlie big time. I asked Cape Town, but he was not able to hit
that extra gear. He got up to third behind Real Quiet, but he
didn't have it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cape Town finished fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, at the Preakness at Pimlico Race Course, Cape
Town and Bailey were back for Round 2 of the Triple Crown, but
Indian Charlie was not. His trainer, Bob Baffert, determined the
colt was worn out by the Derby. Stevens, however, was chosen to
replace Alex Solis on Victory Gallop. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Alex and I are very close,'' Stevens said the day before the
Preakness.. ``Obviously, I feel bad for him. ``But it's happened to
me before, just like it's happened to Alex, and it will happen
again. I'm not an idiot. I'm not going to say, `No, I don't want to
ride the horse because Alex is my friend.''' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stevens had never ridden Victory Gallop, but felt he could not
go over strategy with Solis. Only if a jockey loses his mount
because of injury, and not against his will, is it appropriate to
consult, Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens thus watched replays of the Kentucky Derby to learn what
he could do with Victory Gallop, and relied on his innate ability.
He wanted only minimal instructions from the horse's trainer,
Elliott Walden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to go out there with an open mind,'' Stevens said.
``You don't know what kind of hand you're going to be dealt until
you get out there on the race track and are warming up. I've
noticed a big difference with all three of my Derby winners coming
from Kentucky to Baltimore. Even with the win here last year with
Silver Charm, he wasn't the same horse that I'd ridden in the
Derby. You just hope they can come back to near their form. I think
it's kind of foolish to hope that a horse moves forward after the
Kentucky Derby. It defies logic.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The day before the Preakness, the early favorite, the speedy
Coronado's Quest, was scratched. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stevens initially said he would not change his strategy of
laying back and taking advantage of Victory Gallop's ``devastating
kick.'' But the next day he reconsidered. Believing the only horse
he had to beat was Real Quiet, Stevens used Victory Gallop during
the early portion of the race to keep Real Quiet and his jockey,
Desormeaux, wide. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Real Quiet looked a picture saddling in the infield. I knew it
was going to be a horse race,'' Stevens said. Warming up, Stevens
found Victory Gallop ``lively, but kind at the same time.'' His
ears were moving about, a sign of intelligence and curiosity, and
he responded to the slightest of tugs on the reins. ``Certain
horses, you get on them, and you know they're not comfortable. He
felt like my old Porsche.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as we turned up the backside, Kent was four wide,''
Stevens said, pleased he had kept his rival wide. ``I was one off
the fence. Kent started creeping up. He had a half-length on me.
There was a gap between two horses in front of me. I used my horse
to get up in there and force Kent wide. I angled out sharply. I
didn't want to get caught behind dying horses at the quarter pole. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Approaching the quarter pole, I asked him for his best run,
and he responded. Two strides later, Kent went by me. I knew Real
Quiet wasn't going to stop. You just concede defeat and try to get
second.'' Victory Gallop held on for second. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cape Town, meanwhile, struggled at the back of the pack. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You want a horse reaching out, hitting the ground and reaching
out. A horse in discomfort won't reach out,'' Bailey said.
``There's a shortness of stride, a roughness to his gait. He wears
out quickly. When that happens, you just try to get him home safely
and see what the problem is.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cape Town finished ninth among 10 horses. X-rays later revealed
a fractured bone in the horse's ankle. Cape Town was retired. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bailey will be back in the Belmont aboard one of the trainer D.
Wayne Lukas' two starters, either Grand Slam or Yarrow Brae. Having
changed tactics in the Preakness, Stevens said he would ride
Victory Gallop in the Belmont the same way Solis did in the Derby. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``By changing his style,'' Stevens said, ``I might have taken
away his final punch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
