u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHUTTLE-MIR-HNS &LR;      06-03 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-MIR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCOVERY NEARS FINAL MIR LINKUP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The shuttle Discovery on Wednesday sailed closer to a
final U.S. linkup with Russia's Mir space station, a potentially
historic event that may unfold largely without live television from
NASA.
</P>
<P>
   The two spacecraft were to join Thursday while soaring 240 miles
above Earth. It was the ninth shuttle trip to Mir.
</P>
<P>
   NASA is accustomed to beaming live television views of its
astronauts to Earth almost at will through the satellite
communications network it fully established nearly a decade ago.
However, a puzzling problem with a dish-shaped communications
antenna aboard Discovery has prevented the shuttle astronauts from
transmitting live video since blasting off two days ago.
</P>
<P>
   If U.S. ground control teams are unable to pinpoint the
difficulty, they will have to rely on the Russians for sporadic
live video of the linkup and a post-docking ceremony scheduled to
follow aboard Mir. It may also be possible for the shuttle crew to
transmit video for brief periods over an FM link to ground stations
in California, Florida and Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may not be as much as we have had in the past, and that
will be disappointing for us,'' said Lee Briscoe, NASA's mission
operations director. ``We're all looking forward to it, seeing as
how it's the last flight. But we will just have to cope.''
</P>
<P>
   Engineers believed the difficulty was with an ``on-off'' switch
within the antenna that could be bypassed by the astronauts with a
rerouting of power cables. But NASA was reluctant to attempt a
major repair before today's docking.
</P>
<P>
   The same antenna also functions as the radar transmitter and
receiver the shuttle crew will use during Thursday's rendezvous
activities with Mir. A post-launch test of the antenna in the radar
mode revealed it was unaffected by the switch problem, Briscoe
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Discovery crew plans to retrieve U.S. astronaut Andy Thomas,
who has been living and working aboard Mir since late January. He
is the last of seven Americans assigned to live and work aboard the
Russian outpost as part of a cooperative program to prepare the two
countries for the upcoming assembly of a new international space
station.
</P>
<P>
   Asleep when Discovery blasted off, Thomas was elated early
Wednesday when he learned the shuttle was safely on its way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, excellent,'' he told NASA personnel at the Russian control
center in suburban Moscow when informed. ``You're a saint to get on
the (communications network) and tell me that.''
</P>
<P>
   Temporarily, Discovery's antenna difficulties prevented an eager
team of ground-based physicists from monitoring the readings of an
experimental observatory aboard Discovery called the Alpha Magnetic
Spectrometer.
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday, the shuttle crew managed to rewire its
communications so that it could transmit directly to several ground
stations for brief periods each day. Meanwhile, all of the AMS
findings are being recorded aboard Discovery for post-flight
assessments.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially a 7,000 pound barrel-shaped magnet equipped with
electronic sensors and mounted in Discovery's payload bay, the AMS
was developed to search for evidence of cosmic antimatter.
</P>
<P>
   Some theorists believe that equal quantities of normal matter
and antimatter were created with an explosive event dubbed the Big
Bang that marked the creation of the universe billions of years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Cosmic antimatter, if it exists, has so far escaped detection by
astronomers. Nonetheless, some cosmologists believe it may exist as
antistars or antigalaxies in the distant universe.
</P>
<P>
   The AMS is searching for stray remnants of antimatter created by
the big bang as they race through space near the Earth in the form
of cosmic ray particles with electrical charges opposite those of
normal matter. Electrons, for instance, would be positively charged
and called positrons. Antimatter protons would be negatively
charged and called antiprotons.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists believe that antimatter particles may be so rare that
it will require at least a three-year stay by the AMS aboard the
new international space station to detect it in significant
quantities. The observatory was launched aboard Discovery as a test
flight to ensure it can function reliably aboard the orbital
laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
