A3024 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LIFEGUARD-SHORTAGE     06-03 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LIFEGUARD-SHORTAGE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY FINDS TOO FEW LIFEGUARDS FOR SUMMER CROWDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
 (ja)  
 By MONTE WILLIAMS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This one has city officials stumped: Why are there
not enough lifeguards to staff New York City's seven beaches and 55
outdoor pools, despite an aggressive recruitment initiative?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're simply not optimistic,'' said Alan Moss, the first
deputy commissioner for the Department of Parks and Recreation, the
agency that recruits the expert swimmers. ``There's a genuine
shortage of qualified lifeguards.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though his agency has the budgeted to hire 1,200 lifeguards
each summer, the city has hired only about 400 this year, with
summer less than three weeks away. As a result, since the Memorial
Day beach openings, large sections of the city's beachfront have
been closed, presenting a hardship for bathers and vendors alike.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is so dire that for the first time the city is
allowing nonresidents to apply for the lifeguard jobs, which pay
$8.64 an hour for 48-hour weeks. Furthermore, the Parks Department
has recruited in high schools and colleges in New Jersey,
Connecticut, Long Island and Westchester.
</P>
<P>
   Moss said that with the robust economy, high school and college
students are finding more lucrative jobs that also give them more
leisure time. He also said that there may be a shortage of
candidates because high schools do not emphasize swimming the way
they used to.
</P>
<P>
   But J.D. LaRock, a spokesman for the Board of Education, pointed
out that there has been an increase in the number of swim teams in
city high schools, up to 74 this year from 68 last year. Still only
29 of the city's 208 high schools have swimming pools.
</P>
<P>
   Besides placing ads in 12 local newspapers and magazines and
having the mayor announce openings on his weekly radio program, the
Parks Department has arranged a tie-in with a ``Baywatch'' event on
April 22 in Washington Square Park, in which two of the shows
stars, Michael Bergin and Angelica Bridges made appearances and
urged people to try out for the city's lifeguard positions.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Brooklyn Borough president, Howard Golden, who held a
news conference Wednesday on the Coney Island Boardwalk to
criticize the city's failure to prepare the beach for summer, said
he does not think the Parks Department is doing enough to combat
the lifeguard drought.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a dismal failure,'' Golden said. ``On Memorial Day
10 out of 22 bays were closed here in Coney Island. What's needed
is borough-wide, year-round recruitment.''
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, in which he complained about the
condition of Coney Island's boardwalk and public restroom
facilities, Golden advocated moving lifeguard hiring from the
Park's Department to another agency, perhaps the Board of
Education.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't seem to be able to get their act together,'' he
said of the Parks Department. ``They should provide training year
round for people interested in the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Reichenthal, the district manager of Community Board 13,
which covers Coney Island, said the lifeguard problem has hurt
business for local vendors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get complaints from people in the community and
businesses,'' he said. ``What was the point of replenishing the
beaches? We have long, clean beaches waiting for swimming. People
from Staten Island like one section of the beach and when people
come and find out the section they like is closed, they get upset.
If they have to walk seven blocks to the beach because a section is
closed, they might not come back.''
</P>
<P>
   In order to qualify for the city's week-long, 40-hour lifeguard
course _ passing it guarantees the job _ one must be at least 16
years old, able to swim 50 yards in 35 seconds, have at least 20/40
to 20/30 unaided vision, and have a doctor's note stating that he
or she is in good physical condition. To pass the 40-hour course,
applicants must be able to swim 440 yards in 6 minutes and 40
seconds for beach patrol, and be able to swim 440 yards in 7
minutes and 40 seconds for pool patrol.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't compromise public safety,'' said Henry Stern, the
parks commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that the Parks Department only hired 870
lifeguards last year, so parts of some beaches were closed. ``But
there was no drowning on our watch,'' he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
