<SLUG> BC-BOEING-KOREAN-ORDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOREAN AIR WON'T DELAY ORDER FOR 27 BOEING 737 JETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (dc) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Korean Air, bucking a trend that has seen many Asian airlines
delay orders for new airplanes as a result of the region's economic
crisis, plans to announce next week that it is buying 27 new Boeing
737 passenger jets valued at $1.35 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The new order is expected to be announced Tuesday during the
state visit to Washington of South Korea's newly elected president,
Kim Dae Jung. It is good news for Boeing, which said only last week
that weakening demand from Asia would force it to cut production of
the 747 jumbo jet next year.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Asian economy went into a tailspin last summer,
airline passenger traffic in the region has plunged as well. In the
last week alone, Malaysian Airline System said that it would delay
delivery of several Boeing 747 and 777 airplanes and Taiwan's Eva
Airways, dropped plans to buy at least six long-range A340 aircraft
worth $900 million built by Airbus Industrie, Boeing's archrival.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is also concerned that an order it is expecting to get
from China during President Clinton's state visit there later this
month will be smaller than the company had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are extremely pleased that Korean Air is exercising
leadership in Asia by stepping forward, even during difficult
times, with this order,'' said Carie Cable, a Boeing spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   But selling the single-aisle, twin-engine 737 is not nearly as
lucrative for Boeing as selling wide-body models like the 747 and
777. And Boeing apparently gambled that by the time Korean Air
begins taking delivery of the planes in 2000, Asia's economic
crisis will be over.
</P>
<P>
   Yang Ho Cho, Korean Air's chief executive, said in an interview
that the airline, which is a subsidiary of the Hanjin Group and is
already heavily in debt, has had trouble borrowing overseas since
South Korea's economy collapsed last year. He said Boeing was
willing to accept a smaller down payment for the new planes, giving
the airline time to arrange financing later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe by the year 2000, when our economic situation
improves, financial institutions will offer to finance it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Cho added, Korean Air, too, may have to consider
delaying its purchase of new wide-body jets. The airline plans to
receive a total of 10 747s and 777s and Airbus A330s this year and
a combination of 11 more in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking at right now,'' he said. ``It depends on the
economic situation. We have the option to delay.''
</P>
<P>
   Cho said that the new 737-800 and 737-900 aircraft will replace
26 older Fokker and McDonnell Douglas narrow-body jets. They will
be flown domestically and on routes to China, Japan and
destinations in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Korean Air already flies to dozens of cities in China and it is
betting heavily on China's future economic growth. Cho said that
with the completion of a new international airport in Inchon in
2000, South Korea had the potential to become a major hub
connecting travelers from North America to China.
</P>
<P>
   The new airplanes, which have a longer range and are more fuel
efficient than Korean Air's current narrow-body fleet, will also
lower the airline's maintenance costs and give it more flexibility.
Right now the airline must use a 250-seat Airbus to fly from Seoul
to Ho Chi Minh City because it does not have a smaller plane that
can fly the distance.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts suggested that the order was a way for South Korea
to thank the United States for supporting the $50 billion bailout
the country received from the International Monetary Fund. Cho said
that the timing of the order and President Kim's visit was ``just a
coincidence.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``Probably President Kim will be proud to talk
about this with President Clinton when they meet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
