<HEADER>
A3033 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ORANGE-COUNTY-760&AMP;ADD     06-03 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORANGE-COUNTY-760&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGING INDUSTRY FORCED MERRILL LYNCH TO RETHINK ORANGE COUNTY
SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Calif.) (js) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE with ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the day, more than three years ago, when Orange County,
Calif., shocked the world of finance and filed for bankruptcy, to
the announcement this week that Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.had agreed to
pay $400 million to settle litigation for its role in that matter,
Merrill has maintained its innocence.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, until it agreed to write the check, Merrill had kept a
combative stance _ refusing to fire any employees involved in the
Orange County disaster, hiring platoons of lawyers to defend itself
and keeping up a public relations campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But in the intervening years, much has changed, even though
Merrill continues to assert its innocence. Those changes, say some,
explain why Merrill, around a month ago, signaled to Orange County
that it was ready to negotiate in earnest to head off a scheduled
September trial in a $2 billion lawsuit brought by the county. The
lawsuit alleged Merrill had sold speculative securities, in
violation of California law, to a county-run investment pool that
lost $1.6 billion after making a wrong-way bet on interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, Merrill was finding itself shut out of much
municipal business in California and its reputation as a municipal
bond underwriter and financial adviser was tarnished throughout the
country by this episode. A trial with headlines that would put the
phrase ``investment losses'' in the same sentence as Merrill Lynch
would only rekindle much of this bad publicity just as it was
beginning to die out.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, at a time when the financial services industry is
being reshaped by multibillion-dollar mergers of Wall Street
brokers, like Merrill, and banks and insurance companies, Merrill
would find it easier to be a player in this merger game, either as
a buyer or seller, with no major lawsuits still outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Under its chief executive, David Komansky, Merrill has been a
leading lobbyist in Washington for legislation that would eliminate
many of the regulatory barriers to these mergers and allow them to
proceed more easily. ``From Merrill's point of view, the more
publicity that they would get from Orange County, the worse it
would get for them,'' said Raphael Soifer, an analyst at Brown
Brothers Harriman. ``They were facing the publicity of a long trial
and, also, the uncertain outcome of a home town jury. It seems like
settling would be the reasonable thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   James Spiotto, municipal finance attorney at Chapman &AMP; Cutler in
Chicago, added: ``Right now, Orange County is far enough in the
memory for lots of people that it's like water over the dam.
Merrill wants to keep it behind them.''
</P>
<P>
   Settlement talks between attorneys for Merrill and for Orange
County began in earnest around three weeks ago, after the country
had already gained $172 million from three lesser defendants, KPMG
Peat Marwick, Credit Suisse First Boston and LeBoeuf, Lamb, Green &AMP;
MacRae. Mediation talks, under local rules in federal court in
California, are mandatory, but are not binding on the parties. In
those talks, however, Thomas Hayes, the former California state
treasurer who heads Orange County's litigation effort, said it
``became clear it was a difficult lawsuit that could go either way
before a jury.''
</P>
<P>
   George Schieren, Merrill's general counsel, said: ``The question
for us was whether you are better off with the certainty of a
negotiation or risk the uncertainty of a trial. This has nothing to
do with how we feel about our conduct. A jury could see it
differently. We made a decision that we were much better off with
the certainty of a settlement. We took the mediation process
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   A settlement, even as large as $400 million, clears Merrill to
proceed more easily in the emerging financial marketplace _ freed
from having to go before shareholders and boards of directors of
companies they might wish to acquire or join and provide guesses of
their dollar exposure in Orange County and, again, explain their
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's the argument, and it's all very speculative, that
Merrill is folding its cards quickly to clear the decks,'' said
Samuel Liss, an analyst with Credit Suisse First Boston. This year,
Merrill has taken new strategic steps, spending $7 billion to
acquire Mercury Asset Management, a London-based firm, and taking
an equity stake in the former Yamaichi Securities in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   According to Merrill, the $400 million payment will not hurt
earnings, nor will it affect employee compensation. Schieren said
that reserves had already been set aside to fully cover this and
that any impact on earnings had already been felt.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Still unresolved, however, is a potential Securities and
Exchange Commission action against Merrill. Merrill has confirmed
the SEC has authorized its staff to bring an enforcement action
over allegations of lax disclosure in Merrill's role as an
underwriter of Orange County debt. Merrill has already paid $30
million to Orange County to settle a separate criminal case _ and,
now, is fighting in to keep all documents related to that case out
of the public domain.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Stamenson, the Merrill securities salesman at the center
of the scandal, is still employed at Merrill's San Francisco
office. ``He's working full time on the litigation,'' Schieren,
Merrill's lawyer, said.
</P>
<P>
   For some in Orange County, the settlement is good news,
especially since a strong Orange County economy has softened the
blow of the investment losses. ``It's a major settlement,'' said
Paul Brady, city manager of Irvine, Calif., ``It far exceeds our
expectations when we first got into it. And, when we look at the
county four years later, it's basically business as usual.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 2130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
