<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHIPS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   Chip Sales To Slip, But Rebound Next Year  
   
 By Dan Fost  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
A glut of memory chips, economic woes in Asia and slowing sales of
personal computers have dimmed the luster of the semiconductor
industry, but not its confidence.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Industry sales will slip 1.8 percent this year, but should
rebound to double-digit growth next year, according to a report
released yesterday by the Semiconductor Industry Association, a
trade group based in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   The group expects all the conditions that have dragged down the
chip market to reverse course by near year. It cited potential
growth in China leading a revitalized Asia, a long-awaited recovery
for the memory chip market, and renewed growth in PC sales. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ninety percent of chip companies around the world contributed
their forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   The downturn in the chip industry has been painfully evident
this year with significant job reductions at Bay Area chipmakers
Intel, National Semiconductor and Cypress Semiconductor and chip
equipment manufacturers Applied Materials and Lam Research.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the turnaround won't come overnight, chip companies
expressed optimism that their business is just going through a
temporary down cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a couple of difficult quarters, but we do expect to
be working our way out of them,'' said Steve Tobak, vice president
of corporate marketing for Santa Clara-based National Semi. ``On
the whole, National should be bouncing back with the rest of the
industry, starting with the second half (of this year) and into
1999.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Intel, the industry leader with a microprocessor market
share approaching 90 percent, has seen flat growth for the past
year, and expects the trend to continue through the current
quarter, which ends June 30.
</P>
<P>
   Intel blames slower growth in PC sales, and the move to PCs that
sell for less than $1,000, which means less money for the
chipmakers. In addition, sales in Asia in general and Japan in
particular _ once powerful markets for the chip companies _ have
taken a tumble following the currency crises in several Asian
nations.
</P>
<P>
   While last year's forecast predicted sales to rise 24 percent in
Asia in 1998, revised figures put the growth at 3.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide semiconductor sales grew 4 percent in 1997. With this
year's anticipated 1.8 percent drop, they should hit $134.6 billion
for 1998, the association said.
</P>
<P>
   But with growth reaching 17 percent or better in each of the
next three years, the association expects sales to top $222 billion
by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts at Dataquest in San Jose agree with that view
_ particularly the notion that an oversupply of memory chips has
dragged the whole market down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing lower prices today than even the most pessimistic
observers anticipated six months ago,'' said Dataquest analyst
Nathan Brookwood. ``We're seeing ads now for $1 a megabyte, where
it was $20 a megabyte for four years.''
</P>
<P>
   For consumers, Brookwood said, ``That is just awesome.'' For the
memory chip companies, he said, ``It's not pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the memory chip companies are based in Korea and Japan,
with only one major U.S. supplier, Micron Corp. of Boise, Idaho.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
