<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MCARTHUR-WINNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTIVIST CALLS MCARTHUR FELLOWSHIP A `CHALLENGE GRANT' 
</HEADLINE>
   (ja)  
 By JOYCE WADLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK_ It's bad manners to ask, but when you come across an
activist raised in Oyster Bay and educated in private school who
has devoted her entire working life to human rights, you can't help
but pose the question:
</P>
<P>
   Is there a private income?
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you kidding?'' Dorothy Thomas asks, practically hooting.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is Ms. Thomas, just named a recipient of a $245,000
MacArthur Fellowship for her work in women's rights, going to argue
that the award, paid out over five years at $49,000 a year before
taxes, is not very much money.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not gonna catch me saying that,'' said Ms. Thomas, the
sort of feminist who disdains makeup but is willing to joke about
it. ``To me it's like a challenge grant. No, you know what it is?
License to make a whole heap of trouble. I still can't believe I
got it. Saying I was completely flabbergasted would be the most
minimal way of putting it. I was blown away. I'm still in recovery
from the news.''
</P>
<P>
   The MacArthur Foundation awards grants to 20 to 30 people a year
for work that, in the words of the awards committee, ``helps foster
improvement in the human condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Thomas, 38, who has just begun a job as a consultant with
the Shaler-Adams Women's Human Rights Foundation, was the director
of the Women's Rights Project of Human Rights Watch for eight
years. She received her award for ``helping to redefine
international standards of human rights and making abuses against
women, including domestic violence, a matter of international human
rights law.'' Ms. Thomas investigated violence against women in
Brazil. She has edited reports, as she puts it, ``on every horrible
subject regarding the violations of women's rights you can
imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps Ms. Thomas's most inventive work, which she hopes to
continue with the MacArthur grant, was using international law to
improve the rights of American women in prison. The United States,
Ms. Thomas said, is one of the few countries in which women are
guarded by men _ a system that frequently leads to sexual
exploitation and abuse. There were, however, U.N. resolutions,
which the United States has signed, that offered a way to apply
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to use the U.N. to expose human rights abuse in the
U.S., which doesn't happen too often,'' Ms. Thomas said. ``We now
have an investigator from the U.N. looking into conditions in
American prisons. You don't usually think of U.N. officials coming
here. The United States has one of most active women's movements in
the world and it hasn't explored the use of international pressure.
To me it's a given that everything is going global.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Thomas lives in a sunny rental apartment in Chelsea with a
man she refers to as ``my companion.''
</P>
<P>
   Is the unmarried state a political comment on marriage or hasn't
the subject come up?
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't come up,'' Ms. Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of makeup?
</P>
<P>
   ``A family trait,'' said Ms. Thomas, whose parents divorced when
she was 3. ``I grew up in a feminist family. You know, women are
caught between reality and appearances. The reality is we're
second-class citizens. Let's change the reality: don't waste a lot
of time putting on makeup. My grandmother was a suffragette. She
was always saying, `You can't just be in the world. You have to
better the world.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Thomas graduated from Portledge, a private school in Locust
Valley, which her mother founded, then received bachelor's and
master's degrees from Georgetown University in literary theory and
women's studies. After college, she worked in the anti-apartheid
movement and lived in Namibia, monitoring its independence from
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw people voting for the first time in their history,'' Ms.
Thomas said. ``But even in this incredibly visionary struggle,
women were almost invisible.''
</P>
<P>
   Concern for women's issues has dominated Ms. Thomas' life.
Though she has traveled to a half dozen countries and says she has
seen terrible things, she is uncomfortable telling the stories of
specific women _ even without using names _ because she fears it
will be exploitive.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed to shed some light on her work, she finally, after two
hours, tells the story of one woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three weeks after I graduated college, one of my best friends
was raped and murdered,'' Ms. Thomas said. ``Her body was found on
a bridle path in D.C. I think it devastated me, but it also
challenged me. It made me realize this is a problem affecting all
women, directly or indirectly, and I didn't want to live in a world
like that, where it could happen over and over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the 25th anniversary of the admission of women to
Georgetown University, I was invited to give the commencement
address,'' Ms. Thomas continued. ``I used it as an opportunity to
remember Catherine Schilling, my friend. To discuss, you know,
evil. To say, `It's not just out there. It's in here. My friend was
sitting exactly where you are sitting today and if you don't want
to live in the world where there is that kind of violence against
women, you're going to have to do something about it.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``That sort of violence can suck the meaning out of life,'' Ms.
Thomas said. ``For me, it was just the opposite. All of my activism
was a way to make that one act have some meaning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
