<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLOCAUST SURVIVORS SUE GERMAN BANKS OVER LOOTED GOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (ja)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Deutsche Bank and Dresdner Bank, two large German
banks that the State Department revealed on Tuesday trafficked in
gold the Nazis stole from European Jews during World War II, were
sued Wednesday by three Holocaust survivors.
</P>
<P>
   One plaintiff, Harold Watman, 77, of Queens, said that his gold
teeth were pulled out of his mouth without anesthesia by Nazis at
Auschwitz, according to the suit filed in U.S. District Court in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The class action lawsuit is the first to expand claims by
Holocaust survivors seeking to recover looted gold beyond Swiss
banks.
</P>
<P>
   Dresdner Bank said it had not seen the suit and had no comment,
and Deutsche bank did not respond to messages Wednesday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 2134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0481 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3041 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHY-WORMS-TEX     06-03 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHY-WORMS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S THE NEWEST UNDERGROUND HIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To paraphrase James Brown, it's a worm's, worm's, worm's, worm's
world.
</P>
<P>
   In Godzilla, Matthew Broderick plays earthworm expert Dr. Niko
Tatopolous, known to his peers as ``the worm guy.'' Far Side
cartoonist Gary Larson just published ``There's a Hair in My Dirt!
A Worm's Story,'' a sort of worm fairy tale. Also on bookstands
now: ``The Worm Book: The Complete Guide to Gardening and
Composting With Worms.''
</P>
<P>
   What's up with worms, anyway? Just little things, like sex and
death, apparently.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can take the Jungian psychology point of view: Certain
shapes attract the eye,'' says Noreen Damude, nongame biologist for
the Texas Department of Parks and Wildlife. Damude, who says she
specializes in birds but answers ``all the critter questions,''
says that worms attract us ``for the same reasons snakes both
fascinate and fill us with fear and loathing at the same time.
There are archetypal shapes in nature that are attractive but give
us goose bumps on our back.''
</P>
<P>
   Um, that sorta takes care of the sex part, we guess. What about
death?
</P>
<P>
   ``They're symbols of death and mortality in that we turn to
dust, and worms are one of the major agents in our returning,''
Damude says. ``We arise from dust and we return to dust, and worms
speed up the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Uh, yuck. But really, worms are our friends. They keep the soil
fertile, and they're useful in catching fish. Here are some other
useful things to know about worms.
</P>
<P>
   What is a worm, anyway? According to the Encyclopedia Americana,
``worm'' is a general term for many unrelated animals with soft,
slender, elongated bodies lacking backbones (sort of like some
people we know). They range from 0.02 inches to more than 10 feet
long.
</P>
<P>
   Worms are big business. Among the many worm Web sites is one for
Magicord _ The Wonder Worm! (www.vermicentral.com/magicord.com),
reportedly the BEST fishing bait in the world. A case of 60
two-worm containers goes for $213. Another site is J&AMP;C's Dairy
Worms (no, you don't milk 'em, you use 'em in the soil) at
www.humboldt1.com/dairyworms. If you're really in the mood for
worms, you can buy 2,000 for $28 retail, plus shipping and
handling.
</P>
<P>
   Worms make words. Many words have wormy roots: vermicelli (from
the Italian for ``little worm''), vermin (from the Latin for
``worm''), vermouth (from the German word for ``wormwood'').
</P>
<P>
   Worms form phrases. Examples: ``can of worms,'' an unpleasant
problem; ``you worm,'' directed at a loathsome person; ``the worm
has turned,'' the situation has reversed; ``worm's-eye view,'' the
outlook from a close range but a menial position.
</P>
<P>
   Worms can be bad for you. You don't want a tapeworm in your
digestive tract, nor do you want your pet to have heartworms.
</P>
<P>
   Worms can be good for you. Leeches, which fall under the worm
umbrella, are especially useful in treating some hematomas.
Patients shocked by high medical bills have also been known to call
their doctors ``leeches.''
</P>
<P>
   Worms for dessert. You can have Gummi Worms straight up, or mix
them into chocolate pudding and crumbled Oreos for a dish called
Worms and Dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Worms in your beverages. If you drink tequila, you're not really
macho unless you eat the worm.
</P>
<P>
   People just love to play with worms. One of the most popular
video games is Earthworm Jim, which already has one sequel and
another due out soon. Worms 2 MicroProse is a CD-ROM game in which
you control an army of worms.
</P>
<P>
   Worms are cinematic. The best worm movie of all time is
undoubtedly ``Tremors,'' in which Kevin Bacon and Fred Ward play a
couple of not-too-bright guys leading a small desert town in a
battle against giant earthworms. Other worm movies: ``Squirm''
(1976), ``Lair of the White Worm'' (1988, based on a Bram Stoker
novel), and, of course, ``Tremors 2: Aftershocks'' (1996). Worms
also figured in ``Eraserhead'' and ``Dune,'' both directed by David
Lynch. Coincidence? We think not.
</P>
<P>
   Worms are literary. Bookworms might be familiar with Edgar Allan
Poe's ``The Conqueror Worm.''
</P>
<P>
   Worms are athletic. Cross-dressing, hair-dying basketball star
Dennis Rodman is known as ``The Worm.''
</P>
<P>
   Worms are musical. Danny Kaye sang ``Inchworm'' in the movie
``Hans Christian Andersen.'' The Mills Brothers had a hit with
``Glow Worm.'' But hold on a minute. ``Those are not worms, those
are butterfly larvae,'' Damude says. ``Just because it's called a
worm doesn't make it a worm. Glowworm is another word for firefly,
which is not a fly; it's a beetle.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, then, how about the Pink Floyd song ``Waiting for the
Worms,'' or the popular ditty Eat Worms: ``Nobody likes me,
everybody hates me, I'm gonna eat some worms.''
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot receives e-mail at robp\Nstar-telegram.com Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
