<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-THREEGORGES _ Every day 18,000 Chinese mobilize to build
the most powerful _ and most disparaged _ hydroelectric dam in the
world. Each day they crunch more rocks, dig deeper pits, pour more
and more concrete for the edifice that within five years will
stretch 1.4 miles across the Yangtze River and create a mammoth
reservoir 370 miles long. With swells of national pride, some
Chinese call this dam the modern Great Wall. But it is not a place
that politically cautious visitors like President Clinton _ soon
due to spend nine days in China _ will come and admire as a new
national icon. (Kunstel/Albright, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With THREEGORGES-SIDE _ BADONG, China _ In their spick-and-span,
open-front shop, a patient Chinese couple sat on a humid afternoon
waiting for their future to happen. Their one-room storefront was
new, brimming with sundries from shampoo to socks. Their street was
new and five-story building perched on the hillside was new. The
problem for Li Damin and his wife was that no cars traveled the
street, no people strolled past to eye their wares. Few others had
moved in yet from the old town's shabby riverfront that in five
years will disappear under muddy water. (Kunstel/Albright, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   SIBERIA-COLA _ KRASNOYARSK, Russia _ A local beverage company in
the heart of Siberia has taken on Goliath, challenging the
production and marketing might of Coca-Cola. The Russian company,
Pikra, may have lost its senses, but not its sense of humor.
``Everyone knows it is a joke to go against Coca-Cola. So we called
ours `Crazy Cola,''' says the boss, Yevgenia Kuznetsova. Even
crazier, she adds, Crazy Cola is showing a profit a year after it
was introduced, finding a small niche in a domestic market
increasingly keen to buy Russian-made goods. Yet Coca-Cola's thirst
for domination of the international soft-drink market extends even
to this desolate part of the world. A new Coke bottling plant, one
of four new plants opened in Russia last year, stands at the edge
of Krasnoyarsk, a regional capital in Siberia. Coke last year
became the No. 1 soft-drink in Russia. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
