<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FTC-INTERNET-250&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FTC TO PROPOSE LAWS TO PROTECT CHILDREN ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   (bl)  
 By AMY HARMON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amid mounting public concern about the abuse of personal data in
an increasingly digital world, the Federal Trade Commission is
expected to censure the Internet industry Wednesday in a report to
Congress for doing virtually nothing to insure adequate consumer
privacy protection online.
</P>
<P>
   In a departure from the Clinton administration's hands-off
approach to the Internet, the agency will call for legislation that
would require sites on the World Wide Web to obtain parental
consent before collecting personal information from children,
according to the report. The FTC said it would make recommendations
on privacy for other Web users this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children are told by parents not to talk to strangers whom
they meet on the street, but they are given a contrary message by
Web sites that encourage them to interact with strangers in their
homes via the Web,'' the report says.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Edward Markey, D-Mass., said, ``This is a historic
benchmark that changes forever the discussion of the protections
which children need in a cyberera.''
</P>
<P>
   In a study of 1,400 Web sites in March, the FTC found that 85
percent collect personal information but only 14 percent provide
any notice about what they do with the data. Only 2 percent provide
such notice with a comprehensive privacy policy, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those numbers are frightening,'' he said. ``If privacy
protections are not built into Internet commerce, then a vast
majority of Americans will never trust the Internet.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although few had seen the long-anticipated report Wednesday,
news leaks about it added fuel to a heated debate among industry
leaders and privacy advocates about how to address privacy
concerns. Several companies and trade associations rushed to blunt
the effect of the report with announcements of new policies.
</P>
<P>
   Technology trade groups representing more than 10,000 companies
sent President Clinton a letter asking for a chance to allow
self-regulation work.
</P>
<P>
   And the Direct Marketing Association touted its own study, which
showed that 70 percent of the top 100 children's Web sites publish
a privacy policy. The group, which has lobbied against legislation,
said late Wednesday that it had adopted a new policy to seek
parental consent for online marketing involving children younger
than 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is business stepping up to the plate, moving in the
direction that it needs to, and that is how self-regulation
works,'' said Connie Heatley, senior vice president of the
association.
</P>
<P>
   For many companies trying to do business on the Internet, the
entire promise of the medium rests on the ease with which it allows
the collection of information for focusing advertising and
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Based on forms that consumers fill out when they first visit a
site, or on simply tracking which areas of a site they visit most
frequently, Web site owners can, for example, determine which
advertisements to show them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's not customized and personalized, it might as well be
television,'' said David Card, a senior analyst at Jupiter
Communications, an online consulting operation in New York. ``I'm
nervous that we'll get stuck with a law that would eliminate the
technical ability to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, consumers have continually expressed fears about what
happens to information that they provide in cyberspace. Anxiety
about the use of of medical and financial information online is one
of the top reasons people do not use the Internet, according to
several recent polls.
</P>
<P>
   And some companies have decided that electronic commerce would
be more helped than hurt by ending such practices.
</P>
<P>
   America Online, which has been much-criticized for privacy
lapses, said Wednesday that it would not use the information that
it gathers about what members do online for any marketing purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can be extremely valuable information in the
marketplace,'' said Jill Lesser, AOL's deputy director for law and
public policy. ``The ability to target consumers is extremely
valuable. But you have to strike a balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lesser added: ``It's hard to fault the FTC for calling a
spade a spade. Hopefully this will be a catalyst for companies to
look at privacy protection as a business imperative.''
</P>
<P>
   But government action is needed, privacy advocates said, because
children have never been more more vulnerable to commercial
exploitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're creating a new children's culture, and if we don't set
ground rules for how that's done, we could see a whole set of very
egregious, manipulative practices that could do a lot of harm to
kids,'' said Kathryn C. Montgomery, president of the Center for
Media Education, a child advocacy group. ``And this new culture
could turn toxic.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem with many sites aimed at children is that they make
divulging information seem like a game, Ms. Montgomery said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Popsicle Web site, published by the Good
Humor-Breyers Ice Cream unit of Unilever, asks children to choose
whether they want to be commanders or passengers. Just one catch:
Commanders have to fill out their age, sex, favorite TV show and
favorite popsicle before blasting off.
</P>
<P>
   And in case anyone was inclined to just go along for the ride,
the passenger option cautions, ``Sure, you can ride in the big
stuffed chair, but you'll miss out on the chance to win free
Popsicles. Plus it's really cold in outer space without a
Spaceship. Why not be a commander?''
</P>
<P>
   Popsicle's privacy policy says that it does not release the data
it gathers to third parties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
