<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3051 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-XEROXPARC-SFCHRON &LR;      06-03 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XEROXPARC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Xerox vows to profit from marketing mistakes   By Jamie Beckett  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Xerox PARC, a fabled research center in the hills above Palo Alto,
is best known for its fumbles.
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARC (Palo Alto Research Center) pioneered the personal
computer, the point-and-click graphical user interface, the laser
printer and Ethernet _ but it never capitalized on them.
</P>
<P>
   While ideas languished in the copier giant's bureaucracy,
inventions from Xerox PARC helped spawn companies like Apple
Computer, 3Com and Adobe Systems. Adobe and 3Com were founded by
PARC veterans, and Apple's Macintosh computer was inspired by a
tour of PARC Steve Jobs took in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Now Xerox is making sure that doesn't happen again. These days,
it is spinning off PARC's hot technologies into startup companies _
and reaping huge returns when it takes the companies public.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with Xerox's persona as ``the document company'' (a
focus PARC helped coin), most of the startups specialize in
documents _ organizing, displaying, storing and manipulating them.
</P>
<P>
   Overseeing the spin-offs is an arm of Xerox called Xerox New
Enterprises (XNE). Created in 1996, it allocates seed money and
provides technical, business and marketing advice. It grew out of a
venture-capital fund Xerox founded in 1988, after it was stung by
criticism in ``Fumbling the Future: How Xerox Invented, then
Ignored, the First Personal Computer.''
</P>
<P>
   The book details how Xerox executives were too busy fighting
threats to the company's copier business to realize what was
happening at PARC _ a continent away from Xerox's headquarters in
Stamford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   The XNE firms combine the strengths _ versatility and speed _ of
startups with the clout and resources of a Fortune 100 company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to mimic the clock rate of startups, independent
critters that move fast, forage quickly and survive,'' said Ramana
Rao, chief technology officer of Inxight, one of the spin-offs.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox initially owns 80 percent of the XNE firms; the remainder
goes to the employees over time, giving them strong financial
incentives.
</P>
<P>
   XNE now has eight companies under its stewardship, generating
some $800 million in annual revenues. (Nearly half comes from Xerox
Engineering Systems, an existing unit that was folded into XNE last
year.)
</P>
<P>
   But added revenues for Xerox are just part of the equation _
XNE's $800 million contributes only about 4 percent to the copier
giant's $18 billion in annual revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We develop a lot more technology than we can ever use in our
main business,'' said Colin O'Brien, chief executive of XNE.
Before, innovations like the Alto _ the first personal computer in
1973 _ had no place inside Xerox. With XNE, Xerox has a way to
capitalize on those technologies, developing them into marketable
products, O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   XNE as a whole is currently losing money, O'Brien said, but he
expects it to move into the black next year, when he plans to take
the remaining businesses public.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are optimistic that the changes at PARC will eventually
show up on Xerox's bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``Xerox has moved from a company that fumbled one of the
great franchises in American history to one of the best companies
in its class,'' said Alex Henderson, who follows Xerox for
Prudential Securities. ``They're doing a great job of getting their
technology out front.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Kunstler, who follows Xerox for J.P. Morgan Securities,
said that Xerox is ``determined to get this work (at PARC)
commercialized.'' But PARC has changed, too, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a much more entrepreneurial environment. The place is
much more disciplined about getting its technology patented than it
was before,'' Kunstler said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Nestled in the hills overlooking Silicon Valley, PARC is home
to a collection of &UR;  &LR; would-be entrepreneurs at the XNE companies, as
well as 300 PARC researchers from such wide-ranging disciplines as
psychology, physics, mathematics and graphic design.
</P>
<P>
   Potential XNE companies first get help from business development
experts who work with the scientists to prepare a business
proposal. That proposal is presented to the seven-member Corporate
Innovation Council, which evaluates the project's market potential.
About one-third of proposals get seed money _ ranging from $300,000
to $1.5 million _ to conduct market research. The rest are shut
down.
</P>
<P>
   After the market research is complete, the board has three
choices. If the project is inappropriate for Xerox, the board can
spin it off to venture capitalists. If it's related to Xerox
business but doesn't fit into an existing business unit, it could
become an XNE company. Or the board may assign the project to a
compatible Xerox business division.
</P>
<P>
   One such PARC project, a ``blue laser,'' is being used to
develop what Xerox hopes will be a new printer that produces even
sharper and more vivid images than current laser printers. Much of
the technology in Xerox's digital printers and copiers _ which last
year comprised 36 percent of the company's revenues _ originally
came from PARC.
</P>
<P>
   John Seely Brown, PARC's chief scientist and director, said his
goal is to ``shape technology to people.'' He wants to make using
computers easier and more natural so that people can think about
the work they're doing instead of their PCs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at a document, you never think about what
application made it,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   With its spread-out campus and lush green lawns, PARC looks much
like a college campus. But it has the feel of a top-secret research
lab. Visitors need a badge _ a different one for each building _
and an escort. Even then, most of the labs are protected by several
sets of combination-lock doors.
</P>
<P>
   These days, says Brown, PARC is paying its own way _ as well as
paving the way for some exciting new technologies.
</P>
<P>
   `The money we made from just one (PARC) invention last year (the
high-end Docutech printer) covered the entire cost of PARC for its
entire history,'' he said. ``But if that's all we did, it wouldn't
be all that interesting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
