<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 6/03/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) TOKYO -- June 3, 1998 -- JAPAN-GOLD-RUSH, 6-03 -- Mayumi
Ohata talks with a customer in Tokyo about buying mutual funds from
Fidelity Investments. With $9 trillion in private savings up for
grabs, international banks and money managers are hurtling into
Tokyo to stake their claims. (Stuart Isett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- June 3, 1998 -- NY-LIFEGUARD-SHORTAGE, 6-03
-- A lifeguard surveys the beach at Coney Island on Wednesday. New
York City has the budget to hire 1,200 lifeguards, but they are
proving hard to find. With summer less than three weeks away, the
city has hired only about 400. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- June 3, 1998 -- BBA-YANKEES-HERNANDEZ, 6-03
-- Orlando Hernandez throwing his first major league pitch against
the Devil Rays at Yankee Stadium on Wednesday. The Yankees called
up the Cuban defector on Tuesday in case David Wells, bothered by
shoulder soreness, couldn't pitch. Wells was able to start, but
David Cone got bitten on the pitching hand by his mother's dog. so
the Yankees decided to rest Cone and activate Hernandez for one
game. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) TBILISI, Georgia -- June 3, 1998 -- GEORGIA-YOUTH, 6-03
-- Mikheil Saakashvili was a Manhattan lawyer when he was asked to
help build a post-Communist order in Georgia. Now he's a political
star here. Saakashvili is among the most prominent of several dozen
bright and energetic young people who are playing important roles
in creating a new order. Youth is on the rise not only in
government but also in hundreds of private groups supporting a wide
range of causes. (Staton R. Winter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) FEZ, Morocco -- June 3, 1998 -- MUSIC-FESTIVAL, 6-03 --
Faouzi Skali, director of the fourth Festival of World Sacred Music
in Fez. Under the giant keyhole arch and the crenellated ramparts
of Bab Mekina, one of the gates into this 1,000-year-old city, and
in the courtyard of the Batha Museum, a former sultan's palace,
musicians from four continents gathered to perform devotional
songs, setting aside doctrinal differences to praise the divine.
(Jon Pareles/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- June 3, 1998 -- EXCURSION-DANCE-REVIEW, 6-03
-- Heather Cornell in ``Excursion Fare'' on Tuesday night at the
Joyce Theater. With this imaginative new show, the company comes
close to bridging the gap between old- and new-style tap, with
dancing that is intimate and as intimately involved with the music
as any tap soloist and instrumentalist. (Andrea Mohin/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- June 3, 1998 -- SERRA-HOLOCAUST, 6-03 --
Richard Serra, who had teamed up with the American architect Peter
Eisenmann to submit a favored design for the massive and
much-debated Holocaust memorial in Berlin. Serra says he quit for
``personal and professional reasons'' that ``had nothing to do with
the merits of the project.'' (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- June 3, 1998 -- ROUNDABOUT-THEATER-2-B&AMP;W,
6-03 -- Natasha Richardson and Liam Neeson in the acclaimed ``Anna
Christie'' in 1992, produced by the Roundabout Theater Company.
Twenty years after filing for bankruptcy, a company that staged its
first plays in a supermarket basement with 150 seats has become a
producing powerhouse, the nation's second biggest nonprofit theater
after Lincoln Center's. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- June 3, 1998 -- ROUNDABOUT-THEATER-1, 6-03
-- Todd Haimes, left, the Roundabout Theater's artistic director,
and Rob Marshall, co-director and choreographer of ``Cabaret.''
Twenty years after filing for bankruptcy, 15 years after voting to
close its doors only to escape extinction by a last-minute gift, a
company that staged its first plays in a supermarket basement with
150 seats has become a producing powerhouse, the nation's second
biggest nonprofit theater after Lincoln Center's. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- June 3, 1998 -- EVERYMAN-THEATER-REVIEW,
6-03 -- From left, Joseph Mydell, Johnny Lodi and Josette
Bushell-Mingo in ``Everyman'' at the Majestic in Brooklyn. Although
the tinkering is, on the whole, restrained, it's too bad that the
company felt the need to toy at all with ``Everyman.'' What's best
about the piece, popular with college theater groups and
medievalists alike, is its stark simplicity; the primitive
directness puts you in mind of a children's play. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- June 3, 1998 -- HARLEM-SHOWHOUSE, 6-03 --
Design by Patsy Johnson has an Oriental flair at the first Harlem
United Show House, which opens Saturday and will remain on view
through July 3. ``It's time to show what we've been doing for all
these years,'' says Roderick Shade, an interior decorator, who
organized the show house to raise funds for the Harlem United
Community AIDS Center and also to raise the visibility of
African-American designers. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- June 3, 1998 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 6-03 --
Many homeowners find it difficult to maintain the borders around
the patio, driveway and sidewalks. Fortunately, there are numerous
solutions to the edging problem, all of which require an initial
installation effort but which, afterward, will require less upkeep
than a grass edge demands. (Edward R. Lipinski/New York Times
Illustration) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEWBURGH, N.Y. -- June 3, 1998 -- HUDSON-HOUSE-TOUR,
6-03 -- ``It's well lived in,'' Lillie Hodge says of her Calvert
Vaux house over the Hudson in Newburgh. It has two ballrooms and is
on a weekend tour of Gothic Revival houses. This weekend, this
scrappy river city, home to one of the state's largest and most
significant historic districts, will host ``Tastemakers of an
Era,'' a two-day symposium and house tour that will examine the
lineage of four 19th century apostles and the city that nurtured
them. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WOODSTOCK, N.Y. -- June 3, 1998 -- WOMAN-MONEY-MAVEN,
6-03 -- Colette Dowling, author of ``Maxing Out: Why Women Sabotage
Their Financial Security,'' sold nearly everything to pay off
debts. ``I am a woman of 60 with no savings and no investments,''
says Colette Dowling, shown on the porch of her rented Woodstock
home. ``All things being equal, I should work until I'm 75. But who
knows if all things will be equal?'' (Keith Meyers/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- June 3, 1998 -- SORTERS, 6-03 -- The French
postal sorting desk lends credence to the idea that order can
exist. Is it warm weather that inspires the desire to put household
objects in order? Something that provokes the taking up of arms
against a winter's accumulation, the determination to stem the
relentless tide of miscellany, to put things at last in their
place? Sorting things implies a greater order in one's life.
(Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) UNDATED -- June 3, 1998 -- CIR-COMPUTER-TRAVEL, 6-3 --
Cybertravelers can choose to visit various places and periods in
time with the use of Cds that take the user through the country or
city. The titles shown are, from top, Up To The Himalayas: Kingdom
In The Clouds, Jerusalem and Countries of Romance. (New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) UNDATED -- June 3, 1998 -- CIR-STUDENT-FEEDBACK-2, 6-3
-- With this device known as a ``Perception Analyzer'' students can
now turn the tables (or the lecterns) on their teachers and grade
their performances. Although the Perception Analyzer has been used
for years by corporations and politicians to test the mass appeal
of their products and messages, Market Strategies, the company that
makes it, is now pushing into academia. (John Gress/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) PORTLAND -- June 3, 1998 -- CIR-STUDENT-FEEDBACK-1, 6-3
-- Devorah Lieberman, director of teaching and learning excellence
at the Portland State University uses the Perception Analyzer to
check whether students really understand the material being
presented. ``I think it's really got an incredible amount of
potential,'' she says. (John Gress/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- June 3, 1998 -- CIR-DIGITAL-IMAGER, 6-3 --
Carl Goodman, curator of American Museum of the Moving Image, at a
work station where museum-goers can insert sound effects into the
movie ``The Mask.'' Goodman who is known for his collaboration in
new interactive projects says, ``It's all about the people and the
process, computers are just another tool.'' (Linda Rosier/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) ABINGTON, Pa. -- June 3, 1998 -- CIR-KIDS-WEATHER, 6-3 --
Allison Tausek, 13, a junior high student, checks the weather data
on a recent weekend. Allison and other members of her seventh-grade
science class, take turns gathering information for the Globe Web
site (www.globe.gov). Students in more than 4,000 schools in the
United States and 1,000 schools in 70 countries are using the
Internet to report their weather observations. (Sal DiMarco Jr./New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) LOS GATOS, Calif. -- June 3, 1998 -- CIR-MICRO-NOTEBOOKS,
6-3 -- The NEC Versa SX notebook computer weighs just 4.8 pounds
and measures 1.3 inches thick. Its just one of the new cateory that
analysts and companies call PC companions, a category that includes
palmtops and handhelds. Like the other PC companions, it's more
than an organizer, less than a notebook and of real use only to
people who already have a full-fledged Windows computer. (New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BUCHANAN, N.Y. -- June 3, 1998 -- CIR-SHREDDER, 6-3 --
Carole Harris shows how her shredder cuts paper into strips. ``I
thought, Well, if I've got to tear up envelopes and anything with
names and addresses, that's a lot,'' say Ms. Harris. She enjoys her
Royal shredder so much that she bought one for each of her four
children. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- June 3, 1998 -- HARVARD-II-BOS, 6-3
-- Demonstrators protesting the Harvard appearance of Chinese
President Jiang Zemin were outnumbered last November by a
well-orchestrated show of support by Jiang. For an institution
accustomed to foreign visitors and global influence, the speech -
Jiang's only talk at an American university - still represented an
academic coup, evidence of Harvard's extraordinary standing in
world affairs. (John Tlumacki/Boston Globe Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- June 3, 1998 -- HARVARD-I-BOS, 6-3 --
Carrick Morre Gerety' 98, who perfers the non-traditional reading
stance, catches up between classes in Harvard yard. Harvard has a
higher student-faculty ration than either Yale or Princeton.
(Dominic Chavez/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- June 3, 1998 --
HARVARD-RUDENSTEIN-BOS, 6-3 -- Outside his office, Neil Rudenstine,
the president of Harvard University, stands among the portraits and
busts of famous Harvard alumni. Since taking over in 1991,
Rudenstine has guided a remarkably successful fund-raising drive.
But critics say he's such a nice guy that he doesn't like to say no
- especially to the powerful deans of Harvard's 12 schools.
(Dominic Chavez/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) GRAND CANYON NATIONAL PARK, Ariz. -- June 3, 1998 --
CANYONHIKE-AZG, 6-3 -- Don Renfroe takes a break from his hike
along the steep Tanner Trail. The Tanner begins at the far eastern
end of the South Rim, not far from the Desert View Watchtower. It
is one of the more difficult trails in the park, listed as ``very
strenuous'' by most guidebooks. (Jeff Ignaszewski/Arizona Republic
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) KENDLETON, Texas -- June 3, 1998 --
CHRISTIAN-COLLEGE-HNS, 6-3 -- Dr. James Phillips, board chairman
Bay Ridge Christian College, sits with Verda Beach, the school's
president. ``When I arrived here three years ago, Bay Ridge was on
the respirator and hemorrhaging,'' Phillips says. ``There were
questions about whether we could survive.'' The college is one of
eight higher education institutions nationwide with ministry
programs for the Church of God. (E. Joseph Deering/Houston
Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
