r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLDWATER-FLYBY-AZR &LR;      06-03 0403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDWATER-FLYBY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR FORCE FIGHTER FLYBY IS ULTIMATE MILITARY HONOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By VANESSA DERUYTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The Air Force fighter flyover that thrilled onlookers
at Barry Goldwater's memorial service represents the ultimate
military tribute for an American patriot.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wednesday's ``Missing Man'' formation led by Lt. Wade May
and performed by the 62nd fighter squadron was unusual, Pentagon
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The formation, in which one F-16 jet departs from a four-ship
formation up into the sky, symbolizes the loss of a fallen airman.
</P>
<P>
   Flyovers are typically performed by Air Force pilots during the
funeral services of four-star generals and military personnel who
die in active duty, said 1st Lt. Barry Spencer.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force granted a flyover for Goldwater, who retired in
1967 as major general in the U.S. Air Force Reserve, out of
respect.
</P>
<P>
   The flyover service ``was a tribute to an Air Force officer and
patriot,'' said Maj. Eric Schnaible at the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Family members of a deceased pilot can make a formal request for
a flyover in writing. The person considered the next of kin must
write the request.
</P>
<P>
   The request, along with a biography of the deceased and proof of
military services, is sent to Texas, which forwards the materials
to the Pentagon for review. The Air Force Chief of Staff then
decides whether to approve or decline the request.
</P>
<P>
   Schnaible said to qualify for a flyover, the individual must
have served in the military, but the Air Force makes some
exceptions for public officials.
</P>
<P>
   According to Pentagon records, the formation originated prior to
1935 from the British Royal Air Force, which used it upon returning
from a mission to tell ground officials how many losses were
suffered.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony was used in 1935 during a review by King George V
and eventually evolved into a traditional part of RAF ceremonies
during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The first recorded American use of the flyover was in 1938
during the burial of Maj. Gen. Oscar Westover, Army Air Corps Chief
of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   Today, flyovers are sometimes allowed during other ceremonies,
such as during the anniversary of Pearl Harbor and other patriotic
holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ``The formation is a solemn tribute, so (the Air Force) is
careful to limit the number of events it is used for,'' said
Schnaible. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
