<HEADER>
A3061 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIAGRA-DEATH-BOS &LR;      06-03 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIAGRA-DEATH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEVENTH DEATH REPORTED OF MEN TAKING ANTI-IMPOTENCE DRUG
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG AND RIC KAHN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The state medical examiner is investigating the death Sunday of
a man who had reportedly taken the new impotence drug Viagra,
according to sources at Massachusetts General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   If confirmed, the death of the Cambridge man at MGH would be the
seventh reported death of a Viagra user in the United States.
According to the US Food and Drug Administration, three of the
deaths involved men who were taking heart medication at the same
time despite product warnings, while the others involved men age 60
and over for whom there was no known history of heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew McCormick, spokesman for Pfizer Inc., maker of Viagra,
said yesterday that the company has not received any reports of
deaths in Massachusetts. ``It's possible it happened,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such reports of possible adverse drug reactions are not required
to be made to the manufacturer, although any reports the company
gets must be forwarded to the FDA. By law, the federal agency
cannot reveal identifying details such as a patient's name or state
of residence.
</P>
<P>
   Both the FDA and Pfizer emphasized that none of the reports so
far have prompted any change in the drug's safety profile. Since
the drug was approved by the FDA in March for the treatment of male
impotence, or erectile dysfunction, 1.5 million prescriptions have
been written for Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   The product label already warns that patients taking any
nitrates, including nitroglycerin and long-acting nitrates for
chest pain, should not take Viagra, said McCormick.
</P>
<P>
   The label also warns older patients with poor health, whether or
not they are taking nitrates, to consult with a physician before
taking the drug and having sex, he said, adding that 85 percent of
the prescriptions written to date are for men over age 50.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sexual intercourse is a form of physical exertion,'' said
McCormick. ``We have been advising patients with a cardiovascular
history to discuss this closely with their physician.''
</P>
<P>
   MGH sources said the Cambridge man, who was said to be in his
50s, died in the emergency room at 3 a.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Viagra, or sildenafil citrate, is the first pill to treat
impotence, which affects millions of US men. The drug does not
directly cause erections, but enhances muscle relaxation, thus
allowing increased blood flow into the penis, leading to an
erection.
</P>
<P>
   The drug, evaluated in studies involving about 3,000 men with
impotence associated with diabetes, spinal cord injury, history of
prostate surgery, and no identifiable cause of impotence, was
approved less than six months after submission to the FDA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
