<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3064 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASSES04-COX     06-03 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASSES04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Priests offer comfort for wounded parishoners
 &HT;    By Dan Moffett and Tim Pallesen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. Priests throughout the Diocese of Palm
Beach went to their pulpits Wednesday and tried to comfort
parishioners reeling from pain and disillusionment.
</P>
<P>
   Their bishop, J. Keith Symons, resigned Tuesday in disgrace. Now
they looked toward the altar for solace.
</P>
<P>
   Monsignor Thomas Klinzing celebrated the 8:30 a.m. Mass at St.
Ignatius Loyola Catholic Cathedral in Palm Beach Gardens and
appealed for prayers so healing can begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shock has almost worn off,'' he said before Mass, telling
the faithful to expect sorrow, followed by hurt and healing.
</P>
<P>
   After the service, Klinzing returned for informal questions and
answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must remember that no one knew anything about this
sickness 35 years ago,'' he said. ``Please talk to your children.
We can't say there aren't any more victims, but we pray that there
are not.''
</P>
<P>
   Klinzing said he and other priests were concerned by the
bishop's behavior during Mass last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very confused on Sunday. The priests said, `He's not
making any sense,' '' Klinzing recalled, saying he sensed something
was wrong. Priests received the unhappy news of Symons' resignation
at a meeting called by Klinzing at 9:50 a.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   `He needs our prayers,'' he said. ``The poor man is in
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Klinzing expressed worry that St. Ignatius just committed to a
new construction program by signing a contract with the architect
Friday. The bishop was to play a key role in raising money for the
project, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Klinzing also told the congregation that priests at St. Ignatius
will examine youth programs where they interact with boys in the
parish.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have to draw back a bit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Our Lady of Florida Spiritual Center in North Palm Beach, the
Rev. Damian Towey, retreat leader at the center, celebrated Mass
and, in something less than a sermon, addressed the bishop's
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   He quoted Jesus Christ to the 50 people who attended: ``Judge
not, condemn not.'' Towey put his emphasis on reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forgiveness and reconciliation are the supreme gifts Jesus
left the church,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Don Smith of Juno Beach offered a metaphor: ``Since the apple
was bit, imperfection was invented.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Pecoraro of North Palm Beach was concerned for those who
are hurting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sad for the children,'' she said. ``Then, I feel sad
for the bishop. Each one of us has to look deep in our soul and
find a merciful God. I think I think we can find healing.''
</P>
<P>
   Parishioners who attended evening Mass at St. Vincent Ferrer
Catholic Church in Delray Beach said the misconduct wouldn't affect
their faith or push them away from the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church is divine and it is human. The human part fails,''
said Eileen Stull.
</P>
<P>
   Others said once he was confronted, it must have taken courage
for the bishop to admit his sin.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us is infallible. We're a family. Just because one
person in a family doesn't behave appropriately, it doesn't
diminish the value of the family,'' said Elizabeth Brinkman, a
Delray Beach resident who attends St. Vincent.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Steve Gushee and Monika Gonzalez contributed to
this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
