<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0496 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3066 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SYMONS04-COX     06-03 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYMONS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Symons' case highlights Catholic Church's denial, critics say
 &HT;    By Dan Moffett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. -- After admitting he molested a child,
Bishop J. Keith Symons began a monthlong schedule that was very
busy and very public.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke at the graduation commencement ceremonies of three
Catholic high schools.
</P>
<P>
   He ordained several priests.
</P>
<P>
   He celebrated Mass and dispensed communion.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, he gave the sacrament of confirmation to 163 of the
faithful at St. Ignatius Cathedral in Palm Beach Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   All this while the church hierarchy was working out his removal
and pressing him to give the names of all the youths he had abused.
The night before the confirmation service, Symons admitted there
were four more victims, five in all.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the bishop went through with his holy duties the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows both the arrogance of the bishop and the arrogance
of the Catholic church,'' said the Rev. Tom Economos, president of
Linkup, a Chicago-based support network for clergy abuse victims.
``What does this do to the people he administered sacraments to?
Absolutely the minute he admitted this, he should have stepped
down. To continue the farce and charade is terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Robert N. Lynch, who was named Tuesday as the Palm Beach
diocese's temporary leader, said Symons was permitted to continue
his duties until Pope John Paul II accepted his resignation and
approved his removal. The church acted expeditiously to deal with
the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Holy See (Vatican) usually moves glacially but in this
case moved fast,'' he said. ``We're doing everything we can to help
our church regain its equilibrium and begin to heal.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics claim this is another example of the church's
insensitivity to victims and the double standard it allows its
clergy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a chance to send a powerful signal,'' said David
Clohessy, national president of SNAP (Survivors Network of Those
Abused by Priests). ``The prudent thing to do would have been to
remove him immediately. But again the church missed the opportunity
to do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Church officials said Wedneday that Symons is beginning
psychological treatment at an undisclosed location and won't be
sent to the St. Luke's center in Suitland, Md., where many
pedophiliac priests have been treated.
</P>
<P>
   Symons' eight-year tenure as bishop of the Palm Beach diocese _
which includes Palm Beach, Martin, St. Lucie, Indian River and
Okeechobee counties _ ended five weeks after a victim came forward
and told church officials he was molested some 40 years ago. Symons
subsequently admitted molesting four others. All are believed to be
altar boys.
</P>
<P>
   This was not the first time he had come forward with the
problem, Lynch said. After several years of abusing boys decades
ago, Symons told a spiritual counselor of his addiction. Bound to
keep his confessor's admissions secret, he told Symons to be chaste
and avoid alcohol, according to Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   Economus says that after suffering the anguish of sexual abuse,
victims find that the church still doesn't reach out to them and
the court system doesn't give them a fair hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statute of limitations really is a shelter that works to
the advantage of the dioceses,'' he said. ``In most states, the
window of opportunity for taking legal action is two to three
years. Most victims suffer in secrecy for much longer than that,
then find it difficult to make cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Anderson is a St. Paul, Minn., attorney who has sued the
Catholic church in 36 states, most notably in the case of James
Porter, the Massachusetts priest who pleaded guilty in 1993 to
molesting 36 children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The laws have not recognized the exceptional phenomenon of
victims of abuse,'' Anderson said. ``They have kept the doors
closed.''
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, states have changed their laws to allow delayed
discovery actions where abuses can be considered by the courts many
years after the fact.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Florida has not been a state that historically has been
receptive to this,'' Anderson said. ``Legislatures have not done
enough to remove statute of limitations barriers.''
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, most abuse charges can't be acted upon more than
four years after the incidents occurred. Steve Rubino, a Cherry
Hill, N.J. attorney who has sued the church over abuse cases in
numerous jurisdictions, said the nature of religious faith is
itself an obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is great fear from the religious point of view in
accusing a priest or a diocese,'' Rubino said. ``That is something
that seems terribly wrong to do if you are a devout Catholic. It
goes against everything you are taught.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubino successfully has used this premise to have the statute of
limitations dismissed in some cases.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus among lawyers who have taken on the church is that
they've tangled with a powerful adversary.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are formidable, and they continue to live in denial, in
part because they have never been made accountable in our court
system,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Rubino: ``The Catholic church has virtually inexhaustible
resources and uses them as it needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Linkup's Economus says his group has names of 3,800 priests who
have been accused of abuse, a number church officials say is
greatly inflated. But they concede that 148 priests are behind bars
or have served time on abuse charges. The church is believed to
have paid close to $800 million in settlements, judgments and
therapy costs.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, a Dallas jury awarded 11 plaintiffs $119.6 million
after finding the diocese there negligent in its response to a
pedophile priest. That award, the highest ever in clergy abuse
cases, triggered a new wave of actions by victims. It also steeled
the resolve of the church to defend itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bishops are so petrified they will be the next Dallas, they
shove the problem off to the church attorney,'' Clohessy said.
``They put all their pastoral instincts on the shelf and say
they're letting their experts handle it. This is much more than a
legal problem. I can count on my hand the number of bishops who
have done the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
