<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3070 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALABAMA-ELECT-542&AMP;ADD     06-03 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALABAMA-ELECT-542&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL ATTACKS MARK START OF ALABAMA RUNOFF CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, Ala. _ After forcing Gov. Fob James Jr. into a
runoff in the Republican gubernatorial primary on Tuesday, Winton
Blount III Wednesday cast his coming four-week duel with James as a
chance for Alabama to stop electing leaders who ``continually
embarrass us.''
</P>
<P>
   Several hours later, James rose to the bait in a news conference
performance that Blount will undoubtedly use to illustrate his
point. In essence, the governor responded by saying that Blount is
fat.
</P>
<P>
   Blount, a wealthy and, yes, portly businessman, had backed up
his criticism of James by recalling moments like the governor's
threat to call out the National Guard in support of a judge's
insistence on posting the Ten Commandments in his courtroom. He
also referred to the day several years ago when James mocked the
theory of evolution at a state school board meeting by ``walking
across the stage like a monkey,'' with his shoulders hunched and
arms hanging limply in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   And so when James, a former college football star who made a
fortune in the barbell business, was asked at a news conference to
respond to Blount, he said: ``Well, I'm a monkey that's in good
shape. I'm not a fat monkey.''
</P>
<P>
   James was asked whether he was saying that Blount was fat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I leave that to you,'' the governor replied, ``but if he says
I'm a monkey, I'm not a fat monkey and I'm not a monkey whose daddy
has put $2.5 million in my campaign, either. Make of that what you
want to. If he says I'm a monkey, I must say: `Well, I'm a pretty
slim monkey. I'm not a fat monkey.'''
</P>
<P>
   James' comments were not the first references to Blount's
physique made Wednesday by a member of Alabama's first family.
Early Wednesday morning James' wife, Bobbie, told reporters for The
Birmingham News and The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group
that she did not care for Blount's attacks on her family's
ownership of a landfill that has received some business from the
state. ``He's a big, fat sissy,'' she told the reporters.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday the Blount campaign manager, Sonny Scott, said his
first instinct was to laugh at James' remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then you realize that this is the governor,'' Scott said.
``Governing is supposed to be serious.''
</P>
<P>
   James, whose fervid support for school prayer has made him both
a conservative icon and an object of derision, finished first in a
five-candidate field on Tuesday, but failed to win the majority
needed to avoid a runoff. He took 48 percent of the vote, while
Blount got 41 percent. Former Gov. Guy Hunt, who decided to run
after being pardoned from the state ethics conviction that forced
his resignation in 1993, finished third, with 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican primary has been depicted by James' strategists
and by national leaders of the Christian conservative movement as
an important electoral test for the religious right. Until the June
30 runoff, at least, the test remains inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
   In the Democratic primary, Lt. Gov. Don Siegelman easily
defeated his top rival, Lenora Pate, a Birmingham lawyer, by
winning 78 percent of the vote. Siegelman enters the general
election with more than $3.5 million in his campaign treasury and
the luxury of watching his Republican rivals attack each other for
another month.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Tuesday's primary, while posing the potential to divide
Republicans in November, proved a landmark for the party in
Alabama. The statewide Republican primary turnout of 358,757
shattered the record of 215,046, set in 1996. For the first time,
Republican turnout exceeded Democratic turnout, although by only
1,420 votes.
</P>
<P>
   James, 63, attributed his runoff to the growing pains of a newly
vigorous party. He said he had prevailed in primary runoffs in both
of his successful races for governor, one as a Democrat, and would
do so again. He urged voters to focus on the state's low
unemployment rate, his pledge to reject tax increases and his
efforts to improve schools.
</P>
<P>
   Blount, 54, whose campaign has received $2.5 million in loans
from himself and various family members, clearly hopes to make the
runoff a referendum on James. Like many business leaders in the
state, he argued that James' provocative positions on school prayer
and his pitched battles against the federal courts had damaged the
state's reputation and handicapped its economic development
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of James' recent assertion that the Bill of Rights does
not apply to the states, Blount said, ``These are things that bring
up images of the past that just aren't as good as we are as a
state.''
</P>
<P>
   But James defended his leadership style. ``I think he's out to
lunch on that,'' the governor said of Blount. ``I think my behavior
is every bit a gentleman.''
</P>
<P>
   Iowans Pick Nominees for Governor
</P>
<P>
   Jim Ross Lightfoot, the most conservative of three Republicans
vying to succeed Gov. Terry Branstad of Iowa, easily won his
party's nomination in a primary on Tuesday. State Sen. Tom Vilsack,
the more liberal of two Democrats, won as well, and will oppose him
in November.
</P>
<P>
   Branstad, the nation's longest-serving governor, is retiring
after four four-year terms. Democrats have not held the governor's
mansion in Iowa for 30 years, and analysts say the Republicans once
again go into the fall with big advantages, including Branstad's
continuing popularity.
</P>
<P>
   In the Democratic primary for governor in New Mexico, Martin
Chavez, a former mayor of Albuquerque, topped a field of six to win
a spot on November's ballot against the first-term incumbent
Republican, Gary Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Two House races in New Mexico drew national attention.
</P>
<P>
   In one, state attorney general Tom Udall, a nephew of former
Rep. Morris Udall, won a chance to carry his famous family name
back to Washington, winning the Democratic primary for the House
seat held by Rep. Bill Redmond, a Republican freshman.
</P>
<P>
   In the other, for the seat of Rep. Steven Schiff, a five-term
Republican who died in March, the primary winners were Heather
Wilson on the Republican side and state Sen. Phil Maloof on the
Democratic side.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
