<HEADER>
A3072 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWINSKY-LAWYERS-2TAK     06-03 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-LAWYERS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LEWINSKY LAWYERS OFFER STUDY IN POLISHED PROFESSIONALISM
</HEADLINE>
   (See also CLINTON-STARR-ASSESS) 
(sw) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES and ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the instant celebrity shorthand of capital
power, it was ``Plato and Jake,'' as easy to remember as Mutt and
Jeff, who held this city's attention on Wednesday as they took up
the defense of Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Between them, Plato Cacheris and Jacob Stein have more than
eight decades of experience as leading courtroom lawyers to offer
Ms. Lewinsky, the former White House intern who is at the heart of
the criminal investigation of President Clinton's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Between them, they present a dynamic of differing personality
traits, negotiating skills and courtroom cunning that friends in
the bar say has instantly strengthened Ms. Lewinsky's hand in her
struggle to avoid indictment.
</P>
<P>
   The two were on the case Wednesday, advising Ms. Lewinsky as
battle-hardened elders with as sharp an appetite for high-stakes
trials as for intricate bargaining aimed at immunity. In their
first 24 hours, they paid a lawyerly drop-in visit to the office of
Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel investigating the
relationship between the president and Ms. Lewinsky. They also
began the long unraveling of Ms. Lewinsky's version of Oval Office
events but offered only a glimpse of their initial impressions as a
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jake is more detached and professorial and scholarly than I
am,'' said Cacheris in a telephone interview. ``I am more of an
alleycat in the courtroom than he is. I get a little more
strident.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the two could not be more different. The
73-year-old Stein, the son of a Washington lawyer, had the boyhood
dream of becoming a vaudevillian juggler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that would be a wonderful life, to do something to
perfection,'' he once said, settling instead for 50 years in the
law, a reputation as the unoffical dean of the capital's bar, and
juggling for fun. He himself has been an independent counsel _
hailed as the very model of one in his disciplined investigation
and exoneration of Edwin A. Meese III, the counselor to President
Ronald Reagan. But that experience, Stein said recently, convinced
him the independent counsel office's has ``the power to destroy
people.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the 69-year-old Cacheris, the son of a Greek
immigrant who bought into a small chain of waffle restaurants, had
the childhood fantasy of becoming ambassador to Greece, but became
instead a hardball defense lawyer specializing in high-profile,
highly politicized cases. He hates paperwork, partners' meetings
and procrastinators, but loves notorious defendants.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president and Vernon Jordan are already taken,'' he joked
two months ago as he agreed to represent the relatively minor
figure of the chauffeur to Jordan, the presidential confidant
featured in the Starr inquiry. ``So it's tough luck for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The new team's experiences have equipped them for either
alternative in the evolving Starr investigation: careful
negotiation for immunity or, in the event of the indictment of Ms.
Lewinsky, an all-out court fight. Cacheris' peers credit him with
some spectacular deal-making in recent years, notably the agreement
that spared Aldrich Ames execution as a convicted spy. Stein, in
turn, is respected for winning the sole acquittal in the Watergate
criminal trial during the Nixon era.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say Ms. Lewinsky now has a stunning team,'' said Kenneth
Parkinson, former counsel for the Nixon re-election committee, who
was successfully defended by Stein. ``They're not going to do
anything that would be stupid or out of character.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Starr's office sent out some rare positive vibes on
Wednesday with prosecutors' expressing their relief that finally,
as one put it, they were dealing with seasoned criminal defense
professionals who knew the ways of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The two lawyers bonded two decades ago during the Watergate
trial, when Cacheris represented Attorney General John Mitchell,
while Stein defended Parkinson. The two play tennis at Cacheris'
home in Alexandria, Va., and they see each other in the summer at
their Atlantic beach houses.
</P>
<P>
   They enjoy reminiscing about the fact that they are both
products of District of Columbia public schools, in the days,
Cacheris said, when students from the Maryland and Virginia suburbs
would pay $25 a year to attend. When Cacheris sold the townhouse
that housed his law practice a few years ago, Stein invited him to
take space in his building five blocks north of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost a good-cop, bad-cop team,'' said Paul Rothstein, a
professor at Georgetown University Law Center who teaches with
Stein and is a longtime friend of both lawyers. ``They both shine
in the courtroom and in making deals, but Plato is more garrulous,
more talkative, more slap-on-the-back, hail fellow well met _ but
with the threat that `I could beat you up bad if I have to.' While
that is the reality with Jake, too, he doesn't wear it on his
sleeve as much as Plato does.''
</P>
<P>
   As elite members of the Washington bar, their fees are in the
top range of $400 or so an hour. But the two newcomers to the
Lewinsky investigation also exemplify the small-town closeness of
the capital bar. Stein and Starr crossed paths on the Senate's
ethics inquiry of Sen. Bob Packwood when Stein defended the senator
and Starr vetted the Packwood diaries.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For 17 years, Cacheris was the law partner of William Hundley,
who represents Vernon E. Jordan Jr., the president's confidant who
is being investigated for his role in the Lewinsky matter.
Hundley's son, John, works in Cacheris' office.
</P>
<P>
   Cacheris is also a close friend and former partner of Robert
Bennett, the lawyer who successfully defended President Clinton in
the Paula Jones civil lawsuit. The Jones sexual-harassment suit
sparked the Starr inquiry into possible perjury after both the
president and Ms. Lewsinky submitted sworn denials of a sexual
affair.
</P>
<P>
   Cacheris and Bennett are so close that Cacheris, regretful after
publicly criticizing his friend's rumpled demeanor, took him to his
own $1,500-a-suit tailor in Alexandria, Va. ``I just like to dress
well,'' Cacheris said. ``I told Bennett he needed to straighten
himself out _ sartorially.''
</P>
<P>
   In the tight-knit legal world of Washington, lawyers joust by
day and schmooze by night. ``It's nothing personal and we'll be
friends when the whole thing is over,'' Cacheris said in surveying
the lawyerly terrain in the most high-powered confrontation of
Clinton's incumbency.
</P>
<P>
   As frenetic as it has been, none of Stein's friends expect he
will interrupt his signature habit of closing himself off from the
world for afternoon literary ``siestas,'' when he does not answer
the phone and he indulges his formidable appetite for book reading,
especially in French and English writers of the 18th and 19th
centuries. ``The only talent I've got, I think, is the talent for
staying awake while reading,'' Stein once told an interviewer.
``That's quite a talent.''
</P>
<P>
   To the contary, the city's lawyers eagerly await the wry,
courtly writings on the legal life that Stein composes for bar
journals in the Edwardian comfort of his window-free, book-crammed
office, with its standup writer's desk and rocking chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``The symptoms of deposition torpor began creeping over me,'' he
confessed in one, lyrically describing a typical lawyer's travels
past ``the outer reefs of relevancy and beyond the cape of
materiality.''
</P>
<P>
   A quiet man, Stein exudes the cheer of a bon vivant on the
streets of the city, sporting white suits in summer and usually
stopping to make a respectful offering to street beggars. ``Being
Jake's luncheon partner is amazing,'' said Eugene Fidell, a lawyer
who said Stein's countless acquaintances always stop him on the
street. ``It's like going for a stroll with Jimmy Walker.''
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of the two lawyers sparked intense speculation
about their strategems. ``They're not going to roll over,'' said
Stuart Taylor, the legal affairs writer for The National Journal.
``And to some extent they hold some pretty high cards because a
criminal trial of Monica Lewinsky is a very dicey proposition for
Starr.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky can expect calm, quiet expertise, according to Fawn
Hall, the former White House secretary whom Cacheris defended in
the Iran-Contra investigation. ``Being someone all of 27 years old
when it happened, I was terrified,'' she recalled. ``I was way in
above my head. It was all too much. Plato was always a perfect
gentleman and had a very fatherly approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Cacheris said matter of factly that between the two of them, the
new Lewinsky team is steeped in ``the ability to handle cases of
this nature.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If there were to be a trial, I know I would say, `You do the
opening and I'll do the closing. You take this witness and I'll
take that one.' It's non-confrontation. We've been around this town
for a long time. Neither of us are awed by the personalities
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   The two lawyers are determined to make Washington forget the
verbal ramblings of the capital outsider, William Ginsburg, the
California malpractice specialist and close friend of the Lewinsky
family who was dismissed on Tuesday as her lawyer. ``We're not
going to go on talk shows, neither Jake nor I,'' Cacheris said.
``My disapproval of the prior lawyer is that he was spending too
much time on talk shows and not spending enough time on the case.''
</P>
<P>
   The Plato and Jake team made clear there will be no non-stop
sound bites and certainly no further reference to Ms. Lewinsky's
``poulkes'' _ her chubby thighs as an infant. ``Spare me,'' said
Cacheris.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
