u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RETIREMENT-FORUM-BOS &LR;      06-03 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETIREMENT-FORUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL SERVICES FIRMS HAVE KEY ROLE AT RETIREMENT FORUM
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When President Clinton addresses ``The National
Summit on Retirement Savings'' Thursday, few will take issue with
the thrust of his remarks: that Americans should save more for
their golden years or risk a drop in living standards when they
retire.
</P>
<P>
   But some people are asking why the message is being delivered in
a forum that is heavily stocked with, and partly funded by,
financial services firms that have a business interest in the
savings habits of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Through a law passed last year, Congress created the summit as a
``public-private partnership'' to find ways to encourage Americans
to save more for retirement. Two hundred delegates, chosen by the
White House and Congress, will discuss the topic with lawmakers and
federal officials. They meet at a Washington hotel Thursday and
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   At least a quarter of the appointed delegates come from stock
brokerages, money-management firms, insurers, or similar companies
and trade groups, giving financial services firms the largest
portion of delegates. That compares with 16 delegates from labor
unions and employee trade groups.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, most of the funding for the summit comes indirectly
from Boston's Fidelity Investments and State Street Corp., as well
as other investment firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were hoping to see a larger number of people representing
middle-income working families and the poor, who have little access
to retirement savings vehicles, instead of people who would profit
tremendously from increased retirement savings,'' said Thomas
Matzzie of the Institute for America's Future, a union-allied group
focusing on wage and job security issues that is not attending the
summit.
</P>
<P>
   US Representative Harris Fawell, the Illinois Republican who
sponsored the bill creating the summit, said he hoped some of the
discussion would focus on tax law changes that would encourage
people to save more. ``We've got more than 200 experts from the
front lines coming to Washington, and now they've got the ear of
the president and the Department of Labor,'' Fawell said.
</P>
<P>
   But that troubles the groups representing workers, which say the
government should not undertake the discussion in a forum so
heavily weighted with business groups. They fear business groups
will use it to build support for such tax changes as higher limits
on 401(k) donations, which, in their view, cause the government to
give up tax revenue so wealthier Americans can save money tax free.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, they worry businesses will use the summit to build
support for eliminating ``nondiscrimination rules,'' which link a
company's success in persuading lower-income workers to save in
401(k) plans to its ability to allow higher-income workers to save
in the tax-deferred plans.
</P>
<P>
   They also fear that the ``save more'' message, while sounding
innocuous, will hasten a shift in the retirement burden onto
workers and away from traditional corporate pension plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employers telling workers to save for themselves is a cover
for them to cut costs,'' said Karen Ferguson, director of the
Pension Rights Center in Washington and a delegate to the summit.
``When an employer stops its traditional pension or substitutes a
401(k), it's a pay cut for workers and a cost savings for the
employer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's hardly anybody lobbying for pensions for the average
worker,'' said Cindy Hounsell of the Women's Institute for a Secure
Retirement, referring to the delegate list, which includes her.
</P>
<P>
   Fawell said the delegates include ``a good cross-section'' of
groups involved with the retirement system. In addition to
financial services firms and labor unions, delegates come from
universities, think tanks, federal and state government, large and
small employers, and seniors groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're bound to have some people there who are in the
investment business, but that's OK,'' Fawell said. ``If you're
going to get some good hints about how to educate people on this,
we have to have people who are on the front lines tell us.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial services firms are indirectly covering much of the
cost of the summit, a move that has also drawn criticism.
</P>
<P>
   In the law creating the summit, which also called for similar
events in 2001 and 2005, Congress gave the Department of Labor
$250,000 to set up this year's event. It told the department to
find a private sector partner to pay the rest of the bill and to
help with preparations.
</P>
<P>
   That group is the American Savings Education Council, a
nonprofit educational organization founded in 1995 to promote
retirement savings. It does not take positions on public policy
issues.
</P>
<P>
   The council has a wide membership, including labor unions,
government agencies, and universities, but 75 percent of its
funding comes from 12 ``charter partners.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine of those partners are financial services firms or trade
groups representing companies in the industry. They include
Fidelity Investments and State Street Corp. of Boston, as well as
the Investment Company Institute, American Express Co., and
Prudential Investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Congress wants to do this (summit), why do it with what I
call `charged' or `loaded' money?'' asked Bill Hogan of the Center
for Public Integrity, a nonprofit Washington group that studies
money and ethics in politics. ``This is not disinterested money.''
</P>
<P>
   Hogan said the use of private firm money ``puts the Labor
Department in a bad position'' of potentially owing a favor to one
of the firms that helped fund the summit.
</P>
<P>
   Fawell said his bill called for private funding to help overcome
objections from the Clinton administration, which was ``initially
resistant'' to spending money on the summit.
</P>
<P>
   Don M. Blandin, president of the savings council, said his group
would probably end up covering about 70 percent of the cost of the
summit, which could top $800,000 overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say this is a plot by financial institutions is a bit of a
stretch,'' Blandin said. It was Congress and the president that
required a private-sector partner for the summit, and the Labor
Department asked the council to submit a proposal for running the
event, he said. He said the agenda and panelists were chosen by the
White House and Congress, not by the council or its corporate
sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Blandin acknowledged that companies like Fidelity and American
Express might ``see it in their interest to make sure Americans
save and invest, and they're going to get a piece of that pie.''
But their support for the summit is ``general underwriting and in
an education mode that is not product-oriented,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 2153EDT &QL; 
