<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3075 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-worldcupfeature-HNS &LR;      06-03 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-world </SLUG>
 cup feature-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   France at home with idea of winning '98 Cup
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
The symbolism reeked, in more ways than one.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, when France was chosen to play host to this summer's
World Cup, organizers chose to construct the hallmark stadium for
the tournament at a former waste site.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Stade de France in Saint Denis, just north of Paris,
is a magnificent 80,000-seat structure already being hailed
worldwide as an architectural marvel.
</P>
<P>
   The stadium is consummately French _ a compilation of daring
angles and interesting designs featuring more steel than concrete
and topped by an elliptical roof that gives it a 21st-century
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   International soccer federation president Joao Havelange has
called the site for the 1998 World Cup final the most beautiful
stadium he has ever seen. It also seems to epitomize French soccer,
which has risen from the sad wastelands of the world to a thing of
beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Once a perennial power and Cup contender that reached the
semifinals in 1982 and 1986, France fell into a dismal era in the
early 1990s when it constantly fell short of expectations and
missed qualifying for the World Cup in 1990 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But since risk-taking coach Aime Jacquet took over the national
team just before the 1994 Cup and legendary French star Michel
Platini became a leader in the federation, French fortunes have
changed dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   This 1998 version might in fact be the strongest French team
ever, which is saying something considering the glorious run led by
Platini in the mid-1980s, which included the 1984 European
championship.
</P>
<P>
   And it might be Zinedine Zidane, a 25-year-old superstar with a
game as poetic as his name, who carries the team to a Cup
championship on the home turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly have changed; we have a real team personality,''
said Zidane, a professional star for Juventus of Turin. ``We have a
freshness of spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Zidane, dubbed ``the next Platini'' by Platini himself, is
arguably the best midfielder playing today. At minimum, he is at
the heart of a team that looks strong everywhere and has more
confidence than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that we've done over the last three years has been done
with a single goal in mind,'' Jacquet said. ``We are here to win
the World Cup, nothing less.''
</P>
<P>
   It starts, of course, with group play in the first stage of the
June 10-July 12 tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The French are joined in Group C by South Africa, Saudi Arabia
and Denmark, which are all strong teams but realistically will be
fighting it out for second place behind the French.
</P>
<P>
   After all, in the World Cup there is no such thing as
overstating the importance of the home advantage.
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, England managed to win at home. West Germany (in 1974)
and Argentina (1978) also used the enthusiastic and abundant home
crowds as a springboard to the World Cup title.
</P>
<P>
   With such a strong team and more than 80 percent of 1998 World
Cup tickets going to French fans, this definitely is a unique
opportunity for the hosts, who seemingly are coming together at the
perfect time.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, the French have lost only once in 30 full
international matches. Along the way, France has defeated England
in England and Italy in Italy _ impressive by any standard.
</P>
<P>
   And France has done it with Jacquet's attack-first strategy
paying big dividends. Constantly pressing the ball, the French have
gone on streaks of dominance such as the recent 10-match spell in
which they scored 28 goals and allowed only five. Zidane makes the
plays, and strikers Stephane Guivarc and David Trezeguet score the
goals.
</P>
<P>
   The June 12 French opener against South Africa in Marseilles
promises to be a special scene, with France not only hosting the
Cup in its first appearance since 1986 but showcasing a team that
could make it all the way to the final.
</P>
<P>
   As for the second team that will advance out of Group C, the bid
looks to be up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa figures to have trouble with both the pressure and
burden of playing in its first World Cup, but it is a talented team
nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Denmark has the most Cup experience of the Group C teams, but it
might have too much experience. This is an aging team, virtually
identical to the one of four years ago, with only goalkeeper Peter
Schmeichel probably still at the top of his game.
</P>
<P>
   And Saudi Arabia has been put under tremendous pressure to
succeed, especially after hiring 1994 Brazilian World Cup coach
Carlos Alberto Parreira to lead its team.
</P>
<P>
   The Saudi government and soccer federation have made it clear
that nothing short of a second-round appearance is expected. If
small but skilled Saudi forward Sami Al-Jaber gets on a roll, it
could happen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
