<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3076 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-FOOD-VENDORS-600&AMP;A     06-03 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FOOD-VENDORS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUSHCART FOOD VENDORS PROTEST MAYOR'S CRACKDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS.: Ancela Nastasi is cq.)  
 (ja)  
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As secretaries and stockbrokers alike came to their
defense, hundreds of sidewalk food vendors shut down their carts
Wednesday and paraded through lower Manhattan to protest the Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani's plan to restrict street sales in two broad
sections of Manhattan next month.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers in pinstripes and brokers in cuff links applauded as 800
peddlers of hot dogs, falafel and other cart cuisine marched
through the financial district a few hours after the 5 a.m. start
of a 24-hour work stoppage that left the city bereft of the
ubiquitous carts many New Yorkers view as a convenience but that
Giuliani considers a main cause of sidewalk congestion.
</P>
<P>
   The daylong absence of the $1 coffee-and-bagel specials, the
plastic plates of curried chicken and rice and the
two-dogs-with-mustard-and-onions lunch had time-pressed New Yorkers
grumbling as their stomachs rumbled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get them back!'' said Ancela Nastasi, a lawyer who said she
had voted for the mayor, as she wandered the cartless canyons of
the financial district in quest of a burrito.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's strongest support came Wednesday from proprietors of
the coffee shops and restaurants that compete with the carts. John
Poulos, owner of the Deli-Burger Restaurant in midtown Manhattan,
said he was delighted at the prospect of losing his meals on wheels
competition. ``They were killing us with their $1 coffee and
donut,'' he said. ``When I match their price, I lose 20 cents.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's protest resulted in an increase for Poulos' business
and he's hoping the change will be permanent. The vendors contended
that Wednesday's sidewalk famine could be a taste of things to come
if the mayor goes ahead with his plan to ban daytime street sales
of food, clothing, books and art from most of the financial
district and parts of midtown. Right now the city restricts vending
on many stretches of midtown avenues; the new rules would extend
the ban to many side streets.
</P>
<P>
   Eleni Pulako, 39, a sidewalk saleswoman from Brooklyn, asserted
that Giuliani was forgetting his roots in a quest for statewide or
national publicity as a tough guy. ``New York is dirty-water
dogs,'' she said, using an affectionate term employed by both
vendors and their customers.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference after the vendors marched from Liberty Park
in the heart of the financial district to Battery Park, where they
held a lunchtime rally, Giuliani defended the new rules as a
necessary part of a regulated and civilized society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's going to be out of work,'' he said. ``There are going
to be the same number of permits. They're just not going to be able
to be in exactly the place that they want to be. And that, of
course, makes sense. We can't have three, four, five food vendors
all in the same place, crowding the same place.''
</P>
<P>
   But the vendors, many of whom are immigrants, said the rules
would force them out of work by pushing them on to quieter streets
that would provide them with few customers. ``We are not educated
people,'' said Syed Sheren, 27, who has sold coffee and doughnuts
in midtown since moving from Afghanistan 10 years ago. ``We cannot
go work in the bank or work in the office.''
</P>
<P>
   Mohammed Haque, 39, a father of two who sells knishes and
pretzels near Wall Street, said he might return to Bangladesh to
avoid what he called the shame of welfare. ``I came to this country
with good dreams,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The sidewalk sellers feel they will be put out of business as a
result of a series of votes last month by the city's Street Vendor
Review Panel, a board dominated by mayoral appointees. Acting at
the mayor's request, it voted to close 144 blocks of Manhattan in
mid-July to vending of all sorts.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's work stoppage by food vendors, which appeared to be
nearly total, was organized by a group called the Big Apple Food
Vendors' Association, which contends that the restrictions resulted
from pressure on Giuliani from real estate interests and
restaurants. The group's president, Jeffrey Cicio, said the
shutdown of the carts and the demonstration _ at an estimated loss
to each vendor of about $125 in income _ would be followed by
``lawsuits, lobbyists and everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the limitations apply to artists and booksellers, Norman
Siegel, executive director of the New York Civil Liberties Union,
said he was looking into a possible First Amendment challenge.
Displaying a map of lower Manhattan with yellow highlighting
marking the streets that would be affected by the new restrictions,
he said: ``A court looking at a map like this will be very
suspicious. Is it really about congestion, or is it about
competition?''
</P>
<P>
   Several City Council members have introduced bills to repeal the
Street Vendor Review Panel and to institute a more systematic
approach to regulating the carts. ``The current process is akin to
a kangaroo court,'' said Councilman Anthony Weiner, D-Brooklyn.
``The regulations are anti-working class and anti-New York.''
</P>
<P>
   The new campaign is the latest in decades of efforts by many
mayors to corral the food vendors. Former Mayor Edward Koch said
Wednesday that Giuliani was making the same mistake he had made
when he proposed a bill in 1985 that would have barred food vending
from much of midtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The realtors and the theater owners came in to me and said,
`We don't want these people,' and I listened to them,'' Koch said.
``But then I thought, what are we doing? These are decent people,
and they give people the chance to buy an inexpensive lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   After taking a look at the so-called congestion himself during a
walk through midtown, Koch retracted his own bill.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, however, Koch said some corners looked ``like a souk,''
or a Middle Eastern marketplace. He ordered the police to begin
enforcing a law, on the books since 1983, banning vendors from the
most congested areas of Manhattan, Brooklyn and Queens. More than
1,000 vendors marched on City Hall in protest.
</P>
<P>
   In an agreement with the City Council six weeks later, Koch
relented in return for an agreement allowing no more than 10
vendors on each block in midtown. Shortly after taking office in
1994, Giuliani renewed the debate with the council over how to
enforce laws and regulations regarding vendors, which led to the
formation of the Street Vendor Review Panel.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has not taken his own street survey, said Jack Deacey,
a mayoral spokesman, but he added that the mayor observes the
streets as he drives through the city.
</P>
<P>
   The vendors' procession Wednesday was led by a cart sporting the
Hebrew National umbrella plastered with ``Going Out of Business''
signs. As the vendors wended down Broadway, past Wall Street and
Exchange Place, people emerged from subway stations and offices to
cheer them on.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Kaufmann, 30, a management consultant, said she was bitter
about having to spend twice as much for her morning coffee at a
shop and that she was mystified by the cart crackdown. ``You never
say: `Oh, my God. If that vendor weren't there, it would be easier
for me to get around,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rituals of all sorts were disrupted Wednesday. Lee Keith, a
stockbroker who gets a chili dog from his favorite cart on Mondays,
Wednesdays and Fridays and then tries to ``go light'' on the other
days with a plain hot dog, decided to forego lunch in support of
the vendors. ``They are New York,'' he said of the cart vendors.
``What's Giuliani thinking?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
