<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-TRUCK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TEAM NEGOTIATES LEARNING CURVE IN NASCAR TRUCK SERIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ It wasn't long before David Starr had a
Wizard of Oz kind of feeling. Late in a qualifying race for the
season-opening race of the NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series, Starr
realized he wasn't driving late-model stock cars in Texas anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Starr was two spots away from making the field for the Chevy
Trucks Challenge at Walt Disney World Speedway with two laps to go.
Directly ahead was the rear spoiler of the truck driven by Winston
Cup regular Bobby Hamilton, ``one of my heroes,'' Starr said.
</P>
<P>
   Hero or not, Starr had to get past. So he tried a maneuver that
would have worked when the 30-year-old, Arlington-based driver was
racing stock cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a good run on him coming off Turn 3 and got up beside
him,'' Starr said.
</P>
<P>
   But this wasn't Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ran me all the way to the bottom of the racetrack,'' Starr
said. ``I had to back off the gas. I didn't get by him. I could've
tapped him, but I figured our first race I didn't really need to
wreck a Winston Cup driver.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the unofficial welcome to the big time for Starr and the
Reher-Morrison racing team.
</P>
<P>
   The Arlington engine builders and successful drag racers are
running a limited schedule with an unsponsored entry in the truck
series, their first foray into a major NASCAR series. Their next
attempt at qualifying comes this evening at Texas Motor Speedway,
when they will try to make the field for the Pronto Auto Parts
400-kilometer race tomorrow night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to run as many races as we can,'' said Buddy Morrison,
who runs the truck operation while partner David Reher takes care
of drag racing. ``We need the experience, we need the practice.''
</P>
<P>
   The team's experience in drag racing makes it one of the best in
the National Hot Rod Association Pro Stock ranks. But
Reher-Morrison has no experience racing in a NASCAR series, and
can't afford to buy any.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 9 Reher-Morrison Motorsports Chevrolet traveled to three
of the first seven races. After failing to qualify at Disney World,
Starr put the truck in the field for races at Phoenix and Odessa,
Mo. He finished 25th and 23rd, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know you've got to go out there and pay your dues,''
Morrison said. ``That's the same way we did it in drag racing. We
started a long time ago, and made a lot of mistakes along the way,
but you learn as you go.''
</P>
<P>
   The team has learned several things so far.
</P>
<P>
   One is that the series costs a lot of money, a minimum of
$30,000 per race, and it's tough to do without a major sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a money-making venture by any means,'' Morrison said.
``We're paying for it all out of our pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrison appreciates this week's one-race deal from Dallas-based
Choice Cabs. But if a major sponsor doesn't come on board for next
year, it'll be difficult to do more than 10 races they've scheduled
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we'll attract some good, solid sponsorship and be
able to run the whole series, or enough to run a good partial
series,'' Morrison said.
</P>
<P>
   Another lesson is it takes more than a good motor to make the
truck go fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The engine is the easy part as far as we're concerned,''
Morrison said. ``Learning the chassis and the chassis setups, how
all that stuff works, that's the tough part. It's a big learning
curve.''
</P>
<P>
   The setups were the major problems in the two races so far. The
truck didn't handle well, and with little experience and an
undermanned crew they weren't able to make adjustments. Morrison,
Starr and Danny Keeton are the only full-time employees on the team
that has a part-time crew chief in Ken Simonson, who lives in
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really need six people,'' Morrison said. ``It was kind of a
fiasco.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr has learned that, unlike the racing series in Texas, he
alone can't compensate for a truck with handling problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the car wasn't handling well, I could manhandle it,'' he
said. ``In the trucks, if it's not handling well, you can't do
that. You have to slow down.''
</P>
<P>
   Slowing down requires patience, another lesson Starr is
learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to run up front and be competitive,'' Starr said. ``But
it's such a tough series, and we're such a new team. Our main goals
are to make the field and to finish the race. Every lap you're able
to run, you're getting better. If you crash early, you just missed
out on 195 laps.''
</P>
<P>
   The lessons continue. Morrison soaks them in, but he'd like the
learning curve to speed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 25, 30 years experience racing cars,'' he said. ``It's
something we've proven. We just need a good sponsor to come on
board. With a little backing, I think we can be real competitive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
