<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-INSURANCE-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS INDICTED IN INSURANCE FRAUD CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (dc) 
 By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a crackdown on insurance fraud that began with a
sweeping series of arrests in 1995, federal prosecutors Wednesday
announced the indictments of six lawyers in Brooklyn, Staten Island
and Long Island on charges of bribing insurance adjusters.
</P>
<P>
   Named in the indictments, which charged the lawyers with paying
off adjusters and corrupt insurance company middlemen in exchange
for favorable treatment in personal injury lawsuits, were a
Freeport lawyer who had sought the nomination for Nassau County
district attorney in 1974 and a former president of the Staten
Island Trial Lawyers Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``A system of secret kickbacks such as uncovered in this
investigation undermines confidence in negotiated settlements of
personal injury cases,'' said Zachary W. Carter, the U.S. attorney
for the Eastern District of New York, whose staff investigated the
case with the New York City office of the Federal Bureau of
Investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that these charges involve attorneys sworn to uphold
the law is all the more disturbing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   All six of the lawyers pleaded not guilty and each was released
on $250,000 bond after hearings Wednesday and on Tuesday before
Robert Levy, a magistrate in federal district dourt in Brooklyn.
Trial dates before Judge Carol Amon are to be scheduled on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers, all of whom were charged with a pattern of bribes
and kickbacks over several years, included Alvin Dorfman of
Freeport, who had lost his bid for the 1974 nomination for Nassau
County district attorney and Thomas Rybicki, a partner in the
Staten Island firm of Grae, Rybicki &AMP; Partners, who was identified
in court papers as a former president of the Staten Island Trial
Lawyers Association.
</P>
<P>
   Also named were Fredric Grae, a partner of Rybicki, and, in a
separate indictment, the entire firm headed by the two Staten
Island men. Other indictments named Theodore Bushlow of Brooklyn;
Joseph Levine of Hewlett on Long Island who practices in Brooklyn;
and Robert Malerba, a partner in the firm of Malerba, Downes &AMP;
Frankel in the Long Island town of Huntington.
</P>
<P>
   The indictments charged the lawyers with a pattern of criminal
activity intended to grease the wheels of personal injury lawsuits,
which often take months or years to resolve because of the
conflicting claims of people who are involved in cases like
automobile accidents.
</P>
<P>
   The charges describe a widespread scheme in which the lawyers
engaged a network of corrupt middlemen who worked as insurance
adjusters or had personal contacts inside insurance companies. The
middlemen were known as ``10 percenters'' or ``10 pointers''
because their bribes were calculated as a percent of the settlement
that would ultimately be received in the lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictments, the insurance companies defrauded
included some of the nation's largest _ Aetna, American
International Group, Geico, Continental, State Farm and Fireman's
Fund.
</P>
<P>
   For some of the lawyers charged, the indictments described a
pattern of bribery that had become almost routine. Grae and Rybicki
were charged with using at least four middlemen over a period of
two years and making payoffs in at least 12 cases. Dorfman, using
at least two middlemen, made payoffs in at least 25 cases over 14
years, the indictment said.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Alonso, an assistant U.S. attorney under Carter, said the
maximum penalties sought against each lawyer would be five years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   All six of the lawyers were said by people in their offices to
be away and unavailable for comment. A lawyer representing one of
those indicted, Malerba, called the charges groundless. `` Malerba
has been well respected by his community and his peers for over 35
years,'' his lawyer, Raymond Sotomayor, said. ``We will defend
against this indictment vehemently.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
