A3082 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TERRORIST-ARREST-460&AMP;     06-03 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERRORIST-ARREST-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECTED TERRORIST BROUGHT TO U.S. TO FACE CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Mohammed Rashid, a soft-spoken man who federal
investigators say is one of the Middle East's most dangerous
terrorists, has been brought to the United States amid high secrecy
to face charges for a 1982 airline bombing that killed a Japanese
youth.
</P>
<P>
   Rashid, 51, pleaded not guilty here on Wednesday to a nine-count
federal indictment that includes charges of murder, sabotage,
assault and placing bombs on aircraft. As for how and where he was
caught, a Justice Department spokesman, John Russell, said, ``We're
not disclosing anything _ absolutely nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The mystery surrounding Rashid's apprehension seemed appropriate
for a man who prosecutors say has crisscrossed the world using a
variety of aliases and fake passports to plant bombs meant to kill
total strangers in the name of the Palestinian cause.
</P>
<P>
   For years, federal investigators have sought Rashid for the Aug.
12, 1982, bombing of a Pan American World Airways liner that killed
Toru Ozawa, 16, on a flight from his native Japan to Honolulu. The
victim bled to death before the plane could land.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen other people were injured in the blast, which the
authorities say Rashid set off with a time-delayed bomb he planted
while traveling with his wife and their son on an earlier leg of
the flight, from Hong Kong to Japan.
</P>
<P>
   That 1982 bombing may be all but forgotten, in light of
subsequent terrorist attacks on the air and on the ground, but
law-enforcement officials consider it the first terrorist bomb
attack on an airline.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment accuses Rashid of placing a bomb two weeks later
on another Pan Am plane. That bomb was found before it exploded,
but investigators said its wiring matched that found on a hair-thin
sliver found in Toru Ozawa's body.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment says Rashid belongs to the terrorist 15th of May
organization and was a high-ranking aide to the group's leader, Abu
Ibrahim. The group was based in Baghdad, the indictment says, and
it was in the Japanese Embassy there that Rashid and his wife
submitted false visa applications that helped Rashid carry out the
bombing that killed the Japanese youth.
</P>
<P>
   Rashid's wife, Christine Pinter, who is sometimes known as
Fatima, is also accused in the indictment. She is still at large,
Russell of the Justice Department said today. The whereabouts of
the couple's son, Zuhair, is also unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Russell said the government would seek a sentence of life in
prison for Rashid rather than the death penalty. That fact may
indicate that a nation turned Rashid over to the United States,
since other nations typically ask Washington to promise not to
execute defendants when it hands them over, Russell conceded. There
were rumors early Wednesday evening that Rashid had been handed
over by Egypt.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The indictment charging Rashid, his wife and Abu Ibrahim was
returned in 1987. Rashid was arrested on a false-passport charge in
Greece in 1988, but the authorities there refused a U.S. request to
extradite him.
</P>
<P>
   A Greek court convicted Rashid in 1992 of the fatal airline
bombing, and he was sentenced to 18 years in prison. That sentence
was reduced to 15 years by an appeals court, and Rashid was
released in 1996 for good behavior_ a development that angered U.S.
officials. Rashid then flew to Cairo and was deported to Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
   The arraignment on Wednesday before Judge Aubrey Robinson in
U.S. District Court here suggested that Rashid had not been long in
U.S. custody. The hearing was delayed nearly an hour, until the
arrival of Rashid's lawyer, Tony Miles of the U.S. Public
Defender's office. Miles apologized to Robinson for not wearing a
suit coat, explaining that he had had to rush to court.
</P>
<P>
   Rashid, a baldish, slightly built man, answered questions
through an interpreter, who talked to him in Arabic. Rashid
described himself as a Palestinian who had been ``thrown out'' of
his country in 1948, when Israel was founded.
</P>
<P>
   He said he understood the court proceedings, although he
complained about having to answer the same charges in the United
States that he was imprisoned for in Greece.
</P>
<P>
   Rashid and the prosecutors agreed on one thing, in a sense.
Describing his nationality, Rashid said, ``I have been a vagabond
between the Arab countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly, the prosecutors said, saying he should not be granted
bail under any circumstances. Robinson set a hearing for Friday on
that issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
