r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-BELMONT-TEX     06-03 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECTACULAR BID OFFERS PROOF BEST CAN LOSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ The week of the 1979 Belmont Stakes, trainer Bud
Delp felt like one of the most important men on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   He had a room at Manhattan's plush Plaza Hotel. Every morning,
he was ferried to the track in a chauffeured limousine, compliments
of the New York Racing Association. And his sensational 3-year-old
colt Spectacular Bid was considered a shoo-in to capture the
Belmont and with it an elusive piece of sports hardware.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of us were sitting on a bale of straw at Belmont Park the
morning before the race,'' Delp recalls. ``I said, `All we've got
to do is lead him to the paddock and the Triple Crown is ours.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That brashness was extinguished the next afternoon, when Coastal
won the mile-and-a-half Belmont Stakes. Spectacular Bid, the 1-to-5
favorite, faltered in the stretch and finished third.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet also is expected to be an overwhelming favorite in
Saturday's Belmont in his attempt at a Triple Crown. But
Spectacular Bid's loss, one of the sport's greatest upsets, is only
one illustration of how that road to glory is littered with
unexpected casualties. In the years since, would-be sweepers
Pleasant Colony, Alysheba, Sunday Silence and Silver Charm were
thwarted in the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   Some were unlucky, others outrun. But the story behind
Spectacular Bid's loss is easily the most bizarre, the
quintessential racetrack version of Murphy's Law: If anything can
go wrong, it will, and at the worst possible moment.
</P>
<P>
   Just before sunrise the morning of the Belmont Stakes, the
confident Delp stepped out of his limo at the barn. As soon as his
feet touched the ground, he heard groom Herman ``Mo'' Hall
shouting: ``He's lame, boss. The colt's lame!''
</P>
<P>
   Delp hurried to Spectacular Bid's stall, where the steel-gray
colt was holding his right front foot above the straw bedding.
</P>
<P>
   When Delp picked up the foot, he saw a safety pin bent and
embedded about three-eighths of an inch into the underside of the
hoof.
</P>
<P>
   He knew immediately what had happened. As a playful youngster,
Spectacular Bid liked to use his teeth to tear off safety pins that
secured his protective leg bandages. Hall discouraged ``Bid'' by
placing adhesive tape over the safety pins, and covering the tape
with hot Cayenne pepper.
</P>
<P>
   But Spectacular Bid somehow worked a pin loose, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one in a million,'' Delp said. ``The pin must have
slipped out and went into the straw. Then he probably got hungry
overnight, and he was pawing big time because he wanted to eat.
When he wanted something, he stomped his feet like a
sledgehammer.''
</P>
<P>
   Delp immediately removed the pin, and pus oozed from the small
wound.
</P>
<P>
   Spectacular Bid appeared to walk soundly, and the foot was cold,
but Delp recalled similar experiences with nails and glass. Things
seldom turned out well, especially when such wounds were exposed to
the urine and feces in straw bedding.
</P>
<P>
   Delp packed the foot in cool mud mixed with vinegar and Epsom
salts, headed back to the hotel and phoned owner Harry Meyerhoff,
who agreed that Spectacular Bid would have to be scratched from the
Belmont if the foot became sore during the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Several restless hours later, Delp returned to the barn. Media
swarmed the front of the barn, so Delp sneaked Spectacular Bid
around to the back side and jogged him to and fro.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked 100 percent sound,'' Delp said. ``I said I think we
can get away with it. So we ran.''
</P>
<P>
   Spectacular Bid opened a three-length lead near the Belmont
stretch under young jockey Ronnie Franklin, but Delp soon realized
he had miscalculated.
</P>
<P>
   According to Delp, Spectacular Bid raced the entire distance
while leading with his left front leg to avoid putting pressure on
his right foot. As a result, he grew fatigued in the final
quarter-mile. He came out of the race with a sore left leg and a
badly infected right foot that took two months to heal.
</P>
<P>
   Spectacular Bid went on to become perhaps the greatest racehorse
ever, losing only once more, later that year to 1978 Triple Crown
champion Affirmed. At his Maryland home, Delp has a VHS tape with
all 26 of the colt's lifetime victories.
</P>
<P>
   The Belmont Stakes is not on the tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched it one time and one time only,'' Delp said. ``I
never watched a tape of it, and I never will. I knew what happened.
I tortured him. It was the only time in his whole racing career
that anybody ever passed him in the stretch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
