<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980603.0515 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3086 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AKINWANDE-COX     06-03 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AKINWANDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holyfield foe fought dad first
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A stretch limo picked up Henry Akinwande at his
luxury hotel recently and shuttled him from one television station
to another. A second heavyweight title shot in less than a year was
nearing. So was a $2.5 million payday.
</P>
<P>
   Life as an outcast is good.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in Nigeria, they believe you have to be destitute to be
messing with boxing,'' said Akinwande, who was born in England but
grew up in Lagos, Nigeria. ``My father, he went crazy. He went down
to the gym where I was working out and he told the trainer, `If you
train him again, I'm going to come down and lock you up in prison.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Akinwande decided against a citizen's arrest several
years ago. Instead, he merely disowned his teenage son.
</P>
<P>
   Akinwande is in the unlikely role of challenger for Evander
Holyfield's heavyweight title Saturday night at Madison Square
Garden. His entire career has been unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Akinwande was born in 32 years ago in Dulwich, England, to
Nigerian parents who left Lagos to be educated in England. After
getting degrees, the family returned to Nigeria when Henry was
eight and Joseph Akinwande went into the import/export business.
</P>
<P>
   It was the father's hope that his son would one day pursue a
college degree and take over the business. But Akinwande had other
plans. Wanting to learn how to defend himself, he started going to
a boxing gym as a teenager. The sport became more than a diversion
for him, and by the time he was 17 he decided to pursue it as a
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father wanted to kill me,'' he said. ``He did not want me
to go into boxing. And you have to understand _ in Nigeria, when
your father wants you to do something, you do it. But this was
something I wanted to do. He said, `Fine, if you box, leave.' So I
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Akinwande moved back to England and resumed boxing in a gym in
the London suburbs. He became one of the top amateurs in England,
made the 1988 Olympic team, then turned pro the next year. He
accumulated 32 wins and a draw in his first 33 fights, the most
impressive victory being a third-round knockout of Jeremy Williams
for the lightly regarded WBO belt in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Akinwande and his son eventually reconciled, although
Joseph still dislikes boxing and won't be in New York this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he respects the fact that I was a man _ that I set out
to do something and I made it,'' Akinwande said. ``His friends told
him that there was nothing he could do about it because I was doing
something that I loved and I was making more money than people who
become engineers.''
</P>
<P>
   In terms of respect, however, Akinwande may have earned more
from his family than from boxing fans. His first big chance for a
major title came in July against WBC champion Lennox Lewis in
Stateline, Nev. A number of boxing experts thought that the
6-foot-7 Akinwande might upset Lewis. Instead, he earned the
nickname ``Huggin' Henry'' by continually holding Lewis and was
disqualified in the fifth round by referee Mills Lane.
</P>
<P>
   Another title shot was unlikely. But it was ruled Orlin Norris
was bypassed in the rankings illegally and should have been given a
title shot. Norris was told he would get a bout with Holyfield if
he first beat anybody in the top 10. But promoter Don King offered
only $50,000 to a challenger, and Akinwande was the lone boxer to
accept. Norris lost a 12-round decision, making Akinwande a
mandatory challenger.
</P>
<P>
   The public largely views Akinwande as an undeserving challenger,
as someone who choked in his one big fight. He has issued a series
of excuses for the Lewis loss:
</P>
<P>
   _ The smaller ring in Stateline affected his strategy;
</P>
<P>
   _ The high altitude hindered his breathing;
</P>
<P>
   _ His trainer then, Don Turner, largely ignored him in camp
because he was spending most of his time with Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   The excuses have only increased the criticism. Akinwande's
response: ``I'm here to prove people wrong. The people who say I
don't have any heart, I don't have any guts, they don't know. They
don't know what I've lived through.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
