</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABSOLUTELY ANYTHING FOR A TICKET
</HEADLINE>
  (ja)  
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY, Utah _ On a gorgeous afternoon in a city known
for its laid-back veneer, basketball fans went a little crazy over
their Jazz Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   There was a pregame stream of cars, vans and jeeps decorated in
purple Jazz paraphernalia: streamers, flags and banners. Fans
walked around with ``Beat the Bulls'' placards.
</P>
<P>
   They converged on the downtown Gallivan Center, where a variety
of booths had been set up for fans' participation.
</P>
<P>
   By 2 o'clock the audience had grown to 150. This was the moment
of truth: they had come to watch five fans vie for the right to win
two pairs of tickets to Game 1 Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a promotion by KFAN Radio, fans were asked what they
would do, how far they would go, how desperate they were to win
tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Young Sandy Fender came wearing a bikini and then had a tattoo
man put a Jazz team logo very low on her back. In the back of the
plaza, Tony Dail sat on his custom Softail Harley-Davidson dressed
in leather chaps with two Jazz stickers on his buttocks. At the
appointed time, Dail revved up the motorcycle, drove to the middle
of the square, got off his bike and did a shimmy shake, a la Mark
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The program director of KFAN, David Locke, said the station had
hoped that Indiana would be the Jazz's opponent, because they had
wanted to bring a race car and smash it up. He said it was a little
harder to come up with something for the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Next came Mark Miller, a 25-year-old engineer crossdressed to
look like the pop singer Celine Dion. Miller belted out an
absolutely horrible falsetto version of the love song from
``Titanic'' with Jazz lyrics substituted for the original words.
</P>
<P>
   Each contestant was received politely.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Blair Postma came out and took out a jar containing 15
goldfish that he planned to devour. ``I just figured that 15 is the
number of playoff games we have to win to win the championships,''
he explained. Asked if his mother knew he was doing this, Postma
smiled and said sure, she's right there, and pointed to his mother
and her friends snapping pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Just before he went up to do his thing, Postma said: ``I'll eat
the first 11, then the last four I'm going to chew up, like the
Jazz are going to chew up Chicago tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   As he gulped, fans chanted: ``Blair, Blair, Blair,'' then
``U-tah, U-tah.''
</P>
<P>
   There is clearly a marriage in Salt Lake City, a confluence of
purpose surrounding basketball: fans as desperate to win
championship tickets as the players, especially Karl Malone and
John Stockton, are to win a championship.
</P>
<P>
   The sense in Salt Lake City, if you go by what you hear and
read, is one of supreme confidence that 1998, finally, is Utah's
year:
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls are coming off a grueling seven-game series against
the Pacers, the Bulls are showing their age, the Bulls have no one
to stop Karl Malone. Utah has the home-court advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think we've got them where we want them,'' Postma
said before swallowing the goldfish. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The final contestant of the day was a man known only as Dale; no
one expected him to top Postma. Until he announced was going to eat
a Dennis Rodman sandwich, and produced two slices of white bread
with worms in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   There were shrieks from those at the front, howls of disgust
from those in the back. But everyone applauded wildly for Dale,
even as they averted their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   So Postma and Dale were hands-down winners. They sat next to
each other Wednesday night, rooting with 19,000 others for Utah to
begin the end of the Bulls' dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win ... when we win,'' Postma corrected, ``this place
will be crazy, major hysteria.'' No one here even mentions the
possibility of a loss. Some even predict a Utah victory in five or
six games. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What happens if you lose? What happens if Utah loses?
</P>
<P>
   ``If we lose I think you better close off all the buildings' top
floors,'' Blair said. ``Somebody might try to jump off.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday a lot of people were convinced that Utah was the
team of destiny.
</P>
<P>
   After spending an afternoon at Gallivan Center, things do not
seem as sure.
</P>
<P>
   Fans truly love their Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   But the outward confidence punctured by this underlying sense of
desperation _ all this eating of fish, devouring of worms, even
singing the theme song from ``Titanic,'' it all seems terribly
ominous. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
