<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDWATER-FUNERAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDWATER IS HONORED AS A MAN OF PRINCIPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Former Sen. Barry M. Goldwater once told his
minister at the end of a friend's funeral that it had been a
``damngood'' send-off, and that is what he got himself Wednesday
afternoon when his own time to go came around.
</P>
<P>
   In a memorial service here filled with military pagentry,
tearful reminiscences and glowing encomiums, Goldwater, who was 89
when he died last Friday of natural causes, was hailed as a man of
honesty and principle to a fault and a politician who did more than
any other to set the Republican Party on its current conservative
course.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all the history of American politics, Barry Goldwater will
remain a chapter unto himself,'' Sen. John McCain, his successor in
Washington and a fellow Republican, told three thousand mourners, a
planeload of them from Washington, who crowded into Arizona State
University's Gammage Auditorium to say goodbye to the crusty,
curmudgeonly Republican who lost by a landslide to Lyndon Johnson
in the 1964 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   A private funeral service for the family was held just before
the memorial service. Later, a family spokesman said the senator's
remains would be cremated, and his ashes, in accordance with his
frequently expressed wish, would be spread in the Grand Canyon if
details could be worked out with the National Park Service and
Indian tribes who live there.
</P>
<P>
   During the memorial service, Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt, a
former Arizona governor and the only Democrat to speak, compared
Goldwater to Geronimo, saying ``freedom was everything'' to both
men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barry Goldwater and the great chieftian stand together,''
Babbitt said, ``both unique, both momentous, both among God's
maginificent creations.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Babbitt read a message of praise from President Clinton, in
which the president concluded that the way Goldwater conducted his
life constituted ``citizenship that we all must emulate.''
</P>
<P>
   So the encomiums went, for more than 90 minutes, now and again
interspersed with a bit of martial music (Goldwater was a retired
two-star Air Force Reserve general) and religious song and prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Goldwater's brother Bob, tears glistening, told of how a sibling
he never dreamed would one day run for president had played
baseball (Barry batted crosshanded). He laughed, tears still
glistening, as he rembered Barry teasing girls with mice, back in a
long ago time when Phoenix was just a dusty desert town and Arizona
was the nation's newest state.
</P>
<P>
   He did not dwell on that presidential run, a political debacle
in which the senator took one of the worst beatings ever
administered in a presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, hardly any other of Wednesday's speaker's dwelt
on that defeat, just as few mentioned the intense criticism of the
senator for his outspoken stands on race, welfare and other social
issues, some so conservative as to border on harshness and
insensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did any of the speakers dwell on Goldwater's
sail-against-the-wind penchant in later life to pull back from the
hard right on some hot issues, namely abortion and gays in the
military.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, Wednesday being a day to honor the dead, the speakers
saw the terrible defeat of 1964 as losing a battle and winning a
war as shown by the current Republican dominance in Congress and in
many states. And they saw the senator's hardline bluntness as
courage and refusal to compromise in an age of political
chamelions, as one put it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He new that in the end the most important thing was to tell
the truth,'' Jon Kyl, Arizona's other senator, said of the 1964
race. ``And he died a winner _ witness the people in this
auditorium.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the hundreds of Arizonans who had come to pay final
respects there were in the assemblage the likes of House Speaker
New Gingrich, Senate Leader Trent Lott, former Vice President Dan
Quayle, Gov. Pete Wilson of California and Nancy Reagan, wife of
the former president, toting a brightly colored parasol to ward off
the desert son.
</P>
<P>
   Each of them knew in their hearts that not only was Barry
Goldwater ``right,'' as his campagin slogan in 1964 had proclaimed
but that they, by right, owed much of what they had accomplished in
political life to the conservative revolution he sparked in defeat.
</P>
<P>
   A fitting Goldwater epitaph, Kyl, a Republican, concluded, might
be: ``An honest man who tried.''
</P>
<P>
   The service included a performance by Robert Tree Cody, an
American Indian who said he had written a song for the senator.
</P>
<P>
   He blew a melancholy melody on a flute-like instrument and then
in a voice equally melancholy in his native dialect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sing this song to a great man,'' he concluded, in English.
</P>
<P>
   Then, closing the ceremony, an honor guard marched onto the
stage, gently lifted the American flag draped over the casket of
burnished wood, folded it just-so into a star-studded triangle and
handed it to Goldwater's widow, Susan.
</P>
<P>
   A buglar sounded taps. And a firing squad brought it all to a
end with three crashing volleys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
