<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDWATER-COLOR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAREWELL TO BARRY GOLDWATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE YOZWIAK  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ After a F-16 streaked into the sun at Wednesday's
memorial to Barry Goldwater, scores of visiting dignitaries turned
from their VIP chairs and filed one by one through a back door into
Tempe's Gammage Auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   Watching as Nancy Reagan, Bob Dole, Newt Gingrich and the others
approached the door was nine-year-old Rachael Theorin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighty, eighty-one and eighty-two,'' Rachael counted, as she
totaled the number of who stepped over a plastic TV-cable cover, as
opposed the 200 officials who stepped on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to know,'' Rachael said of her count.
</P>
<P>
   Her friend, Megan Schoultz, 8, another third-grader at Aguilar
Elementary School in Tempe, needed another look at her program to
answer a reporter's question about why she had come to the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came to see the jets and to honor (hesitating as she looked
down) - uh, Barry Goldwater!'' Megan said.
</P>
<P>
   While a novelty for the young, something they can tell their
grandchildren about, Goldwater's memorial was a profound moment for
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a native Arizonan,'' said Margaret Livoni, 80, of Tempe.
``I've watched Barry for many years, and I've admired him for the
longest time,'' she said, sitting at the end of a row in the lower
balcony of the auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Gammage was the perfect place to stage the
memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Parking was easy, the walk was short, and there was a seat for
anyone who wanted one. The building was full except for the last
five rows of the upper balcony.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, about 100 people stayed outside and listened to the
ceremony on loudspeakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice day,'' said Mike Pugh, 24, a business student at
adjacent Arizona State University,
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know a whole lot about him, except that he was
fair,'' Pugh said, sitting beneath a towering silk oak as a light
breeze made the nearly 90-degree temperatures somewhat pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   A few people fainted in the noon-day sun waiting for Goldwater's
cortege to arrive, including four members of a large Luke Air Force
Base contingent _ dressed in heavy, dress uniforms _ who lined the
walks to Gammage.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Frank Barlow, 24, a trumpeter with the 36th U.S. Army Band
of Ft. Huachuca, was awed by the spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've participated in more than 400 funerals. This is
definitely the most visible. I just think it's a great honor,''
said Barlow, who hails from Bluefield, West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, at the public visitation in downtown Phoenix,
Carolynn Robinson reached out to touch the red and white stripes on
the flag over Barry Goldwater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to remember that. I wanted to touch a piece of
history,'' said the Phoenix woman, one of many mothers who took
their children to visit Trinity Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   Among the notables who arrived at Gammage was former Sen. Bob
Dole of Kansas who, like Goldwater, won his party's presidential
nomination, but lost to a southern Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barry was there for me when I needed him. I'm not just talking
about politics. I'm talking about our legislative work,'' said
Dole, making a distinction between lawmaking and running for
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was one of 43 House members who supported him in '64,'' Dole
said of Goldwater's defeat at the hands of President Lyndon
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was there at the beginning, and I wanted to be here at the
finish,'' said Dole, who lost to President Clinton in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Attorney General Grant Woods accompanied Dole:
</P>
<P>
   ``i think Barry Goldwater WAS Arizona. He was here from the
beginning, and he represents all that's best about us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the question now is, how much of his spirt and
character do we carry forward? And I think the answer to that will
determine how well we do as a state,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich, also was touched by Goldwater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was one of those who, as a high school student, read
``Conscience of a Conservative.'' I campaigned for Barry in '64. He
campaigned for me twice in '74 and '76,'' said the Georgia
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it marks the passing of an era; of just a very great
man who had really done an amazing amount to stand up for
individual liberty, and the preservation of freedom.'' Gingrich
said.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Chen, (EDITORS: CQ, AS DISTINGUISHED FROM CHIEN BELOW )
an economic and cultural representative for the Republic of China,
the non-communist Chinese state that Goldwater championed, also
spoke of the former Arizona senator's dedication to freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always treasured his friendship and support for the
Republic of China. He's one of the few true friends of the Republic
of China over the past six decades,'' said Chen, who accompanied
the speaker of the Republic of China's National Assembly, Fredrick
F. Chien.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always stood up for the cause of freedom and democracy. And
we considered him a man of principles; a man of great bravery and
courage,'' said Chen.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone who attended the event remembered Goldwater fondly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barry Goldwater, without any doubt in my mind, was the most
important person in making me be interested in politics,'' said
Louis Rhodes, former Arizona executive director of the American
Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he taught me enough (about politics) so that when I was
old enough to vote, I never voted for him,'' said Rhodes, who
nevertheless felt compelled to attend the memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the auditorium, Pastor Fred Phelps of the Westboro
Baptist Church, led his Topeka, Kan., congregation in one of its
many pickets against those, who, like Goldwater, have supported gay
rights and abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. J.D. Hayworth, R-Ariz., at first claimed he didn't
notice the protesters, though he obviously knew their message.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a free society,'' Hayworth said.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I think there are better ways to cherish one's memory, I
also know that if Barry was about anything, he was about freedom of
the individual, and even those who would sadly use this occasion to
try to further their political agendas.'' &QL; 
Steve Yozwiak can be reached at 444-8810 or at
steve.yozwiak(at)pni.com via the Internet. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
