<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDWATER-ORATIONS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARRY GOLDWATER REMEMBERED IN SPEECHES, MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Arizona and the nation's political leadership honored
former Sen. Barry Goldwater Wednesday, saying good-bye to the
American icon with a funeral service punctuated by tears and
laughter.
</P>
<P>
   More than 3,000 mourners, including former First Lady Nancy
Reagan, 30 U.S. Senators and four decades' worth of Arizona
political figures, filled ASU's Grady Gammage Auditorium to
remember Goldwater's life as a military leader, a politician, a
brother and a father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that if you were to go anywhere in this country,
virtually anywhere in the world, you would discover that there are
two Arizonans who are literally known throughout this planet. One
is Geronimo and the other is Barry Goldwater,'' said Interior
Secretary and former Arizona Gov. Bruce Babbitt.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt carried a message from President Clinton to the
Goldwater family that read, ``Few Americans in our history have
served the people with such a remarkable blend of conviction,
integrity and basic decency.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us who knew Barry were lifted by the sparkle in his
eyes, the warmth of his heart, the depth of his humanity,'' the
message from Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Goldwater's funeral drew two planeloads of Senators and House
members, including Speaker Newt Gingrich, Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott, North Carolina Republican Sens. Strom Thurmond and
Jesse Helms, and Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Also on hand were California Gov. Pete Wilson, former Sen. Bob
Dole, former vice president Dan Quayle and former U.S. House
minority leader John Rhodes of Arizona. Gov. Jane Hull and five of
her predecessors, Fife Symington, Rose Mofford, Babbitt, Jack
Williams and Paul Fannin were in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Goldwater died Friday at his Paradise Valley home. He was 89.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, thousands of Arizonans have paid tribute to the man
known as ``Mr. Arizona'' at the downtown Phoenix church where he
was baptized. Early Wednesday, dozens began up outside Gammage to
ensure a seat for the funeral service.
</P>
<P>
   An Air Force honor guard carried Goldwater's casket, draped with
the American flag, into the auditorium. The service was presided
over by Rabbi Albert Plotkin and the Rev. Carl Carlozzi, rector of
All Saints Episcopal Church.
</P>
<P>
   Six grandssons, including Barry Goldwater III and Michael
Goldwater Jr., served as pallbearers. Family members, including his
second wife, Susan, followed behind as hundreds lined along the
street watched in silence.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, Goldwater's casket was flanked by Organ Pipe cactus and
backlit by a photo of the Grand Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   The five-term senator, born when Arizona was still a territory,
was hailed as the state's favorite son, a man who put Arizona on
the map and who spearheaded the conservative movement in America.
</P>
<P>
   Native American flutist Robert Tree Cody also honored
Goldwater's longtime relationship with the Native American
community with a flute solo and a prayer, ``You are a great man,
you are with the elders now. You are a chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``My people will never forget you as long as we shall live,''
said Cody, a Maricopa and Dakota Indian.
</P>
<P>
   John McCain, who succeed Goldwater in Senate in 1987, may have
summed up Goldwater's political legacy the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barry Goldwater served America, all of America, a country
conceived in liberty, a country that let you pledge any damn thing
you wanted as long as it didn't cost someone else their liberty.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all the history of American politics, he will remain a
chapter unto himself. The rest of us will have to make do with
footnotes.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jon Kyl also spoke, as did longtime Goldwater friend Ron
Crawford, who concluded by saying, ``You really had class. Goldie,
you were really some kind of a guy. Hasta la vista, my friend.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Goldwater's youngest brother, Bob, though, who evoked
gales of laughter as he sweetly recalled Barry Goldwater's hijinks
as a young man and as a manager in the family's retail business.
</P>
<P>
   He brought down the house when he recalled how Goldwater devised
``antsy pants'' men's boxer shorts with ``big red ants'' on them.
</P>
<P>
   The ad slogan was, ``You rant and dance with antsy pants.``
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran that ad in ``The New Yorker,'' and we sold those shorts
in every state in the nation. It was unbelievable,'' Bob Goldwater
said.
</P>
<P>
   The audience chuckled as he also recalled how his brother ``had
a great taste for things that were pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He could buy dresses for women,'' Goldwater recalled, pausing
before adding, ``and sell them.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldwater's son, Barry Jr., touchingly concluded the ceremony by
promising that Goldwater's extensive family would carry on his
legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to wish you, ``Happy trails, Dad.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Michael Murphy can be reached at 444-8546 or at
michael.murphy(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
