<HEADER>
A3106 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLDWATER-DEMENTIA-AZ     06-03 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDWATER-DEMENTIA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NANCY REAGAN, SUSAN GOLDWATER SHARED ROLE OF CAREGIVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN WEST  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Nancy Reagan, who was in the Valley on Wednesday for
Barry Goldwater's funeral, has been in touch with Susan Goldwater
over the past year to participate in what may have been one of the
most exclusive support groups in America.
</P>
<P>
   While their husbands have a connection _ Goldwater was Reagan's
political mentor _ the women also have a separate connection. Both
have served as caregiver second wives to former political leaders
suffering from age-related mental dementia. Both men served as
icons of American conservatism and have similar followings.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan has Alzheimer's disease, and Goldwater suffered the past
year from a form of dementia that kept him out of the public eye.
</P>
<P>
   Dementia is defined as the loss of at least two or more
important mental functions such as memory, language, visual or
spacial judgment due to a stroke, Alzheimer's disease or other
reasons. After Goldwater had a stroke, physicians said that it
triggered a form of dementia, though there were differences of
opinion over the diagnosis. While many people automatically think
of Alzheimer's, there are hundreds of types of dementia.
Alzheimer's accounts for 56 percent of dementia cases, however.
</P>
<P>
   Experts in the field have watched, from afar, with admiration
how Nancy Reagan and Susan Goldwater have eloquently and elegantly
handled difficult situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are fabulously strong women,'' said Geri Hall, a
clinical nurse specialist at Scottsdale's Mayo Clinic who has
worked with families of dementia patients for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Susan Goldwater was not just in charge of her husband's care,
which any dementia patient's family will tell you is no easy task,
but she has also been in charge of Barry Goldwater's historical
reputation. Like Nancy Reagan, she has handled the responsibility
seriously _ role models for those of us who may have to deal with
this in the future,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   With more people living longer, the chances of more people
suffering from Alzheimer's or another form of dementia is expected
to triple over the next 40 years. For those 85 and older, the
chances of having a form of dementia are as high as 50 percent.
Goldwater was 89.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether a family chooses to be very public about it, like the
Reagans, or more private, like the Goldwaters, it's a difficult
path. No single way to handle the situation is more correct,'' Hall
said. ``The family has to keep in mind what the patient would want.
</P>
<P>
   ``For any patient, there is a tremendous need to preserve
dignity, but that is a challenge for a public figure. Some social
activists will want the celebrity's disease to be made public, to
show that anyone can get the disease and de-stigmatize others who
suffer from it.''
</P>
<P>
   The celebrity attention can bring more dollars to medical
research, which has been a conscious objective of Nancy Reagan's
public open-door attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message is, if Ronald Reagan can get Alzheimer's, anyone
can get it,'' Hall observed.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as the '60s and '70s, dementia was regarded as a
mental frailty, not a specific disease. That came in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Many people with dementia withdraw from society, according to
Hall. They often have auditory and language problems. Some also
have visual and spacial problems, and may not feel comfortable with
visitors. It isn't uncommon for someone with dementia to simply
leave a room when visitors arrive or to make inappropriate
statements.
</P>
<P>
   For someone who will be remembered for great accomplishments,
caregivers may feel an extra obligation to choreograph a dignified
last chapter. Whatever they do, however, caregivers will be
criticized _ they are either denying access or providing too much
exposure, depending on the sensibilities of different family
members, friends or supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us have a responsibility to protect our loved ones, but
this is almost a historical responsibility these two women have
had,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Goldwater Jr. thanked Susan Goldwater publicly at the
memorial service at ASU on Wednesday for her professional knowledge
about end-of-life issues and the love she gave to his father.
</P>
<P>
   This week will not be the end of that curatorial work for Susan
Goldwater.
</P>
<P>
   What she learns will undoubtedly be shared with her friend,
Nancy. &QL; 
Maureen West can be reached at 444-8167 or at
maureen.west(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
