<HEADLINE>
EFFIE AWARDS, NEW AD ACCOUNTS, EXECS ON THE MOVE  
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: N.Y., Wash, Mich., Calif, Texas, Ill., Ga., N.J., Va.) (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Effie Awards Are Presented
</P>
<P>
   The M&AMP;M/Mars division of Mars &UR;  &LR; Inc. won the top prize Wednesday
night when the New York chapter of the American Marketing
Association presented its 30th annual Effie Awards, which recognize
effectiveness in advertising.
</P>
<P>
   M&AMP;M/Mars and its agency, BBDO New York, part of Omnicom Group,
won the Grand Effie for a humorous campaign for Snickers candy
bars; one commercial showed a worker on a football field,
painstakingly painting the word ``Chefs'' in the end zone. The
campaign also won a gold Effie in the snacks, desserts and
confections category.
</P>
<P>
   BBDO New York also won a gold Effie for a campaign for the Visa
USA check card that features humorous appearances by Shirley
MacLaine, Bob Dole and Daffy Duck.
</P>
<P>
   Offices of McCann-Erickson Worldwide Advertising, part of the
McCann-Erickson World Group of the Interpublic Group of Companies,
won the most Effies, 14 _ seven for the New York office, three for
Seattle, two for San Francisco and one each for Dallas and Troy,
Mich. DDB Needham Worldwide, part of Omnicom, won nine Effies,
eight for the Chicago office and one for New York. And two agencies
owned by WPP Group PLC _ Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide and J. Walter
Thompson Co. _ each won eight Effies; Ogilvy's were all won by its
New York office while Thompson's were won by offices in Atlanta
(two), Chicago (two), Detroit (two) and New York (two).  &QL; 
MTA Renews Pact With Korey Kay
</P>
<P>
   The Metropolitan Transportation Authority in New York said on
Wednesday that as expected it had renewed its advertising contract
with Korey Kay &AMP; Partners &UR;  &LR;  in New York for another three-year
term. Billings were estimated at $10 million for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Korey Kay, which has handled the MTA account since 1992, kept
the assignment after a five-month mandated review that included New
York-based agencies whose identities were not disclosed. Korey
Kay's recent campaigns for the MTA included the introduction of the
Metrocard and commercials featuring the voice of the actor Mandy
Patinkin.  &QL; 
Three Companies Decide on Accounts
</P>
<P>
   Three advertisers have made decisions on their accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Parmalat USA Corp. in Teaneck, N.J., a subsidiary of the Italian
food company Parmalat SpA, named Arnell Group Brand Consulting in
New York to handle its account, which had been handled by MgM &AMP;
Partners in New York. Billings have not been determined.
</P>
<P>
   Arnell Group was awarded the account after a four-month review
that also included seven agencies whose identities were not
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Hewitt in Virginia Beach, Va., the tax preparation
service unit of the Cendant Corp., named Grey Advertising in New
York to handle its account, which had been handled by the Burford
Agency in Virginia Beach. Billings were estimated at $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came after a two-month review that included
Burford, Grey and the Fairfax, Va., office of Arnold
Communications, a unit of Snyder Communications. Grey is the media
buying agency of record for Cendant and also handles advertising
for the company's Super 8 motel chain.
</P>
<P>
   And National Discount Brokers in New York named
Hampel/Stefanides in New York to handle its account, with billings
estimated at $7 million. The account had been handled for the last
year by Earle Palmer Brown in Bethesda, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Rezak, vice president for marketing at National Discount
Brokers in New York, part of National Discount Brokers Group, said
the decision came after a two-month review that included
Hampel/Stefanides and three other finalists: DiNoto Lee in New
York, Partners &AMP; Simons in Boston and Stein Rogan &AMP; Partners in New
York.  &QL; 
Two Executives On the Move
</P>
<P>
   Two executives, one who headed an agency and the other a
magazine, have announced their departures.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Cronin, 52, chief executive at Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi &UR;  &LR; Business
Communications in Rochester, is leaving there after 11 years. He
will serve as a consultant to the agency. Ann Hayden, 39, vice
chairwoman and chief creative officer at the agency, was named to
succeed him. Ms. Hayden will work with Tom Carroll, chief operating
officer, and retain her creative tasks.
</P>
<P>
   And Jeffrey Cunningham, publisher of Forbes magazine since 1993,
is leaving to open his own multimedia company that will start and
acquire media businesses. Forbes Inc. in New York, parent of the
magazine, is expected to become a minority partner in the new
company.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Karlgaard, 43, editor of Forbes ASAP, a technology
magazine, was named to succeed Cunningham at Forbes, effective July
1. Karlgaard will be based in Burlingame, Calif., and will also
write a column in addition to serving as publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, 45, has also been group publisher of several Forbes
Inc. magazines, including Forbes ASAP, Forbes FYI and American
Heritage. That title will be eliminated.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
People
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Melekson, &UR;  &LR; advertising director at Interview magazine,
New York, part of Brant Publications, was promoted to the new
position of associate publisher. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
