<HEADLINE>
COMPANY NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH TO BEGIN OFFERING TV SERVICE TO ATLANTA
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth Corp. plans to announce Thursday that it has begun to
offer television service to Atlanta residents using digital
wireless technology. The company says it will offer the service,
which includes more than 160 channels, to more than 700,000
households in the Atlanta area.
</P>
<P>
   The service's introduction there is expected to be good news for
Americast, a television venture of BellSouth, Ameritech, GTE,
Southern New England Telecommunications and Walt Disney. Americast
is locked in a legal battle with SBC Communications Inc., which has
withdrawn from the group, over whether SBC owes the venture more
money. The service began in New Orleans last fall, and BellSouth
plans to expand it to cover more than two million homes in Florida
by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   Guardian Life Insurance Company of America, New York, a mutual
insurer, said its subsidiary, Park Avenue Life Insurance Co., had
bought Family Service Life Insurance Co. and Sentinel American Life
Insurance Co. from Torchmark Corp. for $134 million.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   Colonial Properties Trust, Birmingham, Ala., a real estate
investment trust, has acquired Orlando Fashion Square, a regional
mall in Orlando, Fla., for $104 million. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
