<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-REPUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI AND D'AMATO STAR AS REPUBLICANS MEET
</HEADLINE>
   (dc) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Flush with money, politically dominant and free of
outward signs of ideological turmoil, state Republicans began
gathering here Wednesday night determined to transform their
two-day nominating convention into the equivalent of a 48-hour
campaign advertisement for Gov. George Pataki and Sen. Alfonse
D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican convention stands in testimony to how the party's
fortunes have changed. Four years ago, the gathering was seized
with turmoil as party leaders, bowing to pressure from D'Amato,
narrowly nominated Pataki, a little-known state senator from
Peekskill, to challenge Mario Cuomo. Pataki's victory and
subsequent rise in the polls affirmed D'Amato's judgment and
largely accounts for the party's standing as its members began
checking in at the Sheraton New York Hotel and Towers for two days
of tightly scripted proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got their stuff tight,'' said Bill Lynch, a senior
Democratic strategist who managed campaigns for former Mayor David
Dinkins in New York. ``I wish the Democrats had their act together
like the Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in the Democratic Party, there will almost certainly be
no primaries for the Republican nomination to run for any statewide
office.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, D'Amato and William Powers, the state Republican
chairman, took care of that in one last conference call on Tuesday
in which they chose a candidate for state comptroller, a county
legislator from Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the efficiency that Republicans are promising this
week does not necessarily speak to the health of their candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In another contrast between now and 1994, there has been a
political role reversal between Pataki and D'Amato. It is Pataki
this time who is the confident political figure in the Republican
Party, and it is he, rather than D'Amato, who seems more certain of
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with D'Amato and Pataki suggested how much their
places had shifted. The three-term senator left no doubt that he
was looking to Pataki to help him survive what could be a difficult
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's going to help the ticket _ and help me,'' D'Amato
said. ``A strong run on his part can't do anything but help.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato linked himself to Pataki at every turn in the interview.
``I'm hoping that we're going to have an opportunity to really
reflect on the accomplishments of the governor, of the
administration, in the past four years,'' he said. ``We have worked
successfully as a team. We have been delivering. When people say we
couldn't do it, we continued to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Pataki mentioned D'Amato only when prompted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not coordinating; we don't have to,'' Pataki said.
``The state and the federal issues are different, but the
principles are the same. I'm fighting for New York and they're
fighting for New York. Our tough approach to crime, our commitment
to expanding our tax burden are being effectively advanced here and
in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Pataki and D'Amato, the party is expected
formally to nominate Mary Donohue, 51, who is a State Supreme Court
justice in Rensselaer, as lieutenant governor; Dennis Vacco to seek
a second term as attorney general, and Bruce Blakeman, the
presiding officer of the Nassau County Legislature, to run for
state comptroller.
</P>
<P>
   The convention comes in the midst of what has been a coordinated
effort by Pataki to try to win as much publicity for his campaign
as possible. He announced his choice of a running mate last week
and his own candidacy on Sunday. And he began this week with a
heavy schedule of television advertising, just less than $1.5
million worth, that will last a little more than a week.
</P>
<P>
   The choreography notwithstanding, the convention could have at
least a few interesting moments. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, a
Republican who last time endorsed Cuomo against Pataki, will be a
somewhat regular figure at this one. Both Giuliani and Pataki were
invited to a private dinner put on Wednesday night by State Sen.
Roy M. Goodman, the Manhattan Republican chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dinner party will clearly be a love-in: the mayor and the
governor,'' Goodman said optimistically in an interview before any
bread was broken. ``Each knows the other will be there and they
accepted. That's an indication of their unity of purpose. No mud
pies here.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Giuliani and Pataki never crossed paths.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
