<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3114 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-belmont-HNS &LR;      06-03 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-belmont-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Skeptics of Real Quiet not slowing down
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ALAN TRUEX &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ When Real Quiet won the Kentucky Derby, he was
faulted for being laggardly. His meager half-length triumph was
attributed to a ``perfect trip'' from jockey Kent Desormeaux on the
second-best horse in a third-rate field.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet answered those charges with a 2\-length breakaway
victory in the Preakness Stakes. So now, the experts are saying he
was too fast for his own good, that he ran the race of his life and
can't have enough left to win Saturday's Belmont Stakes and claim
the first Triple Crown in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of confidence in Real Quiet is reflected by the size of
the Belmont field, which is expected to be 11 or 12 when it's
finalized this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, a horse gunning for a Triple Crown finds challengers
scarce at Belmont Park. The 11 Triple Crown winners all faced fewer
than eight horses in the final leg of the series. Last year, Silver
Charm encountered only six but finished behind one of them, Touch
Gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, they're throwing more shooters at me,'' said Bob
Baffert, who trains both Silver Charm and Real Quiet.
</P>
<P>
   But the numbers do not worry him. ``I think Real Quiet and
Victory Gallop are the two,'' he said. ``There's not a lot
separating them.''
</P>
<P>
   Victory Gallop, owned by Jack, J.R. and Art Preston of The
Woodlands, was second in both the Derby and Preakness, but trainer
Elliott Walden isn't resigned to being a bridesmaid again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be pie in the sky,'' Walden said Wednesday, ``but I
think the tables can be turned.''
</P>
<P>
   The connections for three other horses also are hoping for
improvement off the Preakness. Classic Cat, Hot Wells and Basic
Trainee ran third, fourth and eighth, respectively, in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of horses ran in the middle of the Derby pack and
bypassed the Preakness but are committed to the Belmont: Parade
Ground, co-owned by Houstonian Will Farish, and Hanuman Highway,
who lost by a head to Victory Gallop in the Arkansas Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Also probable are four newcomers to the series: Limit Out,
Yarrow Brae, New York-bred Raffie's Majesty and Texas-bred Thomas
Jo.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Slam, the second-ranked 2-year-old of 1997, is uncommitted
but may be in the pool when post positions are drawn this morning.
He won the recent Grade II Peter Pan Stakes, signaling recovery
from surgery on his left hind leg. But trainer D. Wayne Lukas isn't
sure he's ready for a mile and a half.
</P>
<P>
   One reason Real Quiet is considered vulnerable is that after an
exceptionally strong race, a horse is supposed to ``bounce,'' which
in racing parlance is a temporary decline in performance.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Brown, creator of the Thoro-Graph Sheets that are widely
utilized by horsemen on the East Coast, said that when he factors
in the difficulty of Real Quiet's wide run from the outside (10th)
post, ``I make it one of the fastest if not the fastest Preakness
since 1982.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Derby, the Thoro-Graph's best score actually went to
Victory Gallop, who came from the unfavorable No. 13 post, while
Real Quiet started from the third slot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we should have won the Derby,'' Walden said. ``We
had a much harder, wider trip than Real Quiet. The public saw what
we saw, so they made Victory Gallop the favorite in the Preakness.
But he flat-out beat us, pure and simple. We were disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   He became more disappointed _ and ``apprehensive'' _ when
Victory Gallop subsequently developed a severe skin rash. But now,
the son of Cryptoclearance, runner-up in the 1987 Belmont, is back
to full health.
</P>
<P>
   It's Walden who is under par, his left leg in a cast (red and
green, to match Prestonwood Farm's colors) because of a broken
ankle suffered in a pickup basketball game.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he is in good spirits, happy with his colt's brisk
59-second, five-furlong work Sunday and his easy 1{-mile gallop
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Walden, who is only 35 but ranks ninth nationally in earnings
this year, said, ``This horse has turned the corner in the past few
days. He has a very big chance to win the Belmont.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said Victory Gallop ``has as good a shot as Real Quiet,
which means he'll be the right bet because he'll be longer odds.
Real Quiet goes into the Belmont with the same problem Victory
Gallop faced in the Preakness. He's coming off his fastest race
ever.''
</P>
<P>
   And that may not be a good thing for him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
