<HEADLINE>
JUDGE BLOCKS LAW BANNING SEX LITERATURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ja)  
 By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ A federal judge has temporarily blocked a
wide-ranging law in New Jersey that bans sexually explicit
literature and other material from the state prison housing chronic
sex offenders.
</P>
<P>
   Two inmates serving long terms for sexual assault had filed a
lawsuit earlier this year contending that the law violated their
First Amendment rights. In response to their suit, Judge Alfred
Wolin of Federal District Court here issued an order on Monday
preventing the law from taking effect at the Adult Diagnostic and
Treatment Center in Avenel, N.J. The prison is reserved for inmates
judges have classified as ``repetitive and compulsive'' sex
offenders. Wolin also ordered a hearing on the constitutional
issues on June 16.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Lustberg, a court-appointed lawyer for the two inmates,
said Wednesday that he was prepared to argue that the law was a
form of censorship that was unjustified unless the state could show
that the ban dealt with security concerns at the prison or another
operational issue.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman signed the law in January after both
houses of the state Legislature unanimously passed it. The
legislation grew out of a state task force's visit to the prison in
1995. The group was studying repeat offense rates among child
molesters and analyzing the effectiveness of Avenel's treatment.
During the tour, some members of the task force said they were
startled to see pinup pictures of naked women and copies of
sexually explicit magazines in some cells.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Avenel officials told task force members that some
sexually explicit materials other than child pornography and
material considered legally obscene had rehabilitative benefits for
some inmates, Lustberg said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But a task force member and sponsor of the law, Assemblywoman
Marion Crecco, R-Bloomfield, said she doubted that the material was
worthwhile. ``It's almost like giving drugs to drug addicts,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The law forbids inmates to receive, possess, distribute or
display publications, pictures or films containing ``sexually
oriented'' material. It defines sexually oriented as ``any
description, narrative account, display or depiction of sexual
activity or associated anatomical areas.''
</P>
<P>
   In a May 21 decision that let the inmates' suit proceed, another
federal district Court judge here, Joel Pisano, called the law
``arguably overbroad.'' He said New Jersey's ``sweepingly broad''
ban did not address any penological interests that would justify
the law's restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was written by Richard Waterman, a 41-year-old
paralegal in Avenel's law library who is serving a 54-year term for
first-degree sexual assault, and Michael Curtis, 56, who is serving
a 20-year term for second-degree sexual assault. Curtis works in
the prison's store for inmates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 2241EDT &QL; 
