<SLUG> BC-NY-ENTERPRISE-ZONES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENTERPRISE ZONES NAMED 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Brooklyn Navy Yard was among 12 sites in New York
designated Wednesday by Gov. George Pataki as enterprise zones.
</P>
<P>
   The new zones were for areas of the state that had lost jobs
because of military and defense cutbacks. Previously, the zones
were designated simply because the areas were economically
depressed.
</P>
<P>
   Enterprise zones provide incentives to businesses such as wage
tax credits, employee tax credits, capital investment tax credits,
sales and local tax relief as well as low-cost power agreements
with utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, there are almost 100,000 New Yorkers employed at more
than 2,000 businesses in the state's enterprise zones, which have
attracted more than $2.7 billion in investment since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The other zones designated Wednesday are in Clinton, Seneca,
Oneida, Herkimer, Albany, Orange, Suffolk, Broome, Montgomery,
Tioga, Onondaga and Chautauqua counties. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
