<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PEGRAM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL QUIET'S OWNER LAID BACK ON THE TRACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ Last year, when Silver Charm raced for the Triple
Crown, owners Bob and Beverly Lewis of Newport Beach rented a jumbo
jet and flew more than 100 friends and business associates to New
York to watch the Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   This week, with Real Quiet chasing the history that eluded
Silver Charm, owner Mike Pegram of Mount Vernon, Wash., thought
about emulating the Lewises and throwing a Belmont-bound party at
36,000 feet. He decided that would be impractical.
</P>
<P>
   The problem wasn't the cost; for Pegram, money is rarely an
object in the way of a good time. The problem was that Pegram has
too many friends in too many places.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming the plane took off from Los Angeles, ``it would have
had to make stops in Seattle and Phoenix and Mike's hometown in
Indiana and Louisiana to pick up Kent's family,'' said Brian Beach,
a Pegram friend who used to be jockey Kent Desormeaux's agent.
</P>
<P>
   Pegram settled for flying 24 people here on a pair of business
jets. But he said almost 200 other friends and relatives will get
to Belmont on their own Saturday to cheer Real Quiet's bid for the
first Triple Crown sweep in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still friends with people he was friends with 30 years
ago,'' said Brad McKinzie, a Los Alamitos Race Course executive who
has known Pegram for a decade. ``I don't think he's ever lost a
friend.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pegram, a 46-year-old grandfather who dropped out of
business school and made his money owning 22 McDonald's franchises
in Washington state, seems to have offended the thoroughbred-racing
bluebloods with his fun-loving good ol' boy demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   He hates to wear a tie. He toasts victories with beer instead of
champagne or Crown Royal. He tests the Jockey Club censors by
giving horses suggestive names like Isitingood and Loveontherail,
the latter referring to the legend of how he and a girlfriend
celebrated Pegram's first major win, Thirty Slews' upset in the
1991 Breeders' Cup Sprint in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   A critic in a New York newspaper described him as ``straight off
the set of Hee Haw.'' The writer might be the only person to meet
Pegram and not like him.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, before the six-week Del Mar season, Pegram bought a
condo overlooking the racetrack, a home that belonged to former San
Diego Padres second baseman Roberto Alomar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `When's the housewarming party?''' Beech said. ``He
said, `Buddy, it starts now and ends Sept. 10.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's how it was. He'd have a barbecue just about every
night, and people would show up who he didn't even know. By the end
of the night, everybody swapping stories, they'd be friends.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, you might see Pegram and a new friend holding
either end of an ice chest, lugging beer into the Del Mar infield.
</P>
<P>
   That casual style got him barred from a Florida saddling paddock
_ for wearing short pants on a 90-degree day. That casual style
ruffled Churchill Downs officials on Kentucky Derby day _ when
Pegram held up the winner's circle ceremony so all 50 of the
Friends of Mike in attendance could crowd into the photo.
</P>
<P>
   Pegram grew up around little Ellis Park in Kentucky, got into
ownership as a partner in his father's cheap horses, and had his
first success when he teamed up with trainer Bob Baffert in the
quarter-horse game in the mid-1980s. If there's anything calculated
about Pegram, it's his determination not to forget his small-time
start.
</P>
<P>
   The beer-drinking, hamburger guy takes on the Sport of Kings.
Pegram likes that image.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a horse fan who ended up owning horses, so my roots have
always come from the racing fan,'' he said the other day. ``And I
think that's one thing in this sport that we have to understand,
that if it wasn't for the fans, there wouldn't be any breeders and
owners because there wouldn't be a product.''
</P>
<P>
   Pegram's ``new money'' makes him more typical of thoroughbred
owners in the '90s _ especially in California _ than the Phippses,
Whitneys and Vanderbilts who dominated the sport in its fatter
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people like to go to five-star restaurants for lunch. I
prefer to go to McDonald's,'' Pegram said. ``It's the same at the
racetrack. I'm comfortable being casually dressed. I go where my
friends are, and most of them are horseplayers who hang out at the
rail more than the turf club. I didn't grow up in that
(coats-and-ties) tradition. I grew up in the stands and that's
where I want to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   His brother, Jim, a jockey agent in California, thinks the ``Hee
Haw'' accent is partly a put-on, Mike's way of suckering business
rivals. And Pegram has done very well in business, well enough to
keep 20 racehorses in training with Baffert, at an estimated cost
of $25,000 a year _ each.
</P>
<P>
   But he and Baffert have done well with cheaply bought horses.
Only one of Pegram's thoroughbred stakes winners cost more than
$100,000. He got Real Quiet at an auction for $17,000.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, he got a Derby winner, a potential Triple Crown
winner, for the price of a car. Who wouldn't want to have beers
with a guy like that?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 2243EDT &QL; 
