u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DEATHPENALTY-TRIAL     06-03 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DEATH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY DELIBERATES DEATH SENTENCE FOR EX-JAIL GUARD
</HEADLINE>
 PENALTY-TRIAL-NYT  (dc) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After a prosecutor urged a death sentence for a
``malignant'' triple killer and a defense lawyer appealed for
``justice tempered by mercy,'' a Brooklyn jury began deliberating
Wednesday whether to sentence a former jail guard to execution for
murdering three people during a robbery.
</P>
<P>
   In the first death penalty trial under New York state's
three-year-old capital punishment law, the same jury that on May 19
found Darrel Harris guilty of first-degree murder heard portrayals
of the convicted man that contrasted as sharply as did the
intensely voiced recommendations on a just penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The jury may sentence Harris to death by lethal injection or to
life in prison without the possibility of parole.
</P>
<P>
   After three hours of deliberation, the seven women and five men
on the jury recessed Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the mechanical, methodical execution of people,'' the
prosecutor, Jonathan Frank, said as he recalled how Harris _ the
former jail guard who the city had honored for saving another guard
during an inmate riot in the 1980s _ shot two victims in the head
execution-style and fatally stabbed the third in an illegal social
club in Bedford-Stuyvesant, Brooklyn, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Insisting that Harris, 40, had shown no genuine remorse for the
``searing, uncompromising cruelty'' with which he had
``slaughtered'' his victims while carrying out a robbery, Frank, an
assistant district attorney in Brooklyn, told the jurors: ``This
defendant has forfeited by his actions the right to his life. He
committed the type of crime for which the death penalty was
enacted.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in soft tones that seemed to enhance his graphic
images, the prosecutor urged the jurors to close their eyes and try
to imagine being the person who could plunge a knife into one of
his victims after seeing the ``terror in her eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   But shortly afterward, a lawyer for Harris, Colleen Brady,
repeatedly sought to convince the jurors that her client, although
he had committed ``horrible'' murders for which ``there is no
excuse, no justification,'' was not ``the worst of the worst'' and
not ``beyond redemption,'' and should be allowed to spend the rest
of his life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the whole person,'' Ms. Brady said to the jurors, who
listened intently as she insisted that Harris was ``remorseful for
the pain and suffering he caused.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brady, who is with the Legal Aid Society's capital defense
unit, offered a picture of a man who not only lacked a criminal
record before this case but who in the past had shown ``there's
some value in him, some good in him,'' by saving a fellow
corrections officer who was being severely beaten by rioting
inmates _ an action for which Mayor Edward Koch awarded Harris a
medal in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brady contended that serious psychological problems,
stemming in part from the trauma of that jail violence, as well as
cocaine and alcohol abuse, had caused her client to plunge from
hero to triple killer.
</P>
<P>
   She argued that those mitigating factors had fueled the rampage
in which he killed Michael Harris, who was not related to the
former jail guard, Jerome Sims and Evelyn Davis _ and in which he
attempted to kill Eddie Brown, who survived a gunshot to the head.
</P>
<P>
   As Harris, his relatives and relatives of the victims listened
closely in the packed courtroom gallery, Ms. Brady stressed that
her client was not a mass murderer like Timothy McVeigh, who has
been sentenced to die for killing 168 people in the Oklahoma City
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reject the call for blood,'' she declared to her client's
jury, holding that life in prison would give him ``time to look
inside and repent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
