<HEADLINE>
ROUKEMA EARNS SLIM VICTORY IN PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rep. Marge Roukema, a moderate Republican and veteran lawmaker,
survived a challenge from the party's conservative wing in primary
voting on Tuesday to win the nomination to run for a 10th term in
her northern New Jersey congressional district.
</P>
<P>
   It was a narrow victory for such an established lawmaker. She
got just 52 percent of the vote against Scott Garrett, who had the
support of abortion opponents and gun lobbyists. The narrow victory
prompted her to say: ``It proves how we have to pull together if we
want to remain the majority party. We have to find consensus
between the different wings of our party.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Roukema's Democratic challenger will be Mike Schneider, a
former television news anchor.
</P>
<P>
   In other primary voting in the state, Rush Holt, 49, a former
official of the Princeton Plasma Physics Laboratory, defeated Carl
Mayer, a wealthy Princeton attorney, to win the Democratic
nomination in the 12th Congressional District in central New
Jersey. Mayer had spent $453,000 on the campaign, much of it his
own money, and Holt spent $69,000.
</P>
<P>
   Holt, who had the endorsement of party leaders, will now face a
conservative one-term incumbent, Rep. Michael Pappas, in November.
Democrats have identified the race as a close one that may help
them win back the majority in the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other contested congressional races involving an
incumbent, Rep. Donald Payne, an Essex County Democrat, was an easy
winner with 91 percent of the vote in the 10th Congressional
District.
</P>
<P>
   In the Fourth Congressional District, Larry Schneider won the
Democratic nomination to face Rep. Christopher Smith, a nine-term
incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   In the 11th Congressional District, John Scollo won the
Democratic nomination to face Rep. Rodney Freylinghuysen, a
Republican.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
