<HEADLINE>
PROPOSALS FOR NEW ARENA MAY BE SOLICITED 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ Responding to the discontent expressed by the New
Jersey Nets and Devils sports franchises over their aging arena,
officials of the New Jersey Sports and Exposition Authority have
taken a first step toward possibly building a new basketball and
hockey arena in the Meadowlands, a spokesman for the authority said
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Authority officials have drafted, though not sent, a formal
request for proposals from stadium developers. The authority would
not offer details of what it would ask the developers to design,
but its spokesman, John Samerjan, said the agency had been looking
at the possibility of renovating or replacing the Continental
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The authority will not send the request for proposals to
developers until it has at least the tacit approval of the sports
teams and Gov. Christine Todd Whitman, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, both teams have suggested that they might
leave the Meadowlands. The Devils' owner, John McMullen, has
proposed building a $175 million hockey arena over the train
station in Hoboken. Nets officials, meanwhile, have privately
suggested that the team could move to Newark or back to Long
Island, New York, where it played in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Rubenstein, a spokesman for the Nets, said the team had
not yet been informed of the full contents of the draft proposal
request. ``They are awaiting details of this proposal,'' he said.
``They haven't received the detailed plan and until then they'll
have no comment.'' McMullen, the owner of the Devils, was away from
his office and could not be reached by telephone for comment.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Nets' lease at the Continental Arena expires in 2020,
although there are clauses allowing renegotiations in 2000 and
2004. The Devils, who threatened to move to Nashville in 1995 after
winning the Stanley Cup, received a new lease deal that year that
runs through 2007. Both teams have expressed a desire for an
increased number of luxury boxes and other amenities.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Robinson, the authority's president, told The Star-Ledger
of Newark that the agency was prepared to send out the requests
``in the near future.'' The newspaper first reported the draft
proposal on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Samerjan and other officials emphasized that simply asking for
ideas from developers was not an indication that state officials
were committed to the construction of a new arena. He said
officials would need to see initial design ideas from developers
before considering exactly where in the Meadowlands a new arena
would be located and how it would be paid for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since December 1997 the authority has talked about the fact
that in '98 it was entirely likely that we would be going through a
formal request for proposal process to investigate the future of
the arena,'' Samerjan said. ``We are still in the process of
preparing that process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
