<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA CHANGES TO DAYLIGHT EXECUTION
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSIE STECKNER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After 25 years and 17 deaths, Douglas Gretzler said he was
sorry, told friends and family they were loved and gave thanks for
life's lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, he was put to death.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzler, 47, had been on Arizo na's death row longer than
anyone else and was the first person put to death during the
daylight hours.
</P>
<P>
   He was given two death sentences for the murders of a Tucson
couple in November, 1973 but confessed to killing 17 - nine at one
time, including two children - during a month-long rampage in
Arizona and California with partner Willie Steel man.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after 3 p.m. Wednesday, strapped to a gurney in the
state's small death house, Gretzler chose to make amends.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the bottom of my soul I am so deeply sorry and have been
for years for murdering Patricia and Michael Sandberg,'' he said,
his voice barely audible. ``Though I am being executed for that
crime, I apologize to all 17 victims and their families.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, he looked squarely at the three people standing closest to
him - two friends and a sister. His final words were to them and
his two daughters, who were not in the room.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzler became emotional as he told them he loved them in Roma
nian, saying, ``Yo teh you besk very much.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you for life lessons learned'', he added.
</P>
<P>
   His supporters held each other and wept quietly.
</P>
<P>
   With that, Gretzler mouthed the words ``I love you'' and then
``Bye'' twice.
</P>
<P>
   He appeared to move his hand slightly, as if signaling goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   Then, staring up at the ceiling, his chest heaved several times,
his lip fluttered, and he was pronounced dead three minutes later,
at 3:11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The family members of three of Gretzler's victims were in the
wit ness room during the execution.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Parkin lost his brother Walter, sister-in-law, niece and
nephew.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, he said in a statement, ``Hopefully this will bring
some closure to a very sad chapter in our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Earl, who lost his uncle, aunt, and two cousins, said he
once visited Gretzler in prison and for gave him long ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't forgotten what hap pened that November. I never
will,''he said. ``I hope that Douglas Gretzler's found his peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzler's partner, Steelman, died in prison - losing his life
to liver disease instead of to the executioner.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, Gretzler was kept alive in part because of
legal battles over his mental health at the time of the crime
spree.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzler claimed in court docu ments that he suffered
schizophrenia and a drug addiction. That latter, he said, left him
in a drug-induced psychosis and therefore temporarily insane when
the killings occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzler and Steelman confessed to killing 17 people in Arizona
and California. They received nine life sentences, two death
sentences and were never convicted for the other murders.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the pair merely robbed their victims. But then, they
began killing to eliminate witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Two men in Mesa. A hitchhiker they robbed near Apache Junction.
Another couple, who had seen them with the Mesa men. A hitchhiker
near Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   Victims seven and eight were Michael and Patricia Sandberg, who
were tied up inside their Tucson apartment, held hostage and then
shot to death.
</P>
<P>
   Their last stop was the small farming town of Victor, Calif.,
the home of grocer Walter Parkin and his wife, Joanne.
</P>
<P>
   After stealing $4,000 from Walter Parkin, the killers lined up
seven victims in a walk-in closet.
</P>
<P>
   They tied them together at the feet and bound their hands.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzler shot each one in the back of the head, then shot the
two Parkin children, Robert, 9, and Lisa, 11.
</P>
<P>
   Killed are the Parkin family and their babysitter Debra Jean
Earl; her parents Richard and Wanda; her brother, Richard Jr., and
her fiance, Mark Lang.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzler spent his last days visit ing with famly and friends,
and eating a last meal of eggs, bacon, toast, coffee and soda pop.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzler was the 12th inmate executed in Arizona since the death
penalty was reinstated in 1992. He was the fourth to die this year.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, prison and court officials discussed the
possibility of holding an execution during the day. They said the
usual midnight hour was often inconvenient for attorneys arguing
cases, and judges ruling on them, particularly those in the East
Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzler wasn't the first to die during the day. In 1995, inmate
Jimmy Wayne Jeffers was to be executed just after midnight but
last-minute appeals kept him alive until about 6 p.m. that day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
