<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PAROLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SHIFT, TOP DEMOCRAT SEEKS TO TIGHTEN PAROLE 
 
</HEADLINE>
  (dc) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Giving in to one of Gov. George Pataki's top
election-year priorities, Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver said
Wednesday that he would agree to end parole for all violent felons,
reversing a position he had held all year and reiterated just a few
days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Silver, D-Manhattan, tied the change to a major expansion of
drug treatment programs as an alternative to prison for nonviolent
criminals, as well as mandatory schooling for inmates and increased
supervision of former inmates after release.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear whether Pataki, a Republican, and the
Republicans who control the State Senate, will accept the
conditions outlined in Silver's bill, which he introduced
Wednesday. Three years ago, the governor eliminated just the kind
of educational programs Silver now wants to make mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick McCarthy, a spokesman for Pataki, accused Silver of
using ``political gimmickry to link several issues that should be
examined separately.'' But he added that he could not rule out
accepting the conditions because the governor had not seen the
Silver bill.
</P>
<P>
   Silver said he expected his legislation to be approved next
week, when he plans to bring it before the Democratic-controlled
Assembly. It includes a provision requiring that all people who are
arrested, no matter how minor the charge, be held until their
fingerprints can be checked through a state computer to determine
whether they are wanted for any crimes.
</P>
<P>
   That proposal came in response to the killing last week of a New
York City police officer, Anthony Mosomillo, by a man whom the
police had arrested but then released before it was determined that
he was wanted for a parole violation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, state lawmakers abolished parole for repeat violent
felons, but this year, Pataki has stepped up his call to eliminate
it for first-time violent offenders as well. He made the issue a
centerpiece of his State of the State address in January and named
his bill ``Jenna's Law,'' after a young woman, Jenna Grieshaber,
who was killed last year; the man charged with the crime had been
paroled.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Grieshaber's parents, Bruce and Janice, stood by Silver's
side on Wednesday, as they have stood alongside the governor at
news conferences. They called Silver's proposal a reasonable
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear that Silver was making a grudging concession to
political pressure. As recently as last week, he proposed leaving
it up to a judge to determine whether to deny parole at the time of
sentencing. But public opinion surveys show that the measure is
popular.
</P>
<P>
   Silver admitted that he had changed his plan in response to the
demands of other Assembly Democrats. ``I think the governor should
be very comfortable with the comprehensive bill we are putting
forward today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   John McArdle, a spokesman for the Senate Republicans, said,
``We're saying, pass Jenna's Law, and then we can discuss other
issues of criminal justice reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Doing away with parole would mean more time in prison for many
criminals, swelling even more a prison population that has tripled
to almost 70,000 since 1982. Silver said his plan would address
that problem by diverting thousands of nonviolent felons each year
into drug and alcohol treatment programs. He would allow criminals
with substance-abuse problems to be sentenced to at least one year
in a residential drug treatment center instead of prison.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker conceded that the change would require a vast
expansion of the state's drug treatment system, but he contended
that treatment is cheaper than imprisonment. His plan would also
require the hiring of more parole officers, and teachers for
prisons.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, most first-time felons receive
``indeterminate sentences,'' or a range of possible time in prison
_ for example, 1 to 3 years, or 5 to 15 years. The low end of the
sentence is always one-third of the maximum, and after a prisoner
has served the minimum time, he becomes eligible for parole. With
good behavior, parole is automatic after two-thirds of a sentence
has been served. Parole supervision ends when the maximum term
expires.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's proposal would not completely do away with parole, but
rather eliminate indeterminate sentencing in cases of violent
crimes. A judge would give a convicted violent felon a fixed
sentence, not a range, and discretionary parole would be
eliminated. Automatic parole with good behavior would come only
after 85 percent of the sentence had been served.
</P>
<P>
   Silver's parole plan is substantially the same as the
governor's, except that it would include 1 to 5 years of continued
supervision after a prisoner's maximum sentence has expired.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
