<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PIRATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIRATES BEAT METS, 3-0, FOR SWEEP 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ The initial impact of having Mike Piazza in the
Mets' lineup has apparently worn off.
</P>
<P>
   After a week of pounding out hits, the Mets were stifled
Wednesday night by a pitcher who carried a 2-7 record into the
game. The Pittsburgh right-hander Jon Lieber shut the Mets down on
four hits over eight shutout innings on his way to a 3-0 victory
that gave the Pirates a three-game sweep of the series at Three
Rivers Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Lieber, an 11-game winner last season, outdueled an extremely
unlucky Rick Reed (6-3), who saw his five-game winning streak end
in losing for the first time since April 21. Of his 64 pitches over
six innings, Reed, who allowed only two hits, made only one
mistake. It came on his first pitch of the game. And, as it turned
out, it cost him dearly.
</P>
<P>
   With an inside-out swing, Jermaine Allensworth rapped that first
pitch over first base and hustled to third with a triple when Butch
Huskey slipped near the right-field line trying to field the ball
on the wet outfield turf. Al Martin followed with a run-scoring nub
of a groundout up the first-base line.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, who struck out five and walked none in lowering his earned
run average to 2.37, was pretty much unhittable from then on. But
Lieber had the only run he would need.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Aramis Ramirez gave him two more with his first major
league hit. The 19-year-old Dominican rookie's bases-loaded two-run
double to left field off Greg McMichael in the seventh snapped an
0-for-24 skid and brought a well-deserved standing ovation from the
crowd of 17,691.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most special moment I've had in baseball,''
Ramirez said.
</P>
<P>
   These new Mets looked an awful lot like the old Mets in the last
three days. After punishing opposing pitching for 100 hits and 54
runs in Piazza's first seven games with the team, the Mets (31-23)
collected only 17 hits and five runs at Pittsburgh. And for the
first time as a Met, Piazza, who went 0 for 4, did not have a hit
in a game.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't as if the Mets did not have any chances in a game
played in only 2 hours 10 minutes. They stranded Carlos Baerga at
second with one out in the second and Huskey at third with two out
in the seventh; they left a runner on base in every inning
in-between.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving Huskey at third really hurt them. After Huskey singled
to right to open the Mets' seventh in what was still a 1-0 game, he
moved to third on Rey Ordonez's one-out line out to right. Manager
Bobby Valentine, sensing a rare chance against Lieber, summoned
Matt Franco to bat for Reed. Franco popped to third on the first
pitch to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   When Reed departed, he had only faced one batter over the
minimum 18. He has given up two runs or less in each of his last
seven starts and in nine of his 11 starts this season.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   According to a person familiar with a situation involving both
Dodgers general manager Fred Claire and Hideo Nomo's agent, Don
Nomura, the Dodgers have had serious discussions with three or four
teams regarding a possible trade of Nomo. The Baltimore Orioles are
apparently one of them. The Mets, who contacted Claire on Tuesday,
may be another. Nomo apparently would like to join the Mets, where
he would be reunited with his best friend, Masato Yoshii; his
former catcher, Mike Piazza, and his former pitching coach, Dave
Wallace. Manager Bobby Valentine said Wednesday that he would not
comment on whether he wanted Nomo on his staff or whether he had
spoken to Nomura since Nomo was designated for assignment on
Monday. Yoshii, meanwhile, left a message for Nomo on Monday in
which he said, ```Call me if anything's up.''' But Yoshii said he
had yet to hear back ... Valentine shuffled his rotation after
Yoshii's outing on Tuesday night was cut short after 24 pitches
because of a severe thunderstorm. He announced that Yoshii would
pitch the Sunday night game against the Boston Red Sox at Fenway
Park. Dave Mlicki (1-4), who was scheduled to pitch on Sunday, will
face the Tampa Bay Devil Rays next Tuesday, instead. The slumping
Mlicki said: ``Either way, it's fine. I kind of knew I was going to
get pushed back.'' ... The Pittsburgh Steelers held a mini-camp
before Wednesday night's game, and a number of Mets, including the
reliever Turk Wendell, participated in punting drills ... Brian
Mcrae was given a rest from the starting lineup because of a tight
right hamstring ... Right-hander Jason Isringhausen (elbow surgery)
has returned to Florida from his Illinois home to begin
rehabilitation.
</P>
</TEXT>
