<SLUG> BC-FBC-PAC10-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAC-10 CONSIDERS ADDING CONFERENCE GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The agenda for this week's Pacific-10 Conference gathering in
Newport Beach is littered by all things mundane and routine, except
for one nugget: altering the football schedules to include nine
conference games, up from the current eight.
</P>
<P>
   The change would limit teams to two non-conference games per
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's on the agenda, and conceivably it could come to a vote
this week,'' assistant commissioner Jim Muldoon said.
</P>
<P>
   Altering the football schedule is a constitutional issue and
would require eight ``yes'' votes. If passed, it would not become
effective for at least five years, as the current schedule runs its
course.
</P>
<P>
   In preliminary discussions, Washington and USC have opposed the
change. (Because of their annual series with Notre Dame, the
Trojans essentially have nine conference games already.)
</P>
<P>
   Under the current formula, each Pac-10 team misses another on a
rotating two-year basis. The exceptions are the natural rivalries
and the four California schools, which play each other every year.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon athletic director Bill Moos is a proponent of the
nine-game schedule because the Ducks are reluctant (financially and
emotionally) to miss their bitter rival, Washington, in the 2001-02
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Other non-California schools favor the change, as well, since a
nine-game schedule increases their exposure in Los Angeles, the
league's most fertile recruiting ground.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most popular topic this week won't be on the
agenda: expansion.
</P>
<P>
   There are rumblings that Baylor may withdraw from the Big 12,
which would rattle its foundation and possibly free Colorado to
join the Pac-10 _ perhaps as a solo entry, perhaps coupled with
Texas or Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor, the theory goes, realizes it can't compete for a Big 12
football title and believes its best course is to join WAC
leftovers Rice, Texas El-Paso, Southern Methodist and Texas
Christian in a renewed, revised Southwest Conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 2316EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
