<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-STURBIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO TROPHIES, NO HARD FEELINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Just like the U.S. Auto Club, we have redone
the math. And close as we can get it, everyone who exited victory
circle after the inaugural True Value 500K night race at Texas
Motor Speedway last June 7 was presented a winner's trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Well, at least two of the three principals involved in the now
infamous postrace ruckus have in their possession first-place
hardware.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a trophy, yeah. Nice-looking trophy. But it came a
little late,'' said Arie Luyendyk, who was declared the revised
winner of the scoring-botched Indy Racing League event on the
morning after.
</P>
<P>
   ``My trophy is very prominent in my office, right there with the
rest of 'em,'' said A.J. Foyt, who to this day swears that his
driver, Billy Boat, drove the first-place race car on that hot
pre-summer night.
</P>
<P>
   Boat indeed received the checkered flag as winner of a race
scheduled for 312 miles//208 laps around the 1.5-mile trioval. But
convinced by his team's telemetry that he had been shorted two
laps, Luyendyk charged into A.J.'s postrace party, ostensibly
looking for an audience with USAC chief steward Keith Ward.
</P>
<P>
   After taking an earful of Luyendyk's protests, Foyt
unceremoniously slapped him on the side of the face from behind and
shoved him to the ground. It was a scene straight out of a Saturday
night short track, choose your state. And it only got more bizarre
after an official protest was filed by Treadway Racing on
Luyendyk's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   The written protest prompted an all-night audit by USAC
officials, who found that their scoring and timing equipment had
failed. Ward disclosed that after the first 18 laps, the electronic
transmitters that register lap counts were not working on several
cars. Luyendyk's transmitters had failed to count laps after his
first and second pit stops at laps 63 and 115.
</P>
<P>
   The audit also confirmed that when Luyendyk passed Tony Stewart
on lap 190, he moved into the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, USAC said Luyendyk _ originally credited with a
third-place finish _ had completed 210 laps. The revised results
declared Luyendyk the winner, followed by Boat, Davey Hamilton,
Scott Goodyear and Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   With qualifying scheduled tonight for the second annual True
Value 500K, Foyt and Luyendyk are civil toward one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually the Tuesday after (the incident), A.J. called me and
apologized,'' said Luyendyk, who had won his second Indianapolis
500 only a couple of weeks before the nightmare in Fort Worth. ``He
said, `It was so stupid of me to do that,' and his wife told him he
was stupid to do it. But A.J.'s a fierce competitor. He's a
hothead. He does things a lot of times before he really thinks
about 'em. That was the case last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Foyt insisted last week that he bears no grudge against the
Dutchman.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Arie knocked my crew chief's wife down, and he used
language that I've used before,'' said Foyt, the first four-time
winner of the Indy 500. ``We didn't go to victory circle just to go
there. We assumed we had won the race. Billy Boat did a hell of a
job, and you just don't do what Arie Luyendyk did. I wouldn't take
it laying down. That's not A.J.'s nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a big mistake on USAC's part. It caused a lot of
bad press for A.J. Foyt that was really senseless. NASCAR, right or
wrong, never has taken a victory away (after the fact). That was
the biggest thing. That was Billy Boat's first victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Boat, who was making only his second IRL start for Foyt at TMS,
was content to slip into the background as the ill will played out
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still kind of a sore subject. We don't joke about it too
much,'' said Boat, now firmly entrenched as driver of Foyt's No. 11
Conseco Dallara//Aurora. ``I wasn't looking to make the controversy
any worse than it already was. It was time to march on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would (that victory) have changed my career to this point any?
Probably not. But I would have gone down in history as the winner
of this race, vs. the guy that crossed the finish line first and
got paid for second. Our team still feels we won this race. I mean,
it's way too complicated to get into why we think that. But we had
counts of all the laps, and we know what everybody did and
according to our records, we won the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Boat said it is weird, but the controversy actually helped his
visibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an odd way to get known, but it didn't hurt as far as
my name recognition,'' said Boat, who qualified on the pole for the
world's greatest auto race, the Indy 500, last month. ``What do
they say, there's no such thing as bad press. It really put me on
the map. And the type of determination that A.J. showed (last year)
really carries over to his race team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team, including the driver, is very hungry for a win.
We're poised for a win.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why, Boat said, he never has asked Foyt for possession
of the trophy from last year's nightmare in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I win my first race, that's when I'll be looking for the
hardware,'' Boat said. ``When it goes down officially.'' THE BUZZ &QL; 
IRL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Texan Greg Ray has secured sponsorship from AT&AMP;T Wireless
Services for the Pep Boys Indy Racing League's True Value
500-kilometer race at Texas Motor Speedway this weekend. Ray, of
Plano, qualified in the middle of the front row for the 82nd
Indianapolis 500 and led 18 laps on May 24 before being sidelined
by a balky gearbox. But his 18th-place finish convinced AT&AMP;T
Wireless to climb aboard the sidepods of the No. 97 Dallara-Aurora
fielded by Thomas Knapp Motorsports. Ray, incidentally, finished an
IRL career-best eighth during last year's race in Fort Worth. And
he is ``anxious'' to carry the momentum from Indy into his
backyard. ``I'm very anxious. I'm anxious because I felt like we
could have won at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway,'' Ray said.
``I'm looking forward to winning in Fort Worth, before a home
crowd. I feel like my small team has gained a lot of momentum, and
we should be in better position to be a contender in this race. I'm
ready to win a race.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   John Paul Jr. was not among the original list of 34 drivers
entered for the True Value 500K. He is now. On Tuesday, team owner
Jonathan Byrd released Mike Groff as driver of the No. 10 G
Force/Aurora and replaced him with Paul, who drove for the
low-budget Team Pelfrey at Indy and finished seventh. Paul led the
race twice for 39 laps, and only winner Eddie Cheever (76 laps)
paced more circuits around the 2.5-mile Indianapolis Motor
Speedway. Groff, meanwhile, finished 15th at Indy _ 17 laps down.
``It just wasn't working,'' Byrd said of his longtime working
relationship with Groff. ``Sometimes you just have to change the
recipe. I don't think John Paul has been given a real opportunity
to show everything he's got.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the seat Paul vacated at Team Pelfrey is expected to
be filled today by either World of Outlaws Sprint Car star Steve
Kinser or Indy-car veteran Johnny Parsons. Brian Barnhart, the
IRL's director of racing operations, said he was having signs made
with Kinser's name on it yesterday afternoon to hang over the No.
81 team's door in the newly renamed Pep Boys Indy Racing League
Garage. That formerly was known as the NASCAR Busch Grand National
Garage. ...
</P>
<P>
   Driver Davey Hamilton has applauded the decision by TMS
management to eliminate the former eight-degree ``dual-banking'' in
the corners, which now are fully banked at 24 degrees. ``Nobody
raced on it, so there was no sense having it,'' said Hamilton,
driver of the No. 6 Nienhouse Motorsports G Force/Aurora. ``Might
as well make more race room with the 24-degree banking.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton is expecting a minimal increase in IRL speeds this
weekend. ``And it's a false speed,'' said Hamilton, who finished
fourth at Indy last month. ``Because what they've done is move the
white line down eight feet in each corner. So it's actually made
the bottom of the track a little smaller. It's still a mile and a
half track. But it's just a shorter distance _ if you run on the
white line.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   McCormack Motorsports and driver Raul Boesel have signed
TransWorld Diversified Services Inc. of Tampa, Fla., as primary
sponsor for the remainder of the season.
</P>
<P>
   If Indy-car legend A.J. Foyt of Houston is still looking for a
suspect in the alleged ``sabotage'' of the car of Indy 500
pole-sitter Billy Boat on the night before the big race, he might
want to check out Cigarette Smoking Man from ``The X-Files.''
Theoretically, he's responsible for every other unsolved conspiracy
in the past 50 years. &QL; 
NASCAR &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For those with short memories, Winston Cup star Rusty Wallace
first broached the subject of a complete make-over at Texas Motor
Speedway when he crashed out in Turn 4 of the Interstate Batteries
500 in April 1997. Brother Kenny Wallace criticized management for
spending too much time and money on luxury suites, condos and fan
amenities at the expense of the 1.5-mile racetrack after the Texas
500 in April. Enter Mike Wallace, brother of Rusty and Kenny, and a
regular in the NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series. Mike Wallace, who
also competed in the inaugural Cup race in Fort Worth, returns this
week as driver of the No. 52 Purolator PureOne Chevrolet owned by
Cup driver Ken Schrader. Wallace said he wants to believe the
water-seepage problems in turns 1 and 4 that plagued the Cup
drivers in April have been remedied, and the reconfigured exit of
Turn 4 and entrance of Turn 1 will prove driver-friendly during
tomorrow night's Pronto Auto Parts 400K night race. ``I know there
will be a tremendous amount of interest on Friday night from
Richmond, Va., where all the Cup cars and Busch cars are this
weekend _ to see what this race is going to do,'' Wallace said
yesterday. ``I mean, that was the buzz when we left Charlotte _
let's see what's going to happen in Texas. I'm sure Schrader is
going to be on the phone asking, `Hey, what did that racetrack do?'
I'm sure the racetrack is going to be fine. But they need this race
to come off with no problems. Because Friday night is the night
everybody (in NASCARland) is going to be watching it _ no
disrespect to the IRL.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Irvan has moved from 23rd in Cup points to 14th since the
Texas 500 in April. Irvan was the first driver out of the TMS race,
thanks to a flat tire in the No. 36 Skittles Pontiac Grand Prix.
``The only flat tire we've had since then has been on the rental
car,'' Irvan said. ``We really like that.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Only five Winston Cup drivers have qualified for all 12 races
this season without use of a provisional start _ Jeff Gordon, Dale
Jarrett, Rusty Wallace, John Andretti and Rick Mast.  &QL; 
WORLD OF OUTLAWS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are few areas of the country where local drivers can give
Pennzoil World of Outlaws regulars a serious challenge. Central
Pennsylvania is one of them. When the Outlaws returned for their
annual Sprint Car tour of the region on May 19, the ``Pennsylvania
Posse'' let it be known they were going to protect their turf.
Local drivers Fred Rahmer and Donnie Kreitz combined to win three
of seven WoO races in Pennsylvania and Maryland. Rahmer was the
only driver to repeat in the seven races, while series regulars
Mark Kinser, Johnny Herrera, Sammy Swindell and Stevie Smith all
posted victories. Mark Kinser took the series points lead with
seven consecutive top-five finishes, including a victory at
Williams Grove Speedway in Mechanicsburg, Pa. Stevie Smith, of New
Oxford, Pa., began the tour with the points lead but lost two
engines in four races between May 21-24 and fell to fourth. Smith
returned to form at Williams Grove with a victory in the
caution-free 30-lap A-main on May 29. &QL; 
FAST LAPS &QL; 
PLAYING ALL THE ANGLES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indy Racing League stars Eddie Cheever and Arie Luyendyk have
downplayed the possible effect the repaving and reconfiguring of
Texas Motor Speedway figures to have on race speeds during Saturday
night's True Value 500-kilometer race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll probably be two or three mph faster than we were
last year,'' said Cheever, the reigning Indy 500 champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new pavement should be quicker, but it might give us too
much grip,'' said Luyendyk, the reigning True Value 500K champion.
``We might have a problem where we have too much grip, and too much
grip slows you down as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Are these drivers in denial?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently not, even when TMS is compared to Atlanta Motor
Speedway, its sister track that underwent a reconfiguring and
repaving last year. The 1.5-mile AMS quad-oval, which like TMS has
corners banked at 24 degrees, witnessed an increase of 11.971 mph
in Winston Cup pole speeds from March 1997 to November 1997. Geoff
Bodine won the pole for the 1997 season-ending NAPA 500 in his Ford
Thunderbird with a record lap at 197.478 mph.
</P>
<P>
   That got the attention of the IRL's Barnhart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went and tested at Atlanta in April with both Team Menard
cars and with Greg Ray, and ran the same speeds we ran here. We ran
215 mph,'' Barnhart said. ``That was very surprising because we
expected it to be 10 to 15 mph faster than before, because the
stock cars increased. That didn't seem to carry over to our cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Like last year, IRL cars will compete at TMS with an aerodynamic
package that requires a 6-degree minimum angle for the rear wing,
and a one-inch minimum wicker bill, or flap. The regulations are
designed to increase chassis drag and downforce.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the 6-degree rear wing and one-inch wicker, our cars are
approaching terminal velocity here,'' Barnhart said. ``I would
expect us to be in the 215, 218 to 220 mph range here. And that
will be a gain as much in horsepower and in tires as the
reconfiguration of the racetrack.'' &QL; 
NUTS AND BOLTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Randy LaJoie is scheduled to drive his final Winston Cup race in
the No. 50 Budweiser Chevrolet at Richmond, Va., on Saturday night.
Wally Dallenbach Jr. will take over the Hendrick Motorsports ride,
normally assigned to Ricky Craven, at Michigan International
Speedway on June 14.
</P>
<P>
   Hut Stricklin, who recently lost his Winston Cup driving job
with the Stavola Brothers to Buckshot Jones, will be teamed with
Ken Schrader in a second Andy Petree-owned Chevy for the Pepsi 400
at Daytona Beach, Fla., on July 4.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran NASCAR crew chief Waddell Wilson has joined Team Sabco
as a consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Rudd's sixth-place finish Sunday at Dover Downs was his
first Winston Cup top-10 of the season. Jeff Burton (second) and
Rick Mast (11th) equaled their best results of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Wallace is in the midst of a 42-race Cup winless streak. &QL; 
LAST WORDS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``''I'm not a professional race-car driver, so I'm not going to
tell you it's this, it's that _ because you won't believe me
anyway. As a layman, it's a completely different racetrack.''''
</P>
<P>
   _ Eddie Gossage, executive vice president and general manager of
Texas Motor Speeway, on the repaved and reconfigured surface.
</P>
</TEXT>
