<HEADER>
A3308 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKEES-HERNANDEZ     06-03 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-HERNANDEZ-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFUGEE'S LONG JOURNEY ENDS AT YANKEE STADIUM
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, re-editing throughout) (ja)  
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Before throwing his first pitch for the Yankees
Wednesday night, Orlando Hernandez stood behind the mound for
several seconds and stared around the outfield at Yankee Stadium.
These were moments to remember for Hernandez, the realization of a
lifelong goal and the culmination of a harrowing journey that began
six months ago with a risky escape from Cuba and ended last night
on baseball's grandest stage.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, forbidden to play baseball in Cuba by officials who
feared that he would defect, survived that trip in a makeshift
sailboat last December and signed with the Yankees this spring
training. He performed so well in the minor leagues that he was
promoted to pitch at Yankee Stadium Wednesday night, against the
Tampa Bay Devil Rays. The crowd roared when he was introduced,
cheered him when he walked to the mound, and burst out with more
cheers when he struck out the game's first hitter, Quinton
McCracken.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez left the game after seven innings, getting the victory
as the Yankees won, 7-1. He gave up the one run on five hits with
two walks and seven strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees called Hernandez up on Tuesday as a contingency, in
case David Wells, bothered by shoulder soreness, could not pitch.
Wells was able to start, but it just so happened that David Cone,
another Yankee pitcher, had been bitten on his pitching hand by his
mother's dog. The Yankees decided to rest Cone and activate
Hernandez for one game; they intended to return him to the minors
Thursday, and then call him up again later this season.
</P>
<P>
   But for Hernandez, one day was enough. He ate spaghetti
Wednesday afternoon, his favorite pre-game meal, and arrived at
Yankee Stadium around 3:30, cheered by fans waiting outside, some
waving Cuban flags. He strolled into the Yankees clubhouse, wearing
bluejeans and a jeans jacket, appearing not the least bit nervous
or anxious. In a sense, he had been preparing for this day for
years.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez was a star on Cuba's national team, known as El Duque,
the nickname given to his father. As a child, Hernandez has said,
he rooted for the Yankees and hoped he could play in Yankee
Stadium. His younger half brother, Livan, defected from Cuba in
1995 and signed with the Florida Marlins. Livan was a World Series
hero for the Marlins last October.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Hernandez is the latest of a handful of defectors from
Cuba who are slowly making an impact in the major leagues. Rey
Ordonez, the Mets' shortstop, won a Gold Glove award last season
for his defensive brilliance, and Rolando Arrojo of Tampa Bay has
been one of the American League's best pitchers this season.
</P>
<P>
   After his brother's defection, Cuban authorities suspected that
Orlando would also try to leave. So even though he was a star
pitcher, they banned him for life from Cuba's national team in
October 1996. Other players who had defected, such as Livan
Hernandez and Ordonez, had walked away while the team was playing
in other countries. Orlando Hernandez would not get that chance.
</P>
<P>
   After he was banned, Hernandez, who is 32 years old by some
accounts and 28 by his own, worked briefly in a psychiatric
hospital, earning, he said, less than $10 a month. He said that
before Christmas 1997, government officials visited him and warned
him against taking any embarrassing action, because the pope was
scheduled to visit Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   With that, Hernandez was determined to leave. On the morning of
Dec. 6, he and seven others, including his wife, Noris Bosch, got a
20-foot sailboat made of scraps, carrying only several cans of
Spam, some fresh water and sugar. It was a dangerous flight. Arrojo
said Wednesday that while he wanted to flee Cuba, he never
considered leaving on a boat.
</P>
<P>
   After 10 hours, Hernandez and his group landed on Anguilla Cay,
a small deserted spit of land that belongs to the Bahamas; for
several days _ Hernandez has been unclear whether it was three or
four _ they huddled under a sail for warmth and survived on seaweed
and conch. They were spotted by a U.S. Coast Guard helicopter and
transported to the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez was offered a visa by the United States, but he
established residence in Costa Rica instead, a firsthand experience
in capitalism; had he taken up American residence, he would have
been subject to Major League Baseball's amateur draft and only able
to negotiate with the team that drafted him. But by going to Costa
Rica, he became a free agent and could field offers from all teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees signed Hernandez on March 7 to a four-year, $6.6
million contract _ more than twice what executives with other
bidders said they had offered.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez worked out with the Yankees for the first time March
21, but the team was not sure what kind of physical condition he
would be in. After all, he had been out of organized baseball for
more than a year. But he shocked them: A team doctor said Hernandez
was in the best condition of any athlete he had ever examined. Joe
Torre, the Yankee manager, saw Hernandez's broad shoulders, his
solid 6-foot-2-inch, 190-pound build, the flexibility in his
movements and his pitching mechanics, and decided then that
Hernandez had a chance to pitch in the big leagues. He just looks
like an athlete, Torre said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Teammates were taken immediately with his enthusiasm, his
outward joy. At the end of a fielding drill on his first day of
spring training, Hernandez bounced around the infield to pick up
baseballs, like a newly hired bat boy, his glove overflowing. He
was incredulous at the food and equipment made available to the
players.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Hideki Irabu, the Japanese pitcher whose assimilation
last season was awkward, Hernandez seemed to fit in with the
Yankees right away. When he first went to David Szen, the team's
traveling secretary, to receive his allotment of meal money,
Hernandez tried to speak only in English. Hernandez shivered in the
relative cold of Florida in March, but refused to buy any warmer
clothes; he needed to adjust, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He always seemed so happy, other players noted. But during
batting practice one day, Jorge Posada, a Yankee catcher, stood
alongside Hernandez in the outfield and asked him about his trip in
the leaky sailboat. Posada remembered Wednesday that Hernandez
replied quietly, his eyes turned downward.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear about the people who make it on the boats,'' said
Posada, who grew up in Puerto Rico. ``But there are so many who
don't. You wonder, how bad is it over there that they just want to
get away? It's sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Posada paused. ``He left all his friends behind,'' he said. ``He
had to leave some of his family behind. That's pretty tough.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Hernandez's agent, Joe Cubas, authorities in Cuba
jailed one of the pitcher's brothers for a few days. Hernandez's
phone calls to his daughters, Yahumara, 7, and Steffi, 2, who live
in Cuba with his ex-wife, are monitored. ``Duque's life is
incomplete until he has his kids next to him,'' Cubas said.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez continued his preparation at the Yankees' training
complex in April, before pitching in a Class A game on April 16;
just 11 days later, he struck out 10 in five scoreless innings for
the Yankees' top farm club, Class AAA Columbus. He continued to
pitch well, compiling a 6-0 record and a 3.83 earned run average
for the Clippers, and his joyful approach to baseball and his life
experience here does not seem to have wavered.
</P>
<P>
   A large contingent of Cuban-Americans recently attended a
Clippers game in Rochester, waving flags and banging drums. An hour
after the game, in the parking lot, the drumbeats could still be
heard outside the stadium _ a group of 20 or so playing music. In
the middle of them, Orlando Hernandez danced. And last night at
Yankee Stadium, he completed his long journey and pitched.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
