<SLUG> BC-INTREPID-DEAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEOPLESOFT INTERESTED IN INTREPID 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMIE BECKETT  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
PeopleSoft Inc., a fast-growing software-maker, is expected to
announce today its acquisition of Alameda-based Intrepid Systems, a
maker of software for the retail industry, sources said late
yesterday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Terms for the deal were not available, but one source said
payment will be in PeopleSoft stock, which has risen 68 percent
over the past year. Yesterday, PeopleSoft closed at $42, down
$1.13.
</P>
<P>
   Intrepid is privately held and, by one estimate, has annual
revenues of about $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   In an analysts' meeting last week, Pleasanton-based PeopleSoft
said it was looking to expand its industry-specific product lines
through acquisitions. Currently, PeopleSoft sells human-resources,
manufacturing-management and financial software used by all types
of businesses as well as specialized software for schools and
government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Retail-management software such as that sold by Intrepid ``is
wide-open territory for PeopleSoft. If they move in and build a
beachhead as they did in higher education and the public sector,
they can get a real advantage,'' said James Moore, an analyst at BT
Alex. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   PeopleSoft currently holds a small equity stake in Intrepid. The
two companies also act as partners to sell products to retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Intrepid's 230 employees, who learned of the deal
yesterday, are expected to have jobs at PeopleSoft. The company,
which had 4,400 employees earlier this year, has been hiring
furiously _ last year it added 2,000 people, and this year it said
it expects to add another 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers use Intrepid's products to manage merchandise,
purchasing, marketing and warehouses and to track promotions. Its
customers include Rite-Aid drug stores, Consolidated Stores, Kmart
and Liz Claiborne.
</P>
<P>
   PeopleSoft had revenues of $815 million in 1997, an 81 percent
jump over 1996. The company has said it expects to grow another 50
to 60 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Founded just a decade ago with five employees, PeopleSoft is now
one of the world's largest manufacturers of software used by large
enterprises. According to a May report by IDC Research, that market
grew 20 percent last year to $14.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   PeopleSoft, which pioneered business management applications
that could run on all kinds of systems, began as a maker of
software used to administer human resources. Later, it added
software for financial management and product distribution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
