<SLUG> BC-NY-CHRISTIE'S-AUCTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTEMPORARY ART AUCTIONED FOR RECORD PRICES
</HEADLINE>
  (ja)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Evoking the Yankees' recent triumph, Christopher
Burge, chairman of Christie's in America, called Wednesday night's
sale ``a perfect game.'' The first auction of contemporary art as
Christie's now defines it _ works dating from 1970 to the present,
rather than art made since 1945 _ was 100 percent sold, with record
prices set for 12 artists.
</P>
<P>
   A small but passionate group of international collectors and
dealers snapped up works by artists like Gerhard Richter, Sigmar
Polke and Blinky Palermo at a relentless pace. Many times, there
were so many bidders that it was hard to keep them all straight.
The sale totaled $16.1 million, far above the auction house's high
estimate of $12.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Six serious contenders went after Richter's ``Seascape'' (1969),
a romantic composition based on two photographs, one of the sea and
one the sky. Expected to bring $800,000 to $1.2 million, it sold
for $2.5 million, more than twice the high estimate, to an
unidentified American bidder. The price nearly triple the previous
record for the artist, set at Sotheby's in 1995 when ``The Barn''
sold for $965,000.
</P>
<P>
   (Final prices include the auction house's commission, 15 percent
of the first $50,000 and 10 percent of the rest. Estimates do not
reflect commissions.)
</P>
<P>
   The first 40 works in the sale came from the collection of
Barbara Herbig, a jewelry designer who is the widow of Dr. Jost
Herbig, a scientist from Cologne, Germany, who died in 1995. The
couple put their collection together over eight years, buying
cutting-edge works from the late 1960's and early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's had staked a lot on the Herbigs' art. In February,
before the auction house knew what or how much of the collection it
would be selling, it issued a fancy $45 museum-style catalogue
(without estimates) and put the works on view at both its Park
Avenue showrooms and its annex at 308 E. 59th St. It even hired
Annabel Selldorf, the trendy SoHo architect, to design the Park
Avenue portion of the exhibition. Christie's also made a
substantial financial investment in the works. While the auction
house would not divulge the details of its financing,
contemporary-art experts said it had to offer Mrs. Herbig a
guarantee (a minimum sum promised to a seller regardless of a
sale's outcome) said to be around $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   The gamble paid off. The total for the Herbigs' collection alone
was $11.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Another painting that brought a high price was Sigmar Polke's
``Solutions I-IV'' (1967), part of a series of seven canvases.
These four show arithmetic problems with the wrong answers in a
parody of mathematics. Estimated at $700,000 to $900,000, it was
sold to Larry Gagosian, the Manhattan dealer for $882,500, a record
for the artist. Gagosian also bought Richter's ``Wheat Field''
(1965) for $552,500, just above its $500,000 high estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Three paintings by Baselitz depicting upside-down eagles were
also fought after. The eagle, a symbol of the German nation, is
shown with thick brush strokes against a bright blue sky.
``Fingerpainting I: Eagle'' (1971-72) was estimated at $450,000 to
$650,000. After a battle between several determined bidders, it
finally sold to an unidentified telephone bidder for $827,500.
``Fingerpainting II: Eagle'' brought $442,500 to an unidentified
American buyer. and ``Fingerpainting III: Eagle,'' sold for
$354,500. Both had been estimated at $350,000 to $450,000.
</P>
<P>
   One of the evening's biggest buyers was Ivon Wirth from the
Zurich gallery Hauser &AMP; With and his New York partner, David
Zwirner, who recently bought a brownstone on East 69th Street where
they plan to open a New York branch. Wirth was seen sitting on the
far side of the salesroom bidding and buying works by Dan Flavin,
Robert Ryman, Sigmar Polke and Blinky Palermo. Wirth paid $288,500
for Mr. Ryman's ``Classico 5'' (1968), a white rectangle painted
over 12 joined sheets of Classico paper, estimated at $150,000 to
$200,000, a record for a work on paper by the artist and $332,500
for Flavin's three-part fluorescent work ``The Nominal Three (to
William of Okham),'' estimated at $100,000 to $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sale shows that Minimal and Conceptual art now has a
truly established international market,'' said Neal Meltzer, who
runs Christie's contemporary-art department in New York. ``Artists
like Carl Andre, Dan Flavin and Robert Ryman sold for higher prices
than ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   So did the work of On Kawara, a Japanese-born Conceptual artist
who lives in New York. A record price was set when an Asian dealer
paid $574,500 for ``May 1-7, 1971 (Today Series Nos. 23-29),''
eight canvases with a date painted on them along with eight
cardboard boxes with newspaper clippings. Christie's had expected
them to sell for $200,000 to $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the sale, dealers and curators all had a different
theories about the sale's success. ``This is the beginning of a
strong market for Minimalism,'' said Lisa Dennison, chief curator
of the Solomon Guggenheim Museum. ``There was a small hard-core
group of collectors were were serious buyers.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Upright, a former head of contemporary art at Christie's
who is now a private dealer, said the ``rarity and quality of the
Herbig property helped carry the evening.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And the rest,'' she added of the high prices, ``was scarily
like the boom of the late 1980s.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-98 2332EDT &QL; 
