<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-DEVILRAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERNANDEZ HELPS YANKS TO 7-1 VICTORY OVER TAMPA BAY
</HEADLINE>
   (dc) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Had Orlando Hernandez kept the Yankees close
Wednesday night, his manager would have been happy. If he lasted
six innings, that would have been enough. But in making his major
league debut, Hernandez gave the Yankees much more, beating Tampa
Bay, 7-1, before 27,291 at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brosius, the Yankee third baseman, drove in four runs.
Hernandez gave up five hits, walked two and struck out seven in
seven innings, but with the slightly injured David Cone expected
back in action next week and the Yankees' machine rolling along,
Hernandez will probably be sent back to Class AAA Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   As Hernandez finished his final inning, fans stood and chanted
his nickname _ Duque, Duque _ and, from the upper deck, a Cuban
flag big enough to cover the pitcher's mound unfurled, slowly
twisting in the wind. Whether to acknowledge the crowd or not,
Hernandez removed his hat and accepted congratulations from his
teammates on the top step of the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter, the Yankees' shortstop, strained an abdominal
muscle taking a swing in the fifth inning and was replaced by Luis
Sojo. Jeter is listed as day to day, but Manager Joe Torre has been
careful about resting his injured players, particularly with his
team running away in the American League East and sporting a 40-13
record.
</P>
<P>
   Straddling the mound, Hernandez wore his baseball pants in a
style straight from the days of Babe Ruth, drawn up just below his
knees, leaving his dark blue socks exposed. Wearing No. 26,
Hernandez pitched in the manner of another Cuban-born pitcher, Luis
Tiant, a former Yankee right-hander. Like Tiant, Hernandez threw
pitches at many speeds, from many angles.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez' fastball has been clocked at 94 mph, but he usually
started hitters with his curveball _ then, sometimes, another even
slower curveball _ and he often wouldn't throw his fastball until
he was ahead in the count. In a sense, he was pitching backward:
the majority of his contemporaries set up their off-speed pitches
with fastballs, but Hernandez was setting up his fastball with
off-speed pitches.
</P>
<P>
   And it worked. He struck out the game's first hitter, Quinton
McCracken, drawing a barrage of cheers. The fans stood and roared
when Hernandez retired the Devil Rays in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   He did not allow any hits until Dave Martinez punched a soft
single into left field leading off the third. Hernandez retired the
next three hitters, and the first two in the fourth. Pitching to
Fred McGriff in that inning, however, Hernandez threw a fastball
that tailed back over the plate; McGriff whacked it over the wall
in right-center field, his first home run since April 28.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees, El Duque's hosts for a day, gave him treatment
that is standard for all of their starting pitchers, packaging a
five-run rally in the bottom of the fourth. Jeter tripled against
Tony Saunders (1-6), then scored on Paul O'Neill's line single. The
Yankees loaded the bases with two outs, and Jorge Posada smacked a
two-run single before Scott Brosius hit a two-run double.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with a four-run lead, Hernandez cut down the Devil Rays in
the fifth and sixth innings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
