u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-NAZI-NYT &LR;      06-03 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NAZI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SAYS UPSTATE MAN, 73, WAS NAZI GUARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A 73-year-old retired tailor from Sullivan County in upstate New
York once worked as a Nazi guard, helping to round up Polish
citizens and ship them to concentration camps, the U.S. Justice
Department said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Dmytro Sawczuk, who has lived in relative obscurity in
the United States for almost half a century, worked as an armed
guard at Nazi labor and death camps in Poland in 1943, Justice
Department officials said in Washington. They added that Sawczuk,
who now lives in Glen Spey, N.Y., participated in the expulsion of
tens of thousands of Jews from the ghetto in Bialystok, Poland, and
helped dispatch them to concentration camps.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department, which is now seeking to revoke Sawczuk's
citizenship, said he had lied about his wartime activities when he
applied for a visa to enter the United States in 1951, telling
immigration officials that he had spent the war working as a farmer
in Poland and cutting lumber in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   If found to have misrepresented his wartime record, Sawczuk will
face deportation proceedings, the Justice Department said. It is
also possible for Israel or another country that prosecutes war
crimes from World War II to request that he be extradited for
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``A number of our defendants have been extradited _ it is a
small number, but it has happened,'' said Eli Rosenbaum, director
of the department's Office of Special Investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Sawczuk nor his lawyer, Askold Lozynskyj, returned
repeated calls for comment. Prior to living in Glen Spey, Sawczuk
resided in Yonkers, N.Y., but it is not clear where he lived before
that.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Spey is a small upstate town of 2,500 in the Catskills
area, and those who know him there said they were shocked to hear
accusations that their neighbor of five years was a war criminal.
Sawczuk, who lives with his wife, Elizabeth, has two sons,
residents said, and had worked as a tailor and a demolition expert
before retiring.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Fahnestock, 18, said Sawczuk lived next door and never
failed to wave a greeting when the two passed on their street. ``He
was always very pleasant and kept his house nice,'' Fahnestock said
from behind the counter of Steve's Country Store, the town's only
gas station and convenience store.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought my first car from him, an '85 Dodge,'' Fahnestock
said. ``He gave me a deal on it and it still runs. And he bought
his house from my stepfather. Always really nice, not the sort of
person you would think to be affiliated with a bunch of Nazis.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials said Sawczuk is among 300 possible war
criminals living in the United States who are under investigation
by the department, which has stripped U.S. citizenship from 59
other Nazi-era collaborators and deported 47 since its Office of
Special Investigations began operating in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White said in a prepared statement that
the proceedings against Sawczuk were ``a result of the OSI's
ongoing efforts to identify, investigate and take legal action
against former participants in Nazi persecution residing in this
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum added, ``This case demonstrates the government's
continuing efforts to make certain that those who have assisted in
persecution do not continue to enjoy the benefits of their
illegally procured citizenship.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Canada, which has amended its criminal code to allow for
the prosecution of Nazi war criminals in its own courts, the United
States has traditionally deported the suspects, citing the
difficulty of prosecuting people for crimes that occurred in other
countries against people who are not American citizens.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Justice Department's civil complaint, which was
filed Wednesday in the Southern District of New York, Sawczuk, who
was born in Liski, Poland, in 1924, was recruited into the German
forces in February 1943. His instruction began at the Trawniki
camp, where men were trained for Operation Reinhard, the Nazis'
successful effort to exterminate nearly 2 million Polish Jews and
force others into labor camps, the complaint said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his training, Sawczuk was assigned to guard prisoners
at the Trawniki camp, the complaint said. It adds that around April
1943, he was moved as part of a special detachment to the Belzec
death camp to guard prisoners as they exhumed and burned the bodies
of ``hundreds of thousands of men, women and children'' who had
been murdered by Nazi troops there in 1942, ``primarily by
asphyxiation with carbon monoxide gas.''
</P>
<P>
   He was transferred to the Poniatowa camp, where he again served
as a guard before being transferred to Bialystok. There, the
complaint said, he helped ``round up and deport'' Jews from the
ghetto to concentration camps, including the Treblinka, Auschwitz
and Lubin camps.
</P>
<P>
   He was admitted to the United States as a displaced person on
October 1951, after telling immigration authorities that he had
spent most of the war as a Polish farmer before fleeing to Germany
in 1944, where he worked at a sawmill, the Justice Department
complaint said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Justice Department officials would not comment on what
led them to check on Sawczuk's immigration forms, John Russell, a
department spokesman, said most similar cases had resulted from the
scouring of wartime archives in Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find names of guards in archive rosters, then we run them
through the Immigration and Naturalization Service records,'' he
said. ``If we get a hit, we look to see if they are alive and are
still in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When we find them, the only thing we can do is deny them the
pleasure and comfort of the United States, because we don't have
jurisdiction for crimes outside the United States,'' he said. ``But
we have been very successful in what we do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
