<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SCOUTS WERE RIGHT ABOUT `EL DUQUE'
</HEADLINE>
  (ja)  
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He hadn't thrown a pitch yet, but he already was
somebody special. His nickname was enough.
</P>
<P>
   After warming up in the bullpen, the Yankees' new Cuban
right-hander was strolling across the outfield toward the Yankee
dugout as the public-address announcer Bob Sheppard intoned the
lineups for Wednesday night's game with the Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   ``And pitching for the Yankees,'' the voice boomed, ``El
Duque.'' Cheers muffled ``...Hernandez.'' Moments later, his blue
Yankee stirrups up to his knees, Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez
uncoiled out of a high-kick windup and fired his first major league
pitch, a fastball. Strike one, called. Moments later, as leadoff
batter Quinton McCracken swung and missed, he had his first
strikeout, and cheers from the turnout of 27,291.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankee scouting reports were correct.
</P>
<P>
   ``He throws strikes,'' Joe Torre, the Yankee manager, had said
earlier. ``He has a curveball, a changeup. He works both sides of
the plate. His command is good. He'll be nervous, but he seems to
have some calm about him. I just hope he takes it to the mound.''
</P>
<P>
   He did. Over seven innings, El Duque allowed only five hits,
struck out seven, walked two and departed with a 7-1 lead, which
became the final score. His only mistake: Fred McGriff, the Devil
Rays' first baseman, whacked a fastball strike over the right-field
fence near the 385-foot sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going back to Columbus after this game,'' Torre had said.
``But win, lose or draw, he's had this experience. If we need him
later, it's got to be a positive.''
</P>
<P>
   In the late afternoon, El Duque had watched his brother Livan,
last year's World Series hero for the Florida Marlins, lose, 5-1,
in Chicago on the television in the players' lounge. Torre,
meanwhile, was being asked how the pressure might affect the
rookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure?'' the Yankee manager said. ``Compared to the
pressure of jumping on a boat and trying to come to the United
States, this is a piece of cake.''
</P>
<P>
   That boat was a leaky sailboat, but it took El Duque with seven
others from Cuba across the Caribbean to a strip of sand known as
Anguilla Cay and a four-year $6.6 million Yankee contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jose Cardenal,'' Torre said, referring to his first-base
coach, ``he left Cuba a long time ago and has visited since. He
says it's awful there.''
</P>
<P>
   Awful enough for El Duque to climb onto that leaky sailboat. And
awful enough for Rolando Arrojo, the Devil Rays' rookie ace, to
defect from the Cuban Olympic team while in the United States
shortly before the Atlanta Summer Games two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo, a 29-year-old right-hander who is 8-3 this season, would
be watching El Duque last night from the Devil Rays' dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Orlando had the best won-lost record in Cuba without having a
big fastball,'' Arrojo said through an interpreter, Carlos Ledezma,
an equipment manager. ``We were on rival teams in Cuba, but we
played on the national team together at the Barcelona Olympics in
1992.''
</P>
<P>
   Had they ever discussed defecting?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Arrojo said. ``It is very dangerous to speak about that
in Cuba, even to another player. You couldn't be sure who you could
trust, so you didn't talk to anybody about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Had he ever thought about leaving on a sailboat?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said, ``but after I got settled here, I arranged for
my wife and two sons to get on a boat and come here.''
</P>
<P>
   More than anybody else in Yankee Stadium Wednesday night, Arrojo
could appreciate the emotions churning inside El Duque.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first game, I was confused, nervous,'' he said. ``I had
dreamed of being in the United States and pitching in the big
leagues, but when that moment came, I questioned if I could do it.
Orlando probably has the same feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   How aware in Cuba had Arrojo been of the major leagues?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not too much,'' he said. ``The Marlin games were on the radio
from Miami, but the only way to listen to the games was to hide so
nobody knew what you doing. It was very dangerous to speak about
it. It's so sad the Cuban people are kept in the dark.''
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo, however, knew of some of the best Cuban players. ``I met
Tony Oliva in Minnesota,'' he said, referring to the Twins
outfielder of another era who remains a Hall of Fame candidate. But
if he really didn't know too much about the majors, why did he
defect?
</P>
<P>
   ``For freedom,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   The same reason El Duque had.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
