<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-COL-SMUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FADING PEEP FOR THE GLITZ OF SMUTLAND 
 
</HEADLINE>
  (dc) 
 By ELIZABETH KOLBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Do you have to love smut to mourn the passing of
Peepland?
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the most recent and possibly the last sex-shop
judgment came down, delivered by the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals. Siding with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani against the sex-shop
owners, the appellate court ruled that the city was within its
rights to use zoning to restrict the sale of pornography.
</P>
<P>
   It may take months for the shops in the smut-free zones to
actually close, as their owners try a last-minute legal gambit. But
still, it seems safe to say that an era of prurience in New York
is, for better or worse, over.
</P>
<P>
   For Giuliani and millions of like-minded New Yorkers, it is
clearly the former. Wednesday, after declaring the court's decision
a ``big victory,'' the mayor announced that the city would move to
enforce the new zoning laws ``as soon as we can.'' From there, it
was easy to imagine him crisscrossing the city with oversized
padlocks, mugging for the camera against a backdrop of ``Girls!
Girls! Girls!''
</P>
<P>
   Yet there are many other New Yorkers who are neither patrons nor
owners of sex shops, and who may not even have found the shops
especially titillating, who will still feel their loss.
</P>
<P>
   The trick of nostalgia, after all, is that it is not just an
attachment to what was good and noble in the past but simply to
what was there.
</P>
<P>
   As we bid farewell to the sex shops, it is worth noting that the
shop owners were never their own best apologists. Rather than
identifying themselves as pornographers-and-proud-of-it, they
conducted their campaign from behind the screen of the almost
comically high-minded-sounding Coalition for Free Expression. Their
defense focused on the First Amendment implications of their trade,
a stand that seemed disingenuous at best.
</P>
<P>
   The dancers and strippers themselves, meanwhile, organized only
at the last minute. And when they protested that the issue was
really one of jobs, it seemed almost too sad and pathetic to be
compelling.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was it quite fair to suggest, as many of the shop owners
did, that Giuliani was trying to outlaw pornographic pleasure
altogether. Even under the starkest interpretation of the new
zoning laws, the mayor is merely marginalizing smut, pushing it
from the center of the city to the periphery. Even in midtown, sex
shops can stay in operation by reducing their pornographic
inventory to 40 percent of whatever it is that they are selling.
(Does this mean that for every four women dancing, there have to be
another six, say, lecturing on Sartre?)
</P>
<P>
   So it isn't as if New Yorkers will not be able to buy XXX-rated
videos or watch topless dancing anymore, just that they will have
to travel farther to do so.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the issue, however, is not so much the
availability of smut but what smut, in all of its rawness, seemed
to signify about the city. On an emotional level at least, this is
what made so many people in New York sympathetic to Giuliani's
campaign, and others so resistant.
</P>
<P>
   For most of its history, New York has been a pretty gritty
place, a city of fierce and sometimes ugly passions. To those, like
this columnist, who grew attached to it during the 1960s and 70s,
when it was self-confessedly, even ebulliently, seedy, the city's
tremendous attraction is bound up in these qualities. For us, it is
hard to imagine them just being sloughed off without the city also
seeming less authentic _ a sanitized, falsely sentimental image of
its genuine self.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani speaks often about the city's resurgence and the recent
redevelopment of areas once given over to urban decay. In
particular, he points proudly to the new commercial vibrancy of
Times Square. Nothing, it would seem, would please him more than if
the neighborhood's porn shops were to be replaced by more
conventional, tourist-friendly establishments. But some of us have
a hard time sharing in that dream.
</P>
<P>
   Niketown, the Gap, Starbucks, Banana Republic and the Body Shop
_ these are now the wholesome storefronts that increasingly set the
city's tone. Such stores are thriving in the soon-to-be-desmutted
New York, even though they have nothing essential to do with it and
all sell precisely the same demographically correct and
scientifically test-marketed designs that appear in malls all
across America.
</P>
<P>
   One thing to be said for Peepland, with the unblinking neon eye
on its marquee, is that at least you had to come to 42d Street to
see it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
