<SLUG> BC-LA-BILINGUAL-ED-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWSUIT FILED TO PRESERVE BILINGUAL ED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVID R. BAKER   AND TERRI HARDY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Hours after voters resoundingly approved a ballot
measure to practically end bilingual education, civil rights
activists Wednesday went to court to stop the new law, while school
officials faced the task of changing how they teach English.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of Proposition 227 filed a complaint in San Francisco
federal court, claiming the law violates the civil rights of
children with limited English skills.
</P>
<P>
   And as Los Angeles school Superintendent Ruben Zacarias said he
is developing a plan to comply with the initiative, a group of
1,500 teachers announced they have signed a pledge to continue to
use or back bilingual education.
</P>
<P>
   Approved by 61 percent of voters Tuesday, the law gives
non-English speaking children a year to learn English in intensive
language training before moving into regular classes. Barring a
court action, the law takes effect in 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights activists argued Wednesday that the initiative
leaves 1.4 million children, most of them minorities, with a
serious handicap in school. Children struggling to grasp English,
they said, will face an enormous, unconstitutional hurdle to learn
when compared with English-speaking kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not going to have the same access to math, to science,
to social studies -- and that's discriminatory,'' said Theresa
Fay-Bustillos, vice president of legal programs for the Mexican
American Legal Defense and Educational Fund, one of the plaintiffs
in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Language can not be an excuse to railroad these kids into a
less-than-equal education,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The proposition's backers Wednesday dismissed that charge,
saying that forcing children to master English quickly would make
them better students.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long run, throughout their academic career, it will be
a huge benefit to the child,'' said Sheri Annis, spokeswoman for
the English for the Children campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts said the initiative's opponents may face a
difficult battle to delay the initiative from taking effect. To
overturn the law, they would need to demonstrate that the new
requirements unfairly place a burden on non-English-speaking kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, do these programs, in fact discriminate? Do
they prevent equal access?'' said Rachel F. Moran, a law professor
at the University of California, Berkeley. ``It's going to become a
battle of the experts.''
</P>
<P>
   If the court challenges fail, it is unclear whether schools can
disassemble their bilingual programs quickly enough to meet the
law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're waiting to see what the district mandates us to do --
they've told us to sit tight and continue with what we've always
done until further notice,'' said Dan Balderrama, principal at
Lankershim Elementary School in North Hills, where 1,400 of their
1,650 children don't speak fluent English.
</P>
<P>
   Zacarias declined to discuss the law, but he said in a one-page
statement that the district ``is developing a plan to comply with
Proposition 227, as best we understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Zacarias said the district's plan could change ``substantially''
depending on the outcome of the lawsuit and yet-to-be-developed
guidelines from the state.
</P>
<P>
   He added that there would be no change of procedure or methods
``until further notice from my office.''
</P>
<P>
   The initiative's supporters said the LAUSD is counting on the
court challenge to buy time. But Annis said the district has no
excuse not to come up with a working plan soon.
</P>
<P>
   Annis added that the district has had a year to prepare for the
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the LAUSD doesn't make this their No. &UR;  &LR; 1 priority, they
will be seen as completely irresponsible,'' Annis said. ``This was
the wish of the people of California, including Los Angeles, where
it won overwhelming support.''
</P>
<P>
   Some district teachers signaled their intention to continue
backing bilingual education, with or without the district's
support. At a news conference late Wednesday, they said 1,500
teachers had signed a pledge to ``use and/or support the use of
bilingual education as one program to meet the needs of students.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our hope officials understand that for every one of the
teachers that have signed the pledge, implementing that policy
would be a greater disservice to our students than violating the
policy,'' said Steve Zimmer, teacher at Marshall High School and
organizer of the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Stone, spokesman for the state Department of Education,
said a task force will establish guidelines for districts by the
end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've suggested that districts should not act precipitously.
They should wait for us to establish more definitive guidelines,''
Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   Suburban districts seemed to be adopting the LAUSD's
wait-and-see approach Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Antelope Valley's largest elementary school districts say they
too are waiting for state guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need guidance from the state Department of Education on
what will be permitted or what are the appropriate strategies,''
said Ned McNabb, Lancaster School District deputy superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators in the Conejo, Las Virgenes, Moorpark and Simi
Valley school districts say they will wait for the outcome of legal
challenges or direction from the state before making any sudden
changes in instruction.
</P>
<P>
   Last school year, 1,157 of the Moorpark Unified School
District's 6,905 students qualified for English language
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't have room for planning; it tells us what to do --
you will teach English by speaking English,'' said Moorpark school
board member David Pollock. ``I don't think we'll have to retrain
teachers, they're just going to be given a new prescription.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
