<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: OFFICES MONEY CAN'T BUY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ala., Neb., Ky.)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, June 4:
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the results of California's primary elections
may cause multimillionaires to rethink their plans for midlife
career changes. Never have so many spent so much to win so little.
The businessman Al Checchi could have gotten a better return by
spending his $40 million on Lotto tickets than by seeking the
Democratic gubernatorial nomination. Rep. Jane Harman, who finished
right behind Checchi in the race, lost both her congressional
career and about $15 million of her husband's fortune. The car
alarm magnate Darrell Issa spent $10 million of his own money
chasing the GOP Senate nomination, to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   Like many elections so far this year, Tuesday's primaries were a
rejection of checkbook politics and unrestricted spending. Lt. Gov.
Gray Davis, who beat Checchi, is a career politician who
categorized his victory as ``an experience money can't buy.'' Matt
Fong, the state treasurer, underspent Issa for the Senate
nomination. Californians rejected Rep. Jay Kim and his financial
scandal. Kim, who recently pleaded guilty to accepting illegal
campaign donations, was confined to his Washington home under a
probation agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The voters' contempt for rich newcomers has not been limited to
California. Businessmen in Nebraska, Kentucky and other states
outspent their opponents and sent overall campaign costs soaring,
only to lose on primary day. Deep down, Americans may not really
want to see their government run like a business after all. Checchi
was not the first businessman-candidate whose history as a
job-cutting downsizer came back to haunt him.
</P>
<P>
   In another primary that was watched closely this week, the
inability of Gov. Fob James Jr. of Alabama to win renomination
outright was seen as the voters' effort to give the state a more
reasonable image. James drew unwelcome attention to Alabama with
his threat to call out the National Guard to defend a judge's right
to post the Ten Commandments in his courtroom, and with his
obsessive crusade for school prayer. Alabamans have good cause to
believe that their real problems lie more in the direction of
economic development and education. James' supporters may take
heart in the fact that the upcoming primary runoff pits him against
Winton Blount, a millionaire businessman. But Blount emphasized
progressive policies, not bottomless pockets.
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic result of Tuesday's voting, however, involved
not rich would-be governors but schoolchildren. Californians voted
overwhelmingly to approve Proposition 227, which would drastically
curtail bilingual education in public schools. The initiative's
passage, which was apparently supported by many Latino parents,
seemed to be more of a protest against the poor quality of public
education than a reasoned analysis of how best to teach children
who are not fluent in English. A more rational approach to the
issue of bilingual education was passed by the California
Legislature this year. But it was vetoed by Gov. Pete Wilson, whose
impulse to pander seems to grow as presidential election time
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Voters defeated another proposal that would have restricted
unions' ability to use their members' dues for political campaigns.
They apparently responded to ads claiming that the proposition was
a plot to quell critics of unpopular special interests, like HMOs.
Californians may have come to realize that legislating by the
ballot box is a rough tool that is easily manipulated and seldom
accomplishes what they might hope.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
