<SLUG> BC-RESTAURANT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH COMPANY BUYING RESTAURANT ASSOCIATES
</HEADLINE>
 ASSOCIATES-SALE-500&AMP;ADD-NYT (dc) 
By GLENN COLLINS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Restaurant Associates, the trailblazing Manhattan
management and consulting group that has created some of New York's
most popular restaurants, including the Four Seasons, is being
acquired by a London food-service company in a deal valued at about
$138 million.
</P>
<P>
   Compass Group PLC, the world's largest food-service company,
said Wednesday that it had agreed to pay $87.5 million for
Restaurant Associates itself and about $50 million for its Acapulco
chain of 46 Mexican restaurants
</P>
<P>
   By being acquired, Restaurant Associates will obtain capital to
expand, and Compass will gain an upscale toehold in the volatile
and highly competitive American restaurant market, analysts said.
They added that Restaurant Associates would use the deep pockets of
its new owner to finance national expansion of its specialty, the
profitable packaging of its stylish brand of elegant dining.
</P>
<P>
   ``The acquisition could be good for Restaurant Associates and
good for Compass,'' said Malcolm M. Knapp, an analyst who heads an
independent restaurant consulting concern in Manhattan that bears
his name. ``The danger is that over time Compass may decide not to
keep R.A. as a unit, which would undo its specialness.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the second time in eight years that the company has been
acquired. The 1990 purchase of Restaurant Associates by Kyotaru
Co &UR; . &LR;  drew wide attention as the first major investment by a
Japanese company in the American restaurant industry during a
frenzied era of trans-Pacific deals. In July 1996, after a yearlong
effort to persuade the financially troubled Kyotaru to let go,
Restaurant Associates bought back all its stock with the help of
investors.
</P>
<P>
   The mystique of Restaurant Associates, which employs 8,500
people, dates from the days when it started trend-setting Manhattan
restaurants like the Brasserie, La Fonda del Sol, Trattoria and the
Forum of the Twelve Caesars.
</P>
<P>
   But the company has been eager to establish its identity as a
high-end food-service provider and creator of such restaurants as
the Sea Grill and the American Festival Cafe at Rockefeller Center
and Cafe Centro and Tropica in the Metlife building.
</P>
<P>
   And these days the lion's share of its profit comes from
bringing gourmet dining to corporations, institutions and
high-profile events, ranging from Sony Music Entertainment, the
Harvard Business School and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter to the
Metropolitan Museum of Art, the John F. Kennedy Center for the
Performing Arts in Washington, the Music Center of Los Angeles
County, the Academy Awards and the P.G.A. Championship.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the United States Tennis Association hired Restaurant
Associates as its new food-service provider at the U &UR; . &LR; S &UR; . &LR;  Open
tournament in August in Flushing Meadows, Queens.
</P>
<P>
   The company will become a wholly owned subsidiary of Compass,
which said it would retain Restaurant Associates' current
management. ``We have absolutely no plans for downsizing,'' said
Michael J. Bailey, president and chief executive of the North
American subsidiary of Compass, based in Charlotte, N.C. ``In the
future, I see more people, not less.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Nick Valenti, chief executive of Restaurant Associates, said
that the company could thrive under the English although it
languished under the Japanese. ``It's my job to make sure that we
preserve our uniqueness under Compass,'' he said, adding that the
deal ``gives us the wherewithal to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey said that Compass expected to keep and expand the
restaurant operations of Restaurant Associates, as well as its
upscale takeout concepts like Cucina Express and Savories.
</P>
<P>
   The high-end clients of Restaurant Associates ``will not want to
see its operations change,'' said Paul King, a senior editor at
Nation's Restaurant News, a trade publication. He said that
although Compass had the largest global revenues of any
food-service company, it had permitted a 1995 acquisition, Flik
International, _ an upscale caterer to schools and businesses _ to
function as a separate entity.
</P>
<P>
   Compass has $7 billion in worldwide revenues, of which the
United States accounts for $2.3 billion, making it the
third-largest American food-service provider, after Marriott
Sodexho Services, with $4.3 billion in domestic sales, and Aramark,
with $3.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Compass is already a powerful presence in supplying food to
corporations; two years ago it won a $60 million, five-year
contract to provide food and vending services for I &UR; . &LR; B &UR; . &LR; M. Its
subsidiaries provide food to colleges, universities, hospitals and
nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   In part, Compass, a dominant player in the highly profitable
European event-catering and stadium-service industry, acquired
Restaurant Associates ``to move us into the concession market in
the United States,'' Bailey said, adding, ``R.A. will allow us to
seriously bid for more museums, performing arts centers and sports
groups nationwide.''
</P>
<P>
   Knapp said that the acquisition, which he acknowledged brought
``a high price,'' would provide substantial profits not only to
Restaurant Associates management but also to backers including
Bruckmann, Rosser, Sherrill &AMP; Co &UR; . &LR; , and Furman Selz, two
Manhattan-based investment funds that helped Restaurant Associates
finance its buyback from Kyotaru.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey said that Compass would buy the Acapulco chain and then
spin it off, selling it to its own managers as a privately held,
free-standing restaurant company with financing from Bruckmann,
Rosser and Furman Selz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
