<SLUG> BC-RUN-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATIENCE PAYING OFF FOR USC DECATHLETE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KIRBY LEE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Danny Haag is 21 years old. And a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   The Granada Hills High graduate is competing today at the NCAA
Track and Field Championships in Buffalo, N.Y., and is a favorite
in the two-day, 10-event decathlon.
</P>
<P>
   Haag was an NCAA academic qualifier out of high school, but he
received no scholarship offers despite placing fourth in the high
school state meet in the long jump and qualifying for the finals in
the long jump.
</P>
<P>
   So for the past four years, Haag has awaited a chance to
showcase his talents at a Division I university. He trained
full-time while attending college part-time, first at Pierce
College and then at UCLA and Valley College. He attended all three
schools concurrently for a semester before finally enrolling at USC
last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was getting impatient when and where I was going,'' Haag
said. ``I didn't think it would take this long, but I think it
helped prepare me for college.''
</P>
<P>
   In March, at his first official competition in two years, Haag
posted a personal-best and USC-freshman record 7,623 points to
automatically qualify for the NCAA Championships.
</P>
<P>
   After missing the last two months of training because of an
inflammation of his pubic bone, Haag would be happy to equal his
total at the NCAAs. Haag, who had been training seven hours a day,
was forced to a sedentary lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   The condition known as osteritus pubis results from the
irritation of the pubic symphesis and can also cause hamstring,
groin and back pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Training was like a full-time job,'' Haag said. ``I like to
work hard and I get bored doing one or two events. I always have to
be doing something to keep me busy. I couldn't do anything except
go to class and watch TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Training partner Shawn Wilbourn advised Haag to rest. Wilbourn,
who placed third in the 1997 U.S. nationals, suffered the same
injury last year.
</P>
<P>
   After three cortisone shots and no workouts, Haag decided to
compete in the Pacific-10 Conference championships in the 110-meter
high hurdles, long jump and high jump two weeks ago as a litmus
test for the NCAA meet.
</P>
<P>
   He competed without any severe discomfort and placed seventh in
the 110-meter high hurdles in 14.65, less than two-tenths of a
second off his best of 14.50.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very worried. I didn't know if I would hold up,'' Haag
said. ``Now I know that I haven't really lost much without a day of
training.''
</P>
<P>
   The primary concern for the NCAA meet is whether Haag can make
it through the long jump and the 110 hurdles without aggravating
the injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he progressed through the season without injury, we'd be
looking at a totally different score,'' said USC jumps coach Allan
Hanckel, who has coached Haag for the past three years. ``The most
important thing is to get him running again.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Hanckel's guidance Haag has improved to 15-5 and 195-6 in
the pole vault and javelin and timed 48.90 for the 400.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, Haag has two priorities _ break Henry Gonzales'
school record of 7,960 points set in the 1984 U.S. Olympic Trials
and win an NCAA title.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was my plan for this year before the injury,'' Haag said.
``Realistically, I thought I had a chance. I figure I am going to
be hurting physically at the NCAAs because I haven't been training.
I'd like to do well and get back right into training and post a big
score just to show I could have won it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
